<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-EXPOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT POWERS RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With time to kill, Carl Everett Sunday sampled a
pregame film, ``The Edge.'' The one in which Anthony Hopkins's
character, warring with a growling grizzly, spews the same
obscenities Everett fired at home plate umpire Ronald Kulpa
Saturday in the head-knocking tirade that put him on a fast track
to a probable suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But once he left the clubhouse, Everett kept his thoughts to
himself and showed with his bat and glove against the Montreal
Expos how much the Red Sox could miss their premier slugger if he
lands in baseball's penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   The newly tight-lipped Everett, who would speak publicly only
through a team spokesman, hit a two-run, sixth-inning homer to give
starter Tim Wakefield a 5-2 lead, which held up for Boston's third
victory in four games since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Everett also walked and scored in the second inning, doubled to
spur a run-scoring rally in the fourth, and raced to the warning
track in the third for a sliding, inning-ending catch that robbed
Geoff Blum of an extra-base hit and saved a run.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Everett's 25th. But the chorus of boos he
received during introductions were a first. And he apparently was
pleased that his work in the field quieted the fallout from his
extracurricular outburst the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here in Boston, they appreciate playing hard,'' he
said through a spokesman. ``That's all I do. I'm out there to cut
down runs as well as score runs. That's how the fans have responded
all year. They enjoy the way I play the game. I appreciate them as
much as they appreciate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett answered only one other question that he agreed to field
from reporters through the intermediary. Asked whether Saturday's
violent outburst had marred his concentration, he said,
``Obviously, I had no problems with my concentration,'' referring
to his homer, double, and two walks in four plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Wakefield (6-5) suffer a concentration deficiency, as he
unhinged Montreal hitters for seven innings with his knuckleball.
He scattered four hits and allowed only one earned run to win his
fourth consecutive start since his emergency entry into the
rotation last month.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Sox starter to win four straight this year is
Pedro Martinez, who was asked if Wakefield should be dubbed ``Pedro
Wakefield.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Martinez, a two-time Cy Young Award winner. ``Call
him Cy Wakefield.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Expo to overpower Wakefield was the gifted slugger,
Vladimir Guerrero, who sent a knuckleball towering over the Green
Monster in the third. It was the only earned run Wakefield yielded.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Wakefield faced few obstacles in ensuring the Expos
remained 0-for-Fenway. Montreal has not won in four tries here in
interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal scored its only other run after Nomar Garciaparra
fielded a two-out grounder by Terry Jones in the second inning and
made an errant throw that pulled Brian Daubach off first. Jones
stole second and scored on a single by catcher Lenny Webster, who
entered the game hitting .157 (.100 on the road).
</P>
<P>
   Before he left in the seventh, Wakefield struck out two and
retired 13 others on grounders.
</P>
<P>
   He fared better than Montreal's starter, righthander Mike
Johnson (4-4), who was called up from Triple A Ottawa in May to
fill Hideki Irabu's spot in the rotation after Irabu was sidelined
by knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Everett keyed a Red Sox rally in the second by drawing a one-out
walk. He scored from first on a Jason Varitek double down the
right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Daubach singled, moved to third on Everett's
line-drive double off the left-field scoreboard, and scored on Troy
O'Leary's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox took a 3-2 lead in the fifth without Everett's help.
Manny Alexander singled, took second on Darren Lewis's sacrifice
bunt, and scored on Morgan Burkhart's two-out single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Everett again in the sixth. After Garciaparra reached
on a one-out walk, Everett sent Johnson's next pitch beyond the
Sox' bullpen for the 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl just went out there and played his game,'' Garciaparra
said. ``Whatever happened yesterday happened. He didn't come in
here and worry about it. He just went out and did the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett had no interaction with Kulpa, who was stationed at
third. And he had no beef with plate umpire Randy Marsh, who had
said before the game that he planned to warn Everett about staying
within the boundaries of the batter's box if Everett was ``too
extreme'' in his stance.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dispute over Everett straddling the line of the
batter's box that ignited his outburst Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the switch-hitting Everett, who batted righthanded Saturday,
batted from the other side against Johnson. His lefthanded stance
is markedly different and does not place his foot as far across the
line as his righthanded stance does.
</P>
<P>
   But even when he batted righthanded in his last at-bat, adopting
the same stance he used when he drew a warning from Kulpa, Everett
was not warned by Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams and Everett's teammates appeared pleased
that Everett's focus had returned to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a big game for us,'' said Williams, who was
particularly impressed by Everett's sliding, run-saving catch.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield expressed similar admiration. ``I'm not surprised,''
he said of Everett's post-tirade performance. ``He's a great
ballplayer, and the thing that happened yesterday is yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, though, Everett could learn how long he might not be
playing ball for the Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
