</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE EFFORT SHOULDN'T QUIET CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A small percentage of the fans at Fenway Park booed
Carl Everett the first time his name was announced over the public
address system Sunday, but the reception for Everett got better as
the game played on. When he made a nice catch in center field to
end the top of the third, fans behind the dugout stood and cheered
as he came off the field. Then he ripped one off the wall in left.
Then he hit a 413-foot homer to right-center and it sounded like
Larry Bird had just been introduced. Another homer no doubt would
have produced a curtain call. Is there still time to name the New
Fenway ``Carl Everett Field''?
</P>
<P>
   It was a different scene 24 hours earlier when fans behind the
same dugout covered the ears of children and worried what might
happen next as a crazed Everett swore at his teammates, bashed
coolers, and tossed a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Everett will be suspended in the next couple of days. It's
inevitable because he clearly bumped, then head-butted umpire
Ronald Kulpa before turning his rage on those who were trying to
prevent him from possibly ending his career by doing something even
more stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's apparent that the folks in charge at Friendly
Fenway will continue to let Everett do as he pleases as long as he
keeps producing like he has so far (.327, 25 homers, 71 RBIs).
Regarding Everett's occasional outbursts and penchant for
tardiness, manager Jimy Williams says, ``We'll handle it
in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The Sox are afraid of Jurassic Carl. He's a
wonderful talent, so just leave him alone and hope the next
explosion isn't directed at a teammate, umpire, or law officer.
</P>
<P>
   Williams clearly has no intention of getting into another George
Bell situation (when he managed in Toronto, Williams tried to
sanction Bell, but was not backed by the front office). And general
manager Dan Duquette isn't about to find fault with this
multitalent who's on board for three years, plus a club option for
a fourth, to the tune of $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the dugout before Sunday's 5-2 victory over the Expos,
Williams took a few questions regarding Saturday's episode, but
dismissed it as Everett ``just being competitive out there.'' Then
he said, ``Anything else about the game? Not about Everett.''
</P>
<P>
   Master of the obtuse, Williams is good at dodging things he
doesn't want to discuss. This is why we'll never know for sure if
Duquette walked into the manager's office after Friday night's game
and said, ``Play Izzy (Israel Alcantara) or we fire you.''
</P>
<P>
   But his being ``competitive'' is no explanation for what Everett
did Saturday. Pressed on the point, Williams said, ``I was talking
about when he was telling the ump where he wanted to stand. As for
after, we're basically all responsible for what we say and do.
Hopefully, things will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   And Everett's behavior in your own dugout was OK with you, Jimy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there with the umpire,'' he said. ``By the time I got
back he was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Duquette, no one from the club spoke with Everett
Saturday or early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy indicated he'll handle it in-house,'' said Duquette.
``The league will take action against Everett. Carl is a very
intense competitor and he's done an excelllent job so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believes Everett has a problem managing his anger,
the GM twice issued non-answers. Duquette said he was aware the
outfielder had a volatile temper when he made the trade to acquire
Everett. He said he thought Red Sox fans would support Everett, but
admitted, ``I would hope this type of behavior would be a one-time
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   If Everett chooses to apologize to Bret Saberhagen, Tommy
Harper, Wendell Kim, Jose Offerman, and other teammates he
manhandled and swore at, that's certainly team business. We know he
apologized to Sox publicist Glenn Wilburn after verbally abusing
him in Chicago two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't Boston management _ ever proud of Friendly Fenway _
think Everett owes fans an apology for losing his cool, offending
paying customers with his obscenity-laced tirade, shaming the
organization on national television, and taking himself out of the
divisional race at a crucial juncture?
</P>
<P>
   We all have bad days. We all have tempers. Why won't the ball
club speak to Everett's post-bump tirade, which should have
embarrassed everyone associated with the organization? Sox CEO John
Harrington witnessed Saturday's eruption. Is anything OK if you can
hit a home run the next day?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Everett went 2 for 2 with two walks, two RBIs, and two
runs scored. He opted not to speak to the media and had the PR
department release his comments regarding the ballgame: ``The fans
here in Boston, they appreciate that I play hard. That's all I ever
do. That's how they've responded all year. They appreciate the way
I play the game and I appreciate them as much as they appreciate
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd talk about Saturday's events down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Good. Let's all leave him alone, watch him play, and hope it
doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. Watch that homer go clear over the Red Sox bullpen! What a
shot! Oh, and there's Carl pointing to the heavens again! Yahoo!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
