<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD ON SUSPENSION COULD COME TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-EVERETT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Hall of Famer Frank Robinson, the man in charge of
discipline for on-field infractions in major league baseball,
levied a five-game suspension on Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez May
3, he announced his decision on the third day after Martinez hit
Cleveland's Robbie Alomar with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   If he adheres to the same timetable, Robinson will have an
announcement Tuesday regarding Red Sox outfielder Carl Everett, who
twice bumped umpire Ronald Kulpa after his ejection Saturday and is
expected to receive a suspension at least as severe as the one
given Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's not too hard on Carl,'' Martinez said Sunday,
``because that will make it harder on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette implied the Sox would take no
additional action against Everett, who hit a home run and a double
and walked twice in Sunday's 5-2 win over Montreal. ``That will be
addressed in-house by Jimy Williams,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, meanwhile, said Sunday he had not spoken with Everett
about the incident. ``He was at the family cookout after
(Saturday's) game,'' Williams said. ``I didn't see a reason to talk
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams characterized Everett's behavior as ``just being a
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he had not spoken to major league officials
Sunday, but essentially conceded the team assumes Everett will be
suspended. Everett would not answer questions from reporters
Sunday, agreeing only to answer questions about the game relayed to
him by team publicist Kevin Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from past experience that whenever there is physical
contact on the field, it usually results in a suspension for the
player or manager,'' Duquette said. ``I would expect we would hear
in the next couple of days, after they've had a chance to review
the tape and read the umpires' report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league is very specific. They do not sanction physical
contact and generally when there is physical contact, it results in
a suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was asked whether he believed there were anger or
behavioral issues that needed to be addressed by the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league (i.e., the commissioner's office) will make
its position very clear,'' Duquette said. ``The Red Sox
organization does not condone behavior that results in physical
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was disappointed that Everett would jeopardize his
availability to the team by his behavior, Duquette said: ``Carl is
a very intense competitor. He's done an excellent job for us so far
and I anticipate he'll be able to return and continue to be a
productive player for us. I would hope this behavior is a one-time
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a quirk in scheduling, the umpiring crew that worked
Saturday's game in Fenway Park was here again Sunday. Crew chief
Randy Marsh, who agreed to speak with reporters Sunday, said that
the umpires' report on the incident with Everett was faxed to the
commissioner's office and was in Robinson's hands by Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh stressed that contrary to the suspicions of Williams, no
one from the Mets had contacted the umpires before Saturday's game
asking them to make an issue of whether Everett was standing too
close to home plate. Rule 6:03 of the Official Rules of Baseball
stipulates: ``The batter's legal position shall be with both feet
within the batter's box.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Case Book of the Official Playing Rules Committee, which
is incorporated into the handbooks used by major league umpires, it
further states: ``Umpires are directed to keep the batter within
the box when he bats, particularly not to allow a hitter to stand
so close to the plate that he is out of the batter's box. No part
of the batter's foot is to be closer than 6 inches from the side of
home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard where they said this was a setup deal,'' Marsh
said, addressing Williams's allegations that ``it had to be the
opposing team who called the umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one from the Mets said anything to us before the game,''
Marsh said. ``No one came to our dressing room and said anything
about him being outside the line. If anything, the person that came
to our dressing room and said something about somebody doing
something wrong was Jimy Williams the night before. The Mets never
came to me. No phone call, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that was generated the night before was when
(Mets pitcher Dennis) Cook hit (Everett). He'd complained that he
was standing inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marsh also contradicted the claim made by Mets catcher Mike
Piazza that he ``didn't say a thing'' to Kulpa when Everett came to
bat for the first time Saturday. Marsh said that after the first
pitch from Mike Hampton, Piazza raised the issue of where Everett
was standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Piazza looked at the line and said, `C'mon, what's
the deal? The guy's inside,' '' Marsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh, who umpired his first major league game in 1981 and
became a regular member of the National League staff the following
year, said he could not recall ever dealing with a dispute about a
batter standing too close to home plate. Usually, issues about
whether a hitter is in the batter's box revolve around whether a
player's foot is outside the back line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual,'' Marsh said. ``Not many people could hit
like that. Obviously, Carl feels very comfortable in that position.
It's his right to get as close as he can, but there are parameters.
People always want to take things to an extreme. You've got to draw
the line somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh was behind the plate Sunday, when the issue did not arise.
</P>
<P>
   Williams acknowledged after Sunday's game that he had gone to
the umpires' room before Friday's game with a baseball thrown by
Cook, to support his contention that Cook was raising the seams of
the ball with his thumbnail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy Williams asked us to check the ball,'' Marsh said,
explaining the umpires' actions in inspecting baseballs used by
Cook Friday night. ``We checked the ball. The times we checked the
ball, there was nothing wrong with the ball. But it was within the
parameters of our job, something we had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, when we came to this (Everett's stance), they (Mets) were
trying to throw it back at them (Red Sox), obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice during Everett's at-bat Saturday, Kulpa marked a line with
his foot to indicate where Everett needed to stand. The first time,
Everett erased it with his own foot. The second time, he said
something to Kulpa that resulted in his ejection, and subsequently
he erupted in anger, twice making contact with the umpire, the
second time with a head-butt.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, Williams suggested it was an open question
about who initiated the contact, even though television replays
seemed to leave no doubt that Everett was the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looked to me like somebody bumped somebody there
yesterday _ the umpire bumped him or he certainly bumped the
umpire,'' Williams said. ``It depends how you want to look at it. I
guess it depends which body was going forward, which body might
have been going backwards. If, in fact, there was any role-playing
or play-acting there, I don't know. The umpire (Kulpa) went back.''
</P>
<P>
   In their report, Marsh said, Kulpa alleged that Everett made
contact with him twice. Marsh denied that Kulpa was ``acting'' when
he was hit in the face the second time by Everett, causing his head
to snap back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a mark on his forehead,'' Marsh said. ``We did have him
check it after the game. We had them put some ice on it after the
game. He definitely was poked pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett did not leave the field for nearly four minutes after
his ejection. Sox base coaches Tommy Harper and Wendell Kim, along
with players Jose Offerman and Troy O'Leary, struggled to restrain
Everett, who yelled at Offerman, then was seen speaking sharply to
teammate Bret Saberhagen in the dugout before narrowly missing him
in the face with a baseball bat he flung onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh said he did not fear for Kulpa's safety while Everett was
raging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the Boston organization had everything under
control,'' Marsh said. ``The Boston coaches were trying to keep
everything under control. They were doing their best to get Carl to
go ahead and get off the field. They were doing everything they
possibly could. I think (Kulpa's safety) was something to be aware
of, but I think the Boston organization handled it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
