<HEADLINE>
THIRD TIME CHARM FOR JONES IN LONG JUMP 
</HEADLINE>
 OLYMPIC TRIALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ As she prepared for her third and final
qualifying jump Sunday, Marion Jones clenched her teeth and closed
her eyes. She shook out her arms, brushed the hair out of her face,
and exhaled as if about to dive off a very high board into a very
deep pool. A pool someone had forgotten to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the blink of an eye, it was like, OK, I have one more,''
said Jones, recounting her emotions when she turned around at the
end of her second jump, a long one, to see a red flag, signaling
her second foul on two attempts. ``If I don't get into this, this
dream will be over.''
</P>
<P>
   If she fouled again, she would be eliminated from the long jump
competition at the US Olympic Track and Field Trials, and her
historic chase of five gold medals in Sydney would be over. If she
jumped too early, she would lose valuable distance and maybe miss
the cut anyway, with the top eight of 12 jumpers moving into the
final round.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear lasted only an instant. After turning to see the
dreaded red flag, she kept turning. There in the stands were her
coach, Trevor Graham, and husband, shot putter C.J. Hunter. ``They
were just pumped up, because they knew if I got a legal one, it
would go far. When I saw they believed in me, there was no problem;
I was ready to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it sudden death, but for Jones it was sudden life. Trying
to control her formidable speed even while she employed it, she
chopped her last steps, hit the board, and jumped. No flag. Mark:
22 feet 1 3/4 inches. Place: Fourth. Dreams of five: Still alive.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the afternoon, in the final, Jones would unleash a
jump of 23- 1/2, to win the competition and check off another event
_ after Saturday's 100-meter victory _ on her Olympic to-do list.
Joining her on the team will be Dawn Burrell (22-10 1/2) and Shana
Williams (22-6 1/2). Absent will be Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who
trudged her way into fourth place in the preliminaries, her best
effort 21-10 3/4, but completed only one jump after that, finishing
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have Jackie on this team,'' said Jones.
``She still is, in our opinion, the greatest ever. Nothing will
ever take away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Joyner-Kersee's fifth jump, the 38-year-old felt
something in her left hamstring and passed on the attempt. On her
sixth try, she pulled the plug halfway down the runway, an
anticlimactic end to a surprising comeback try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never be disappointed, because I've been on four
Olympic teams,'' she said. ``This was a long shot. I thought maybe
I could put it together. (The top three) deserve to go, and I
deserve to go back home.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones, Saturday's event got the blame for her early
trouble Sunday. Coming off the final of the 100 meters, she said,
``I was running pretty fast, so I think my speed picked up. So I
had problems adjusting to that on my first two jumps. I thought I
was jumping pretty well, and that even if I wasn't on the board I'd
still make it to the final. And that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, said Joyner-Kersee, who laughed when asked if
the afternoon's outcome reflected a symbolic passing of the torch.
``For me, this was it,'' she said, spent. ``There's nothing
symbolic about it. To me, it would be a great loss if the greatest
long jumper was not at the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jones's last-chance jumps after the two fouls, she and
Joyner-Kersee chatted. Her heir apparent, she reported, didn't seem
concerned, and Joyner-Kersee was impressed. ``If you're going to be
the best in the world, you can't worry about what's happening or
what you have to do to execute. She knew she was going to get that
jump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
