<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK SETS TOUGH TONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was 8:30 in the morning, on the dot. The
Patriots were already in their seats and new coach Bill Belichick
stood in a crowded and silent room and began to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Pete Carroll,'' said one player, ``guys would still be
talking even after he'd come in. With Bill, he walks in and
everyone shuts up and pays attention. It reminds me of college a
little bit, where the players didn't say anything when the coach
was about to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious,'' said defensive back Tebucky Jones. ``He's a very
serious coach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vacation's over,'' said linebacker Tedy Bruschi. ``It's time
to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Belichick is inheriting an 8-8 team that went 2-6 in the
second half of last season, there's a lot of bad karma to smooth
over. By the end of the Carroll era there was backbiting and
general chaos in the locker room. The self-policing ways of Carroll
didn't work, and when he tried to be tougher, that didn't work,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has made it clear since walking away from the New York
Jets that he is in charge. The message has gotten to the players,
who begin two-a-days Monday after reporting Sunday and taking their
conditioning tests and physicals.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said the four points he emphasized to the team are the
ones he'll continue to emphasize.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main things I'll ask of them, and be pretty firm on, are
that they be on time, that they be attentive, be in condition, and
give 100 percent effort,'' he said. ``If they do those things, it
will run pretty smoothly, and if they don't, it's very difficult to
manage a group this size when we don't have that type of
cooperation and conformity.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach said everyone was on time except for one unnamed
player and rookie running back J.R. Redmond, who has not signed a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond will not be able to participate in training camp for a
while as he recovers from an inflamed tendon in his groin. But the
Patriots had not had a holdout since Robert Kraft took ownership of
the team in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The players, who seem to relish the new direction, want to put
last season behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's behind us,'' said offensive lineman Max Lane.
``It's you guys who keep it in front of us. It's not even in our
minds right now. We've erased it. It's all about trying to get
better and get ready for the scrimmage against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all business, but playing football is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has ``brought a lot of structure and discipline,''
said lineman Todd Rucci, who will miss some of training camp after
undergoing arthroscopic surgery recently. ``He got things on the
right page right away. We had a great offseason and it's been a lot
of fun around here. Everyone is real excited. You just want to play
under the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucci would not go so far as to say the old regime wasn't fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have fun when you're losing,'' he said. ``You get
a bad taste in your mouth. We haven't won any games yet. He put a
big challenge to the guys on offseason workouts. It's been fun
taking on a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Belichick, his team will start training camp
with numerous injuries, especially on the offensive line. Top draft
pick Adrian Klemm likely will miss most of camp following knee
surgery, ditto Rucci, and newly acquired guard Lance Scott will
miss the early weeks recovering from knee problems. This will give
Derrick Fletcher, Greg Robinson-Randall, and Ed Ellis more playing
time early in the exhibition season. Redmond, who likely will be
the primary running back, will also be behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone comes to camp with their own personal
expectations and team expectations, but there's going to have to be
a significant price we're going to have to pay to get those things
done,'' said Belichick. ``There's a lot of blood, sweat, and tears
ahead. That's what the players need to focus on. The dessert comes
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious, too, that players will have tighter lips. The
players saw firsthand that Ben Coates spoke out last season and is
now a free agent. Players refused to discuss the simplest details
of their injuries Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to start pretty quickly here in the next day or
two,'' said Belichick. ``For a coach, it's like standing on a
treadmill. It's going faster than you want it to. There was a time
when training camp was graduated. Now, with two weeks before your
first preseason game . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will scrimmage the Giants at the University of
Massachusetts July 27 and play San Francisco in the Hall of Fame
Game July 31 in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to understand as a team it's a tough division, a
tough schedule, a new system, and there's a heavy price that needs
to be paid,'' said Belichick. ``That's what they need to respond
to. If we do that, we'll be all right. If we're not going to pay
the price in the environment we're in, then we'll run into trouble.
We'll have to make personal sacrifices for the team to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson believes the change is already reaping
benefits. He said he's familiar with the defense Belichick wants to
run and that he expects it'll be a combination of a 4-3 and a 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't put the pads on yet, but we've been addressed by
the coach and he set the tone and he's set a pretty tough tone from
the start,'' Johnson said. ``He's businesslike. I like change. I
like experiencing new ideas. He brings a fresh approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Belichick will be challenged. All coaches are. How he
responds to those challenges by players, such as when he sent
J'Juan Cherry packing, also will set a tone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
