<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESSELS FEASTS ON KNIPPSCHILD 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ A Dutch treat at the Casino didn't mean Peter
Wessels had to share the money. No, the $49,500 first prize was all
his because the husky young man from the Netherlands stood as
perhaps the stingiest champion in the annals of the last surviving
grass-court tennis tournament in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never gave me a chance,'' sighed German Jens Knippschild,
who was beaten, 7-6 (7-3), 6-3, Sunday in the final of the Hall of
Fame Championships.
</P>
<P>
   That was more dinner money than Wessels, a 6-foot-4-inch
22-year-old, ever had seen, and he promised to take his father,
Gert, out for large lobsters. Gert never had watched the kid play
outside their country, and so he was most pleased to laze and look
amid 3,605 sunbathing customers while his bashing son served
spotlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner probably tasted pretty good because No. 133 Wessels
entered Newport very hungry, never having won a tournament in 26
previous starts or even participated in a final. Same for No. 150
Knippschild in 47 tries. This was a final for the famished, and it
went to Wessels _ the only Dutchman to win at the Casino _ because
he was such a tightfisted server. With phenomenal 80 percent
first-serving, garnished with 10 aces, he permitted Knippschild to
gnaw on zero break points.
</P>
<P>
   ``On grass, how can you do anything when a guy puts in so many
first serves?'' asked the German. Not that he was overly generous.
Knippschild let Wessels look at one breaker, and Wessels snatched
it with a return to go up, 2-0, in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it was a tournament for have-nots. Neither player
was seeded. Favorites long have been jinxed at the Casino. Only in
1976, the first year for the tourney on the ATP Tour, did the top
seed go all the way: Vijay Amritraj of India. This year's top guy,
Chris Woodruff, the defending champion, vanished in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' said Wessels. ``I didn't sleep at all
last night. You know, your first final. It's a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as big as his serve. Wessels, who is from a fishing village
called Elburg, was the biggest fish in Narragansett Bay, for a day
anyway. He and Knippschild had company in that the doubles final
was also filled with unseeded guys.
</P>
<P>
   It went to Israelis Jonathan Erlich and Harel Levy over the
Anglo-American entry of Kyle Spencer and Mike Sprengelmeyer, 7-6
(7-2), 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first Israelis to win a doubles title outside of
their homeland (only the second ever, following Shahar Perkiss and
Gilad Bloom, who won Tel Aviv in 1987).
</P>
<P>
   Informed of that, Levy said, ``Maybe it's a good omen. We stay
on the road to play Davis Cup against Bulgaria this weekend at
Sofia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYC-TOURDEFRANCE-BOS &LR;      07-17 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG IS ON GRAND TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France _ A few days ago, Italian rider Marco Pantani
and American Lance Armstrong finished the Tour de France's stage to
Mont Ventoux side by side. As they crossed the finish line,
Armstrong seemed to let Pantani scoot ahead of him, and while both
racers were given the ``same time,'' the Italian notched the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, it looked like he was handed the win by the
American, who held a comfortable 10-minute lead over him after
almost two weeks of racing and could afford to finish second.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani was determined to erase those accounts, though. So
Sunday, he bolted in front of Armstrong and finished almost a
minute ahead of him. It wasn't much, but it was enough for Pantani
to prove he didn't need anyone's help to score a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more satisfying to finish alone,'' Pantani said.
``There's a different taste of victory when you leave everyone
behind, the taste of triumph. I wanted to win it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   To Armstrong, it didn't really matter. He gained time on the
rider in second place, and wore the overall leader's yellow jersey
for the sixth straight day.
</P>
<P>
   He did acknowledge he felt in good form as he and the 140 other
riders covered the 108-mile course that went up and down two
mountains in the Alps before finishing at this ski resort. The
temperature hovered around 40 degrees amid snow-capped mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, personally, I felt better today than yesterday, but it was
a tough stage,'' said Armstrong. ``Yesterday most riders were on
the bike almost nine hours and today had three hard climbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the race looked like a repeat of the past few
stages, with the yellow-jerseyed rider staying in the middle of the
pack while a few racers whose lead would do nothing to affect the
overall standings went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the final climb, the pack of 25 riders was more
than 4 minutes behind the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Then the race got interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani broke away from the group, and a few others followed,
but it was Armstrong who would catch up with Pantani and trade the
lead for the first part of the ride up the mountain. The thousands
of fans who lined the narrow mountain road waved flags and cheered
wildly as they watched the winner of last year's Tour battle the
winner of 1998. It was the man in yellow vs. the 5-foot-6-inch
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   But with fewer than eight miles to go, Pantani shook off
Armstrong for good to catch up to the leaders and eventually pass
them. Some comic relief entered the race when two cyclists _ one in
a yellow jersey _ jumped onto the course, but they were quickly
laughed at and shooed off.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani's win was a kind of revenge for printed reports that he
was angry at Armstrong for appearing to give him the win the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Armstrong told me to speed up, I think he was trying to
provoke me,'' Pantani had reportedly said. ``If Armstrong thinks
it's over, he's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was more gracious after the win Sunday, when he said, ``I
hold Armstrong in great esteem, and I'm not saying that to flatter
him, that's my way. Armstrong is very strong, but today I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   German rider Jan Ullrich, who had been in second place, lost
time in the overall standings after finishing more than 3 minutes
behind Pantani. Ullrich is still in second place overall, but is
now 7:26 in back of Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   To put the last week of racing in perspective, Armstrong won
last year's Tour by almost that same margin _ 7:21 _ over Swiss
rider Alex Zulle.
</P>
<P>
   But the American won't yet commit to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a week to go in the race, and I refuse to say
I've won the race until I arrive in Paris,'' Armstrong said. ``I
can't see sitting here and telling you that; it wouldn't be fair or
respectful to the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously smelling a victory for his team, postmaster general
Bill Henderson arrives Monday to travel the last week of the Tour
and cheer on Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Marblehead, Mass., moved up to 30th place
overall and is now the highest-ranking American after Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 12-year-old boy died Sunday from injuries sustained after he
was hit by a publicity vehicle while watching the Tour last week.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle hit the boy Friday, swerving along the shoulder of
the road to make room for a passing car as fans lined the route to
watch cyclists heading to Draguignan in the race's 13th stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
