<HEADLINE>
STORY OF BLIND RUNNER JUST STARTING TO UNFOLD 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-RUNYAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Before June 8, the day she hurt her hip
during a training run when she stepped aside to avoid a bicycling
child, Marla Runyan had been tapped as a Story, capital S. Legally
blind since the age of 9, Runyan burst onto the international scene
last summer when, in just her eighth race ever at the distance, she
finished 10th at 1,500 meters at the World Championships in
Seville.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to run for five weeks after the injury, which eventually
crept down toward her left knee, Runyan just days ago thought about
pulling out of the trials. The Story seemed near an end. But
Sunday, after getting physical therapy right up until race time,
there she was on the victory stand after finishing third (4:06.44)
to Regina Jacobs (4:01.01) and Suzy Favor Hamilton (4:01.81) in the
much-awaited women's 1,500. Although she becomes the first legally
blind athlete to compete in the Olympic Games, that is not how she
sees herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really think much about my vision,'' said Runyan,
``and I don't think my competitors think about it, either. I'm
definitely an athlete. I think my vision is just kind of a
circumstance that happened. I never said to myself I want to be the
first legally blind Olympian, I just said I want to be on an
Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   A converted heptathlete who finished 10th in the 1996 trials,
this will be Runyan's first Olympic team; it's the fourth for
Jacobs and third for Favor Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``My strategy basically was third,'' said Runyan, citing concern
that her bad leg wouldn't hold up with an effort too strenuous. ``I
said Regina and Suzy can just go do whatever they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Favor Hamilton and Jacobs began in the rear but had moved up to
second and third by 900 meters, with Runyan sixth and conveniently
right behind Shayne Culpepper, the woman she considered her likely
rival for the third spot. That way, the vision she does have
allowed her to see where Culpepper was at all times. Just before
the bell, Favor Hamilton and Jacobs, running stride for stride,
caught early front-runner Collette Liss, as Runyan and Culpepper
made their moves. Running a last 400 meters of 57.6 seconds, Jacobs
began to pull away from Favor Hamilton in the backstretch, even as
Runyan, with about 250 meters to go, did the same to Culpepper in
the vital race for third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping some of my instincts from last year would kick
in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan, 31, now living in Eugene, Ore., suffers from macular
degeneration, a condition that allows her some fuzzy peripheral
vision at 20/300 around a blacked-out center. As a Paralympian, she
won four gold medals before turning to the heptathlon, which she
left after 1996 in favor of the 800. After an injury-plaqued 1997
and 1998, she turned to the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her reluctance to be labeled, Runyan acknowledges the
impact she has had. ``I can't even tell you the letters I've gotten
from so many parents and children and teenagers who have the same
condition I have or similar, and so it makes me feel really good
that it's affecting people in a positive way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
