<HEADER>
A4043 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ACTS OF COURAGE AT TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - No one was risking life or limb in the name of his
country Sunday at the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials. The only
casualties to speak of on the third day of competition at Cal State
Sacramento's Hornet Stadium were a few Olympic dreams, hardly the
worst of losses in the grand scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, we don't believe it's belittling the word to say that
courage was the catchword of the day. Like the red-white-and-blue
bunting ringing the stands, it was displayed all around the track.
</P>
<P>
   The women's long jump finals gave us Jackie Joyner-Kersee, a
four-time Olympian, to immerge from a warm cocoon of immortality to
flit like a butterfly over the sand pit a few more times.
</P>
<P>
   What a simple act of courage it was, risking failure after so
many years of unqualified success. Joyner-Kersee, 38, was two years
removed from her last competition and only four months into a
difficult comeback when she stood on the runway for her final
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   All she needed was a leap that she used to be able to summon
while half-asleep to earn a berth to Sydney. Joyner-Kersee was here
because America's top jumpers hadn't been exceeding the distances
she used to routinely cover, and she didn't want to spend the rest
of her life wondering, ``What if I had been out there jumping?''
</P>
<P>
   In two days of jumping, Joyner-Kersee saved herself decades of
regret. She finished sixth, then made it clear she was headed right
back to her rocking chair. The competitor was disappointed in the
result, but the person was content knowing she at least had tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe I could put it together but it wasn't there,''
Joyner-Kersee said. ``That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was half-right. It was all over but the second-guessing by
people who would have preferred that Joyner-Kersee remain a picture
in their mind, an image of excellence frozen in time.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been the easy thing; to rest on her laurels.
Instead, Joyner-Kersee gave us a crash course in personal growth,
teaching us by example that it's not in trying that we fail but in
failing to try.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones got it. Joyner-Kersee's sixth-place finish
``doesn't take anything away from Jackie,'' Jones said after
showing her own mettle in winning the long jump. ``She's still in
my mind the greatest ever. Nothing will ever take away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen. We're not surprised Jones could dig it. After all, it
takes courage to declare to the world one's intention to accomplish
something no other track and field star has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   The easy thing would have been for Jones to keep quiet about her
goal of winning five gold medals at the Sydney Olympics. Few people
would have put themselves out on a limb like that, knowing a smug
world would be watching intently to see if the branch gives way.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stayed out on a limb even when the branch started swaying.
It takes fortitude to keep hanging on. The easy thing for Jones
would have been to leave the long jump for others after struggling
with the event throughout most of the winter and the spring.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple act of courage Jones showed Sunday when she
sprinted down the runway and summoned a fair jump after fouling on
her first two attempts. With that leap she staved off elimination
and with her fifth jump she surpassed 23 feet for the first time
this year, effectively ending the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's dream of winning five Olympic events remains alive
because she kept trying when others were suggesting she'd be better
off failing to try.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Marla Runyan has never placed limitations on herself.
She doesn't see herself as special, even though every time she
steps on the track it is a small act of courage.
</P>
<P>
   That she was running Sunday despite tender tendons in her left
leg is the least of her handicaps. Runyan, 31, was legally blind
since the age of 9 because of a degenerative retina condition.
</P>
<P>
   She has only slight peripheral vision, making her third-place
finish in the 1,500 meters a vision of lionheartedness. All you
need to know about Runyan is that when she said, ``I keep think
that the next treatment is going to be the miracle cure,'' she was
talking about her injured tendons, not her ruined retinas.
</P>
<P>
   Her blindness, you see, she takes in stride. By holding off
Shayne Culpepper down the stretch for the last Olympic berth,
Runyan became the first legally blind athlete to make a U.S.
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very awesome,'' she said of her place in history. ``I
never really think as much about my vision as the media does. I
just think the person I am, I'm definitely an athlete. My vision is
just a circumstance that happened to me. I never looked at it as a
barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of her eyesight didn't keep Runyan from becoming a
winner. That's what happens when you let courage be your guide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
