<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO RIGHT REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Mauricio Wright is at a loss to explain the
demise of the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   They were hoping for a home crowd boost Saturday against the
MetroStars after five games on the road without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The boost never came as New York-New Jersey blanked New England,
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit different to try to go out and win, with the goal
that we have to play differently, so we had to push a bit more,''
said Wright, a defender. ``I can't explain what's going on with the
team. Everything is bad for us right now . . . we miss on our
chances and everything becomes difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is 50-50, they take the ball, we take the ball, and
they didn't get too many chances,'' Wright said about the
MetroStars. ``We had so many chances and we missed. We have to
concentrate on the game and getting better while their team has
been getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution outshot the MetroStars, 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of working hard in practice for everybody,''
said Wright. ``We have to play like a real team. At one point, we
were winning, now we have to start doing that again.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing the Revolution can do about the past, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try not to make the same mistakes we've been
making,'' Wright said. ``We're right in the middle of the season
now. We have games coming up that are quite important. We have to
try to make things better. Getting goals has been difficult. We
have to get our confidence back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we play well in the front, sometimes we play well in
the back. Now we have to make sure we do both situations at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has now played seven games with the Revolution and has
one goal since being traded from San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my best, I feel good,'' Wright said. ``I play 100 percent
every single time I'm on the field. I try to do my best. Sometimes
I make a mistake; we all do. I'm human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing the same way that I did in San Jose. I don't have
time to change. I try to play the way the coach wants me to.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has been. ``He's a class act; he's cool,'' coach Fernando
Clavijo said. ``He's always working hard in the back and he adapts
well, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wright always tries to be a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be a good partner,'' Wright said. ``I think I'm a
nice guy. I try to show my experience in the back to the young
players like Rusty Pierce and the others. And at the same time, I
try to take every practice seriously. I work hard throughout the
week so that it feels better when I get into a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Wright has to lead the Revolution to a series of wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
