<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EXCITE-CHAIRMAN-SFCHR     07-17 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-CHAIRMAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHANGE TAKES HOLD AT EXCITEATHOME  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ExciteAtHome, the world's largest provider of
high-speed Internet cable service, has been going through a wave of
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, George Bell, just took over in
January and became chairman in May, when Tom Jermoluk left to
become a venture capitalist; a wave of other executives has been
replaced; AT&AMP;T signed pacts with other shareholders to take control
of the company; and after reporting an operating profit for the
first time, ExciteAtHome recently announced it will scrap
short-term profits in favor of expanding its customer base.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle recently sat down with Bell to talk about the
changes at the Redwood City, Calif., company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: You recently mentioned that you want to focus on
expansion. But this is a time when other companies are retrenching
and focusing on profits to make Wall Street happy. What's the
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Our market conditions are much different than the majority of
companies. We have exclusive contracts (with our cable partners)
through the year 2002. We have extended contracts through the year
2008. We have a regulatory environment where the forced-access
issue has diminished in scope and scale. AOL bought a cable
company. In sum, the market conditions that we face over the next
two years are enviable and may never come again. We would be
irresponsible by not adopting a growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: Are you thinking of just cable?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: No. We come to life as a company with cable contracts. But
that's not where our mission terminates. We have added DSL (digital
subscriber line). We will look at any other viable technologies.
Our goals are 3 million customers by this year, 6 million by the
end of next year and 10 million by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: You said recently that in terms of the Excite
portal, you want to focus on adding broadband features. Is this a
change?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Yes. Because we have the privilege of setting the start page
for a national broadband service. Most people leave the Excite
start page as the default page on their browser. However, nobody at
other portal companies has that privilege until 2002. Of course, we
want to focus on the features and applications that we think are
going to be particularly valuable to broadband users. But the vast
majority of people still take our service as a narrowband service;
we don't want to walk away from narrowband.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: How do you plan to serve both?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Take BlueMountain.com, by far the largest provider of
electronic greeting cards in the world. What is it in broadband
that is different? The ability to attach audio and video to the
card. If I send you a Christmas card, I can attach ``Jingle
Bells.'' If I send you a Valentines' Day card, I can send you a
video clip or voice clip. These are all things that
BlueMountain.com can do, which wouldn't be altogether appealing for
narrowband customers because of the constraints of the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: As you think more about broadband, are you less
concerned if Yahoo and Lycos grow faster in narrowband?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: I don't think we can be all things to all users. My answer is
predicated on the assumption that as the PC is to the '80s, and the
Internet is to the '90s, broadband is to the first decade of the
21st century. This is the broadband decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: When do you plan to launch your broadband version of
the Excite portal?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: You recently announced a wireless portal. How does
that fit into your strategy?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Our principal interest in wireless is the personalized
distribution of content and, specifically, notification
technologies. We don't think the microbrowser is the place where
you are going to want to digest a lot of text or reconfigure your
stock portfolio. You are going to do that on your PC. But wireless
offers a level of convenience. You can use alerts that say: Tell me
when my stocks go up or down by 5 percent. Tell me whether my bid
on eBay has been a success. So, wireless is part of a larger effort
to try to get the most number of people to personalize their
content.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: As you undergo this growth strategy, you've had a
lot of executives leave the company and made a lot of management
changes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: You say a lot of executives have left.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think you should make a presumption that when people
leave a company they have all _ 100 percent _ chosen to leave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: One analyst pointed out that when a new CEO takes
over, he usually tries to build his own team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Some of that is going on. I'm not going to be specific. I'm
not going to say this guy is leaving, and this guy was fired. But I
think it is an important distinction for you to make. I get to say
what makes me comfortable as a manager in terms of the type of team
that makes me comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: Will there be more management changes?
</P>
<P>
   I am under a very large-scale effort to upgrade the quality of
management. I feel very comfortable with the recruiting pitch. I
can look you in the eye and say, ``This is the company we are going
to build.'' Six months ago I could not have said that. Who controls
the company? What happens past 2002? What about regulatory issues?
Who really runs the company? T.J. (Jermoluk) or George? Or AT&AMP;T?
These were all questions that were unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: You mentioned the stock market. The stock has been
down lately.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: One of the things that a depressed stock price does is it
gives you more courage to make the right moves for the business.
The problem is that you've got a very choppy Nasdaq as a backdrop
to all this. I don't know that the clarity investors are looking
for is around profitability. It is: Do you have a business? Amazon
is not profitable, has never been. But nobody is saying it's a bad
business. They are just saying that the risk profile is a big one.
No one is saying that our business _ which by the way will leave us
with a half-billion dollars in revenue from our subscription
business alone _ is a bad business. It's just unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: I imagine the reason that churn is so low is that
people like high-speed access and often don't have an alternative.
Do you worry about problems _ long hold times for customer service
and slowdowns in some neighborhoods _ as people have more choice?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: Yes, I worry about that a lot. Word-of-mouth will overtake
the value of our marketing campaign. We have 7 percent penetration
in markets we serve. In many markets, we're at 20 percent or 25
percent. This is not a backwater, techie phenomenon. This is
getting to be a mainstream phenomenon. I don't care how funny your
commercials or how palatable your economic offers are. If it
stinks, it stinks.
</P>
<P>
   The old saw is that a $100 million marketing campaign for a
movie is ruined overnight by a bad review. So, we are investing in
our network. We are adding very aggressively in the whole customer
service area. We are adding tools so customer service
representatives can say: ``Oh, you are calling us from Muncie, Ind.
We know your e-mail is slow. It should be slow for three hours. We
have technicians working on it. Call us again if it's not fixed in
three hours.'' Right now, our customer support people have to say:
``Describe the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: Let me ask you about slowdowns. You had some
problems with people abusing the network. How big is the problem?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: DSL is a shared network just like cable. The sharing occurs
at the central office. Please don't have the illusion that one is
shared and one is not. I think one of the things that frosts me
about the Pac Bell (ad) campaign is that there is an implication
that somehow they are not shared. That is not true. All networks
are shared networks. Second, can we fix it? Absolutely. Some people
are sending (large amounts of) MP3s out of their home, for
instance. The solution is you go to those users and say, ``We have
a product for you. But it's not $40. It's a business product.'' The
fix is easy, but unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: Pac Bell claims it has more subscribers in the San
Francisco Bay Area, even though it was later to market high-speed
Net service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: We have just begun to light up S.F.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Chronicle: Exactly. You still don't have any service in Oakland
or San Jose at all. Wouldn't it make sense to start offering DSL in
those areas now, since it will take years to offer cable service in
every neighborhood?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell: We are happy to employ DSL. But it's AT&AMP;T's decision, not
ours. It's also not my impression that (Pac Bell) is doing that
well. Their TV commercials suck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
