<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: MUCH TO APPRECIATE AT SEMICON WEST SHOW  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Back in the late 1980s, I lived in San Mateo,
Calif., near the Bay Meadows racetrack and the adjoining
fairgrounds. Most of the year, the modest expo center there would
be occupied by down-home shows featuring distinctly nontech
products like dolls, guns and costume jewelry. (Just recently the
site hosted a rubber-stamp festival.)
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, though, something called Semicon West would appear
on the marquee. It obviously had something to do with computers,
but I never knew quite what. I hadn't heard of most of the
companies exhibiting, nor even the products and technologies they
were showing _ and I never paid a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Semicon West has left the fairgrounds far behind and
has become the Bay Area's biggest trade show, filling both the
Moscone Center in San Francisco and the McEnery Convention Center
in San Jose, Calif. And I now know what it is: the annual reunion
of SEMI, or Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International,
the trade association of the companies that provide the ingredients
and machinery out of which chips are made.
</P>
<P>
   I also now understand that it's a very big deal, and not just
because of the havoc it wrought on downtown parking and traffic
last week. I've come to appreciate how much the whole high-tech
universe depends on these mostly obscure companies. Without their
ability to turn scientific discoveries into workable production
systems, Moore's Law on increasing semiconductor power would have
hit a brick wall long ago, and the forward march of computing and
communications would have slowed to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I understand most of what they do _ I may be a geek by
some standards, but when it comes to on-bonder curing, diode-pumped
lasers and PECVD (plasma-enhanced chemical vapor deposition, I
finally figured out), I'm as much in the dark as you probably are.
</P>
<P>
   That, I suppose, is why most of the news coverage out of the
show, including my own, focused on the industry's impending
transition from 200- to 300-millimeter silicon wafers. It's not the
only change sweeping the field, nor is it the most challenging
technically.
</P>
<P>
   But explaining the benefits of switching from salad plates to
dinner plates _ you get 2.5 times as many chips per serving _ is a
heck of a lot easier than communicating the merits of nanometer
geometries, not to mention low-k dielectrics and dual-damascene
copper interconnects.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, though _ I won't try to redress the balance here,
except to say that those last three innovations are shaping up as
critical factors enabling the Intels, IBMs and AMDs of the world to
keep making their processors smaller, faster and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   INSPECTOR GADGETS: Some other trends, however, are easier to get
your head around, even if you know nothing about semiconductors per
se. One I noticed is a growing emphasis on integrating testing and
measurement throughout the production process, instead of just at
the end of the line or at a few critical junctures. Considering
that a modern 300mm fab will cost an estimated $2.5 billion to
build and equip, it makes more sense to spend extra for instruments
that detect defects on the fly than to keep working on damaged
goods.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like good news for KLA-Tencor, the San Jose company
that dominates the market for ``process control and yield
management solutions'' for the semiconductor industry. But the
increased importance of these elements also seems certain to
attract more competition to the field, not the least from the titan
of the whole semiconductor-equipment industry, Applied Materials,
also of San Jose (market cap: more than $71 billion). Applied is
already building more test capabilities directly into its
production machines, and the trend is bound to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   (As an aside, I can only assume that today's ``metrology'' tools
are more effective than those considered state-of-the-art in the
machine shops I worked in a quarter-century ago. My first job as a
machinist, heaven help me, was making parts for ``people sniffers''
for fighter-bombers _ devices designed to trigger the automatic
release of bombs when the plane flew over a campfire in the jungle
or desert.
</P>
<P>
   The parts were made of alloys that expanded or contracted,
depending on the temperature. For better or worse it was almost
impossible to machine them to the tolerances required with the
equipment we had. But I soon learned how to get my output past the
government inspector and his fancy tools: Savvy co-workers taught
me just how long to leave each part on a shelf above a radiator, or
else on a cold window sill, to bring it into spec.)
</P>
<P>
   SMIFs and FOUPs: Another trend related to the increasing value _
and delicacy _ of in-process wafers is the growing role of
automated material-handling systems _ not just the robots that load
individual wafers in and out of production tools, but also the
overhead networks that transfer and track them from station to
station.
</P>
<P>
   These systems are anything but toys, but if you ever enjoyed
model trains, as a kid or as a parent, you'd get a kick out of
watching them. Like the railroads, they have their own lingo, too:
The sealed, ultra-clean boxes in which wafers are now transported
are known as SMIFs, for Standard Mechanical InterFace; equivalent
cases for the new 300mm wafers are called FOUPs, for front-opening
unified pods.
</P>
<P>
   Existing fabs, of course, are already highly automated, but
workers still sometimes have to pick up sealed cassettes full of
wafers and carry them by hand to another bay. I saw that happening
at an Intel fab I had the pleasure of touring not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the move to 300mm, however, wafers become both heavier and
more valuable. A FOUP-ful would easily exceed federal weight limits
for unassisted lifting and, in late stages of production, it could
be worth as much as $5 million, according to Fremont, Calif.'s
Asyst Technologies, the leader in the field. At that price, no one
wants to run the risk of a pod-carrying worker tripping over his or
her bunny shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Automated materials handling also has an important benefit: If
wafers never get outside production bays, SMIFs and FOUPs, and the
air within those ``minienvironments'' can be kept in line with the
increasingly stringent cleanliness standards semiconductor
production requires, chipmakers don't have to keep the surrounding
cleanroom quite so clean _ they still need advanced filtration
systems, but they can live with a few more particles per billion.
</P>
<P>
   And since building and running a high-class cleanroom is a major
part of the cost of a modern fab, even a modest relaxation of
requirements translates into significant savings.
</P>
<P>
   Asyst, which saw revenues more than double in fiscal 2000
(admittedly, relative to a disastrous 1999), should continue to
benefit from the automation trend. But as in the test and
measurement field, a growing business attracts competitors. Last
week, for example, I saw an impressive demonstration of intelligent
machine controllers developed by Berkeley Process Controls, a
privately held Richmond, Calif., company that supplies such
products to Boeing, among others, and now seeks to move into the
semiconductor-equipment market.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, what I found most striking about Semicon West is how
diversified and competitive the industry remains, even after
decades of development. Even Applied Materials doesn't offer
complete production systems _ its execs were boasting last week
that their lineup encompasses 75 percent of the hundreds of
processes involved in building semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the 1,777 companies that exhibited at the show are
all much smaller; most of them specialize in only one or a few
types of equipment. They've met the needs of the chip industry _
and enabled it to accomplish the wonders it has _ not by
consolidating into a handful of highly integrated behemoth, but by
maintaining an ecology where hundreds of smaller organisms have
thrived by adapting to their own narrow niches _ and by cooperating
around open standards.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time someone tries to justify a monopoly
as essential to technical progress.
</P>
<P>
   BEING FOLLOWED? An insidious threat to privacy that I _ like
most users, I'm sure _ wasn't previously aware of has surfaced in
recent weeks, thanks mainly to the efforts of the well-known
programmer and security sleuth, Richard Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is embodied in a mechanism called a ``Web bug.''
Smith explains how they work on his ``Web Bug FAQ'' page
( &LR; www.tiac.net/users/smiths/privacy/wbfaq.htm &LR; ); Cnet also has a
good story on the subject at
 &LR; news.cnet.com/news/0-1007-200-2247960.html?tagst.ne.1002.tgif.ni. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Web bugs'' are also known as ``invisible GIFs'' because in
some theoretical sense they're Web graphics, but they're only one
pixel in size and therefore effectively invisible. Linked to each
such bug is code that can report your every move on the Web to the
site that planted it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites using this new device, according to Smith, are
Quicken.com, FedEx.com and, predictably, the detestable
DoubleClick. Freevibe.com, an anti-drug site created by the White
House Office of National Drug Control Policy, also used them until
last month, when a presidential edict barred them from all federal
sites. (Curiously, President Clinton apparently didn't order the
site to get rid of its ``summer romance board,'' which still
invites visitors to ``tell us about your crush.'')
</P>
<P>
   Such bugs can also be embedded in e-mail messages to determine
who's read the message and perhaps to connect it to a previously
deposited cookie. Companies known to have used this approach,
according to Smith, are Barnes and Noble, eToys and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to detect these little beasts _ today's
cookie-blocker utilities don't detect them _ but Smith has created
a page that, with help from AltaVista, identifies Web pages that
carry them. Unfortunately, there's apparently nothing we can do to
destroy them, but disabling cookies limits the damage they can do,
according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   One more good argument, at least in my book, for strict privacy
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
