 BIOTECH PRICES FALL WITH GAIN IN HIGH TECH  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Biotech stocks tumbled late last week as a wave
of profit-taking and a renewed infatuation with Internet stocks
ended a six-week run that had brought biotech shares near their
record highs in March.
</P>
<P>
   Since the biotech retreat began Wednesday, the American Stock
Exchange biotech index, a basket of 17 large companies, has dropped
7.3 percent to close at 685.28.
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in last week's reversal, however, this key
biotech stock index is still up 69 percent from its April 17 low of
405. Since June 1, the biotech index has registered a gain of 38
percent, outperforming the tech-heavy Nasdaq, which rose 25 percent
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the Nasdaq's recent gains came during the last three
days, and analysts said it's no accident that biotech stock indexes
slumped at the same time the Nasdaq was jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong Yahoo earnings started to revive interest in
Internet stocks and money started to move that way, probably at the
expense of biotech,'' said Steve Burrill, of Burrill &AMP; Co., the
biotech investment firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, called last week's decline in biotech shares a ``much
needed pause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stocks couldn't continue going up as fast as they had
been,'' said McCamant, who thinks biotech will recover and continue
growing, albeit much more slowly than June's blistering pace.
</P>
<P>
   One of the factors that had fueled biotech's summer run was an
increasing flow of money into biotech mutual funds, as small
investors tried to catch some of the gains being registered by
biotech indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Adler, president of AMG Services, a firm that tracks mutual
fund money flows, said that during the past three weeks, investors
poured more than $680 million into biotech mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, biotech mutual funds attracted $353 million in
new funds, compared with the $388 million that flowed into
technology mutual funds. Although high tech drew more money, Adler
said the amount flowing into biotech was remarkable given that
high-tech funds are four times the size of the biotech mutual fund
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Whether investors now shun biotech, or take last week's retreat
as a buying opportunity, could be heavily influenced by Genentech
Inc.'s earnings report due out before the stock market opens today.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate the South San Francisco, Calif., biotech giant
will report earnings of between 27 cents and 32 cents a share
today, with the average falling at 29 cents. A good showing by
Genentech would boost the likelihood of a quick bounce for biotech,
while a disappointment could spark a sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech shares rose $7.56 Friday, a gain of 5 percent, to
close at $161.50, bucking the negative trend that caused more than
half of all biotech stocks to lose ground. Chiron Corp. of
Emeryville, Calif., also defied the downturn, gaining 31 cents to
close at $52.69.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead Sciences of Foster City, Calif., and Incyte Genomics of
Palo Alto, Calif., weren't so lucky. Shares in Gilead, which has a
flu drug on the market and is in late-stage clinical trials with an
AIDS treatment, lost $1.56 to close at $80.63. Stock in Incyte, one
of several firms selling gene databases, slipped $2.38 to end the
day at $91.13.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dietz, a biotech specialist with Pacific Growth Equities, a
San Francisco investment bank, said biotech stocks are likely to
seesaw for the rest of the summer, a traditionally slow season for
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But come fall, when scientific conferences give biotech firms a
chance to talk about their newest experimental drugs, he predicts
biotech stocks will heat up again, as happened last year at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
