<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-ABATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: COURTESY MATTERS IN BUG KILLING  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If someone offered to do a $250,000 job for
free, and to get it done in a day instead of several months, how
long would it take you to accept the offer?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if you're the United States government, and the job
happens to be the genetic analysis of the bacterium threatening
California's vineyards, the answer isn't so simple because
accepting the free offer could mean offending a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, I reported that state and federal officials
would collaborate with Brazilian scientists to sequence the genome
of the bacterium that causes Pierce's disease, a fly-borne
bacterial infection that clogs the plumbing of wine plants, causing
vines to wither and die.
</P>
<P>
   That deal looked like a winner at the time, because the
Brazilian scientists recently finished unraveling the genome of a
related bacterium that infects citrus crops in their country.
</P>
<P>
   But after learning that it might take the Brazilians several
months to complete the project, some wine industry executives
started looking for a faster way to get the data _ courtesy of the
Joint Genome Institute, a Department of Energy facility in Walnut
Creek, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   JGI is one of the five public labs that recently finished
sequencing the human genome. The facility is a gene-reading
factory, crammed with hundreds of instruments that now sit somewhat
idle, given that the big push on the human genome work is over.
</P>
<P>
   When the Energy Department scientists heard about the wine-bug
project through the scientific grapevine, they volunteered to do
the genetic analysis of the Pierce's disease bug, overnight and for
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be less than a day's work for us,'' said JGI deputy
director Trevor Hawkins, who was astonished to discover that
American authorities, led by the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
were reluctant to accept the offer for fear of offending the
Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   USDA officials took a diplomatic tone Friday when asked how they
planned to assuage Brazilian pride, without dismissing what seems
like an unbeatable offer closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are exploring the situation and trying to see how different
people can help out in understanding the disease,'' said USDA
spokeswoman Susan McAvoy.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian authorities did not respond to an e-mail requesting
comment.
</P>
<P>
   PROLEUKIN POSTSCRIPT: Last week I reported how stock in Chiron
Corp. rose after publication of a scientific article describing how
Chiron's Proleukin drug, which was originally approved to fight
certain cancers, seems to help AIDS patients by giving their immune
systems a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The day my story appeared I got a call from Kelly, a San
Francisco man with AIDS who got himself enrolled in an experimental
program to receive Proleukin as a supplement to his other AIDS
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   I knew Kelly from a story I wrote last year, when he was trying
to get Blue Shield to cover his Proleukin treatments. The insurance
company refused to pay for what is still an experimental therapy.
But Kelly was pleased to report that he had circumvented that
roadblock by enrolling in a clinical trial program in which Chiron
footed the $5,000 cost for a year's worth of Proleukin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving me an update on his situation _ ``I'm
still here,'' he said cheerily _ Kelly passed on this intelligence
about Proleukin's treatment regimen and side effects.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the drug through self-injection, over a period of five
days, and each time he gets flu and cold symptoms _ headaches,
chills, etc. _ which he controls with pain relievers and other
remedies. These symptoms clear up after a few days. Kelly isn't
sure if his symptoms are typical of other patients in the trial. In
any event, doctors reduced his Proleukin dosage to lessen the
fluish effects.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, the booster shots seem to be paying off. Kelly
e-mailed me records of his T-cell count. Doctors use blood tests to
count these disease-fighting cells, and gauge how far AIDS has gone
in attacking the immune system. The higher the T-cell count, the
healthier the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kelly began the Proleukin treatments, his T-cell counts
were hovering under 170, toward the worrisome end of the spectrum
though not immediately life-threatening. Since beginning his
Proleukin shots a year ago, Kelly's T-cell count has risen
steadily, and now stands around 345.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seems to be working for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly couldn't resist a jab at Blue Shield, pointing out that
the cost of the year's treatment is less than what it would cost
for a couple of days in the hospital, where he might have landed
had his T-cell count stayed at the lower levels.
</P>
<P>
   A Blue Shield spokesman noted that when Kelly's request for
payment was denied, outside medical experts advised the insurance
company that the immune system connection was unproven. Since then,
no other AIDS patient has asked Blue Shield to cover the cost of
Proleukin booster shots, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FIGHT: The Senate seems poised to approve a bill that would
prevent states and municipalities from enacting food labeling
requirements that did not conform to federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, S. 1155, has more than 30 co-sponsors,
including Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. It would stop
states from requiring manufacturers to label genetically modified
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of genetically engineered foods hope the Senate will
bring the bill to a floor vote and, if it passes, fold it into a
Senate-House conference committee, which could make it law.
Opponents of genetically engineered foods are concerned that
passage of this federal act would thwart their efforts to get
states like California to impose labeling requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Cohen, senior staff attorney for the Center for Science
in the Public Interest, said a vote on the measure could come at
any time.
</P>
<P>
   On a related front, opponents of genetically engineered foods
are still waiting for federal District Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly
to rule on a lawsuit challenging the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration's process for regulating genetically modified foods.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mendelson, an attorney with the Center for Food Safety, one
of the groups that brought the case, said it was a year ago last
week that final arguments were submitted. If successful, the
challenge could overturn the current regulatory process.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH PORK: A few weeks ago I reported that the biotech
industry was seeking three tax breaks from the California
Legislature. In the horse-trading that produced the final state
budget, the industry got two of the favors it had sought _ a boost
in the state's R&AMP;D tax credit from 12 to 15 percent, and an
increase in the amount of time firms can carry forward losses until
they are profitable and therefore need the deductions.
</P>
<P>
   The R&AMP;D credit really meant more to Silicon Valley than to
biotech, but the carry-forward provision was particularly important
to biotech firms, which can run in the red for a decade. The old
law allowed five- to eight-year carry-forwards, and biotech
interests were pleased that a bill carried by Assemblyman Ted
Lempert, D-San Carlos, extended that to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The third tax break sought by biotech didn't make it into this
year's budget. The vast majority of biotech firms lose money and so
tax breaks are meaningless. The red-ink firms would like to trade
certain tax breaks with the few biotech firms that do have earnings
_ and tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators were reluctant to embrace such a novel concept last
year, but lobbyists are nothing if not patient, and biotech
promoters will doubtless return to Sacramento next year in hopes of
convincing lawmakers that the state's biotech firms need and
deserve this additional break.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD READ: Alert Chronicle readers found a hole in my article
last week about a new technology that inactivates viruses and
bacteria in blood that is donated for transfusions. (``Pathogens
Glued Shut,'' July 10).
</P>
<P>
   The technology uses chemicals that seek out and bind to nucleic
acids _ the scientific name for the active molecules in DNA and
RNA.
</P>
<P>
   I avoid unfamiliar scientific terms wherever possible, so
instead of referring to nucleic acids, I described how the
technology worked on DNA, which is a double-strand molecule,
resembling a twisted ladder. The chemicals lock the two halves of
DNA together, preventing it from replicating and stopping the
infection.
</P>
<P>
   But, as several puzzled readers pointed out, some viruses are
made of RNA, a single-strand nucleic acid. So how could this
chemical process lock them up?
</P>
<P>
   As I should have explained last week, these blood-cleansing
chemicals handcuff RNA in a similar way. When RNA is between
replication cycles, it curls up like a garden hose. The chemicals
in the blood-cleaning process trap RNA in this curled state. Since
RNA has to uncurl to replicate, the process kills the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Writing is the art of simplification. In this case, however, I
oversimplified, as several readers _ including Gerry Hill, Patricia
Hamm, Marshall Dinowitz and Mina Davenport _ e-mailed me to point
out.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ORACLE-STOCKDIP-SFCHR     07-17 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-STOCKDIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ORACLE TAKES SOME HITS  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oracle Corp., the mammoth
database-softwaremaker, isn't exactly in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   But after a string of unusual announcements and some catch-up
maneuvers by a couple of competitors, some wonder whether the
Redwood Shores, Calif., firm is as invincible as it seemed a few
short months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The chief concern among those who follow Oracle is the loss of
its steady-at-the-helm president and chief operating officer, Ray
Lane. Late last month, Lane resigned after the company's flamboyant
chief executive Larry Ellison _ who has taken a more active role in
Oracle's day-to-day operations over the past year _ took over most
of Lane's remaining duties.
</P>
<P>
   Though most expected Lane's eventual departure, the move shocked
Wall Street and sent the company's stock down almost 10 percent in
the two days after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before Lane's abrupt resignation, Ellison confirmed
the company had hired investigators to look into groups with
potential ties to Microsoft, highlighting the high-stakes game
between the world's two most powerful software companies.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more.
</P>
<P>
   Though Oracle's fourth-quarter earnings surged 76 percent and
handily beat analysts' expectations, growth in its flagship
business _ database software _ didn't. Pair that with some new and
improved products from rivals, and some analysts question whether
Oracle is faltering just as Ellison is promising to boot Microsoft
from the No. 1 softwaremaker spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put it all together, there's a lot of tarnish on a
previously shiny software company,'' said Joshua Greenbaum, an
analyst at Berkeley, Calif.'s Enterprise Applications Consulting.
``In no way is Oracle dead, but it's not as pristine as it was two
months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle insists that the furor over Lane's departure and the
``Dumpster diving'' are overblown. It also says Ellison warned
analysts that the company would no longer offer steep discounts
late in the quarter, a policy that hurt fourth-quarter database
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an incredible run for the past 18 months, and it's
easy to take potshots at a company that's been on such a great
ride,'' said Oracle spokeswoman Jennifer Glass.
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts suspect there may be more than backlash _
and the spring correction in the tech sector _ behind the recent
dip in the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   For one, many saw Lane as Oracle's compass. Whereas Ellison is
the dreamer who can afford to be ``the gadfly, the fighter pilot,''
according to Greenbaum, many credit Lane with lending the company
professionalism and establishing relationships with big customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ray and Larry show worked well because there was a yin and
yang relationship there,'' Greenbaum said. ``Ellison is a
visionary; he's everything you want at the top of the company. But
he's not necessarily the person you want to have doing the
day-to-day operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that's exactly what Oracle needs as it tries to
tailor its software to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has changed, and the company's entire focus has shifted
into areas where Larry is reasonably the expert,'' said Bob
Austrian, an analyst at Bank of America. ``A year ago that wasn't
true. But today, Oracle is about vision and e-business software and
less about operations and services. Oracle is on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lane's departure will leave a void, said SG Cowen analyst
Andrew Brosseau.
</P>
<P>
   Lane ``understood industry dynamics well and was effective at
closing big deals,'' he said. ``That's probably more than anything
where they're going to miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now more than ever, it appears, the company needs Lane's
attention to detail and ability to execute on Ellison's often-brash
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Database software, the workhorse programs that corporations use
to collect and track hoards of data, has been Oracle's mainstay.
And in the past year, the segment has served Oracle extremely well
as more and more Internet-connected companies like Amazon.com look
to store information on sales and inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Oracle took it a step further, proclaiming _ loudly _
that its ``e-business suite'' of applications that automate
financial, human resources and other tasks would let any company
take advantage of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Investors listened and Oracle's stock price soared fourfold
since late last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's follow-through time. In May _ almost seven months late
_ the company released 11i, a suite of business applications that
sits on top of a company's database software.
</P>
<P>
   While the suite is an ``OK starting point, there are a variety
of pieces that they don't have yet,'' said David Yockelson, an
analyst at the Meta Group in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Although Oracle has been promising to be a one-stop shop for
e-business needs, Yockelson said the company falls short of that.
``Oracle's been saying it has everything for a long time _ and
they're not the only company that does that. But there is a
pattern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's stock is still up dramatically, compared with a year
ago, but it has fallen about 12 percent since earnings were
released June 20. Oracle stock closed Friday at $76.13, up 38
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that may stem from some of Oracle's competitors, who are
often quick to seize on, and publicize, any apparent chink in the
company's armor.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasanton, Calif.'s PeopleSoft last week announced PeopleSoft
8, what it calls the first ``pure'' Internet-based software for
managing customer service, manufacturing, accounting and other
operations. Though Oracle touts its business applications' roots in
the Internet, PeopleSoft officials and analysts say bits of Oracle
code still reside on the desktops of the employees using the
software.
</P>
<P>
   But Terilyn Palanca, a Giga Information Group analyst who worked
at Oracle in the late 1980s and early 1990s, says Oracle should be
less worried about PeopleSoft and more concerned about IBM Corp.'s
threat to its bread and butter. The Armonk, N.Y., firm has made a
major investment in database development. In addition, IBM's DB2
software can cost half of what an Oracle database costs, and the
company has a warmer, fuzzier relationship with customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a sweet time in the market for Oracle. Will
it last forever, who knows?'' Palanca said. ``If I were Larry and I
had this behemoth IBM sitting behind me, I'd be scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
