<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4054 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-CO     07-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-CORRECTING/UPDATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE, JOHNSON DESERVE THE BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 STATS-LBPT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have more questions than
Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   They have plenty of millionaires, thank you, but they have no
ready answers for any of the queries lying at their cleats. The
middle of July finds them not sinking in the National League West
as much as floating, bobbing on the surface and getting nowhere
fast. They could use a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   The longest winning streak of the season has been six games, and
that was two months ago. Since June 22, they are 8-13 and have seen
San Francisco zip by them in the division and the Angels take two
of three from them in the first post-All-Star series.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want perspective on the Dodgers' status, align
their record (46-44) alongside those of the financially-deprived
Expos (43-45) and Marlins (46-45). That sound you hear is your head
shaking in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult question facing the Dodgers may be, ``Where
does one start fixing things?'' It may be preferable from a fan's
perspective to start on the field, but Gary Sheffield and friends
have a lot less to do with the situation than one would think.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Malone and Davey Johnson are the fellows who put this team
together after Fox needed only six months to torch 41 years of
tradition and goodwill. As much as one may like reminding the
Foxies of this, it's been two years, more than enough time to chart
a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   The one blazed by the general manager and manager has gotten the
Dodgers nowhere. People inside the franchise know it and sides are
being taken, although a handful are bright enough to distance
themselves from both wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Daly, who casts the biggest shadow as the club's new CEO,
took a side this week when he said Malone's job was safe. It took
Johnson less than two days to start a campaign for his own job by
intimating he's being prepped as the fall guy.
</P>
<P>
   Daly has restored a lot of the team's credibility after becoming
a minority owner and being named CEO, but keeping Malone around
would test it. Malone hasn't made a single good move since becoming
GM in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Want a list?
</P>
<P>
   1. Publicly said he would deliver Felipe Alou as manager and
didn't, leading the Foxies to select Johnson even though he wasn't
Malone's second choice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Signed Devon White to a three-year contract even though the
outfielder would be 36 in 1999. White hit .268 last season and has
been injured most of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   3. Signed a 34-year-old pitcher, Kevin Brown, to a seven-year,
$105 million deal. Not only did it break the previous free-agent
ceiling, but it was $15 million more than the next best deal on the
table. Brown's a stud, but for how long?
</P>
<P>
   4. Traded a Gold Glove catcher, Charles Johnson (.302, 20 homers
in 2000) to the Mets for a catcher, Todd Hundley, coming off elbow
surgery. Hundley hit .207 last year, and while he's hitting .316
with 17 home runs in 2000, he's been ailing the last two months and
has thrown out only seven of 49 base stealers.
</P>
<P>
   5. Signed Carlos Perez, who had shoulder surgery in 1996 and one
winning season in his career, to a $15 million, three-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   6. Traded Dave Mlicki and Mel Rojas to Detroit for Robinson
Checo in a financially-motivated deal.
</P>
<P>
   7. Traded Raul Mondesi for Shawn Green in a deal suggested and
bartered by the agent for both players. Mondy's having a fine year
on a team (Toronto) in playoff contention. Green has played well
but he hasn't magically changed the standings.
</P>
<P>
   8. Traded a starting pitcher, Ismael Valdes, and the team's
second baseman and leadoff hitter, Eric Young, for a setup man,
Terry Adams, in another financially-motivated trade.
</P>
<P>
   In summation, he's been used by two agents, traded two starting
pitchers, signed two free agents in their late 30s to multiyear
deals, and retained and obtained two players with medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's just my opinion, but I don't keep Malone around waiting for
the ninth wonder of his world. The aggregate of all of these deals
has backed the team in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the eight highest-paid players on the team were
obtained or signed under Malone's watch, the only exception being
Sheffield, who renegotiated his deal after he was obtained in the
Mike Piazza deal. The only player on this list who was part of the
team at the start of the 1998 season is Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   The aggregate payroll of Brown, Sheffield, Green and Karros is
$45 million a year, and the years on their contracts make them
untradeable. Hundley, Jeff Shaw, Perez and White make another $20
million per year, and their age or ailments make them untradeable.
</P>
<P>
   This is why young players like Darren Dreifort and Adrian Beltre
are the only ones ever mentioned in trade talks, because they're
the only players other teams want or can afford.
</P>
<P>
   It's also why four rookies are on the roster (Eric Gagne, Alex
Cora, Matt Herges, Paul LoDuca), and why four non-roster players
(Mike Fetters, Chad Kreuter, Kevin Elster, Geronimo Berroa) made
the team, and why journeymen like F.P. Santangelo, Jim Leyritz and
Gregg Olson are still employed.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the Dodgers' roster hasn't looked this bad since
the years between the Koufax-Drysdale and the Lopes-Garvey-Cey
eras.
</P>
<P>
   All this shouldn't be viewed as tacit support for Johnson. The
manager certainly deserves some consideration for being dealt a bad
hand, and his visit to a hospital Sunday to check out an irregular
heartbeat is surely job-related.
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't lived up to his reputation as a can-do manager. He
played his own role in Raul Mondesi's departure, supported the
Hundley trade because he was desperate for a left-handed hitter,
vexed a few pitchers on the team with some of his decisions, and
didn't make Orel Hershiser feel at home in his bid to keep pitching
at 41.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers say they want to be a player in the Alex Rodriguez
sweepstakes, but is there room for another $15 million-plus salary
at the top of roster on a team that's already out balance? Plus, do
they really need another middle-of-the-order hitter?
</P>
<P>
   Worse, what if Rodriguez announces he doesn't want to play for
the Dodgers because he's not sure the team can win? Now there's a
$64,000 question I don't want answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
