<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> no timestamp </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4056 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     07-17 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRUNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BREAKS NEWS BLACKOUT TO VOICE OPTIMISM ON MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to update top of story with remarks by Clinton; story is now
an added starter on The New York Times front page)  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton violated a White House news
blackout at the Camp David summit meeting on Sunday night when he
told the New York Daily News that he was ``more optimistic'' about
reaching an agreement than when the talks opened six days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the comments after he was informed of the
opportunity to call the Daily News and answer questions about
allegations in a book that his wife Hillary made anti-Semitic
remarks more than two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, P.J. Crowley, said that after talking
about Mrs. Clinton, the president answered two questions about the
Middle East summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`m more optimistic than I was when they got there,'' the
president said. ``We might make it. I don't know. God, it's hard.
It's like nothing I've ever dealt with, all the negotiations with
the Irish, all the stuff I've done with the Palestinians before,
and with the Israelis, the Balkans at Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, the president said: ``What's
really troubling is they know if they make a peace agreement, half
of their constitutients will have to be angry at them for a while.
But I would be totally misleading if I said I had an inkling that a
deal is at hand. That's just not true. But we're slogging.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was going on his scheduled trip to Japan on
Wednesday, Clinton replied: ``I hope so. I'm going to do my best to
finish here.''
</P>
<P>
   As the scheduled departure for that trip begins to crowd in on
the Camp David summit talks, the stream of chatter by Israelis and
Palestinians on the outside who say they know what is going on
inside rose steadily on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And what they say _ some of it gloomy, some of it upbeat, and
all of it calculated to influence opinion back home in the Middle
East _ is that it is still too early to tell whether there will be
an agreement at all or, if there is one, what kind of agreement it
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it is impossible to know where it is heading,'' said
an official who has spoken to participants by telephone. ``That's
the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   A common assumption was that it would not be clear until
Tuesday, the eve of Clinton's scheduled departure for Japan,
whether the talks are ``going in the right direction or not,'' the
official added.
</P>
<P>
   Only then would the White House decide whether the talks were
ripe enough to warrant keeping Clinton at Camp David and sending
Vice President Al Gore to the meeting in Okinawa of the leaders of
the world's major industrial nations. Clinton is scheduled to leave
on Wednesday to join other leaders there and meet the Russian
president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been saying since the opening of the summit
meeting that Clinton would go to Okinawa. But in the lead-up to
Camp David, and in private, Clinton administration officials have
said that, for the president, the Okinawa trip was not necessarily
written in stone.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it is still premature to assess whether there will be
any kind of accord is that, so far, there has been no real test of
wills, according to those who have spoken to participants. Arafat
and Barak have not yet been through a major blowup on the substance
of the issues, the officials said. Those issues are the most
nettlesome separating the two sides, including borders, water
rights, the fate of Palestinian refugees and what to do about
Jerusalem, which both Israelis and Palestinians claim as their
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Only if a ``big crisis'' occurred _ a threat to walk out, a
defiant refusal to compromise on an issue _ could it be known
whether there was going to be a breakdown or a breakthrough, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently there was what one official called a ``small crisis''
involving Arafat when he was presented with some proposals on
resolving the status of Jerusalem. The Palestinians let it be known
that Arafat threatened to leave because the proposals, apparently
presented by the Americans, were too close to the Israeli public
position.
</P>
<P>
   But one Palestinian official said the flare-up appeared to be
tactical. If he is to compromise, Arafat, who has insisted for
decades that East Jerusalem must be the capital of a Palestinian
state, could not afford to stay hidden at Camp David and then
emerge having deviated significantly from his stance, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, where tens of thousands of demonstrators marched in
Rabin Square in Tel Aviv against proposals that would allow some
settlements to remain inside a Palestinian state, there was a flow
of gloomy talk.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister, David Levy, who refused to come to the
summit meeting with Barak, said the gaps between the parties
remained as wide as ever. The justice minister, Yossi Beilin, who
tends to be less harsh in his judgments, told Israeli radio, ``It
is hard at this point to give some kind of impression of optimism
more than yesterday, or the day before yesterday, because there has
been no breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the mayor, Ehud Olmert, held a meeting at City
Hall to express concern about the future of the city. Eli Yishair,
the leader of the Shas Party, which quit Barak's government just
before the prime minister's departure for Camp David, told the
gathering: ``The president of the United States has to understand
that here, the people of Israel are mostly united. Most of the
people are against dividing Jerusalem. Most of the people are for a
united Jerusalem under Israeli sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cabinet minister, Haim Ramon, again spoke out about Jerusalem
on Sunday, sending a warning that concessions on the city were
impossible and that, as he has often stated, the future status of
Jerusalem should be decided at another time.
</P>
<P>
   And in keeping with this fairly stern line from the home front,
Israel radio reported that the Israeli delegation at Camp David
believed that Palestinian officials were spreading upbeat
interpretations about the talks in order to avoid blame for a
breakdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
