<HEADLINE>
KREUTER CONSIDERS SUING CHICAGO FAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chad Kreuter's eight-game suspension is over, but
the Dodgers catcher isn't ready to forgive and forget in regards to
the May 16 incident at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter said Sunday he is considering filing a lawsuit against
the Chicago man who allegedly struck him in the head and took his
cap, which ignited a brawl with fans in the stands and led to mass
suspensions and fines for Dodgers players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter, who has not retained a lawyer or discussed the matter
with agent Scott Boras, said he would sue the man to recover the
cost of the team's fines. Kreuter received the stiffest punishment,
a $5,000 fine and an eight-game suspension, which ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will definitely seek him out and make sure that he is held
accountable,'' Kreuter said. ``He should be responsible for each
and every fine that was leveled on myself and my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone into hiding, but he will resurface, and when we find
him, he'll find himself in a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   He's back: Teammates cowered and covered their faces in mock
fear as Mark Grudzielanek grinned sheepishly and walked to his
locker in the Dodgers' clubhouse Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who had missed the previous six games with a
mysterious viral infection, pinch hit in the seventh inning and
struck out. He said he might be able to return to the starting
lineup today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a (heck) of a week,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I really
felt like jumping out of a window for a while there.''
</P>
<P>
   The illness came at an unfortunate time for Grudzielanek, who
had rebounded from a slow offensive start to lift his batting
average over .300 at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora has been a capable defensive replacement at second
base, but the Dodgers miss Grudzielanek's bat at the second spot in
the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek has been more concerned about being able to eat
solid foods, which he finally accomplished Friday. He estimated a
loss of 8-10 pounds because of the illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it was kind of scary, because I'd never experienced
anything like that before,'' Grudzielanek said. ``The doctors
didn't know what it was, so I was afraid it might be serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was 90 years old. I couldn't even get out of
bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Late scratch: F.P. Santangelo, scheduled to start in center
field, was removed from the lineup because of a contusion on his
left hand, which he suffered Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cora was moved to the leadoff spot and Todd Hollandsworth
started in center field. Santangelo pinch hit in the eighth inning
Sunday and grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Todd Hundley (fractured thumb) took batting
practice Sunday and might return to the starting lineup today. ...
A baseball rarity occurred Sunday, when catchers Paul LoDuca and
Jason Kendall both batted in the No.2 spot in their teams' batting
order. ... Center fielder Devon White, on the disabled list since
May 5 with a partial tear in his left rotator cuff, participated in
a special batting practice session with Dodgers coach Rick Dempsey
before the game and could be activated later this week. ...
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Gregg Olson, sidelined since mid-April with a strained
right forearm, walked one and struck out one in a scoreless inning
for Triple-A Albuquerque on Saturday night. ... Starting pitcher
Carlos Perez began his five-game suspension Sunday for the Wrigley
Field incident. The Dodgers are expected to recall Mike Judd from
Albuquerque to start Tuesday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
