<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' JOHNSON HOSPITALIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers' tumultuous season took another
dramatic turn Sunday morning when manager Davey Johnson was
hospitalized due to dizziness caused by an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 57, remains at Centinela Hospital in Inglewood, where
doctors await test results to determine the cause of his
accelerated heart rate.
</P>
<P>
   Team physician Dr. Michael F. Mellman stressed that Johnson did
not have a heart attack and ``is safe, and not in any danger,'' but
could not offer a timetable for Johnson's return. Bench coach Jim
Tracy will manage the team on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I recall, Davey went through a similar situation four or
five years ago,'' said Mellman, who could not recall the specifics
of Johnson's medical history. ``We'll know a lot more in the next
day or two, but until then I can't comment on his recovery time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellman said he received a phone call Sunday morning from
Johnson, who complained of discomfort in his chest. On Mellman's
advice, Johnson's wife, Susan, drove him from their La Canada
Flintridge home to a hospital in Verdugo Hills at approximately 9
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's future with the Dodgers, who are just two games over
.500 after Sunday's victory over Pittsburgh, has been questioned
recently, leading to talk Sunday about whether rumors about his
status may have contributed to Johnson's health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I talked to him, a few days ago, he was down,''
Dodgers general managing partner and CEO Bob Daly said. ``He thinks
the team should be doing a lot better too. We're all feeling
pressure over this.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our manager, and we need him desperately. This is not
like losing a pitcher for a day. We need our leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, who last managed in 1994 with Montreal's Triple-A team in
Ottawa, held two closed-door meetings with his players before
Sunday's game as the Dodgers attempted to maintain some sense of
normalcy amid the confusion and concern for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shocked,'' reliever Jeff Shaw said. ``But from
what I understand, this might be something that just flared up on
him and it's not all that serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's still scary, because he had to go to the hospital.
Any time you have to go to the hospital, you know it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have been through this sort of thing before,
although not many of the current players were around in 1996 when
then-manager Tom Lasorda suffered a heart attack and subsequently
retired to take a front-office job.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Dodgers have already dealt with a bizarre brawl with
Wrigley Field fans in May, in additional to various player
injuries, but several team members talked about gaining a sense of
perspective from Johnson's health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all very concerned about Davey and his condition,'' said
bullpen coach Rick Dempsey, one of Johnson's closest friends in the
organization. ``As much as he tries to tell us that (the team's
struggles) doesn't bother him, it does. It bothers all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the game a long time, probably longer than
anybody here, and I've never seen a manager better than him. I
learn something new from him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers remained hopeful that Johnson's absence could serve
as a rallying point for a team in search of some type of spark.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game, in which the Dodgers rallied with a five-run
eighth inning, was a first step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we can pick up the slack and start playing the way
we're capable of playing,'' Dempsey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
