<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS STAGE INSPIRED RALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took the Dodgers eight innings to craft their
get-well gift to manager Davey Johnson, but the finished product
was quite a thing to behold.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson in the hospital, undergoing tests for an irregular
heartbeat, the Dodgers rallied for six runs in the eighth and beat
the Pittsburgh Pirates 7-3 in front of 34,116 Sunday night at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' said right fielder Shawn Green, who singled and
scored in the eighth, ``is to get on a hot streak and make things a
lot more pleasant for Davey, and for us too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers achieved their goal, at least temporarily, and
avoided falling to .500 for the first time since early April, but
they needed some late heroics to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers trailing 3-1, catcher Paul LoDuca led off the
eighth with a walk, moved to second on a wild pitch and to third on
Green's single, and scored on Gary Sheffield's single to left.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the flood gates, and the Dodgers hammered Pittsburgh
reliever Jeff Williams (2-2), who entered the game in relief of
Jason Christiansen after Green's single but couldn't record an out.
</P>
<P>
   The big hit came when Todd Hollandsworth singled to right with
the bases loaded, and Williams was finally pulled when Kevin Elster
followed with a run-scoring single. Chris Peters got the next two
outs but gave up the final run on a RBI single by LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of the rally, however, may have come an inning
earlier. Pittsburgh starter Jimmy Anderson allowed just two hits
through six innings but gave up an unearned run and allowed four
baserunners in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Dodgers interim manager Jim Tracy sent up Mark
Grudzielanek as a pinch hitter. Grudzielanek, who had missed the
previous six games with a viral infection, was still weak, but his
.303 batting average no doubt convinced Pittsburgh manager Gene
Lamont to make a pitching change.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek struck out, but the Dodgers fared much better
against the Pirates' weak bullpen than they did against Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anderson) threw a great game,'' Green said, ``so it was great
to come back and score (six) in the eighth. That gave us a big
boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, normally the Dodgers' bench coach, also made a gutsy
decision in the sixth when he stuck with starter Eric Gagne. Wil
Cordero led off the inning with a home run to give Pittsburgh a 3-0
lead, and the Pirates loaded the bases with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   With Anderson at the plate, Tracy stayed with Gagne, who came
back from a 3-1 count and induced a ground ball to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that other than the eighth, that was the key to the
game,'' Tracy said. ``He wound up getting the strikeout and keeping
it at 3-0. A walk or a base hit might have taken the wind out of
our sails.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne allowed six hits and three runs in six innings, but Matt
Herges, Terry Adams (4-3) and Mike Fetters each pitched a scoreless
inning of relief to help set up and preserve the rally.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, all of the thoughts centered on Johnson, whose
condition will be better determined today when team physicians
examine the results of the manager's tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey is a very special person to me,'' Sheffield said. ``He's
like a father figure. He showed me a lot of respect from the
beginning, and I show him a lot of respect in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about him being rushed to the hospital ... I had
to pull over and say a little prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can turn this thing around, win some ballgames and make him
feel a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
