<SLUG> BC-CAR-STREET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FOOT NOTE TO RAUDMAN'S WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A broken left foot isn't conducive to an auto
racer staying comfortable on a road course with constant braking
required.
</P>
<P>
   Ask NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series veteran Craig Raudman,
who broke his foot in an April 29 NASCAR Winston West accident at
Fontana's California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The crash kept the 38-year-old Bakersfield resident out of his
car for almost all of the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Raudman, bum foot and all, handled a brutal L.A. Street Race
course to win Sunday's Southwest Series event at Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing extensive physical therapy, Raudman ran half of
last month's Southwest race at Sears Point before excruciating pain
forced him to vacate the driver's seat in favor of his brother
Chris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard. I don't want to see anybody driving my race car.
It's really frustrating to have a hurt foot. I just can't believe
what it does to you,'' said Raudman, whose win Sunday was the
eighth of his Southwest tour career.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring his injuries healed, Raudman overcame a one-mile
course that took its toll on the field. Starting fourth, he slipped
past Eric Holmes during a lap 76 yellow-flag dash to the
start-finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Matt Crafton straddled the rear bumper of
Raudman's Chevrolet Monte Carlo but couldn't make a pass over the
final eight of 125 total laps. Raudman's margin of victory was two
seconds over Crafton.
</P>
<P>
   Raudman's reward for surviving a track that brought out 11
caution flags for 49 laps was a Southwest Series-record-winning
purse of $18,175.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun because you can drive these tracks so hard,'' said
Raudman, one of the tour's top road course performers. ``I enjoy
the shifting and the hard braking and the turning.''
</P>
<P>
   Others didn't have such a positive review of the one-mile track
that circles the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven of 36 cars finished on the lead lap and 20 completed
the race. Agua Dulce's Bob Lyon, despite brake problems and a
collision with Jeff Hill on pit row, limped home in 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the track was really poor. There's just some
constraints with tightness and curves. Unless you want to tear down
part of the Coliseum and the Sports Arena ... you're not going to
change that,'' Lyon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show was just doomed. I think NASCAR fans ... deserve a
better show.''
</P>
<P>
   Pole sitter Greg Pursley of Newhall led the first 31 laps and
had a strong car but like many of the participants was a victim of
bad breaks. Pursley scraped the wall in turn four of lap 91, pitted
but came back to place 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even pushing it yet. I mean we had a fast car,'' said
Pursley, who has yet to win here despite starting on the pole the
past three years. ``I was trying to save it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saugus' Sean Woodside, fourth in points, had similar rear-axle
trouble that forced him to take a provisional starting spot
Saturday. He finished 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills' Nick Joanides came in 10th, Quartz Hill's Frank
Maronski Jr. 15th and Frazier Park's MK Kanke 21st.
</P>
<P>
   In other L.A. Street Race events:
</P>
<P>
   Ultra Wheels Spec Trucks: Vince Little of Clovis passed points
leader Mike David of Modesto on lap 15 to post his fifth win of the
season in a 29-lap non-points race. Santa Clarita's Steve McCord
was seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Race Series: Harry Rady of La Jolla won the 36-lap race.
Steve Cross of Hidden Hills finished second.
</P>
<P>
   North-South Pro Trucks: Ron Swartzbaugh of Vista took the
checkered flag in the 28-lap race win his second consecutive L.A.
Street Race.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra Cup Series: Dan Luckow of Tarzana finished second to
Dennis Olthoff of North Carolina. Jay Parille of Sherman Oaks was
11th in an 11-lap race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
