<SLUG> BC-SWIM-EVANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING FAVORITES TAKE CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Life in the pool returned to normal Sunday for the
final day of the Janet Evans Invitational. No upstart teens upset
any world-record holders.
</P>
<P>
   Just the world-class swimmers taking care of business in this,
the last major meet before the U.S. Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Krayzelburg of USC, the world-record holder in the 100-
meter backstroke, won easily and set a meet record in 54.60
seconds, breaking his two-year mark.
</P>
<P>
   And Jenny Thompson of Stanford, who hasn't lost a national or
international 100-meter butterfly race since 1997, continued her
streak by setting a meet record during qualifying, then winning the
event in a slightly slower time.
</P>
<P>
   It was Krayzelburg who made big news on Friday when he lost the
200 backstroke - another event in which he holds the world record -
to 16-year-old Aaron Peirsol.
</P>
<P>
   Peirsol was entered in the 100 on Sunday, but he never was a
factor. Krayzelburg got off to a strong start and won going away in
a time one second off his world record.
</P>
<P>
   Peirsol broke badly and finished sixth in 56.78.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are entitled to one bad swim,'' Krayzelburg said.
``I'm still where I need to be. I'm really happy with this time.
Obviously, I was a bit down on Friday, but you have to put a race
like that behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding two world records has put pressure on Krayzelburg. He
knows it but can't do much about it, since he knows swimmers are
judged by what they do in the Olympics. Krayzelburg never has swam
in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't win two gold medals as an individual, my career
will be very disappointing,'' he said. ``I got a shot in a relay,
so if I don't win three gold medals, I'll be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's 100 butterfly streak dates to the 1997 Summer
Nationals, although she doesn't know how many meets that covers.
</P>
<P>
   What she knows is she broke her year-old meet record when she
qualified in 58.37 seconds. Later, she won the event in 58.48.
</P>
<P>
   She thought she could have finished under 58 seconds had she not
taken in a mouthful of water as she approached the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she has no complaints. She set an American record on
Friday in the 100 freestyle, finished a close second to Dara Torres
in the 50 freestyle and set a meet record in the 100 butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there was that fourth-place finish in the 200 freestyle, but
that's her off event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meet was really good for me mentally,'' Thompson said. ``I
think it's a great springboard for what will happen at trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Another swimmer excited about the trials is Cal's Staciana
Stitts, who won the 100 butterfly in 1:09.49, just .33 slower than
her personal best; and in finishing fifth in the 200 individual
medley, she swam a personal-best 2:19.15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right on my best times, and I'm not even rested yet,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In other events, Westlake graduate Jason Weber, now swimming at
Brown and representing Conejo-Simi Aquatics, finished fourth in the
100 backstroke bonus final. He was the top qualifier for the bonus
final after swimming 59.70, but he slowed to 59.83 in the final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
