r s BC-BKN-SUMMER-NOTES-LBPT     07-17 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER LEAGUE IS TRAINING GROUND FOR REFEREES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ ``TWEET''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Nakasone raises her hand. She takes a look at the two
players on the ground in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``White four-zero,'' says Nakasone who has put both hands on her
waste to signal a blocking foul.
</P>
<P>
   While the players on the floor are looking to improve, Nakasone,
a WNBA and NCAA official from Costa Mesa, is at the Summer Pro
League working on her officiating game. She's one of 27 referees
attending a 13 day officiating camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to learn a little bit more about the game and to
better my skills,'' said Nakasone, who has been a referee for six
years, and is an NCAA and WNBA referee.
</P>
<P>
   Referees in the camp at the Pyramid range from NCAA, CBA and
WNBA levels. Aside from becoming better, most of the referees are
hoping to impress and move into the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   That's not easy. There are only 60 NBA referee jobs and a
handful are filled each year. Camps, like the one at the Pyramid,
provide a major opportunity for upcoming referees to give an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is bring out candidates who are in our program for
training,'' said Lee Jones, supervisor of officials for the NBA.
``They can only get better from coming to our camp. They are trying
to come up to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the camp go through class in the morning and work the
games at the summer league. Up in a corner of the Pyramid, current
NBA officials watch the game with one official critiquing the play
as it happens.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the officials watch the tape to see how they can
improve.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of things Jones, who was an official for 25
years, looks at to evaluate an official: physical fitness, running
ability up and down the court, and presentation on the court. He
said that making good calls also fits into the evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have college officials who are trying to get into the
league,'' said Lee Jones, supervisor of officials for the NBA. ``We
want to see if they fit in with our program.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakasone played basketball at Cypress Junior College and then
entered into officiating. She began at the high school level and
then progressed up to the NCAA and to the WNBA this season.
</P>
<P>
   While officials like Jones are watching, her goal each game is
not to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope to apply the rules in a fair manner,'' Nakasone said,
``so both teams have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Officiating is) a challenge because no game is the same. It's
a challenge in management skills.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT KOBE OR MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   There were rumors that Kobe Bryant and/or Magic Johnson would
show up for the game between Bryant's Olimpia Milano and Johnson's
team on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case and most of the fans emptied the Pyramid
before the game reached halftime. Magic's team won 101-90.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHTOWER
</P>
<P>
   Cory Hightower finished with a team-high 20 points against the
Clippers Sunday. Hightower, who entered the NBA out of junior
college, scored many of his points late in the game but continued
to impress offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost to the Clippers 105-91.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKS WITH CLIPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Sean Rooks, acquired on draft day by the Clippers for Eric
Murdock, played in his first game with the team. Rooks was playing
out some of the summer rust and finished with six points and eight
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean brings eight or nine years experience to a very young
team,'' said Clipper coach Dennis Johnson. ``That is going to bring
maturity. He is going to say things that a coach might not be able
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of a coach, there is still no word on the Clipper
coaching vacancy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
