<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTSPOT-AZR </SLUG>
  
Land &HT;    BC-HOTSPOT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DEVELOPERS COVET EAST VALLEY HOT SPOT(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CHRIS FISCUS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 45,000-plus acres are so far east they aren't even shown on
some aerial maps of the Phoenix area. Yet the desert land east of
Maricopa County on the road to Globe is already on the radar
screens of developers.
</P>
<P>
   The huge chunk with views of the Superstitions and room for tens
of thousands of homes may become the next East Valley housing hot
spot. When developed, it could consume more land than Washington,
D.C. One real estate analyst suggests the remote area about 35
miles southeast of downtown Phoenix could eventually resemble
sprawling residential communities such as Desert Ridge in northeast
Phoenix or Anthem along Interstate 17 in north Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   And all this at a time when much of the development in the
Phoenix area seems headed to the north and northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blank canvas just waiting to be painted,'' said Stanley
Paul Cook, who monitors Arizona real estate for Landiscor Aerial
Information. ``It's the next logical leap in the development
cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Land Department, which owns the site, agrees. It
hasn't decided when to sell off most of the land, but interested
developers already call. And one has taken the first bite.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson International has applied with the state to purchase
about 1,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Developers, analysts and the Land Department said the area is
attractive because it's close to freeways and to major East Valley
employers. It's also near a large shopping mall, Superstition
Springs Center, and has mountain views. And the land likely will be
cheaper because it is so far out.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said some of it could be developed within five years.
</P>
<P>
   The land is east of the Pinal County line and south of U.S. 60
as it curves toward Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson International plans to buy about 1,080 acres roughly
bounded by Baseline and Guadalupe roads, Ironwood Drive and
Tomahawk Road.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of the Phoenix area's growth will go to north of
Phoenix and northwest of Phoenix, builders also will continue to go
farther and farther east.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our members are looking beyond Maricopa County,'' said
Connie Wilhelm, president of the Home Builders Association of
Central Arizona, which includes the Phoenix area. ``It's a logical
progression.''
</P>
<P>
   As the development continues, she said, much of it will be on
lands like the 45,000 acres in the far East Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, our future for development is state trust land.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Chris.Fiscus(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-7942.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
