<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-FINGER-AZR &LR;      07-17 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINGER-AZR </SLUG>
  
S &HT;    BC-FINGER-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW LAW REQUIRES TEACHERS' PRINTS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By LORI BAKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of Arizona teachers and administrators will have to
submit their fingerprints for criminal checks before renewing their
state certificates under a new law that takes effect Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new law will create a safer environment for children,''
said Craig Emanuel, chief investigator for the state Board of
Education's certification division. ``I've surveyed all 50 states
and few have such a tough requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law, which will affect about 45,000 Arizona educators,
requires anyone who applies for a new certificate or who is
renewing one to be fingerprinted. Those files will be kept in a
computer so the state Department of Public Safety can be alerted if
an educator is arrested for any of a number of specific offenses.
DPS will then notify the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has required fingerprinting of school employees since
1990, but those who already had certificates were exempt. In
addition, DPS only began keeping fingerprints in computer files
since August and those files include no one who already had a
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of different offenses would prevent an applicant from
holding a fingerprint clearance card, including incest, child
abuse, aggravated assault, driving under the influence, domestic
violence, writing a bad check, shoplifting and forgery. In some
cases, the applicant can appeal to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an obligation to find out if there is anything out
there that we don't already know about,'' said Panfilo Contreras,
executive director of the Arizona School Boards Association.
``School districts will have to use some judgment about whether the
offenses will affect the performance of the individuals to do their
job.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes about a month for the national criminal check to be
completed so educators are encouraged to apply for certificate
renewal a few months before it expires.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another new law that took effect earlier this year
providing reciprocity for teacher applicants from 19 states that
have local and national fingerprint checks like Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the certification division of the
Arizona State Board of Education at (602) 542-4367.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Lori.Baker(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-7120.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4115 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LIBRARY-AZR &LR;      07-17 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARY-AZR </SLUG>
  
Libraries &HT;    BC-LIBRARY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    LIBRARIES BEGINNING TO JOIN COMPUTER REVOLUTION(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BETTY BEARD(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing declines in circulation and tough competition from the
Internet, libraries throughout the Valley are turning to new ways
to attract users.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, the bastions of books are using computer age
techniques. Some have begun offering electronic books. Others offer
the use of free computers and Internet access. The Phoenix Central
Library is even planning to give teens a rockin' computer center,
with loud music if they want.
</P>
<P>
   At some libraries, people just aren't checking out as many books
as they used to. In Tempe, where circulation fell 7 percent in the
past year, Director Teri Metros concedes she's a bit concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're still checking out a million items a year. We're
just in a time of great transition. You can get depressed or
excited about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa and Scottsdale libraries also reported circulation declines
of 2 or 3 percent over the past year. Circulation at Phoenix
libraries has increased. It has also risen at Chandler and
Glendale, but directors attribute that in part to new branches and
the growth of their cities.
</P>
<P>
   But while people are checking out fewer books, they're
definitely checking more into library computers. Almost 600,000
Mesa residents logged on at their libraries over the past year, an
rise of 300-plus percent.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Clements, a Kentucky amateur photographer vacationing in
Mesa, is one of several who stopped in at the Main Library in Mesa
last week to check e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a bunch of free e-mail sites on the Internet,'' he
said. He added that not all libraries offer access and you have to
shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Erma Salas of Mesa has used public computers to do genealogical
research.
</P>
<P>
   She also represents other common library computer users -
parents who take their kids, so everyone gets to use a computer.
Her son, David, 14, checked out winners of the National Academic
League, in which he participated at Carson Junior High, on one
computer. His sister, Evonne, 12, sat at another, checking details
of the (beginitalic)Survivors (enditalic)TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Moore, 65, of Mesa, has a home computer but prefers to
use the library's for e-mail because ``I'm so unsure about issues
of privacy and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking three two-hour computer classes at the library, she
was venturing out on her own, researching a medical problem {ndash}
another common use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeane Widom, Glendale Library director, said books can no
longer keep up with the Internet in some areas, especially in
medicine, legal advice and business(beginitalic).
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic) Magazine articles are generally available on
computer databases for five to a dozen years back.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation of children's books remain strong, and adults are
still flocking to libraries and joining waiting lists for fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for print is still out there. We can't begin to
supply the number of bestsellers,'' Mesa Library Director Pat
Hansel said.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) (enditalic) If electronic books take off,
libraries could see their fiction circulation go down. too. But
some libraries are going there anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe and Scottsdale libraries are offering card-holders access
to NetLibrary, a service offering about 1,500 non-fiction books.
When card-holders ``check out'' an electronic book, they don't
download it to their computer but get access to it for a day or
longer instead.
</P>
<P>
   Widom said Glendale libraries passed up e-books for now because
of the expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bestsellers are usually the things people want to read on and
off and they want to curl up with. That's not conducive to
e-books,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mesa Libraries soon plan to offer some Rocket E-Books,
which are about the size of a regular paperback book. Each one can
hold about half a dozen books, and there's a growing number of
fiction titles available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real readable,'' said Hansel, who has been testing one.
``I was surprised at how much I enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the advantages is that you can read {hellip} with the
lights off if you're in bed with someone who wants the lights off.
And there's a lot more titles available than there were just six
months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Williams, 25, a network analyst assistant at the Mesa
Library, was enthusiastic about the Rocket E-Book he tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that as it gets cheaper, it could be used in
schools. Instead of carrying {hellip}five or six textbooks, you
would just carry one.''
</P>
<P>
   As libraries give people more reasons to use computers, some
librarians wonder what where it will all lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more people get personal computers and get savvy, perhaps
we'll get less traffic. I certainly hope that's not true,'' said
Rosemary Nelson, administrator of the Central Phoenix Library.
</P>
<P>
   But Widom said, ``I don't think libraries will be out of work
for a long time because people need help with research. {hellip} A
lot of students don't have the patience we do. It's helpful to have
someone walk you through it instead of working on your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libraries will stay, but they will change.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Betty.Beard(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-7982.
</P>
<P>
   &AMP;lt;/default&AMP;gt; Tim Koors/The Arizona RepublicBrandon Williams
of the Mesa Library was enthusiastic about the Rocket E-Book. The
small device can store several books and will soon be available for
patrons to check out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
