</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 23) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BONE BY BONE &LR;  By Peter Matthiessen. (Vintage International,
$14.) The last of three novels about the life and times of Edgar J.
Watson _ cane planter, entrepreneur and mass murderer _ recounts
his conquest of Florida's Gulf Coast, an obsession with echoes in
the imperialistic impulses of a growing America. ``This is a work
of genuine dignity,'' Sven Birkerts wrote in The New York Times
Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLONE AGE: Adventures in the New World of Reproductive
Technology &LR;  By Lori B. Andrews (Owl/Holt, $15.) A lawyer traces her
career as an expert in the legal and moral aspects of assisted
reproduction from the birth of the first test-tube baby in 1978 to
the threshold of the clone age. ``Hers is a fine and readable
book,'' John R.G. Turner wrote last year. ``She has a wonderful dry
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TURN OF THE CENTURY &LR;  By Kurt Andersen. (Delta, $14.95.) This
sprawling comedy of millennial manners revolves around a nomadic
power couple _ a hypersuccessful Silicon Alley CEO and a struggling
television producer _ at play in the infotainment economy of New
York. Andersen ``wins back terrain for the novel that has been
ceded to new media, demonstrating that the novel is as alive and as
nimble as its high-tech competitors,'' Po Bronson wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CLEARING IN THE DISTANCE: Frederick Law Olmsted and America
in the 19th Century &LR;  By Witold Rybczynski. (Touchstone/Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $15.) The suburban visionary who designed New York's
Central Park and other monuments of green is portrayed as a humble
man with little formal training who believed in the restorative
power of landscape for ordinary citizens. Last year the reviewer
Suzannah Lessard called this an ``excellent biography'' that is
``thorough and respectful, yet easeful in a way that is reminiscent
of Olmsted himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOUGH, TOUGH TOYS FOR TOUGH, TOUGH BOYS &LR;  By Will Self. (Grove,
$12.) The killing of a fly imagined as blood sport. A Londoner who
finds a giant rock of crack cocaine under his house. These
outlandish stories both amuse and horrify as they render everyday
reality plastic and absurd. Last year the reviewer Jonathan Lethem
admired Self's ``vibrantly caustic prose and his anarchic and
florid satirical premises.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BYRON: Child of Passion, Fool of Fame &LR;  By Benita Eisler.
(Vintage, $18.) According to this biography, the poet was both an
arrogant English patrician and a prodigious libertine whose
devotion to sexual freedom got him into a world of trouble. ``The
seesawing moods and volatile allegiances of Byron ... are reported
with sensitive understanding,'' Claude Rawson said in 1999. The
book ``astutely identifies links between Byron's defiance of
prevailing moral codes and his political radicalism.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REAL WILD WEST: The 101 Ranch and the Creation of the
American West &LR;  By Michael Wallis. (St. Martin's Griffin, $21.95.)
The 101 Ranch, a vast private spread founded after the Civil War
that once covered nearly 110,000 acres in northeastern Oklahoma,
helped to shape popular perceptions of the American frontier for
many years. Wallis ``is the first writer to tie together the 101
Ranch's many stories,'' Allen Barra wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EARTH SHALL WEEP: A History of Native America &LR;  By James
Wilson (Grove, $16) is not so much a survey of Indian cultures as
it is a study of the calamitous impact of white conquest on
indigenous societies and a dissection of the many myths generated
by the conquerors. Last year the reviewer Richard E. Nicholls
called this a ``carefully researched and wide-ranging narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEMENTO MORI &LR;  By Muriel Spark. (New Directions, $11.95.) In
this mystery set in 1950s London, a group of elderly friends (with
more than a few skeletons in their closets) is tormented by an
anonymous telephone caller who informs each of them, ``Remember you
must die.'' ``Spark's trim, unloitering narrative reveals a fairly
complete gamut of human seaminess,'' Robert Phelps wrote in The New
York Times Book Review in 1959. The result is ``a daffily hilarious
book, even though it is pervasively concerned with the importance
of Death and Judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUN CATCH KISS &LR;  By Amy Sohn. (Scribner, $12.) Ariel Steiner,
the precocious young heroine of this first novel, is a sex
columnist for a New York newspaper who kicks up a citywide scandal
when it's discovered she's been making up colorful material for her
column. ``It's hard not to be entertained by the hapless but
indomitable Ariel'' and her misadventures, Matthew Flamm wrote in
1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
