<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4198 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-IMMIGRANT-VOTERS-$ADV     07-17 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-VOTERS-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLOOD OF NEW CITIZENS COULD INFLUENCE PRESIDENTIAL VOTE
 &HT;    800&AMP;add. With IMMIGRANT-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories for release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Millions of recently naturalized immigrants are
eligible to vote for president for the first time in the November
elections, and some analysts predict they could be a deciding
factor in key electoral states.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS), in another
burst of election-year activity, created 466,221 new citizens in
the first six months of this fiscal year and expects that number to
grow to about 900,000 by October
</P>
<P>
   That would bring the number of new citizens to nearly 4 million
since 1996. They are concentrated in large states such as Texas,
Florida, California, New York and Illinois, which provide the bulk
of the electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that these new voters are being actively
courted by Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigrants can definitely make an impact,'' said Don
Nakanishi, director of the Asian American Studies Center at the
University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new citizens tend to vote Democratic, some
Republicans are suspicious that the number of naturalizations is
reaching another peak during an election year.
</P>
<P>
   After 1996, when the number of new citizens doubled over the
previous year to more than 1 million, Republicans lodged complaints
that led to a still-unreleased Justice Department study of an INS
program called Citizenship USA, which was credited for the sharp
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans charged that the Clinton administration had
created the program to naturalize as many immigrants as possible
for the 1996 election. In its haste, the critics said, the INS
naturalized nearly 6,000 immigrants with criminal histories.
</P>
<P>
   This year's peak is no coincidence, said Allen Kay, spokesman
for Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the House immigration
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given their history of having used naturalization for their
own political advantage, it does raise the question whether they
are doing the same thing this time,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said INS last year started delaying the processing of
requests for other services. ``They have noticeably shifted their
efforts away into the naturalization process,'' he said. ``Why
favor one group of immigrants over other groups?''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Komis, an INS spokeswoman, said these claims are
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bipartisan Congress supported us in this effort (Citizenship
USA). We succeeded, but we found that our service structure had
weaknesses and we began the restructuring process'' to ensure the
ineligible residents do not become citizens, Komis said.
</P>
<P>
   Komis also said that while additional funding from Congress has
been allocated to three major INS programs with significant
backlogs _ naturalization, renewal of legal residence and
adjustment of status _ resources for dealing with other
applications have not been reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Desipio, acting director of the Latino Studies program at
the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, agrees that the GOP
suspicions might be misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost don't think (INS) is organized enough to do this,''
Desipio said. In addition, he noted, ``INS put the resources for
Citizenship USA in Miami also, where (new citizens) would become
Republican.'' Researchers see other reasons for the citizenship
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Many applications were sparked by the introduction of tough laws
limiting government benefits for illegal and legal immigrants, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson of California, a Republican, drew the hostility
of many immigrants with his backing of tough immigration laws,
including Proposition 187, a ballot initiative approved in 1994 to
deny deny public health, education and welfare benefits to illegal
immigrants and their children.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Republican-controlled Congress approved
tougher deportation laws and restrictions on welfare benefits for
immigrants who were not naturalized.
</P>
<P>
   INS said another factor was the large pool of immigrants who
became U.S. residents in the late 1980s. Because of legal waiting
periods to apply for citizenship, this group generated a flood of
naturalization petitions just as the INS was slowing down the
process to avoid the kind of errors that allowed criminals to
become citizens.
</P>
<P>
   A backlog built up, which the INS has been addressing by
reducing the processing time. Officials said they hope the lag will
fall to six months by October.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential hopefuls have been working especially hard to
attract Hispanics, which make up about 30 percent of the new
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   A recent TV ad in Spanish features Bush's nephew, George P.
Bush, saying that his uncle believes in opportunities for
Hispanics. The 23-year-old Bush is the son of Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida and his wife, Columba, a native of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking this month to the National Council of La Raza, the
leading Hispanic political advocacy organization, Bush said he
would spend $500 million to reduce the time it takes to process
immigrants' applications.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his own speech to La Raza, said he plans to support
affirmative action, improve health care insurance and create a
diverse cabinet. He said he would do something about the high death
rates of undocumented Mexicans who die trying to cross border with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrant advocates believe naturalized voters will lash
back at anti-immigrant sentiments, which are often associated with
Republican policies.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of the Hispanics registered to vote in
California are new citizens, according to a study conducted in
February of this year by the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute, a
research group for Hispanic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory is still there, and it shows in the registration
votes,'' said Harry Pachon, president of the Rivera institute.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows 70 percent of Hispanics are registered Democrats
and 17 percent are Republicans. But the study also shows that Bush
draws more support from Hispanics in California than any other
Republican, said Pachon.
</P>
<P>
   However, a large portion of naturalized citizens are not
strongly aligned with one political party, Nakanishi said. As they
become acculturated to U.S. politics, their vote can go in any
direction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, immigrants' votes are influenced by ethnicity and the
states they live in.
</P>
<P>
   Americans tend to vote Republican. The Asian vote is also
divided, with Vietnamese favoring Republicans, Filipinos and
Japanese favoring Democrats, and Chinese Americans divided between
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Naturalized immigrants' ``votes cannot be taken so lightly, and
candidates have to reach out to them,'' Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new voters are more passionate about issues
affecting immigrants, they seek the same things from government as
the U.S.-born generations, Desipio said _ health care, education,
public safety and other basic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show naturalized Asian immigrants are more likely
to vote than U.S.-born second-generation immigrants, Nakanishi
said. But Hispanic immigrants historically go to the polls even
less often than the voting-age public at large, fewer than half of
whom turned out in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant advocacy groups attend citizenship oath ceremonies to
register new citizens to vote, and visit immigrant communities to
encourage turnout. But political analysts say candidates do not
make a serious effort to recruit immigrants as they become new
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to see is more Latinos showing up at the polls,
and that takes grass-roots campaigns. Neither candidate is doing
that,'' Desipio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there isn't outreach in the year 2000, it is likely (new
voters) will be lost for future elections,'' Desipio said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Tomas Rivera Policy Institute, www.trpi.org/
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
