<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-VANDEVELD     07-17 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-VANDEVELDE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN DE VELDE HASN'T LOST GRIP 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With every decision and every swing of the golf club, the
heartwarming summer tale was sent spiraling, from comical to
ghastly to unthinkable. The Frenchman with the infectious charm had
taken us to the edge of wonder at last summer's British Open, but
with one hand on the Claret Jug, he stood in something called the
Barry Burn, his pant legs rolled to his knees, his golf ball
immersed in water.
</P>
<P>
   The joy ride was about to end in a horrific crash and Jean Van
de Velde couldn't stop it. Surely, he was going to be scarred
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, you jest, because in &UR;  &LR; Van de Velde's world, the sun was
out the day after that debacle at Carnoustie had cost him a piece
of history. He was in Mont de Marsan, his birthplace in the south
of France, and childhood friends were at the cafe table. They all
knew about the triple bogey, the playoff loss, and the dizzying set
of golf swings that had made Van de Velde an easy target of
ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   But they also knew something else _ that Van de Velde was
stronger than all those who did not have to swing the clubs that
fateful Sunday, people who only had to hide behind microphones and
notebooks and not tackle the impossible monster that was
Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all my friends around and it was huge. It was big,''
said Van de Velde. ``I was very tired, very drained. I was very
happy, but very disappointed not to have won it.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics, Van de Velde knew, were having a field day, but
c'est la vie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who are going to be supportive to you are the ones
who are close to you,'' he said. ``They're the ones who are there
for the bad times, which are the ones that count. The good times
don't count, you know. What about when things are going bad? Who's
around?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jean Van de Velde walked out of the shadows of anonymity and
into golf folklore last July. At 33, he had been a professional on
the European PGA Tour since 1988 and only golf fans of strong
convictions knew of this charming gentleman who had had limited
success. There was the victory in the Roma Masters in 1993, a
splattering of top 10 finishes, and some respectable rankings in
the Order of Merit, but for the most part, observers had to check
the media guide when his name topped the leaderboard through 54
holes of the 128th British Open at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   The media guide told us very little about Van de Velde. His
handling of the disastrous closing hole told us everything.
</P>
<P>
   To the so-called golf experts in the TV towers and print media,
Van de Velde was a fool for losing a three-shot lead on the 72d
hole. But to tens of thousands of fans, Van de Velde became a
person around whom they could rally. In a style that was Arnold
Palmer-like, Van de Velde had refused to play safe, and people
liked that. What's more, he had screwed up like they all had. Even
more, he was willing to talk about it and take full blame, all the
while showing great dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde apologized that Sunday afternoon in the Scottish
dusk and he's been doing so ever since. He blew it, yes. He felt
badly, yes. He took full responsibility, yes. He did not blame his
caddie, no.
</P>
<P>
   On countless occasions, Van de Velde has been told how well he
has handled things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, what can you do, man? I still finished second. I was tied
after 72 holes and lost in a four-hole playoff. Why should I be
ashamed of anything? People can say, `Ah, he blew three shots,' but
they should look at it from the other angle and say, `He did well
to be three ahead of everybody.' That's reality.''
</P>
<P>
   When he walked to the 18th tee in the early evening of July 18
last year, Van de Velde was 3-over par for the tournament, 3 over
on his round. Native son Paul Lawrie had birdied the 18th hours
earlier to close out the best round of the competition, a 4-under
67, and was in the clubhouse at 6-over 290.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Lawrie concerned himself about finishing second, because
Van de Velde _ who had vaulted to the lead on the strength of 68-70
in the middle rounds _ could afford a double bogey and still
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Up in front, Van de Velde watched Justin Leonard dump his second
shot into the Barry Burn. Minutes earlier, Van de Velde's playing
partner, Australian Craig Parry, had three-putted the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crazy golf tournament,'' said Davis Love, who posted just
one subpar round, a 69 on Sunday, yet finished in a tie for
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   For 71 holes it had been crazy, with the cut falling at 12 over
and just 11 subpar rounds.
</P>
<P>
   On the 72d, it passed crazy and went over the top to absurd.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary of that 18th hole approaches, Van de Velde
has had countless opportunities to offer his regrets, but he has
not done so. That's because he has none. He played the hole the way
he felt it should have been played, though perhaps, in looking
back, he could have gone another route with his third shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' he said. ``It's something that happened.
Out of a hundred times it would probably happen once and that was
the one. Unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie's 18th hole, said Van de Velde, was a monster. ``You
cross the burn three times. It's 480 yards and there's
out-of-bounds 5 yards left of the green and the green is something
like 15 feet wide. It's as tough as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A drive well right, then a 2-iron that went even farther right
and rattled off the bleachers, bouncing backward into an impossible
lie in the hay. His third shot was chunked into the burn, so he
took a drop, and knocked his fifth shot in the bunker. No. 6 found
the green, and No. 7 was a 6-foot putt that pushed him into a
three-way playoff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a sequence of shots that will be remembered forever, but
what should not be overlooked is this: The men who were there are
supportive of Van de Velde. The execution, they concede, was not
effective, but the strategy should not be criticized.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting driver? Listen to Parry: ``What no one really knew is
that the wind had turned and we went into it on our tee shots. So
we had to hit driver. I hit driver, too. It was late at night, it
was cold and starting to rain a little bit. You couldn't hit
2-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting 2-iron toward the green on his second shot? A surprise,
said Parry. ``However, he cleared the burn by 15 yards. That wasn't
the problem. He got unlucky when it (bounced off the grandstands
and) went back into the long rough. He would have been better off
had it gone into the water hazard. Then he could have taken a drop,
chipped it on, and won the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said, ``It's hard when you're sitting there 200 yards
with a perfect lie, you're leading the golf tournament, plenty of
room around the green to miss it. I don't think there's a player on
tour that would have pulled out a wedge or 9-iron (and played it
safe).''
</P>
<P>
   Love agrees. ``If he gets a good bounce, or if it bounces
forward, he wins the golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a near-impossible third shot, Van de Velde brought
the madness to a more incomprehensible level by challenging the
heather in an attempt to muscle a shot onto the green. Instead, he
hit it fat, deposited it into the Barry Burn, then removed his
socks and shoes and went in there after it.
</P>
<P>
   For several minutes, Van de Velde stood in the water, hands on
his hips, pondering his options. The crowd buzzed, almost fighting
back laughter, and players milled around trying to figure out what
in the name of Old Tom Morris was unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard was behind the 18th green. ``Disappointment was setting
in,'' for his double bogey at the 18th had left him at 290, tied
with Lawrie. ``But at the same time, I was trying to get ready for
a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 0948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-VANDEVELD     07-17 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-VANDEVELDE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... a playoff.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parry watched Van de Velde standing in the water. Most of his
thoughts were blurred because ``I was pretty disappointed myself. I
three-putted 17 from nowhere and made a triple at the 12th, as
well. I thought that I threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the bridge leading toward the 18th green, Parry
looked toward the comical scene in the burn. ``Half the ball was
showing, so he could have played it,'' he said, though as Van de
Velde mulled over his choices, the ball sank. The Frenchman's
decision was made for him _ he would take a drop.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a few minutes for Van de Velde to dry his feet and
put his socks and shoes back on, so Parry turned to his playing
partner and said, ``Do you want to play your shot?'' Van de Velde
declined. ``He told me to play and I holed out (from the bunker to
complete a 73-291),'' said Parry. ``I said, `Follow me in the
hole,' '' and Parry turned to walk away. Yes, he said, it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't believe it. We wanted to get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde did follow Parry into the hole, but not until he
had followed him into the bunker with his fifth shot. His
triple-bogey 7 completed a round of 77 and in the buzz of the
stunning collapse it was easy to lose sight of the fact Van de
Velde still had a chance to win. He had, after all, drained a
pressure-packed 6-footer to finish at 290, tied with Lawrie and
Leonard, but given the misfortune that had just unfolded, it was
not hard to predict Van de Velde's playoff fate _ he needed 18
strokes to play four holes (as did Leonard), which lost to Lawrie's
15.
</P>
<P>
   As Lawrie accepted the Claret Jug and a nation's embrace _ he
was the first Scotsman to win the British Open since Sandy Lyle 14
years earlier _ the spotlight tracked not the man who had won, but
the man who had lost.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbish, said Leonard. ``There are a lot of holes we all could
have played differently and played better, but that didn't happen.
He was doing what he thought was right at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is the sales pitch: ``Jean Van de Velde has always
preferred Bordeaux wines to Scottish water.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Van de Velde, who has a passion for wine (he was born an
hour from Bordeaux) and is the namesake for a wine from that
region. They promote the wine thusly: ``Made in his image, with
character and panache, frankness and generosity.''
</P>
<P>
   The description is perfect. Thanks to the $289,025 he earned for
finishing in a tie for second at Carnoustie, Van de Velde was able
to secure his playing privileges on both the European and American
PGA tours in 2000. He chose America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enjoyed it a lot. It's discovering new courses and
meeting new people,'' said Van de Velde, who has had small success.
He finished second in Tucson, posted a top 20 at the Masters, but
is just 84th on the money list ($353,458). That, however, doesn't
come close to explaining why he is a gallery favorite _ and a media
darling.
</P>
<P>
   The famous picture of him standing in the burn, pant legs rolled
up? ``I've signed hundreds of them . . . thousands,'' said Van de
Velde. His wit and European charm were the star attractions in a
30-minute infomercial for Never Compromise, the putter he uses.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Van de Velde, over dinner late last summer with some
friends, joked, ``You know, I could probably have done better with
just my putter.'' Sitting at the table was a Never Compromise
official, and immediately an idea was born. A few weeks before
Christmas, Van de Velde returned to Carnoustie and filmed the
infomercial over an 18th hole that was covered in December frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were freezing our hands and feet off and other parts of our
body as well,'' said Van de Velde, who used a putter with 6 degrees
of loft, a stronger shaft, and extra glue on the head as he played
the hole three times. First he made a 9, then an 8, then a 6, the
score that would have sealed a victory a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that his shot would have ended up in pretty good shape
had those bleachers not been constructed near the green, Van de
Velde grinned and quipped: ``You think I should sue the R&AMP;A?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he imagined himself in a similar position at this
year's British Open at St. Andrews, Van de Velde started to laugh.
The closing hole at St. Andrews is a relatively tame 357-yarder
whose protection comes in the form of a big swale _ the Valley of
Sin _ up near the green. The only water is a short distance off the
tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is for sure,'' said Van de Velde. ``If I hit it in
the water off the tee, I'll take my pants off this time to go hit
it.''
</P>
<P>
   More laughter, more handshakes, more smiles. Another interview
is over, but before Van de Velde moves 15 feet there is a new
reporter with an old topic. Did he have a minute? Van de Velde said
yes, then was asked just how it is he's been able to cope with the
memory of Carnoustie's 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, we're always ready to take the good times, but
we have to be ready to take the bad ones, too,'' he said. ``Around
the corner, they're going to be here and you have to be ready to
take the hammer shot when it comes. If not, the game's going to get
at you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
