<HEADER>
A4237 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-COLOR-VARIETY-KANSAS-     07-17 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOR-VARIETY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FAST BECOMING A MIX-AND-MATCH WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GUTIERREZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grown-ups wrinkled their noses when H.J. Heinz Co. unveiled its
green ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Green ketchup?
</P>
<P>
   Some things are meant to be green, and ketchup isn't one of
them, you say. Green is the color of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Someday, thanks to gene-tinkering scientists at The
Scotts Co., you might carpet your lawn with red grass, according to
recent reports.
</P>
<P>
   While you ponder these color swaps, kick back with some blue
M&AMP;Ms, fire up your strawberry hued iMac and order blue potatoes for
your garden from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a color revolution,'' says Margaret Walch, director of
the Color Association of the United States in New York, a leader in
color research and marketing. ``The question is why not? And the
answer becomes _ of course! _ why not?''
</P>
<P>
   As in the case of green ketchup, ``We have not seen this
deviating from the norm very often,'' says noted color guru and
forecaster Leatrice Eiseman of Eiseman and Associates in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen some of it in the last few years, the blue M&AMP;Ms,
which flew in the face of `you never eat blue food.' And blue corn
chips. And the whole iMac thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people are open to experimentation. There's less dogma
attached to color _ `you never do this, you never do that.' People
are open to using more color now.''
</P>
<P>
   Spinning the color wheel, however, can be as risky as Russian
roulette. ``Color sells ... if you select the right color.
Otherwise, it's called inventory,'' Eiseman told an audience at the
International Housewares Show in Chicago earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with color tradition has already resulted in macho NHL
and NFL players wearing teal logos, Minute Maid orange juice in
black cartons and Volkswagens the color of milky pea soup. News
from the national gardening front reveals near-black sunflowers
growing in test gardens and black pansies coming to your
neighborhood garden center. At the Chicago housewares show, the
Sharp company introduced fruit-colored Half Pint microwaves.
</P>
<P>
   In case you hadn't noticed, take a walk through the supermarket
or retail store with fresh eyes, as we did on a recent visit to
Target. Notice teal rubber ice trays, fluorescent green feather
dusters, purple flyswatters, wildflower-pink trash bags. Blue
Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Raid Roach and Ant spray, with its country fresh
fragrance, comes in a pretty pink can. In the office-supply aisle,
no-nonsense staplers come in frog green and baby blue.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of our purchase decisions are based on color,
says Eiseman, author of a new book, Colors for Your Every Mood:
Discover Your True Decorating Colors. ``There are always going to
be other things that get involved, not the least of which is the
quality and value and the price. But color is an emotional
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the impact of color, banks and insurance companies
have long used blue logos because blue implies dependability and
reliability. Capitol Federal Savings is one high-profile example of
the color's use in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman of the board John C. Dicus says that in the late 1950s,
when officials were planning a new Capitol Federal main office in
Topeka, the bank's late chairman Henry Bubb was inspired by blue
mosaic tile he and Dicus saw on an office building in Dallas. The
color struck Bubb as friendly, yet connoting strength.
</P>
<P>
   That's why blue was chosen for the company's logo and even its
buildings. In 1995 the company emphasized the point by adopting the
motto ``True Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain associations that go with certain colors
largely based on imprints on the human mind,'' Eiseman says. ``Blue
is dependable because it's the color of the sky and water. Even if
it's a dull day, we know that behind it is a blue sky, which makes
blue even more symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue, still America's favorite color, is the color of the
moment, says Eiseman, who told housewares makers that ``you almost
can't go wrong if there is something blue, but especially as we
transition into the new century.'' She predicts turquoise will be a
strong color for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, color experts coach companies to stay away
from certain pairings. Take soap. ``If you wanted to get the idea
across instantly that it's going to soften your skin, you can't use
colors that are so blatantly bright that they come across as too
powerful, too astringent,'' Eiseman says.
</P>
<P>
   Theories of color psychology hold that people build strong
emotional attachments to colors. But some of us haven't had time to
build those ties. Much of the color explosion under way plays to a
younger crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Blue applesauce and dorm-sized microwave ovens as purple as
grapes are targeted at consumers not old enough to remember
black-and-white TV, who don't have baby boomer hangups about
avocado green, who crave cell phones in candy colors. Nokia was the
first to offer colored cell phones in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer Inc. co-founder and CEO Steve Jobs predicts
``What's your favorite color?'' will become one of the most
important questions for personal computer buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Before Apple's fruit-colored iMacs were introduced last year,
computers were kind of deadly and serious, Walch says. ``Then all
of a sudden, they (Apple) realized that young people were eating
these flavors. Why not see them, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with the color of real food, however, is tricky, as
director Alfred Hitchcock discovered. A story from the Color
Association tells how he once served steaks at a dinner party but
made the mistake of lighting the room with blue light. The
grayish-blue, diseased-looking meat sickened his guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone put a glass of royal blue milk in front of you,
most people would be so turned off that you wouldn't drink it,''
Eiseman says.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently ketchup is no such sacred cow. Kelly Stitt, brand
manager for Heinz Ketchup in Pittsburgh, admits adults in the
company were taken aback when grade-school children in test groups
from coast to coast said they wanted their ketchup in colors.
``When you say `colored ketchup' to kids, they don't even flinch,''
Stitt says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids live in a world of color. Everything is bright, bold
color. And I think Heinz just jumped on this to say kids are our
No. 1 fans. Let's give them what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the kids wanted ketchup in green and one other
color: blue.
</P>
<P>
   History has shown that color is a successful attention-getter in
the marketplace, especially when used unconventionally. It works so
well for Apple that the company, not wanting to tip its hand to
competitors, is tight-lipped about which iMac color is most
popular.
</P>
<P>
   At Chicago housewares show, Eiseman illustrated the power of
color marketing by noting that, until around 1917, pink _
considered a strong color because it's derived from red _ was the
color for baby boys. The more serene baby blue was for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Then a prominent American retailer decided to attract attention
by reversing the colors. The rest is ... well, you know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the marketplace it's a great ploy,'' Eiseman says. ``If we
see things that are used in a bizarre, unexpected way, it must
capture our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching our eye, though, is not the same as confusing us. We
recognize Coca-Cola in its red cans and Tide in its bright orange
boxes and bottles. Companies tweak so-called ``recall images'' with
care. Clinique, for instance, chose orange packaging for its new
perfume, Happy, but didn't mess with its signature serene green in
its other products.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was successful in modifying its ``male, corporate royal blue
to a pretty periwinkle,'' Eiseman says. Kodak nicely warmed up its
recognizable yellow. ``But they've both done it within
parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Walch and Eiseman are skeptical of green ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hesitant because it's a classic,'' Walch says. ``It's
going against nature. Personally, yes, I might buy green ketchup as
a whim, and that would be it. It seems too much like a trumped-up
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it's very well-suited to children. They picked the
prime nasty color to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stitt at Heinz says to stay tuned for another ketchup color down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think other people will jump on the bandwagon once they see
big market leaders doing this,'' Eiseman says. ``What could happen
though is, once everybody gets into the act, it won't be unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you'll have people go back to the good ol' red ketchup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
