<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And justice for none
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Paul Thompson is a pig farmer on a piece of
land three miles west of Stuart, Fla. He and his wife moved there
in 1957. Over the years he's raised and sold hogs, all the time
picking up side jobs to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   He's been a carpenter, a commercial fisherman, and a sheriff's
deputy. He says for folks who weren't born rich, it's just what
they do to survive.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s, Farmer Thompson heard somewhere that the music
he was playing for his own pleasure was good for the animals too,
so he hung a couple of speakers in the pig pen and began serenading
the livestock with the local country music radio station, from 8:30
in the morning until 5:30 in the afternoon. Ever heard the
expression, ``Happy as a pig in the sunshine''? This was a textbook
case.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the mid-1990s, a developer moved in and built a
golf course right next door to the pig farm. Pretty soon the land
tycoon was complaining about music noise and pig stink. Said it
discouraged the sale of home sites and ``annoyed'' club members.
</P>
<P>
   Well, la-di-da.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, the developer tried to buy out the farmer,
but offers of money apparently haven't spoken loudly enough to
Thompson to get him off the land he's occupied for 43 years, and
that before the entrepreneurs moved in, was out in the middle of
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   I say it's tough pig poo for the city boys. Farmer Thompson was
there first.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we have the case of some folks living under the approach
to Toledo Express Airport's east-west runway. They weren't there
first, but guess what! They're getting new windows and central air
conditioning _ compliments of the Port Authority (translate that to
``taxpayers'') _ anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because airplanes are noisy.
</P>
<P>
   No fooling? It took them this long to figure that out?
</P>
<P>
   An acquaintance of mine is one of the homeowners who will be
sharing the windfall. I asked her the obvious question: Was the
airport there when you bought the house? She said it was. And did
you know you were setting up housekeeping at the end of the main
runway? She did.
</P>
<P>
   So why, I wanted to know, if you object to airplane noise, did
you buy that house?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she explained, ``we didn't expect the airport to be
busy. We didn't know an air freight company was going to move in
and fly a bunch of airplanes in and out all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, really. And why not? Isn't that what airports are for? Does
it make sense to you that the Port Authority is going to pave a few
miles of runway and then tell the airlines they can't use them?
That they can't take off and land there because the noise is
upsetting the folks who've gone and built houses where there
shouldn't have been any?
</P>
<P>
   The airport was there first, just like Farmer Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, I have this gut feeling that once again, injustice
shall triumph. Farmer Thompson and his pigs will be pushed around
by the big boys, mercilessly, until he has to move or lose it all.
That's how these things turn out because money talks.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the airport? My answer to the complainers would be:
Tough stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But wait and see. By the time the ambulance chasers get through
with it, the airport is going to be responsible for slow drains,
school violence, and hens not laying within a 10-mile radius of the
east-west runway.
</P>
<P>
   Makes no sense to me - you figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
