<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0718-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Sony's Speed Punks is nothing new but fun all the same By Staff
Reportsc. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Why Sony continues to devalue their own video game library by
releasing so many like-minded games is beyond comprehension. Take,
for example, Speed Punks ($40; www.playstation.com; for the
PlayStation), yet another pip-squeak fantasy car game stuffed with
chortling fathead characters racing around in karts across
repetitive little speedways while scooping up various vehicle
power-ups and ``special'' one-timer weaponry. All that said, Speed
Punks is a fine game, puffy with memorable elementary-school-brat
characters each with distinct personalities. The graphics are as
good as they get on the aging console, yet since no one broke the
mold after Nintendo's landmark Mario Kart, Sony copycats such as
this do nothing to stand out. They merely continue the deluge of
overabundant redundancy on the consumer. Crash Team Racing, Motor
Toon Grand Prix, Chocobo Racing, Circuit Breakers, the list goes
on. Pick one, not all.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare Creatures 2 ($45; www.konami.com; for the Dreamcast)
seems much too busy with dark slapstick humor and inflated graphic
violence to actually contain solid gameplay or treacherous
adventure. Instead, this game relies on a near-brainless controller
interface _ run, jump, block, attack _ and aggressively repetitive
mutant-zombie hacking. It lacks the depth of fierce adventure found
in the Legacy of Kain and Tomb Raider games. In fact, the game
encourages so much arbitrary bashing of crates and cupboards, which
may or may not contain something useful _ let alone even react to a
hearty ax swing _ that the unremitting dismemberment of freak-show
wannabes becomes a bother. To add insult to inanity, puzzle-solving
elements are about as tricky as a Hullian maze for lobotomized
rats. An adventure game so decidedly brazen and violent that they
forgot to add the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing more heroic than a bunch of space-age troopers
surmounting improbable odds and saving the solar system, and
Starlancer ($40; www.microsoft.com; for the PC) allows gamers to
play out precisely that scenario. While the thrust of combat calls
for interaction with artificial-intelligence team members, there's
more fun to be had in prima donna maneuvering and flat out,
lone-berserker rampaging. Created by Austin's Digital Anvil and
published by Microsoft, Starlancer's intelligent level design with
branching mission parameters offers a lot of repeat playability,
inadvertently more so considering the difficulty, the finicky
objectives and lack of mid-mission save points. The sheer fluidity
of play comes via a well-designed, intuitive interface that makes
Starlancer a must-have for the sci-fi epic heroism of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
