A4244 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-KIDGEAR0718-COX     07-17 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great for Tigers in training
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   It's well-known that golf prodigy Tiger Woods started playing
the game when he was just knee-high to a grasshopper. But while an
early introduction to a millionaire's motor skills does have its
merits, there probably aren't a whole lot of parents fond of the
idea of arming their toddler with nasty dimpled projectiles and
dangerous shafts of iron. Fortunately, Fisher Price's Grow to Pro
Golf ($15; www.fisher-pice.com) is made up of durable but mostly
harmless plastic parts. More importantly, this exceptionally
affordable ``golf training center'' is a bona fide,
enthusiastically tested and well-received hit _ according to my
little aspiring Nike endorser, anyway. The colorful ``bag'' not
only holds a light pair of clubs (an ambidextrous putter and
wedge), it also holds five oversized, underweight, pretend golf
balls and dispenses them, one at a time, by means of spring-loaded
cantilever gizmo, positioning each one on an appropriately sized
tee. The whole thing just exudes grip it and rip it without the
need to yell ``fore'' every time one does so. At this point,
there's a whole lot of hockey being played with our Grow to Pro
Golf set . . . but, hey, it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-LINK0718-COX     07-17 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LINK0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ mystockoptions.com _ So, you think you're a big
and bad because you've got a couple of measly stock options? I bet
you don't even know what they're worth, do you? You'd better hit
this site, myStockOptions.com, which seeks to demystify stock
options with a resource center, expert Q&AMP;As and lots of calculating
tools to determine your questionable on-paper worth.
</P>
<P>
   www.untitledmagazine.com _ Every now and then you find a site
that just speaks to you, in simple, elegant terms. Untitled
Magazine includes a series of professional photographs set against
unassuming backgrounds with a minimum of clutter. Sometimes the
photos are gritty; very often they're beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   www.kissthisguy.com _ A site celebrating the common practice of
screwing up song lyrics while singing along, kissthisguy.com allows
users to send in their stories about misheard words and phrases in
songs. It's the place where The Prodigy's ``Breathe'' changes its
lyrics from ``Exhale! Exhale!'' to ``Bake sale! Bake sale!''
</P>
<P>
   www.atomfilms.com/default.asp?spotid &QC; 85 _ We've been a fan of
Aardman Animation from the days of our Plasticine/clay heroes
``Wallace &AMP; Gromit'' to the current hit ``Chicken Run.'' ``Angry
Kid,'' one of the studio's newest creations, is available as a
series of Web shorts on atomfilms.com. Strange and very, very
funny.
</P>
