<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feed shows growth needn't be fast
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazon.com founder Jeff Bezos' mantra, ``Get big
fast,'' isn't the only way to succeed online.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes going slow and waiting for the right opportunity will
get you to the pot of gold at the end of the Web rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's not as glamorous or headline-grabbing, but the
results are the same, and in the end that's what matters. Take the
story of Feed Magazine (www.feedmag.com). Feed is a small
publication of ideas and commentary that has run since its
inception in 1995 with a staff of fewer than 10 people, the
generosity of angel investors and a lot of elbow grease. The
magazine watched the huge success of Salon and considered going for
broke, but founders Steven Johnson and Stefanie Syman decided they
didn't want to go broke and they couldn't possibly grow to
Salon-size without changing the entire focus of their publication.
</P>
<P>
   So they stuck it out for five years, and last week, Feed
announced a partnership with fellow online cult-classic
publications Suck.com and Alt.Culture. The new company, called
Automatic Media, will provide its partner sites with capital,
infrastructure, traffic, and distribution, while at the same time
allowing each site to retain editorial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos Ventures has a 25 per cent stake in the new company. It's
nice, in these chilly economic times, to see venture companies
investing in content sites that have proven they can go the
distance on very little money and very little sleep. Perhaps no
site deserves a helping hand more than Feed.
</P>
<P>
   Feed Magazine was a Web site on a budget long before it was
fashionable or even necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy has always been to keep the company kind of
small, sometimes by default and sometimes by conscious strategy,''
Johnson says from his New York office. ``Right now I'm sitting in a
chair I think has had people sitting in it since the Eisenhower
administration,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Feed was one of the first online journals of ideas and
community. Long before Salon was even a gleam in David Talbot's
eye, Feed was churning out unexpected articles on everything from
political interviews on the BBC World Service to essays on
alternative musicians selling out to TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Feed has always flown under the radar, while Salon and Slate
nabbed the big name scribes and the big budgets. Johnson estimates
that keeping Feed up and running over the past five years has cost
about $2 million. ``We can put things up online that made it look
like there were more people here than we actually have,'' Johnson
says.
</P>
<P>
   While Feed was humming along on a shoestring budget, Joey Anuff
and Carl Steadman were running Suck.com (www.suck.com) with
practiaclly no money at all. Back in 1995, Anuff and Steadman
published their anonymous one-page rants against new media players
of all persuasions. The site was a must-read for Internet
professionals, pundits and onlookers. Everyone wondered who was
behind Suck until Nov. 24, 1995, when Suck announced it had sold
the venture to HotWired, now part of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995 Steadman (who now writes a column for trade
magazine The Industry Standard) and Anuff understood the value of
joining up with a media company like HotWired. As they wrote in
their 1995 ``sell out'' column, going corporate sure beats hustling
venture capitalists at every cocktail party in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Steadman and Anuff knew what they had to do, but Feed chose to
hold out. Johnson thought about making Feed bigger, but he and
Syman knew their audience would never reach the vast mainstream
readership of Salon, so they started looking at viable options _
including perhaps being part of a network that would give Feed more
exposure without altering the site's presentation or content.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson laughs at the idea that a new cash infusion from Lycos
and other investors means Feed has gone corporate. ``The day-to-day
pressure of being in an indie environment will go off our
shoulders,'' he says. ``We'll have much more support, an ad sales
staff and an HR guy and things a real company should have. So we
can go back to thinking creatively, which we haven't been able to
do because we've been so focused on the business side. ``
</P>
<P>
   It may be too soon to tell, but it looks as if Feed will be OK.
After five years, they've made the leap from start-up to a
bona-fide Internet company. ``Get big fast,'' is one way to go, but
perhaps being true to yourself and making careful decisions about
the future of your company is a good plan, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
