<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scan article with OCR
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to learn how to scan a newspaper or magazine article,
store it on a disk, then retrieve it at a future date and be able
to read the information scanned. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   _ Theresa Snipe, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Sue: For folks who don't have a scanner, check
computers.cnet.com for which one to buy and where. There actually
are scanners for $80 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: There are lots of options. Let's look at one approach.
Many scanners come packaged with OCR software. File ``OCR'' away in
your mental dictionary of acronyms. It stands for optical character
recognition. Basically, it translates text. It helps the scanner
``look'' at a document or a newspaper or magazine article,
recognize letters and words and then translate them into a usable,
editable electronic computer file.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Keep in mind that OCR software will not recognize every
character, so you can expect to make text tidy-ups and tweaks.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If OCR software didn't come bundled with your scanner,
check the Net. Go to computershopper.zdnet.com and search for OCR
software. You'll see all kinds of software packages, with pricing
from several vendors. Costs run the gamut. The mother of all OCR
programs for Mac or PC is OmniPage Pro. The full package can be
pricey, ranging from $440 to $499.95. A lighter version of Omnipage
already is wrapped into many scanner purchases out there. If you're
brave and can't resist liquidation sales, go to
dirtcheapsoftware.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: TextBridge Pro is another option. We've seen it as low as
50 bucks and as high as $89.99, depending on where you shop and
whether it's for Mac or PC. Take time to look for good deals. At
bargainbins.com we found OCR software as low as $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Or, imported into many word processors. Be aware, because
it's a picture of the article, the type may not be easy to read.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You also have space considerations. Where do you store what
you scan? Do you have enough room to store them on the hard drive
of your computer? Other storage possibilities include floppy disks,
ZIP or Jaz cartridges, or CDs. What you choose depends on the
hardware you have. It's your call.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: It's important that we mention copyright infringements
here. It's not an infringement for an article to be scanned and
stored on a disk for future use if that use is entirely personal,
noncommercial and nonprofit. It is a copyright infringement,
however, if the scanned article, or parts of it, are republished
for non-personal, commercial uses.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
