<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revealing Web site lets some of Victoria's corporate secrets
slip
 &HT;    By Sharyn Wizda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We had no idea wearing all black was this
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``All professional attire must be predominantly (95 percent)
black,'' intones the six-page Victoria's Secret dress code.
``Predominantly black means no bold checks, houndstooth or wide
stripes. Outfits trimmed in another color are acceptable as long as
95 percent of the outfit is black.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the lingerie purveyors are just as concerned with what
some folks are wearing out in public as getting you to buy Second
Skin Satin underwear. In addition to the ``all black, all the
time'' credo, the company's rules for its sales staff include
instructions on tattoos (none should be visible), jewelry (no more
than two earrings per ear and two rings per hand, as long as those
rings are not on the thumb) and nail length ( 3/4 inch from the
base of the cuticle). All this is courtesy of thesmokinggun.com, a
Web site archive of court and other official documents, which
recently posted the code.
</P>
<P>
   Following the code helps convey the message of a ``sophisticated
and classic look,'' one in keeping with the ``high standards'' of
Victoria's Secret, the company explains. (That's in the dress code,
by the way _ a spokeswoman declined comment.) Lest anyone dare
question the style strictures, VS also points out, ``The Victoria's
Secret Dress Code is a reflection of our culture and our client's
expectations, rather than your own personal taste.''
</P>
<P>
   And, just in case you're still thinking about piping up, the
code includes a Q&AMP;A with breezy but firm exchanges like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: What if I don't have the money to refurbish my whole
wardrobe?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A: The beauty of wearing black is that you can buy separates
and mix and match them frequently, allowing your clothing budget to
go a lot further.''
</P>
<P>
   You can read the whole thing at www.thesmokinggun.com/
archive/victorias2.html. Better get there fast, though. The site
(which got the document from a employee whose renegade spirit
apparently couldn't be controlled) has already received an angry
letter from Victoria's Secret lawyers demanding the ``internal''
company document be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Guess they're not kidding about that ``secret'' part.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
