<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net2Phone knows Jack
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Net2Phone, Inc., a company focused on
voice-enabling the Internet, is giving people something to talk
about. Using the new Yap Jack ($160, www.yapgear.com), you can make
Internet phone calls without a PC. Although access to an Internet
service provider is necessary, configuring the sleek black box
takes less than 15 minutes and voice-prompted instructions are
idiot-proof. If anything, the Yap Jack is too easy to use, making
chatting long distance at low rates irresistible. Time-outs in
conversation are occasional reminders that the Yap Jack doesn't
rely on conventional phone lines, but the loss in quality is more
than regained by low costs, like nickel-per-minute calls to Tokyo,
or calls for mere pennies in the United States. The Yap Jack
practically guarantees you won't shut up about the savings.
</P>
<P>
   DVD, JAMES BOND DVD
</P>
<P>
   The best part about seeing a James Bond movie like ``Moonraker''
($35; www.mgm.com/dvd) on DVD is the widescreen presentation. After
all, the 007 films are always delightfully stuffed with
over-the-top action, tremendous stunts and stunning special
effects, but those ornery ``formatted for your TV'' VHS versions
hack a full third of the movie off the sides (think rectangular peg
in a square hole). Without widescreen, viewers are robbed of the
grandness of scope and details lingering at the edge of the screen.
MGM's latest James Bond push includes every incarnation of the Ian
Fleming hero digitally mastered and available separately or as part
of collector's sets (''Moonraker'' is also part of the James Bond
007 Collection Volume 2; $150). A small bonus with this DVD is the
ability to select individual characters, events or
gadgetry-in-action and zip directly to the relevant highlight
scene. Also included is a dated but informative making-of
``Moonraker'' documentary and several other DVD-ophile extras.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUER'S DECK HAND
</P>
<P>
   Does your grill drool grease or sputter sparks? At one time or
another most grills become the source of a deck-top mess. Instead
of pressure washing wood or stone after every cookout, why not buy
a bib for the barbie? The ``Original'' Grill Pad ($25 to $40
depending on size; www.diversitech.com) is little more than a pad
of thick, felt-like material coated in colored concrete. But it's
big enough (30-by-42-inch rectangles or 30-inch rounds) to protect
the deck and can be cleaned off with a shot from the garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
