</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sticky business
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   It's a guilty secret of many: all those business cards collected
at the last trade show end up in the trash bin. Or worse, all that
pertinent business falls into that hopeless pile of ``things to
file'' near the Rolodex. You can change all that with simple yet
ingenuous ShowOffs ($10 for 50; www.magzone.com), little fridge
magnets exactly the size and shape of a standard business card with
a self-adhesive side for quick and easy mounting of your
never-to-be-lost-again business card. Stick in their minds as you
stick on their fridge.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALARMING TO THIEVES
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the biggest problems faced by the commuter
with a computer is not the grand cyber hack or the techno-thief
embezzling your digital-age information; it's the old-fashioned
felon who just wants your laptop for a quick, cheap resale.
Fortunately, there's the Targa DEFCON 1 Notebook Security Alarm
($50; www.targus.com), a combination of stalwart cable, touchy
motion sensor and 110-decibel alarm that easily attaches to one's
laptop computer or carrying case. Not that the compact computers of
continual commuters should ever be left unguarded, but that brief
respite at the coffee bar or the airport lounge can now include
more peace of mind with this skullduggery deterrent.
</P>
