<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a car trip, try CDs, Game Boy, preparedness
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We are about to go on vacation. At least that's the
plan, but I have miles of chores to do before I leave.
</P>
<P>
   We are driving, so are there are necessary supplies I must pick
up.
</P>
<P>
   There's the supply of batteries I need to lay in for Game Boys,
CD players and night lights. Any parent who has driven long
distances with children knows the value of these portable
entertainment units.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime over the past year, my children acquired their own
personal music tastes and have begun to object vigorously to the
steady diet of oldies but goodies I have fed them musically most of
their lives. Their taste elicits one quarter appreciation, one
quarter horror and one half inability to distinguish one song from
another on my part.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the driver, I retain control of the car radio, hence
the value of CD players. Ten hours of Britney Spears, Smashmouth,
Santana (who I like but less so after the 17th time), Jock Jams,
etc. is more than any adult over 29 can stand.
</P>
<P>
   Since we will be completing our summer reading on this trip, the
night lights come in handy when at dusk, the backseat chorus begins
to sing, ``I can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly evolving highly individual tastes have led to me to
decide it would be a good idea if each boy had his own bag. That
way one brother's extensive Pokemon card collection and
paraphernalia won't hog all the space from the other's baseball
card collection (thank you All-Star Game for reviving interest in
it just before we leave!). So I printed packing lists for the other
items that might come in handy such as underwear, socks, shorts,
swim trunks and toiletries.
</P>
<P>
   We're meeting family. Two months ago, my sister mailed me
directions. Two months spent preparing for vacation was not in the
top 10 on my to-do list. Now it is, but the directions have
mysteriously disappeared. I have the utmost confidence they will
reappear. In the meantime, I used the Internet to print new ones. I
also used the Internet to find out what attractions are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone going on this trip has a different notion as to what
constitutes a vacation. I know from experience that my own view of
doing nothing more taxing than reading and eating will be outvoted,
so I may as well find out what is potentially ahead.
</P>
<P>
   While I was on the Internet, I decided to search for tips on
traveling with kids. At www.about.com, I clicked on Travel with
Kids, which led to a site that suggested playing charades during
vacation as a way to enjoy quiet evenings. I have actually never
played it, so I read with interest an article on how to play at
www.family.com that provided tips for playing with kids. The
article suggested using movie title when playing with kids. I can't
wait to try pantomiming ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' and ``Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel with Kids has several pages of suggestions on making long
car trips bearable. I found two lists of car games, some familiar
like ``Twenty Questions'' and a few new ones like ``Geography,''
where one person names a place, say Philadelphia, and the next
person must name a place that begins with the last letter, in this
case A, so Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the help I've gotten from technology in preparing
for this trip, I'm really looking forward to being unplugged when
we finally get there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
