<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zoom in on a digital deal
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   I've stayed away from digital cameras as they've been introduced
because only the most expensive ones seemed to offer decent
resolution and features comparable to 35 mm cameras. Now, with
megapixel cameras (those capable of producing high-quality images
suitable for printing) dropping in price to about $500 or lower,
there's been no better time to invest in one. The camera I chose to
buy, the Fujifilm MX-2900 ($799; www.fujifilm.com), offers
resolution up to 2.3 million pixels, a 3x optical and 2.5x digital
zoom, and a sharp viewscreen for previewing, editing and deleting
pictures. Amazon.com and some online auction sites have featured
this camera for about $550 in a fully loaded package that,
including an external flash and a USB SmartMedia card reader, which
reads the included eight-megabyte disk and speeds up transfers to
your PC or Mac) in one fully-loaded package. The quality of images
is exceptional, and the features such aslike red-eye reduction make
its a good deal for enthusiasts and amateurs alike.
</P>
<P>
   PLAY ALL DAY _ IT'S ERGONOMIC
</P>
<P>
   A brilliant gaming peripheral befuddled only by a few flimsy
components and a lack of buttons, VR Standard's Air Stik 2000 ($90;
www.vrstandard.com) is an innovative joystick simply for its
duality function. Mounted to a sturdy, weighted base, the Air Stik
sits firmly at one's workstation and offers an ergonomic grip with
intuitive access to a trigger, five buttons (two mirrored to each
side for ambidextrous access), a ``throttle'' slider and an
eight-way hat switch. The Air Stik's most abiding feature, however,
is its innate ability to pop off its sturdy rocker and convert to a
free-form, motion-sensing pistol grip utilizing tilt detection
technology first borrowed from the automobile industry and used in
similar fashion in the FreeStyle Pro. Unlike Microsoft's
aforementioned controller, the Air Stik operates as a one-handed
device and offers comfortable, intuitive play for many flying and
driving games. Unfortunately, the unit could really use still more
buttons to be a truly effective flight stick, and the buttons that
are there have that tell-tale ``clack'' of cost-effective
production value.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
