<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pesky codes inspire love or indifference
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once more, and for the last time if I can manage it,
the subject is codes.
</P>
<P>
   For the reader who just stumbled over this column, we have been
embroiled in a firefight involving WordPerfect adherents who insist
they couldn't live without that program's ``Reveal Codes'' feature,
and my argument on behalf of those who don't want any codes
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   This has been, for the most part, an entirely pointless
argument, because my stance against codes was largely a sham for
the sake of injecting a little humor into the proceedings. That
effort having been lost on most readers, who now regard me as a
lumpish know-nothing trying to deprive them of their codes, I'll be
more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, one learns what one needs to learn. Being a Word
user, if I wanted to do any fancy formatting I would learn to use
the program's style sheets. But I don't want to do any fancy
formatting, so I will forgo using the style sheets.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, I do most of my writing these days in
WordPad. That shows you how much formatting I need.
</P>
<P>
   Things like the style sheets and the reveal codes feature are
there for those who need them. Those who don't need them needn't
bother with them.
</P>
<P>
   This, essentially, is what led to the demise of the relatively
low-powered word processors. They didn't have these advanced, often
relatively difficult-to-use features, but people discovered that
really wasn't an advantage. If it turned out the user wanted some
big-time formatting, it wasn't there. With the heavy hitters, they
could be used as simple word processors until it came time for the
heavy armament.
</P>
<P>
   In the plethora of e-mail that rolled in, there was an
interesting note from Steven Pair, who described himself as a
computer scientist involved in an effort to make codes accessible
to all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that you should not have to learn codes and most
people won't want to. I also don't want to,'' he wrote. ``But those
codes enable you to accomplish some additional, more complex task,
that you are otherwise unable to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, to accomplish these tasks, you are forced to
learn a new language, a language of codes, rather than point, click
and type. It's a more difficult language and it follows an entirely
different set of rules than the usual language used by word
processors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is needed is a language that enables you to accomplish
even the most complex tasks with a single consistent language. Not
only should this language be used with word processors, but most
other software as well. This language should not be text (or code)
based, but rather it should be entirely visual, entirely point and
click. With this language, you can work at a very basic level, or
if you desire, dive deeper, doing more complex things, all without
having to learn a new set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the basic goal of a project currently being funded by
Walt Disney Imagineering. They are combining the concepts of
operating systems, computer languages, and databases into a clean
and consistent environment. This 'environment' runs in a Web
browser, as an operating system (on just about any hardware), or on
top of any traditional operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system is called Squeak.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. I can't wait. But in the meantime, as several readers
so astutely noted, the world's best word processor is the one you
know how to use.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
