<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-EDIT0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Edit and create your own professional quality
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you have a camcorder, chances are you've got
dozens of old tapes gathering dust. Most of the stuff on the tapes
is worthless, but you don't throw the tapes away because of the one
or two treasured scenes mixed in with the dreck.
</P>
<P>
   A digital video editing machine can help you cull the scenes you
want from those you don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Draco Systems Inc. of Boulder, Colo., has made video editing
equipment for professionals in the past, but now it's offering a
line of editors designed for the home market. The Casablanca Avio
LT sells for $1,495 and is for the novice; the Casablanca Avio ST
has a few more sophisticated features and sells for $1,795.
</P>
<P>
   Both units work without a computer. To create an edited video,
the user connects the Avio to a camcorder or other video source.
The Avio records the sound and pictures in digital form on an
internal hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Once the footage is on the hard drive, the person doing the
editing picks the scenes he wishes to save and arranges them in
order on a ``storyboard.'' From there, the editor can add special
effects, background music, titles, transitions between scenes and
other features to give the final video a professional feel.
</P>
<P>
   The Avio ST has a 20-gigabyte hard drive and can store up to 12
hours of video at VHS quality.
</P>
<P>
   Draco says Avio video editors are being shipped, and the first
stores in the area scheduled to stock them are the Alamo
Electronics stores in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the video editors, visit www.draco.com
and click on the Avio link.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
