<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Q: We wanted to buy a few stocks for our grandson's graduation.
We'd like him to enjoy watching the movement of the values, but
buying individual stocks has proved difficult. Can you help us?
</P>
<P>
   _ Claudia T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Lucky grandson. It is possible (albeit expensive) to purchase
one share of several stocks, but do you want to?
</P>
<P>
   Each purchase (one share or 10) involves a fee. For small
amounts (say, $500-$1,000), a mutual fund may be the best way to
go, advises personal asset manager Michael Kentor. The risk is
minimal, and your grandson may follow the fund's individual stocks.
You pay for one investment transaction rather than several. Brokers
should be willing to accommodate whatever you decide, notes
full-service discount broker James Kaighin. Q: I'm the CEO of a
small software company that builds a system used by foster agencies
to track children. I read that Danny DeVito and his wife, Rhea
Perlman, are interested in children's issues. He might be
interested in working with us. How do I contact him or his manager?
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Bishop
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact Mr. DeVito at Creative Artists Agency, c/o Kevin
Huvane, 9830 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, Calif. 90212. Worth a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
