<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4271 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0718     07-17 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why don't the TV bigwigs see the flaws we do?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here we go again. . . . The nation's TV critics
are heading off to cool (relatively speaking) and breezy Southern
California to stay in a luxury hotel, hobnob with stars and assess
the new fall season.
</P>
<P>
   Tough job? Oh, please. The hard part is plowing through 20 hours
of preview tapes, which I did last weekend. The rest is a romp.
Well, a seven-day-week, 12-hour-day romp that includes reporting
and writing, but which is certainly better than paving streets in
Texas right now.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my colleagues in the Television Critics Association are
already grumbling that this is the worst batch of pilots they've
seen in years. No fast-paced brainy dramas such as ``The West
Wing,'' no painfully realistic yet deeply fulfilling dramas such as
``Once and Again,'' and no sitcoms that rise above annoyingly
sophomoric.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't find the pilots quite that depressing. I laughed at two
sitcoms (Bette Midler's ``The Bette Show'' and Christine Baranski's
``Welcome to New York''). And I hold out hope for a few dramas,
including NBC's soft-focus, comedy-drama ``Ed,'' CBS's
philosophical medical drama ``Gideon's Crossing'' (starring Andre
Braugher), Fox's quick-moving ``$treet,'' about the roller-coaster
lives of young Wall Street professionals, and Fox's scary anthology
``Night Visions.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ball gets rolling in Pasadena, here are some of the
burning questions we will pose to the assembled stars, creators and
network executives, along with a few queries we not only won't ask
but won't listen to if someone else asks:
</P>
<P>
   Why is Fox determined to be the X Network? The fall schedule
boasts six series that are scary, futuristic or somehow infused
with science fiction. That's not counting the animated
``Futurama.'' Fox started out as a niche network targeting urban
teen and twenty somethings. It has evolved into a haven for
conspiracy theorists and wackos. Not that some of the sci-fi shows
aren't good, because a few are. We wonder, however, why Fox is
branding itself creepy.
</P>
<P>
   We definitely do not want to know why Calista Flockhart, Lara
Flynn Boyle and Portia de Rossi disappear when they turn sideways.
We're sick of the weight questions from rude reporters and the
whiny answers from the paper-thin stars. (``I'm just scrawny,''
Boyle said recently on ``Entertainment Tonight.'') I might ask
David E. Kelley if he's worried that de Rossi's exposed rotator
cuff might alarm some viewers, but that's as far as I'll go.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Couric and Matt Lauer will meet with critics to tout
``Today's'' forthcoming expansion to three hours. Why in the world
do they want to lengthen a show that most people watch for only 15
minutes? Did NBC insist on bloating the show because it's NBC's
biggest money machine? Is there research indicating millions of
people are hanging around an extra hour in the morning with nothing
to do? Gotta know.
</P>
<P>
   No actors, no matter how boring they are in an interview, should
ever be asked why they took a role. If there's any reason beyond
the obvious (the need to work and receive a paycheck), we don't
care. Every role is interesting, challenging or against the grain.
Always. So don't ask, don't tell.
</P>
<P>
   With David Janssen setting the gold standard in the original
series and Harrison Ford doing a bang-up job in the movie, what's
left for Tim Daly to do with CBS's remake of ``The Fugitive?'' The
pilot is impressive, but Daly pales compared with those who went
before. And it's hard to imagine what new ground can be broken with
the concept, but I'll ask.
</P>
<P>
   I will not ask anyone at NBC why they yanked the plug on
``Freaks and Geeks'' so quickly. The real answer is, they have no
taste. But nobody will say that, so why bother? Ditto ABC and
``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Are network execs worried the bottom will fall out of the drama
trend and leave everybody bankrupt? It's a known fact that hourlong
dramas don't sell as well as sitcoms in syndication. They cost
millions more to produce and die in the ratings when they're
repeated. This fall, like last fall, there are more new dramas than
comedies, and that seems risky to the point of foolish from a
business standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Do you care that just about nobody is paying attention to the
content ratings (the little alphabet-soup box that precedes each
network broadcast) or using the V-chip that the ratings are
intended to trigger? I sort of care, but those questions are best
asked of parents, especially the ones who complain all the time
about the evil effect TV has on their children, not TV executives
camped out in Pasadena. They definitely don't care.
</P>
<P>
   What about that prime-time animation trend? Where did it go? The
big animation hit last season was supposed to be ``God, the Devil
and Bob,'' but it was scrapped after a couple of episodes. Several
other animated series were in the works last spring but are nowhere
to be found now. An invisible trend? Whassup with that?
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing we want to know is when the networks
are going to wise up and stop showing so many reruns during the TV
season. Ratings continue to fall, reruns continue to rise. Is there
a connection there, guys? Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
