<HEADER>
A4282 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     07-17 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, July 17, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-TAPES (Undated) _ Twenty-six years after former President
Richard Nixon resigned in disgrace, an elite team of electronics
experts will meet to discuss whether science can unravel one of the
biggest mysteries of the Watergate era: What is on the baffling 18
1/2-minute gap on one of Nixon's White House audiotapes? On Sept.
21, they will gather in College Park, Md., at the request of the
National Archives to consider whether exotic new technologies could
resolve mysteries of the 1970s Watergate scandal. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MORMON (San Francisco) _ Joining the Mormon Church is easy.
Getting out can be hell. So says Owen Edwards, a 28-year-old San
Francisco masseur and student aesthetician. Born into the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Edwards faces a disciplinary
hearing and possible excommunication for submitting his
resignation, explaining his reasons and asking to have his name
removed from the Mormon Church's membership records. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   TWO-BY-TWOS (Guilderland, N.Y.) _ They don't smoke, drink or
watch television. And though their numbers rival groups like the
Moonies or Rajneeshees, this conservative Christian sect has
managed to remain virtually unknown. Outsiders call them ``Two by
Twos'' because ministers travel in pairs to convert new members.
But to those who follow the austere lifestyle prescribed by the
sect, the religion does not have a name and is referred to simply
as ``The Way'' or ``The Truth.'' By KIM MARTINEAU.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-FEUD (Junction, Texas) _ When the bad blood between the
aging Cardwell brothers ended in gunfire at the old family ranch
outside of town, Bill Cardwell, 80, lay in the dirt with a hole
through his chest. His younger brother Cody, stood nearby, holding
a deer rifle. Cody, now 79, says he shot in self-defense. In August
he will go on trial in nearby Sonora for Bill's murder. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RELIGION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ God and taxes are the
central tenets of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's compassionate
conservatism. It's an attempt, a new paradigm, his campaign says,
to deal with a familiar social and moral dilemma. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-JENNINGS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gabe Jennings, a Stanford
junior, jumped on the 1,500-meter field like a wolf pouncing on a
rabbit and made the race his own to highlight the third day of the
U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials at Sacramento State's Hornet
Stadium. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RICE (Stockton, Calif.) _ Jerry Rice made the early-morning
drive from his home in Atherton to the 49ers training camp at the
University of the Pacific _ his mind drifting to other days.
``Steve, he's going to be missed,`` Rice said, referring to the
prospect of camp without just-retired quarterback Steve Young. By
BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Stockton, Calif.) _ Jeff Garcia says he's ready to
assume the role of the 49ers' No. 1 quarterback. Coach Steve
Mariucci, pleased with his starting quarterback's improving play,
isn't so sure about the rest. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
