<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FAMILY-FEUD-HNS &LR;      07-17 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-FEUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ELDERLY MAN AWAITS MURDER TRIAL, CLAIMING SELF-DEFENSE IN
FRATERNAL FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNCTION, Texas _ When the bad blood between the aging Cardwell
brothers ended in gunfire at the old family ranch outside of town,
some of their relatives were surprised that only one shot was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be like the O.K. Corral, a battle royal,''
recalled one relative.
</P>
<P>
   When the last argument was over on May 5, 1997, Bill Cardwell,
80, lay in the dirt with a hole through his chest. His younger
brother Cody, stood nearby, holding a deer rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that trouble old Bill and I been having? Well, it's
over,'' Cody said when he called the Kimble County Sheriff's
Department, asking for help.
</P>
<P>
   Cody, now 79, said he shot in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   In August he will go on trial in nearby Sonora, charged with
killing his brother. Also pending is a wrongful death suit filed in
civil court against Cody by Bill's three adult sons.
</P>
<P>
   Few facts about the shooting are in dispute, and there is not
much mystery either about the fraternal animosity that led up to it
or the family suffering it has caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the oldest story in history, going back to Genesis. Cain
killed Abel. Brother killing brother. It's very unfortunate, but
that's all I can say,'' said District Attorney Ori White, whose
office will prosecute Cody.
</P>
<P>
   The killing has bitterly divided the Cardwells, one of the
pioneer families in this town of 3,000 people 100 northwest of San
Antonio. Just a year before the shooting, 75 Cardwells attended the
family reunion in Junction.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cardwells believe Cody shot in self-defense. Others do not.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe the family can ever be made whole again, and most
who talked about the shooting asked that their names not be used in
print.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Cody were the eldest surviving sons of the legendary
one-armed family patriarch, O.W. ``Dad'' Cardwell, who settled in
Kimble County in 1910. Cardwell and his wife Mildred reared 11
children on a 10,000-acre ranch that straddles the Kimble and
Sutton County line.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the theme of many of Cody's public complaints
was his problems with older brother Bill. Sheriff's deputies were
called to the ranch to settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the two had been partners in a cattle-raising
enterprise on the family ranch, and Cody thought Bill had cheated
him. He went so far as to sue over the issue, but after an audit
that showed otherwise, the suit was dropped just months before the
fatal shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were ever the best of friends, over
girlfriends or ranching or anything else. They had a difference of
opinion about everything,'' said Ruth Cherry, 77, younger sister of
the brothers and one of three surviving siblings.
</P>
<P>
   And, like others, she thought the dispute would more likely end
with Bill standing and Cody on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought it was going to be the other way around. I
think they threatened each other all their lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Cardwells, however, said the conflict has been
exaggerated, that it was not a sibling rivalry of biblical
dimensions. The brothers often worked side by side without
squabbling and looked out for each other, too, said one in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people in town that would love to turn this
into an old Western,'' she said. ``But Cody was angry. He wanted a
confrontation. He'd made a lot of accusations that weren't true. It
was a time of sickness, and things just got out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever earlier differences they had, the relationship got
worse in the early 1990s when Cody returned in poor health to the
old family ranch. He had been diagnosed with cancer and was also
told by the doctor to quit smoking, which made him even edgier.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the Cardwell Ranch after decades living away, Cody moved
into a house that faced Bill's across 200 yards of open ground.
Years earlier, the spread had been divided among the five children
who wanted land instead of money.
</P>
<P>
   The problems were aggravated because Bill regularly drove right
past Cody's house over an easement in order to tend to cattle on
another section of the ranch owned by a sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this flashpoint, as Bill was passing through the gate
by Cody's house, that the fatal shooting occurred three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The only eyewitness was Cody's wife Millie, who saw the argument
unfold through a living-room window. Both she and Cody have since
sold their property and moved to a ranch near Menard.
</P>
<P>
   Strangers now live there, and Bill's son, Odie, occupies his
father's house.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial approaches, the lawyers say everything hinges on
the issue of self-defense. Although Bill was known to regularly
carry firearms, he was unarmed when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a bizarre, old-timey case. Cody Cardwell is 79
going on 80, and we're charging him with killing his older brother
Bill,'' said Mike Brown, the assistant district attorney who will
try the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill didn't have a weapon on him, other than a pair of pliers,
and you're not going to find a rancher out here without something
on him. I don't believe the self-defense issue and I don't think a
jury will either.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody's lawyer, however, called it a ``classic self-defense
case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one weapon. Bill was carrying some fencing tools, he
had one on his belt, and he had drawn that to hit Cody,'' said
Preston Douglass Jr. of Kerrville. ``Bill wouldn't leave. Bill
wouldn't back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Odie Cardwell, Bill's son, said he spoke to his father the night
before he died. As usual, the conversation turned to family
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `How are things with Cody?' and he said, `It's not any
better. He's blabbing all over town about everything I've stolen
from him. He needs to shut up,''' Odie recalled his father saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Dad, when you go to Thelma's place, go around. Don't
go by Cody's. And he said, `Son, that's easy for you to say,' and I
guess it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
