<HEADER>
A4333 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SOLAR-GADGETS-POPMECH     07-17 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR-GADGETS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SING AROUND THE SOLAR-POWERED CAMPSITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of solar-powered outdoor equipment are available
on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By RICH TAYLOR 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clear sunlight contains 1,000 watts of power per square meter at
sea level. That's enough to give you a healthy tan in a few minutes
or a third-degree burn in a few hours. It's also enough to power
everything on Earth 1,500 times over if we could just figure out a
way to harness all the free, nonstop solar energy that bathes the
globe every day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in a very real sense everything on Earth is already
solar-powered _ we just release that power in different ways.
Burning long-buried hydrocarbons to get at stored solar energy, as
we've been doing, isn't particularly efficient. But other ways to
use solar energy are available. There's a whole campsite worth of
clever outdoor gear that runs directly on sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this solar equipment depends on photovoltaic cells first
developed at Bell Laboratories in 1954. A PV cell consists of a
nonconductor _ often a silicon wafer similar to those used for
computer chips _ coated on one side with exotic metal atoms that
produce a surplus of electrons when exposed to sunlight. The other
side of the PV cell is coated with atoms deficient in electrons.
Run a wire from each side to an electrical device, expose the
positive side to sunlight, and you have an electron flow capable of
useful work.
</P>
<P>
   But not much of it. Current PV cells are only 10 percent to 15
percent efficient, so most solar-powered camping gear is small
stuff that requires less than 1 amp to operate. On the other hand,
virtually anything with a microchip fits into this category _ a
handheld GPS, cellphone, radio or a laptop computer. You name it. A
PV cell is the perfect power supply.
</P>
<P>
   A standard 10-watt PV flat-panel module is 9.5 by 18 inches,
weighs 17 ounces and produces 0.6 amp at 16.5 volts. At $12 per
watt, it's about three times as costly as the huge solar panels
designed to fit on your roof. But you can't carry rooftop PVs in
your backpack.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of PV-powered devices were tested, including a couple
of radios, camp lights, flashlights and even a power supply
specifically engineered to run a laptop computer. Most of the items
that have built-in PV cells feature alternate sources of power.
Why? Well, on rainy days, your radio stops. Therefore, most small
solar-powered equipment also includes a battery pack and a
hand-cranked dynamo to provide backup power.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect use for PV cells is recharging batteries on a boat
or RV that isn't used a lot. One compact PV panel is enough to
maintain a trickle charge on a battery that's already charged up,
or to replace the charge bled off by a small bilge pump. Thanks to
their simple construction and the fact that they're designed to be
out in the sun all day, PV cells should last forever _ literally _
lying quietly on your RV's dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   One popular solar gizmo is the Wattz-In-A-Box. A 21- by 23- by
9-inch travel case holds a 10-watt PV panel and 150-watt AC
inverter. These, in turn, are used to recharge a 12-volt DC power
supply. The box includes a built-in flashlight, gooseneck reading
lamp and cigarette lighter outlet, among other nifty features.
</P>
<P>
   Other solar devices use sunlight directly, without having to
convert it to electricity first. Hang a black plastic bag filled
with water in the sun for an hour or two, and you get a supply of
hot water perfect for showering on a beachfront or boat deck.
</P>
<P>
   This is the principle behind the two solar showers tested for
this article. One was the Super Solar Shower, a 5-gallon black
plastic bag you can hang from a tree branch or halyard. It is
fitted with a shower head on a plastic hose. The Solar Air Power
Shower was equipped with a foot pump that is supposed to pressurize
the 7-gallon water bag. We preferred the Super Solar Shower, as
gravity proved more dependable and easier to use than foot power,
particularly when the pressure ran out while trying to rinse off
soap.
</P>
<P>
   Two different solar ovens were also tested. Both work by
collecting sunlight and concentrating it in one spot. The Solar
Cooker is nothing but a sheet of foam to which reflective foil has
been laminated. Slide Tab A into Slot B and it turns into a
self-supporting oven capable of heating to 300 degrees. When you're
finished cooking, the whole thing neatly folds into a flat,
flexible and virtually weightless package that easily fits in a
backpack.
</P>
<P>
   More elaborate is the Sun Oven, a 21-pound wood, metal,
fiberglass and glass box that unfolds to form a solar oven with
interior dimensions of 14 by 14 by 9 inches. By carefully adjusting
the polished reflectors, the built-in thermometer climbed up to 400
degrees. That's hot enough to roast a chicken or even bake a cake.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite solar product of all is the Acqua Cone, an
emergency water maker/purifier that's devilishly clever. It
consists of an inflatable plastic ring, a clear plastic cone
supported by four rods and a black circular wick that floats inside
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The wick laps up water, which is turned into pure water vapor by
sunlight streaming through the cone. The hot water vapor condenses
on the cooler cone, leaving any impurities in the wick. Eventually,
pure water runs down the sides of the cone and collects in a trough
on top of the inflated ring. A plastic tube drains the trough to
provide you with a pint or more of safe water per day, and it
tastes only faintly of plastic. Who cares? It could literally save
your life.
</P>
<P>
   As more people take to the outdoors and insist on carrying
conveniences with them, the market for solar-powered gear is sure
to grow. PV cells become more efficient with each new generation of
technology, which already makes these products economically
feasible. You also gain genuine satisfaction from getting power for
free, out of thin air, like magic. No wonder some people worship
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   All the solar-powered outdoor equipment mentioned here is
available from Real Goods, 200 Clara Ave., Ukiah, CA 95482;
800-919-2400; www.realgoods.com.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
