<HEADLINE>
AUTOMOTIVE REPORTS FROM AROUND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following ``separate-buy'' material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of the POPULAR
MECHANICS news service. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by
special arrangement. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 ART ADV: Color photos of the automobiles discussed below are
available by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE SPY REPORT
</P>
<P>
   2004 MERCEDES-BENZ E-CLASS: Obviously highly disguised, this is
the next generation E-Class wagon. A lowered hood houses a new
series of engines, and the revised bodywork sits on a longer
wheelbase, with less overhang and a similar overall length compared
to the current generation. The headlamp treatment is highly
disguised as well, but we're betting on tiny projector-beam
headlamps. Look for a raft of high-tech features like credit-card
entry and keyless ignition, voice recognition and radar-controlled
gap-maintaining cruise control and automatic braking.
</P>
<P>
   2002 PORSCHE SUV: Finally, the long-rumored Porsche SUV has been
captured in an advanced state of development. We know it's the
Porsche rather than the companion Volkswagen version from the shape
of the headlamps _ obviously related to the ones on the 911 and
Boxster. The fat tires and alloy wheels imply that this vehicle is
intended as an autobahn burner, rather than as a true off-road
stump-jumper. Expect innovative drivetrain engineering to achieve
Porsche-class ride and handling when this sees the light of day
late next year.
</P>
<P>
   2002 MERCEDES-BENZ MAYBACH: Cobbled together from S600 bodywork,
this test mule is the Mercedes-Benz Maybach hyperluxury sedan.
Somewhere in excess of $200,000 will get you into one sometime late
in 2002. A long and a longer-wheelbase version is planned, and
powerplants will be turbocharged or supercharged (or both) versions
of the 5.8 liter V12 used in the current S600.
</P>
<P>
   2001 PORSCHE GT3: Last year, Porsche produced a limited number
of GT3 road cars. All were sold immediately. Duh. And if these cars
were legal to bring into the United States, Porsche probably could
have sold twice as many. So, the powers that be in Stuttgart have
wisely decided to make a second crop. Unlike the 911 Turbo, the GT3
is rear-wheel-drive. The variable-deployable rear wing and front
airdam/headlamp treatment hint at the styling direction expected of
the new 911 Carrera due next year. Lighter than the 911 Turbo by an
unspecified amount, the GT3's 380 horsepower is sufficient to
propel it 0-to-100 kph (0-to-62 mph) in 4.8 seconds with a top
speed of 187 mph. It purportedly was the first production vehicle
ever to break the 8-minute barrier at Germany's Nurburgring
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   2000 KIA SPECTRA: This relative upstart carmaker from Korea is
trying to buck the trend and common wisdom with its latest model,
Spectra. The car offers the flexibility of a hatchback but its
packaged with all the allure of a four-door sedan. Spectra is based
on the chassis that Kia uses for its Sephia line. But essential
differences show up in a number of areas, including exterior
styling. Two models are offered, the $10,795 GS and the $12,995
GSX. Both have a 1.8 liter, DOHC, 125-horsepower Four and the
choice of either a five-speed manual or four-speed automatic. If
you want a different Spectra, Kia has the Spectra K, which boasts
engine and suspension modifications to appeal to the growing market
of Asian-car hot rodders. Perhaps the most striking feature of the
Spectra K is the paint, which changes hues under different light
and viewing angles. Prices for the Spectra K are to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   2000 AUDI TT ROADSTER: When you drive a TT, people come up to
you to to talk about it. That's been true since the tidy little
coupe was introduced a year ago. And it's even more true with the
introduction of the Roadster. Designed in parallel with the Coupe,
rather than engineered onto the Coupe's platform ex post facto, the
ragtop chassis is devoid of any evidence of cowl shake. The
convertible top can be had in manual or power-operated style. Along
with the Roadster's introduction, Audi has more power for the TT: a
225-horsepower version of the current engine. This powerplant rates
a six-speed gearbox, and quattro all-wheel drive is standard. The
225-horsepower Roadsters also get the power top. One interesting
feature is the glass windbreak divider that rises from behind the
seats at the touch of a button. A notable option is the dusky
orange baseball-leather interior treatment, complete with
hand-stitched baseball-glove lacing around the seatbacks.
</P>
<P>
   2000 SAAB 9-5 AERO WAGON: Through solid marketing and even more
solid products, Saab's sales have continued to grow. Now they'll
grow just a wee bit more thanks to another new and niche model: the
9-5 Aero Wagon. Besides the body cladding that gives this station
wagon that ``aero'' look, it packs the same 2.3-liter turbocharged
Four that's in Saab's pocket rocket, the 9-3 Viggen. Thanks to the
car's sophisticated engine controls, the small turbo is rated at
230 horsepower and, with a manual gearbox, 258 ft.-lb. of torque.
Other benefits of the drivetrain include altitude compensation so
the engine can perform as well at 10,000 feet as it can at sea
level. And after driving around much of New Mexico, we can say that
it performs just fine, thank you. Unfortunately, Saab intends to
sell only 750 of these wunderwagons for this model year. This is
also the first European nameplate to be equipped with OnStar.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
