<HEADLINE>
CAR CARE Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A graphic on changing an oil filter and O-ring is
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By MIKE ALLEN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LORD OF THE RINGS
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently replaced my oil filter. Within a couple of miles,
the filter started to leak. I just barely made it home with any oil
in the engine. I walked down to the gas station, and paid list
price for another oil filter and oil. This time I really cranked
the new filter on _ about 112 turns after the gasket touched
instead of the three-quarter turn the instructions on the side of
the filter called for. Sure enough, the filter leaked again within
a couple of miles. I ducked into a 10-minute oil change place, and
paid to have the oil and filter changed by professionals. But what
do they know that I don't? How hard can it be to change a filter?
Now it doesn't leak _ except for the oil still dripping on my
driveway from the bottom of my car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adler Dempsey, Perth Amboy, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm only guessing, of course, but I'll bet the original oil
filter you took off at the first change left its gasket attached to
the bottom of the filter-mounting boss on the engine. This
square-section O-ring is supposed to stay with the filter as it's
removed. This does not always happen. If the old O-ring stays stuck
to the engine, the new O-ring won't be properly supported when the
filter is replaced. And as soon as the engine warms up, it will
squirm out of the way, and you're oiling down the street. Whenever
you remove an oil filter, be sure to check that the old O-ring is
in place. If not, reach in to the filter mount, and pick it off
with your fingers or a screwdriver. In any case, it's good practice
to thoroughly clean the filter-mounting boss and lightly coat the
new O-ring with clean oil before installing the new filter.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK IS BEAUTIFUL
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 1999 Mustang GT. All of the plastic panels on the
car, including the bumpers, ground effects rocker panels and the
air vents behind the doors, are painted black. Unfortunately, there
are several shades of black, ranging from a true black to a
brownish tint. I've been to two different dealers. The Ford rep at
the first said that's the way it is because they are painted by
different suppliers, and offered no remedy. The body shop manager
at a second dealer said all the '99s are coming through this way
and offered to repaint the panels. He wouldn't guarantee they would
match, however. Before I have someone start painting, what's the
correct fix?
</P>
<P>
   _ John Davidson, Suwanee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: This mismatch is generally more of a problem on body-colored
panels rather than on black ones. The problem is that steel panels
are given a different kind of prep and often a different type of
paint than the different types of plastic. You've got urethanes,
sheet-molding compound and any of several thermosetting plastics to
match. Because they take the paint differently, and require a
different chemistry for adhesion, they may not match precisely. A
sharp painter can improve your color match considerably.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 1986 Bronco lost its heat a couple of months ago. My
husband added antifreeze, and it was fine for a short time. But
soon after, it happened again. He's added coolant five times so
far. There's no leak we can find. Someone suggested that it's
leaking into the oil, but we can't find any in the oil. Where is it
going?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jane Gulka, Saskatchewan
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I wouldn't be so sure it's not going into the oil. If
you drive the truck long enough to boil off all the liquid coolant
in the oil pan, you might not see it on the dipstick. An oil
analysis would find traces of the coolant's additive package.
Otherwise, your leak may be in a lot of places. Check for seepage
at the water pump weep hole, the intake manifold, the perimeter of
the head gaskets and all of the hoses and the heater core. It may
be nothing more than a radiator pressure cap that's not holding
pressure, allowing the coolant to escape as vapor. You may find it
necessary to enlist the aid of a mechanic with a black-light leak
detection kit to find any leakage.
</P>
<P>
   WATER OR NOT
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently noticed a puddle of what appeared to be water on
the ground under my Lumina. It smells and tastes like water,
anyway. What could be leaking? The leak comes from near some steel
lines under the a/c compressor and behind the oil pan. The cooling
system is working normally. I haven't used my air conditioning in
months, so it's probably not from the evaporator pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rob Olsen via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: It's water from the evaporator pan. It's draining from the
evaporator pan's drain tube, and running along something under the
car to where you see it dripping. Even if you haven't used your a/c
for a while, your a/c compressor runs when the system is set to
Defrost.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHTY-NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed that you warn against using ether starting
fluid, but you've never said why.
</P>
<P>
   _ Earl Kennedy, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   A: I personally have seen two engines destroyed while using
ether to start them. The first engine caught on fire. The other
broke a connecting rod, punching a hole in the side of the block
and nearly hitting me in the chest with shrapnel. Good enough?
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
