<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic on experimental arthritis treatment, photo of
road-traffic camera, photo of bicycle solar panel, image of solar
activity are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NONSURGICAL TREATMENT FOR ARTHRITIS PAIN
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 million people could benefit from a new treatment for
rheumatoid arthritis. Called Boron Neutron Capture Synovectomy, it
removes the synovial membrane that surrounds and lubricates joints,
without the side effects of surgery or injections of radioactive
isotopes, the currently favored treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The arthritic joint is injected with a boron-rich compound, then
exposed to a beam of neutrons. The boron absorbs some of the
neutrons, forming a radioactive substance that quickly decays.
Radiation from this decay kills the synovium, and then vanishes as
soon as the neutron beam is turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Initial results with arthritic rabbits are encouraging, says
Jacquelyn Yanch, a professor of nuclear engineering at MIT. Human
tests are still a few years away.
</P>
<P>
   EARLIER SOLAR ALERTS
</P>
<P>
   When the weather on the sun gets stormy, blasts of solar wind
can disrupt communications on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Michelson Doppler Imager on the Solar and Heliospheric
Observatory, researchers can track millions of points on the
surface of the sun. A computer program looks at changes in rhythmic
motions and traces these anomalies to the unseen eruptions that
caused them, in effect creating a ``window'' through the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Solar Physics Research of Tucson, Ariz., and
Northwest Research Associates of Boulder, Colo., the technique
gives 10 days of warning.
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR PUSH FOR ELECTRIC BIKES
</P>
<P>
   Adding an electric drive to a bicycle makes hill climbing
easier, until you forget to plug in the charger, when it becomes
dead weight. Energy Enterprise's solution to forgetfulness comes in
the form of a solar panel that attaches above the rear wheel and
provides a trickle charge as long as the sun keeps shining.
Initially, the Newport, Wales, company plans to sell Solar Drives
to bike rental concessions.
</P>
<P>
   DATING THE START OF LIFE
</P>
<P>
   A new look at old rocks from the moon reveals a surprising
correlation between meteoroid impacts and major biological events
on Earth, say researchers at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   After dating minute glass beads thrown out by impacts over the
millennia, researchers concluded that the earliest known evidence
of life on Earth coincides with the tapering off of the first peak
of bombardment of the moon by large comets and asteroids.
Presumably they also struck Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe life began on Earth many times, but the meteors only
stopped wiping it out about 3 billion years ago,'' says Paul R.
Renne, of the Berkeley Geochronology Center.
</P>
<P>
   CAMERAS REPLACE IN-ROAD SENSORS
</P>
<P>
   A waterproof camera with built-in weather-monitoring gear could
replace traffic-counting and temperature sensors now buried in
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Com One (www.com1.fr) of Cestas, France, the
Videomodem communicates with a control center via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to introduce its cameras to road departments
in the United States later this year. The Videomodem can be
equipped with fog sensors and can collect air pollution data.
</P>
<P>
   THEORY SUPPORTS EUROPA LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Scientific support is growing for the theory that primitive
aquatic life exists beneath ice-covered Europa, one of Jupiter's 16
moons.
</P>
<P>
   A new theory proposed by Christopher Chyba of Stanford
University proposes that the energy needed to create essential
biological fuels could originate from the billions of charged
particles that constantly rain down on Europa from neighboring
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know in the next 10 years if there's an ocean,'' says
Chyba. ``If there is, Europa will be the site of a series of new
space missions.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
