<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     07-17 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Taxation could use a different emphasis
 &HT;    For release July 17, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a wonderful time we live in: the president is proposing all
sorts of giveaway programs, the presidential wannabes proffer plans
designed to save us all sorts of money and the folks on Capitol
Hill keep creating new legislation designed to return some of the
huge financial largess of this nation back to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is that few of us have seen any of it, or ever hope to.
</P>
<P>
   There are the traditional, partisan-based battles over things
such as whether the elimination of estate taxes will help the
little shopkeeper as much as it will the wealthy class, and other
tax-cutting ideas of that ilk.
</P>
<P>
   So often, the argument perseveres that if things are good for
business, then they are good for the little guy who works for
business. Wasn't that Ronald Reagan's ``trickle down'' theory?
Wasn't that also called ``voodoo economics'' by none other than
George Bush?
</P>
<P>
   Make it good for the guy on the top and the guy below will do
well, too. Make it bad and the guy below suffers as well. Example:
Slam it to Big Tobacco but, wait, won't the little tobacco farmers
get hurt if Big Tobacco bites the dust?
</P>
<P>
   Recall, please, Jimmy Carter's war on the two-martini lunch a
quarter-century ago. Jimmy didn't mind business writing off some of
its pleasureful excesses as legitimate expenses but he felt it had
gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   As America suffered double-digit inflation, and the little guy
was reeling, Carter picked on those who were not, those who were
living it up and writing it off. He got nowhere. Among the
responses to his assault on figurative two-martini lunches was that
waiters and waitresses would make less money if those extravagant
lunches were eliminated from the write-off column. It scared hell
out of underpaid waiters and waitresses and his two-martini lunch
war had no allies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the extravagance of business deductions has
magnified. There is no greater example than the Super Bowl, where
corporate jets fly to the game site, outlandish parties are held
and thousands of dollars paid for tickets to a football game _ all
to appear as deductions at tax times.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and football stadiums, basketball and hockey arenas are
being constructed specifically to facilitate and lure luxury suite
and box customers, almost exclusively companies that spend hundreds
of thousands of dollars for them and then write them off as
legitimate business expenses, although little legitimate business
ever takes place in them. Much of the time, in fact, the luxury
suite is empty.
</P>
<P>
   Those millions of dollars being poured into political campaigns
by companies and their executives also are being written off at tax
time as a legitimate means of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cost of burying your mother and father, or your
husband or wife, is not given any consideration as a tax deduction.
Or is the cost of prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Someday the politicians will get serious about taxation and
correct the imperfections of the tax codes. That day is not yet
here. Primary attention continues to be given to the business
aspect of taxation and not enough to the average person who, in
recent decades, even has suffered the loss of being able to deduct
interest
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     07-17 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
