correct the imperfections of the tax codes. That day is not yet
here. Primary attention continues to be given to the business
aspect of taxation and not enough to the average person who, in
recent decades, even has suffered the loss of being able to deduct
interest paid on a car loan or department store account.
</P>
<P>
   We need someone to stress a ``trickle up'' philosophy, one that
recognizes that if it is good for the lower economic strata of the
nation, then by putting something in their pocketbooks, they might
go out and buy more and better things and make it better for
business that way.
</P>
<P>
   Estate taxes are about people with more than $600,000 to leave
behind. Burying your mother costs about $5,000 -- whether or not
you have it. And the interest on paying for it is not deductible.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
