<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-RELIGION-HNS &LR;      07-17 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S GUIDING PHILOSOPHY ON POVERTY MAY FACE PITFALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush believes social
salvation can be found in the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   When voters hear Bush on the campaign trail talking about
``compassionate conservatism,'' Bush often means increasing tax
credits so more people and corporations can deduct charitable
contributions, so more religiously inspired groups can receive
government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   God and taxes are the central tenets of the Republican
presidential hopeful's guiding philosophy. It is a new paradigm,
his campaign says, for dealing with issues such as poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to next week's Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia, Bush has turned once again to his earliest and most
potent campaign theme. But what is ``compassionate conservatism''?
And how would Bush, if he becomes president, try to change the way
America treats the poor?
</P>
<P>
   In symbol, compassionate conservatism has come to mean a
concerted effort to appeal to minority groups, such as Bush's
speech to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People last week. Bush is almost never seen on stage without an
African-American or Hispanic child nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Compassionate conservative has also come to mean Bush talking
about the environment, proposing limited government spending on
social programs and health care changes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Democratic Vice President Al Gore and Bush have spoken
in unison about the need to involve organizations, particularly
churches, with government to help the poor. Bush has spoken
frequently about marshaling the ``armies of compassion,'' just as
his father, former President George Bush, spoke about a ``thousand
points of light.''
</P>
<P>
   But religious organizations are, during this political season,
cautious about becoming ``shining anecdotes'' or political slogans,
said the Rev. Jim Wallis, the author and founder of Call to
Renewal, a network of religious church working on poverty and
social problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush and Gore want to be partners with faith-based
organizations, then we're saying you've got to put poor families
and poor kids on the political agenda,'' he said. ``We just don't
see that. If they do that, then we can talk about solving the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative commentator Arianna Huffington, who is working with
Wallis on poverty issues and is co-founder, with Bush adviser
Marvin Olasky, of the Center for Effective Compassion, said Bush's
compassionate conservative model does not put enough emphasis on
healthy government funding for effective programs.
</P>
<P>
   She said the private sector is much more interested in giving
money to fashionable museums or universities, rather than to
homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to just say, `I'm unleashing the armies of
compassion' without the government backing,'' Huffington said.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, Bush has described compassionate conservatism like
this: ``This will not be the failed compassion of towering, distant
bureaucracies. . . . It will be government that both knows its
limits and shows its heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, much of his plan is tax credits and other
government incentives to encourage charitable donations,
particularly to religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expand the ``charitable choice'' section of the 1996 federal
welfare overhaul to allow more government investment in religious
groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow people who do not itemize their taxes to deduct
charitable expenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Permit individuals older than 59 to contribute to retirement
savings to charities, without having to pay income tax on the
amount withdrawn from individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another plan would raise the cap on corporate charitable
deductions from 10 percent to 15 percent of a company's taxable
income, and provide lawsuit protection for corporate donations of
equipment or facilities to charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just slogan,'' Olasky said in an interview.
``There is a gritty reality there. There is meat on these bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush watchers and critics are wary of the overwhelming
emphasis on tax reform to solve social problems. They have heard
the same argument before from Republican candidates, and tax cuts
almost always seem to benefit the wealthy, they contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we heard a politician talk about this, it was
called `trickle-down economics,''' said the Rev. Herman Foster,
president of the NAACP Texas Hill Country chapter. ``We heard that
in the Reagan-Bush administration, but it just didn't trickle
down.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and Bush have encouraged religious organizations to
become more involved in social reconstruction, Bush believes there
should be more active collaboration between government and
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's philosophy relies to a great extent on churches,
synagogues and mosques working to solve social problems. The
government comes in as a last resort to handle the bigger problems,
or to assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell them they have to check their religious commitment
at the door, then you are discouraging a lot of people from coming
through the door, and that's not going to help poor people,'' said
Olasky, a University of Texas journalism professor and senior
fellow at the Acton Institute for the Study of Religion and
Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Erasing the traditional line between religious groups and
government bothers civil libertarians and traditional liberal
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Justice was troubled because the religious
groups, despite receiving public funding, are still allowed to
discriminate based on religious beliefs, and libertarians simply
don't like any government involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get the foot in the door with church or
religious-based activities it lends itself to be a very dangerous
thing,'' said Andrew Bernstein, a philosophy professor at Pace
University in New York who has criticized Bush's version of
compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The notion of compassionate conservatism also raises questions
about whether churches have the capacity or the will to tackle the
country's enormous social problems and whether taxpayer dollars
should be used to support these religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are talking about faith-based organizations may
have unrealistic expectations about what they are expected to do,''
said Eugene R. Tempel, executive director of Center on Philanthropy
at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups have already stepped back and said, `Wait a
minute, we're a church, we're not a social-service organization.'
Faith-based organizations also should not think that stepping
forward and accepting government money won't affect their work,
because it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Olasky said he did not know whether churches had the capacity to
respond, but that did not matter as much as the need to look at
poverty and social ills in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen over the past few years that there is a lot more
capacity than a decade ago,'' Olasky said. ``We don't know. The
reason we don't know is we've tried the top-down version, where we
go to Washington first if there is a problem. It seems to me that
we should go to Washington as a last call, not the first call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
