<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-GOP-SMITH-NYTSF &LR;      07-17 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GOP-SMITH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GHOST OF ROCKY HAUNTS PHILADELPHIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for release Sunday, July 16, 2000)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD NORTON SMITH  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unconventional convention? That's what planners of the coming
GOP coronation in Philadelphia are promising, with no stem-winding
keynoter and no interminable roll call of the states to ratify the
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Survivor Republicanism, with Pat Robertson, Alan
Keyes and most of the party's congressional leadership voted off
the island of prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Some rules, however, are inviolable. Sentiment is to national
party conventions what cleavage is to the Academy Awards. Anyone
watching the Philadelphia proceedings will be reminded most
emphatically that today's GOP is the party of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Just as surely, no convention orator will identify himself as a
Rockefeller Republican. To party loyalists, now as a generation
ago, the term is an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, however, one should pay less attention to what
politicians say than to what they do. Among the most prominent
convention speakers will be Colin Powell, whose frank avowal of his
Rockefeller sympathies earned him instant denunciation from the
gatekeepers of Republican orthodoxy while doing nothing to diminish
his near-universal voter appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the spotlight will be a host of successful governors
such as George Pataki, Tommy Thompson, John Engler and
vice-presidential prospect Tom Ridge. Though Reaganesque in their
preference for low taxes, free trade and less federal regulation,
these highly popular figures emulate Rockefeller's ambitious
approach to problem-solving at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush himself has earned high marks for reforming
education and juvenile justice in Texas. His recent appearance
before the NAACP was clearly intended to broaden his appeal to
swing voters. For months now, the presumptive Republican nominee
has been rolling out a series of proposals addressing Social
Security, health care and other areas all but ceded to the
Democrats in the past.
</P>
<P>
   That few voters can describe these initiatives in detail hardly
matters. Their cumulative effect is to strengthen Bush's claim to
be a different kind of Republican.
</P>
<P>
   How far we have come since 1981, when President Reagan asserted
in his first inaugural: ``Government is not the solution to our
problem _ government is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a claim unlikely to be repeated before delegates in
Philadelphia, or by the Bush campaign between now and Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But then George W. Bush has profited handsomely not only from
his father's mistakes, but also from Bill Clinton's successes. Just
as Reagan bequeathed to his successors a broad consensus
challenging half a century of ``Washington Knows Best,'' so
Clinton, cushioned by prosperity, has been able to nudge the center
of political gravity several degrees to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the State may have been buried, but the states thrive
as laboratories of policy innovation. Ironically, the very success
of Reaganism's devolution of power from Washington has placed a
premium on activist government _ at the grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller predicted as much, warning in a 1964 speech at
Harvard that the federal government would inevitably move to fill
any vacuum left by the states' abdication of social
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   For Reagan, government was an unwelcome camel, forever trying to
get its nose under the tent and into taxpayers' pockets. For
Rockefeller, government was one more weapon in an overstocked
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Given enough money, brains and good will, he argued, there was
no problem beyond solving. The United States could triumph in the
Cold War. The Republican Party could regain the majority status it
had known under the first Roosevelt and surrendered under the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Rockefeller's fiscal creativity, and a parallel
government made possible by quasi-public state agencies and the
miraculous power of bonds, New York's polluted waters could be
purified, its slums cleared, trains to Long Island made to run more
or less on time and Albany transformed from an eyesore into an
international showcase.
</P>
<P>
   In his sunny optimism, Reagan, the proverbial Big Tent
Republican, had more in common with his ideological opposite than
with his allies in the grimly sectarian right, for whom it was
always Midnight in America.
</P>
<P>
   A classic get-the-job-done pragmatist, Rockefeller took much of
his liberal coloration from his New York surroundings. For his
part, Reagan the revolutionary rarely forgot George Will's maxim:
``The American people are conservative. What they want to conserve
is the New Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1964, with California polls showing him trailing Barry
Goldwater, with his fundraising a joke and the candidate himself
displaying an impolitic enthusiasm for racially integrated housing,
Rockefeller's campaign manager, Stu Spencer, urged his boss to tap
the Eastern Establishment, that fabled nexus of money, influence
and condescension that for 30 years had repeatedly frustrated party
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at it, buddy,'' Rockefeller said. ``I'm all
that's left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Establishment may be history, but the Republicans could do
worse than rehabilitate a visionary politician whose favorite
adjectives were ``bold,'' ``imaginative'' and ``exciting.'' A party
disdainful of yesterday's labels, friendly to innovation and eager
to blend entrepreneurship with compassion is not your father's GOP.
</P>
<P>
   You may not hear this proclaimed from the podium in
Philadelphia, but Nelson Rockefeller's ghost must be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Norton Smith, a historian and past director of four
presidential libraries, is writing a biography of Nelson
Rockefeller.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
