<SLUG> BC-OPED-JERUSALEM-ARMSTRONG-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM: SOLVING THE UNSOLVABLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for release Sunday, July 16, 2000)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By KAREN ARMSTRONG  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most difficult issue that Ehud Barak and Yasir Arafat will
have to deal with is likely to be the future status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem has become so central to the interior landscape of
Jews, Christians and Muslims that politicians have a difficult time
engaging in a rational debate about rights and sovereignty. Even
those Israelis and Palestinians who have no religious beliefs
contend that Jerusalem is ``holy'' to them, so sacred to their
cultural and personal identity that it is beyond the normal
give-and-take of political negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could doubt Barak's commitment to peace, but he holds
fast to the claim that has acquired the force of a mantra in
Israeli politics: Jerusalem is the eternal and indivisible capital
of the State of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This policy, however understandable, is not politically
expedient. There can be no lasting peace in the Middle East unless
there is a solution for Jerusalem that will satisfy not only the
Palestinians and the Arabs, but also the whole Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem has been sacred to Muslims ever since the Prophet
Muhammad began to preach in 610 A.D. Muslims have lived and
worshiped in Jerusalem as long as Anglo-Saxons have been in
Britain, and Jerusalem is the third-holiest city of Islam. Muslims
in the Arab countries, Iran, Pakistan, central and southeast Asia
and Africa may accept a compromise, but not total, permanent
Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Muslims are likely to become more intransigent. History
shows that Jerusalem has always become more important to a people
after they have lost it and after political catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   The city only became central to Judaism after its destruction by
King Nebuchadnezzar in 586 B.C., the deportation of the Jews to
Babylon and the subsequent building of the Second Temple after
their return. But the new cult of Jerusalem became exclusive,
forbidding access to the temple not only to gentiles, but even to
Israelites who had not been exiled.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, after the Muslims lost Jerusalem to the Crusaders in
1099, the holy city became more crucial to Muslims than ever
before. When Saladin took Jerusalem from the Crusaders in 1187, the
city became far more aggressively Islamic and more wary of other
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   The situation today is particularly explosive, because there is
a clash between two peoples who have either lost or may be in the
process of losing Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Jews have returned to rule the holy city after an exile of
nearly 2,000 years. After the Holocaust, Jerusalem has become even
more sacred to Jewish identity. Many see Jewish Yerushalayim
arising phoenix-like from the ashes of Auschwitz. Jews are,
therefore, in the first flush of their reunion with the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians see Jerusalem, now surrounded by the towering
new Jewish neighborhoods, as a symbol of their own beleaguered
identity. Their exile has only just begun _ as they watch their
holy city slipping daily from their grasp, Palestinians feel a
renewed passion for Al Quds, ``the Holy.''
</P>
<P>
   This clash is exacerbated by the fact that, rightly or wrongly,
the Muslim world feels humiliated by the West, with the loss of
Jerusalem an intolerable symbol.
</P>
<P>
   After the Six Day War of 1967, the Arab-Israeli conflict was
complicated by the emergence of a new religious Zionism and a
Muslim fundamentalism that have no time for the cautious pragmatism
of security politics.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot but recall the last Middle East summit held at Camp
David, attended by President Anwar Sadat, who would be murdered in
1981 partly because he signed a peace treaty with Israel. The
assassinations of Sadat and Yitzhak Rabin, both killed by fellow
countrymen who were religious fundamentalists, remind us of the
violence and terror that is often the result of giving politics a
sacred, absolute dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither Sadat nor Rabin had to deal with anything as
potentially dangerous as the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Once an issue like Jerusalem is elevated beyond the reach of
compromise, the most extreme and immoral actions become not only
possible but ``holy'' to a disaffected minority. Great courage will
be needed to cut through the prevailing rhetoric _ but without it,
irrational mythology will prevail over sober rationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Israel began as a defiantly secular state. It was made possible,
against great odds, by the inspired pragmatism of Zionist leaders,
who accepted anything they were offered, even if it fell lamentably
short of what was required, and did not allow themselves to be
boxed in by ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem has not always been the ``eternal and indivisible''
capital of Israel. Theodor Herzl, who made Zionism a political
force, deplored the ``musty deposits of 2,000 years of inhumanity,
intolerance and foulness,'' when he visited in 1898. His first
impulse was to tear the Old City down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, during the discussion leading up to the partition of
Palestine by the United Nations, the Zionists first proposed that
they take the modern Western suburbs and cede the old city and East
Jerusalem to the Arabs. Then they agreed that Jerusalem would
become an international zone. The priority was the creation and
survival of the Jewish state, not an impracticable seizure of the
holy city of Zion.
</P>
<P>
   After the war between Israel and the Arabs in 1948, Israel
occupied West Jerusalem and agreed that Jordan should take the old
city and the eastern suburbs. It is only since 1967 that Israel has
claimed exclusive control of the whole city.
</P>
<P>
   Such exclusive policies do not work in Jerusalem. When the
Byzantine Christians gained control of the city in the fourth
century, they systematically dispossessed the pagan majority and
permanently banned Jews from Jerusalem. Their intolerant policies
alienated the local populace, and when Muslim armies invaded
Palestine in 634, Jews greeted them and gave practical help.
</P>
<P>
   When the Muslims captured Jerusalem in 638, they invited the
Jews to return to the holy city and left the Christian shrines and
residences undisturbed. Until the Crusades the city had a huge
Christian majority, and the three religions coexisted in relative
harmony. The Muslims exercised this policy not simply because the
Koran told them to respect the People of the Book, but also because
it made shrewd political sense.
</P>
<P>
   Pragmatic coexistence has worked better in Jerusalem than rigid
ideology. Is such a solution an impossible dream today?
</P>
<P>
   In 1871, the new kingdom of Italy appropriated the papal states
and confined Pius IX to the tiny city-state of the Vatican, where
he lived in high dudgeon as a self-proclaimed prisoner. Until 1937,
the popes refused to recognize the new Italy or to negotiate with
it. Today Rome is the capital of two sovereign states, which live
together in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be a model for a future Jerusalem?
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Armstrong is the London-based author of ``Jerusalem: One
City, Three Faiths'' (Knopf, 1996) and ``The Battle for God''
(Knopf, 2000).)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
