<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-LI     07-17 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLLEGE ADMISSIONS DIRECTOR TELLS THE TRUTH ABOUT ``GETTING IN''
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By ANONYMOUS (A college admissions director) 
 c.2000 New York Times
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I went to a good college and had a great experience. It's not
the type of college that raises eyebrows at a party, nor does it
require the person I'm speaking with to mentally adjust his
perception of my intelligence. But I had a tremendous time, made
lifelong friends and grew to appreciate the world in different
ways. I recall very little stress related to the
college-applications process.
</P>
<P>
   My life today is quite different. I work as the director of
admissions at a school that does raise eyebrows. The students I
meet on a daily basis seem as intelligent as my friends did 20
years ago, only much more interested in attending a distinguished
institution (read: a school with marquee value). They want
everything I wanted, but at a place that will impress everyone.
</P>
<P>
   As I see it, three factors drive the quest to enroll at the most
selective schools: prestige, parents and fit _ in that order.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to make sweeping generalizations about the world of
college admissions. One of the major themes that I convey to
parents and students during college-information nights is that
admissions is not a fair process.
</P>
<P>
   I take solace _ as you should _ in the fact that my colleagues
tend to be thoughtful, caring people. We know that this process
deflates egos and strains family relationships. However, even, our
rejections can help steer a candidate to a sound choice, especially
if fit has been as important a consideration as prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I was standing in the reception area of the admissions
office observing families progressing through the ritual known as
the multistop college tour. I noted that there was little joy in
the room. During my 14 years in college admissions, I've seen this
dynamic change. What was once an exciting time for parents to
explore new horizons with their sons and daughters has become, for
many, an almost overwhelming endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, parents looked anxious and students seemed dazed _
perhaps because they believe, in the end, that colleges
(particularly the most competitive ones) are far too unpredictable,
fickle even, in the way they determine who makes the cut.
Frequently, I find the subtext of these visits is to clear up
rumors: Is it true the university really likes my high school? Are
there vacancies in your band that will influence your
deliberations? Are you hoping to build the classics program? These
steer much of the conversation associated with college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could give unqualified answers, but I can't. And herein
lies the frustration for all those weary parents. The objectives of
an institution are like a moving target. They can change almost
annually. One cannot adequately prepare to be a top candidate for a
brand-name college by cultivating a set of skills that meet today's
priorities; tomorrow's may be very different.
</P>
<P>
   So, amid all these shifting currents, what do those of us who
make these borderline decisions value most in a candidate?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, we want to see academic commitment and initiative,
a rigorous scholastic record and demonstrated excellence in
nonclassroom activities. As admissions officers shape a class, we
realize that a diversity of talents and interests creates a
stronger learning environment. Often, though, there's an abundance
of students with attention-grabbing attributes, forcing us to
choose among thousands of compelling candidates. We ultimately
arrive at conclusions that may be seen as capricious.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, I would argue that our choices are thoughtful
and deliberate. When the orchestra conductor tells us that the
brass section is dwindling, we look extra hard for trombonists and
tuba players. The prospect of having no orchestra is even more
alarming than admitting a student whose SAT scores are well below
our average.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, it's true: as we narrow our field of candidates, most
admissions officers will give extra consideration to
underrepresented minorities, athletes in whom the school has
already shown interest and children of alumni or others who have
the potential to donate handsomely to the institution one day. Do
these factors drive the decision? Absolutely not! However, they do
influence the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Consider an applicant who's able to fill a pivotal position on
the soccer team. A blue-chip athlete might well determine the
success of a sports program. The added value of a winning team
promotes school spirit and alumni pride, something both students
and parents weigh as they assess potential colleges.
</P>
<P>
   On a larger scale, at Division I institutions a successful
football season can generate enough revenue to support every other
athletic team. College admissions is about trade-offs. I must
consider issues affecting the entire campus and its viability when
admitting candidates whose greatest strengths may be nonacademic.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues also come into play in the case of legacy
candidates. Naturally, we all hope that our alma maters will be
responsive to our children during the admissions process. We value
the family traditions we have created. And if our children are
happy with their schools, we're more inclined to support annual
giving. The benefit of these gifts can stretch to include
sponsoring endowed chairs and improving physical facilities. Again,
the responsible admissions officer cannot lose sight of the big
picture.
</P>
<P>
   If this is not always good news for students, it can be just as
disappointing for their parents. We want what's best for our
children, but we also want to be proud of their accomplishments.
However, it's been my observation that overly ambitious parents can
sometimes turn what should be four of their child's best years into
something considerably less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivy League may make for great dinner party conversation, but
is it the best match for your child? Along those lines, parents
sometimes insist that their children take test-preparation courses,
or they hire independent counselors for them. I'm not a big fan of
either, though I understand parents usually arrange for such help
with the best of intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Similar motivations have prompted many families to consider
early-decision options. Some institutions say that students who
enroll this way are happier, but I've seen few facts to support
this claim. One advantage to enrolling students early is that it
allows an institution to lower its admissions rate, bolstering its
perception as a selective (and therefore more prestigious) school.
But as you review statistics about early admissions, keep in mind
that your child may change between the autumn of his senior year
and the following spring. What appears to be an ideal choice in
October could be viewed as less so come April.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, college selection is an imprecise, fallible
process. Last year's truth is this year's unsubstantiated
assumption. So I urge parents to think about what an institution
has to offer their son or daughter before they consider the
school's name. Help your child find value in himself and his
achievements. Most important, help him understand that if he does
not attend a school with a big name, he can still have a terrific
college experience. I did.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
