<HEADLINE>
FOR THE LOVE OF LOBSTER, THE BEST OF THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of a lobster and of the White Barn Inn are
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can't get enough of the king of crustaceans, here's how
you can get your fill, regardless of where you live.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICNIC
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Seafood Direct of Rockland, Maine, will overnight its
Lobster Dinner Special _ two one-and-a-half-pound lobsters, alive
and definitely kicking _ in a freezer-pack-lined cooler. Also
included: bibs, cooking how-tos, three pounds of steamer clams, a
plump shrimp cocktail, velvety lobster bisque and, for dessert,
chocolate truffles.
</P>
<P>
   Before cooking your lobsters (we prefer steaming), cover them
with a damp towel and store them in the bottom drawer of your
refrigerator _ not in the bathtub or on ice _ for no longer than 24
hours. And don't get too attached, warns ASD's Emanuel Angelos:
``They're ornery, cutthroat critters,'' no matter how sweet and
tender the end result. $131.75, shipping included; (800) 227-1116.
</P>
<P>
   CHEFS' BESTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomas Keller, French Laundry, Yountville, Calif.; (707)
944-2380: ``We do a wonderful butter-braised lobster; braising
prevents lobster from getting tough. I also like lobster steamed
and dipped in butter _ on the dock in Stonington, Maine, the
lobster source for the French Laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Carole Peck, Good News Cafe, Woodbury, Conn.; (203) 266-4663;
``Our menu has a lobster baked macaroni that's so popular I can't
take it off the menu, even though it's a rich, wintry dish. It's
made with penne, Swiss chard, imported provolone, heavy cream and
chives, all laced with truffle oil.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonathan Cartwright, The White Barn Inn, Kennebunkport, Maine;
(207) 967-2321: ``I like to do a steamed lobster on a bed of
homemade fettuccine, with a julienne of snow peas, carrots and
ginger. It's a very simple dish, but my Cognac and coral butter
sauce makes it deliciously less so.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Freeman, The Wauwinet Inn, Nantucket,Mass.; (508)
228-0145: ``We serve lobster that's been removed from its shell and
sauteed in herb butter with lobster-caviar fettuccine, oyster
mushrooms and asparagus. We mix lobster roe into the pasta itself _
it turns the pasta red and lends it flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jasper White, Jasper's Summer Shack, Cambridge, Mass.; (617)
520-9500; ``I can't really say what my favorite way to make lobster
is _ there are so many good ways. But I do love lobster roll. It's
a humble dish, but that warm buttered roll with the cool salad on
the inside is a perfect taste experience. At Red's Eats, a little
place in Wiscasset, Maine, they give you almost a whole lobster in
each roll. That's hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST BEACH READ
</P>
<P>
   Even if it weren't the only new book set on a fictional island
off the coast of Maine peopled by gruff lobstermen and a crew of
local eccentrics as lovable as anything out of Dickens'
imagination, it would still be our favorite. ``Stern Men''
(Houghton Mifflin; $24), Elizabeth Gilbert's engaging first novel,
features a smart-talking 18-year-old heroine who spends a memorable
summer searching for her place on this granite rock 20 miles out in
the hard, cold sea. To order this book or Jasper White's cookbook,
``50 Chowders,'' call Books Now at (800) 962-6651.
</P>
<P>
   LOBSTER FACTS
</P>
<P>
   According to the Maine Lobster Promotion Council, lobster
(Homarus americanus) has fewer calories than a comparable amount of
chicken. Lobster is also low in fat and cholesterol (if you don't
dip it in butter) and high in Omega-3 fatty acids, an important
nutrient.
</P>
<P>
   Lobsters must molt in order to grow. They shed their shells an
average of 20 times over a five-to-seven-year period before they
become adults. During the molting season, roughly July to October,
they have paper-thin shells and are called ``new shell lobsters.''
Many people consider them to be more tender than those with harder
shells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homarus americanus'' is found on the East Coast of North
America from Newfoundland to North Carolina. Other kinds of
lobsters are found throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled by Anthony Barzilay Freund, Kristen Carr and Alexa
Yablonski, who are on the editorial staff of ``Town &AMP; Country''
magazine.)
</P>
