<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENTAL-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FILLINGS WERE IN FAVOR: A SHORT HISTORY OF MY TEETH
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By ANNIE LUBLINER LEHMANN 
 c.2000 New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Piece by piece my body is being plundered by time. ``Wear and
tear in exchange for experience and wisdom'' is my mother's
reasoned thinking about the physical changes that accompany aging.
And while I accept this with relative ease, I dispute the equation
vigorously when it comes to teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with good genes, many people I know smile at themselves
in their bathroom mirrors and see reflections of the same pebbly
whites that broke through their swollen 6-year-old gums five
decades before. They are like the teeth excavated by archaeologists
that bit and chewed long before the toothbrush was invented, teeth
so rich with detail they tell stories about culture right down to
what, once upon a time, constituted an evening's meal.
</P>
<P>
   These teeth _ eternity makers, I call them _ outlive their
owners by centuries. They are the kind of teeth I wish I had.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up before water was fluoridated, when floss was
considered esoteric and pain-free dentistry was oxymoronic. A candy
lover and a sloppy brusher, I spent lots of after-school time at
the dentist's office, inhaling the clove-scented air and getting my
teeth drilled. Those cavities, mini-mines of mercury-silver
amalgam, generated much income for my dentist, whose own smile
needed some serious attending to.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, I never cottoned to Dr. Levine and his fake
cheeriness. But I did grow to love Hannah, his dental assistant, a
rosy-cheeked woman who wore a stiff nurse's cap and rubber-soled
shoes that squeaked against the high-gloss floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll do better next checkup,'' she would say reassuringly as
she dabbed my welling eyes and let me grip her ringed fingers as
the dentist drilled. She inspired me to tell my junior high school
yearbook editor that my professional goal was to someday become an
oral hygienist.
</P>
<P>
   On the cusp of puberty, with barely any white enamel surface
left to fill, I moved to the next tier of dental care,
orthodonture.
</P>
<P>
   My buck-toothed smile, the result, I was told, of shameless
round-the-clock thumb sucking, would undergo six years of
restructuring. In the end I would chew more efficiently, and in the
bargain, gain a winning smile.
</P>
<P>
   My appointments for appliance adjustments were scheduled on
Fridays, after school, so that weekends often began with dull
throbbing pain and lots of aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   One particular November afternoon, everything seemed in its
place _ the gurgling fish tank, the ``Highlights'' magazines strewn
all over the floor and the wall hangings, artwork signed by the
orthodontist's wife. Instead of the usual Muzak, however, there was
talk, solemn and urgent.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kennedy is dead; we repeat, President Kennedy is
dead,'' I heard. The receptionist sobbed and the phone rang and
rang unanswered. Death and dentistry became entwined, forever
cemented.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother's teeth were gone long before her death at 93.
She wore dentures, look-alikes of the souvenir wind-up chatterers I
had won at a carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Each night she soaked them in a glass of water perched atop her
night table, a sunken treasure of pink and pearls. Before sliding
them in each morning, she looked pinched and puckered, her tongue
like a lost horse searching for its corral. But she accepted her
toothless fate good-naturedly, rarely complaining about her diet of
easy-to-swallow, baby-food-like concoctions _ soups, custards and
overcooked pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Spring, with its holiday barbecues, presented the exception. It
was the time of year when she watched us enviously as we ate our
blackened meats to the bone and husks of corn on the cob bare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is God in those kernels,'' she would say, lingering over
spoonfuls of mashed potatoes, forcing us to think about the impact
and end of simple pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   My sister, a Bavarian pretzel eater, someone who goes for the
toothsome and crunchy, recently had a permanent molar removed
because of disease that had descended into her jawbone. This
ominous reminder has pushed to full-throttle my small-scale war on
plaque, gingivitis, tartar and other Madison Avenue-fueled teeth
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   I own a top-of-the-line electric toothbrush, a WaterPik and an
arsenal of toothpastes so varied, they crowd the shelves of my
sizable medicine cabinet. To stymie the periodontal disease that
has wreaked havoc on my ascending gumline, I undergo two extra
cleanings a year.
</P>
<P>
   And while I am loath to admit it, I floss in my rearview mirror
while waiting for traffic lights to turn green. It is my vain
attempt to keep a part of me going long after I am gone.
</P>
<P>
   (Annie Lubliner Lehman writes on health for Detroit Free Press.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
