<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MEDICINE-WEB-SITES-LI     07-17 1821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-WEB-SITES-LIFEBEAT-1,400&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING HEALTH-RELATED WEB SITES YOU CAN TRUST
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A Web page from the OncoLink site is available on Newscom
or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By SUSAN COBURN 
 c.2000 Susan Coburn  
 FROM: The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Victor Strecher, the associate director for cancer
prevention and control at the University of Michigan's
Comprehensive Cancer Center in Ann Arbor, is well aware of the
profound influence of the Internet on the practice of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge numbers of my patients,'' he said, ``come in with stacks
of information from the Web and demand, `See, this is what I've
learned; now, what do you know?'''
</P>
<P>
   While Strecher said that he appreciated patients who assumed
responsibility for their own health, he noted, ``Anybody can put
anything out on the Web, and patients are inundating physicians
with all this information and expecting us to sort out the proven
from the suspected from the absolute dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a daunting task, particularly when an ever-greater number
of patients are asking time-pressed doctors to do it. Cyber
Dialogue Inc., a Manhattan Internet research firm, reported that as
of last month more than 40 million adults had used the Internet to
search for health information, an increase of 30 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Dr. Donald Palmisano, a New Orleans surgeon
and a trustee of the American Medical Association, is that given
the uneven quality of data on the Web, do-it-yourself medical
research does not necessarily make a more informed patient. Nor
does lugging journal articles to a checkup create the ideal
beginning for a productive doctor-patient
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't bring in a telephone book to your doctor and expect
him to read it and examine you at the same time,'' Palmisano said.
``But you can use the Internet to become more knowledgeable about
your disease and facilitate a more focused discussion of treatment
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Gleaning the information you need from the seemingly boundless
Web is a matter of knowing how and where to find it. The challenge
is whittling down huge online databases into a manageable quantity
of relevant information that you can discuss with your doctor.
</P>
<P>
   First, familiarize yourself with the medical terminology for the
information you are seeking. An online search for ``cancer,'' for
example, will result in an unwieldy amount of data. Narrow your
search to ``Stage IIIB breast cancer'' and your search results will
be more focused. Also, do not hesitate to ask your doctor to
recommend reliable Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   To locate useful Internet sites on your own, head to a health
directory, ideally one sponsored by the government, an educational
institution or a well-respected medical institution. In contrast to
general-purpose Internet search engines, like AltaVista, which spew
out a list of thousands of Web sites in no particular order or
format, health directories organize your search results into
categories that can be reviewed quickly. While computerized search
engines sift through thousands of Web sites for a particular term,
health directories do most of the legwork by compiling and
organizing your search results into a logical format.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health directories, for example, offer a trove of
filtered information and data. A search on the Web site
Healthfinder (www.healthfinder.gov), for example, which is
sponsored by the Department of Health and Human Services, generates
a manageable list of reliable government and nongovernment
publications, clearinghouses, databases and Web support groups on
hundreds of topics.
</P>
<P>
   You can use Healthfinder to develop a general understanding of a
diagnosis and treatment options, but watch out for some of the
site's quirks: a search for ``colon cancer,'' for example, yields
few results, while ``colorectal cancer'' locates much data.
</P>
<P>
   For intensive medical research, the directory for the National
Institutes of Health (www.nih.gov) provides free access to Medline,
a database of more than nine million references and abstracts.
Avoid information overload by limiting a Medline search to the last
two to five years, and by narrowing the search topic as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But before visiting your doctor with intriguing Medline
references, double-check the relevance of your findings with
university medical centers and well-known clinics that use the
latest technology and treatments. The University of Pennsylvania
Cancer Center's OncoLink (www.oncolink.com) provides easily
understood information on all types of cancers. The Mayo Clinic's
Health Oasis (www.mayohealth.org) offers data and guidance on a
wide range of medical conditions (including cancer), fast-breaking
health news and interactive tools like Ask the Mayo Physician and
Ask the Dietician.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations can be excellent sources of
disease-specific information. A general rule is to consult only
organizations that are recognizable and respected.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society (www.cancer.org) and the National
Alliance of Breast Cancer Organizations (www.nabco.org), for
example, offer a wealth of information, a list of questions to ask
your doctor and news on evolving cancer treatment protocols from
the National Cancer Institute. But not all nonprofit organizations
are as altruistic: a surprising number of sites are created with a
specific bias (say, toward a particular pharmaceutical brand) or
marketing agenda _ another reason to stick with well-known names.
</P>
<P>
   Though the reliability of disease-specific ``listservs,'' or
Internet mailing lists, is variable, a good list can put you in
touch with a network of patients who may provide more information
about your problem than your doctor. One source worth checking is
the Association of Cancer Online Resources (www.acor.org). Gilles
Frydman, the husband of a breast cancer survivor, created the site
several years ago when he was helping his wife research the
disease. His network of mailing lists has grown to 150.
</P>
<P>
   Dot.com fever has produced a number of commercial ventures, many
with catchy mottos and eye-catching graphics. Most of these
commercial sites, however, include the same standard offerings,
including breaking medical news, medical encyclopedias, information
on clinical trials, chat groups and ask-an-expert services to
provide answers to your basic health needs.
</P>
<P>
   Financing for commercial sites generally comes from
advertisements, sponsorships and online stores. A growing number of
sites are offering additional services and products to boost
revenues, including insurance-claims processing (linking doctors
and health insurers) and customized Web sites for doctors,
pharmaceutical companies and health care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   MedicaLogic/Medscape is one of the most popular of the
commercial ventures. Registered users of its site for
professionals, Medscape (www.medscape.com), and its site for the
lay consumer, CBSHealthWatch (www.cbshealthwatch.com), together
numbered 2.2 million at the end of March. The editor in chief for
both sites is Dr. George Lundberg, a former editor of the Journal
of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Medscape.com is a favorite of doctors because of its specialized
medical information and next-day conference summaries.
CBSHealthWatch.com, a joint venture of MedicaLogic/Medscape and CBS
News, provides a layperson's account of health issues and an
assortment of personal-health-management features, like interactive
health diaries and a nutrition calculator.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest challenge in finding health information on
the Web is assessing what you get. The Internet remains an
unregulated medium with little standing in the way of charlatans
offering misguided information cloaked in scientific jargon.
</P>
<P>
   But though no Web site is perfect, the best ones share the same
distinguishing features. You should be able to easily spot who
manages the site and how it is financed. Look for clear
identification of the writers and editors; ideally, contributors
are affiliated with respectable and longstanding academic or
medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Online health industry leaders are taking steps to provide
consumers with guidelines to evaluate Web sites. One visible effort
is the Health on the Net Foundation, a Geneva nonprofit
organization focused on improving the quality of health
information. There is no guarantee that all the material on a site
with the HON logo is accurate, but those that display it have
agreed, in principle, to certain standards of conduct pertaining to
credentials, references, confidentiality, financing and advertising
policies.
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR SIFTING THROUGH HEALTH SITES
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips on making the most out of the health
information sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY: Steer clear of sites that ask for a lot of personal
information. If you need to register to access information, study
the site's privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   DATES: Health information changes rapidly, particularly in
fields like cancer and heart disease, in which new research
findings abound. Reputable Web sites include a date for each posted
article.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIBILITY: The most clever quack sites are wrapped in cloaks
of scientific jargon. Look for peer-reviewed, published studies by
well-known academic centers or research institutions. Be wary of
personal testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   LINKS: Web sites usually have a policy on how they establish
links to other sites. Don't assume that links from a reputable site
will always lead to other reputable sites. If the link is
unfamiliar, use common sense in evaluating its information.
</P>
<P>
   SPONSORS: Running a Web site costs money. The source of funds
should be stated clearly. The best sites also clearly separate
advertisements, sponsorships and online stores from content.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Coburn writes a column on health Web sites for the
Greenwich Time.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
