<P>
   FINDING HEALTH INTERNET SITES YOU CAN TRUST
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE-WEB-SITES-LIFEBEAT _ A Manhattan Internet research firm
recently reported that more than 40 million adults have used the
Internet to search for health information. However, given the
uneven quality of data on the Web, do-it-yourself medical research
does not necessarily make a more informed patient. Gleaning
accurate information on the Web is a matter of knowing how and
where to find it. By Susan Coburn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A Web page from OncoLink is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A COLLEGE ADMISSIONS DIRECTOR TELLS THE TRUTH ABOUT ``GETTING
IN''
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-LIFEBEAT _ According to the director of
admissions at a prestigious college who chooses to write
anonymously, there are three factors that propel candidates toward
the most selective schools: prestige, parents and fit _ in that
order. There are many well-qualified students, and ``admissions is
not a fair process.'' An institution's objectives ``are like a
moving target.'' They can change almost annually as admissions
directors strive to balance the incoming class and meet the
school's needs.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN FILLINGS WERE IN FAVOR: A SHORT HISTORY OF MY TEETH
</P>
<P>
   DENTAL-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT _ The author, who ``grew up before water
was fluoridated, when floss was considered esoteric and pain-free
dentistry was oxymoronic,'' spent lots of after-school time with
her dentist and later, with her orthodontist. Now, she owns ``a
top-of-the-line electric toothbrush, a WaterPik and an arsenal of
toothpastes so varied, they crowd the shelves of my sizable
medicine cabinet.'' Knowing that a good set of choppers can survive
the owner, she says that this is her ``vain attempt to keep a part
of me going long after I am gone.'' By Annie Lubliner Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE LOVE OF LOBSTER, THE BEST OF THE BEST
</P>
<P>
   LOBSTER-FAVORITES-LIFEBEAT _ You don't have to live in New
England to enjoy a fresh lobster. You can have one shipped to you.
Some well-known chefs discuss their favorite ways of preparing and
eating lobster. For additional inspiration, the authors recommend a
book about lobstering on the Maine coast and reveal a few facts
about ``the king of crustaceans.'' Compiled by Anthony Barzilay
Freund, Kristen Carr and Alexa Yablonski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of a lobster and of the White Barn Inn
available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
