<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-SCOOPS-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF WWD, W MAGAZINE AND DNR 
 (Art is available.) 
 Culled from WWD, W magazine and DNR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 DOLCE &AMP; GABBANA COSTUMING MARY J. BLIGE'S CONCERT TOUR  
 &HT;    LOS ANGELES _ Dolce &AMP; Gabbana is hitting the concert circuit
again, this year outfitting R&AMP;B superstar Mary J. Blige for her
48-city tour.
 &HT;    Blige is strutting stages nationwide in 15 glitzy looks
specifically created by Dolce &AMP; Gabbana for her summer tour.
 &HT;    ``The Mary Show,'' as it's billed, kicked off on June 10 in Los
Angeles at the Universal Amphitheater and continued at New York's
Radio City Music Hall the following week and will include a
performance at Mandalay in Las Vegas during the MAGIC show on Aug.
26.
 &HT;    ``There was an instant attraction between us and Mary J. because
we loved her music from the minute we heard it and she liked our
designs from the first time she wore them,'' Domenico Dolce and
Stefano Gabbana said.
 &HT;    That first time Blige wore their designs, according to the pair,
was in 1994, when they outfitted the singer in a head-to-toe
ocelot-printed chiffon tunic and matching pants for her debut
album. That ensemble appeared in The Metropolitan Museum of Art's
``Rock Style'' exhibit in December.
 &HT;    Dolce &AMP; Gabbana also provided specially designed wardrobes for
Whitney Houston during her 1999 tour, as well as for Madonna
several years ago. The experience has schooled them in ``the
tricks'' required to create wardrobes that can rock and roll while
also moving and dazzling.
 &HT;    ``It is a new kind of glamour, a glamour that is wearable yet
luxurious,'' they said. ``This is achieved by the construction of
the garments and by using fabrics that are always stretch.''
 &HT;    Looks for the ``The Mary Show'' include sparkling gold
wide-ribbed stretch pants with a matching one-shoulder top and hot
pink and green pants paired with a strappy top speckled with the
same color of sequins. Everything is cut to show off Blige's
well-toned figure.
 &HT;    ``Mary J. has great style and has the remarkable ability of
taking street fashion, making it into couture, and then conveying
the message to the masses,'' the designers said.
 &HT;    So will Blige's fans get to buy a piece of that message?
 &HT;    ``Given the response that Mary J. gets when she's onstage, we
are highly considering incorporating some of these looks into our
next women's collection because they are very sexy, which is what
we find women like,'' Dolce and Gabbana said.
 &HT;    
 BODY HEAT  
 &HT;    If art imitates life, then fashion imitates sex, or that's what
happened at Gucci's recent party.
 &HT;    The party, perched on the same balcony at Milan's Stazione
Centrale where Benito Mussolini used to greet guests, may have
represented the flash point in a steamy European men's-wear season.
 &HT;    Tom Ford's guests included actress Heather Graham and ``Saturday
Night Live's'' Molly Shannon. The two were dancing back-to-back on
a tiny, raised platform when an enterprising disc jockey turned
them face-to-face, and the girls were _ as they say _ into it.
Bumping. Grinding. Turning. Churning. Hey, that's how rumors get
started.
 &HT;    At GQ's recent party at the trendy Roialto, designers Roberto
Menichetti of Burberry and Richard Bengtsson and Edward Pavlick of
Richard Edwards turned out. So did actor Matthew Modine, frontman
for Vestimenta's spirited fall campaign shot on the canals _ and,
in some cases, in the canals _ of Venice.
 &HT;    Sandy Dalal, now backed by Italy's GTR, staged his first runway
show in Milan, but the 23-year-old designer didn't turn up at the
party. Instead he sent his mother. His mother?!? Hey, Sandy, it's a
party, not a parent-teacher conference.
 &HT;    Before Milan, where Donatella Versace was sending men who looked
like boys (and boys who looked like girls) down the runway, it was
Florence, where Esquire and Pitti Uomo flew in a busload of
specialty-store retailers.
 &HT;    Marzotto had the gang for lunch at the 15th-century country
villa in the hills 20 minutes outside of Florence. Matteo Marzotto,
the 33-year-old heir to the business, piloted in his own helicopter
_ in suit and tie, no less _ to meet the group for a tour of the
billiards room and the music room, and a tasting in the wine
cellar, followed by lunch in the rotunda of the residence owned by
the Corsini Prince.
 &HT;    The New York Times feted its men's fashion editor, Robert Bryan,
at the Palazzo Peruzzi, a fitting venue for the always elegant
men's fashion director.
 &HT;    You want to throw a party in Florence? It helps to have a sense
of history, or know a family with its own history.
 &HT;    The Zegnas, Anna and Gildo, turned to one of Florence's oldest
families, the Pandolfinis, for a fitting location: the Palazzo
Pandolfini. (By old, Florence means, oh, the 13th century.) So on a
balmy summer night, the Zegnas and Esquire hosted the kind of
flawless barbecue-cum-antipasto sit-down buffet dinner that would
make a father proud on his daughter's wedding day.
 &HT;    
 ON THE ROCKS  
 &HT;    ``Poor Harry. He won't know what hit him,'' Tessa Fane said at
her husband's exhibition of Verdura jewelry at London's Mandarin
Oriental Hotel.
 &HT;    Fane wasn't talking about the jewels; she was outlining her
plans for a swimming pool and tennis court at their house in the
country.
 &HT;    Harry Fane was busy worrying about whether such guests as Lady
Victoria de Rothschild, Baron and Baroness Bentinck and the new
couple Prince Maximilian and Princess Angela of Liechtenstein were
planning to pick up a jewel or two.
 &HT;    At least Katy Tome was in the buying mood _at the strict
instructions of her absent husband.
 &HT;    ``He's so good,'' she said. ``Even if I don't want anything,
he'll insist I buy something.''
 &HT;    Many of the same guests zipped across Hyde Park to the
Dorchester Club for a late-night party to celebrate the opening of
the French jeweler Chaumet's new London boutique _ and to catch a
glimpse of Catherine Deneuve.
 &HT;    In New York, Lisa Heiden, Sandy Golinkin and Peter Bacanovic
invited a few of their friends backstage before American Ballet
Theater's ``The Taming of the Shrew.''
 &HT;    And in the Hamptons, Marjorie Gubelmann threw a dinner at Club
Colette, and the first thing her guests noticed as they arrived was
the thick string of stones hanging from her neck.
 &HT;    ``Wait a minute,'' said Jill Kopelman, ``Isn't that the...''
 &HT;    ``Yes, it is,'' Gubelmann interjected. ``'Mission: Impossible
2.'''
 &HT;    Her Bulgari necklace of pink, blue yellow and white sapphires
was the very same one that Thandie Newton, who played the cat
burglar, stole in the opening scene of the film.
 &HT;    Out on the patio, there was talk of the upcoming premiere of
``Rocky &AMP; Bullwinkle.''
 &HT;    ``Rocky? Bullwinkle?'' Bettina Zilkha cried. ``We've got to!''
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
