<HEADER>
A4397 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u l BC-TV-FASHION-TRENDS-FAI     07-17 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FASHION-TRENDS-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV VIEWERS WATCH AND WEAR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By STAN GELLERS 
 (Color art is available.) 
 From WWD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Not since the days of Don Johnson's Armani jackets on ``Miami
Vice'' or Davy Crockett's coonskin cap way back when has anything
struck America's fancy like Regis Philbin's tonal shirt-and-tie
twosome.
 &HT;    Fashion pundits might complain that the dark shirt/satin tie
combo isn't new or chide that the look isn't all that classy, but
it certainly made Father's Day for many stores around the country.
Like it or not, Regis proved once again that the TV is arguably one
of the most potent influencers and image makers for the modern
American.
 &HT;    But it's the people behind the scenes who make it happen _ the
stylists who dress the TV actors on TV and know how their clothes
make the man, and the show.
 &HT;    These Los Angeles-based professionals know their way around
Rodeo Drive and Melrose Avenue as well as New York's Madison
Avenue. They can reel off the names of the hot designers and best
brands, but they're more interested in creating the appropriate
wardrobe that adds a real lifestyle dimension to a TV character.
And they're literally playing to an audience of millions.
 &HT;    Take Dorothy Cline-Metz, a 12-year veteran in this business who
has dressed her share of game-show hosts, like the anchors on
``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``The Price Is Right.'' She's currently
dressing Bob Goen on CBS's ``Entertainment Tonight'' and calls the
assignment ``a perfect marriage between the designer and the
talent.''
 &HT;    What is it like dressing an anchor who appears every weekday
evening at 7 o'clock? Cline-Metz admits, ``It's a challenge because
you have to project a look that has to keep the producer happy and
the anchor comfortable.''
 &HT;    She gives Goen ``an anchor look _ a white dress shirt with
three- and four-button dark suits and, occasionally, a
double-breasted. We get the clothes from manufacturers and stores.
I like Perry Ellis dress shirts and ties, Kenneth Cole and
Nautica.''
 &HT;    Adds the wardrobe whiz, ``I personally like having some fun,
like putting a print tie with a Regis dark shirt and do it with a
leather blazer, or a soft shirt-jacket with a more casual feel. I'm
not tied down to a suit, and using one depends on the person I'm
working with and his likes and dislikes.''
 &HT;    And for her take on the Regis phenomenon: ``I'm not surprised it
happened because the icons we see on TV set the fashion trends, and
people are influenced by the images they see. This certainly
affects my thinking.''
 &HT;    Catherine Wagner, a costume designer who has worked for
independent producers and dressed ``Beverly Hills 90210'' for the
past two seasons, is scheduled to turn her talents to ``Titans,''
already described as the 2000 version of the over-the-top nighttime
soap of the '80s.
 &HT;    She comments, ``The new show's about very wealthy people. And
it's not as formal as `Dynasty.' `Titans' is about young, hip
people.''
 &HT;    Discussing ``90210,'' she explains that a lot of situations
happen to be about people at work and this is her rule of thumb:
``The clothes show what they do. A Wall Street type would wear a
dark, expensive suit. I feel the clothing tells you something about
the man's career. A young guy? I'd put him in a suit for work and
for a date, an open-collar shirt and trousers. I hate jeans and I
think men really underdress.''
 &HT;    She brings up another situation: ``A professional athlete doing
a press conference would probably wear some exclusive designer ...
a very expensive sweater, sport shirt and slacks.''
 &HT;    Wagner says she gets her clothes from stores and mentions names
such as Hugo Boss, Banana Republic and Club Monaco. She says, ``I'd
like to go to the showrooms, but there aren't enough in L.A.''
 &HT;    Her comment on Regis: ``It almost sounds like he invented this
monochromatic look. It's been done for years. Why is it so
important? Well, he's dressed up and not wearing another polo shirt
and khakis. People aren't dressing up any longer just for the
novelty of it, and we also have to remember that women are probably
buying many of those dark shirts.''
 &HT;    Debra McGuire, who does ``Friends,'' the long-running hit series
on NBC, has the best of two worlds. She operates her own eponymous
women's store in Pacific Palisades, Calif., and recently designed a
line of Big &AMP; Tall men's wear that will be sold on the Internet
this fall.
 &HT;    Aside from ``Friends,'' she also did ``Jesse,'' ``Judging Amy,''
``Jack &AMP; Jill'' and ``Freaks and Geeks.'' She says, ``I love them
all.''
 &HT;    When asked whether her TV clothes have any impact on the way men
dress, she confesses, ``Frankly, I work in a little bubble. I don't
think about anything else than who the character is, what he's
doing, what's been written for him and what the clothes need to
support.''
 &HT;    But for an office that enforces shirt-and-tie dressing, she
likes a ``conservative, preppie Brooks Brothers suit, but the
clothes must have a great fit.''
 &HT;    For a creative career, she likes suits or sportswear that are
``postmodern with simple, clean lines. Monochromatic is always
good.
 &HT;    ``I find corporate casual and men wearing a sport shirt in
corporate settings very odd. I'm all for casual and comfort, but I
think men are taking it to the extreme. I love casual Friday, but I
also love men in suits who dress appropriately and in a
professional way. The problem is men who dress casually really
haven't a sense of style. They often look like buffoons. Get 20 of
them together and I can't handle the visual.''
 &HT;    But fixing her gaze on the club scene, she'd use ``comfortable
casual clothes _ not sloppy _ and more body-conscious. For hanging
out? Comfortable, athletic and unself-conscious. I call it sloppy
preppie'' Which sounds a lot like ``Friends.''
 &HT;    McGuire literally uses the world for her inspiration and it
comes from ``the streets of New York, Tokyo and London.'' She also
has a long list of favorite stores: Banana Republic, Polo, Agnes
b., Tommy Hilfiger, Planet Blue, American Rag and Hugo Boss.
Preferred labels include Zegna, Paul Smith, Polo Sport, Diesel, Ted
Baker and Prada _ and not necessarily in that order.
 &HT;    Finally, her spin on the Regis look: ``I loved it until he
started wearing it. But the show is seductive and people feel he
looks stylish.''
 &HT;    That's the power of TV.
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stan Gellers is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
