<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; TUESDAY, July 18, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Developments in the Mideast
peace talks at Camp David. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-POLITICS (Cairo, Egypt) _ In his inaugural speech as
president of Syria, Bashar Assad on Monday focused on fixing his
country's ailing economy and gave no sign that he will be any more
flexible than his late father in negotiating a peace deal with
Israel. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS (Moscow) _ Boris Berezovsky, a tycoon
businessman, quit parliament Monday in protest of President
Vladimir Putin's authoritarian ways. Speculation was rife that he
will try to unite oligarchs and regional governors _ whom Putin is
squelching _ against the president. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta) _ President Abdurrahman Wahid said
Monday that he may seek international assistance to halt 18 months
of sectarian violence in the eastern Maluku islands, where rogue
army units have taken sides and joined in the intensifying clashes.
(Byline to come) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-NAZI-LABOR (Berlin) _ The agreement on compensation for
Nazi-era slave laborers was signed Monday. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM-SHEEP (Boston) _ Three flocks of sheep imported from
Belgium may be infected with a sheep equivalent of mad cow disease
and have been ordered destroyed. The disease, officially known as
bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE, affected some 180,000
head of British cattle and has been linked to a similar illness in
humans, known as Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-EEUROPE-BANKS (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney,
Robert Morgenthau, is scheduled Monday to announce the indictment
of a father-and-son team accused of taking millions from Eastern
European banks. By Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING-KITES (Undated) _ When the fighting kite flyers enter
the field of battle, they are not bearing fanciful contraptions of
balsa wood designed to swoop gracefully on curtains of wind. Their
lean fighting kites are shaped like hawk wings and have strings
coated with powdered glass, all the better to cut loose the kite of
one's opponent. By Shaila K. Dewan.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Based on the frenzied
pace of speculative construction here this summer and the frazzled
lives of craftsmen doing the building, the Hamptons have never
before been invaded by so many rich people wanting to be wowed and
demanding that it happen fast. By Blaine Harden. (This article is
tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ This fall, a few hundred books will
take a new form on the Internet. They will be sold in component
parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _ that can be mixed and
matched. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-MERGERS (Undated) _ On what comes next in the food industry
after Diageo PLC sold Pillsbury to General Mills. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MARKETS-MERGE (Undated) _ The London and Frankfurt stock
exchanges, which plan to merge, say they are also exploring a full
merger with the Nasdaq stock market. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RATES (Tokyo) _ The Bank of Japan voted Monday to leave
interest rates unchanged, citing in part the bankruptcy of the
retailer Sogo. Until Wednesday's bankruptcy filing, the central
bank had been widely expected to raise rates by a quarter point, to
0.27 percent, which would have been the first rate increase since
1990. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
