<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u l BC-DARTING-AN-ELEPHANT-D     07-17 1805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARTING-AN-ELEPHANT-DISCOVER-$ADV11-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., July 11, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is included.) 
 By JACK McCLINTOCK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    In the cool morning, Oumar the Tuareg guide announces that the
elephants might have arrived at watering holes near the
InAdyatafane oasis, so everyone piles into the Land Rovers to cross
60 miles of hot open desert.
 &HT;    Six hours later, the vehicles lurch to a stop a mile from where
the herd should be. The rest of the distance must be covered on
foot to keep from spooking the elephants.
 &HT;    Wildlife veterinarian Billy Karesh carefully screws the barrel
of his rifle into its stock and drops two fully charged anesthetic
darts into the pocket of his cargo pants.
 &HT;    He strides briskly across a desert landscape _ his senses on
full alert. A six-ton pachyderm could be just feet away.
 &HT;    ``It's easy to walk up on them by accident in the thorn scrub,''
he says. ``I don't want to encourage anybody to get close to these
elephants. It's very possible a human could die in this.''
 &HT;    The elephants Karesh hopes to track fatten themselves during the
rainy season in the lush countryside of Burkina Faso, 100 miles
south of here. When the vegetation withers in October, they wander
north to these few reliable water holes in the Gourma region just
south of Timbuktu, in Mali. It's the longest elephant migration in
Africa _ a 600-mile round trip.
 &HT;    To outsiders, the herd remains virtually unknown, but recently,
as the advancing Sahara has eroded the elephants' habitat and
nomads-turned-farmers have seized more of it to grow crops,
scientists have taken notice.
 &HT;    Karesh has come to help Anne Orlando, a wildlife biologist from
the University of California at Davis, who plans to put radio
collars on 10 elephants, track their movements over two years and
develop a conservation program.
 &HT;    Karesh is one of a half dozen globe-trotting wildlife vets, and
Orlando chose him because he knows how to fell wild animals without
injuring them.
 &HT;    Not long ago, scientists studying wildlife diseases simply shot
a few animals and studied their carcasses. But with Karesh in
charge, ``the risks to the elephants will be minimal, so I can
justify putting collars on them,'' Orlando says. She laughs. ``I
have to follow these elephants for the next two years on foot, and
I don't want them to have a bad experience, so that eventually
they'll forgive me. It's rare to find someone with his sensitivity
to animals.''
 &HT;    As the intrepid vet for the Wildlife Conservation Society based
at the Bronx Zoo in New York, Karesh has collected blood samples
from vampire bats in Peru, darted buffalo in Gabon and extracted a
mass of maggots from the festering head wound of an okapi in the
Congo.
 &HT;    ``Billy's kind of beyond real life,'' says his girlfriend,
Stacey Beard, a publicist for Neiman Marcus. ``He has a tremendous
sense of joy, he's enormously compassionate, and he's very real,
very authentic.''
 &HT;    Over the years, Karesh has brought down more than 100 elephants.
He's familiar with the calm, tourist-acclimated elephants of East
Africa. He understands their aggressive cousins in Cameroon, where
poaching is rampant.
 &HT;    He has tracked the vehicle-shy elephants of the Congo and the
hard-to-find forest elephants in the Central African Republic.
 &HT;    But Mali is different. The rangy, short-tusked desert elephants
are mysterious. One thing he does know is that they're
unpredictable.
 &HT;    And dangerous. Last year, they killed two of the goatherds.
 &HT;    As dry limbs crunch under his feet, Karesh moves from a
sun-blasted clearing into a patch of acacias, followed by Orlando
and Anders Lindgren, a technician whose Swedish firm, Televilt,
manufactured the 10 elephant-sized collars from tough fire-hose
material.
 &HT;    Behind them come Oumar, the Tuareg translator and guide, and
Samake, a uniformed Malian forestry official armed with a
high-powered rifle _ at the government's insistence, he's there to
protect Karesh if an elephant charges.
 &HT;    Karesh ignores him. No matter how dangerous the situation,
Karesh refuses to carry any weapon except his C02 rifle.
 &HT;    A hoarse cough from the bush stops him in his tracks. Then comes
a screaming roar, and everyone instinctively ducks. The first
elephant appears over the stunted treetops 90 feet away, followed
by a half dozen others and an enormous bull.
 &HT;    He trumpets, and at the sound two Tuaregs _ nomads who have
known elephants all their lives _ drop their walking sticks and
take off at a full run.
 &HT;    Karesh sets his feet, calmly raises his rifle and fires at a
medium-sized female, hitting her cleanly in the haunch.
 &HT;    Karesh yells and waves his arms to drive off the other
elephants. The herd melts away and, in the silence, there's a slow
crash as the female topples sideways into a thorn tree, shoving it
over as she falls asleep.
 &HT;    The team swarms over her warm body. She's snoring, and her feet,
big as dinner plates, shake.
 &HT;    Karesh drapes a moist blue cloth over her eyes to protect them
from the sun. He injects the dart wound with a long-lasting
antibiotic normally used to prevent mammary infections in lactating
cows.
 &HT;    Karesh inserts a pulse oximeter into her trunk to check her
heart rate (43) and blood oxygen level (95 percent). She's doing
fine and soon stops twitching.
 &HT;    Orlando begins measuring leg length, shoulder height and tusk
size, trying to estimate the animal's age. Lindgren crouches by the
elephant's head, her breath hot and wet on his face as he drapes an
eight-foot-long, 18-pound collar around her neck and fixes it there
with bolts through grommets.
 &HT;    The radio-tracking collar contains a tiny global positioning
satellite receiver linked to a memory chip. As the elephant moves
about, the collar will record her position in latitude and
longitude every two hours.
 &HT;    Every eight weeks, the collar will transmit the data to a radio
receiver, from which it can be downloaded into a laptop computer.
 &HT;    The computer, fitted with geographical software, can plot the
herd's movements on a map. Orlando can then analyze the travel
patterns of the elephants and assess their needs by plugging in
other variables, such as the location of water holes, the density
of vegetation and the movements of nomads and the goatherd.
 &HT;    The research will help her develop a conservation plan for the
Gourma-region elephants.
 &HT;    Karesh finishes examining the elephant for parasites and wounds
as Orlando measures a front leg.
 &HT;    ``I'd get that quickly,'' he says. ``We don't want her to get
overheated.''
 &HT;    He finds a vein in the elephant's ear and injects the antidote
that will wake her. The elephant shivers.
 &HT;    ``OK, I think it's time to go now,'' Karesh says.
 &HT;    Everyone backs away without taking their eyes off the trembling
elephant.
 &HT;    She's waking quickly, eyelashes fluttering and crushing the tree
beneath her as she tries to get to her feet. She waves her trunk in
the air, staggers erect and stands there dazed, swaying.
 &HT;    Karesh, Orlando and the others continue backing away. The
elephant shuffles, senses strangers, lifts her head and turns to
face them. Her eyes focus.
 &HT;    Karesh yells, ``Get the hell out of here!'' as the elephant
throws a cloud of dust into the air with her trunk and charges.
Karesh is already running. Oumar runs. A cameraman sets down his
lenses and runs.
 &HT;    The uniformed Malian official begins to raise his high-powered
rifle, then lowers it, turns and runs.
 &HT;    Panicked, everyone stumbles through the rough gullies and across
the thorn-strewn clay while the elephant crashes through the trees.
 &HT;    Finally the sound fades as she slows, turns and heads upwind to
join the herd.
 &HT;    Scattered and alone in the cover of thorny bush, people lean on
trees, catch their breath and glance around quickly, hearts
pounding. Karesh shakes his head, recalling what some local
``experts'' had proclaimed.
 &HT;    ``Oh, no, they never charge,'' he says with more than a touch of
irony.
 &HT;    The team doesn't spot a single elephant the rest of the day. In
the evening, Karesh divides the blood into ampoules and labels
them. Normally, he'd do a blood-cell count and then freeze samples
in liquid nitrogen, but a promised consignment of nitrogen hasn't
materialized.
 &HT;    ``This is Africa,'' he says, and shrugs.
 &HT;    He smears blood one cell thick on glass slides to be checked for
immune function and parasites.
 &HT;    Later, in New York, he will compare his data with that of other
scientists who monitor the incidence and spread of wildlife
diseases. More blood goes onto filter paper for genetic and
infectious-disease
 &HT;    Time and again during the research expedition, Karesh gets the
best data he can and keeps the team safe. But his concern about
elephants' unpredictability is not misplaced.
 &HT;    One day, as Oumar's 12-year-old cousin tends the family's sheep
and goats at the edge of the forest, an elephant attacks from
nowhere, crushing the boy's skull and leaving his dismembered body
scattered across the sand.
 &HT;    When Karesh arrives at the family's leather-roofed tent, all he
can do is splint the broken arm and leg of the boy's screaming
4-year-old friend, who was injured in the same attack.
 &HT;    The family shrieks in misery as Karesh hydrates the child and
tries to pull him out of shock before sending him off to what
passes for a hospital hours away across the desert.
 &HT;    For a week, Karesh can barely speak of the incident.
 &HT;    When he finally tells Beard about it, she is stunned _ and
relieved.
 &HT;    ``I'm incredibly sad for the child and the family,'' she says.
``And selfishly, I can't help thinking, `That could have been
Billy.'''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Jack McClintock is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
