<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-NIXON-TAPES-HNS &LR;      07-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-TAPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TECHNOLOGY COULD CRACK A WATERGATE MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Twenty-six years after President Richard Nixon
resigned in disgrace, an elite team of electronics specialists will
meet to discuss whether science can unravel one of the biggest
mysteries of the Watergate era: What is on the baffling 18
1/2-minute gap on one of Nixon's White House audiotapes?
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, these specialists will gather in College Park, Md.,
at the request of the National Archives, to consider whether new
technologies can resolve mysteries of the 1970s Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers want to know if it is possible to recover any of
the erased sounds on the tape, possibly shedding light on Nixon's
activities and state of mind as his presidency crumbled in the
aftermath of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the (Watergate) tape recordings were poor quality.
The microphones were hidden in the president's office and other
places, so we don't always have the best sound,'' said Susan
Cooper, spokeswoman for the National Archives, which is responsible
for maintaining federal historical records, including the
Constitution and the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason the Watergate tapes are so hard to hear is
because they are so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were purchased by the Secret Service at a local drugstore
across from the White House,'' Cooper said. ``They weren't meant to
be kept for posterity; They were meant for the president's personal
use in writing his memoirs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest shocks of the Watergate scandal came in 1973,
when a former Nixon White House official, Alexander Butterfield,
told a congressional committee about the president's secret
audiotape network in his White House office.
</P>
<P>
   A battle ensued for the tapes, which might have revealed what
Nixon and his aides were up to before and during Watergate, which
involved accusations of break-ins, payoffs, cover-ups and other
misdeeds by White House employees.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon fought attempts to release copies of the tapes. But in the
summer of 1974, the U.S. Supreme Court unanimously ordered him to
do so. He complied, and resigned several days later, on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Long before then, investigators had learned that one of the
tapes contained the 18 1/2-minute gap. Nixon's secretary, Rose Mary
Woods, admitted erasing part of that section of the tape.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, experts tried unsuccessfully to extract
intelligible sounds from the erased section.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, technologies for tape analysis have improved
greatly. That is why the National Archives is assembling the expert
panel, whose names are confidential for now, to see whether
prospects today are better.
</P>
<P>
   If so, National Archives officials will face a far tougher
question: Should they actually turn over the tape to the scientists
for study?
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate tapes are so delicate that they are kept in a
frigid room in the National Archives office in College Park, a
Washington suburb. The chill lessens the risk of damage due to heat
and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most promising technologies is called a
magnetoresistive microscope. By mapping magnetic-field variations
on audiotapes and computer disk drives, the gadget can detect
evidence of tampering. It can also recover some erased information.
</P>
<P>
   Before the work can be done, however, officials must be sure the
technology cannot damage the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that talk of a re-analysis of the tapes is
``extremely preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first commitment, our first priority,'' Cooper said, ``is
to make sure we preserve that tape. . . . As I'm sure you can
appreciate, we have to take this very slowly. This (tape) is an
artifact with high intrinsic value. And we're not going to subject
it to any and all technologies just for the love of science. We
have to be very careful how we proceed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
