<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-AGGREGATION-BOS     07-17 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-AGGREGATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING ALL OF YOUR FINANCIAL STUFF IN ONE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of people still get jittery at the thought of giving
credit-card numbers or bank-account information to Web sites. They
imagine, with some justification, the nastiness cyber-thieves could
inflict on their personal finances.
</P>
<P>
   I am not one of those people.
</P>
<P>
   For me, any online service that saves time or simplifies my life
is a good service. Laziness, in other words, trumps caution.
</P>
<P>
   The next big thing in Web finance promises to get both Nervous
Nellies and folks like me excited, if for very different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   So-called aggregation services put all of a person's financial
information on a single Internet site behind a single password.
Using a process known as ``screen scraping,'' they log on to all of
your financial accounts, often nightly, and download the
information to a central place.
</P>
<P>
   The services might, for example, spider through your various
mutual funds, checking and savings accounts, frequent-flier
accounts, and even credit-card statements. The idea is to list your
account balances and recent transactions on a single, personalized
Web page.
</P>
<P>
   That strikes me as a great way to save time and energy, but it
also raises significant privacy questions and creates a galaxy of
juicy targets for would-be identity thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, security concerns wildly outweigh concerns over
privacy,'' said Octavio Marenzi, an analyst with Celent
Communications. ``But (aggregators) are just so convenient that
we're seeing the number of users grow 10 to 15 percent per week.''
</P>
<P>
   Unheard of a year ago, aggregation sites now number more than
two dozen. Between 400,000 and 500,000 Americans use them already,
and a recent Celent study forecasts 7 million regular users by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   That prediction, though, came before Chase Manhattan Bank
announced last month it was teaming up with Yodlee.com to offer
all-in-one-place service to its 30 million online customers. Other
banks and brokerages will almost certainly announce similar
ventures in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a natural progression of financial services
online,'' said Jaime Punishill, an analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge. ``The first stage involved basic transactions, the next
is bringing all your accounts together in one location.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's the best part: Most of the sites are free, at least
for now. Financial institutions such as Chase Manhattan pay the
freight to give their clients access to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a valuable service for people whose Internet lives have
become very complicated,'' Marenzi said. ``Remembering all those
passwords and taking time to visit all those sites is a problem for
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for critics is that you have to give aggregators
your account names and passwords for the process to work. That
alarms privacy advocates, who don't like the thought of giving one
company access to your entire financial life, and security pros,
who worry that hackers will someday gain access to financial
dossiers on millions of unsuspecting people.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to those concerns, aggregators have begun to partner with
old-line financial companies rather than market themselves directly
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Early adopters, Marenzi said, primarily came to the services
through Web portals such as Lycos. But most future customers, he
said, are likely to stumble across aggregators by going through
another institution, such as Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage is that customers already trust banks, brokerages,
and insurance companies with their money. Those institutions also
have the resources to cover their customers in the event of cyber
theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of amazing that anybody would go to a company named
Yodlee and put information about their life's savings there for the
taking,'' Marenzi said. ``That is going to be incomprehensible to
many people, but those same people might be perfectly happy to use
Yodlee's service through their bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry is also starting to grow and mature in ways other
than distribution.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of aggregators are developing services that allow
customers to analyze their combined accounts and, eventually, make
changes as needed. Others are beginning to aggregate information
for the benefit of specific, niche audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Woburn-based ByAllAccounts.com, which launched its aggregation
service this week, is doing both. It specifically targets investors
who want to analyze their far-flung holdings, comparing them
against model portfolios using factors such as risk and
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't sign up for ByAllAccount's WebPortfolio service at
the company's Web site. It will be available, said chief executive
L. Patrick Gardner, only through financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to try an aggregator on your own, a handful of
others let you sign up directly:
</P>
<P>
   --www.yodlee.com is the early leader in the industry. It offers
to pull information from a wide range of services, not all related
to money.
</P>
<P>
   Yodlee, which pulled its name from a Hindi song with the phrase
``Yahoo, Junglee, Yodlee,'' aggregates financial accounts, e-mail,
news, and frequent-flier programs, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't show transaction histories, though, and has
relatively few tools for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   --www.ebalance.com doesn't aggregate information from as many
sites as Yodlee, but it offers more in the way of investment
research and tools. You can, for example, record and categorize
transactions, use financial calculators, and be alerted to analyst
changes in stocks you follow.
</P>
<P>
   --www.1ViewNetwork.com also focuses more on investors than a
general audience. As added bonuses, it allows you to download your
information to Microsoft Excel spreadsheets (so you can sort the
numbers as you see fit) and give financial advisers access to the
numbers (so they can make recommendations).
</P>
<P>
   If you like, it will also send you e-mail notes when account
balances run low or stocks you monitor hit predetermined prices.
</P>
<P>
   --www.ezlogin.com is more of a bare-bones aggregation site, with
no transaction history and only a handful of tools. You can,
though, set up multiple profiles, in case you want to look at
things differently at different times.
</P>
<P>
   --www.GainsKeeper.com is a different animal entirely.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it's not free. After a 30-day trial period, you'll
have to pay $35 to $199 annually for a membership, depending on how
active an investor you are.
</P>
<P>
   Also unlike the other aggregators, GainsKeeper is geared
specifically to simplifying investors' tax lives. It tracks
purchases, sales, splits, and mergers, in addition to pulling all
of your brokerage accounts and mutual funds together in a central
location.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
