<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AFRICA-NEW-RIGHT-BOS &LR;      07-17 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-NEW-RIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXING AFRICA _ IN OUR MINDS, FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woe, woe is Africa.
</P>
<P>
   There is the corruption and the revolution, to say nothing of
the obvious and onerous legacy of the colonial centuries,
compounded by decades in which Africa's nations were, in the truest
sense, pawns in the Cold War chess match. There is AIDS, on the
scale of a Middle Ages plague, and, of course, there is famine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the continent is such a huge mess that voices on the
political right are suggesting a new round of colonialism _ of
benign and humanitarian intent, to be sure _ as the only way to get
the African nations moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   George B. N. Ayittey, a Ghanaian and economics professor whose
columns appear on the op-ed page of The Wall Street Journal, writes
that it may be time for the establishment of ``free economic
zones'' in select African countries that would lure businesses with
tax breaks and waivers on duties. In exchange, the host governments
would essentially give up sovereignty in significant portions of
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Governments unenthusiastic about trading territory for the
promise of foreign assistance likely could be persuaded to give up
``say, 30 square miles . . . for, say, 20 years'' in return for
forgiveness of part of their vast international debt, Ayittey
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a lot like what the Western powers did in China in the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Others stand ready to go considerably farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I)t's time we revisited the notion of a new kind of
colonialism _ though we shouldn't call it that,'' writes Jonah
Goldberg, an editor at National Review Inline, asserting that the
United States ought to be ``going in _ guns blazing if necessary _
for truth and justice. . . . The United States should mount a
serious effort to bring civilization (yes, ``Civilization'') to
those parts of Africa that are in Hobbesian despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Hage Geingud, the prime minister of Namibia, has a one-word
description for what he believes is at the root of such proposals:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ignorance,'' Geingud says. ``They maybe really think Africa is
hapless, they maybe really think that Africa is lost. Had they been
informed, I think they wouldn't have come to such a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   But decades of effort to establish an understanding,
appreciation, and affinity for Africa among Americans have not made
much progress, many scholars and educators say; the dominant view
of Africa in this country remains rooted in Tarzan films and the
writings of adventurers and journalists the likes of Henry Morton
Stanley and Joseph Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white American cultural self-image is strongly reaffirmed
in Tarzan movies, while Africa is a blank slate for them to project
unfavorable images of the opposite of themselves _ wall-to-wall
incompetence, disorder, and danger,'' says James Lorand Matory, an
Africanist and professor of anthropology at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Lesego Malepe, a South African professor of African politics at
Wheaton College, says the American tendency to view Africa as an
undifferentiated mass also springs from the country's experience
with slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped to partially justify such a horrible thing as
slavery, to portray the places the slaves were coming from as very
dark and uncivilized,'' Malepe says. ``So there was this idea that
slaves were from Africa, not from a country or a tribe. The first
problem is getting people to think of Africa as a continent, not a
country.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 54 nations in Africa, some of which _ like Namibia,
the last colony, and Eritrea, which was moshed into Ethiopia by the
United Nations _ have gained independence only in the last decade.
Almost none was independent before World War II. About 15 have
governance that is substantially democratic. About 10 are the scene
of armed conflict either internally or with neighbors. Politically,
culturally, and economically, these nations are in tremendously
varied states of becoming.
</P>
<P>
   But ``what similarities exist between Botswana and Liberia?''
says Malepe. ``Really, very little.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Americans do not appreciate the diversity found among
African countries is that, unlike Europe and Asia, there is no
clear reason for Americans to focus on Africa. For while many in
the United States can trace their ancestors to England, or Italy,
or Germany for instance, the institution of slavery destroyed most
black Americans' chances of ever tracing their roots to Senegal, or
Congo, or Nigeria. And while most Americans who are aware of the
waves of technology and globalization transforming the world
understand keenly some of the differences between, say, China and
Japan, movement toward postindustrial, information-based societies
has reduced the importance of knowing which nations produce copper
and which gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places that are highly differentiated because they
are very important to the geopolitical interests of US political
elites, US capitalist elites, and journalists who spend their time
talking with government officials, and following the course of
economic negotiations and developments,'' Matory says. But ``there
is not all that much difference among US political and economic
interests toward sub-Saharan African countries, except South
Africa. That is why South Africa is talked of as a country, while
the rest of sub-Saharan Africa is lumped together, and Arab Africa
is lumped together as part of the Middle East. Most Americans
wouldn't know the difference between Iran and Libya either.''
</P>
<P>
   A colloquialism often heard in Washington about why African
nations do not have high profiles in US policy or media goes like
this: They are no threat to us, they don't make anything we need,
and they are not a top priority for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Brown, a Bunting Fellow at Radcliffe who works on
Africa-related education programs through Boston University's
Center for African Studies, says that though some African Americans
take pride in the kingdoms, cultures, and music of Africa, young
students ``whether second graders or tenth graders, arrive in class
thinking Africa is yukky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers tell me African American students feel uncomfortable
about Africa,'' Brown said. ``They see Africa as failed, and are
uncomfortable with the association.''
</P>
<P>
   Among students, ordinary citizens, and perhaps pundits too,
``there is a naive and incorrect assumption that Africans have been
running the show in Africa since independence, and that is just not
the case,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say Africa needs to be recolonized or taken over by the
West ignores the fact that the West has been one of the major
players'' all along. ``We kept Mobutu (Sese Seko of Zaire) in power
for years. We kept (South Africa's racist system of) apartheid in
power, along with local interests. We helped overthrow the
government in Uganda. We have never not intervened in Africa . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   But intervention of a far deeper variety is what the proponents
of a new neo-colonialism have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ayittey suggests that American aid be made
contingent on a country having a strong central bank, and
independent media, courts, and security forces.
</P>
<P>
   In some nations, even that medicine would be too mild. In a
recent Journal column, he proposed that the United Nations simply
take over war-torn Sierra Leone, spend whatever was needed to clean
out the country's twin scourges _ warlords and economic locusts _
and sell off as much of the country's diamond deposits as necessary
to cover the tab.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, advocates of a new colonialism reject the
proposal _ espoused by a forces ranging from Pope John Paul II to
President Clinton to the recent World Bank-International Monetary
Fund protesters _ to forgive African nations' probably
forever-unpayable debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, perhaps the real first problem has much more to do
with the United States than with the continent of Africa or its
nations. Among both Africanists and conservative pundits, there are
those who feel the US is fumbling for a grand-enough project for
its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``American policymaking is still reeling from the absence of the
Cold War, from its inability to define national interest and
strategy,'' Malepe says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems foreign policy is up for grabs,'' writes the National
Review's Goldberg. ``The internationalist Right has some good
rhetoric . . . but they are hard-pressed to lose their Cold War
baggage. Spending billions and spilling American blood in Africa
``would be imperial . . . French writers would break their pencils
in defiance . . . Kofi Annan would need a pacemaker. Pat Buchanan
would move to Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he concludes, citing the British Empire's efforts against
slavery, ``being imperial is not necessarily a bad thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
