<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAREGIVERS-TRUST-BOS &LR;      07-17 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREGIVERS-TRUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARY PARENTS USING CAMERAS, CRIMINAL CHECKS ON CAREGIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some parents insist on reviewing criminal records, even of
part-time baby sitters. Some want a constant eye, choosing day care
centers with Web video cameras. Others go to the extreme of
declaring they would never hire a man to baby-sit, saying data show
sexual predators are overwhelmingly male.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's discrimination. I feel awful saying it,'' said Kim
Arnold, a 34-year-old mother of a toddler. ``But I go with females.
All the statistics show that sexual abusers are usually men.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioning their knack for judging others, parents more than
ever are seeking the power of raw information to assess the adults
in their children's lives. Gut instinct _ that mixture of visual
and verbal cues that create impressions _ hasn't been abandoned,
but is viewed as far less foolproof as a way to screen caretakers,
coaches, and counselors.
</P>
<P>
   In this highly mobile and diverse society, parents say it's hard
to get credible information about a person's trustworthiness. And
with so many working parents and children in a flurry of
activities, parents depend on unknown adults more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relying on intuition, worried parents have fueled a
sevenfold increase in the number of criminal background checks of
child-care applicants processed by the state since 1973. Many also
ask for repeat interviews of child-care workers and engage in
exhaustive reference checks.
</P>
<P>
   Others have a modified-avoidance strategy. Julie Puncochar, a
mother of two, said she now works part-time as a pediatrician,
cutting back her hours in part because she couldn't bear the
anxiety that comes with full-time child-care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved of the burden,'' she said. ``If there's
full-time care, there seems a greater chance that something could
be amiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually the likelihood that a child could fall victim to child
abuse appears to be low. State figures show there was a 1 in 5,000
chance last year that a child would be abused by a non-family
caretaker, such as a child-care worker, teacher, or youth counselor
_ similar to the odds that a person would die in an auto accident
in a given year.
</P>
<P>
   The odds that a relative would abuse a child physically or
sexually was about 50 times higher, according to state figures on
substantiated abuse cases in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents and child-abuse specialists suspect the rate of
abuse is actually far higher; others are sure it's not as bad as it
seems. Regardless, many parents try to fall somewhere between being
obsessive and oblivious, then work for better ways to navigate the
world of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Given wide publicity of many notorious child-abuse cases,
parents have long had an eroding sense of confidence in their
ability to judge trustworthiness. And it may have hit an all-time
low recently with allegations about Christopher Reardon in
Middleton, Mass. If this newlywed youth minister and camp leader
who grew up in a well-respected local family is the sexual predator
he is charged as being, who among us couldn't be fooled?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become less trusting over time,'' said Linda Post, a
Westwood bond trader and a mother of a 7-year-old boy. ``You hear
so many bad things happening. There's always anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioning our gut instincts may be a good thing, say some
psychologists, because people so often allow wishful thinking to
sweeten their impression of people. They said people are often
unconsciously affected by looks, such as adult faces with
child-like features are often viewed as more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As human beings, we're easily duped,'' said Colgate University
psychology professor Caroline Keating, who specializes in the study
of deception. ``We have a truth bias. We see what we already
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists say gut instincts, while still important, are
often influenced by mistaken impressions. Some parents assume
sexual predators or physical abusers will have telltale signs, like
shifty eyes or disheveled clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we should have a preconceived idea of what a
pedophile looks like. Or what mentally ill people look like. We
don't always know,'' said Elizabeth Childs, a child psychiatrist
who recently hired a part-time nanny to watch her infant.
</P>
<P>
   While some specialists in nonverbal behavior say people who
avoid direct eye contact may be lying, others say these cues are
worthless. Colgate researcher Keating conducted a study showing
adults have only a slightly better than 50-50 chance of
distinguishing between video footage of someone lying or telling
the truth, odds that she noted were ``only slightly better than a
flip of the coin.''
</P>
<P>
   She ran studies showing people often let visual signs lead them
astray. For instance, adults with baby-like faces, such as large
eyes, long lashes, smooth skin and soft chins, are often viewed as
more trustworthy than others.
</P>
<P>
   During President Clinton's sex scandal, Keating showed pictures
of his face with digitized distortions. The ones that made him look
more child-like were viewed as more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of confidence in gut instinct is why some parents
devise their own play-it-safe strategies, including the no-male
hiring policy for babysitters. Even the past president of the
Massachusetts Psychiatric Society, Jerome Rogoff, recently said,
given the choices of two equally good candidates, one male and one
female, to baby-sit a hypothetical grandchild, he would choose the
female.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys are more likely to offend sexually and violently,'' he
said, referring to statistics that do show that more than 90
percent of those arrested for sexual crimes are men.
</P>
<P>
   On this point, others offer a different view. William Pollack, a
clinical psychologist and author of ``Real Boys,'' a book about boy
development, concedes that men are the perpetrators of most sexual
crimes. But, he said, parents must remember the benefit of having
male role models for children.
</P>
<P>
   Child-care specialists and psychologists say if parents have the
time and know-how to ask the right questions, they can expand their
odds for finding trusting adults.
</P>
<P>
   While specialists say parents shouldn't abandon their
intuitions, they emphasize that dispassionate information-gathering
is a good thing. They say collecting as much information on a
caretaker's personal history is key, making sure the pieces all fit
and there are not any strange gaps in a resume.
</P>
<P>
   Some child psychologists said it's important to make sure a
caretaker's interest in children reflects a mature decision, not
that they are child-like themselves and want to exist in a world of
emotional peers. They also say parents should worry about
caretakers who want to spend a lot of time alone with a child, when
their activities would normally put them in groups.
</P>
<P>
   Child-care agencies have also detected that parents feel a
slipping sense of resolve about their own intuition, often asking
for repeat face-to-face interviews. They said criminal background
checks, even of part-time babysitters, is standard industry
practice, even though it was a rarity a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Morrison, 36, said she chose a day care center with Web
video cameras so she could get firsthand information about her
son's day. She said she believes day-care workers under
surveillance will be on the best behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the cameras are there will deter them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents say that, while they aggressively seek out new
information, they know a risk-free world for children is impossible
and trying to create one would be tantamount to locking the doors
and living in a prison.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Lamkin, a Middleton neighbor of Reardon, said many local
parents like him thought Reardon was a kind man who was dedicated
to youth. Despite his sense of betrayal, Lamkin said parents like
him have to find way to tolerate the risks involved in raising
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to live your life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-BOS &LR;      07-17 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TACTICS SHIFT SENTIMENT ON ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Right to Life Committee's campaign to
outlaw what it calls ``partial-birth'' abortions got derailed in
the US Supreme Court last month. But the antiabortion movement's
larger strategy _ to shape and sway public opinion against abortion
rights via graphic debate has not lost ground. In fact, it is
solidly on track.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are not as sure about abortion rights as they were a
decade ago. According to a Los Angeles Times poll conducted last
month, 43 percent of those surveyed said they supported Roe v.
Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court decision that legalized abortion.
That's down from 56 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Just as significant in the Times poll is the finding that 65
percent of the respondents, and 72 percent of women, believe
abortions should not be available in the second trimester (the 13th
through the 26th week) of pregnancy. Asked if abortion should be
severely restricted _ that is, legal only in in cases of rape,
incest, and to save the mother's life _ 46 percent said yes. On
either side of that position, 43 percent said abortion should be
``always legal,'' and 8 percent said it should be ``always
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The erosion of support for legal abortion coincides almost
exactly with a repositioning in the early 1990s of
antiabortion-rights forces away from an all-out assault on Roe,
which had failed, to more calculated attacks on certain abortion
methods and on the point in pregnancy when the procedure takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, antiabortion-rights groups began to dramatize and
demonize a relatively rare, gruesome-sounding second-trimester
procedure known in medical terms as ``dilation and extraction,'' or
D&AMP;X. Instead of dismembering the fetus in the womb (the more common
``dilation and evacuation'' abortion technique) a physician
performing a D&AMP;X pulls the fetus, intact and up to its head, into
the birth canal. Because the head is too large to pass through an
undilated cervix, the doctor uses an instrument to collapse the
skull and remove its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion doctors prefer other methods but use D&AMP;X when the
health of the mother warrants it. In cases in which the fetus is
found to be severely deformed, for example, a D&AMP;X can be the
preferred prodecure.
</P>
<P>
   Antiabortion-rights activists created an attention-getting, less
clinical name for D&AMP;X _ ``partial-birth abortion'' _ and they did
not correct the media for calling it a late-term procedure, even
though it is performed most often to abort nonviable fetuses in the
12th to 24th week of gestation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did antiabortion-rights activists object when politicians,
sensing voter disgust with a procedure being portrayed as
infanticide, pushed through bans of the procedure in 30 states.
Abortion-rights advocates, convinced their foes' strategy was to
end abortion by restricting access to it, could not wait for the
Supreme Court to put one of these laws to Roe's constitutional
test.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor was the swing vote on June 28 when,
in Stenberg v. Carhart, the court struck down the state of
Nebraska's ban on that abortion method. The ban might have passed
constitutional muster if it applied specifically to the D&AMP;X method
and made an exception in cases where a woman's health was at risk,
O'Connor said. Instead, the language was so vague that it
potentially banned most procedures for second-trimester abortions,
which are allowed under Roe, and put an ``undue burden'' on a
woman, restricting her right to choose to end her pregnancy before
the fetus is viable, O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's opinion was consistent with the high court's two key
abortion precedents: Roe, which gave women the constitutional right
to have an abortion, and Planned Parenthood of Southeastern Pa. v.
Casey, a 1992 decision that held states cannot put ``substantial
obstacles'' in the path of a woman exercising that right.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia's dissent in Stenberg was out of sync
with court precedent but perhaps more in step with the country's
moral climate when he wrote that ``the method of killing a human
child _ one cannot even accurately say an entirely unborn human
child _ proscribed by (Nebraska's) statute is so horrible that the
most clinical description of it evokes a shudder of revulsion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that the Constitution of the United States,
designed, among other things, `to establish justice, insure
domestic tranquility . . . and secure blessings of liberty to
ourselves and our posterity' prohibits the state from simply
banning this visibly brutal means of eliminating our half-born
posterity is quite simply absurd,'' Scalia wrote. ``If only for the
sake of its own preservation, the court should return this matter
to the people and let them decide, state by state, whether this
practice should be allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the closeness of the vote assures that abortion
will be on the agenda in the fall presidential campaign; the next
president's Supreme Court nominations could reverse the court's
balance on the issue. And far from giving up the legislative fight,
abortion rights opponents believe Congress will send a bill banning
D&AMP;X-method abortions to President Clinton, who twice has vetoed
similar measures, right before the November election.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom holds that because of strong public
support for keeping abortions legal, Vice President Al Gore, who
supports abortion rights, benefits if the issue gains altitude in
his contest with Texas Governor George W. Bush, who opposes
abortion rights. But conventional wisdom may be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If the polls are any guide, Americans want restrictions on
abortion. According to the Los Angeles Times poll, which has a
sampling error of plus or minus 2 percent, 49 percent of those
surveyed believe women should have the consent of the biological
father before an abortion, and 82 percent say girls under 18 should
have the permission of a parent. A majority oppose public money
being used to pay for abortions for poor women; 85 percent believe
women should be allowed abortions if their physical health is at
risk, but fewer _ 54 percent _ would permit abortions when the
woman's emotional health is seriously endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, women in the poll support abortion in cases of
rape and incest, but oppose it after the first trimester of
pregnancy. Their conflicting values also show up when 61 percent of
women say abortion is murder and 68 percent say abortion would not
be an option for them; at the same time, they feel the abortion
decision should be private, made by a woman and her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Karlyn Bowman, a researcher at the American Enterprise
Institute, has detected a shift in public attitudes against
abortion, and she attributes it to three things. One is the debate
over the D&AMP;X method; a second is the widespread use of precision
sonography that gives pregnant women a clearer picture of fetal
development; and a third is the trend to delay childbearing. ``It's
been suggested that as older couples experience problems with
conception, they have more of a sense of the preciousness of
life,'' Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation is that many Americans, including a
generation born after the Roe decision, simply do not understand
that the landmark ruling left room for states to limit access to
abortion. Roe is not an abortion license; the Supreme Court has
ruled that states can impose restrictions, including
parental-notification rules, 24-hour waiting periods, and bans on
third-trimester abortions, when the fetus is viable. And states
have done just that; in many regions, access to abortion is
difficult, at some distance away, or for other reasons, nearly
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents have framed the debate to make people believe you
can't have restrictions on abortion without overturning Roe, and
that has caused public opinion to shift against Roe,'' said Bob
Blendon, a professor of health policy at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion and complex emotions make abortion dangerous turf
for the presidential candidates. Bush, who opposes abortion except
in cases of rape, incest, and the mother's health and supports
banning the D&AMP;X method, has won the National Right to Life
Committee's endorsement. But he is being careful not to sound too
strident to married, suburban women who do not want all abortions
outlawed. Gore is more assertive about his support for abortion
rights, but his vow to appoint justices who will uphold Roe could
turn off voters who believe the Supreme Court already has veered
too far in protecting the right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, more than 60 percent of those surveyed by the Los
Angeles Times said they did not know the presidential candidates'
positions on abortion. Once they do, it could have consequences,
since 31 percent of men and 37 percent of women said they would
switch their vote to the candidate who shares their views.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
