<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TRAGEDY, COUPLE NEEDS TO DIVERSIFY INVESTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. Tragedy struck, and we had to liquidate all assets to pay
off huge medical bills. This included our home, our savings, the
cash value of insurance policies, and our retirement plans. So we
are starting over.
</P>
<P>
   I will probably never be able to work again. After being laid
off, my husband has a new job and became eligible for the 401(k) in
April, and he anticipates a bonus this year.
</P>
<P>
   An inheritance let us put $13,000 in a CD, which we treat as our
emergency fund. After paying off $2,000 of the medical bills each
month, there is nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   Where should we invest? Clearly, we have very little time to buy
a house and save for retirement. Have we selected the right 401(k)
funds? After the medical debt is paid off, where should we invest?
We are frugal people and committed to investing as much as
possible. Should we lower the amount we are paying on the debt and
begin investing now? Should I start an IRA, even though we would
not qualify for a deduction?
</P>
<P>
   G.A., Eugene, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Please accept my consolations. It will be a long road back,
but you sound like the kind of people who rise to challenges.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, your retirement savings are going into the
401(k), so let's start there. Although you use five funds, they all
focus on large-cap domestic stocks. That, of course, has been the
place to be recently, but it's a poor long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you add positions representing 10 percent of the
portfolio in two of the other options that would broaden your
market diversification: the Principal Mid-Cap Index and Fidelity
Overseas funds. I would do this by reducing the American Century
Ultra holding to 20 percent, cutting the two Fidelity offerings to
15 percent, and cutting the Principal Large-Cap Index position to
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   My instinct, given the current market, would be to stick with
the 401(k) contributions and your current course of paying off the
medical bills as quickly as you can. The prospects for general
market gains in excess of 10 percent a year are pretty dim over the
course of the next 16 months, and paying off the medical bills
strikes me as a much more certain proposition. At that point you
could both begin Roth IRAs, which would eventually provide you with
tax-free income in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   As for investing after you the medical bills are paid off, I
suggest a portfolio made up mostly of Vanguard Index funds plus the
Vanguard Health Care fund. The latter, since it has the highest
potential for gain, would be the appropriate investment for the
Roth IRA accounts _ and of course you know from your own experience
the way the health care industry can generate
</P>
<P>
   profits.
</P>
<P>
   As for the balance, I would put 50 percent in Vanguard Index
500, 20 percent each in Vanguards Mid-Cap Index and Small-Cap Index
funds, and 10 percent in Vanguard International Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently, my company was bought by another. I don't know how
good the new company is. I would like to take my money out of my
401(k) and invest in other financial ventures. Would you recommend
any other financial institution?
</P>
<P>
   V.T., Fountain Valley, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The trick is not to take money out, but to transfer it. If
you just take the money out of your 401(k), that would amount to a
withdrawal, and that amount would be added to your taxable income
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do with no short-term tax consequences is to move
the money into a rollover IRA. Have the new company that you will
be doing business with present the paperwork directly to the
managers of your old company's 401(k) plan, who will then send the
funds to your new institution.
</P>
<P>
   You could easily replicate your current portfolio at Vanguard by
taking a 20 percent position in Vanguard's Total Bond Market Index
fund, 30 percent in Vanguard Balanced Index fund, 30 percent in
Vanguard Index 500, and 20 percent in Vanguard Small-Cap Index
fund. But I'd break the final segment into two parts, putting 10
percent in Vanguard Small-Cap Index and the other 10 percent in
Vanguard Mid-Cap Index. This would give you better market
representation.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of a rollover IRA is that as long as you do not
add other funds to these accounts, you can at any future date merge
these funds into another 401(k), if you choose. Perhaps at some
point you will be more certain of your new employer, and be offered
some financial incentive for building your 401(k) account with it.
So if you now have other IRA accounts, or decide to open some, make
sure the rollover IRA is kept separate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Q. I'd like to start investing. I have thought about stocks and
mutual funds, but I don't know if that would be a good start. I
have been told that stocks are a good investment, but risky. I have
a few CDs but would like higher returns. I am talking about a
$1,000-plus investment. What is a good investment for someone my
age?
</P>
<P>
   K.P., Port Arthur, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A. Before you can make a sensible choice, you need to decide
what the eventual purpose of the money is likely to be. The
beginning of a retirement pool? Then one sort of investment would
be appropriate. A down payment on a house in five to 10 years?
Quite a different investment would be appropriate. Buying a car in
about three years? Still another route would be the right one.
</P>
<P>
   The last case is the easiest to deal with. If you expect to call
on the money within five years, CDs are the right place for your
savings. Neither the stock nor the bond market can be expected to
deliver predictable returns in such a short time; you could end up
with less money than the CDs would have provided.
</P>
<P>
   For an intermediate-term investment _ in which you would need
the money in five to 10 years _ most people favor balanced funds.
They balance a stock position with bonds and other fixed-income
holdings, typically with about 60 percent of the funds in stocks.
Solid examples include Fidelity Puritan, Fidelity Asset Manager,
Dodge and Cox Balanced, and Vanguard Balanced Index.
</P>
<P>
   For a long-term investment (10 years or more), you want stocks,
stocks, and nothing but stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is with what most people view as a core
holding _ money that's invested in large, well-established US
companies. The largest such fund is Vanguard Index 500, which
simply holds the 500 stocks in the Standard and Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   If you do view this as retirement money, I suggest you look into
IRA accounts. They will give you tax-deferred growth until the
funds are withdrawn in your retirement years.
</P>
<P>
   You are allowed to put up to $2,000 a year into IRAs; depending
on your income, marital status, and whether you participate in a
retirement plan, all or some of the IRA contributions may be
deductible from your taxable income. If you don't qualify for a
deductible IRA, consider Roth IRAs. They offer no deductions but
let you withdraw money tax-free in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   What's the catch with IRAs? If you take money out before age 59
1/2, you must pay the taxes plus a penalty. (There are a few
exceptions, but they are pretty tightly defined and unpleasant,
such as disability or high medical expenses.)
</P>
<P>
   You can learn a great deal about mutual funds and IRAs from the
major fund families. Since those I cited are no-load fund families
(which have no sales charges and rely on mail solicitations), your
mailbox will never be the same if you ask a half-dozen companies
for information. But most provide clear and responsible
descriptions of what they offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
