<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-NUDE-BEACH-ART-BOS &LR;      07-17 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-BEACH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ON CAPE COD, A PUSH IS ON FOR NUDE BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN, Mass. _ There are people for whom public nudity is
experienced only in bad dreams. And then there are people like Bill
Falconer, who wants nothing more than to go a beach unregulated,
uninhibited and undressed.
</P>
<P>
   Falconer, who spurns what he calls ``textile beaches,'' wants a
nude beach on Cape Cod so badly that for four years he has gathered
scores of nudists to clean up the Cape Cod National Seashore _
wearing clothes, even _ in the hopes that their contributions will
generate good will for their cause. He thinks it's helping, that
rangers have begun to treat traditional nudist areas of the
Seashore as a ``quasi-hands off area,'' but he concedes that
sunbathers still scramble for their clothes when rangers do show
up.
</P>
<P>
   But with an avowed naturist on the board of selectmen,
Provincetown is once again waging an effort to get some areas of
the Cape Cod National Seashore designated as clothing-optional
beaches. Last week, the board wrote a letter urging the National
Seashore to reconsider the prohibition against nudity _ and to
recognize a 1996 unanimous Town Meeting vote that called for the
same.
</P>
<P>
   But the forecast isn't good for nude sunbathers. The Cape and
Islands, some say, treat people like Falconer as an embarrassing
little secret: While town officials only reluctantly crack down on
nudists _ no one, it seems, wants to take credit for taming
personal freedoms _ they aren't offering open invitations or
advertising their beaches as free-for-alls.
</P>
<P>
   Take the cautious explanation of Nantucket Deputy Police Chief
Jack McGrady, who couldn't remember the last time someone was fined
for indecent exposure while on what's known as ``Nude Beach''
between Miacomet and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nudity is a very delicate subject,'' said McGrady. ``Nudity in
and of itself supposedly isn't against the law in certain places
and it's not for me to make decisions on it. Call the district
attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there are spots on Martha's Vineyard _ near the
lighthouse in Gay Head, and at Lucy Vincent Beach in Chilmark _
where nudity is tolerated, but not advertised.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cape, the only legal nude beach is a private one: In
Marstons Mills, visitors pay $15 to enter a nudist trailer park.
There, visitors are greeted by topless middle-age women and naked
couples, and skirted to a pool area _ a gated-off pond of ocean
water _ no bigger than a neighbor's backyard. One can swim out to a
roped-off raft, but not sit upon it naked, for fear of disturbing
the neighbors' peace.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the National Seashore, Chief Ranger Kevin FitzGerald
said people sunbathing nude more often receive verbal warnings than
fines; it's only the persistent ones, like Provincetown Selectman
David Atkinson, who find themselves in trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, a naturist who has championed the cause for years,
said he has paid more than $600 in fines. (The judge said, ``If we
see you naked again, we'll throw you in jail,'' he recounted.) He
admonishes those who think nudity bespeaks of vanity or
exhibitionist tendenies. It is natural and spiritual, he said, and
not the least bit sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Except to the gawkers, of course, for whom it is quite a show.
When nude sunbathing was permitted on sections of the Cape Cod
National Seashore in the 1970s, the lure of a beach stocked with
bare skin was so attractive that hundreds of tourists flocked to
the beaches, tramping over dunes and ruining vegetation for years
to come, said Maria Burks, Seashore superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can still see the damage today where that occurred,''
Burks said. ``People were chartering buses from Boston, bringing
folks down. The town of Truro was overrun with people parking on
lawns. It is pretty horrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the bulk of the damage was caused by ``the peepers, not
by the bathers,'' Burks said, the bathers were banned in 1975, when
the Cape Cod National Seashore became one of only two national
parks that prohibit nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite New England's puritanical image, the region has a
healthy number of naturists, said Eric Schuttauf, executive
director of the American Association for Nude Recreation. What they
lack is a home, which disturbs Atkinson. ``People from Europe, they
all have places to go,'' Atkinson said. ``People are so surprised
when you come here that there's no place to go to be naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson ran unsuccessfully on the Libertarian ticket for
secretary of state in 1998, and when the Globe printed photographs
of all the political candidates in suits, Atkinson wore his
birthday suit. Though he spearheaded the latest push for a nude
beach along the Seashore, he is not alone in a town that enjoys its
freedoms, both personal and civic.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, 1996, Town Meeting members unanimously approved an
article instructing the board of selectmen to request that the
National Seashore ``designate a clothing-optional area at an
appropriate distance from the southeastern end of the Herring Cove
parking lot.'' The selectmen did so three weeks later but never got
any satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dare I say we have nothing to show for our efforts?'' said
Town Manager Keith Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman is hopeful that the time is ripe for change, since the
selectmen are beginning discussions with the Seashore on beach
access and plan a public forum in August on issues such as dune
erosion. ``We fully expect the issue of nude beaches to show
itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burks, of the National Seashore, said officials will look into
the board's request, as they do each time they get an appeal for a
clothing-optional spot. But she said the issue is more complicated
than it appears and that it would be irresponsible right now to
open the beaches ``without guaranteeing some kind of resource
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   There are unintended consequences that need to be assessed _
like gawkers, for instance. Legal nude beaches could cause a
dramatic spike in visitation, which the towns would resist, she
said. And though FitzGerald, the Seashore's ranger chief, says some
now tramp over dunes to find remote spots for nude sunbathing, they
fear that many more would show up if nudity were sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Or not. Nobody is really certain, which makes this a cause for
study of what's changed in 25 years, and, as Burks put it,
``whether the sociology of nudity seems to be changing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson said it's as simple as finding good, remote locations
and posting signs clearly warning clothed visitors. ``Most
voyeurs,'' he said, ``would rather not walk a long way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
