u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-17 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASUALTIES OF CASUAL-DRESS CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep reading about a mental condition called body dysmorphic
disorder, which causes people to think they're unattractive when
they're not.
</P>
<P>
   Lately I've been wondering if there isn't a mental disorder that
works the other way, that convinces people they look good when they
don't. Because how else to explain some of the things I see in
public these days?
</P>
<P>
   Let me pause here for a moment to confess that I am, as my dear
mother would say, no oil painting. I see that quite clearly every
time I look into a mirror, which is why I take care to keep the
most objectionable parts of my anatomy covered when I go out in
public. I don't like looking at my fat, my spider veins, and all
the other horrors, large and small, that come with age. Why would I
want to inflict the sight of these things on innocent strangers?
It's not just vanity, it's a matter of courtesy, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Tall Ships were a spectacle, and so too were many of the
people who came out to see them, dressed for the occasion as though
they were auditioning for a role in a soft-core porn movie. Acres
of bare flesh were on view, and much of it was not a pretty sight.
There were flabby midriffs, love handles, dewlaps of every
description, hairy backs, and even hairy backsides. True, it was
hot. And we were near the water, so maybe people convinced
themselves they were at the beach and dressed accordingly. You
expect to see people in all states of undress at the beach. But we
weren't at the beach. We were in the middle of the city.
</P>
<P>
   My personal breaking point came when I found myself sitting on a
crowded Red Line train with my nose about 2 inches from some guy's
hairy bellybutton. I looked up at his face. He was old enough to
know better. But there he was, in a cropped T-shirt and shorts that
hung low on his hips. I tried to imagine him looking at himself
approvingly in the mirror just before he left the house and saying,
``There. Perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a kind of reverse BDD, a mental disorder that causes
people to think they look great when they don't, this guy had an
acute case. I suppose there may be some other explanation. Maybe he
had been kidnapped by space aliens, dressed by an otherworldly
personal shopper, and sent back among us to test our gag reflexes.
Or maybe he just didn't care what he lookedlike. Or maybe he just
didn't know any better.
</P>
<P>
   Why should he know better? Nobody dresses anymore. Casual is the
rule, on the street and at work too. Casual Fridays weren't enough;
now every day is casual day. How much more casual can we get before
we're all walking around naked? Already companies are finding it
necessary to send out memos reminding people that casual work dress
doesn't include halter tops or short shorts or muscle shirts.
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking: This woman is an old fool, totally
out of touch with the times. Yes, I am old. I admit it. I am so old
that I actually remember when people wore clothes in the
summertime. No kidding. People went around fully covered. Believe
it or not, nobody wore shorts in public back then. There was a kind
of unwritten rule that adults would not wear shorts shopping, or in
restaurants, or on the street. And nobody ever wore them to work.
It seems so long ago. It was so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that back then we carried the covering up too far. We
wore little white gloves, and girdles and hose, even on the hottest
days. I wouldn't want to go back to that, but there must be some
reasonable point between wearing a rubber panty girdle and having
to look into that guy's hairy bellybutton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
