<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-PROTESTANTS-B     07-17 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PROTESTANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ULSTER, PROTESTANTS FIND WANING APPEAL IN BELLIGERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCECOURT, Northern Ireland _ Philip Martin was going to
take his two sons to see a 12th of July parade, but he thought
better of it and instead brought them here, to the Marble Arch
Caves, a subterranean world of rivers and waterfalls nestled in the
remote hills of County Fermanagh.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 38, a Protestant, grew up in Northern Ireland and in his
youth belonged to a pipe band that marched in some of the 3,000
parades held each year by the Orange Order, a group akin to the
Masons, to celebrate William of Orange's victory over Catholic King
James in 1690.
</P>
<P>
   But this time he chose to spend what Orangemen call the Glorious
12th at the Caves rather than watching a parade, because, he said
only half-jokingly, ``better the caves than the cavemen.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching two weeks of sometimes violent protests by the
Orangemen and their supporters over being barred from marching
through a Catholic neighborhood in Portadown, Martin is not the
only Protestant who believes that some in his community are
behaving like those from a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin and other moderate Protestants also are encouraged by
what they have seen. While the Orangemen in Portadown threatened to
shut down the country, it didn't happen. The violence organized by
loyalists who support the Orangemen was limited compared to 1996,
1997, and 1998, when much of Northern Ireland was paralyzed, and
several Catholics were murdered by loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of plunging Northern Ireland back to the bad old days,
the last two weeks suggest Northern Ireland may have turned a
corner. Extremists, who have set the agenda for more than 30 years,
seem more marginalized than ever; moderates are speaking out more
forcefully than ever; and the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 _ and
the power-sharing government that is its cornerstone _ seems to be
taking root.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is one of those watching anxiously. He went to college in
England and stayed there, preferring multicultural London to the
two-tribes mentality and warfare back home. He regularly returns
here, mainly to visit his parents. He considers himself thoroughly
British, wants Northern Ireland to remain part of Britain, and
believes the Orange parades should continue. But he is disgusted by
the violent protests to support Orangemen who want to march down
the Garvaghy Road in a Catholic area of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   He would someday like to return here, and says he will if the
Good Friday Agreement transforms this place, and the newly growing
prosperity flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Many Protestant unionists who want to maintain the union with
Britain see their traditions and culture under threat from the new
order envisioned by the Good Friday Agreement, which sought to
bring an end to a 30-year cycle of political and sectarian
violence. The agreement, brokered by former US senator George
Mitchell of Maine, calls for power-sharing with Catholic
nationalists, who make up more than 40 percent of the population,
as well as closer ties with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of the Orange parades are blocked by authorities
each year, and a handful of others have restrictions placed on
them. But the Orangemen are used to having their way in Northern
Ireland and see the objections raised to their marches as evidence
that their way of life is threatened. Catholics see the marches as
triumphalist, and the British government largely agrees with the
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Orange Order described the past week as their Alamo,
their last chance to make a stand. But, like those who fell at the
Alamo, the Orangemen found their numbers dwindling as the days wore
on.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of all the main Protestant churches, in an
unprecedented call for restraint, pleaded with the Orangemen to
call off their protest at Drumcree Church on the outskirts of the
Garvaghy Road in Portadown, where the British government's Parades
Commission barred the Orangemen from marching.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more sad than angry, the Reverend Robin Eames, the
Anglican primate of Ireland, said the Orangemen had to accept that
their defiance attracted and incited loyalist thugs who used
violence and intimidation against Catholics, the police, and
British soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order's leader in Portadown, Harold Gracey, responded
by calling the Protestant clergymen traitors. Gracey drew loud
cheers from a crowd at Portadown last week, but many Protestants
were appalled by his comments and the response he provoked. They
were equally appalled when Jim Rodgers, a Belfast city councilor,
was heckled by loyalists in Belfast after he told the largest
gathering of Orangemen on the Glorious 12th that attacks on the
police and British Army were unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, who opposes the Good Friday Agreement and is widely
regarded as a hard-liner within his own moderate Ulster Unionist
party, said he was not bothered by the heckling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people are a distinct minority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His assessment was borne out by the small numbers who rose to
the call by the Orange Order to take to the streets this past week.
Police said the number joining the protest was far down from
previous years, as was the accompanying violence.
</P>
<P>
   Most loyalist paramilitaries went out of their way to prevent
violence the last two weeks, which marked the climax to the annual
marching season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days when violence was seen as a solution to problems in
Northern Ireland are over,'' said David Ervine, a former loyalist
paramilitary leader, who is now an enthusiastic democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it seems cool to be cool in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last century, Protestant unionists were widely
seen as belligerent and intransigent. The British government
reluctantly created Northern Ireland in 1920, calculating that the
threat posed by armed Protestants who would revolt against being
left a minority in a Catholic-dominated Ireland was greater than
that posed by Catholic nationalists clamoring for a united and
independent Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a gerrymandered Northern Ireland that was carved
out of six of the nine counties of the ancient province of Ulster
in order to ensure that it would have a majority Protestant
population loyal to the British crown. Those in the 26-county Irish
Free State, which later became the Irish Republic, fought a bitter
civil war over the compromise. But moderates prevailed, and since
1922 the Irish government has sought the reunification of Ireland
through peaceful, democratic means.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking has taken longer to take root in Northern Ireland,
where extremists generally have held sway, especially for most of
the last 35 years. But having concluded that violence was getting
them nowhere, the main paramilitary groups have, with some
murderous exceptions, observed cease-fires since 1994. It now seems
that being a moderate in the new Northern Ireland counts for more
than the snarling, menacing sort of unionism that is on display
every year in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Many here sense a shift in strategy by the unionists. It mirrors
the path taken by Irish republicans more than a decade ago when
Gerry Adams, Martin McGuinness, and other former IRA commanders
decided the fastest, most practical way to unify Ireland was to end
their shooting war and seek the consent of the majority of those
living in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   For unionists, at least the narrow majority within the
Protestant community that supports the Good Friday Agreement, the
strategy is to convince enough Catholics that their rights and
aspirations will be respected, that they will be treated equally,
and that their lives will be better if Northern Ireland remains
part of the United Kingdom than if it becomes part of the Irish
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   But to do that, Protestants will have to spend less time
focusing on the glorious past that so enchants the men on the hill
at Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   As Philip Martin, the Northern Ireland exile, put it as he
watched his young sons frolic on a grassy knoll, ``I used to think
about the past all the time. It was what we were taught as kids.
But now I don't give a toss about the past. I care about the future
and my two wee boys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
