<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES FLY IN ATLANTA SCANDAL, BUT FROM CORRUPTION NOT RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When black officials in Atlanta and Fulton County began
pleading guilty last month to corruption charges in an ongoing FBI
investigation, one charge appeared notably absent in this widening
scandal _ the charge of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps never before has a federal investigation been aimed at
so many high-ranking black officials, and more are expected to be
indicted or fired before this probe is over.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, a federal grand jury indicted Fred B. Prewitt,
the chairman of the city's Civil Service Board and a minority
contractor with the city. Prewitt, 70, a fund-raiser for Mayor Bill
Campbell and also a close friend, was charged with three felony
counts of making false statements on his 1996-1998 personal income
tax returns, according to the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also reported that Fulton County Commissioner
Michael Hightower, 43, pleaded guilty to accepting $25,000 in
payoffs from a local businessman. In addition, Josh Kenyon, chief
of staff to County Commission Chairman Mike Kenn, was fired from
his job and later pleaded guilty in federal court to accepting
money from businessman George Greene. Greene, in turn, pleaded
guilty to bribing Hightower. Prewitt, Hightower and Greene are
black; Kenyon is white.
</P>
<P>
   All this has left the city and county reeling _ and left a taint
on a city proud of its African-American leadership. Atlanta, known
as the gateway to the South, is recognized as the city where
African-Americans have proudly held the mayor's seat since the
election of Maynard Jackson in 1973, and where blacks hold many
other high-ranking positions.
</P>
<P>
   The political landscape in Atlanta began to shake less than a
year ago when Raymond McClendon, a former investment manager for
the Atlanta Pension Board and once the chairman of then-Mayor
Jackson's finance committee, was indicted for defrauding Atlanta of
millions of dollars from the pension fund. McClendon was as close
to Jackson as Prewitt is to Mayor Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   McClendon's trial is expected to begin this summer, but as it
unfolds, it is unlikely that the charge of racism will be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is shocking is that, in all of my years in politics, I am
witnessing black elected officials being indicted or pleading
guilty and no one is saying that these investigations are racially
motivated,'' said Harry L. Ross, an Atlanta-based political
pollster. ``In traveling around metro Atlanta, I have yet to hear a
single person at various meetings I've attended say that this
corruption is based on race.''
</P>
<P>
   That has not always been the case in America. There have been
cities in which black officials were indicted where the charge of
racism might have had some validity, particularly if there were
only one or two black elected officials in a predominantly white
city or county government.
</P>
<P>
   And if this corruption scandal had broken 10 years ago in
Atlanta, Ross noted, ``There would have been charges that it was
racially motivated, that the white establishment was trying to
erode the political power base of the black populace. But no one is
able to make that claim in this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for that. One is that at least two
officials have pleaded guilty to corruption charges since the
investigation began earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the fact that US Attorney Richard Deane, who is
directly involved in the probe, is African-American, as is Theodore
Jackson, in charge of the FBI in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Deane himself further eroded the racial aspect when at a
televised news conference he asked the people of mostly black
Atlanta and Fulton County that if they know of any corruption, to
please notify the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   As the probe continues, the people (and a few politicians) are
waiting uneasily for the next shoe to drop, and more indictments
will certainly be handed up by the federal grand jury. Meanwhile,
incumbents in Tuesday's state and county elections worry they will
be tarnished by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of black incumbents up for reelection are afraid that
they could be victims of a backlash from the corruption scandal,''
Ross said. ``They're afraid that the tarnished image of black
elected officials will cause many voters who usually support them
to stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal may have an impact even on next year's mayoral race.
With Campbell forbidden to run for a third term, three
African-Americans are vying to succeed him: City Council President
Robb Pitts; Gloria Tinubu, a former city councilor and on the
Spelman College faculty; and Shirley Franklin, a former chief
administrative officer to Andrew Young who recently stepped down
from the Georgia Transportation Board.
</P>
<P>
   So Atlanta will continue its run of black mayors, but be scarred
by this investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Atlanta and Fulton County have been hit hard by the
same disease that has hit many other seats of government across the
nation. As blacks in Atlanta and the surrounding county have
learned how to rise above segregation and racism to attain
political power, they will now have to learn how to survive the
crippling disease of political corruption.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
