<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS &LR;      07-17 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERYTHING IN THE ROOM BEGAN TO BURN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ A few minutes before the red candle tumbled
to the floor, Julie Barnes and Tom Levesque were coloring.
Coloring, and then fighting about whether to have sex, pushing each
other back and forth on a makeshift bed until the candle fell, and
some clothes ignited.
</P>
<P>
   The deadly fire that resulted turned the nation's attention to
the vacant meat-processing plant a few blocks from downtown
Worcester, and to the thin, scruffy homeless couple who had been
squatting inside.
</P>
<P>
   A court will have to decide whether the two street people,
charged with manslaughter, are responsible for six firefighters'
deaths. But on Friday, as Barnes was released from prison on bail,
their lawyers were insisting that the charges should be dismissed.
They point to grand jury testimony that was made public this month,
and say it demonstrates that the couple were not treated fairly
when manslaughter charges were brought against them.
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony also provides the first vivid details of the
sequence events that led to one of the deadliest fires in state
history, and of the simple, squalid life the couple had been living
in the months before. It shows that they spent nights in a
warehouse without heat, sleeping on a wooden pallet covered with
blankets, eating and playing and having friends over to visit,
alternating between the most childlike activities and the most
adult.
</P>
<P>
   They lived there even though city officials determined that the
owner had sealed the warehouse adequately from trespassers, even
after a police officer witnessed their squalid living conditions,
and had to leave the building because of the stench. They used the
empty warehouse as a home and refuge until the fire forced them
out, killing their dog and cat and destroying their few belongings,
and changing life in Worcester forever.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic end to a situation that Worcester activists
for the homeless say is disturbingly commonplace; some suspect that
dozens of people live in the empty warehouses that once made up a
vibrant industrial district. Last December, a neighborhood priest
said he has walked past many of those buildings at night, and seen
small fires burning inside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester Cold Storage and Warehouse Co., was 190 feet long
by 70 feet wide, constructed of brick, with freezers inside and
walls lined with cork, styrofoam and styrene. The meat processing
plant it once housed went out of business in 1987. The building had
been abandoned since then, save for the homeless people who have
found their way inside.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Barnes, 20, and Tom Levesque, 37, got in through a back
entrance, near the loading dock, following a cement walkway to an
L-shaped set of steps, which led to an accessible door. They hid a
flashlight behind a steel beam, and used it to help make their way
down dark corridors to a room on the righthand side.
</P>
<P>
   The room was in the northeast corner of the building, on the
second floor, with windows that looked out onto Franklin Street. It
was strewn with clothes and brown paper bags, bread and cold cuts,
mustard, mayonnaise, and cans of soup. The couple kept a kerosene
heater, a cat and a dog. For a bed, they used a wooden pallet lined
with blankets: two to make it soft, four or five to keep warm. Next
to the bed was a wooden end table, and on top of the table was a
radio and the thin red candles they used for light.
</P>
<P>
   At a day laborers office in Worcester, they met Scott Swedis,
another young drifter who made a connection with Julie. They
invited Scott to see the room, and let him stay there a few nights.
Julie and Scott got romantically involved. Tom got jealous.
</P>
<P>
   Julie and Tom had a volatile relationship _ they argued and
sometimes got violent _ and Scott seemed to have been caught in the
middle of it. In early October of last year, Julie applied for a
restraining order against Tom, saying he was kicking Scott. As an
address, she left a nearby homeless shelter. The request was
deined.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 27, Swedis contacted police himself, likely with a
similar complaint. In response, a K-9 officer, Daniel Sullivan,
went into the warehouse with his dog at about 10 p.m. that night.
His report was read to the grand jury in February.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked in the building, Sullivan wrote, he was overcome
by the stench of rotting garbage, feces, and urine. He made his way
down a hallway with a flashlight, and entered one room to find
mountains of trash: garbage bags, take-out containers, half-eaten
meals, and, at the far end, piles of human waste. He saw more food
trays, more animal and human waste, as he continued down the
corridor. ``You couldn't take a step,'' he wrote, ``without walking
on rotting garbage or feces.''
</P>
<P>
   In the makeshift bedroom, where he found a closet with a box
inside. The box was overflowing with cat feces. At that point,
worried for the safety and health of his dog, he left the building.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether Sullivan or anyone in the Police Department
contacted the city building inspector or public safety department,
or the building's owner, Framingham developer Ding On ``Tony''
Kwan.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they did not receive a report of someone
living inside the building. A Police Department records official
said she could find no record of Sullivan's report on file from
October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julie moved out of the warehouse a week before the fire. She and
Tom had broken up, and Julie went to stay at the nearby Regency
Hotel, with a friend named Bruce Canty. She returned to the
warehouse in the afternoon of Dec. 3. to check on her dog, who had
been sick.
</P>
<P>
   As she headed to the back door, Julie told police, she spotted
Tom at the Kenmore Diner, and figured he was following her. He came
into the warehouse a short time after she did, asked what she was
doing there, and sat next to her on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with you today?'' she asked him.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was none of her business.
</P>
<P>
   They continued to argue. He poked her, and she told him to leave
her alone. He started to smoke a joint, and she told him it
bothered her nose. She pulled out a coloring book, lay down on the
edge of the bed, and started to color.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Tom decided he wanted to have sex. Julie didn't.
Tom pulled the book away, and they argued and pushed each other. At
some point, Tom's leg knocked over the red candle that had been
providing their light. At first, neither of them noticed. But then
Julie realized the clothes were burning.
</P>
<P>
   They tried stepping on the clothes, but the fire wouldn't go
out. They hit it with a pillow, and the pillow caught fire. The
fire started to spread to the paper on the floor, and to grow.
``Everything in the room began to burn,'' Tom later told police.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to get their pets out of the room, but couldn't
manage. So Tom told Julie to put on her shoes. Julie turned off the
kerosene heater, and they left.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They took a short walk to the Worcester Common Outlets mall to
the MediaPlay store, where they often listened to music on
headphones, flipped through magazines, and bought candy. The store
manager overheard them arguing. ``I can't believe I lost all my
stuff,'' Julie was telling Tom. ``I lost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   They left the store and headed for dinner _ Tom says they went
to the Mustard Seed, a place that serves meals to the homeless.
They returned to the mall and lingered for a while, then went to a
friend's apartment, where Tom spent the night. Julie went back to
the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, by this point, had been burning for more than five
hours, and was raging. Julie could see the engines and flames from
the hotel window. By the end of the night, 300 firefighters from
Worcester and nearby communities were battling the blaze. It
started as a routine fire _ light haze inside the building,
firefighters able to move freely, a district chief told the Fire
Department's board of inquiry, in testimony that became public this
month. ``All of a sudden, things went bad,'' he said. ``Things went
from light haze to black and hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie kept calling to Canty, telling him to look out the window.
She couldn't seem to pull herself away.
</P>
<P>
   By that evening, police were already on Tom and Julie's trail;
they had interviewed the owner of a diner who remembered seeing
them enter the building, as well as homeless people who knew them
from city shelters. In the weeks after the fire, the details of
their little-noticed lives trickled into public view: How Tom had a
troubled family life and a background of mental illness; how Julie
was described by friends as slow, and had drifted between parents
until she dropped out of school and wound up on the streets. Five
days after the fire, Tom and Julie were arrested and charged with
involuntary manslaughter. He is still waiting to hear whether his
bail will be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after the fire, investigators cleared the rubble from
the warehouse's second floor. They found a charred wooden pallet,
the remnants of plastic milk crates, a well-preserved prepaid
telephone card, and the remains of a cat and a dog.
</P>
<P>
   They also found a piece of carpet with a red substance on it. A
State Police laboratory determined that it was wax. The remains of
a red candle, which had burned into the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
