<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4576 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-MEXICAN-RIVIERA-LADN &LR;      07-17 2646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-RIVIERA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE GOOD LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by LANG) 
(Eds: Fact box and captains below) 
Story and photos 
by Eric Noland 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
IF YOU GO &QL; 
RATES: Carnival's 7-day cruise of the Mexican Riviera starts at
$809 per person, double occupancy, for an off-peak trip booked far
in advance. Standard brochure rates start at $1,339 in peak season
($1,1139 off-peak) for an interior cabin. For a porthole, expect to
add $200 to those rates; for a window, slightly more. Fares are
discounted for a third or fourth occupant in a cabin. &QL; 
INFORMATION: Carnival Cruise Lines can be reached at (800)
227-6482. Web: www.carnival.com. &QL; 
MEXICO CRUISE TIPS &QL; 
WALKING AROUND MONEY: Before leaving, go to your bank and get
single dollar bills. A lot of singles; maybe $50 worth. There are
countless opportunities to tip on this trip: dock porters, ship
porters, land-tour guides and bus drivers, cab drivers, deliveries
to your cabin, musical entertainment, cabin stewards, waiters, bus
boys (although the latter three are customarily tipped once, at the
end of the cruise). Elation cabins are outfitted with room safes,
which you can customize with the swipe of any credit card (I used
Chevron), so you can keep the excess dollar bills _ along with
other spare cash, your passport, camera, etc. _ secure during the
cruise. No need to change money into pesos; Mexican service
providers prefer U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   PHONING HOME: Tell your loved ones you'll write post cards but
might not call. Satellite calls from the ship cost about $10 per
minute. I tried to circumvent this by calling from a pay phone on
the Puerto Vallarta dock, using my American Express card. A
three-minute call to Los Angeles, operator-assisted (the only
option available), was billed to my card as $29.95. At several pay
phones in Cabo San Lucas, meanwhile, it was impossible to use any
American credit card _ only direct-dial calls with peso coins
(you'd need a wheelbarrow full) or collect calls were permitted. A
Mexican operator said the use of AT&AMP;T calling cards had to be
discontinued because of a high incidence of fraud. Cell phones
won't work at sea; they can be hit and miss on land.
</P>
<P>
   QUENCHING A THIRST: The don't-drink-the-water adage in Mexico is
no joke; it's strongly advisable. Unfortunately, the ship's store
does not stock bottled water. Instead, Evian is available as a bar
or room-service item, like Coke or martinis (with prices to match).
Try this: Pick up a six-pack of quart water bottles at the
supermarket and pack some in your luggage, the remainder in a
carry-on bag. That way, you'll have about one bottle available per
day _ particularly important when you go ashore. And as you discard
the bottles, this will give you extra packing space for shopping
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   APPETITE ISSUES: Beg, plead, whine for a late dinner seating.
Believe it or not, this cruise travels significantly east, not just
south, such that you set your clocks back an hour on each of the
first two nights. If you're stuck with the early seating (6 p.m.),
this means dining the third day at the equivalent of 4 p.m. Pacific
time. The word is out on this one, though. On the first day, a few
members of our dinner table (including me) submitted formal
requests for a switch to late seating; all were politely denied. &QL; 
(TRVL Mex Cruise 13)
</P>
<P>
   The Carnival cruise ship Elation glides by the massive rocks of
Mazatlan's harbor as it departs the Mexican resort city.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL Mex Cruise 12)
</P>
<P>
   The Elation, a Carnival cruise ship that makes week-long trips
along the Mexican Riviera, lies at anchor near Cabo San Lucas'
distinctive Los Arcos.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL Mex Cruise 5)
</P>
<P>
   Cruise passengers crowd the deck as the ship passes the tip of
Baja California on its journey along Mexico's west coast.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL Mex Cruise 4)
</P>
<P>
   A popular refreshment spot on Carnival's Elation is the Plaza
Bar in the ship's central atrium. Classical musicians often provide
the entertainment here.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL Mex Cruise 2)
</P>
<P>
   Particularly popular with kids is the Elation's corkscrew water
slide, which whisks its riders into the ship's seawater pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OFF MEXICO'S WEST COAST _ It's not difficult to ascertain why some
people favor a cruise ship as their primary mode of transportation
on a visit to Mexico. All you have to do is leaf through a few
guidebooks on the country, paying particular attention to the
sections on driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. insurance is invalid in Mexico'' (Frommer's); ``an
uninsured accident is a crime under Mexican law, which presumes the
defendant guilty until proven innocent'' (Hidden Baja); ``do not
drive after dark if at all possible'' (AAA TravelBook); ``driving
in Mexico ... almost inevitably involves at least one brush with
bureaucracy or the law'' (Mexico: The Rough Guide); ``cavernous
potholes,'' ``banditos who favor the cover of darkness'' (Fodor's).
</P>
<P>
   On a cruise ship, someone else takes the wheel _ or at least the
rudder. And on a vacation excursion far south of the United States
border, that can reduce the anxiety quotient considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, on a recent weeklong Mexican Riviera cruise on
Carnival's Elation, after a few encounters with passengers, one
fact became unmistakable: You wouldn't want some of these people in
control of a motorized anything.
</P>
<P>
   Before we'd even untied from the dock in San Pedro, at the
compulsory lifeboat drill, one woman was already so drunk she
couldn't get her life jacket on. Another passenger arrived with his
lifejacket securely buckled in place _ and a cocktail in hand. The
following day, an elderly, tattooed man in a sleeveless Dodgers
jersey was grumbling about his inability to find a bar open so he
could get a beer; it was 7:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The casino jangled with life nearly at all hours. One evening,
the Dance Till Ya Drop bash at the Jekyll &AMP; Hyde Dance Club didn't
even (ITAL)begin(END ITAL) until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival has a well-established reputation for throwing one
whale of a party on its cruises, and while its mass-market pricing
obviously has considerable appeal for families and seniors, the
Elation fairly bobbed with raucous diversions throughout our trip.
</P>
<P>
   As with most cruises, this is not a vacation for travelers who
like to be independent _ exploring on their own, operating without
a schedule, contriving their own entertainment. Rather, it is ideal
for someone who doesn't want to deal with the fuss of finding a
hotel in the dark, fumbling with unfamiliar words on the menu ...
or deciphering Spanish-language road signs on blind, unlit curves.
</P>
<P>
   If you're prepared _ eager, even _ to turn off your mind for a
few days, this is the trip for you. It features a dawn-to-wee-hours
orchestration of amusements in a setting that brings to mind the
Sahara Hotel if it were suddenly to slip its Las Vegas foundation
and slide into Lake Mead.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday-to-Sunday, year-round itinerary is well-geared to
urban dwellers who have wound themselves into knots, in that the
first two full days are spent at sea, cruising along Mexico's
coast. This provides ample daytime opportunities for sunning and
snoozing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, right about the time the restlessness begins to set in for
many, there are three consecutive days of port calls _ at Puerto
Vallarta, Mazatlan and (briefly) Cabo San Lucas. Pick the right
shore tours on the first two stops and you can get a look at
Mexico's interior: ancient churches, bustling villages, workers
making pottery, furniture and adobe bricks.
</P>
<P>
   It was exhilarating to be out on the open ocean the first couple
of days. The low mountains of the Baja California peninsula
provided companionship much of the way _ as did an enormous pod of
dolphins that played in the wake one morning. This mode of travel
kind of puts you in touch with other seafarers _ Hurtado, Drake,
Cavendish, Cochrane _ who plied and occasionally plundered these
waters during a period of 300 years before things finally quieted
down in the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Most of our passengers seemed to be drawn to the pool area
amidships, an area that has the aspect of a giant sun-tanning
reflector shield (two-story wind screens all around). Deck loungers
are positioned edge to edge, and a convoluted, corkscrew water
slide sends kids and a few infantile adults hurtling into the
seawater pool (alas, the security guards only let us use it for
short periods each day).
</P>
<P>
   And there is a stage. If extended moments of silence cause you
to get antsy, you'll delight in this. It never seems to rest. On
the first morning, as at least one passenger nearby was trying to
plunge into the opening pages of ``The Milagro Beanfield War,'' the
frenzy of the morning aerobics class diffused into the country
dance lesson, which gave way to the reggae band with the amplified,
pile-driver snare drum. (It seemed relentless, but most everyone
else, sucking on rum drinks in tall, pink glasses, bobbed
delightedly to the rhythm.) Then came the hula-hoop contest.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a quiet place to read or contemplate the
vast expanse of sea, you might want to repair to the forward tip of
the uppermost Sun Deck. There, you hear only the wind rushing
overhead, the radar equipment spinning innocuously and the clatter
of shuffleboard disks on the wood decking.
</P>
<P>
   For indoor serenity, this cruise offered a pleasant surprise. A
few years ago, Carnival began supplementing its high-energy troupe
of hoofers, crooners and DJs with classical musicians. On this
trip, three young adultsfrom Poland _ pianist, violinist, cellist _
set up at various times each day for performances that often took
on the feel of recitals.
</P>
<P>
   The trio played daily at high tea in the Musical Cafe, which
often resulted in a curious scene: the musicians pouring their
energies into a Loeillet sonata as white-gloved waiters served tea
and delicate, layered pastries ... to people in tank tops and damp
bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   The higher-brow entertainment might be a subtle nod to Joe
Farcus, the architect of the 2-year-old Elation, who fashioned the
ship's interior design after the Muses of Greek mythology. Examine
the ship's elaborate decor closely and you might detect Clio's
scrolls, Terpsichore's lyre, etc. Various public rooms, meanwhile,
are christened after such figures of music and letters as Cole
Porter, Duke Ellington, Gilbert and Sullivan, Mark Twain, Robert
Louis Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, though: The ship doesn't take itself too seriously.
It is still, at its core, a Carnival party boat.
</P>
<P>
   One night in the Mikado Lounge, the dancers were kicking up a
storm in a Vegas-style (or at least Laughlin) show titled
``Rhythm,'' although some of the music was cleaned up for the
family audience. You couldn't help but wince when the J. Geils
lyric ``My angel is a centerfold'' was somehow mutilated into ``My
girl is on the calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   Another mild disappointment came later when the piano bar opened
for the evening. This seemed a great opportunity to perhaps hear
(or even sing along on) the chestnuts of Jerome Kern, Sammy Cahn,
Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart. But the piano man opened up with
the Mickey Mouse Club theme before segueing into the Oscar Mayer
wiener song. Fearing that the ``Gilligan's Island'' theme had to be
just around the corner, I ducked out. But everyone else in the
joint seemed to be thrilled silly.
</P>
<P>
   A few nights into the cruise, one entertainment option was
particularly well-received. In Puerto Vallarta, Carnival has
contracted with some local folk dancers, a nine-piece mariachi band
and even a young charro who does exotic lariat tricks. They come on
board just before the ship's 10 p.m. sailing, deliver a brisk
half-hour show in the main showroom, then scoot off the ship, the
gangway literally being pulled up right behind them. It was an
excellent show, and there was standing room only for this fleeting
glimpse of folklorico.
</P>
<P>
   What do the passengers' young children do during all of this
revelry? Throughout the cruise, there seemed to be extensive
provision for them.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, Camp Carnival operates as kind of a seabound
child-care program, with youth directors overseeing activities for
different age groups. (For toddlers: coloring, video cartoons,
Legos, story time, computer games.) At night, baby-sitting _ in the
guise of a pajama party _ is available until 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line also constructed a Children's World play room in
an area that housed penthouse suites in previous incarnations of
this ship class (demand for the suites reportedly was slack).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's proven to be very, very popular,'' said Elation hotel
manager Aaron Thomas. ``The kids love having their own place. They
don't have to hang out with Mom and Dad all day.'' He added that
during the summer months ``we're chockablock with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of its success in marketing to families, Carnival's
reputation as a singles-friendly line still holds up on its Mexican
Riviera run _ at least judging from the turnout at the
opening-night mixer held for them. But it's probably advisable to
travel in a group, or at least to bring along a friend or relative
so you won't be randomly matched up with a roommate.
</P>
<P>
   My wife couldn't make this trip, and I discovered the first
night that solo travelers are gathered together at one desperate
dinner table. One older man arrived at our table, which was set for
12, and took a seat at the extreme side, directly opposite our
meager huddle of three early arrivals. When a member of our clutch
asked the fellow if he would like to join us, he lowered his menu
and said without smiling, ``No, I think I'd prefer to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   After we were all assembled, the excruciating conversation
bounced from high-tech stocks to roommates who snore to the
irregularity of bus service in San Francisco to the merits of not
going outdoors. It brought to mind the scene in ``Animal House''
where Flounder and Pinto are shunted into a roomful of misfits at
the snobby fraternity's pledge party, and the smarmy frat guy says,
``You should have (ITAL)lots(END ITAL) to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   After two nights of this, it seemed preferable to opt for the
ship's alternate dining choice, the Tiffany buffet. The food wasn't
nearly as elaborate or good _in fact, it was fairly ordinary _ but
at least there were carving stations and a considerable salad bar,
plus one feature the main dining room couldn't match: the
opportunity to take your food outside to a deck table and dine in
the fresh, tropical air, the ocean ripping past far below.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed like a particularly viable option as the ship left
Mazatlan _ precisely at the hour of the early dinner seating. The
craggy rock formations that protrude from the water at the harbor's
mouth were dazzling in the setting sun; the prospect of another
night at the solo travelers' table couldn't possibly compete with
this.
</P>
<P>
   Another departure from port was also memorable, for different
reasons. As we pulled out of Puerto Vallarta late at night (right
after the Mexican folk dancers and musicians disembarked), a deck
party was convened at the main pool area. Before long, it seemed as
if the entire passenger list of 2,200 had turned out for it (pajama
party be damned).
</P>
<P>
   The Lido Stage dance floor was packed solid. The reggae band had
that pile-driver snare drum going again. Waiters scurried about in
the dark, dispensing blue margaritas (keep the souvenir glass) for
all they were worth. The only food available at this juncture in
the gluttony calendar was pizza and frozen yogurt in the Tiffany
room, and, duly, I spotted a guy woofing pizza and frozen yogurt
simultaneously. The ``'70s fun and games'' were due to begin in an
hour. The ``R-rated'' stand-up comedy act was to commence in one of
the bars at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   On this cruise, they were assured a party. They got it.
</P>
<P>
   The captain drove. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
