<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      07-17 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCIUM AND ARTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Some coronary artery obstructions are described as calcified.
How do they develop? Should calcium-rich foods be avoided?
</P>
<P>
   A. Heart doctors generally suggest consuming plenty of calcium,
though seeking out low-fat dairy products; fat and cholesterol are
thought to be risky, not calcium.
</P>
<P>
   As people age, ``The Mayo Clinic Heart Book'' explains, the
smooth, elastic artery walls normally become thicker, and their
calcium content increases, in effect hardening all arteries to some
degree. But the dangerous type of hardening called atherosclerosis
involves chiefly the large arteries, including the coronary
arteries. The inner layers of the walls become thick and irregular,
and some areas accumulate fats, cholesterol and other materials.
Initially, the deposits are only streaks of fatty cells. But as
they enlarge, they may invade deeper layers, with scarring and
calcium deposits. Large areas are called atheromas or plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Plaque has a firm shell that may contain calcium deposited from
the blood along with areas of fatty material and a center of soft
cholesterol. The shell may break open, exposing the inner part, and
a blood clot tends to develop at this site. Such a clot may reduce
blood flow so much that chest pain or a heart attack results.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent studies suggest that calcified areas of plaque may
be more stable than those where the buildup is chiefly fatty, and
that they may be less likely to rupture and cause a heart attack.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(at)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
