</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-U.S.-TV (Undated) _ Two top U.S. television shows, ``Who
Wants To Be A Millionaire'' and ``Survivor,'' are 100 percent
British-made television ideas. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   WILDE-LOVER-BIOGRAPHY (Undated) _ Douglas Murray, who is ending
his second year at Magdalene College, Oxford, thinks that Lord
Douglas Alfred, the lover of Oscar Wilde, who was convicted of
``gross indecency'' and imprisoned because of his homosexual
activities, has gotten a bad rap. Murray, 20, is the author of
``Bosie,'' a new biography of Douglas. Wilde ``was not sent to
prison for Douglas,'' Murray said. ``He was prosecuted for his
relationship with rent boys,'' a British term for male prostitutes.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   O'NEILL-NEW-PLAYWRIGHTS (Waterford, Conn.) _ For 35 summers the
National Playwrights Conference has been the tall ship of the
Eugene O'Neill Theater Center, giving a berth to hundreds of new
plays and new playwrights. This year there is a major difference:
James Houghton as the new artistic director. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-NOVEL (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: Ring Lardner was
not merely America's incomparable analyst of a baseball pitcher's
psyche but of much else about the America of his time and ours. By
Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Birds of Passage,'' by Robert
Sole (Harvel/Harcourt Brace), reviewed by Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-THEATER-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``True West,'' at Circle in the
Square, reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ This fall, a few hundred books will
take a new form on the Internet. They will be sold in component
parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _ that can be mixed and
matched. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   SKECHERS-LAGEAR-GREENBERGS (Undated) _ Skechers, the maker of
trendy shoes, is on a roll: It is now the third most popular brand
among teens, company sales were up 40 percent last quarter from a
year ago and its stock has been among the market's best performers
this year. But the Greenbergs, the family that runs Skechers, also
ran L.A. Gear, one of retailing's most explosive collapses. Some
analysts and investors are concerned with what they see as
parallels between the two companies. By Kruti Trivedi.
</P>
<P>
   GENERALMILLS-PILLSBURY (Minneapolis) _ A look at General Mills
now that it will be a more formidable player in the food industry
after the acquisition of Pillsbury. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (With)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-MERGERS (Undated) _ On what comes next in the food industry
after Diageo PLC sold Pillsbury to General Mills. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MARKETS-MERGE (Undated) _ The London and Frankfurt stock
exchanges, which plan to merge, say they are also exploring a full
merger with the Nasdaq stock market. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RATES (Tokyo) _ The Bank of Japan voted Monday to leave
interest rates unchanged, citing in part the bankruptcy of the
retailer Sogo. Until Wednesday's bankruptcy filing, the central
bank had been widely expected to raise rates by a quarter point, to
0.27 percent, which would have been the first rate increase since
1990. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   PAPER-MERGER (Undated) _ General Pacific, the nation's second
biggest forest-products company, has agreed to buy Fort James for
$7.8 billion, becoming the world's biggest tissue maker and
lessening its dependence on the housing market. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   LAW-MERGER (Undated) _ Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro of San
Francisco, and Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam &AMP; Roberts of New York are
expected to announce a merger. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-DVD-SUIT (Undated) _ A federal judge in New York is
scheduled Monday to take up the case brought by eight Hollywood
studios against a Web site that posted DeCSS software, which allows
users to bypass the security system of DVD movie disks and, studios
say, leads to pirating. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-INVESTMENT-CLUBS (Undated) _ While Web sites like the
Motley Fool have long provided forums for investment club members
to meet and educate themselves about how to run clubs, a new crop
of Internet companies are taking it a step further, offering
one-stop shops merging communication tools with software engines
that handle complex administrative bookkeeping functions and
compile tax returns. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   CLAIROL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Clairol lady just got younger
_ 18 years old, to be exact. After years of working with more
mature celebrities, Clairol, a unit of Bristol-Myers Squibb, will
feature the pop singer Britney Spears in a new print and television
advertising campaign for its Herbal Essences shampoo line. By
Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROZAC-SAFETY (Undated) _ The new book ``Prozac Backlash''
claims that the drug has more serious and more frequent side
effects than the public is aware of or than the label indicates.
But other medical experts take a much more cautious approach and
point out that all drugs have side effects. A thorough examination
of the safety of Prozac and other antidepressives. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CALIF-ANTS (La Jolla, Calif.) _ Due to a quirk of evolution
and genetics, Argentine ants are taking over California while
forming what scientists believe could be the biggest ant colony in
the world, stretching over 600 miles from San Diego to San
Francisco. By Jon Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHTNING (Undated) _ An eight-week long experiment on
lightning and severe weather turned up some stunning surprises in
Goodland, Kan., the home of the nation's most violent
thunderstorms. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOMES-EARTHQUAKES (Undated) _ Wood-frame houses are being
tested for damage with an earthquake simulator. The conventional
belief has been that because wood can bend without breaking, a wood
building would survive an earthquake better. However, stucco, which
was downgraded after the 1994 Northridge earthquake, proved to
provide more earthquake resistance, but more testing needs to be
done. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUNGUS-HERBICIDE (Bozeman, Mont.) _ A native bioherbicide
fungus, Fusarium oxsporum, attacks coca plants, and some
researchers and politicians want to put it to work against the coca
fields of Colombia. But biologists see pros and cons. By Jim
Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAWAII-TRASH (Undated) _ Though Hawaii's coral reefs are
healthy compared to others in the world, they are the unfortunate
host to huge quantities of trash discarded into the Pacific Ocean.
This debris, like large fishing nets, threaten the coral and
endangered animals like the monk seal, &UR;  &LR; as well as the green sea
turtle and the humpback whale. By Rachel X. Weissman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BODY-IMAGE (Baltimore) _ Most psychologists believe that
women, men and even children are feeling worse than ever about the
way they look, especially about their weight. Girl Scouts and women
attending a tour called Feast, Famine and the Female Form _
Exploring Body Image Through Art, learned of the pitfalls of
dieting and that beauty comes in all shapes and sizes. By Leslie
Berger.
</P>
