<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SYRIAN LEADER KEEPS HARD LINE ON ISRAEL IN INAUGURAL SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ In his inaugural speech as president of Syria,
Bashar Assad focused Monday on fixing his country's ailing economy
and gave no sign he would be any more flexible than his father was
in negotiating a peace deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, an ophthalmologist by training, officially began a
seven-year term after taking the oath of office before the
250-member Syrian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He has been running the country since the death of his father,
Hafez Assad, on June 10. In a referendum last week, in which the
choice was saying ``yes'' or ``no'' to Assad's presidency, he won
the approval of 97 percent of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering the Golan Heights, the Syrian plateau that was
occupied by Israel in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, is a top priority,
Assad said. But he repeated the formulaic language of his father in
adding that Syria would not make peace unless all of the Golan was
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``However long it takes, this land is ours and it will return to
us in full,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations have been frozen since
mid-January, mainly over the future of a small strip of land that
borders the Sea of Galilee, the major source of Israel's water.
Syria has insisted on regaining its piece of shoreline, while
Israel has sought to maintain control over access to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   American and European efforts over the last nine years have
failed to find a compromise that satisfied both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Many Western diplomats had hoped that Assad, who was an infant
when Syria lost the Golan Heights, would bring a less ideological
approach to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   His father, who was defense minister during the 1967 war and
president in 1973 when Syria failed to regain the Golan in renewed
fighting, repeatedly proclaimed that any compromise with Israel
would tarnish Arab dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Assad's speech, his first major policy address, was
devoted to economic issues. He pledged to reform the Syrian
economy, which remains largely state-controlled and dependent on
oil exports, by streamlining the government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, who spoke about the need for modernization but
approved few changes in Syria's laws and ubiquitous security
apparatus, the new president pledged to move slowly. Economic
change, he said, will come about step by step.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian business owners, who have labored under a system with no
private banks and strict controls on currency flows, have urged a
major overhaul of the economic system.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who is 34, began his tenure by eschewing the
state-orchestrated personality cult that his father cultivated.
Syrian newspapers, which are all run by the state, said he did not
want to see his picture adorning every public and private building.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made a point in his inaugural speech of saying he
did not intend to pursue political reform that would threaten the
dominance of the one-party system that his father built.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom of expression should be encouraged, he said, but in the
form of ``positive criticism'' of government policies. Democracy as
practiced in the West, he added, can not and should not be grafted
onto Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have our own democracy to match our history and
culture, arising from the needs of our people and our reality,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1543EDT &QL; 
