<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAFFEINE FOUND IN SEATTLE WATERS; MEDITERRANEAN ALGAE MIGRATES TO
SAN DIEGO; AND SUGAR DISCOVERED IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COFFEE EVERYWHERE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jitters brought on by too much coffee can ruin many a
delicate, hands-on scientific experiment. But too much coffee, it
seems, has ruined a much larger experiment in the latte capital of
the world, Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Water-quality experts with King County, which includes Seattle,
have abandoned plans to use caffeine as a tracer to determine where
treated waste water flows when it enters Puget Sound. The problem,
they found, is that caffeine is everywhere in the sound.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mickelson, a water quality planner with the county, said
that caffeine had been thought to have great potential as a tracer
because it was not found naturally in the local environment but got
into the waste water through coffee drinking. The idea was to
analyze water samples in the sound for caffeine concentration to
determine where plumes of effluent traveled.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists found small concentrations of caffeine in
nearly all of the samples, totaling more than 200, that they
gathered. ``It's all over the place,'' Mickelson said. Because the
sound has about the same concentration of caffeine everywhere, it
couldn't be used to determine any kind of gradient that would track
waste water flow.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Mickelson said, is that a lot of coffee apparently
ends up in storm drains, and then goes directly into the sound.
``We have an awful lot of sidewalk baristas out here, he said,
``and at the end of the day, the dregs go out into storm drains.''
</P>
<P>
   TROUBLESOME ALGAE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A feather-like algae that has caused severe ecological problems
in the northwestern Mediterranean has been found for the first time
off the West Coast of the Americas. The algae, Caulerpa taxifolia,
was discovered by divers with a biological consulting firm studying
transplanted eelgrass beds in a coastal lagoon about 20 miles north
of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Caulerpa is native to the tropics, and when introduced into more
temperate waters it quickly crowds out other species as there are
few marine animals that graze on it. It was used for decoration in
saltwater aquariums in Europe starting about two decades ago. Then
in the late 1980s it was found in the Mediterranean (the source was
believed to have been an oceanographic museum in Monaco that
drained its tanks).
</P>
<P>
   The seaweed now covers thousands of acres of the Mediterranean
floor from Croatia to Spain, smothering native sea grass beds that
are the habitat for many other marine organisms. It spreads
rapidly, often carried by the anchors and anchor chains of boats.
</P>
<P>
   Caulerpa had been available for use in home aquariums in the
United States until last year, when its importation was banned. The
San Diego patch probably came from aquarium water dumped into a
storm drain or into the lagoon directly. The patch, which measures
about 60 feet by 30 feet, will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   CLUES TO EARLY EARTH
</P>
<P>
   To the list of things found in space _ giant planets, dark
matter and the Voyager 2 spacecraft, to name just a few _ can be
added sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers using a radio telescope on Kitt Peak in Arizona have
discovered a simple sugar molecule, glycoaldehyde, in a gas and
dust cloud near the center of the Milky Way. With eight atoms of
carbon, oxygen and hydrogen, it is one of the more complex of the
roughly 120 molecules found in interstellar clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Given the right conditions, glycoaldehyde can combine with other
molecules to form ribose, which is the basis for the nucleic acids
RNA and DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Because the interstellar clouds are the material from which new
stars are made, the finding shows that it is increasingly likely
that some chemicals that are thought of as the precursors to life
formed before the planets developed.
</P>
<P>
   Because in some cases the conditions in a cloud are similar to
conditions on the just-forming earth, the discovery may provide
some insight into how such molecules formed on the early earth, the
astronomers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
