A4605 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-17 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT IS WORTH REPEATING: SLAVERY WAS EVIL  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAGG HINES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reconstruction, it seems after more than a century
and a quarter, was not nearly radical enough.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rancid eruptions of Confederate fervor point to a
culture that was dealt with too leniently. We may know the
political and economic rationale that led to relatively easy
reintegration of the South into the fabric of the nation, but that
doesn't mean we can't regret the current consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Spare me your moss-draped cards and letters. I am the descendant
of slave owners, and a great-grandfather was captured at Vicksburg.
I know veneration of family almost as a religion, a sort of
Southern Shinto, and I revel in it.
</P>
<P>
   But I have no hesitation in saying that slavery was evil and a
despicable cause for rending the republic. I am saddened (not to
mention appalled) that a number of Southerners still cannot seem to
join in this simple statement.
</P>
<P>
   And this heritage and states' rights hogwash with which some
folks try to dress up their racism? Forget it. It's thinner than
the sheets some of this crowd wear on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Manifestations of this illness are well known. Most obvious of
late is the bizarrely zealous defense of the Confederate flag. But
there are other sinister outcroppings, including the recently
formed secessionist Southern Party.
</P>
<P>
   You want to laugh these people off as cranks or badly misguided
nostalgics. But having, within my adult lifetime, seen George C.
Wallace and Orval E. Faubus at work, that's not the best response.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect answer, of course, would be a change of heart, but
let's not hold our breath. Another option is political leadership.
And that's why the speech of George W. Bush to the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People last week was so
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our nation there is no denying that slavery is a blight on
our history,'' Bush said. ``And that racism, despite all the
progress, still exists today.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting President Lincoln's warning to a divided nation, Bush
went on to say: ``We cannot escape our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither can the Texas governor. Less than six
months ago, in the heat of the South Carolina Republican
presidential primary campaign, Bush could not see his way clear to
speak out against the Confederate flag flying above the statehouse
in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted the flag question was a local issue. He knew
better. He just wasn't willing to take a chance that South Carolina
Republicans would understand his acting like a leader instead of a
political calculator.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Bush said at the time that he would refuse the
Confederate flag as a symbol in Texas, and he has recently seen two
commemorative plaques removed from the Texas Supreme Court, one of
which depicted the banner. In the campaign ahead _ and in a Bush
administration if there is another one _ let's hope there will be
more of the NAACP speech and less of the South Carolina posturing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 100 years, with the exception of the racist fringe
including the Ku Klux Klan, there was little widespread use (much
less adoration) of the Confederate flag until it was dragged from
under the bed in opposition to the civil rights movement. Only then
was it incorporated into some Southern state flags and hoisted atop
the South Carolina Capitol. With these actions, the old flag took
on the official coloration that makes its continued display so
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said they can't fly the flag,'' NAACP President
Kweisi Mfume said last week as Confederate sympathizers taunted his
convention-goers in Baltimore. ``We just said they can't fly it on
public buildings, as in South Carolina. If they want to fly it at
home, on the back of their car, wherever, that's property rights,
which I support. That's not our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume was being supremely statesmanlike.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point was the view expressed by NAACP board Chairman
Julian Bond, who called the demonstrators ``apologists for
slavery.'' They are, as Bond said, ``beneath contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cragg Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in
Washington. Contact him by e-mail at cragg.hines &LR; chron.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
