<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-17 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROJECT VOTE SMART A RESPECTABLE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CLAY ROBISON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It is tempting to label Project Vote Smart an
oxymoron, in deference to the disrespect that many voters and
nonvoters alike heap upon our political system and the politicians
who prevail on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it is a project that is attempting to make politics
more respectable by encouraging more people to vote and helping
them to cast their ballots in an informed manner. It is not a task
for the fainthearted, and it is made particularly difficult by
politicians who _ not surprisingly _ are more interested in getting
elected to and remaining in office than in improving the
respectability of their calling.
</P>
<P>
   An informed vote isn't dictated by a certain partisan or
philosophical line. Rather, it is cast by a person who actually
knows something about the candidates and their positions on
relevant issues.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept!
</P>
<P>
   Project Vote Smart's political neutrality is guaranteed by a
board with such diverse selections as Michael Dukakis and Newt
Gingrich. The late Barry Goldwater was a founder, as was George
McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Funded by member-donors and private foundations, the project
through its Web site and toll-free hotline offers voters a range of
informational services.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, people can use its resources to find out who
represents them in Congress or the Texas Legislature, if they don't
already know _ and many people don't.
</P>
<P>
   Project Vote Smart also offers information on officeholders'
voting records, their evaluations by special interest groups and
candidates' campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   One of the project's potentially most useful tools is an
ambitious and pretty detailed election-year survey of presidential,
gubernatorial, congressional and state legislative candidates on a
wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, dubbed the National Political Awareness Test, has
been conducted since 1992, but it has never realized its full
potential because many candidates refuse to cooperate, despite
repeated pleas from Project Vote Smart staffers and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was the first state to have the survey responses from its
congressional and legislative candidates compiled this year, and
the return rate was poor. Only 113 of 374 general election
candidates _ fewer than one in three _ returned the questionnaire
by last week's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Their responses can be viewed on the project's Web site at
www.vote-smart.org or can be obtained by calling 1-888-VOTE-SMART.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also can find out which candidates refused to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Challengers and minor party candidates were more likely to
complete the questions than incumbents because most challengers and
minor party candidates have to scramble for public attention and
are eager to take advantage of any forum to publicize their views.
</P>
<P>
   Most incumbents are more likely to be cautious. More often than
not, they are well-funded by special-interest groups and want to
control the presentation of their messages through paid
advertising, Web sites or news releases. They don't want to answer
questions they have no control over selecting or devising.
</P>
<P>
   They may use the convenient excuse that they are flooded with
questionnaires from various groups and just don't have time to
respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, they fear that opponents would use their
responses to questions, even to the point of misrepresenting their
answers, to develop campaign attacks against them.
</P>
<P>
   The most noteworthy Texas incumbent to complete this year's
survey was Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, who has only
nominal re-election opposition.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush completed the questionnaire during his 1994 and
1998 gubernatorial races. But neither he nor Vice President Al
Gore, the two likely major party nominees, completed the survey for
presidential candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   So Project Vote Smart filled in the questionnaires for them,
based on the two candidates' statements, speeches and position
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Completing their objective questionnaire is the ``right and
honorable thing'' for a candidate to do, project staffers contend.
Many candidates, however, fear that too much information in the
hands of voters can be downright unhealthy for their political
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Clay Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
Contact him by e-mail at clay.robison &LR; chron.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
