<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUM TO CHEW AWAY TOOTH DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Minn., Mass., Pa.)   (Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chewing gum that contains a substance found in birch bark can
help suppress the bacteria that cause tooth decay, The Journal of
the American Dental Association reported in July.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Minnesota selected 151
patients with high levels of mutans streptococci, the bacteria that
causes tooth decay. After they were treated for two weeks with an
antimicrobial mouthwash, they were given either sugar-free gum, no
gum or gum containing the subtance, xylitol, to chew for five
minutes after meals for three months.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria levels quickly returned to pre-treatment levels
among those given regular gum or no gum. Those chewing xylitol, a
sweetener, had their bacterial levels rebound roughly half as much
as the other patients, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Used in conjunction with other cavity-control strategies, such
as diet modification, fluoride and sealants, a xylitol-sweetened
chewing gum appears to be a helpful treatment for controlling tooth
decay,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: A LENS, SOME SLEEP AND BETTER VISION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By wearing contact lenses when their eyes are shut at night,
mildly nearsighted people may be able to improve their vision
enough to do without glasses or contacts, according to the July
issue of Optometry and Vision Science.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Ohio State University gave eight people a new
kind of contact lens called reverse geometry lenses.
</P>
<P>
   All rigid contact lenses exert enough pressure on the eyeball to
change its shape temporarily, and the researchers hoped that
reverse geometry lenses could flatten the cornea in the same way
that refractive eye surgery does.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional contact lenses are convex; reverse geometry lenses
are flatter at the edges and steeper at the center. The research
subjects wore the lenses at night. After a week, their vision
improved significantly.
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks, six were able to go without lenses during the
day; the other two dropped out of the study complaining of
discomfort. None of the eight were severely myopic and they had
little or no astigmatism, an irregular curve across the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Barr of Ohio State said that if further studies
showed similar results, the reverse geometry lenses could present a
cheaper alternative to refractive eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: TEETH-CLEANING GUIDELINE OFTEN IGNORED
</P>
<P>
   Too few patients who need protective doses of antibiotics before
dental cleaning are getting it, and too many patients who do not
need the medicine are, according to a study published this month in
The Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   In rare instances, bacteria from the mouth can enter the
bloodstream during dental work and cause potentially
life-threatening infections of the heart valves. About
three-quarters of those infected are people with existing heart
problems, including leaky or significantly thickened valves.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, doctors have been recommending prophylactic
doses of antibiotics for patients at risk. Those guidelines were
updated and simplified three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, researchers from Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center in Boston followed up on 218 patients who had been examined
for potential heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   They found that the guidelines were being followed for the
patients most at risk, nearly 90 percent of whom were told to take
antibiotics for specific procedures, wrote Dr. Warren Manning, a
cardiologist at Beth Israel Deaconess.
</P>
<P>
   But only 60 percent of the far larger group of patients whose
risks were lower but who still should have gotten the drugs were
told to do so, and 25 percent of low-risk patients were given the
drugs unnecessarily. And 13 percent of patients who were told to
take antibiotics decided on their own not to do so, Manning wrote.
</P>
<P>
   DIAGNOSIS: A COMPOSER'S SLEEP APNEA LULLABY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brahms may have had a good reason for writing lullabies: he may
have suffered from a sleep disorder, according to an article
published last week in the journal Chest.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell L. Margolis, a pulmonologist at the Philadelphia
Veterans Administration Medical Center, wrote that the composer may
have suffered from sleep apnea, a condition involving the
interruption of breathing during sleep with consequences that can
range from annoying to life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snoring is the most common clue to sleep apnea, but
because Brahms never married, the most common form of documentation
is missing. A traveling companion, however, once complained
bitterly of the noise that Brahms made.
</P>
<P>
   But Margolis said that Brahms exhibited other common symptoms,
including falling asleep at odd times and places (the sight of
Brahms asleep in a Viennese cafe was common enough to draw
tourists), an obese neck (the composer wore collarless shirts after
age 50) and irritability. (Brahms is said to have announced once,
``If there is anyone here I have not offended, I apologize.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders if the disorder contributed to lifelong alienation
from friends and marriage,'' Margolis wrote, ``thereby indirectly
nurturing his determined devotion to the creation of his immortal
music.''
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: DEADLY MOVES WHEN A HEART ATTACK HITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least in the abstract, most people know what to do if they
are struck by severe chest pain: call an ambulance and get to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But when it really happens, people turn out to be far more
reluctant to dial 911, much to their own detriment, a new study
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published last week in the journal Circulation,
compared survey responses in which 962 people were asked about the
proper course of action when a heart attack was suspected and the
actual steps taken in 875 cases in the 20 communities covered.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the Oregon Health Sciences University in
Portland and the University of Utah Medical Center in Salt Lake
City, found that while 89 percent of the people surveyed said that
they would use emergency medical services to go to a hospital, only
23 percent of the real-life cases ended up arriving at the hospital
by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent were driven to the hospital by someone else,
while 16 percent drove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Prompt treatment of heart attacks has come to be considered
critical, especially since the development of clot-busting drugs
that reduce death rates but which can be administered effectively
only within a few hours of an attack's onset.
</P>
<P>
   Those who took the longest time to reach the emergency room were
those who took antacids, suspecting that the pain was severe
heartburn, those who took aspirin in an attempt to treat the heart
problem themselves, and those who called their doctors for advice.
</P>
<P>
   One of the researchers, Dr. N. Clay Mann of Utah, called that
particularly disturbing. ``Speaking with a doctor may have reduced
patient anxiety in a way that made EMS transport seem optional,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   People who were charged for emergency services called 911 in
lower numbers, the study also found.
</P>
</TEXT>
