A4614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-TEXAS-BASHING-HNS &LR;      07-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BASHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MESSAGE TO AL GORE: `DON'T MESS WITH TEXAS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE ELY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Obviously, George W. Bush is fair game for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it quite rightly can be expected that anyone who is a
Democrat can, and likely will, talk tacky about the Republican
Texas governor who is only a couple of weeks away from officially
being nominated the GOP candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   But, let's get one thing straight _ very straight: Talking bad
about Bush is one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Talking bad about Texas is quite another, and, clearly Al Gore
doesn't need any help in that department. And he, by golly for
sure, doesn't need any help from Texas Democrats in slamming Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question there's going to be a lot of Texas Dems
available to go around the country between now and Nov. 7 to speak
ill of the governor and to claim all that's good that's happened in
Texas since Bush took office is because of the hard and honest work
of Texas Dems.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Beth Malcolm, the head of the Texas Democratic Party, is
one who's got that routine down pat. To hear her tell it, if there
hadn't been Democrats in the Texas Legislature, there wouldn't even
be a state left for Gore to denigrate. To Malcolm's credit,
however, she seems to have done a good job of keeping her awful
gripes aimed at Bush - not at the state she suggests he's quite
inclined to ruin. And, she usually does speak well of Texas - or at
least the parts of it on which she thinks the Dems have done such a
boffo job.
</P>
<P>
   And, to a great extent, this has held true for a lot of other
high-profile Texas Democrats who've felt compelled to share their
uncomplimentary opinions of Bush with folk in various other parts
of the country. They've managed to do OK by Texas while contending
Bush hasn't managed to do OK by Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the report about state Rep. Garnet Coleman of
Houston, whom the Gore campaign brought in late last week to speak
ill of the reported budget predicament facing Texas. Bless his
heart, from all reports Coleman doesn't seem to have done Bush much
harm. What he appears to have told the national press is that he's
now decided the tax cuts Bush pushed through the last Texas
Legislature weren't a good idea after all. We can but presume Bush
_ or someone _ had convinced Coleman they were when he voted for
them last year.
</P>
<P>
   If that alone fails to have much effect on Gore and his
anti-Texas mode, it looks like Texas Dems would work on him to find
something on which to harp besides the horror he claims is Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, you'd think even folk from other states
would be tired by now of hearing the Democratic candidate spend so
much time, sweat and effort talking about how awful Texas is.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's true or not, there's a lot of Texans who are sick
to death of hearing their state portrayed as some sort of hellhole
where people with untreated open sores couldn't read their
insurance policies if they had any. Nor, for that matter, could
they seek help from a teacher in a Texas school for reading because
they're as wretched as all the other wrongs Gore keeps finding in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a group of right prominent Texans has just emerged to
counteract what its members characterize in a letter to Gore as
``misrepresentations by your campaign to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Proud of Texas Committee,'' organized by Texas Monthly
publisher Mike Levy, is a self-described ad hoc group of
independents and Democrats. In a letter to Gore, the members told
the veep they ``are disturbed by the extent to which the Gore
campaign appears to be willing to distort the facts about our state
in order to discredit Gov. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   They took strong issue with what they claim as
misrepresentations in education, health care and the criminal
justice system in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In an obvious attempt to appear independent of Bush and/or the
Republican Party, the group also sent the governor a letter
declaring their intent ``to speak out when information presented in
the media about Texas is incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   In a somewhat harsher wording than that ending the letter to
Bush, the committee wrote Gore: ``All Texans have a vested interest
in ensuring that Texas receives an accurate, fair assessment in the
media. ... We believe that both candidates in this presidential
campaign have a responsibility to uphold the public trust by
sticking strictly to the facts between now and November, and we
call on you to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, friends and neighbors, is what you might call a real
polite way to say: ``Don't mess with Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear. Hear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jane Ely is a columnist for the Houston Chronicle columnist.
Contact her by e-mail at jane.ely(at)chron.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
