   E-COMMERCE (moved in the ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   THE NEXT BIG LEAP? IT'S CALLED XML
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOM-NEW-WEB-LANGUAGE-NYTSF _ In the beginning, the Web was
made possible by a simple innovation known as Hypertext Markup
Language, or HTML. Through this language, which arranged text,
images and buttons in a World Wide Web browser, information could _
and very much still can _ be read by computer users all over the
world. Yet despite its power, HTML has flaws, the most obvious
being an inability to make distinctions between the presentation of
computer data and the data itself. Now the next generation of Web
language, called XML (for Extensible Markup Language), is emerging.
Here, a report on how XML has the potential to establish a real
Internet lingua franca. By John Markoff. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH BOOM NEAR SANTA'S HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOM-UNLIKELY-TECH-BOOMTOWN-NYTSF _ Oulu, Finland, must rank
as one of the world's most improbable technology boomtowns. Except
for forests and lakes, there isn't much within 100 miles of Oulu.
The most notable town to the north is Rovaniemi, which has built
its economy on the assertion that it is the true home of Santa
Claus. Yet this town of 100,000 people is home to hundreds of
electronics companies. Driven in part by Nokia, the Helsinki
company that is the world's biggest manufacturer of mobile
telephones, Oulu thrives as a center for research on wireless data
communications. It also has also become a hotbed for Internet
start-ups. Find out why in this feature. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   POPULAR MECHANICS (moved in the ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   SING AROUND THE SOLAR-POWERED CAMPSITE
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR-GADGETS-POPMECH _ Clear sunlight contains 1,000 watts of
power per square meter at sea level. That's enough to power
everything on Earth 1,500 times over if we could just figure out a
way to harness all the free, nonstop solar energy that bathes the
globe every day. Of course, in a very real sense everything on
Earth is already solar-powered _ we just release that power in
different ways. Burning long-buried hydrocarbons to get at stored
solar energy, as we've been doing, isn't particularly efficient.
But other ways to use solar energy are available. There's a whole
campsite worth of clever outdoor gear that runs directly on
sunlight. By Rich Taylor. (900 words.) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
