<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXERCISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUNCHED FOR TIME? WORKOUT ON AISLE 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lynn Weisbach walks on a treadmill five days a week between the
deli and produce sections of her grocery store. That's because the
health club she belongs to, CardioTheater Express in Alpharetta,
Ga., is tucked into the front corner of a Kroger supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves time because I have to shop anyway,'' said Weisbach,
a 46-year-old painter, who started walking on the treadmill six
months ago to lower her blood pressure. ``If this wasn't here, I'd
have to drive somewhere. In that case, I don't think I'd be
exercising.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, commercial health clubs are turning up in
interesting places. These kinds of exercise centers within other
centers have a name: mini-fusion workout centers. They are usually
smaller and generally less expensive than full-scale health clubs,
and are in areas where people would go anyway, like Laundromats,
truck stops and airports. Their purpose is to fuse exercise with
another activity to make it more convenient for time-squeezed
Americans who also want to get and stay fit.
</P>
<P>
   The American Council on Exercise, a watchdog organization in San
Diego, named mini-fusion centers a major fitness trend for this
year. Exercise centers in hotels and apartment complexes are now
common. Mini-fusion centers are a twist on that theme, said Ken
Alan, a personal trainer and college exercise instructor in Los
Angeles, who is a spokesman for ACE.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 reason people say they don't exercise is because of
time,'' Alan said. ``But this kind of facility brings the club to
the consumer, to make working out easier and more accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association,
the trade organization for health clubs, has also taken note of the
mini-fusion trend. Though the organization has no specific data on
these kinds of clubs, William C. Howland Jr., the association's
director of public relations and research, said that more and more
small facilities were popping up in unusual places. It makes sense,
he added. If workout centers are in places where customers can come
and go easily, they will join.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, people appreciate working out in places where once
they get in, they have nothing to do but wait. Like the airport.
Paul Rorden, a pilot for National Airlines, exercises for an hour
and a half a couple of times a week at 24-Hour Fitness, a health
club that opened this year in McCarran International Airport in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you do as a pilot is wait around, then sit for five hours
and then eat,'' said Rorden, 33, who flies out of Las Vegas four to
10 times a week. ``Exercising here is convenient and time well
spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Airport Fitness, runs a health club at the
Pittsburgh International Airport and hopes to expand into nine more
airports in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling is stressful, not just for pilots and flight
attendants but for everyone, said Michael E. Michno, president and
chief executive of Airport Fitness in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse than sitting in place and breathing
recycled air. Exercise is a great way to bounce back,'' Michno
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people like mini-fusion centers because they feel more
comfortable and less intimidated exercising in a familiar place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people just don't want to walk into a large,
full-service health club full of hard-bodies,'' Alan said. ``They
would prefer to get started and build their confidence in a
facility that's more comfortable. That's why I expect to see more
and more health clubs in places like malls and supermarkets over
the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisbach added: ``I was the beginner of all beginners when I
started. I had tried to join a regular health club, but I didn't
make it past the lobby. I'm this gray-headed, middle-aged lady and
I felt too intimidated. Kroger's is more intimate. Plus, after I'm
finished, I can pick up a few groceries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
