<HEADER>
A4618 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-STALKER-2TAKES-TEX     07-17 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STALKER-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 6 YEARS, STALKING VICTIM FEARS FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By GABRIELLE CRIST 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Charles says the man who is stalking her has stolen her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's worried he will end it, and the criminal justice
system can do little to help her.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Alexander Lewis, 47, a mechanical engineer from Arlington,
Texas, adjacent to Fort Worth, has been in the Tarrant County Jail
for about a week, accused of leading police on a high-speed chase
after they tried to arrest him on two felony stalking warrants out
of Arlington and nearby Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was following Charles when police tried to arrest him,
prompting the chase, Grand Prairie police Detective Marc Taddonio
said. Lewis is on probation for harassing Charles, whom he dated
for about a year after they met in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Family Violence Court Judge Jamie Cummings delayed a
scheduled bond hearing so that Lewis could be evaluated by a
psychiatrist to see if he is competent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis is deemed competent, a bond hearing will be scheduled
within the next couple of weeks, attorneys said. Bail must be set,
but the judge has discretion over the amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if he gets out of jail, I'm done,'' said Charles, her
hands shaking and her eyes filling with tears.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said she wanted to tell her story in the hope that
publicity might protect her from harm.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is in custody and could not be interviewed for this
article. Lewis' attorney, Danny Burns, declined to comment, saying
he has just been retained and is unfamiliar with the details.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Daniels, Lewis' friend and boss, described Lewis as a
``fine man'' and single father of three who is being stalked
himself, by Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a stalker. I kind of figured she was following him,''
Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, 37, is right to be frightened, said Brad Clark, a
former Tarrant County prosecutor who handled Lewis' prior stalking
and harassment cases.
</P>
<P>
   The short length of their relationship and the intensity and
duration of the stalking have made the case the worst he has seen,
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis ``really, really concerns me,'' said Clark, who is now in
private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Stalking is a class A misdemeanor in Texas, punishable by up to
one year in jail and a $4,000 fine. If a person is convicted of
stalking for a second time, it becomes a third-degree felony,
punishable by up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   National studies show that most stalkers are former husbands or
boyfriends. Only about 25 percent of stalking cases involve someone
who doesn't know the victim, according to some studies.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has left about 100 voice-mail messages for Charles at her
workplace in Grand Prairie, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the guy who makes things even, and I guarantee you
I'll make it even till the day I die,'' a male voice says in one
message. Charles identified the caller as Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   When Daniels was told about the messages, he said Lewis ``might
be smitten. ... The boy's just at the end of his rope.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Lewis began dating a few months after they met in
February 1993. The relationship quickly turned tumultuous, and when
Charles tried to end it, he wouldn't leave her alone, she has told
police.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said she has moved six times and changed her phone
number repeatedly, but Lewis always finds her. She said she's not
sure how Lewis keeps getting her number.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been arrested four times on charges related to
harassing her. Each time, he becomes angrier, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five years, Charles has lived in apartment
complexes because she worries that no one would hear her screams in
a house. Fearing that he might follow her, she takes different
routes home from work each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men like this, they do it a little at a time,'' she said.
``Take away your spirit, take away your heart, take away your
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles said she hadn't dated Lewis long before she began to see
signs of possessiveness. He called her constantly, always wanting
to know where she was, wanting to control every moment. Sometimes,
he would pound on her windows late at night, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The pair fought frequently, often loudly, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   When she tried to break up with him late in 1993, the phone
calls increased and the late-night visits became more frequent, she
told police.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Charles would let Lewis in simply to quiet him, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Frank got his way, everything was fine,'' Charles
said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Charles would call Lewis, screaming and cursing,
to tell him to stay away from her.
</P>
<P>
   She began filing reports with Arlington police almost
immediately after they began dating. One report says that someone
removed Charles' mail from her mailbox without permission in May
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Possible known suspect is harassing the victim by leaving
trash at her door and window and by banging on her door,'' says
another, from February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspect intentionally and knowingly entered the victim's
apartment without effective consent of the victim, after having
been warned off of the victim's property,'' says another, from
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Lewis posted at her apartment pornographic pictures
of a woman resembling Charles, according to the arrest warrant
affidavit filed by Arlington police. Her name, a description of her
car and her phone number were written on some of them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said a friend took photographs of her name and work
phone number scrawled near several pay phones in Arlington, along
with a lewd sexual comment.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believed that the harassment would end after the
cases against Lewis began making their way to court in June 1999.
(MORE)
nn
</P>
<P>
   The law defines stalking as engaging in behavior on more than
one occasion that threatens bodily injury or death of the intended
party or that person's family, destroying the intended party's
personal property or causing the intended party or that person's
family to fear bodily injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic violence cases, the victim can seek a protective
order from a judge. If the order is violated, the offender can be
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles is not eligible for such an order because she and
Lewis haven't been married, never lived together and aren't blood
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis pleaded guilty to misdemeanor stalking and harassment in
June 1999, in a plea agreement reached with prosecutors. He
received no additional jail time for the stalking charge because
he'd spent some time in and out of jail awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   He received two years' probation in a deferred sentencing
agreement for the harassment. Unlike regular probation, if an
offender fulfills the terms of the deferred sentence, a conviction
is not entered in the court record.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis received an additional year's probation for driving while
intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of the deferred sentencing agreement, Lewis had
to get a job and was allowed to work for Daniels in Oklahoma City.
Lewis was not supposed to leave Oklahoma without the judge's
permission.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't supposed to contact Charles.
</P>
<P>
   But he did, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said her life got pretty quiet _ she was getting only
about 10 calls a week _ until November 1999, when Lewis showed up
at her Arlington apartment and banged on her bedroom window,
according to the arrest warrant affidavit from Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   About two months ago, she began getting the calls at work.
Charles said she has saved nearly 100 voice-mail messages that she
said Lewis left for her.
</P>
<P>
   On numerous messages, a male voice repeats, ``July 18, 1993,''
the first time they were intimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave you all my love, all my heart, gave you everything I
had to give,'' the man says in one message. ``You remember July 18,
July 18, 1993? Do you remember? Do you remember that July 18 of
1993, July 18?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the messages become more ominous.
</P>
<P>
   In one voice-mail message, the man says, ``You (expletive) up my
life and now you don't want to be a part of it? It ain't my fault
now, it ain't my fault. It's your fault. You've got to be a part of
my life until I die. Kill me, that'd be the best thing. Kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a whisper, the male voice then says: ``That'd be the best
thing. Susan, evil (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' 22-year-old daughter, Erin Lewis, acknowledged that her
father had called Charles.
</P>
<P>
   The message didn't mean that he wanted to be with Charles, she
said. It meant that Charles cannot accuse him of committing crimes,
then walk away from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that he's the freakin' pope,'' Erin Lewis said.
But Charles, she said, is ``trying to act like she's princess and
he's evil.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
