<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-WEB-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE IS POPULAR NEW STOP IN NURSING HOME SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL HULSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The emotionally painful task of finding a nursing
home once centered on meeting with medical advisers and a phone
survey of nearby facilities. For an increasing number of Americans,
the search now starts in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people are logging on to a comprehensive
nursing home database operated by the federal Medicare agency,
using it to locate homes in their communities, check the patient
mix and staffing levels, and see how the homes performed in recent
state inspections.
</P>
<P>
   After attracting just a few hundred hits a month following its
launch in 1998, the Nursing Home Compare section of the
www.medicare.gov Web site is thriving. It records 500,000 page
views per month and is by far the most popular stop on the site,
which also includes information about Medicare managed care plans,
Medigap coverage and general Medicare information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea of the kind of interest that is out there,''
said Nancy-Ann DeParle, head of the Health Care Financing
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home section provides individual information on
17,000 nursing homes certified for Medicare and Medicaid and allows
consumers to locate them by name, state, county, city or ZIP code.
Besides details about ownership and staffing levels, the site makes
available inspection records and shows how each center compares to
state and national averages for deficiencies. The surveys rate the
risk any deficiencies pose to residents, ranking them from
immediate jeopardy to minimal threat.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer advocates and nursing home representatives find
fault with aspects of the site, both groups say it fills an
information vacuum and should be an essential tool for anyone
struggling with placing a relative or loved one in the care of a
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question it is an advantage,'' said Elma Holder,
director and founder of the National Citizens' Coalition for
Nursing Home Reform. ``It is more than we have ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Holder, federal health care officials and nursing home
executives say the Web site should be used only to supplement
information gathered independently by consumers and should not be
the sole basis of a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can certainly be part of their search process but it cannot
and should not be the only stop in the process,'' said Tom Burke,
spokesman for the American Health Care Association, which
represents for-profit nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups say the most important part of a nursing home
search is personal visits to homes under consideration, including
going at different times of day or night to gauge the overall
atmosphere and level of care.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection reports posted on the Web site, however, provide
information on quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it really does help people understand about quality
even if you don't understand all the jargon,'' said DeParle, who
said the site has had the added benefit of motivating homes to
improve care to burnish their Web portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Holder and Burke said the data on the site had the potential to
exaggerate problems at a facility or give false confidence to
consumers if the survey was not rigorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as good as the survey data is, that is the key to it,''
said Holder, who cautioned that data on the site could be out of
date if a nursing home had undergone staff changes. ``A nursing
home can change dramatically in a very short period of time if they
lose key staff, which they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke agreed, saying inspection reports could be up to 18 months
old _ ``ancient history'' in nursing home terms. The information is
``convoluted, exceedingly complex and often leads to a
misunderstanding about the true nature of a facility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But California lawmakers referred to the site in recent months
to alert residents about nursing home problems in their
communities, and it has been recognized by outside experts for its
content.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle attributed some of the site's popularity to the growing
Web savvy of older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare agency continues to tweak the type of information
available and added staffing figures this spring, listing the
number of registered nurses, licensed practical or vocational
nurses and nursing assistants in each home.
</P>
<P>
   Holder, who said she found the site fairly easy to navigate,
said her group was pressing HCFA to provide the specific name of
the corporation that owns each home, an idea the agency was
pursuing. ``We think that is valuable information for consumers
because if they run into trouble that is where they are going to
end up,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
