<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, July 18. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ As the Camp David peace summit
meeting moved closer to the supposed deadline of President
Clinton's Wednesday morning departure for Japan, the White House
remained officially committed Monday to reaching ``an agreement''
before then. But some U.S., Israeli and Palestinian officials began
deliberately lowering expectations for a breakthrough, even
suggesting that there may need to be additional summit meetings. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS (Moscow) _ Boris Berezovsky, the archetypal
Russian tycoon, politician and, until lately, a force within the
Kremlin itself, said Monday that he would quit his seat in
parliament and try to form an alliance of big business and regional
politicians aimed at curbing President Vladimir Putin's growing
power. By Michael Wines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-GARBAGE (Manila) _ Loosened by a week of monsoon
rains, Manila's massive garbage mountain _ the symbol of the
nation's poverty _ collapsed last week and smothered hundreds of
squatters who make a living picking through it with metal hooks for
scraps of refuse. One week later, rescuers were still digging
through hundreds of tons of muck Monday, working in one-hour shifts
because of the rot of the soaking garbage, the poisonous gasses it
emits and the stench of the decomposing bodies that are buried in
it. So far, about 200 bodies have been recovered. Residents
estimate that as many as four times that number may have died,
though a complete death toll will probably never be known. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP (Washington) _ When George W. Bush is asked
what factors he is seeking in his running-mate, he talks about
things like preparedness to be president and compatability. But he
never mentions the one factor that several of his advisers say is
hovering over his entire selection process: abortion. This is the
first presidential campaign in which the Republican candidate can
talk about picking a running mate who supports abortion rights and
not be laughed off stage. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAMS (Pioneer, Calif.) _ The future of the Pacific Gas and
Electric hydropower system, a complex of 174 dams on 17 river
systems that is the largest privately held collection of dams in
the world, is at stake under current plans for its pieces to be
auctioned off to the highest bidder by sometime next year. That
specter had prompted a coalition of environmental groups and
outdoorsmen to demand that any sale be tied to arrangements
intended to ease the toll being inflicted on California's rivers.
By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Based on the frenzied
pace of speculative construction here this summer and the frazzled
lives of craftsmen doing the building, the Hamptons have never
before been invaded by so many rich people wanting to be wowed and
demanding that it happen fast. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ This fall, a few hundred books will
take a new form on the Internet. They will be sold in component
parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _ that can be mixed and
matched. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
