<SLUG> BC--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANAGH SHAKES UP SHAKESPEARE _ AND CRITICS _ WITH A '30S-STYLE
MUSICAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By MARK LOWRY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of Fred Astaire, Ginger Rogers and Gene Kelly don't have to
worry about their Hollywood icons being overshadowed by
Tinseltown's new generation of song-and-dance performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were not really attempting to dazzle in the
way that Astaire or Rogers could, or Kelly,'' says Kenneth Branagh,
whose musical version of ``Love's Labour's Lost'' opened Friday in
Dallas. ``Because we didn't have the time or resources to do that.
Or the talent, quite frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say ``Love's'' a failure as a musical or as a
film experience. In fact, it might just be the most inventive and
audacious cinematic undertaking of the summer, being at the same
time an adaptation of the Shakespeare comedy of the same name and
an homage to the great Hollywood musicals of the '30s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   While it does offer recognizable stars (Branagh, Alicia
Silverstone, Nathan Lane), ``Love's'' biggest attraction is the
off-screen talent involved: First, Shakespeare, and second,
Broadway legends of yore like Irving Berlin, Cole Porter, George
and Ira Gershwin and Jerome Kern.
</P>
<P>
   The latter's music is more than filler for the gaps in the text
caused by Branagh's wholesale editing (some 70 percent of the play
was excised to suit his purposes). Instead, in classic Broadway
musical form, signature tunes such as ``I Get a Kick Out of You,''
``The Way You Look Tonight'' and ``You Can't Take That Away From
Me,'' sung by the cast, become part of the narrative, accompanied
by breezy choreography in lavish production numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have called the project foolhardy or even crazy.
But Branagh, sitting in his Adolphus Hotel suite in Dallas more
than a month ago while on a press tour for the movie (which was
originally supposed to hit the Dallas market in mid-June), talked
with confidence about the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, to begin with, is old hat for Branagh, who has
directed and starred in ``Henry V'' and a four-hour version of
``Hamlet,'' among other adaptations of the Bard. With ``Love's,''
the challenge for Branagh wasn't Shakespeare's dialogue, but the
footwork that accompanied the songs. ``For me, it was absolutely
physically exerting,'' he says, ``way more difficult than doing
`Hamlet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, putting Shakespeare into musical form is not a new
concept. Duke Ellington created a famous version of ``Twelfth
Night,'' Rodgers and Hart added music to ``The Comedy of Errors''
for the 1940 film ``The Boys From Syracuse,'' and, of course,
there's ``Kiss Me Kate'' and ``West Side Story,'' which use ``The
Taming of the Shrew'' and ``Romeo and Juliet,'' respectively, as
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, in Hollywood, musicals are a dead issue.
They don't work onscreen anymore, no one wants to see them, and so
no one wants to make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite wanting to do a musical, like many other people, I had
been wondering why they hadn't worked in any significant way in 40
years,'' the actor and director says.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't particularly like the answer, though he understood it
_ and thought he could transcend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel deeply the cynicism of the age, absolute
second-guessing of every single thing that we do,'' he says. ``As a
culture, we're examining everything for the calculation behind it.
`They're doing this, but what do they really mean?' We're looking
for postmodern twists for irony, for meanings.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll get none of that in ``Love's Labour's Lost,'' and Branagh
_ who made the film with a relatively small budget _ believes
people might just find that refreshing. The comedy and simple plot
of ``Love's,'' one of the Bard's earliest comedies, are designed
for flights of fancy _ and are ripe, he believes, for an old-school
musical adaptation. The story concerns a young king (Alessandro
Nivola) and three lords (Branagh, Adrian Lester and Matthew
Lillard) who vow to devote three years to their studies and nothing
else, including women. This quickly changes when they meet the
visiting Princess of France (Silverstone) and her three ladies
(Natascha McElhone, Emily Mortimer and Carmen Ejogo).
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a young man's play,'' Branagh says. ``It's so
technically sophisticated, there's an enormous amount of rhyme.
There's an exuberance in the writing, and a sort of disregard for a
conventional playwright's discipline. What I loved about (both) the
play and (classic musical theater) were a sort of
heart-on-its-sleeve silliness, a delight in silly gags and not
necessarily explaining much.''
</P>
<P>
   This sense of whimsy is certainly evident in the movie. In one
scene, where Branagh's character, Berowne, says ``this love is as
mad as Ajax, it kills sheep,'' he looks out a window and a passing
sheep stops and keels over, in a very cartoony manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, why don't we do that, and not really explain it,''
he says, ``and just say it's silly. That makes me laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, some critics aren't just laughing at the silly
scenes. While ``Love's'' does include stage musical veterans Lester
and Lane, most of the actors were new to singing and dancing, and
their lack of experience shows. Which, on the whole, is OK with
Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate instinct about the casting was that people should
be cast for their appropriateness for the character, and for their
ease for Shakespeare,'' Branagh says. ``I wanted the singing and
dancing informed by character.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which may fall far short of the ideal for Broadway
aficionados or Shakespeare lovers, but it's still something unique
for a generation of filmgoers raised on ``Star Wars'' and ``The
Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However sort of `throwbacky' some of what we do is, in the
context of what's out there now, it feels very original,'' Branagh
says. ``I wanted to make a film that was heartfelt and innocent and
honest and uncaring about whether people mocked it or not.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-BRANAGH-MUSICAL-TEX     07-17 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANAGH-MUSICAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANAGH SHAKES UP SHAKESPEARE _ AND CRITICS _ WITH A '30S-STYLE
MUSICAL
</HEADLINE>
  (Resending to add slug) 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By MARK LOWRY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of Fred Astaire, Ginger Rogers and Gene Kelly don't have to
worry about their Hollywood icons being overshadowed by
Tinseltown's new generation of song-and-dance performers.
</P>
