<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONACO GRAND PRIX
</P>
<P>
   Q. For our anniversary next May, my husband and I would like to
attend the Grand Prix of Monaco automobile race. Could you tell me
when the race is and provide other details? _ L.L., Avon, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. The 59th Grand Prix Automobile de Monaco, part of the
international Formula One racing series, is set for May 24 to 27,
2001. The race itself, run through the streets of the principality
on the Riviera, will be May 27. Practice sessions for the Formula
One cars are May 24 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Monaco is unlike that at any other Formula One
event. The circuit twists and climbs through the principality,
which is half the size of Central Park, with the howl of racing
engines reverberating off towering condos and Belle-Epoque hotels.
</P>
<P>
   To order tickets, contact the Comite d'Organisation, Grand Prix
Automobile de Monaco, Boite Postale 464, 98012 Monaco Cedex, or
call the Automobile Club of Monaco at (377) 93.15.26.00.
</P>
<P>
   The best viewing areas are the grandstands at the Ste.-Devote
turn, the narrow corner immediately after the start. The
grandstands near the casino and the Albert I public swimming pool
are also good.
</P>
<P>
   Although ticket prices have not been determined for 2001, you
can expect them to be slightly higher than this year's prices.
These ranged from $114 to $400 (at 7 francs to $1) for seats in the
grandstands for Sunday's main event, and $57 to $143 for the
Saturday practice session, during which the drivers compete to see
who can run the fastest lap and thus earn the starting berth at the
front of the lineup for the Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to watch standing up, you can buy a general
admission ticket. The general-admission area just below the palace,
called Rocher de Monaco-Ville, can be particularly tricky, since it
is a steep, slippery hillside. Tickets in the Rocher were $36 on
race day this year; in the other two general-admission areas, they
were $57 to $114.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a parking spot is about as difficult an event as the
grand prix itself. The train line that runs along the Cote d'Azur
stops in Monaco (Nice is a particularly good place to look for a
hotel room on race weekend) is the most sensible way to get to the
race.
</P>
<P>
   A tour operator can streamline the planning of your trip. Grand
Prix Tours, 1071 Camelback Street, Newport Beach, Calif. 92660;
(949) 717-3333, fax (949) 717-3344, conducts tours to several
Formula One races. Among its Monaco package this year was one that
included five nights at the Grand Hotel, which overlooks the
slowest turn on the track. Guests can stand on the roof and watch
the race. The package also included a cocktail party at which tour
participants could talk to one of the Grand Prix drivers, daily
breakfast, a race-preview party and airport transfers. The price
this year started from $3,950 a person, based on double occupancy.
Air fare is extra. A two-night package at the Novotel or Sofitel in
Nice was $595 a person, double occupancy. This did not include air
fare or race tickets. Next year's prices have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   A Montreal company, Formula Tours, (888) 367-6851, also operates
tours to the Monaco Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   APARTMENTS IN SYDNEY
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to go to Australia for several months over Christmas
and rent a small apartment in Sydney to use as a base for tours. Do
you know of any companies that can arrange this for me? _ Charlotte
F. Zartman, Sun City West, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   A. Manly Seaside Holiday Apartments, Shop 2/39 East Esplanade,
Manly NSW 2095, telephone (61-2) 9977 5213, fax (61-2) 9977 7062,
has 137 apartments in 37 buildings in Manly, a beachfront suburb of
Sydney. They are available for as little as three nights, and range
in size from a studio to three bedrooms, either in town or along
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The apartments are cleaned each week and come with linen,
towels, television, telephone, kitchen facilities and, in most
cases, parking. The cost per week from Dec. 16 to Feb. 4 ranges
from $642 to $993, at $1.71 Australian to $1. For listings, call up
www.manly-seaside.com.
</P>
<P>
   L.J. Hooker, telephone (61-2) 9283 5511, fax (61-2) 9283 5030,
has apartments ranging from $700 to $1,460 a week during this
period. Call up www.ljhooker.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you rent an apartment through a real estate agent, prices
will be considerably lower, perhaps half as much. But it is likely
that you will have to rent for a minimum of three months and sign a
lease, as well as provide four weeks' rent as security and the
first four weeks' rent in advance, as well as arrange your own
utility service. Contact the Australian Tourist Commission, 2049
Century Park East, Suite 1920, Los Angeles, Calif. 90067; (310)
229-4854.
</P>
<P>
   CATHEDRALS, CLOSE UP
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am planning a trip to England this summer with an
11-year-old who would like to tour one or more cathedrals in some
depth. Where are such tours are given? _ Lore L. Holmes, Glen Cove,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. A number of England's great churches offer such
behind-the-scenes tours. For a complete listing, contact the
British Tourist Authority, 551 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10176;
(877) 899-8391.
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul's in London offers a variety of tours. Basic admission
is $7.65 (at $1.53 to the pound), $3.80 ages 15 and younger. For a
more in-depth look, the Triforium tours explore the level between
the ground floor and the Whispering Gallery, an area not normally
accessible to the general public. This tour takes in the library,
the geometric staircase and Christopher Wren's Great Model of St.
Paul's. It must be booked in advance and is offered Tuesday and
Thursday. The fee, $15.30 a person, includes admission to the
cathedral. To reserve, call (44-20) 7246 8319.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest of London, there is Salisbury and its famous
cathedral. Regular admission is $4.50, ages 5 to 18 $1.53. This fee
includes the general cathedral tour includes the ground floor and
chapels, the Cloisters, the Chapter House and Magna Carta.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute Tower Tour, in which participants climb 330 steps
and are rewarded with views from the building's uppermost reaches,
is conducted four times a day Monday to Saturday June through
August, once on Sunday May through September and less frequently
other months. It must be booked in advance and is limited to 12
people. It costs an extra $4.50, ages 5 to 18 $3.
</P>
<P>
   The Cathedral Craft Workshop Tour, a 30-minute excursion offered
Monday to Friday, provides a look at the stone and glass
maintenance and craft shops. It costs $1.53; ages 5 to 18, 75
cents. Call the cathedral at (44-1722) 555121, fax (44-1722) 555116
to reserve. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
