<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HAWAII-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ATTENTION FOR THE EFFORT TO SAVE THE MONK SEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By RACHEL X. WEISSMAN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One late spring day in 1982, John Henderson, a fisheries
biologist at the Honolulu Laboratory of the National Marine
Fisheries Service, was scouting for recently weaned Hawaiian monk
seals on Lisianski Island, one of a dozen coral reef atolls
northwest of the main islands, and one of six breeding grounds for
the federally endangered seals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shallow reef on the windward side of the island
where the mothers take their pups to avoid shark attacks,''
Henderson said. ``Once the pups are weaned at five to six weeks,
they begin ranging further afield.''
</P>
<P>
   That day, standing on a beach covered by bunch grass and low
shrubs and strewn with plastic containers, fishing floats and empty
liquor bottles, Henderson heard the bleating of an animal that
sounded like a weaned pup. Through binoculars, he saw the seal on
the reef shallows some 100 yards from shore.
</P>
<P>
   He waded out through the low tide and found a two- or
three-month-old seal weighing some 200 pounds pinned to a reef by a
fragment of a fishing net. He and his colleagues were able to free
the seal, but if they had not been there, he said, ``the rising
tide would have drowned him within a few hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Hawaii's coral reefs are healthy compared with others in
the world, they are the unfortunate host to huge quantities of
trash, including large fishing nets lost or illegally discarded
from vessels in such far-flung places as Japan, Russia and Alaska.
In El Nino years, currents shift slightly and the flotsam and
jetsam wash up on the Big Island.
</P>
<P>
   Besides entangling endangered animals like the monk seal, the
green sea turtle and the humpback whale, the nets also break off
pieces of coral that range from cauliflower size to boulder size.
Some pieces involve 100 or more years of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge coral reef refuge, a beautiful resource and it's
getting hammered,'' said Dr. Mary Donohue, a biologist with the
National Marine Fisheries Service, who heads a multiagency task
force effort started in 1998 to clean up the reefs.
</P>
<P>
   While the trash problem has existed since the fishing industry
began using plastics in the 1950s, it is receiving new attention
largely because of the cleanup effort, begun with a goal of
stabilizing the monk seal population. The population has dwindled
to about 1,300 or 1,400, about half the total in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many seals are lost to entanglements in
floating trash. Since 1982, the fisheries service has documented
196, but many more animals are believed to have perished, their
bodies caught below sea level and scavenged by sharks.
</P>
<P>
   While it is difficult to isolate what role entanglement plays in
the overall decline of the species, said Jason Baker, the leader of
the agency's seal population survey, it is one of the few factors
that can be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Seals also suffer starvation, as do the fish on which they prey.
At least one epidemic, whose cause was never determined, killed off
one-sixth to one-quarter of the nearby Laysan Island population in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is male aggression, which occurs when the sex
ratio of a given population shifts. ``Because the sub-populations
are so small,'' Baker said, ``if just a few females die, the sex
ratio becomes skewed.'' In these populations, scientists have
observed sexually aggressive behaviors in males resulting in the
deaths of females and younger animals. ``That's the kind of
situation that can really wipe a population out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the agency's first monthlong reef clean-up mission in
November 1998, six tons of marine debris _ including nets, marine
lines, ropes, plastics and batteries _ were collected from the
reefs by divers. In the second effort, in October 1999, workers on
two ships supplied by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration and the United States Coast Guard picked up 25 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Each mission costs an estimated $1 million. So far, just 5
percent of the reefs have been surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The trips are timed for good weather and the safety of the crew
and seals. ``We choose October because we don't want to go when the
mother monk seals are nursing pups on the reefs because the pup
will die if it's separated from its mother,'' Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
   The crew also avoids the period when albatross chicks hatch
because tiger sharks roam the waters to prey upon the chicks and
pose a threat to divers.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the Hawaiian reefs _ which represent 84 percent of
all reefs in the United States _ and their animal inhabitants will
be highlighted in August, when an international conference on
marine debris will be held at the Humpback Whale National Marine
Sanctuary in Honolulu. The weeklong conference will be attended by
conservationists, scientists and political leaders from Pacific Rim
nations, including Japan, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Rusty Brainard, who will be part of the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Association delegation at the conference, said he
planned to urge the use of detailed satellite images to pinpoint
debris as it approached the Hawaiian islands. A plane would then be
sent to verify that the object was debris and a boat would pick it
up. Another method likely to be discussed, he said, is mandatory
tagging of fishing nets so discarded or lost nets can be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Coe, who directed the now-defunct Marine Entanglement
Research Program between 1985 and 1995, said that while the method
sounded good, it was abandoned in the late 80s because of the
expense of setting up an international reporting system and the
lack of consensus on enforcement issues like fines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, junk keeps piling up on the Hawaiian shores. ``I just
got a call the other day about a 500-pound trawl net that washed up
on the beach at Kure Atoll, and there's likely to be more on the
reefs,'' said Donohue, who will find out just how much more when
she returns to the reefs in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
