<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN PRESIDENT MAY SEEK INTERNATIONAL ASSISTANCE IN MALUKUS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ President Abdurrahman Wahid said on Monday
that he may have to seek international assistance to halt 18 months
of sectarian violence in the eastern Maluku islands, where rogue
army units have taken sides in the intensifying clashes.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that brought to mind last year's East Timor
crisis, Wahid said he may have to call for international help if a
three-week-old state of civil emergency fails to stem the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have ordered the governor (of Maluku province) to work as
hard as he can to control the situation,'' Wahid told a meeting of
regional administrators at the state palace. ``If the outcome is
still not satisfactory after we have done our best, we may ask for
international help in the form of equipment and logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab went further, telling reporters
later that the government was pondering whether to allow
international peacekeepers into the Malukus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international aid is limited to humanitarian aid, but if
it comes to the level that we are not ready to handle, we may have
to consider it,'' Shihab said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``This is a very hypothetical premise. We are
doing our best to stop the bloodshed. I think that within the
coming week it will get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 days ago, Shihab had flatly ruled out foreign
intervention in the conflict, in which more than 2,500 people have
been killed.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is now a widespread perception that Wahid has
lost control of the crisis as well as his armed forces. Dramatic
television footage aired Monday showed soldiers fighting
side-by-side with Muslim militants in attacks on Christian
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The footage, shot over the weekend by an Associated Press
cameraman in the Maluku capital, Ambon, confirmed claims by
Christian leaders that army units were supporting the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid had ordered military commanders to remove units deemed too
emotionally involved in the conflict after accusations that both
the police and army were taking sides based on their religious
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Indonesia is Muslim, but Malukus residents
are roughly split between Muslims and Christians. The region, once
known as the Dutch Spice Islands, lies 1,300 miles northeast of
Jakarta and consists of Maluku and North Maluku provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the government also lost control of the armed
forces when pro-Jakarta militias and rogue military units began a
killing and arson spree in East Timor after the territory voted for
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia eventually bowed to international pressure and allowed
an Australian-led peacekeeping force into East Timor, which was a
humiliation for both the government and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The American defense secretary, William Cohen, told reporters in
Australia Monday that Australia would probably also coordinate any
international intervention in the Malukus.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has accused political and military extremists of
instigating the latest violence to protect their business interests
and destabilize his government ahead of a crucial showdown with
Parliament next month.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 people have been killed since Wahid declared a
civil emergency in the Malukus last month, including as many as 20
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, local residents reported hearing sporadic gunfire in
Ambon, as well as loud explosions as fighting continued for a fifth
day.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has forced up to 500,000 people to flee the Malukus
and has destroyed tens of thousands of houses, buildings and places
of worship in a region where Muslims and Christians had peacefully
co-existed for centuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
