<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE FAILING TO SERVE END-OF-LIFE PATIENTS, PANEL TOLD
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cuts to Medicare are threatening access to
compassionate and specialized care for the dying, a congressional
panel was told Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare often cannot provide hospice care for the dying because
the reimbursement rate has not kept pace with the changes in
end-of-life care, said Linda Todd, a member of the board of
directors for the National Hospice and Palliative Care
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The increased cost of prescription drugs and out-patient
therapies, as well as more intensive services required from
hospices, have been responsible for the gap in Medicare
reimbursement, Todd said. She called on Congress to immediately
increase the reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the Balanced Budget Act of 1997 reduced
the inflation adjustment in Medicare reimbursement rates for
hospices and other health care providers. ``We need to eliminate
the reductions,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   An independent study this year found that patients are enrolling
in hospices closer to the time of death, Todd told the Senate Aging
Committee. That means they need more intense and frequent services
than were common when Medicare established the reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   The average hospice stay has dropped from 70 days to 40 days,
the study showed. The rates were based on longer hospice
enrollments with less intense care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far too many patients die without ever being referred to
hospice care, and this is often the result of an unawareness that
hospice programs are available,'' Todd told the Senate Aging
Committee. ``Education is the only thing that will change this
situation, and we need it for consumers, health care professionals
and physicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, who last year introduced a bill to
improve care for dying Medicare patients, said Congress needs to
re-examine how Medicare helps care for people at the end of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is more that we can do to relieve suffering,
respect personal dignity and provide opportunities to people to
find meaning and comfort at life's conclusion,'' Collins said.
``Patients and their families should not have to fear that the
process of dying will be marked by pain, distress, or care that is
inconsistent with their values or wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins's bill would expand Medicare beneficiaries' access to
effective pain medications and develop end-of-life care for those
who do not qualify for hospice benefits, but it does not include
higher Medicare reimbursement rates for hospice care.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are more likely to talk to their children about safe
sex and drugs than to their terminally ill parents about choices as
they near death, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education and communication is needed for the terminally ill
and their families, so that the dying can be provided with
compassionate and specialized care,'' she said. ``In our survey,
nine of of 10 respondents didn't realize that as Medicare
beneficiaries, their terminally ill family members are entitled to
all inclusive hospice care.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Committee on Aging: www.senate.gov/aging
</P>
<P>
   National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization: www.hnpco.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
