<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-JENNINGS-HNS &LR;      07-17 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JENNINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WILD JENNINGS CAN'T BE TAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ While it's not true Gabe Jennings was
raised by wolves in the remote California mountain hamlet of Forks
of Salmon, you should have heard him howl on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, his black hair and wispy goatee suggest a lupine
presence lurking inside this ferocious runner.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, a junior at Stanford University, jumped on the
1,500-meter field like a wolf pouncing on a rabbit and made the
race his own to highlight the third day of the U.S. Olympic Track
and Field Trials at Sacramento State's Hornet Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings seized control of the race with 500 meters to go and
won comfortably in 3 minutes, 35.90 seconds to earn a trip to the
Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   This is one man who's free, wild and 21.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, as a 17-year-old high school kid in Madison,
Wis., Jennings recalled working in a running shoe store and
watching the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember dreaming, thinking of where I'd be in four years,''
he said. ``All young kids do that. Here I am now. I can't explain
it. It's one thing to dream it, quite another to make your dreams
come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreams came true for the second- and third-place finishers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Pyrah, a 1996 Olympian, came across second in 3:36.70 and
bettered the Olympic ``A'' qualifying standard of 3:36.80 in the
process. In third was Jennings' teammate at Stanford, Michael
Stember, a Sacramento native who thrilled the home crowd by making
the Olympic team in the time of 3:37.04.
</P>
<P>
   The only qualification for Stember is that he must attain the
Olympic standard by Sept. 11 or else relinquish his spot on the
team to fifth-placer Steve Holman, who already has a qualifying
time. Stember will get his chances right away, in special meets
designed for the purpose at Stanford on July 26 and 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty intense, this high I'm on,'' Stember, a
22-year-old Cardinal senior, said. ``It's amazing. So much work, so
many sacrifices. In front of the hometown crowd, my 94-year-old
grandmother in the stands, waving her arms, screaming her heart
out. I can't put into words how it feels. I'm ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty fair description of their coach at Stanford, Vin
Lananna, who put two runners on the Olympic team and nearly a third
when Brad Hauser finished fifth in the 10,000 final Friday night.
Hauser and twin brother Brent get another chance in the 5,000,
starting with Monday's first rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a visionary,'' Stember said of Lananna, who led
Stanford's men's track team to its first NCAA team championship in
64 years last month. ``He's a great balancer of egos. How he
balanced mine and Gabe's, I don't know. I credit a lot to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings and Stember could not be more dissimilar, as runners
and as young men. Thirty years ago, Jennings would have been a
world-class hippie with his penchant for percussion instruments and
free-form expression. Every time he opens his mouth, a stream of
consciousness spills out.
</P>
<P>
   A Jennings sampler:
</P>
<P>
   ``The moon kept getting full and the air kept getting fresh. . .
. I feel we're all brothers and sisters out there. I felt I wasn't
alone out there. . . . The crowd was a part of this experience. We
all raised the roof and broke on through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this only comes around every four years. It's
so momentous in so many ways. It's something we all train for. It's
the ultimate ritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my speed, I believe in my kick, I believe in my
heart. Races like this, you want to believe in your heart. . . . I
put my hand on my heart and felt the rhythm. I told my coach this
is my day. You can manifest your dreams and make them come true. I
did. I've been feeling the cosmic energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no nervousness and that stinky fear that exudes from
your sweat glands. . . . I started crying. It was a happy cry. It
was the happiest cry I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Stember interrupted his teammate, looked at him
and said, ``I love this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stember is pragmatic where his teammate is philosophical. He
also has a boyish look that recalls a young Joe Montana. At another
juncture in their postrace press conference, they embraced and
shared a moment that only two friends who had just made the Olympic
team can know.
</P>
<P>
   Pyrah, the man in the middle, had a story to tell as well. The
31-year-old Brigham Young University graduate spoke of his parents
and sisters watching him from the stands, of his recent marriage
and of his brother with cerebral palsy, welling up with tears as he
went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race I run I dedicate to him,'' Pyrah said of his
brother. ``It's great to make the Olympic team. I train by myself.
I know what it's like to work hard. I couldn't be happier with my
second place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
