<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of cool Canadian air masses that have
prevailed in the Northeast this month will spread from the Great
Lakes to New England Tuesday. A few showers will occur near a front
marking the leading edge of the cool air in central and northern
New England. Partly sunny and very warm conditions will precede the
front in the Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   A wavering front separating near record heat in parts of the
Southern states from cooler air to the north will be the focus for
clusters of showers and thunderstorms from the northern and central
Plains to the Ohio and Tennessee Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be very warm. Ample sun will bathe deserts
of the Southwest. Farther north, scattered afternoon thunderstorms
will form in the Rockies, especially over northern Wyoming and
southern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAT STREAK
</P>
<P>
   An unusual streak of hot days in Denver ended on Sunday as a
weak front with clouds and showers moved into northern Colorado.
The temperature had reached 90 degrees or higher every day since
June 29, peaking at 101 degrees on July 6. The 17-day streak fell
one day short of tying Denver's record for consecutive days of 90
degrees r higher. Hot streaks of 18 consecutive days had been
measured in July 1874 and July 1901. Although Tuesday will be very
warm, increased afternoon thundershowers in Denver later this week
are expected to interfere with the start of a new heat streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
