<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     07-17 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS EXPRESSES ITS CONTEMPT FOR WILDLIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the Casper (Wyo.)
Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First Amendment
commentary. His e-mail address is levendos(AT)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress has been working on appropriations bills this summer so
that government programs and the people who work for the federal
government continue to be funded in the next fiscal year. Members
of Congress want to leave the Capitol early and campaign for the
elections. They certainly don't want to be held up or embarrassed
by presidential vetoes of appropriations bills in the early fall.
Members of Congress played that game with President Clinton once
before and lost. The Republican Congress doesn't want to give
Clinton and his party a political edge going into the elections, so
members want to get these appropriations bills done and agreed upon
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But anti-environmental politics is still a lively game in the
U.S. Senate. And the Senate version of the Department of the
Interior Appropriations Bill is being loaded up with
anti-preservation, anti-nature riders. Riders are attached to
appropriations bills with little or no debate and without public
scrutiny. Often these riders fund pork barrel projects the senators
want in their districts. Locally, such riders help the senator get
reelected using the American taxpayer's money to build some
unnecessary bridge or dam.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-environmental riders can also be pork barrel amendments
such as the rider that Sen. Craig Thomas, R-Wyo., has threatened to
add to the Interior Appropriations bill. Thomas' amendment would
delay the National Park Service's ban on snowmobiles in most
national parks.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway communities outside of Yellowstone National Park rent
and sell snowmobiles to winter visitors. As many as 12,000
snowmobilers enter Yellowstone National Park a day in December and
January. Naturally, the gateway communities will vote for Thomas in
their gratitude _ despite the harm to wildlife, air and water
quality and other recreational uses that snowmobiles create.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., has threatened to offer a floor
amendment to the bill that would limit the funding for the
administration of national monuments. Nickles isn't acting because
of local pressure. President Clinton hasn't named a national
monument in Oklahoma and isn't likely to. To date, there are no
sites in Oklahoma under consideration. In the 1995 to 2000 Senate
election cycle, Nickles received more than $500,000 in campaign
contributions from oil, gas and mining industries and the utility
companies.
</P>
<P>
   A second attack against national monuments was already attached
to the appropriations bill when it came out of committee. This
``committee report language'' gives a $1 million windfall to the
Montana Stockgrowers Association under the rubric of the
organization's Undaunted Stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Wilderness Society, the Montana Stockgrowers
Association has been actively campaigning against Clinton naming
the Missouri Breaks, an especially scenic area along the upper
Missouri River, as a national monument. Secretary of the Interior
Bruce Babbitt has held meetings in Montana to discuss the Missouri
Breaks as potential national monument.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., attached a rider to the bill that
exempts the White Mountain National Forest in northern New
Hampshire from the Clinton administration's roadless policy. The
White Mountain National Forest is already threaded with an
interstate highway and numerous state highways. Not enough roads
for Gregg, though. Never mind that roadless areas in large forest
areas provide clean waters without chemical pollutants, without
spending taxpayer dollars, and protect the state's wildlife and
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., plans to offer an ``extinction
rider'' to the Interior Appropriations bill. The rider would
permanently block all conservation measures to prevent the
extinction of the Rio Grande Silvery Minnow by blocking efforts to
keep sufficient water in the Rio Grande River. At one time, the Rio
Grande Silvery Minnow could be found in nearly 1,000 miles of the
river out to the Gulf of Mexico. It is one of four genetically
distinct subspecies of minnow. Imagine having your name attached to
an authorization that could wipe out an entire subspecies: Sen.
Pete ``Extinction Rider'' Domenici.
</P>
<P>
   Two dangerous riders have been withdrawn and one may still be
attached to the appropriations bill in the next few weeks:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, withdrew his floor amendment to
limit spending on the administration's roadless policy in our
national forests.
</P>
<P>
   _ A rider that would have taken at least 93 acres from the Cape
Hatteras National Seashore and 33 acres from the Pea Island
National Wildlife Refuge and given those acres to the Army Corps of
Engineers to construct two rock jetties in North Carolina's Oregon
Inlet was withdrawn. The jetties, had they been built, would have
provided better access to the ocean for commercial fishing fleets _
all at taxpayer expense and the expense of a precious ecological
area.
</P>
<P>
   _ And finally, to top off the list of those who believe ``if you
can't mine or drill it, it ain't worth nothin','' Sen. Frank
Murkowski, R-Alaska, had planned to attach a floor amendment to
another appropriations bill in order to mandate oil drilling in the
ecologically sensitive Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, and it is
conceivable he may offer this same amendment for the Interior
Appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski's timing is suspect. In the past, he has suggested the
rationale that such drilling in the refuge would keep the oil and
gas prices down. Now that the cost of gasoline has spiked to a new
high, Murkowski obviously thought that he could fool the American
public. It's a transparent ruse.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups estimate that the oil supply under the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge would only last six months.
However, the potential damage to the ecology of the refuge by
drilling would likely last for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term profits often blind people to long-term damages. And
unfortunately, short-term memory often leads voters to forget those
who would sacrifice the public's natural heritage for a few quick
bucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
