u a BC-CONVENTIONS-TODAY-ART     07-17 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-TODAY-ART-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GORE CAMPAIGNS HOPE CONVENTIONS WILL KICK-START VOTER
INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 17, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: Two photos, of attendees at the 1996 Democratic (NNS1) and
Republican (NNS2) national conventions). 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once upon a time, conventions offered cliffhanging
drama. They became arenas in which two or more claimants truly
battled for the nomination and the outcome was in doubt, with many
successive roll call votes before a winner finally was chosen. No
longer.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a major party candidate failed to win nomination
on the first ballot was in 1952, when Democrat Adlai E. Stevenson
won on the second ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And today, with pollsters and political leaders shaking their
heads over the current low level of public excitement about the
presidential race, the opposing camps of Republican George W. Bush
and Democrat Al Gore are counting heavily on their upcoming
national conventions to kick-start the attention and enthusiasm of
millions of voters.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the most important remaining purpose of modern
political conventions in an era when the presidential nominations
are sewn up months ahead of time in the primary process.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republicans get ready to stage their big, choreographed
and packaged ceremonial show in Philadelphia July 31-Aug. 3,
followed by the Democrats' similar extravaganza in Los Angeles Aug.
14-17, the only real suspense is the identity of Bush's and Gore's
running mates.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly will be no surprises in the party platforms.
Those are being carefully crafted to steer each party close to the
nation's political center, while embracing the broad themes and
specific programs that Bush and Gore have been test-marketing
throughout their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush faces a tricky task at his convention, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   He must simultaneously make the case for both ``continuity and
change,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center
for People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent contradiction, Kohut said, results from
overwhelming public satisfaction and comfort with the prevailing
economic conditions and with the policies of the incumbent
Democrat, Bill Clinton. It's a mood that co-exists alongside a
clear desire for relief from leadership regarded as personally
flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush wants to blur the issue differences (with
Gore), particularly in the area of economic and social policy,''
said Thomas Mann, a political scientist at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, he wants to make a case for low-risk change, and
that change will be focused mostly on the way we conduct politics.
It's not going to be substantive issue change, it's going to be,
`Let's stop this awful bickering in Washington, let's get this
sleazy, untrustworthy, lying behavior out of the Oval Office,'''
Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention \roMDUL\ &UR; -provides Bush with a potential
national audience, one that may be ready to begin paying a little
more attention as the candidate tries to explain the meaning of his
slogan, ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   It will also help fire up party workers and political activists
for the campaign drive to November.
</P>
<P>
   Although the major television networks will not offer the
gavel-to-gavel coverage of the conventions they once provided,
cable television and the Internet will make sure no interested
citizen or political junkie is shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention will be available on cable in 69 million
homes, ``two-thirds of the households in America,'' Republican
National Chairman Jim Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both parties will attempt to reproduce, if not
surpass, the historic intensity, look, sound, flavor and feeling of
past national political conventions, with music, hats, banners,
bunting, confetti and balloons, ``spontaneous'' marching
demonstrations of support for favored political figures and causes,
and, naturally, speeches -- lots of speeches showcasing past heroes
and new young talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, when you have a birthday party you always have a
birthday cake and you sing `Happy Birthday,''' said Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention is still a chance to project yourself to the
nation and to the world,'' Nicholson said. ``At the same time, it's
a coming together of the grass-roots activists in the party every
four years to examine ourselves and express to the American people
who we are, what we stand for, and what our vision is for the
country and its future. And we'll do all of that, as will the other
great political party.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Conventions are still a vital part of the political process that
goes beyond formalizing the nominees of the two major parties for
the highest office in the land, said Democratic National Chairman
Joe Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``People learn things from conventions,'' Andrew said.
``Conventions define who the candidates are, what concerns them and
what the issues are. You can tell from the convention what kind of
president and what kind of administration you would have.''
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence that conventions have direct impact, Andrew
said, is the measurable ``bump'' the nominee immediately gets in
public opinion polls afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That represents ``massive movements of voters,'' Andrew said.
``People learn more or change their minds'' based on what happens
at conventions. ``Bill Clinton in 1992 went up almost 20 points in
20 days. Clearly that meant the convention was important.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, Gore has a lot of work to do at his own convention,
according to Mann of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's most important task, by far, is to stop being vice
president, which is a weak position, and become the standard-bearer
of the party,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   The convention is his big chance to make the transition. The
script calls for Clinton to make an early appearance that allows
him ``to jump his job approval rating up to about 62 or 63
percent'' on the convention's opening night, Mann said, ``and then
have him leave town, giving Gore three days to establish himself as
the leader of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, Gore must use that time ``to clearly frame the election as
a referendum on the economy,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, reversing the Bush strategy, Gore ``must sharpen the
differences on the key issues of taxes, domestic priorities and
Social Security,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush have to accomplish their tasks without
further boring a national electorate in which the voting turnout
indicators are already sagging below 50 percent, according to
Kohut's polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in five voters say that who wins the election isn't as
important as it used to be, and 30 percent say it doesn't make a
difference who gets elected,'' Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   A ``bare majority'' think the candidates have different
positions on the issues and the rest are convinced the two
candidates ``are more alike than they are different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynicism over what the next president can achieve is running
at the same level as it was in August 1976, when the country was
still recovering from Watergate and the oil shortages,'' Kohut
said.
</P>
<P>
   The conventions will be the candidates' opportunity to change
those perceptions -- or to deepen them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
