<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4657 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SMUGGLING-PSA-NEWHOUS     07-17 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLING-PSA-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD CAMPAIGN WARNS IMMIGRANTS AGAINST TRUSTING SMUGGLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 17, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By STEVE CHAMBERS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Border Patrol rescued two Mexicans abandoned by
smugglers in the Arizona desert last week, U.S. immigration
officials saw a hint of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   They sent in video cameras and captured the men's harrowing tale
for use in public service announcements to be shown in Mexico and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a sweeping program launched two years ago by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, the often-graphic TV spots
and posters show bodies of migrants who died in the desert or
testimonials from relatives who lost loved ones. They are aimed at
potential migrants and relatives in the United States who might
finance their journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the aunt or uncle in Los Angeles or Newark or Chicago
that is saying, `Send up your son or daughter. Here's some money to
pay for a smuggler,''' said Don Mueller, an INS spokesman who is
helping to coordinate the public service campaign. ``If we can
reach that audience, we can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has taken on new urgency along the Mexican border,
where more than 230 undocumented immigrants have died from exposure
or drowning this year, making it the deadliest year on record.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign is also being launched in places such as China,
the Dominican Republic, Haiti and Central America. The same public
service announcements, which focus on the dangers of paying
smugglers, known in Latin America as coyotes and in China as
snakeheads, have aired on Spanish-language TV programs broadcast in
states where large numbers of Latinos reside.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, new public service announcements produced for
the first time in collaboration with the Mexican government are
scheduled to appear on 91 TV stations and 1,300 radio stations
across Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   INS critics blame tougher enforcement for forcing migrants into
more isolated and dangerous parts of the desert and mountain
passes, but even they agree the public service announcements could
save lives.
</P>
<P>
   When INS Commissioner Doris Meissner visited China two weeks ago
in a bid for anti-smuggling cooperation, she carried with her
posters the service would like the Chinese government to display.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous high-profile incidents in recent years are proof that
the public service announcements are not just scare tactics. Last
month, the bodies of 58 Chinese immigrants were found aboard a
truck entering England, and last year eight migrants died after
being caught in a freak snowstorm while crossing mountains outside
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human smuggling is a nightmare. Don't mistakenly get involved
in it,'' one of the posters for use in China states. It goes on in
poetic Mandarin: ``A stormy journey. By the time you reach the
shore you are near death. Then everyone is sent back immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   A poster destined for use in Latin America shows a funeral and
warns: ``Your brother trusted coyotes. Don't risk your life.''
</P>
<P>
   INS officials in Washington concede that public education alone
will not stop the hundreds of thousands of illegal migrants
streaming into the country each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure of the size of the impact,'' one INS agent
stationed in the Caribbean said. ``I go out with the local Navy and
interview these people after they are picked up, and they tell me,
`Tomorrow, I'll get on another boat.'''
</P>
<P>
   But both the INS and its critics in the immigrant advocacy
community agree that the public service announcements could save
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it represents a response to the extraordinary loss of
life,'' said Cecilia Munoz, vice president for policy at the
National Council of La Raza, one of the nation's most influential
Latino advocacy groups. ``It's important that the U.S. and Mexican
governments respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar de la Torre, minister for migration affairs in the Mexican
Embassy in Washington, said the announcements may serve to educate
some Mexicans and Central Americans to the dangers they face.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live in rural areas far from the border cannot
imagine how it is,'' de la Torre said. ``They live in places where
the temperature is comfortable and the land is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government also has shown increasing interest in
combating smuggling. Last week, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji met with
European Union officials and vowed to work harder against
international gangs that run the smuggling trade.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz said that in addition to public outreach, the Border
Patrol should re-examine its get-tough strategy, dubbed Operation
Gatekeeper. Instead, the government has announced better safety and
rescue training for agents.
</P>
<P>
   The two men saved July 12 had been in the desert for three days
and were out of water. They were located by Operation Skywatch, a
new initiative that deploys helicopters and planes to scan the
desert for migrants in trouble. A third migrant alerted the Border
Patrol that his friends had been abandoned when they couldn't keep
pace.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, tensions have run high in Mexico about the
increasing number of deaths on the border and the vigilantism of
some Arizona ranchers who have taken to rounding up migrants
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Russo of the U.S. Embassy in Mexico said the State
Department gave the Mexican government veto authority over language
in the most recent public service campaign but has gotten excellent
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we prefer to focus on the common ground we have with
Mexico,'' Russo said. ``We both agree that coyotes are a very
serious problem. They often victimize the undocumented, abandoning
them or stealing their money.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Torre said there must be understanding on both sides of
the border, however, about the underlying issues of poverty driving
the smuggling trade.
</P>
<P>
   And although the public service announcements advise potential
migrants that there are legal avenues, for most Mexicans, Chinese
and other poor immigrants, the odds are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only come if a close family member or employer in the
United States petitions for you,'' Munoz said. ``For someone
without connections, it is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Chambers is a staff writer with The Star-Ledger of
Newark, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
