<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICE DISPLAYS NO FEAR OF UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Jerry Rice made the early-morning drive from
his home in Atherton to the San Francisco 49ers training camp at
the University of the Pacific with his mind drifting to other days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve, he's going to be missed,'' Rice said, referring to the
prospect of camp without just-retired quarterback Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about him on the drive down. . . . He's a hard
guy to replace. He meant so much to this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice also reminisced about his early camps with ``(Joe) Montana,
Ronnie Lott and all those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like another world. About half the players who will be
in this camp are new. Rice was one of a handful of veteran players
joining more than 30 rookies at 8:45 a.m. Sunday for the first
practice of training camp 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they've got their names on their helmets,'' Rice said
of the large contingent of newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 16-year wide receiver was the oldest player on the
field, and enters camp as the team's undisputed star, Rice arrived
at camp acting a bit like a fretful rookie. Most of the other
veterans don't report until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get back in there, get back into the best shape I
can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice always arrives early, he always is in shape and he always
jumps right into practice, acting as if there was some doubt he'd
make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Young once said that a key to Rice's success was that he ``still
acted like a kid trying to make the junior varsity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, of course, owns 14 NFL records, has been in 12 Pro Bowls
and was named to the NFL's 75th Anniversary Team. He may be the
best wide receiver of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have to do is throw everything out the window,'' he
said, looking to adjust to second-year quarterback Jeff Garcia.
``I've got to start from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice earned the first cheers of training camp. With several
hundred fans looking on during passing drills, Rice ran an out
pattern into the left flat. Rookie quarterback Tim Rattay was off
the mark, throwing the ball behind Rice as he broke for the
sideline. Rice, making it look easy, reached back with one hand,
caught the ball, turned upfield and sprinted 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci was obviously delighted that Rice was in camp and
giving the rookies a lesson in proper deportment _ right down to
his meticulous appearance in a fitted No. 80 red jersey and black
tights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed it today,'' Mariucci said. ``He dresses exactly like
you should, he showed the young guys how to practice, how to carry
out the run. . . . He's doing it mostly by example.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rice was delighted to be in camp. He said he was looking
forward to ``hanging out with the new guys.'' He ran strong routes,
caught everything and finished each play with a burst downfield. He
was jovial and upbeat in talking with writers. He enthusiastically
ran over to the fence after practice to sign autographs for fans.
He was in his element.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enjoyed coming to training camp,'' he said. ``I didn't
look at it as a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice had slipped into the past-tense in his comments. He
acknowledged the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm trying to enjoy every second of it,'' he said.
``Because I know it's coming to an end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
