<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-17 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRADLEY _ BELATEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Bradley's begrudging, belated endorsement of
Vice President Al Gore last week enables Gore to go to the
Democratic National Convention with a technically united party.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, the former senator from New Jersey won't
make much difference in the general election. His time came _ and
has already gone.
</P>
<P>
   Doing the right thing did more for Bradley himself than for
Gore. The defeated presidential candidate, who lost every primary
and caucus to Gore, seemed over the last four months to be panting
for the Sour Grapes Cup. That dubious award was long thought to
have been retired by former Sen. Eugene McCarthy of Minnesota after
losing the Democratic nomination to Hubert Humphrey in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, in the early primary stretch, Bradley looked like
an attractive candidate, a viable alternative to Gore. During the
campaign, Bradley initially took the high road. But he became
increasingly testy as he failed to break Gore's lock on the
nomination. No resilience.
</P>
<P>
   In politics everything is timing. If Bradley had accepted defeat
gracefully when the game ended in March and promptly endorsed Gore,
he would have seemed like a statesman and a good sport. And he
would have lived again to run another day, perhaps in four years if
Gore loses the election.
</P>
<P>
   But sore losers are bad politicians. Bradley's endorsement four
months too late was strained. The two men did not even hold a joint
news conference afterward, for fear that things better left unsaid
would be said.
</P>
<P>
   During their brief competition, Bradley had accused Gore of
being ``tricky'' and ``the elephant of negative campaigning.'' Gore
returned the compliments with his own charges of Bradley
malevolence.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Bradley gave no indication he had changed his mind.
``Experience is what you get when you don't get what you want,'' he
pouted.
</P>
<P>
   Gore put a sunny face on this awkward moment. He won, after all,
and could afford to be magnanimous. ``This is one of the most
important days in the election,'' Gore told reporters afterward. It
was a political overstatement rivaled for sheer hypocrisy only by
President George Bush's claim in 1991 that he nominated Clarence
Thomas to the Supreme Court because he was the best-qualified
person in America.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? It is better for Gore to have Bradley inside the
tent spitting out than outside the tent spitting in. Tradition
decrees that presidential nominees be surrounded at their
coronation by defeated rivals pledging their loyalty, in order to
reassure partisans that all's well that ends well.
</P>
<P>
   This was so important to President Jimmy Carter that at the 1980
Democratic convention he literally chased his primary challenger,
Sen. Edward Kennedy, around the stage trying to be photographed
clasping hands with Kennedy in a victory salute, a gesture the
Massachusetts senator was reluctant to make.
</P>
<P>
   There was never much philosophical difference between Gore and
Bradley, but the latter couldn't get over the fact that when
pushed, Gore pushed back much harder. With Gore, it wasn't
personal. With Bradley, it was. More's the pity. Good men, both.
</P>
<P>
   Given his sullen attitude, Bradley's usefulness on the campaign
trail is doubtful. If Gore picks House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt as his running mate, Gephardt, not Bradley, will become
the prime symbol of party unity. In contrast to Bradley, Gephardt's
team instincts function well.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush solved his own divisive primary
problem when Sen. John McCain of Arizona endorsed him in early May,
saying he was taking his ``medicine'' but promising to work hard
for the ticket. McCain's support does matter. He remains a popular
figure with a steady following, and Bradley does not.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bradley's supporters have turned to Ralph Nader, the
Green Party nominee, but most have simply gone underground.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of political rivals getting together in their mutual
interest after a period of name-calling is as old as the written
word. According to William Safire in ``The New Language of
Politics,'' the term ``strange bedfellows'' was probably first
coined by Shakespeare in Act II of ``The Tempest.'' The jester
Trinculo huddles with a monster during a storm, noting wisely that
``misery acquaints a man with strange bedfellows.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd alliances for expediency's sake make the world go around.
Sometimes, of course, they work better than at other times.
</P>
<P>
   Safire recalls former House Speaker Joseph Martin musing on the
double meaning of the bedfellows phrase. Martin recalled that a
House member shouted, ``Politics makes strange bedfellows,
especially since women got into 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, politics. An ever-changing marvel to behold.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
