<HEADLINE>
`SPIN' SCRIPTS WON'T GLOSS OVER SHEEN'S BAD-BOY PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Can a sitcom lose its star and still succeed?
More to the point, when that star is America's boy next door and
his replacement is Peck's bad boy, will the viewers give a hoo-ha?
</P>
<P>
   ABC is betting ``Spin City'' with Charlie Sheen will do as well
as ``Spin City'' with Michael J. Fox, even if the stars have public
personae as different as Hollywood and New York.
</P>
<P>
   When Fox decided to leave the series to concentrate on his
battle with Parkinson's disease, producer Gary David Goldberg
thought the show was over. ``Everyone's first instinct was to end
the show,'' Goldberg said yesterday. ``There was no thought
whatsoever as to whether this show should go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said the idea to continue came from Fox, and Goldberg
sought out Sheen, with whom he had shot a comedy pilot that wasn't
picked up. Sheen signed on, several other cast members signed off,
and production will move from New York City to L.A., with Heather
Locklear continuing as Caitline Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest reason we decided to go forward was Charlie,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen's character, New York deputy mayor Charlie Owen, will have
a past not unlike Sheen's, replete with escapades that end up on
the front page for the wrong reasons. But he said he's OK with art
imitating life. ``I think in a self-effacing way, to meet some of
those elements head on and deal with them comedically and laugh at
myself is a good way to dispel a lot of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen also doesn't mind that he'll be going up against his
father on Wednesday nights. ``Spin City'' will air opposite the
second half of NBC's ``The West Wing,'' in which Martin Sheen plays
the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chernuchin, creator of a new TNT series about maverick
investment bankers, says he has been pitching the idea of a Wall
Street drama for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept getting the reaction that nobody cares about people who
make money, that it's too elite a world,'' Chernuchin said.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Now that about 60 percent of Americans own stock in
publicly traded companies, the American TV industry agrees that an
ensemble show about bankers and traders and wheelers and dealers is
timely. So timely that, in the grand tradition of TV, there will be
two such shows this season.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin's is called ``Bull'' and will premiere Aug. 15 on TNT
cable. The other, titled ``The $treet,'' will debut on Fox this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin, former executive producer of ``Law &AMP; Order'' and
``Brooklyn South,'' hastens to say the two shows aren't identical.
His is about venture capitalists. ``The $treet'' is about
high-pressure traders. What's more, ``The $treet'' is from Darren
Star (``Sex and the City''), whose style hews more closely to
prime-time soapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
