<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER18-COX     07-17 1909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Adoptions and absent fathers
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush says fathers have no right to prevent the
adoption of their children if they don't claim responsibility soon
after birth. He was in President Clinton's home state of Arkansas
today to promote a 1997 Texas law creating a Paternity Registry.
Fathers of out-of-wedlock children must sign the registry to
maintain a legal claim of parenthood. Bush said the policy gets to
the core of two questions: ``What can we do to encourage dads to be
a part of their children's lives. And, if you cannot make sure a
dad is (responsible), what can we do to expedite adoptions.''
</P>
<P>
   ROAD SHOWS BY RAIL AND WATER
</P>
<P>
   In a transportation showdown aimed at making presidential
politics appealing in the heat of summer after the conventions, Al
Gore plans to cruise the Great Lakes and down the Mississippi River
while George W. Bush will take to the rails through the industrial
Midwest and California. The competing caravans are part of the
effort by both campaigns to extend the euphoria generated by their
conventions toward Labor Day, when many undecided voters are
expected to begin cementing their impressions of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   CAREFULLY PLANNED ROUTE TO PHILLY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, campaigning in Arkansas today, announced that
the first stop in his pre-Republican convention trek will be in
northwest Arkansas. He'll then travel to Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio
and West Virginia _ all states won by President Clinton in 1996 _
before arriving in Philadelphia on the third night of the
convention, Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   SEEING SOME NIXON IN GORE
</P>
<P>
   Ex-House Speaker Newt Gingrich says Al Gore reinvents himself so
often in the presidential campaign he has become the Democratic
Party's Richard Nixon. In an interview broadcast this morning on
NBC's ``Today''' show, Gingrich said Gore had been both negative
and ``kaleidoscopic''' in his campaign, changing his image
frequently like the Republican Nixon during his campaigning. ``They
used to talk about a new Nixon, but we get a new Gore about every
10 days,'' said Gingrich, who resigned after the Republicans lost
seats in the November 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   NADER: PUT DEMS IN HOUSE, NOT WHITE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader told an audience
at Creighton University in Omaha, Neb., that he would consider it a
victory if his third-party presidential candidacy cost Al Gore the
election. Nader: ``Al Gore is a plastic person who doesn't know who
he is anymore. I think the two parties have had their chance. We
have one corporate party wearing two heads with diferent makeup.''
Nader said he'd consider his candidacy a success if George W. Bush
wins, if his Green Party ``emerges stronger, and if enough voters
cast their votes to put the Democrats back in control of the
House.''
</P>
<P>
   NADER THREAT DOWNPLAYED
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore dismissed questions about whether Ralph Nader's
presidential bid is siphoning away support from his candidacy,
saying that by election day most voters will want to choose between
``two very stark alternatives'' _ Gore or George W. Bush. Recent
polls have indicated Nader's Green Party candidacy could hurt Gore
in key states such as Michigan and Pennsylvania. But Gore said he
expects that to change.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE BUSH SHORT LIST
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has narrowed his list of possible running mates
down to about four candidates, including two senators and two
governors, according to the Washington Times. The newspaper, citing
officials involved in the vetting process, said today that four of
the remaining names on Bush's dwindling list are Govs. Frank
Keating of Oklahoma and Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, and Sens. Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska and Fred Thompson of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   NOW, LET'S SEE IF BUSH THINKS SO, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse News Services' Quin Hillyer has his bet down for George
W. Bush's running mate selection: Rep. Christopher Cox of
California, age 48. His reasons: ``Possibly the brainiest
Republican in the House, and easily among the most diligent. ... He
would energize the Republican base, impress the pundit classes,
attract both baby boom and Generation X married couples, make
single women swoon, and turn delegate-rich California into a highly
competitive battle. And in front of the cameras, Cox remains cool
and virtually unflappable.''
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE GORE SHORT LIST
</P>
<P>
   With House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri reportedly
removing himself from consideration for vice president, chatter now
is focusing on a few other possibilities. Said to be still strongly
in the running are ex-Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, and current
Sens. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Bob Graham of Florida and Dick
Durbin of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE BY SIDE BY ASIDE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush have yet to meet face-to-face in a
debate, but they they gave voters a chance for the first time to
make a side-by-side comparison as the two sat for hourlong
interviews on network television Sunday talk shows. Gore faced
aggressive questioning from Tim Russert of NBC's ``Meet the Press''
on his record and past statements, while Bush was asked questions
of a more political nature by Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts on
ABC's ``This Week.'' The questioning highlighted some stark
differences between the candidates, for example on Social Security,
the death penalty and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   EASY DECISION FOR FORD
</P>
<P>
   Ramping up the abortion debate, ex-President Gerald Ford is
urging George W. Bush to stare down the GOP's anti-abortion zealots
and pick a running mate who favors abortion rights. ``There's no
question about it,'' Ford told the New York Daily News in an
exclusive interview. ``A pro-choice running mate would help
Governor Bush and help the party. I feel very strongly that way. A
responsible pro-choice candidate will really strengthen the
ticket.'' Anyone in mind? Ford, who turned 87 last Friday, thinks
Tom Ridge, the Catholic governor of Pennsylvania, would be a
splendid veep choice.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORD FROM CAMP DAVID
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak found time during the Middle
East summit to update Al Gore and George W. Bush about the status
of the peace talks. Both campaigns characterized the telephone
conversation as friendly and brief, and said Barak told them both
the Israeli and Palestinian delegations were working diligently.
Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan, who was not called, said he
worried that peace might come at an enormous price tag to the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   BARELY BREAKING A SWEAT
</P>
<P>
   Out on the campaign trail, George W. Bush is molding the image
he wants by creating carefully choreographed television images in
battleground states. Town hall meetings where large audiences are
free to ask questions vanished months ago when John McCain
disappeared from the presidential race. Now, audiences rarely get
to ask Bush anything. On many days he makes no more than one or two
public appearances, and occasionally they last no more than 15
minutes. The events make him seem to be governing rather than
campaigning. It is almost as if he's running on the Rose Garden
strategy _ with the rose gardens in a few swing states.
</P>
<P>
   FORGET ABOUT MOVIE PREMIERES
</P>
<P>
   From the Playboy Mansion to Paramount Pictures studios, from
Wolfgang Puck's trendy Spago restaurant to Los Angeles' Union
Station, from the Petersen Automotive Museum to the J. Paul Getty
Museum, the convention parties will present the mother lode of
wheeling, dealing and hobnobbing for visiting Democrats. At least
one private fest, whose location was not available but rumored to
be headed up by Barbra Streisand, is expected to see donations to
the party of $15,000 a person.
</P>
<P>
   BUT WOULD HE GO TO HOOTERS?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore objects strenuously to the event, but Rep. Loretta
Sanchez (D-Calif.) is going ahead with her plan to hold an
invitation-only reception at the Playboy Mansion during the Los
Angeles convention. The Playboy Foundation, six corporations and a
40-member host committee are underwriting the event, which will
benefit Hispanic Unity USA, a political action committee chaired by
Sanchez. About 600 people are expected to attend. Playboy founder
Hugh Hefner is scheduled to drop by; Gore is not.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS, Y2K-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   When the Democratic Party's 4,368 delegates arrive in L.A. for
the convention, beginning Aug. 14, they'll plan meetings with each
other online using an Internet scheduling system. They'll chat by
Internet phones and e-mail from computer kiosks throughout the
Staples Center, site of the convention. And back home, folks can
keep in touch with them and watch every second of the gathering
live with Web cameras linked to the convention's extensive Internet
site.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE HELP FROM OUTSIDE
</P>
<P>
   Special-interest groups played an unprecedented role in key
primary elections this year, a new report finds, with conservative
groups battering John McCain in South Carolina and labor unions
providing crucial support to Al Gore in Iowa. ``If the level of
ferocity of the primaries is any indication of the cross party
battles in the fall, we are in a for a very bloody fight,'' said
the report, ``Getting Inside the Outside Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW CITIZENS, NEW VOTERS
</P>
<P>
   Millions of recently naturalized immigrants are eligible to vote
for president for the first time in November, and some analysts
predict they could be a deciding factor in key electoral states.
The Immigration and Naturalization Service expects the number of
new citizens created this fiscal year (ending Sept. 30) to be about
900,000. That would bring the number of new citizens to nearly 4
million since 1996. They are concentrated in large states such as
Texas, Florida, California, New York and Illinois, which provide
the bulk of the electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   BARRING ANY UNFORESEEN CIRCUMSTANCES
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, during the first of several chummy debates in
Georgia, Rep. Bob Barr's three Democratic challengers made a
profound discovery: They agree on just about everything. So, rather
than spar over issues, the Democratic primary battle has centered
on who has what it takes to unseat the outspoken Republican
incumbent, known for his criticism of President Clinton and his
unyielding support of the gun lobby. The three: millionaire
businessman Roger Kahn; ex-Atlanta police officer Chip Warren; and
Jim Williams, an ex-county commissioner. The primary is Tuesday .
</P>
<P>
   HIS OWN BEST (OR WORSE) EXAMPLE
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. George Nethercutt built his campaign in 1994
around his term-limits pledge, holding up then-House Speaker Tom
Foley ``as a creature of Washington, D.C., born and raised in that
system.'' Now the eastern Washington state congressman insists his
promise was ``gratuitous on my part'' and ``something I blurted out
in a debate with my predecessor.'' Says Nethercutt: ``To term-limit
yourself really reduces your effectiveness. I'm less enamored with
the idea of term limitations, and I'm the perfect example of why we
don't need them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
