<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW NINERS QB FULL OF CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Jeff Garcia says he's ready to assume the
role of the No. 1 quarterback for the San Francisco 49ers. Coach
Steve Mariucci, pleased with his starting quarterback's improving
play, isn't so sure about the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a work in progress,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia reported to camp Saturday with the rookies and was on the
field practicing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Garcia said. ``I'm coming out here without
any question marks in my head. I know I'm the No. 1 guy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first 49ers training camp in 20 years when the
starting quarterback hasn't been either Joe Montana or Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome considering those were two of my favorite
quarterbacks growing up,'' Garcia said. ``It's a tremendous
feeling. I don't want to let myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci says Garcia is handling the pressure well, although he
noted it was a potentially difficult situation following in the
wake of two future Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would probably be devastating for a quarterback to dwell
on that,'' Mariucci said. ``Therein lies the potential of being
overwhelmed. . . . He's got to be Jeff Garcia.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was rushed into the starting job last year during his
rookie NFL season when Young was lost with a concussion. But it was
still Young's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Steve is on the field, Steve is the leader. Period,''
Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Garcia's leadership, Mariucci said that would come with
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Steve is not around anymore lets Jeff start to
step into that position,'' he said. ``It doesn't happen
overnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
