<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CYC-TOUR-LANCE18-COX     07-17 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-LANCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour takes day off but Armstrong feuds with Italian racer
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France - The Tour de France took the day off Monday,
but that didn't stop race leader Lance Armstrong from feuding with
Italian competitor Marco Pantani
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who has dominated the race the past two weeks, has
been criticized allowing Pantani, the 1998 Tour victor, to win
stage 12 Thursday on Mont Ventoux.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Armstrong turned feisty, referring to Pantani as ``Il
Elephantino,'' a jab at the Italian's bald head and large ears, in
front of 500 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he has shown his true colors,'' Armstrong. ``I
felt like (the stage win) was a gift. I also feel now that it was a
mistake to give the gift. Pantani wasn't the best man on Ventoux.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disappointed in his actions. I thought he had more
class than that. The strongest should win the stage. At the time, I
thought it was the right thing to do, the classy thing to do. Since
then, I've been disappointed with his attitudes and his
declarations.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Pantani did not see Armstrong's gesture as a gift.
He was quoted in a French publication as saying ``If Armstrong
thinks it's all over, he's wrong. In any case, he's not finished
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper ``L'Equipe'' also quoted Pantani as saying, ``When
Armstrong told me to speed up he was looking to provoke me. This
diminished him in my eyes, and I felt closer to him (in form and
strength). The Tour is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   The spat between two of the biggest names in cycling will add
spice to the rest of the race, including today's 121.8-mile
mountain climb from Courchevel to Morzine.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has a commanding 7-minute, 26-second lead over 1997
Tour champion Jan Ullrich, his nearest competitor. Pantani is
seventh, 9:57 behind Armstrong, but he has won two mountain stages
_ the one Armstrong said he gave him and stage 15 on Sunday, when
he dashed past Armstrong within 10 miles of the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's race, Pantani said he preferred to finish alone.
``It's much more satisfying,'' he said. ``There's a different taste
to victory when you leave everyone behind. It's the taste of
triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Replays of the finish of the Mont Ventoux stage show Armstrong
pulling back just before he crossed the finish line, allowing
Pantani to ease past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought at the time it was the right thing to do because I
like Pantani and I respect him as a rider,'' Armstrong said. ``I
know that the last 12 months have been hard on him. I thought he
rode a tough race. I'm disappointed with the way things have
transpired. I made a mistake (in allowing him to win). But it
doesn't change the fact that I respect him as a rider.
</P>
<P>
   Today ``is his last day to do anything,'' Armstrong said.
``Marco came here to win stages. I'm here to win the Tour de
France. I feel very comfortable with where I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani is one of the more popular athletes in Europe. The
Italian media started calling him ``Il Elephantino'' early in his
career. Pantani then started calling himself ``Il Pirata.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Armstrong, of Austin, Texas, has a huge lead over a
field that features two other Tour champions, he is without a stage
win. If he wins the overall race, he would be the first Tour
champion to do so since Greg LeMond in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also responded Monday to criticism from Tour director
Jean Marie LeBlanc, who was quoted in French publications as saying
that Armstrong would be more popular in France if he spoke French.
Armstrong can speak French but prefers to use a translator when
giving interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that (LeBlanc) said that,'' Armstrong said. ``I'm not
here to win a popularity contest. I love the country of France. I
live in the country of France. I like the people here. But
unfortunately, I can't speak French very well. I did try to speak
French last year, and I was taken advantage of several times. I
don't want to put myself in that position again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to win a bike race, not a popularity contest.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
