<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LEMONDADE18-COX     07-17 2720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMONDADE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The A-to-Z guide for a sure-fire successful lemonade stand
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Carey O'Donnell is a lemonade-stand
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, she opened a stand next to the Flagler Museum and
flagged down customers by tying a fishing line between two trees.
Those riding by on bikes would ... well, they'd have to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably not the best way to get customers,'' admits
O'Donnell, who now owns a West Palm Beach PR firm.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Donnell has other good ideas for making your lemonade
stand tops in the neighborhood. And so does developer Joel
Channing. And home-improvement wizard Bob Vila.
</P>
<P>
   We asked them and other grown-up experts how to build, market,
staff and run the perfect, profitable stand.
</P>
<P>
   The Entrepreneurial Personality
</P>
<P>
   First of all, you need to decide if you have what it takes to
squeeze profits out of lemons.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Administration provides wannabe entrepreneurs
with the following quiz to determine if they've got the makings of
a self-made man, woman or child:
</P>
<P>
   - Am I a self-starter? (A good test: Do you clean your room on
your own or do you need constant prompting from Mom and Dad?)
</P>
<P>
   - How well do I get along with a variety of personalities?
</P>
<P>
   - Do I have the physical and emotional stamina to run a
business? (Consider that running a South Florida stand requires
standing in the heat for several hours a day.)
</P>
<P>
   - How good am I at making decisions?
</P>
<P>
   - Are my attitudes and drive strong enough to maintain
motivation? (Or will you want to reach for the Game Boy Color when
you hit a lull in customers?)
</P>
<P>
   - How well do I plan and organize?
</P>
<P>
   - How will the business affect my family? (Will big sis mind
that your bustling biz may block the drive?)
</P>
<P>
   Attracting Customers in a Competitive Marketplace
</P>
<P>
   You gotta figure that the kids down the street are going to take
the boring route: Two orange crates, a piece of plywood, lemonade
in Dixie cups.
</P>
<P>
   You can do better than that!
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of something eye-catching that nobody's done with a
lemonade stand; make it unique,'' suggests Sloan Kamenstein, whose
downtown West Palm Beach ice-cream store contains a working model
train, an explosion of neon colors and fuzzy textures, and
transparent restroom doors that instantly fog up when locked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the whole store to be something unusual that people
would remember and they would go home and talk about.'' Decorate
your own stand with bright, fun colors. ``It adds to the
atmosphere, it sets the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sloan's, they get creative, serving special ice-cream sundaes
in flower pots, for instance, decorated with pinwheels, toy monkeys
and palm trees. Why not put a paper umbrella in each cup of
lemonade?
</P>
<P>
   Or, Kamenstein says, you could add food coloring for 'ades of
crazy hues. Or serve the drinks in hollowed-out lemons (for kids)
or grapefruits (for adults).
</P>
<P>
   But remember, great presentation can't disguise a lackluster
product, Kamenstein says. No matter what, ``make the best lemonade
possible. Use the best ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Structure
</P>
<P>
   No need to get too fancy when you're building a temporary stand,
says home improvement guru Bob Vila.
</P>
<P>
   ``A card table and nice linen cloth are best,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (Best of all, those are two items that Mom and Dad might already
have around the house. Read: Working with materials at hand means
keeping start-up costs down.)
</P>
<P>
   But let's say you want to build a permanent stand...
</P>
<P>
   Says Vila: ``In that case, I would suggest mahogany planks
straddling a couple of coconut palms.''
</P>
<P>
   Very Florida, which you'd expect from a Miami native and
University of Florida graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel: Your Human Resources
</P>
<P>
   You're going to need help running your stand, but not everyone
is front-counter material. Who among your friends and family is up
to the task?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the world's top food-service companies say they look
for when hiring:
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's _ Employees who are ambitious, creative and looking
for a challenging career.
</P>
<P>
   Tricon Global Restaurants (Taco Bell, Pizza Hut, KFC) _ ``People
who are committed to quality food and satisfying customers better
than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's _ ``Individuals who critically value collaboration,
recognition of individual and team contributions, new ideas and
dedication to `best practices' in all areas of expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrols Corp. (owners of Pollo Tropical and franchisee of Burger
Kings) _ Applicants looking for excitement and personal growth.
</P>
<P>
   In short, steer clear of the couch potato or computer junkie in
your home, and opt for the kids in your neighborhood who are the
first ones to wheel their bikes onto the street each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Dispensing a Quality Product
</P>
<P>
   Courtesy ``Martha Stewart Living''
</P>
<P>
   3 cups freshly squeezed lemon juice (about 20 lemons)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   4 cups ice
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons, thinly sliced, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cranberry juice (optional, for pink lemonade)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Into a large serving container, strain the lemon juice and mix
it with the sugar. Stir until the sugar is dissolved. Add the water
and stir again until well-combined. Add ice to fill and a few lemon
slices to garnish. The recipe is for strong lemonade that can
tolerate dilution by an afternoon's worth of added ice.
</P>
<P>
   Martha also recommends these good things to supplement your
beverage income: Construction-paper fans, folded by hand and priced
at a $1 each; stick candy purchased at the corner store and marked
up to 15 cents a piece; bar cookies at $1 each; and cups of Jell-O
kept chilled in a pan over ice.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting a Location
</P>
<P>
   Think visibility and traffic (pedestrian is obviously better
than vehicular in this case). That's the advice from local
developer Joel Channing.
</P>
<P>
   When Channing set up his first lemonade stand in 1946 in
Washington, D.C., he put it on a bustling thoroughfare (luckily, he
happened to live on the busy street).
</P>
<P>
   ``It did very well _ must have made a dollar,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Channing Corp. is developing PGA Commons, a $50 million retail,
residential and office project scheduled to open in Palm Beach
Gardens in October.
</P>
<P>
   But, hypothetically speaking, Channing says his best bet for
this kind of business is on the island: ``A lemonade stand on Worth
Avenue would be great. There's no really convenient place to stop
for just a quick drink, and it gets pretty hot out there
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But remember, you may need friends in great locations. The city
of West Palm Beach, for instance, doesn't allow lemonade stands on
public land. You'll have to set up your citrus on private property,
either your own or someone else's, if you have permission.
</P>
<P>
   Product Positioning
</P>
<P>
   Carey O'Donnell, whose public-relations firm handles accounts
for CityPlace and PGA Commons, gives the following tips for making
your stand stand out in a crowd:
</P>
<P>
   - Location, location, location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go where you're likely to find thirsty people. Anywhere people
exercise is a good bet, but there's two sides to that. If they're
exercising, they may not have any money in their pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Or follow a retailing principle: ``A corner is always great.''
</P>
<P>
   - Safety first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is to select a place where it's safe for people
to stop and for kids to have their stand.''
</P>
<P>
   And try to set up under a shade tree. ``That way they don't get
hot and neither do their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   - Signage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would make absolutely sure that the sign was written by a
child. I would even throw in a backward letter or two. People are
charmed by that. You don't want to it to look professional.''
</P>
<P>
   And add something like, ``Voted the most delicious lemonade in
all West Palm Beach by my entire family.'' Humor will boost sales
since most adults buy lemonade ``to help out the children, not
because they're thirsty.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, O'Donnell says, ``I don't recommend my fishing line
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasing Revenue through Advertising
</P>
<P>
   A basic rule of advertising: Establish how your product is
different from your competitors' and how it fulfills the needs of
the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the more nontraditional the approach is, the better off
you're going to be in positioning the product,'' says Lori McAlear
of McAlear &AMP; Associates, whose clients include Cushman Fruit Co.
and the Pete Rose restaurants. ``The more unique it is and the more
it catches somebody's attention, the more successful the marketing
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a McAlear idea: Make a series of signs leading from the
waterfront or a major roadway to your stand.
</P>
<P>
   The first few signs don't tip off the viewer that you're selling
lemonade. Instead, they capitalize on the emotional appeal of a
cool drink.
</P>
<P>
   Sign 1: ``Feeling hot?''
</P>
<P>
   Sign 2: ``Feeling tired?''
</P>
<P>
   Sign 3: ``Need something cool and refreshing?''
</P>
<P>
   Intersperse these with designs that convey ``cool and
refreshing'': blocks of ice, an old rotary fan ... (If you need an
adult's help visualizing this, ask your grandparents about the old
Burma Shave signs.)
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the signs will lead the pedestrian or commuter
straight to your stand, where you will handily capitalize on the
emotional appeal of drinking something cool on a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, if you sell lemonade, make sure you're
marketing lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to position yourself as gourmet dining and then
have customers disappointed, which is the worst thing you can do,''
McAlear says.
</P>
<P>
   The Profit Margin
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, one of the main reasons you're opening a stand is to
earn a little extra cash. But how?
</P>
<P>
   A few helpful pricing hints from ``The Accounting Game: Basic
Accounting Fresh from the Lemonade Stand'' (Sourcebooks, $16.95):
</P>
<P>
   To determine a price per glass, you need to total the cost of
your lemonade ingredients and count how many glasses of lemonade
you've made. Divide the cost of ingredients by the number of
glasses. Now you have the cost per unit.
</P>
<P>
   To turn a profit, you obviously need to charge more than the
cost per unit. How much more?
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask around,'' say authors Darrell Mullis and Judith
Orloff. ``You ask your family and your friends and your neighbors
and your dog or pet turtle. You think about what restaurants charge
for drinks. You remember that last summer the kid down the street
(who you don't like) got a dollar for his lemonade which was made
from some awful-tasting powder mix.''
</P>
<P>
   You want to strike a balance between clearing a profit and not
scaring away business. In ``The Accounting Game,'' for example, the
fictional lemonade stand charges 50 cents for a glass of lemonade
that cost 20 cents to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the Deal
</P>
<P>
   At long last, a customer approaches. How do you send him or her
away with a glass of lemonade, and earn a pocketful of change in
the process?
</P>
<P>
   Start by asking questions that your customer can't say ``no''
to, advises Gemmy Allen, About.com's sales expert.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of saying to a passer-by, ``Do you want a lemonade?'',
entice your customers into saying ``yes'': ``Is it hot enough for
you today? Need something cool to drink?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be discouraged if you get a negative response. ``If people
tell you `no,''' Allen says, ``it will help you learn how to
satisfy their needs in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're using the Martha Stewart recipe provided here, you
might mention that in your sales pitch. That's called brand
recognition, and people associate a certain level of quality with
Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if you're selling lemonade made from a recipe that's been in
your family for 100 years, make that part of your spiel. ``That
appeals to people's emotions,'' Allen says. ``The lemonade
satisfies their thirst, but people have other needs, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But if people are ready to buy, ``you close (the sale)
immediately. You don't give them the story'' of your lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, use basic customer service techniques. Look the
customer in the eye. Smile. If there's a line, tell them you'll be
right with them and apologize for the wait. And always, always
thank them for their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you make money in business is through your repeat sales,''
Allen says. ``You want to build a relationship with yy'' and a
natural subject for him to explore. ``In the opening moments of our
history of baseball that we released six years ago, writer Gerald
Early told us that when they study our civilization 2,000 years
from now, Americans will be known for only three things: the
Constitution, baseball and jazz music. They are the most beautiful
things Americans have ever created.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over, ``WWF Smackdown!'' Get ready for ``BattleBots!''
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking: What the heck is a BattleBot?
</P>
<P>
   ``BattleBots'' is a new Comedy Central series in which homemade,
remote-controlled metallic robots fight to the ``death'' in a
48-foot-by-48-foot Thunderdome-like arena. In this bizarre _ some
might say insane _ series, such fierce-sounding contraptions as
Vlad the Impaler and Biohazard crash and smash each other until
only one is left standing. But that's not all. The battling robots,
which can weigh up to 488 pounds, must also dodge such weapons as
spikes and buzz saws that emerge from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over this madness are twins Randy and Jason Sklar
(MTV's ``Apartment 2F'') and ``Baywatch'' babe Donna D'Errico.
</P>
<P>
   Is Comedy Central serious?
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Comedy Central as you may not have seen it before,''
admits Bill Hilary, the network's vice president and general
manager. ``We think it'll be slightly shocking at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, from the in-your-face clip I saw, ``BattleBots,''
tentatively scheduled to debut next month, will make ``Smackdown!''
look like ``Masterpiece Theater.'' Sklar, however, sniffs at those
comparisons. ``It's not like World Wrestling Federation where it's
fake,'' he says. ``There are real pieces of robot flying around.
This is real pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly painful for the viewer, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, this is a real sport. There is an actual
league and winners do take home prize money (up to $30,000) and
something called ``The Golden Nut.'' (No jokes please.) The sport
is thriving in Japan and Germany. Some robots even cost up to
$75,000 to make. ``They're deadly serious about it,'' notes Mack
Anderson, a ``BattleBots'' executive producer. ``I mean, people
spend years designing these robots. I ran into one of the
competitors in San Francisco and he was pacing the streets late at
night. And I said, `What's the matter, my friend?' He said, `I've
got to face Biohazard tomorrow and I'm a wreck.'''
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not into raw destruction, look for hidden
educational messages. ``It's about teaching kids how to build
things,'' Trey Roski, ``BattleBots'' creator and president, says
with a straight face. ``Building these robots is difficult and you
have to be a little bit intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   And probably a little stupid to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Newshour with Jim Lehrer'' and ``Frontline'' will join
forces with National Public Radio in a live election broadcast
scheduled to air in November, PBS announced. ``Time to Choose -- A
PBS/NPR Voter's Guide'' will air live on Nov. 1 for three hours
from five PBS stations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   PBS will also unveil a new promotional campaign this fall.
``Come to Public Television if You're Curious'' will become PBS'
new slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to Adam Schiff, the gruff ``Law &AMP; Order'' D.A.
played by Steven Hill. The 78-year-old actor will not return to
NBC's long-running series. Hill reportedly grew tired of the show's
long shooting hours. He'll be replaced by two-time Oscar winner
Dianne Wiest, whom you may recognize from such Woody Allen movies
as ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' and ``Bullets Over Broadway.'' She'll
become the show's new D.A. I'll miss the gravelly-voiced Hill,
though. No one delivered irony-dripping lines better.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the weekend: Jonathan Winters on why he uses a cane:
``I'm not crippled. I'm just trying to deal with violence. I'm
afraid.'' You can catch more of Winter's rib-tickling shtick on
``Jonathan Winters: On The Loose,'' a PBS documentary scheduled to
air Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
