<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-INTERNET-DOMAINS-$ADV     07-17 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DOMAINS-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    250&AMP;add. With INTERNET-SOFTWARE. Moving in (w) Washington and
(f) financial categories for release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's pressure on the new Internet Corporation
for Assigned Names and Numbers to expand the number of ``top
level'' Internet domains.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet currently uses seven top-level domain names, the
broad categories that appear at the end of World Wide Web addresses
in the United States:
</P>
<P>
   gov _ federal government sites. (www.senate.gov)
</P>
<P>
   mil _ military sites (www.navy.mil)
</P>
<P>
   edu _ four-year accredited institutions of higher education
(www.harvard.edu)
</P>
<P>
   int _ international treaty organizations (www.nato.int)
</P>
<P>
   com _ commercial enterprises (www.amazon.com)
</P>
<P>
   org _ nonprofit organizations (www.naacp.org)
</P>
<P>
   net _ networking companies (www.earthlink.net)
</P>
<P>
   Campanies and groups pay a fee to register .com, .org and .net
domain names.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two-letter codes are use to identify sites in 247
countries. For example, FR for France, JP for Japan and SA for
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   However, as many desirable domain names have been used up in
recent years, there has been a cry to create more top-level
domains, and thus more ``room'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting last week in Japan, ICANN agreed to expand the number of
top-level domains, probably by next year. But no decisions have
been made yet about the new names. Here are some that are being
pushed by interested groups:
</P>
<P>
   banc _ financial services companies
</P>
<P>
   travel _ travel agencies
</P>
<P>
   shop _ online retailers
</P>
<P>
   union _ labor unions
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The address system for locating sites on the Internet originally
involved numbers rather than names.
</P>
<P>
   To make the Internet easier to use, the ``domain name'' system
was introduced in the mid-1980s. Its purpose was to convert a
numeric IP (for Internet Protocol) address, such as 192.0.34.65,
into an easy-to-remember name, such as www.icann.org.
</P>
<P>
   Each top-level domain (such as .org) can be divided into many
second-level domains (such as icann.org). Second-level domains can
be divided into third-level domains (such as members.icann.org),
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
