<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4706 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-INTERNET-HARDWARE-$AD     07-17 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HARDWARE-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS INTERNET GROWS, CAN HARDWARE KEEP PACE?
 &HT;    1030&AMP;add. With HARDWARE-DATA and INTERNET-SOFTWARE. Moving in
the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for release Sunday,
July 23.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the Internet expands the horizons of
millions of users and energizes the world economy, fears have
arisen that it could fall victim to its very success.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the World Wide Web offers about 2.1 billion pages and
growing by more than 7 million pages a day. A new study by
Cyveillance, an Internet research company, sees the number of pages
doubling by early 2001. Likewise, the community of users, now 275
million people around the globe, is projected to reach 1 billion by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the amount of information traveling across the
Internet is doubling every three months. But such growth rates pose
the very real nightmare that this massive online structure,
representing a $650 billion investment, could come crashing down in
gigantic cyber-traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the system has remained a going concern because key
service providers keep installing more and better hardware. The
question is, how long will this solution work?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think that adding capacity will solve the
problems,'' said Paul Segan, president of Akamai Technologies. ``It
simply will not.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagan, whose firm distributes online data through 4,000 servers,
told an industry conference in Chicago this month that the
Internet's backbone is already taxed to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   As high-speed broadband services become increasingly available,
he predicted, content providers will offer more streaming media and
users will spend more time on line, canceling out the hardware
gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, Sagan added, ``was never designed to be a
business-critical, 7-by-24 marketplace where real-time commerce,
entertainment and information is exchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, at least, online activities are safe from
catastrophic failure for much the same reason that they remain
vunerable to hacker attacks. Since the Internet was designed as a
decentralized network, it can ``repair'' itself by automatically
re-routing of data to ``healthy'' hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with keeping nightmarish failures in check are the
unsung people _ part cybercops, part cyberdocs _ who manage the
hardware that undergirds the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly employees of private companies rather than government,
they monitor traffic patterns to see where the load is increasing
fastest, so that new data lines and switching equipment can be
installed before the system can be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   At its physical core, the Internet is vast network of copper
wires and optical fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttling packets of data across these ``pipes'' to their proper
destinations are tens of thousands of special-purpose computers
known as routers, all programmed with same protocol, or addressing
language. Backing up those machines are simplified routers, known
as switchers.
</P>
<P>
   As Internet use continues to mushroom, so does the demand for
more sophisticated routers and switchers and higher-capacity pipes.
The technology is moving so rapidly that the $100,000-plus routers
that manage the Internet's ``backbone'' need to be replaced with
more powerful units every 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the upgrades resemble the way today's PCs are improved:
through more sophisticated processing chips and caching techniques,
coupled with larger storage and transmission capacities.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet's rapid convergence with telecom, video and
wireless devices are making ever more massive demands on the
network. A few years' hence, the only way to avoid gridlock may be
through now-experimental technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, experts see promise in ``photonic'' switches.
If such optical devices replaced electronic switches, there would
be no need to covert the light pulses carring data swiftly through
fiber-optic cables into electrons at central router hubs, a current
choke point in the data flow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another future prospect: Integration into the network of
Internet II, a blazingly fast closed system now being tested at
more 170 U.S. universities.
</P>
<P>
   Internet II is a four-year-old partnership among academia, the
government and industry. Its huge bandwidth, routed through some
some 30 dedicated hubs known as gigapops, make for both reliable
and efficient links that enable distant researchers to routinely
perform tasks that would be impossible to achieve on the public
system.
</P>
<P>
   They can, for example, watch full-motion video images _ in real
time, in full color and on large screens _ from a telescope in
Arizona and to simultaneously steer that huge tube around the
cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation helping the Internet keep up with growing
demands are ``server farms,'' huge data centers that consolidate
many high-volume Web operations in one location.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of these ``engine rooms'' of the Internet is one run by
IBM in the western Chicago suburb of Schamburg, Ill. It powers the
Web sites and electronic commerce operations of more than 500
companies and organizations, including BankAmerica, Macy's,
Goodyear Rubber and the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to own their own information but they don't want
to maintain it, and that is driving the shift back toward
centralization,'' said Adele Goldberg, a member of the team at
Xerox Palo Alto Research Center on the Stanford campus in the early
1970s that eventually spawned today's pervasive network-friendly,
PC-oriented computing universe.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike prior commercial revolutions _ telephones, power lines,
railroads, highways and airplanes _ government regulators play no
role in making sure the Internet keeps pace with explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, those tasks are being largely met by Cisco Systems
Inc., a Silicon Valley hardware giant with a current valuation of
some $460 billion. Cisco, which sells its products in some 115
countries, enjoys an effective lock on the world's high-speed data
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fiber (optical cables) are the railroad tracks, and Cisco
makes the trains,'' said Hal Varian, dean of the School of
Information Management at the University of California in Berkeley.
``There's been a lot of investment putting fiber into the ground.
But if you want to use that fiber, you need Cisco routers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Once users are connected to the Internet, routers serve as an
``intelligent device that works almost like a post office,'' said
Kevin DeNuccio, Cisco's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It understands where you're trying to get to and where that
is, and what's the easiest way to get you there, and it actually
directs your question, your request, to a server.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's clear dominance over the Internet networking scene _ the
company controls 65 percent of all Internet routers and continues
to grow at the rate of 40 percent a year _ raises the question of
whether it is likely to become a future target in the government's
antitrust gun sights.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the company has managed to avoid the fate of Microsoft
Corp., which has been branded in a federal court as a predatory
monopolist that needs to be split into two competing firms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, at about the same time as the Justice Department filed
its civil suit against Microsoft, the Federal Trade Commission
began to probe charges that Cisco had illegally colluded with two
other big players in the telecom hardware market: Lucent
Technologies and Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency subsequently dropped its inquiry. Since that
time, Cisco general counsel Dan Scheinman and other key executives
have meeting regularly _ on their own initiative _ with antitrust
chief Joel Klein and other Justice Department officials to contend
that Cisco lacks a monopoly choke hold on the Web and should be
left alone by federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's ``pipes'' present yet another facet of intense
market concentration. On July 10, the two largest fiber-optic
firms, JDS Uniphase and SDL, announced merger plans. If their $41
billion deal goes through, it promises to be the largest technology
merger ever.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by industry-watching Red Herring magazine noted
that ``three vendors _ JDS Uniphase, SDL, and E-Tek _ own their
market now and for the foreseeable future.'' In late June, after
the report was published, JDS acquired E-Tek.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.cisco.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
