<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-INTERNET-SOFTWARE-$AD     07-17 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SOFTWARE-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW INTERNET GOVERNING BODY FINDS ITS AUTHORITY CHALLENGED
 &HT;    WITH INTERNET-ICANN, INTERNET-DOMAINS, INTERNET-TAKEN and
INTERNET-HARDWARE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Www.any-site.com.
</P>
<P>
   To American ears, this familiar pattern identifies a World
Wisses will be assigned to keep pace with rapid Internet growth.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   If plans to establish private control over the Internet's
address system founders on technical details and political
disputes, the global expansion of the online community could become
gridlocked.
</P>
<P>
   But if it succeeds, Americans will have to get used to having
the Internet governed by an international body that may be located
in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force for change is an explosion in Internet use.
More than 14 million Web sites are now registered, with 59 percent
of them based in the United States. But with the rest of the world
discovering cyberspace, industry experts estimate that by 2003, the
Internet will be populated by some 160 million registered sites,
most of them overseas.
</P>
<P>
   So many companies are trying to squeeze themselves onto the
Internet that people everywhere are clamoring for more virtual real
estate beyond the already-crowded ``.com'' category. They want
addresses that end ``.shop,'' ``.travel,'' ``.banc,'' ``.med,'' and
even ``.porn.''
</P>
<P>
   And Internet users everywhere want a simple, inexpensive system
for resolving disputes over addresses and trademark names.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping up with the dizzying growth is technically
complicated and politically charged.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the rules is ``like rearranging the streets of a
city,'' said Frederick Weingarten, of the American Library
Association, a group trying to stir Internet users' interest in the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Because one's address is also one's name in cyberspace, the
issues also are legally complex, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you choose to call yourself ... has free speech
implications and it has intellectual property implications,''
Weingarten said. ``It essentially boils down to a fight over
identity who you are and what you call yourself in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming months, many of the key issues about the future of
addresses will be settled by a group charged with taking away
control of the system from the U.S. Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   That group is the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and
Numbers (ICANN), based in Marina del Rey, Calif. Put together in
1998 at the prompting of the Clinton administration, ICANN's
mission is to assemble a permanent international board to run the
Internet's address system and help settle disputes over trademarks
and names. Eventually, ICANN may move its global headquarters to
Switzerland, a country widely regarded as neutral ground.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have questioned the legitimacy of ICANN, calling it an
illegally formed quasi-government entity. But earlier this month,
the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress,
found nothing illegal about ICANN's formation.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report also concluded that ICANN can impose fees on
Internet registrars to defray operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, (July 12-16) ICANN's interim board met in Yokohama,
Japan, to continue hammering out the procedures for electing a
permanent board. ICANN plans to hold online elections this October
open to any Internet user 16 or older who registers on the ICANN
Web site by July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Staging a fair, free election on a global level in cyberspace
will be an unprecedented event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic election,'' said Scott Harshbarger,
president of Common Cause, a non-profit group trying to get
Americans registered to vote. Even people who have no interest in
the U.S. presidential election may want to get involved in ICANN,
he said, because ``the Internet may matter much more in their daily
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet address system got its start decades ago when the
network of computer networks was being cobbled together by computer
lovers employed by universities or government. Decisions tended to
be made informally and by consensus among a fairly tight-knit
group.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Internet's use expanded in the early 1990s, a more
sophisticated system evolved that divided addresses into major
categories, called domain names. An example is the familiar .com.
The system also uses two-letter country codes such as ``.uk'' for
the United Kingdom and ``.fr'' for France.
</P>
<P>
   To handle the growing number of addresses, the U.S. government
awarded an exclusive contract for registering commercial sites to
Network Solutions Inc., a Herndon, Va.-based company. At first,
Network Solutions' business was slow. Then Internet use exploded in
the mid-1990s, and demands grew to further ``privatize''
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of continuing to grant government contracts to register
names, the Clinton administration started putting together ICANN to
act as a private, non-profit corporation to administer policy for
the address system.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, ICANN and Network Solutions agreed to the terms under
which other companies could enter the registration business. Today,
more than 100 entities have been approved by ICANN to compete with
Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   With so many companies registering names, ICANN's role is vital.
It must coordinate with the Internet Engineering Task Force, the
Internet Architecture Board, and other organizations dealing with
Internet protocols and standards so that addresses can be ``read''
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   This coordination will be especially important when the Internet
starts grappling with new top-level domains.
</P>
<P>
   And that day is coming soon.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting in Japan, ICANN's interim board agreed to add new
top-level domain names in the coming year. But it did not yet
settle the issue of what the suffixes will be or how many can be
added.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to create new top-level domain names is so great
that even before ICANN finalizes its plans, Internet users are
finding ways around the rules. For example, one California company
has agreed to pay $50 million to Tuvalu, a tiny island group in the
South Pacific, for rights to Web addresses ending in that country's
code, ``.tv.'' The plan is to make money by getting media companies
to register television-related Web sites in the ``.tv'' domain.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out its mandate to administer the address system, ICANN
needs funding. But today, its budget is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ICANN's $4.3 million annual budget comes from the fees paid by
private companies that have registered their Web sites. Last year,
ICANN decided to raise 35 percent of its budget from national
governments, which have registered about 5 million addresses ending
with country codes.
</P>
<P>
   But ICANN is having trouble collecting $1.5 million owed from
many of the 247 nations taking part in the system. Dues are based
on the number of registered Web sites in each country, with bills
ranging from $500 in small nations to $500,000 in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ICANN's relationship with the country-code operators is so
ill-defined that many countries have been refusing to acknowledge
ICANN invoices, calling the fees a ``domain name tax'' imposed by a
U.S. corporation with no power to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At its Japan meeting, ICANN decided that any group trying to
create a new domain name will have to pay ICANN a non-refundable
application fee of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even if ICANN is able to bolster its budget, it faces other
challenges in expanding the list of countries that should get
codes. It was only after years of lobbying by Palestinians that
ICANN this March approved a ``.ps'' domain name. That move came
only after the United Nations added Palestine to its list of
country and territory codes.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, ICANN's single most important role may be to
help settle commercial trademark disputes as the Internet grows. It
is striving to create a process that is fair, fast and reasonably
priced.
</P>
<P>
   The first major test of its ability to settle disputes came this
year after the organization changed the rule that had limited names
to 22 characters. To create more room for new Web sites, it boosted
the number of allowed characters to 63.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a battle between the World Wrestling Foundation and
a California man. The WWF had www.wwf.com, a site it had held since
1994. But a California stockbroker, Michael Bosman, took advantage
of the ICANN change to register the address
www.worldwrestlingfederation.com for $60. After registering the
name, he contacted the Federation, which said he offered to sell
the name for ``a significant profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation filed a complaint using ICANN's Uniform Dispute
Resolution Process. ICANN uses the mediation services of World
Intellectual Property Organization, an arm of the United Nations,
to help settle the disputes. The WIPO ruled in favor of the
wrestling federation.
</P>
<P>
   Already, hundreds of trademark disputes have been submitted for
mediation. Critics believe the ICANN process may be too slow for
the volume of disputes that will be brewing. Others worry ICANN
will make it too easy for trademark holders to take away the names
of people who staked legitimate claims to them. But at least for
now, the ICANN experiment in global cooperation offers the best
hope for expanding the Internet create new cyber-neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: ICANN at www.icann.org.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog group at http://www.icannwatch.org/
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
