<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-AUTHORS-PEARSON-SPI &LR;      07-17 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-PEARSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER JUNKIE PEARSON OFTEN AHEAD OF FRONT-PAGE STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the season of the ``beach read,'' and crime novels by
Northwesterner Ridley Pearson are finding their way onto many a
towel spread at water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Other writers might aspire to have their work on library shelves
or in handsome homes, but having his work right there amid the
sunscreen, the sand granules, the cold drinks and the hot rays is
just fine with the 47-year-old crafter of high-adrenaline page
turners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a storyteller than a writer. I'm the first to
admit that,'' Pearson said in an interview. ``I like to write in as
smooth and literary a fashion as I can, but, first and foremost, I
want to entertain you. I want you to forget there's a clock on the
wall. I want you to forget there's laundry in the washer. So having
my books taken on vacation and being considered a `beach read' is a
real compliment. It is certainly better than having what you write
considered a `doorstopper.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's latest is a heart-stopper at times but never a
doorstopper. ``Middle of Nowhere'' (Hyperion, 375 pages, $23.95)
zings with high-tension narrative electricity, tantalizing twists
of plot, hard-edged realism straight from the headlines, plus such
a welcome return appearance by his two signature characters that
this is Pearson's first hardback to make the national best-seller
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm doing a little jig today,'' he said, although
the dance was too subtle to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's Lou Boldt, the knight-errant of a Seattle homicide
lieutenant, is back on the case, assisted by Daphne Matthews, the
Seattle police psychologist of stunning good looks and sharp-witted
insights. Their intense partnership is tested from without and
within, as Boldt's marriage again suffers from this flawed
loyalist's total immersion in work.
</P>
<P>
   Boldt has no choice in ``Middle of Nowhere.'' Seattle police are
staging a sickout, this ``blu flu'' decimating the force and
inviting a rash of thefts and assaults that has the tense Emerald
City teetering on the edge. Few officers remain on the job, and
some who do are subjected to attack, including Boldt, with fellow
officers among the suspects. The threat of retaliation hangs in the
Puget Sound air, along with precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   A police sickout in New Orleans provided some of the impetus for
``Middle of Nowhere,'' as did news reports of prison inmates
getting paid to work as telephone solicitors (a discovery that
satisfied Pearson's pledge, after being interrupted during dinner
by a telephone solicitor, that ``I now know who the next book's
villain will be!''). But the Sun Valley, Idaho, writer _ the first
American to receive the Raymond Chandler Fulbright Scholarship at
Oxford University _ had a larger theme in mind when he started the
novel.
</P>
<P>
   As Pearson stressed, ``Despite these books being seen as genre
fiction, it's still the intent of most writers in this field to
tell a good story and have it be more than some surface cop chase
seen on TV. I always try to start my books with a concept. `Middle
of Nowhere' was to be a story about loyalty and trust, actually the
loss of loyalty and trust, and how that affects the principal
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I seized on wanting to isolate Lou Boldt,
professionally, emotionally, and the vehicle I came up with was the
`blu flu.' So I came to Seattle police and wanted to talk to some
isolated officer, and I was led to a gay African American woman _
you probably can't get much more isolated than that _ and she was
marvelous. I put what she told me into Boldt and his situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is a stickler for realism in his 13 novels, right down
to the latest high-tech innovations (triangulation to track the
user of an analog cell phone in his new novel). The Brown
University graduate's reputation for accuracy has earned him many
fans in blue uniforms, as has his uncanny ability to have his
novels foreshadow upcoming headlines, which often break almost upon
publication.
</P>
<P>
   That started in 1988 when ``Undercurrents'' led to two murder
convictions in Washington after prosecutors linked up with the
oceanographer cited in the acknowledgements of Pearson's novel, an
oceanographer whom the writer had consulted on similar crimes for
his book. This strange prescience has continued in the wake of four
other Pearson novels, with such subjects as high-tech arsons,
illegal adoptions and the deaths of foreign stowaways in cargo
containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a weird thing,'' Pearson admitted. ``People ask if
I'm psychic, and of course I'm not. It may be nothing more than I
get interested in little things from reading papers so thoroughly.
I read a small item about a cargo container being found in Houston
with human waste and food, and I thought there's my story (``The
First Victim'' in 1999). Halfway through the writing, there was a
container found with dead stowaways in California; three weeks
before publication, there was one found in Tacoma and later more in
Seattle. It is awfully coincidental.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is a soft-spoken, erudite and earnest fellow, so dead
serious about writing that he devotes 65 hours a week to the task
(but then he also spent eight years writing fiction without earning
a penny).
</P>
<P>
   He has gentlemanly manners and many enthusiasms, including fly
fishing, tree climbing and public service (volunteer teaching at a
nearby alternative high school). He is also a confirmed family man
whose writer's Web site (www.ridleypearson.com) includes a
heart-tugging account of the pilgrimage that he and his wife,
Marcelle, made to China last year to adopt tiny Storey, who joined
a big sister named Paige.
</P>
<P>
   Music has always had a part in Pearson's life, and he plays bass
guitar in the Rock Bottom Remainders, the much-noticed garage band
that includes some of the country's best-selling authors (Stephen
King, Amy Tan, Dave Barry, Barbara Kingsolver) and has raised
$400,000 for charity.
</P>
<P>
   His recollection of his first meeting with other band members is
vintage Pearson: ``I thought it would be little old me with all of
them _ these guys are going to have egos the size of New York, and
I would cower in the corner. But they were all like brothers and
sisters, so normal, so wickedly bright and all so funny. We all
feed off each other. Some of my best friends now have come from
that band _ Dave Barry was even the best man at my wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Remainders hit the road again this fall for gigs in Denver,
Boston and Washington, D.C. It will be a time of considerable
change for Pearson. The writer and his family are moving to St.
Louis, although they will still spend summers in Sun Valley.
</P>
<P>
   And after many disappointments from busted Hollywood deals, it
seems likely that Lou Boldt will finally be making it onto the
screen for a series of TV movies on the Arts &AMP; Entertainment
Network. Pearson hopes the two Boldt films a year will be shot in
Seattle, with Richard Dreyfuss probably in the title role (even if
Ed Harris looks more like Pearson's vision of Boldt).
</P>
<P>
   Whoever plays Boldt on film will probably never top what
happened when Pearson met Don Cameron, a veteran homicide sergeant
with Seattle police (since retired) whom the writer had admired and
gotten to interview with the assistance of a prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   As Pearson recalled, ``I was buzzed into the homicide office,
and I stopped dead in my tracks _ Cameron looked that close to the
Lou Boldt I had imagined. I had an interview with him in an
interrogation room, and at its close, I said, `If I've stumbled or
gagged in this interview, please forgive me. It's just that you
bear an uncanny resemblance to my character.'
</P>
<P>
   ```I know,' Cameron responded, `I am Lou Boldt, Ridley. I've
read all those books.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
