<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4726 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-ALLISON18-COX     07-17 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ALLISON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emory fest hosts author Dorothy Allison
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy Allison isn't sure whether storytelling saved her life,
but she knows it saved her sanity.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in a world of poverty, violence and sexual abuse in
a Greenville, S.C., mill village. Her stepfather began raping her
when she was 5, she says, and for years she and her younger sisters
tried to find ways to kill him. ``You can leave pork chops out in
the sun, it won't kill him,'' she says. ``You can pour castor oil
in his tea, and it won't kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was helpless to stop him, Allison says, because there
was no battered women's shelter, no money to flee, and no one
urging her to do anything other than try to be a good Baptist wife.
(Allison's mother is dead; her stepfather denies the abuse.)
</P>
<P>
   Allison coped with her nightmare by reading voraciously and
hiding under the porch, listening to the stories her aunts and
grandmother told. Laced with humor and bawdy details, these were
vivid accounts of family members who killed or were killed or drank
themselves to death.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Allison will tell students at Emory University's
Summer Writers' Institute and Festival how she turned the horrific
material of her life into award-winning fiction. For the first
time, the focus of the festival will be on the work of one writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, having several writers sometimes diluted the
focus,'' says institute Director Judson Mitcham. ``Dorothy
Allison's work is very powerful, and it evokes the atmosphere and
conflicts of the South very well. She has one of the strongest
voices of anyone writing about the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous writers at the summer festival have included Fred
Chappell, Shay Youngblood, Tony Grooms and Judith Ortiz Cofer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storytelling can be a strategy to help you make sense of your
life,'' says Allison, 50, who finally escaped from her world of
poverty and violence when she won a scholarship to Florida
Presbyterian College.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, she still felt overwhelming shame, not because she
was an incest survivor and a lesbian, but because she had run away
from her family. Eventually she moved to Brooklyn, became involved
in the feminist movement and decided that the only way she could
write about her past was to confront it.
</P>
<P>
   The result was her acclaimed, semi-autobiographical ``Bastard
Out of Carolina,'' published in 1992 and later made into a Showtime
movie by Anjelica Huston. Ted Turner turned it down because of the
disturbing content, and ``Bastard Out of Carolina'' continues to
spark debate, Allison says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very forthright book on sexual violence, and there
aren't that many books that have been written about that,'' she
says. ``And it's written in an accessible style, so that teenagers
can read it. That disturbs a lot of people who don't want to
discuss the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison has become a magnet for young people who have come out
of abusive situations. They flock to her at book signings and write
her letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to listen,'' she says. ``I'm from the South, and when
somebody comes up to you crying, you have to listen. Mostly what
they want to do is tell me their story.''
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Bastard,'' Allison has written a memoir, ``Two or Three
Things I Know'' (1995), and a novel, ``Cavedweller'' (1998), about
an alcoholic rock singer who returns to her Georgia hometown to try
to make amends with the daughters she left behind. The novel is
being produced as an off-Broadway play.
</P>
<P>
   Allison is finishing another novel, ``She Who?'' the story of a
young woman who loses her memory after she is assaulted in a
parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about what happens in a family when you lose people, how
they have to adjust. ... I had a student, Earl, who was in a car
accident and was in a coma from head injuries. When I went to see
him, he was doing really well, but the Earl who had been a great
writer was not there. I found myself wondering what would happen in
that kind of situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now living in San Francisco with her partner and their
8-year-old son, Allison says life is better for her these days. ``I
do miss the South _ the food, the people, the smell,'' she says.
``It just smells different.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
