<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4741 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-PAUL-VERHOEVEN-DIRECT     07-17 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAUL-VERHOEVEN-DIRECTS-HOLLOW-MAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGHT UNSEEN: PAUL VERHOEVEN IS BACK WITH `HOLLOW MAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of director Paul Verhoeven on the set of
``Hollow Man.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It takes a tough man to make a tough movie.
 &HT;    So argues Paul Verhoeven, the director of such envelope-pushing
films as ``RoboCop'' (1987), ``Total Recall'' (1990), ``Basic
Instinct'' (1992), ``Showgirls'' (1995) and ``Starship Troopers''
(1997).
 &HT;    ``I'm supposed to be a hard taskmaster, and I am,'' Verhoeven
says in his still-thick Dutch accent. ``I'm described by people who
have worked with me as a man who tries to get as close to the edge
as possible without pushing people into the abyss.
 &HT;    ``I am trying very hard to reach the maximum of a movie, whether
it is science-fiction or sex or decadence or violence,'' he says.
``I have always done that, even in my early Dutch movies. There is
an element of provocation in that, because I'm trying to go where
other people aren't going.
 &HT;    ``There has been a tendency in the movies to embellish life and
portray it in a more principled way than the reality of life as we
know it,'' he adds. ``So filmmakers shy away from the sexual, from
the functions of the body, from violence.
 &HT;    ``The essential elements of our existence cannot be shown _ on
television in America you still can't show a person going to the
bathroom _ and that's absurd,'' Verhoeven continues. ``I show these
things. I don't sweeten it. I show it as I think it is, as I
perceive it.''
 &HT;    All of which ups the ante on the director's latest cinematic
gamble, ``Hollow Man,'' a variation on the ``Invisible Man'' saga.
Kevin Bacon stars in the Aug. 4 release as Sebastian Caine, a cocky
scientist working on a covert government project to develop an
invisibility serum. Elisabeth Shue and Josh Brolin play associates
who must stop Caine after he injects himself with the serum,
becomes invisible and, while losing more and more of his humanity
with each passing moment, takes full advantage of his new powers.
 &HT;    ``We abandon the idea that invisibility should be funny,''
Verhoeven says by telephone from a Los Angeles editing bay, where
he's putting the final touches on the film. ``So it plays more with
morality and with fear or danger or whatever word you want to use.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, the idea goes back to the time of Plato, and we
didn't even know that until very recently,'' the director adds.
``As a philosopher he wrote about invisibility, and he said that a
man who was invisible would steal left and right and, more
importantly, would enter everybody's house, rape the women, kill
the men or, if necessary, go into the prisons and free the men so
that all the criminals could run around.
 &HT;    ``Plato not only predicts what our movie will be about _ because
that is our theme _ he also tries to state why a human being would
behave that way,'' he says. ``For him, human beings in general
might naturally do such things, but they don't because of the
restraints society puts on us.
 &HT;    ``In other words,'' Verhoeven continues, ``if you could get away
with it, everybody would do it. The restraints would fall away,
because a man is only moral or just when society keeps an eye on
him. That theme, in its deepest sense, is what `Hollow Man' is
about.''
 &HT;    Films about invisible men are nothing new. But Verhoeven points
to advances in digital effects as his secret weapon in creating a
film the likes of which no one has ever, well, seen before.
 &HT;    ``The outstanding and most important reason why this movie could
be done at this moment _ and perhaps you could say should be done
at this moment _ is that we can do it,'' he says. ``All of the
amazing elements of how you can express invisibility or express an
invisible man are fun to play with.
 &HT;    ``You can shine a light through him and not see him, but if you
pour sand or water over him, you can see his form,'' Verhoeven says
animatedly. ``He's like a walking waterfall. This could not be done
before, and it can be done now. So I experimented with it and went
a step further than had been done before.
 &HT;    ``It goes beyond the T-1000 in `Terminator 2' (1991),'' the
director says. ``It goes beyond the dinosaurs in `Dinosaur' (2000).
We have almost 600 effects shots in `Hollow Man,' and the film
takes the element of digital possibility a step further.''
 &HT;    Verhoeven declares himself something of a reluctant sci-fi
specialist. He first won notoriety in America with ``RoboCop'' and
``Total Recall,'' then branched out with the suspense thriller
``Basic Instinct.'' However, he followed ``Basic Instinct'' with
the disastrous ``Showgirls,'' a universally maligned epic about Las
Vegas dancers, and had to return to the genre fold for ``Starship
Troopers.''
 &HT;    If ``Hollow Man'' proves solid at the box office, the
62-year-old Verhoeven can probably parlay that into another shot at
directing a more reality-based film. One story he'd like to tell is
that of Victoria Woodhull, the 19th-century feminist who was
America's first female presidential candidate.
 &HT;    ``She was a provocative, sexual and spiritual woman who was as
much a prostitute as she was a woman running for president,''
Verhoeven says. ``It's the first time I've found a person in
American history who would give me the responsibility to do in the
United States what I had been doing in Europe, where I was not
typecast as a special-effects or science-fiction director. I would
love to do something like that.''
 &HT;    Should that not work out, there are always the further
adventures of author/ice-pick wielder Catherine Tramell, Sharon
Stone's ice-queen character in ``Basic Instinct,'' to consider.
Stone recently signed on for a reprise, and the buzz is that
Verhoeven might do so, too.
 &HT;    ``I think it will be a great movie,'' he says, ``if I direct
it.''
 &HT;    Which is a big ``if.'' So, for the record, is Verhoeven actually
interested in ``Basic Instinct 2?''
 &HT;    ``If there's a great script and the conditions were perfect,
yes,'' he says. ``If not, no.''
 &HT;    Whatever happens, whatever Verhoeven's next film turns out to
be, don't expect him to go soft. After all, who'd want to see a
film by a mellow Paul Verhoeven? Certainly not Paul Verhoeven.
 &HT;    ``Some people would think they'd be less offensive,'' he says.
``Is that better? I don't know. They could lose their visceral
aspects. They could lose their energy.
 &HT;    ``I might even lose my motivation then,'' he says with a laugh.
``If that happened, I'd probably prefer to sit at home and read a
book.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
