<SLUG> BC-THE-ALLMAN-BROTHERS-BAND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKY ROAD: THE ALLMAN BROTHERS RIDE OUT ANOTHER STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the Allman Brothers Band, including
Jimmy Herring, Butch Trucks, Oteil Burbridge, Derek Trucks, Marc
Quinones, Jaimoe Johanson and Greg Allman.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    In ``Midnight Rider,'' one of its most popular songs, the Allman
Brothers Band boasts triumphantly that ``the road goes on
forever.'' But that doesn't mean the Southern rock band's road has
been a smooth one.
 &HT;    During the 31 years since its founding in Macon, Ga., the group
has withstood drug addictions, the deaths of founding members Duane
Allman and Berry Oakley, member defections and enough intraband
squabbling to make ``The Simpsons'' look like a functional family
unit. It also survived a near-decade of inactivity during the
1980s, before coming back together in 1989 for a reunion that's
lasted _ but not without its share of bumps.
 &HT;    The latest is the group's split, apparently intended to be
temporary, with guitarist Dickey Betts, whose past drug and
behavioral problems have led to previous hiatuses from the group.
 &HT;    The Allmans made the move in May, bringing in Jimmy Herring from
the band Aquarium Rescue Unit to take Betts' place for their
current summer tour.
 &HT;    Betts, meanwhile, reportedly plans to sue the group. Having only
received a fax stating that ``you have not been performing well and
our shows have been repeatedly disappointing to both us and our
fans as a result,'' the guitarist feels his bandmates _
particularly fellow founding members Gregg Allman, Butch Trucks and
Jaimoe Johanson _ owe him a better explanation.
 &HT;    In a posting on the group's Web site, Betts told fans that ``the
implication was that I was suffering from some sort of health or
drug problem. THIS IS TOTALLY, ABSOLUTELY UNFOUNDED!''
 &HT;    The rest of the band issued a brief public statement of support
for Betts, indicating a desire to have him back in the lineup at
some point. And singer/keyboardist Allman says that there's little
more to be said about the issue.
 &HT;    ``We still love him,'' the 52-year-old Allman says. ``He's still
our friend. It's nothing personal. I don't know _ maybe the road
got to be too much for him or something.''
 &HT;    Pressed a bit, Allman explains that Betts had become a divisive
personality within the group, and that his attitude had even
jeopardized this summer's tour.
 &HT;    ``If somebody's bummed out, it goes through the whole band like
a cancer,'' Allman says. ``Just about anybody that put in any kind
of suggestion, he had something to say about it. This had gone on
for a long, long time. I really hate to even go there, man.
 &HT;    ``Now, on to the music!''
 &HT;    On that front, Allman has a lot to say. The 38-year-old Herring,
he says, has injected new energy into a group that in recent years
has been driven by the youthful infusion of bassist Oteil
Burbridge, another Aquarium Rescue Unit member, and guitarist Derek
Trucks, drummer Butch Trucks' 21-year-old nephew.
 &HT;    ``I'm telling ya, it's smokin','' gushes Allman, who's been
clean and sober for nearly three years and recently replaced a
longtime cigarette habit with chewing gum. ``They bring youth and
vitality, of course _ that's the No. 1 thing. And a boatload of
talent.
 &HT;    ``These guys, at their ages ... '' He shakes his head in
wonderment. ``They play multiple instruments. When I was their age
I could whip out some Chuck Berry, maybe, and they can cut their
own demos! It took me awhile to get turned on to Coltrane and Miles
(Davis) and all these different jazz guys _ they listen to those
parts, and can just whip 'em out like that.''
 &HT;    As for Herring, he admits to feeling ``uneasy'' about stepping
in for Betts, who was a major influence on his playing. But the
chance to work with the Allmans was too good a chance to pass up.
 &HT;    ``It's about playing the music _ really, that's what it comes
down to,'' Herring says. ``It's great music. It's legendary music.
It's a chance for me to play with legendary musicians.
 &HT;    ``(The Allmans') albums, they were ringing through my house from
the time I can remember, from the earliest memories I have of
listening to music,'' he adds. ``I had two older brothers and they
were Allman Brothers fanatics, so I became one, too. That's what
made me want to pick up guitar in the first place.''
 &HT;    Herring says that, in the Allmans' new order, he's largely taken
Betts' role, while the younger Trucks covers Duane Allman's
territory, including the slide-guitar parts that were his
trademarks.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Herring says that he and Trucks have felt free to
explore their own ideas and styles within the Allmans' framework.
 &HT;    That enthusiasm for the material has led the group to resurrect
``Mountain Jam,'' a lengthy, improvised piece that usually
stretches beyond a half-hour, meandering through solos and changes
in time and tempo. It was a staple of the Allmans' early shows, but
was laid aside after Duane Allman died in a 1971 motorcycle
accident.
 &HT;    Now, however, the song is back in the band's repertoire.
 &HT;    ``That was Butch's idea,'' Allman says. ``He said `Man, how many
times have we gone out there and heard somebody yell ``Play
`Mountain Jam!''' for the last 30 years?'
 &HT;    ``We have heard that for years,'' Allman says, ``and I don't
think it's the same guy following us around. So we decided to bring
it back. The first night, in Virginia Beach, we opened up with it,
and it was great _ I mean, people started hitting their cell phones
and calling their friends. It was something else.''
 &HT;    Though the band is freely dipping into the past for its current
repertoire, Allman says that he has his eye on the future.
 &HT;    ``It's definitely time for the Allman Brothers to get into the
studio again,'' says Allman, who has five children and plans to
marry his fiancee, Stacy Fountain, this fall, as well as do a solo
tour. The group members have been working on new material, he adds,
and have ``all kinds of songs'' ready, some of which occasionally
pop up in the live show.
 &HT;    Recording that music, Allman says, ``will all come to pass,
probably very soon.''
 &HT;    Assuming, of course, that no more bumps appear on the road.
 &HT;    ``Well, we do have to wait,'' Allman acknowledges. ``We have to
get everything sorted out before we go back into the studio. But
we're itching to do it, man. We really are.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
