<SLUG> BC-PETER-FONDA-IN-THOMAS-AND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIDING IS STILL EASY FOR PETER FONDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Peter Fonda in a scene from ``Thomas and
the Magic Railroad.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Peter Fonda is riding again.
 &HT;    But 31 years after ``Easy Rider'' made him an icon, it's not a
Harley that he's gunning one stormy summer morning on his Montana
ranch. It's a power mower.
 &HT;    ``Hon, he's out there getting all dirty,'' Portia Crockett
Fonda, his wife of 28 years, tells a telephone caller. ``Let me go
round him up.''
 &HT;    If it's hard to believe that the one-time Captain America of
``Easy Rider'' (1969) has gone domestic, try this: The 61-year-old
counterculture icon's latest film is ``Thomas and the Magic
Railroad,'' opening July 26. And, yes, it's a kiddie picture.
 &HT;    ``I've always wanted to do a children's film,'' Fonda says.
``And basically I did this movie because lots of people only think
of me as Captain America smoking pot. But that's not me anymore.
I'm a parent and a grandparent.
 &HT;    ``Plus, inside I'm really an 8-year-old,'' he adds. ``I just
pretend to be this cool dude.''
 &HT;    After several lackluster decades, Fonda kicked his career back
into gear with an Oscar-nominated performance in ``Ulee's Gold''
(1997), then followed it up with solid work in ``The Passion of Ayn
Rand'' (1997) and ``The Limey'' (1999).
 &HT;    ``I feel like I've been given a second chance with my career,''
the actor says. ``I think part of it has to do with something going
on inside of me _ I honestly think it's all about getting hungry
again. And I'm starving for good parts.''
 &HT;    Another reason, he says, is that he's at a happier place in his
life, finally having come to terms with his place in the Fonda
acting dynasty as son of Henry, brother of Jane and father of
Bridget.
 &HT;    ``People get mixed up and think I'm living in the past,'' he
says. ``But honestly, I've gotten rid of the baggage by talking
about it. It doesn't bother me anymore.''
 &HT;    He remembers the first time he saw his father up on the big
screen.
 &HT;    ``I freaked out,'' he admits. ``I ran up to the screen and
pounded on it, yelling, `Daddy! Daddy!' My mother had to say,
`That's not your father. It's a character named Chad Hanna. Your
father is in the Pacific, fighting the war.'
 &HT;    ``I went home and looked at all the pictures of my father in our
house,'' Fonda recalls. ``I thought, `How did Chad get in those
pictures?' It was so confusing.
 &HT;    ``Then my father came home on a short leave from the service,
and his only son catches a glimpse of him and goes outside to hide
in the bushes.''
 &HT;    The elder Fonda was a remote, emotionally distant man who rarely
spoke to his children and was capable of going through with a
Broadway performance in 1950 only hours after learning that his
wife _ Peter's mother _ had killed herself.
 &HT;    ``We had no service, no funeral for my mother. We didn't talk
about it,'' Fonda says. ``It was like it didn't happen.''
 &HT;    Despite his difficulty relating to his father, the actor says,
they had come to terms by the time Henry Fonda died in 1982.
 &HT;    ``There's no more baggage _ it has been cleared away,'' he says.
``The last words my father said on this planet were `Son, I love
you very much.' So that was rather cool. I wasn't happy that he
died, but he was in pain and he didn't cotton to living that way.
And I'm glad, at the end, we came to some understanding.''
 &HT;    A gift from Crockett on his 35th birthday was a turning point
for Fonda.
 &HT;    ``This woman I eventually married gave me her childhood copy of
`Stuart Little,''' he recalls. ``She didn't know that my love of
Stuart was one of my biggest childhood fears. I refused to even
tell Jane that I loved Stuart, because I thought she would make fun
of me.
 &HT;    ``Stuart was my hero,'' Fonda says. ``He was born into a
seemingly normal family, but it was tough. He longed to be part of
a normal family. I felt like that mouse.''
 &HT;    That dogeared book told the actor all he needed to know.
 &HT;    ``I knew this was the person I was supposed to love for the rest
of my life,'' he says. ``Take one look at my wife, and you know
that I've got bragging rights here.''
 &HT;    His own past has given Fonda his share of ghosts, but nothing
too grim, he adds.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't an angel,'' he says. ``But I never had an addictive
personality. I never did cocaine. I watched too many friends get
addicted or die. I think I was rather lucky to escape those times
in one piece, because so many others lost so much.''
 &HT;    He's tried to have the kind of relationship with his children
that he always wished he had with his father, and has become
especially close to his daughter in recent years.
 &HT;    ``We're tough on each other,'' he says. ``We also listen. I'll
get a call from Bridget, who will say, `Dad, I've had it with that
makeup person! And if they put me in that water tank one more time,
I'll scream!'
 &HT;    ``Then she will say, `Oh, gosh, Dad, all I've been doing is
unloading on you,''' he says. ``I'll say, `My dear, who better to
unload on?'''
 &HT;    The Fondas gathered en masse at Jane's home in Atlanta for the
Fourth of July, and Peter Fonda reports that he put some concerted
effort into talking his sister into returning to moviemaking in the
wake of her impending divorce from media mogul Ted Turner.
 &HT;    ``The first move is already made,'' he says cheerfully. ``Jane
said she was interested in perhaps acting in a great play in
Atlanta _ that's just a hop and skip away from doing a film.
Bridget and I have both said we would love to work with her.
 &HT;    ``I'd want to direct her,'' Fonda adds. ``It would be really
stylin', right out there, for us Fondas to do a project together.''
 &HT;    As for Turner, Fonda doesn't have much to say.
 &HT;    ``I liked Ted. I'm kind of feeling `shame on him' now,'' Fonda
says, his voice heated for the first time all morning. ``I told
Ted, when he married my sister, how important it was for someone to
`be on Jane's bond.' That's a saying that means there's someone
there for you until the end.''
 &HT;    Family is the center of his own life, Fonda says. But that
doesn't mean that he's chained to his power mower. Every now and
then, he admits, he likes to get out onto the highway for some
serious biking.
 &HT;    ``If someone recognizes me on a Harley, they smile and wave,''
he says. ``They yell, `Keep doing it, man!'''
 &HT;    Still, no one is likely to mistake him for Captain America these
days.
 &HT;    ``I don't like to ride fast,'' he says. ``I like to cruise. I
take a fly rod, just in case I pass a brook that needs to be
fished. But I don't keep the fish _ I release them. Live and let
live, man.''
 &HT;    As for his career, don't ever expect Fonda to retire to Montana
once and for all.
 &HT;    ``I want to die hearing, `That's a wrap, buddy,''' the actor
says. ``I want people to whisper, `What happened to Fonda? Oh, he
died right when the curtain dropped and the show was over.'
 &HT;    ``Now, that's an exit.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Thomas and the Magic
Railroad,'' consult the official Web site at www.magicrailroad.com.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
