<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS18-COX     07-17 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Entertaining convention delegates falls to Big Business
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - It'll be party time in more ways than one when the
Republicans meet in Philadelphia and the Democrats in Los Angeles.
Because the nominees of each political party already are shoo-ins,
entertaining the delegates becomes the No. 1 priority of convention
planners, Business Week (July 24) says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is Big Business coughing up most of the $95 million
that Philadelphia and Los Angeles need to put on the conventions,
but it's also shelling out millions to host hundreds of
invitation-only bashes that give execs and lobbyists face time with
elected officials and power brokers,'' the magazine reports.
</P>
<P>
   To Common Cause and other watchdog groups, the conventions have
evolved into the Super Bowl of Lobbying, well out of the public
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Looking abroad
</P>
<P>
   After five fat years, we finally see that markets also go down,
Money (August) says in its midyear investing guide. Since tech
stocks have fizzled, the best places to look for winners in the
next round of stock investing are overseas and in wireless
technology, Money says.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds (August) agrees in its midyear forecast, suggesting
that ``as the new century unfolds, the focus on hot funds may be
spinning toward Europe. Germany's Deutsche European Equity was the
No. 1 mutual fund in the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild, wild Wall Street
</P>
<P>
   The worst that most financial analysts get when they lower their
stock ratings or earnings forecasts is a growl of disappointment
from shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Barron's (July 17) says Jonathan Joseph of Salomon Smith
Barney got a more hostile response after he lowered his forecast
for popular semiconductor stocks _ a series of death threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the folks at Salomon took the threats rather
lightheartedly,'' says Barron's. ``But the eerie e-mail and
telephone messages persisted, and giggles gave way to bodyguards.''
</P>
<P>
   The millennial generation
</P>
<P>
   The newest generation _ the millennial, which began in the 1980s
_ has grown up with prosperity, the Internet, high divorce rates
and high school violence. And according to a Fortune (July 31)
survey, they don't want to live or work the way their parents do.
</P>
<P>
   They ``assume that jobs and money will be available as needed
and that they will be able to indulge in luxury that few of their
parents could; they don't want to be consumed by work ... and they
view their friends as their strongest role models and support
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoils to the winners
</P>
<P>
   Smart Business (August), meanwhile, has found role models for
Fortune's millenial generation: stock market winners.
</P>
<P>
   The market has created more than $8 trillion in wealth during
the past five years. So what are these new millionaires and
billionaires spending it on? On $300,000 watches, $95,000 Cellini
sapphire brooches and $4,000 bottles of champagne, among other
``toys for the super rich,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
