</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENRY-SIMMONS-IN-NYPD-BLUE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE `BLUE': HENRY SIMMONS ADJUSTS TO LIFE ON `NYPD BLUE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Henry Simmons in a scene from ``NYPD
Blue.'') 
 By KEN CARRIERE  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before July 30. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born to be blue?
</P>
<P>
   Some television cops are born, others are made _ and to judge by
his childhood memories, ``NYPD Blue's'' Henry Simmons is one of the
former, a fact that has been apparent since he was 5 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember running around, pretending to be on a SWAT team,''
the 30-year-old, 6-foot-4-inch actor says. ``My favorite shows were
`Starsky and Hutch' and `S.W.A.T.,' which nobody remembers.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, Simmons is still running around and
pretending to be a cop, but he's got a lot more people watching.
Last season, he joined Steven Bochco's long-running police drama
``NYPD Blue'' as the mysterious Det. Baldwin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   So far, little has been revealed about Baldwin's background and
personal life, except that he's very even-tempered. That makes him
a natural contrast to series star Dennis Franz's character, the
explosive Det. Andy Sipowicz, but not all that far from the
levelheaded Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baldwin doesn't let anger rule him,'' Simmons says. ``I try to
live that way, as well. Adversity and hurdles challenge us and make
us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, fresh out of college, Simmons landed a good
job with a prosperous financial firm. The only problem was, it took
only a week for him to realize that he wouldn't be happy in a Wall
Street career. He wasn't sure what he wanted to do _ only that
business wasn't it _ so on a whim, spurred by the pleasure he'd
gotten out of a college acting class, he decided to try his hand as
an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured, I'm young, I'm not married, I have no
responsibilities,'' he recalls. ``I'm gonna go for it!''
</P>
<P>
   Some early stage work led to Simmons' big-screen debut, in a bit
part in the not-especially-well-received basketball flick ``Above
the Rim'' (1994). Television proved more hospitable, however, with
guest spots on such series as ``New York Undercover'' and ``The
Cosby Mysteries'' giving the young actor hope that he could make a
go of his chosen profession.
</P>
<P>
   His first regular gig followed not long afterward _ a recurring
role on the popular daytime soap opera ``Another World.'' He stayed
for two years, until he got the chance to move into prime time with
``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Baldwin Jones wasn't a slam dunk, however. It isn't easy
to join an established show, vying for writers' attention with fan
favorites such as Franz. Moreover, Simmons found himself under
something of a microscope, because he was stepping into the shoes
of another fan favorite, Nicholas Turturro, who had left the show
after a full six seasons on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the actor says, the esprit de corps of the ``NYPD
Blue'' cast helped. It didn't hurt that Rick Schroder's
near-simultaneous arrival, stepping in for the departing Jimmy
Smits, took some of the heat off Simmons. Furthermore, the show's
producers and cast were used to the problems of assimilating new
actors, and went out of their way to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I wasn't nervous at all,'' Simmons says. ``My fellow
cast members helped me along.''
</P>
<P>
   Solidly in his corner was Franz, who has played the troubled
Sipowicz since the show debuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is like a family here,'' Simmons says, ``and Dennis
is the center of it. He just exudes confidence, and there's
something paternal about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since its first episode, ``NYPD Blue'' has been the edgiest
series on network television, with nudity and very gritty story
lines, not to mention a large cast whose complicated histories
aren't easy to keep straight. It's a tough show for an actor to
integrate himself into, but Simmons feels he's succeeded in doing
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of that,'' he says. ``You can't be a casual viewer _
you really have to be vested in the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case last year, the next season of ``NYPD Blue''
won't begin until January 2001. Last season, ABC's decision to push
the show back to make room for ``Once and Again'' _ which became a
hit _ prompted threats and posturing on both sides, with producer
Bochco going so far as to talk of taking the show to a different
network.
</P>
<P>
   However, a two-year ABC renewal has soothed feelings on both
sides, and now Simmons views the entire experience positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it worked out, it was to our benefit,'' the actor
says. ``We would go through 22 episodes in 22 weeks, without
reruns. Often `NYPD Blue' was the only show on that wasn't a rerun
_ which may have helped the series to its best ratings since
1996-97.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken Carriere is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``NYPD Blue,'' consult the
official Web site at www.nypdblue.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
