<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, July 18. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-PRIVACY-REGULATE (Washington) _ With concern growing among
lawmakers and privacy groups about a new FBI system that easily
intercepts and searches private e-mail, the White House on Monday
proposed legislation to set legal standards for surveillance in
cyberspace similar to those required for telephone wiretaps. By
Stephen Labaton and Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ As the Camp David peace summit
meeting moved closer to the supposed deadline of President
Clinton's Wednesday morning departure for Japan, the White House
remained officially committed Monday to reaching ``an agreement''
before then. But some U.S., Israeli and Palestinian officials began
deliberately lowering expectations for a breakthrough, even
suggesting that there may need to be additional summit meetings. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ The Frommer's guide to France may be
made up of chapters and maps, but most readers know it as an
indivisible and coherent whole: a book. This fall, that book and a
few hundred others will take a new form on the Internet. They will
be sold in component parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _
that can be mixed and matched. Readers will be invited to create
customized books by picking pieces of content a la carte from an
array of already-published guides. Buyers will have the option of
receiving their books electronically or ordering them printed,
bound and delivered to their door. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP (Washington) _ When George W. Bush is asked
what factors he is seeking in his running-mate, he talks about
things like preparedness to be president and compatibility. But he
never mentions the one factor that several of his advisers say is
hovering over his entire selection process: abortion. This is the
first presidential campaign in which the Republican candidate can
talk about picking a running mate who supports abortion rights and
not be laughed off stage. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Based on the frenzied
pace of speculative construction here this summer and the frazzled
lives of craftsmen doing the building, the Hamptons have never
before been invaded by so many rich people wanting to be wowed and
demanding that it happen fast. The invasion has jacked construction
costs to record levels, seduced builders, architects and even
carpenters to build houses on ``spec,'' choked roads with commuting
workmen and encouraged subcontractors to insist on bonuses merely
for showing up on time. It also has enriched and exhausted nearly
everyone willing to drive a nail, paint a wall or dig a swimming
pool. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-APPLE-GROWERS (Milton, N.Y.) _ Poor weather and a number of
economic forces, from depressed apple prices to spotty insurance
coverage to consumer demand for flawless fruit, have pushed New
York's Hudson Valley apple farmers to the brink. Many are wondering
aloud whether the 10-minute hail bursts in May and June will be the
straws that finally broke them _ and in the process altering an
austere landscape of gnarled trees and open sky forever. As the
apple growers band together to ask the federal government for
direct cash assistance of $20 million to cover their losses, they
are talking as much about open space and suburban sprawl as
agriculture, speaking a language they know resonates with
politicians, tourists and the many owners of weekend houses here in
Ulster County, the second largest apple producing county in the
state. By Lisa W. Foderaro.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
