<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-WEAR18-COX     07-17 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WEAR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke plans line of clothing in Europe to drive future beverage
sales
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Coca-Cola wants more Europeans to wear what they drink
and drink what they wear.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant will announce today that it
plans to sell a line of casual wear and sports-inspired clothing in
both Eastern and Western Europe. Currently, the line of clothes is
primarily sold in the United Kingdom, with a sprinkling of sales in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes wholesale sales in continental Europe will
build to $500 million between next spring, when the clothes become
available in stores, and 2009.
</P>
<P>
   But Coke is not teaming up with Fashion Box of Italy to enter
the apparel business. Instead, it hopes the clothes, which it is
licensing to Fashion Box to distribute, will connect with young
consumers and drive future beverage sales in those key markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many countries in the world, Coke is considered cool, and
this serves two purposes,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher
of Beverage Digest. ``It gives young people the chance to wear
clothing that they think will be fun and interesting, and it gives
Coke yet another chance to reinforce the visibility of its flagship
brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Williams, Coca-Cola's director of merchandise services for
Greater Europe, said the company is ``reacting to and feeding off
of what consumers have been telling us in the U.K. They connect
with the clothes. The whole idea is to make it affordable and
reflective of our brand. ... This is a marketing asset. This builds
... an experience with the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   That experience is designed to be a subtle one, Williams said.
Research in the United Kingdom among teen-agers and young adults
told Coca-Cola and Fashion Box to downplay the Coke logo on the
clothes, which include shirts, jeans and hooded sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of the clothes don't even have Coca-Cola written
on the outside of the garment. Instead a ``dynamic ribbon''
symbolizing the company is used, but this icon is far less known to
consumers than the likes of the Nike swoosh or Ralph Lauren polo
player.
</P>
<P>
   On some garments, ``Enjoy Coca-Cola'' is written in Korean, even
though the items are not sold in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers told us they would connect better with clever and
quirky, as opposed to overt branding,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman
Scott Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   On other clothes, Jacobson said, there is just a small
silhouette of a Coke bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
