<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HEALTH-FEATURES-BUDGE     07-17 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-FEATURES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   (The following ``separate buy'' articles from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, are available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN ON AUTO ASSEMBLY LINES HAVE MORE RISK OF BREAST CANCER
</P>
<P>
   ASSEMBLY-LINE-CANCER-NYTSF _ Women who put together America's
cars may be up to 20 percent likelier to get breast cancer than
other women, say preliminary results of a study. The exposure of
automotive assembly line workers to metalworking fluids over time
increased their chances of getting the disease, but the
environmental epidemiologists who did the study, are quick to add
that this does not prove a cause-and-effect relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say that exposure to metalworking fluids is the
cause of disease. We can say there is a statistical association,''
says Deborah Thompson, a doctoral student in the University of
Massachusett's Department of Work Environment. The final study
results are being completed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers think that toxic components -- like polyaromatic
hydrocarbons, biocides, nitrosamines and chlorinated paraffins --
in the metalworking fluids react with the female hormonal system,
elevating the risk of breast cancer. In this scenario, the fluids
behave like estrogen and attach themselves to cells in the fatty
breast tissue.
</P>
<P>
   By Fran Berger, HealthScout. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVASTATION OF FETAL ALCOHOL SYNDROME
</P>
<P>
   FETAL-ALCOHOL-SYNDROME-NYTSF _ Seventeen years ago, when Linda
LaFever was eight months pregnant, she went on a drinking binge.
For two weeks, she drank a half bottle of vodka a day. Five years
later, she learned the price of that binge. A panel of experts told
her that her son, Daniel, with an IQ of 58, had fetal alcohol
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``My world stopped. It took about three seconds to link those
words. I picked up my child and put him on my lap and rocked him,''
LaFever recalls. ``I'm still trying to get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Daniel is a 17-year-old whose high school curriculum in
Hawaii includes learning to make his own bed and doing laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time alcohol is mixed in with pregnancy, it's going to
cause some damage,'' LaFever says. ``Don't think it can't happen to
your child. And when it happens to your child, it happens to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetal alcohol syndrome is a diagnosis that means a child will
probably suffer stunted growth and facial deformities, attention
and behavior problems, and, in some cases, mental retardation.
Worst of all, it's a diagnosis that's never outgrown; adults with
the syndrome will never function normally.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a diagnosis that's becoming increasingly common -- up
six-fold since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By Julia McNamee Neenan, HealthScout. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETES USE HYPOXIC TRAINING FOR UPCOMING OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   HYPOXIC-TRAINING-NYTSF _ Spencer Duval doesn't want to go to the
mountains, so he brings the mountains to him. Well, at least the
high altitudes. Duval, 30, is a British runner training for the
2000 Olympic Games in Sydney by sleeping in a hypoxic tent -- set
up in his own bedroom -- to recreate the lower oxygen levels of a
high-altitude mountainous atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who will represent Britain in the 3,000-meter
steeplechase, started sleeping in the tent last November and will
continue using it until the Olympics. The tent, although not
air-tight, is attached to a small generator that pumps in levels of
oxygen that match an atmosphere of 9,000 feet above sea level.
That's equal to about three-quarters of the way up Mont Blanc in
the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   While he sleeps, Duval's body acclimatizes to the lower oxygen
levels by producing more red blood cells. The increase in red blood
cells increases oxygen flow to his muscles, delaying the onset of
fatigue and improving performance.
</P>
<P>
   Tests at the University of Staffordshire's Sports Performance
Center by sports scientist Steve Day showed that Duval's body is 10
percent more efficient now than before he started using the hypoxic
tent.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Preidt, HealthScout. 600 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
