<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-TV-2TAKE     07-17 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-TV-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH OVERCAME RESISTANCE TO EXPORT `MILLIONAIRE' AND
`SURVIVOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is a game show, the other a pseudo-survival test on a desert
island, but in terms of impact on American culture, ABC's ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and CBS's ``Survivor'' qualify as
another British invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in terms of paternity if not artistry, Michael Davies,
the British-born executive producer of ``Millionaire,'' said,
``It's actually a pretty good analogy: `Millionaire' as the Beatles
and `Survivor' as the Rolling Stones.'' Both ``Millionaire'' and
``Survivor'' are 100 percent British-made television ideas, and
Davies had a hand in bringing both shows to American audiences.
</P>
<P>
   They are also providing a bit of cultural revenge for the
British, who have lately felt disrespected and mistreated by
American films like ``The Patriot'' and ``U-571.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``Millionaire'' has been widely told in the last
year as that game show has gradually colonized much of prime time.
``Millionaire,'' turned down for two years by the ITV network in
Britain, went on the air there in late 1998 and was an instant hit.
But it was the expansion to the United States and myriad other
outposts that stamped the show as possibly England's most
successful cultural export in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit like the old days of the British empire,'' said
Paul Smith, managing director of the British production company
Celador, which came up with the game show. ``We've got a map of the
world in the office colored in pink where we've placed the show.
Most of the world is pink.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is the scruffier newcomer, and its roots are less
well known, largely because the show never got onto British
television. Instead ``Survivor'' went through one of the longest
gestation periods of any breakthrough television show. It took 12
years, during which it was rejected by every network in Britain and
two in the United States, before it finally emerged into the
relative obscurity of Swedish television.
</P>
<P>
   The show made it principally because of the commitment of its
creative team, a threesome that includes an Irish rock singer, the
leading producer of what the British press call ``yoof TV'' (as in
``Youth TV'') and the youngest life peer in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   The latter, surely the first member of the House of Lords to
bring a hit television show to American television, is Waheed Alli,
35. Alli was the principal business executive of Planet 24, a
television production company responsible for often controversial
but usually successful British shows. These included ``The Big
Breakfast,'' in which the anchor, Paula Yates, often interviewed
guests from her bed; ``The Word,'' a music- and occasionally
raunch-filled late-night show; and ``Gaytime TV,'' a magazine show
about gay life that critics described as ``deliberately
frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   The rock star is 45-year-old Bob Geldof, the organizer of the
``Live Aid'' benefits for famine relief in Africa. But by all
accounts the chief creative force in the team is Charlie Parsons,
42, a longtime producer and creator of shows and a man Davies calls
``the brightest guy I've ever been around in television.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons and Alli, partners in life as well as in business, have
contributed media advice to Prime Minister Tony Blair and are known
for lavish Christmas parties on their estate in Kent, attended by
many of the most prominent members of the Labor government. Alli is
famously press shy, reputedly having given only one interview in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Parsons says, Alli divides his time between his political
duties in the House of Lords and his duties as a television
executive. ``It's a bit mad,'' Parsons said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, after the years of waiting, it is gratifying to
own the hottest show in television.
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of lucrative. Parsons, Alli and Geldof divided
about $20 million when they sold Planet 24 to Carlton Television a
year ago. And thanks to Parsons' insistence on excluding the
``Survivor'' concept from that sale, the partners stand to reap
another big payoff.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
