<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0718-C     07-17 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0718-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS TIME RUNS DOWN ON SUMMIT, CLINTON PRESSES FOR PEACE DEAL
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ With time running out before his planned
Wednesday departure for Tokyo, President Clinton hunkered down with
Israeli and Palestinian leaders Monday for a seventh straight day
of Camp David peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   With no outward signs of a peace agreement in sight, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said negotiators from both sides would
likely be working into the morning Tuesday in an effort to strike a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties understand the schedule here,'' Lockhart said.
``The pace and the intensity has quickened.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid speculation that Clinton could delay his departure for the
G8 summit in Okinawa to shepherd the parties the final painful
steps toward a peace accord, the White House sought to use his
schedule as a deadline to force negotiators into the vice of
decision-making that would make or break a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who said Sunday that no agreement was in view, was
still hopeful that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak would resolve the issues at the core of
their 52-year bloody dispute by the time Air Force One is slated to
take off Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that when the president leaves,'' Lockhart said,
``the parties will have wrapped up their business.''
</P>
<P>
   With the two sides still reportedly far apart on key issues,
though, Lockhart declined to rule out the possibility that the
president might postpone his departure for Japan, where he is to
meet with his counterparts in the so-called Group of Eight big
democratic powers _ Britain, Japan, Germany, Italy, France, Canada,
the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I know is that the president intends to get on a plane
Wednesday morning to go and fulfill his requirements as an
important leader in the G8,'' Lockhart said. Leaving open the
prospect that Clinton's departure could slip, though, he said,
``You'll know that we're following through on the schedule when you
see the president walk up to the top of the steps and wave and the
door close.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has some leeway.
</P>
<P>
   He's scheduled to arrive in Tokyo Thursday afternoon for a
bilateral meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   If he postponed that meeting _ there's little on the agenda _
Clinton could depart Thursday morning and still arrive in Okinawa,
the southernmost island in the Japanese archipelago, by Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 summit is to begin in Okinawa Friday afternoon. Clinton
is scheduled to preside over a memorial service there Friday
morning for the Americans and Japanese killed there during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began the day Monday meeting with Barak, then held
strategy sessions with his top Mideast aides throughout much of the
afternoon in preparation for an evening meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations on core issues such as territory and security,
the future of Jerusalem and the question of Palestinian statehood
stretched deeper into the night, parties to the talks were
beginning to show signs of wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   The White House released a photograph Monday showing U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, with dark circles under her
eyes, holding the hand of Arafat as the two listened intently to
his interpreter while strolling through the darkness of the
presidential retreat in the Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Albright appeared to be steadying the aging Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult coming continually back to the same issues with
the same people,'' said Lockhart. ``That kind of environment is not
always the best for the warm and fuzzies.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
