<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-TV-2NDTA     07-17 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-TV-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: big payoff.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea for ``Survivor'' came up in 1988, Parsons said, in a
segment for one of his earlier creations, ``Network 7.'' He was
looking for something ``cutting edge,' he said, something that
hadn't been tried before. So Parsons dumped four participants,
including a tennis star and an ex-convict, onto an island with
cameras recording their efforts to survive together. He refined the
idea until he had the current format: 16 people, lots of tests and
games, a vote to eliminate teammates and one winner.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a buyer was the tough part. No British television entity
was interested. But Parsons had a British connection in American
television: Davies. Shortly after graduating from the University of
Edinburgh, Davies started out in Hollywood writing for the game
show ``Let's Make a Deal.'' By the time Parsons called, Davies was
an executive at Buena Vista Television, the production arm of Walt
Disney. He was, in Parsons' words, ``very keen on `Survivor.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davies pitched the show around and won some interest at both ABC
and Fox. This was 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pretty interesting reputation in those days,'' Davies
said. ``I'd go around and there'd be these raised eyebrows: `What's
this crazy Brit going to come up with today?'''
</P>
<P>
   At ABC Stu Bloomberg, then executive vice president for
entertainment, was enthusiastic about the island survival show.
``Stu really got it,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that there was no pilot, and there could be no
pilot for such a series. So Davies took $150,000 in development
money from Bloomberg and built a model of the island. The show was
never picked up.
</P>
<P>
   It might have ended there if another British expatriate had not
dropped himself into the scene: Mark Burnett, a former paratrooper
and outdoorsman, had developed ``Eco-Challenge,'' an
environmentally correct adventure road race for MTV. Burnett's
background is deep in adventurism, starting with his decision to
join the elite British Parachute Regiment at 18, and when he heard
the concept, he campaigned to acquire the American rights. ``He
always kept hustling for it,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no American network would bite. So Alli and Parsons sold
the idea to Swedish television under the title ``Expedition
Robinson,'' as in ``Swiss Family.'' Now they had proof of how the
concept worked on television. The only problem was that the first
participant to be kicked off the island committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Davies, by then at ABC as executive in charge of alternative
series, was worried about the suicide but ``I had so much faith in
Mark Burnett as a producer that I sent him to Disney.'' There the
concept was enthusiastically supported by Lloyd Braun, the head of
Disney's production company.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point that another television idea percolating in
Britain dropped unexpectedly onto Davies' doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   In London a friend of Davies, Duncan Gray, who worked for the
ITV network, attended the first taping of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and immediately sent off a tape to Davies. ``I said
to myself, This is the best quiz show format, perhaps the best
format, I have ever seen,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the networks had for decades disdained game shows in
prime time, mainly because they were thought to attract older
viewers, Davies sent tapes of the show around ABC corporate
meetings. Bloomberg again was enthusiastic. So was Michael Eisner,
the Disney chairman. ``I got this e-mail from Michael saying
something like, `I'm not sure if I'm embarrassed by this, but I
really, really like this program.'''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the biggest hurdles was the format established in
Britain, where the show played 13 nights in a row.
</P>
<P>
   That tournament-style format was one of the show's great assets,
Smith said. And it was far more typical of British television,
which does not depend on yearly runs of 22-episodes, to break away
from the traditional once-a-week series format.
</P>
<P>
   Davies needed a crosscultural breakthrough. He brought in
another key player, Ben Silverman, an agent with the William Morris
Agency who had been living in London and watching British
television for four years. ``I needed somebody on the ground in
London to explain the difference between American and British
television to Paul,'' Davies said, speaking of Paul Smith,
Celador's managing director.
</P>
<P>
   With Silverman's help, Smith made the deal with ABC. Davies then
made a decision of his own. He quit his executive job at the
network to become the executive producer of ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' still had no American home, though Burnett had
promising negotiations going with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that in some quarters of ABC there wasn't enough
passion for `Survivor,''' Davies said. ``And I wondered whether we
could launch `Millionaire' and `Survivor' in the same year.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS stepped up. ``All credit to CBS for taking on the risk,''
Parsons said. The show went on CBS in June and eclipsed last
summer's ``Millionaire'' ratings, especially among younger viewers,
whom CBS had not been able to reach with any other programming.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Davies said, he is glad to be part of the
trend toward ``globalization of television concepts.''
``Millionaire'' is a hit in 29 countries and has sold in 50 more.
`Survivor' is already sold in Germany, Argentina, Denmark and Spain
and expectations are that with the American success, it will sell
far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago,'' Davies said, ``if I had said the two biggest
things in television are going to be a young-skewing show on CBS
that's a reality concept based on a British-created Swedish
television program produced by a former British paratrooper and
part owned by a member of Parliament, and a prime-time quiz show
hosted by Regis Philbin, that would have been an inconceivable
notion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``It is even more inconceivable that American
television had completely boxed itself in, that everybody thought
television was only dramas, sitcoms and news magazines. I think
it's fantastic now that everybody's thinking, What can we do
next?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
