<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4772 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-O'NEIL-NEW-PLAYWRIGHT     07-17 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'NEIL-NEW-PLAYWRIGHTS-1030(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOMING NEW IDEAS INTO A PLAYWRIGHTS' NEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn. N.Y.)   By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERFORD, Conn. _ For 35 summers, the National Playwrights
Conference has been the tall ship of the Eugene O'Neill Theater
Center, giving a berth to hundreds of new plays and new
playwrights. This year there is a major difference: James Houghton
as the new artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton, 41, the founder and director of the Signature Theater
Company, has succeeded Lloyd Richards, 80, the first, and until
now, the only head of the conference commonly known as ``the
O'Neill.'' Looking ahead, Houghton said, ``The O'Neill is about to
be born again.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first season at the conference Houghton is trying to put
the emphasis even more firmly on the writers, and he has made small
but significant alterations. For the first time, all the writers
are living on the O'Neill ``campus'' for the month of their
residency instead of being boarded at a nearby college, and they
are encouraged to bring their families with them.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, playwrights were very much in evidence in
the grand O'Neill environment, an elegant estate with a green lawn
leading down to Long Island Sound. The writers were in rehearsals
or staged readings, talking to members of the staff or simply
meeting their colleagues and comparing notes about their plays in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, there were critical forums following the readings,
with directors, dramaturges and critics (from the National Critics
Institute, an adjunct of the conference) speaking out about the
plays while the playwrights were asked to remain silent. In some
cases the result was a wounded playwright. Now there are no longer
such sessions. Criticism of the work may be offered privately and
informally.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting the audience at the opening event of the monthlong
conference, a staged reading of ``Parts Unknown,'' a new play by
Ron Fitzgerald, Houghton spoke about ``the need to take the time
and to have the patience to allow the writers to create.'' He said
that when the process works, ``it elevates us all.''
</P>
<P>
   John Henry Redwood, one of this year's playwrights, was at the
O'Neill in 1995 with ``The Old Settler,'' which was later presented
at Primary Stages in New York City. Looking back on his first
residency, he said, ``It served me, and it served the play.'' His
new play, about the rape of a black woman by a white man in North
Carolina in 1949, has the provocative title ``No Niggers, No Jews,
No Dogs.'' Redwood, who is black, said he was aware that the title
might present problems for any theater producing the work.
Informally, he was referring to it as ``The No Play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the limited rehearsal time he had not done much work on it,
but the actors (Tonya Pinkins and Ruben Santiago Hudson) and David
Esbjornson, as director, were adding their touches. The playwright
said he would be seeing the results that evening when the play had
the first of two readings.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night theatergoers, some from Boston, some from New
York, many of them from the O'Neill center and the surrounding
area, filled the bleachers in the outdoor theater, named the Edith
in memory of Edith Oliver, the longtime Off-Broadway critic for The
New Yorker and an O'Neill dramaturge.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton made his introductory remarks, again stressing that the
conference was for the playwrights. Then on an open stage under a
large tree Redwood's play began. After the performance, as is
customary at the O'Neill, the actors did not take a curtain call.
But the audience, realizing that the playwright was seated in a
rear row, rose, turned and applauded him.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward there was no critical forum, no outsiders dissecting a
writer's work, but Redwood has the option of private conversations
with his director, Houghton or others. Then, in the O'Neill
tradition, he can go back to work on his new play.
</P>
<P>
   Each year at this conference a dozen or more plays go through a
period of brief but intensive rehearsal and then have public
readings on the various stages. Many of the plays have gone on to
great success, beginning with the work of August Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   George C. White created the center in 1964, leasing 8{ acres of
the former Hamman Estate. The next year, with Richards, he began
the playwrights conference. The center itself also includes a music
theater conference, a symposium on cabaret, the National Theater
Institute and the Monte Cristo Cottage, Eugene O'Neill's childhood
home in nearby New London. White, 64, is retiring at the end of
this year, to be succeeded as executive director by Howard Sherman,
38, the managing director of the Geva Theater in Rochester. During
White's years in Waterford, the O'Neill has inspired similar
conferences in other states and also in Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Houghton said that he admired the pioneer work
of Richards and White, but he also made it clear that he was aware
of his position as a new artistic director in a new century. He
said that his first responsibility was ``to empower the
playwrights, to give writers a place where they can explore their
plays in a relatively safe environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In various developmental programs ``there are too many chefs in
the mix way too soon,'' he said. ``I'm trying to take the emphasis
away from fixing and doctoring plays and to encourage writers to
listen to the impulse that's inside them and to honor that impulse.
Across the country plays are being `developed' to death. I'm
encouraging a notion of play evolution versus play development. I
want to let a play find itself and to let a writer find himself
within a play.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are 13 playwrights at the O'Neill, including
Sarah C. Diamond, who is there with her first full-length play, to
experienced writers like Lee Blessing and Daisy Foote. There are
also several graduates of the playwriting seminar taught by Marsha
Norman and Christopher Durang at the Juilliard School.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years four or five directors would each stage three
plays. Now there are 13 directors, one for each play. Houghton has
also made staff changes, and many of the actors are new to the
O'Neill. There are three special projects, including one (written
by John Belluso and directed by Joseph Chaikin) that dramatizes
experiences of the disabled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Computers have been installed, and a script department helps
playwrights find information. For example, Wendy Hammond, one of
this year's playwrights, needed to clarify a minor point in her
play. She wanted to know if a cell phone could be bugged. After
inquiries were made to the CIA and the FBI, she was quickly given
an affirmative answer.
</P>
<P>
   Some things remain the same. Plays are rehearsed over four days,
and when they are performed, actors carry their scripts onstage.
There is a minimum of modular scenery. The emphasis is on the
process, and during the rest of their time at the conference
playwrights can restudy and reshape their plays. As in the past the
O'Neill is a cross between a festival and an adult summer camp,
with playwrights, actors and directors freely communicating.
Wherever one turns, there is theater talk: over meals, a drink in
the O'Neill pub or a walk across the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier days producers and agents often scouted plays. White
said that there was one stricture. No negotiations were to take
place on the O'Neill grounds: ``If a playwright said, `So and so is
interested in my play, who's interested in yours?' that would ruin
a playwrights conference.'' As before Houghton places no
restriction on who can see the plays; they are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the principal change is in the play selection process,
which has been broadened geographically as well as aesthetically.
In order to ``open this conference up to a national theatrical
landscape,'' Houghton enlisted readers from around the country,
more than 60 theater professionals who read plays without knowing
the names of the authors (always the case at the O'Neill). This
year the process winnowed 750 submissions to 45, which then went
before a selection committee. Every script accepted had been read
by four people. Houghton said that as director he retained the
prerogative to name two writers of his own choice.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton has invited guest artists (Edward Albee, Paula Vogel,
Ed Bullins and Doug Hughes, the head of the Long Wharf Theater in
New Haven) to give seminars. In one session Romulus Linney spoke to
the playwrights about his own choice of material for plays, saying
that even when the subject is historical, it has a relationship to
his own life.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that the playwrights have to take
responsibility for their work. ``You have to decide at what point
you're willing to please people in order to get your play on,'' he
said, ``and at what point you don't care if they do it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   For Linney the Signature Theater was a turning point. After
Houghton had appeared as an actor in one of Linney's plays, he
raised the possibility of producing an entire season of his work in
New York. That was the beginning of the Signature, and it was
followed by seasons of plays by Blessing, Albee, John Guare, Arthur
Miller and others. It was Houghton's work with playwrights at that
company that brought him to the attention of the O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   White said the principal reasons he was chosen to head the
conference were that he was highly recommended by a search
committee of playwrights and other theater professionals and that
he had never been to the O'Neill before. ``I wanted somebody to
come in and see it fresh,'' White said. ``He brought no baggage,
none of this, `It's always been done this way.' '' He added: ``The
O'Neill needed an infusion of youth. There's a new spirit blowing
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
