<HEADER>
A4776 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ASSEMBLY-LINE-CANCER-     07-17 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSEMBLY-LINE-CANCER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ON AUTO ASSEMBLY LINES HAVE MORE RISK OF BREAST CANCER  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY FRAN BERGER  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Women who put together America's cars may be up to 20 percent
likelier to get breast cancer than other women, say preliminary
results of a study.
</P>
<P>
   The exposure of automotive assembly-line workers to metalworking
fluids over time increased their chances of getting the disease,
but environmental epidemiologists at the University of
Massachusetts/Lowell, who did the study, are quick to add that this
does not prove a cause-and-effect relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say that exposure to metalworking fluids is the
cause of disease. We can say there is a statistical association''
between environmental exposure and breast cancer, says Deborah
Thompson, a doctoral student in the University of Massachusett's
Department of Work Environment.
</P>
<P>
   She and a team of researchers did the study, which looked at the
exposure of almost 5,000 women to metalworking fluids between
l940-1996. She received no financing from the auto industry; the
final study results are being completed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers think that toxic components _ like polyaromatic
hydrocarbons, biocides, nitrosamines and chlorinated paraffins _ in
the metalworking fluids react with the female hormonal system,
elevating the risk of breast cancer. In this scenario, the fluids
behave like estrogen and attach themselves to cells in the fatty
breast tissue. Such fluids are commonly used in industrial
workplaces to cool and lubricate parts during machining.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says, ``once they form a bond with the receptors in the
breast, they are absorbed into the cell's nucleus, setting off a
cascade of disregulated growth leading to carcinogenesis.''
</P>
<P>
   These results are the latest to come out of this entire group of
50,000 auto workers (45,000 are men). Previous studies on this
whole group have linked them to a risk of cancers of the larynx,
esophagus and pancreas. In Thompson's study, they only looked at
women and also took into account the family history of breast
cancer, lifestyle and whether they had children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated a negative study and were surprised to find an
association between environmental pollutants and breast cancer,''
she says. They measured the risk by calculating how much of these
compounds were in the air and found that when they reached a
certain amount, the risk increased 20 percent. That amount was a
milligram of metalworking fluid per cubic meter of air per year,
and was added up over time to arrive at a risk level.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer is the most common cancer among women in the U.S.
More than 180,000 women will be diagnosed with it this year, and
more than 40,000 will die of it this year, according to the
American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like there may be a lot of hazardous things out
there in the workplace and the environment that might put us at
risk, not just for breast cancer, but for other hormonally related
cancers, for example, ovarian and prostate,'' she Thompson. The
difficulty lies in how to measure these hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson added that this study, as others before it, was done
with permission from the United Auto Workers Union (UAW) and
General Motors (GM), both of which have formed a scientific board
to evaluate the worth of each piece of research. Despite repeated
phone calls over two weeks, neither the UAW nor GM would respond to
questions from HealthSCOUT.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Mullen, executive director of the Women's Informational
Network Against Breast Cancer in San Diego, embraces the results of
this study and sees it as indicating there may be even broader
problems. Pesticides and other chemicals _ in the water we drink
and the air we breathe _ have been linked to cancer, she says. And
cancer rates are rising. ``Everywhere you look, somebody's been
impacted, and we have to look at the big picture _ the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's study was funded by the Massachusetts Department of
Public Health Breast Cancer Research Program.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
