<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DELTA-LATAM18-COX     07-17 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-LATAM18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta set to add Bogota service in December
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Delta Air Lines announced Monday it will start flights
between Atlanta and Bogota, Colombia, Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That will be in addition to three other routes from Atlanta to
Mexico and South America that Delta already is set to launch:
Santiago, Chile, Nov. 1; Leon, Mexico Oct. 1; and Los Cabos,
Mexico, Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Delta subsidiary Atlantic Southeast Airlines also is starting
regional jet flights between Atlanta and Monterrey, Mexico, Sept.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The new routes continue Delta's 2-year effort to build service
to Latin America, a region where it previously had no significant
presence. The strategy hinges on drawing travelers from the eastern
United States through Delta's Atlanta hub. Most Latin-bound traffic
flows through Miami, where American has a hub.
</P>
<P>
   When all the announced new flights are added, Atlanta-based
Delta will serve 15 destinations in Mexico, Central America and
South America from Atlanta, an increase from four at the beginning
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Bogota flights are allowed under a new U.S.-Colombia air
treaty that allows seven more weekly round trips by a U.S. carrier.
The U.S. Department of Transportation designated Delta in a
preliminary decision. The DOT picked Delta over Continental
Airlines, which proposed serving Cali, Colombia, from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serving Colombia is an integral part of our strategic plan to
expand Delta's overall Latin America presence and to compete more
aggressively in the region,'' said Scott Yohe, senior vice
president-government affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America still accounts for only 3 percent of Delta
revenue, and the airline remains well behind American and
Continental in passenger volume and destinations. But Delta
executives say the region produces a 15 percent profit margin,
higher than the margins achieved by its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that Delta has focused on flying to national
business centers rather than tourist destinations, and more of its
passengers travel on higher, less restrictive fares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
