<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HYPOXIC-TRAINING-NYTS     07-17 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYPOXIC-TRAINING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES USING HYPOXIC TRAINING FOR UPCOMING OLYMPICS  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY ROBERT PREIDT  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Spencer Duval doesn't want to go to the mountains, so he brings
the mountains to him.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least the high altitudes. Duval, 30, is a British
runner training for the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney by sleeping in
a hypoxic tent _ set up in his own bedroom _ to recreate the lower
oxygen levels of a high-altitude mountainous atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like going camping. It takes a couple of days to get
used to it, but after that, it's not a problem. It's like a two-man
tent, but it's got two big clear panels that you can see out of.
It's quite light and airy,'' says Duval, who will represent Britain
in the 3,000-meter steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   He started sleeping in the tent last November and will continue
using it until the Olympics. The tent, although not air-tight, is
attached to a small generator that pumps in levels of oxygen that
match an atmosphere of 9,000 feet above sea level. That's equal to
about three-quarters of the way up Mont Blanc in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   While he sleeps, Duval's body acclimatizes to the lower oxygen
levels by producing more red blood cells. The increase in red blood
cells increases oxygen flow to his muscles, delaying the onset of
fatigue and improving performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to spend a certain number of hours in it each
night _ just whatever time you happen to sleep there. It's the
cumulative effect over a couple of weeks that's the key. If you
just keep using it, then you're going to get the benefits,'' Duval
says.
</P>
<P>
   Tests at the University of Staffordshire's Sports Performance
Center by sports scientist Steve Day showed that Duval's body is 10
percent more efficient now than before he started using the hypoxic
tent.
</P>
<P>
   Day says Duval is one of only two athletes in Britain using the
hypoxic tent, though others around the world are using the
technology and it will probably become more popular. He says this
type of conditioning has no health drawback or hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tried in various formats over the last few years. I
know the East Germans, quite a long time ago ... sealed a house up
and pumped in particular concentrations of oxygen. I believe the
Australians may do something similar, but only on a more high-tech
approach. But in terms of affordability and size, this is a
relatively new approach,'' Day says.
</P>
<P>
   While high-altitude training is known to benefit athletes,
getting to such places is expensive and time-consuming. The hypoxic
tent, which costs about $7,000, means athletes can stay at home to
get the same benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Duval says the hypoxic tent may seem expensive, but it's much
cheaper than having to travel to a high-altitude training center
for three weeks, four or five times each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is fairly expensive and accommodation is fairly
expensive and also, you have the problem of coming down from
altitude to sea level to actually do the training part of the whole
process. This system is incredibly portable and relatively cheap
and enables the athlete to live at home, particularly if the
athlete doesn't have a great deal of sponsorship and needs to work
to support himself. This could be an amazing benefit for them,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of home, Duval says his wife accepts the presence
of the tent in their bedroom at their Stafford home. She's a former
athlete who appreciates the necessities of conditioning and on
occasion will even join Duval in his enclosure, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better me being in the U.K. than being away for weeks at
a time. That's my argument,'' Duval says.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
