r b BC-COUNTRYBOY-TEX     07-17 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYBOY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE BILLY GILMAN, AGE 12, HAS NASHVILLE LISTENING
</HEADLINE>
  (Resending to add slug) 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hi! It's Billy Gilman!''
</P>
<P>
   It's 9 a.m. Monday, and Billy Gilman, the boy wonder of country
music, is on the line _ and sounding very upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   At 12, Gilman's already seen his debut single, ``One Voice,''
hurtle onto ``Billboard'' magazine's country singles chart, and he
replaces Brenda Lee as the youngest artist ever to do so. Just last
week, his debut CD, also titled ``One Voice,'' debuted at No. 4 on
the country charts, vaulting over George Strait, Tim McGraw and
Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   And on the phone, he sounds about ... 9 years old. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the (Grand Ole) Opry and my manager called me and it
was my debut on the Opry and I was `flippin' _ it was really
surprising!'' he says breathlessly about the moment he heard the
news about his single. ``I, like, froze!''
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable. Becoming one of the hottest young stars in
Nashville before you're old enough to shave or drive isn't
something you can prepare for _ although in several ways, the tiny
(4 feet 7 inches), blond-haired Gilman really has been rehearsing
for this nearly all his short life.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up in suburban Providence, R.I., he listened to
Tammy Wynette, George Jones, Eddie Arnold and other classic country
artists. Singing along with a Pam Tillis video led to performing at
local functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wanted to do this when I was 7,'' Gilman says.
``After a show, I was asked if I had ever made a record and I was
like, `I'm 7 years old,' and that was the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a series of introductions, Asleep at the Wheel's Ray
Benson became a fan, and cut a demo with Gilman in Austin, Texas.
Benson then introduced him to to Scott Simon, who manages Tim
McGraw, among others. Blake Chancey, Sony Nashville's senior vice
president of artist and repertoire, flew to Providence, where
Gilman was opening a show for Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing Blake said to us was, `I'm going to play you
this tape _ I want you to talk me out of this,' '' says Michael
Kraski, senior vice president of sales and marketing for Sony
Nashville. ``We couldn't. We weren't looking to sign a child, but
he's not a contrivance. He's a prodigy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``One Voice,'' song and CD, were recorded in short order;
Chancey produced the CD with David Malloy (Reba McEntire, Eddie
Rabbit) and Don Cook (Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Lonestar). No surprises here:
The CD features several tried-and-true pop or country staples,
including Tammy Wynette's ``'Til I Can Make It On My Own'' and
Bobby Goldsboro's ``Little Things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One Voice,'' though, is clearly the standout track. Written by
Malloy and Cook, it's a sentimental pining for the way life used to
be, and should be, complete with references to the golden rule and
kids riding their bikes to school. ``What I'm trying to do with
`One Voice,''' Gilman says earnestly, ``is hopefully get all the
violence out of the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation for Gilman was primed with a well-received
appearance this spring at the Academy of Country Music Awards; when
``One Voice'' charted several weeks ago, Gilman was still 11, so he
edged out Lee, who was 12 when she first made the country charts.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lee, Gilman often edges into rockabilly territory. Unlike
her, though, he has to worry about his voice breaking: On several
tracks, he sounds like a young woman. Is he worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we're looking at that,'' he says. ``But with the proper
voice training, I'll be able to hit the high notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Proper voice training? Do 12-year-olds really talk this way?
Gilman does. He peppers his speech with several such adult phrases;
unlike other young musicians, he is enthusiastic and expansive.
Sony, Kraski says, is betting that his appeal will cut across age
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that show in Providence, grown women were coming up to the
stage and laying bouquets at his feet,'' Kraski says. ``Country is
adult-driven music _ the core audience is a 35-year-old female. We
feel we'll connect with preteen females and moms. But we've found
he has gotten response from dads and teen-age boys _ and teen-age
females.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gilman hasn't even started touring to support his hit. He
doesn't know who he'll be touring with _ there are no Fort
Worth-Dallas dates on the schedule yet _ and these days he's doing
TV shows (he's off to Los Angeles to do ``The Tonight Show With Jay
Leno'') and then starting work on a Christmas CD.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing much, it seems, gets him down, not even after being hit
in the face by a golf ball recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Gilman says. ``I hit a ball right next to a
creek and one kid hit his ball across the river facing the creek.
It hit me right in the mouth. I held my mouth and closed my eyes
and my tooth fell out. It was gross! We put it (the tooth) right in
and it'll take six to eight weeks to heal. I feel great. I'm really
getting back on my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, anyway, nothing seems to slow Gilman down.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
