<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO CAMPAIGN IN CLINTON COUNTRY ON WAY TO CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Ark., Ohio, W.Va., Mo., Pa., Ky.)  (See also BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ With the Republican National Convention two weeks
away, Gov. George W. Bush began trying to build excitement about it
Monday in his playful, teasing manner, saying for the first time
that he was closing in on his selection of a running mate and
letting his advisers dribble out details about the five-day trip he
would make to the event.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday morning in Little Rock, Ark., where
he campaigned before heading here, Bush said that he could no
longer pretend he was not busily winnowing the field of vice
presidential possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of saying the list is shrinking and growing are
over,'' Bush said, with a broad smile, referring to the coy refrain
he has been using to answer questions about his deliberations.
``I'm getting closer to a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor shed no light on what that decision would be,
but the possible timing of it was made clearer in the details that
his advisers released about the trip Bush would make to
Philadelphia, where the four-day convention begins on Monday, July
31.
</P>
<P>
   Karen P. Hughes, the director of communications for the Bush
campaign, said the governor would leave Austin on July 28 and
arrive in Philadelphia on Aug. 2, the day before he formally
receives his party's presidential nomination and makes his
acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also said Bush would probably introduce his running mate
in Austin, which suggested that the announcement would come just
before Bush was scheduled to leave town, perhaps sometime in the
middle of next week. But she added that nothing was confirmed, and
that Bush still had not decided when he would announce his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   The route that Bush will take to the convention, making stops
along the way, will begin in Arkansas, and then move on to
Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the Republican presidential nominee has lost all
five of those states in the last two presidential elections, but
Bush believes he can prevail in each one. Bush's father won all but
West Virginia in winning the 1988 election.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said other states could be added to the trip.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Monday, Bush also repeated a promise that
he and his advisers had already made: that this Republican
convention would not look, feel or sound like previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a convention that is going to have some new
wrinkles to it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to plans to devote each night to a different
theme, to keep the oratory generally upbeat and to skip the
practice of devoting one night to attacks on the other party's
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bush's advisers said Monday that immediately after
the convention the Texas governor would probably travel by train
for several days of whistle-stop campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats, whose national convention will
be in the middle of August, are working to make the spotlight that
these events throw on the political parties and their presidential
nominees last as long as possible. Vice President Al Gore is
expected to campaign by boat through key states in the Midwest
after the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush's news conference in Little Rock, he unveiled a
modest proposal designed to cast himself as an especially
compassionate conservative, and he discussed it briefly at a
private social services agency where he was flanked by several
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that if he were elected president, he would direct the
Department of Health and Human Services to encourage states to set
up registries for the fathers of children born out of wedlock, but
he did not call for any new federal spending to be directed
explicitly toward that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started such a registry in Texas in 1997, and he said it
served one of two benefits, either encouraging fathers to take
responsibility for their children, or making it easier, if these
fathers chose not to do that, to get their children adopted.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush campaigned in Arkansas and Wisconsin on Monday, he also
continued to raise money for the Republican Party, bringing in an
estimated $1.4 million at four events.
</P>
</TEXT>
