<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND: NATIONALIST STEPS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Alex Salmond, leader of the Scottish National Party, said he was
stepping down after 10 years in the post. The party, which
advocates full independence, had been gaining against the ruling
Labor-Liberal Democrat coalition in the new Scottish Parliament,
and the resignation was a surprise. Salmond, 45, said he expected
the nationalists to win the next election three years from now and
he feared that would ``lock'' him in for another decade.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: WOODWARDS ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Louise Woodward, the English au pair convicted of
manslaughter in 1997 in the death of an infant in Massachusetts,
went on trial in Chester accused of forging invoices claiming
$15,400 in rent from her defense fund while they were living free
of charge in Boston during her trial. Gary and Sue Woodward, now
separated, have pleaded not guilty to fraud. The trial is expected
to last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: PROTESTS ON BASQUES
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people across the country marched and
held silent rallies to protest three attacks by the Basque rebel
group ETA in less than a week. The largest protest was in Malaga,
where a suspected ETA gunman shot to death a city councilman. The
group was also blamed for two car-bomb blasts in Madrid and the
northern city of Soria, setting off fears of a new rebel offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIA: PRESIDENT'S LAST TERM
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was disgusted by corruption, President Emil
Constantinescu, 60, said he would not run for re-election this
fall. ``There is a blind fight for personal interests,''
Constantinescu said in a television address. ``People buy and sell
places in the Parliament, using lies and blackmail.''
Constantinescu is trailing in opinion polls behind former President
Ion Iliescu. Elections are expected in November.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: RIGHTIST TO RUN
</P>
<P>
   Stockwell Day, Canada's rising right-wing politician, will seek
to enter Parliament by running in a special by-election in British
Columbia. Prime Minister Jean Chretien is expected to call the
by-election before mid-September to allow Day, the new leader of
the Canadian Alliance, to run for a southern British Columbia seat
vacated by Jim Hart, an alliance member who is retiring. Day, an
Albertan who once lived in the district, was elected July 8 as
leader of the alliance, the largest and newest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: PIPELINE DEATHS RISE
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in the latest oil pipeline blaze climbed to 100
as local authorities prepared a mass grave for the victims,
government officials and hospital workers said. The explosion near
the oil town of Warri came less than a week after more than 250
people were killed in a similar incident 6 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF REFUSAL
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif refused to testify before a
special court trying him for corruption. In remarks to the
one-judge Accountability Court, he said the hasty trial was
designed only to convict him. Sharif said he had boycotted the
trial, on tax evasion charges, because it had been started without
allowing him to consult his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: GERMAN FREED
</P>
<P>
   Muslim rebels freed an ailing German woman, one of 19 mostly
foreign vacationers who have been held hostage for nearly three
months. Renate Wallert, 57, is the third to be released, after two
Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: SMOG HITS CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   A blanket of smog from forest fires in neighboring Indonesia has
returned to the capital, Kuala Lumpur. Some haze has also been
reported in Singapore. The pollution comes from illegal fires set
mostly by plantation owners who were protected by the government of
former President Suharto and appear to be beyond the control of the
current president, Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ANWAR TAKES OVER
</P>
<P>
   Taking over from his lawyers to make his own closing statement,
former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim called the sexual
misconduct case against him ``a dirty, despicable conspiracy.''
Anwar faces a prison term of up to 20 years in addition to the
six-year term he is already serving for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   DIEGO GARCIA: ISLANDERS SUE BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of islanders deported from the British-run Chagos
archipelago 30 years ago to make way for a U.S. military base, sued
the British government in the High Court in London for the right to
return home. The islanders were moved to the Seychelles and
Mauritius in the late 1960s so the United States could build a base
on Diego Garcia. Britain leased the island to the United States and
in 1971 barred anyone without a permit from entering. The islanders
say they have a right to return.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: JOURNALIST JAILED
</P>
<P>
   A journalist convicted of insulting Islam was sentenced to a
five-and-a-half years in prison, the official news agency reported.
Emadeddin Baqi was convicted of ``insulting Islamic sanctities,
spreading falsehoods to divert public opinion, libel and insult,''
his lawyer was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC
</P>
<P>
   FIJI: SANCTIONS IMPOSED
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand announced penalties against Fiji and warned of
stiffer curbs if a new government does not restore multi-ethnic
democracy. Indigenous rebels in Fiji ousted a government led by an
ethnic Indian. New Zealand development aid will be cut in half, to
$1.15 million. Joint military exercises, as well as training, have
been suspended, and government-backed student visits have been
ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
