<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-DEAD-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYCE'S ODD LITTLE PLAY WITH MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after July 19, 2000 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
Its creators call ``James Joyce's The Dead'' a play with music.
They might just as easily have dubbed it the ``Un-Musical.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title should have been the first clue that ``The Dead,''
despite its Broadway success and critical acclaim, isn't one of
those rock-your- foundation events. Where mega-musicals like ``The
Lion King'' and ``Phantom of the Opera'' are known for their size,
costumes and special effects, ``The Dead'' is positively intimate:
small cast, manageable sets, no stage-swamping production numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a show function like this one,'' says Richard
Nelson, ``The Dead's'' adapter, co-lyricist and director of the
production, which opens tonight at the Ahmanson Theatre. ``I'm
primarily a playwright, so for me it's the person who is the be-all
and end-all. Everything, even the dances, we knew would have to
come out of the character situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Shaun Davey's music, which isn't likely to leave anybody
with ringing ears or leap off the Top-50 bins at Tower Records. At
one point audiences will see characters converse over the sound of
an on-stage violinist and a cellist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so un-Broadway,'' agrees Stephen Bogardus, who plays
Gabriel Conroy, the play's narrator and central figure. ``And it
really demands a lot from its audiences because the sound is a very
acoustical sound. It's not blown out of the speakers as people are
used to both in movie theaters and in Broadway shows.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark draws an enthusiastic amen from Bogardus'
co-star, Faith Prince, who, despite her past participation in
several such big musicals, seems to be enjoying ``The Dead's''
quieter ambience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really noticed it last night,'' says Prince, who plays
Gabriel's wife, Gretta. ``I went to see `The Perfect Storm,' and I
was saying, `Oh my God, can they just, like, turn this !ital!down?'
It was just too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, you might say that a couple of hours spent watching a
fishing boat on the gale-tossed Atlantic is a far cry from spending
Christmas Eve in the Dublin living room of two spinster aunts,
circa 1904. And why wouldn't it be? The play's source material,
after all, sprang from the pen of James Joyce, the Irish author
known for cramming pages of minutia-like details into a single day
or event. ``The Dead'' was first a 50-page short story, the last in
the ``Dubliners'' collection. It later became the basis for
director John Huston's final film in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In the story _ which is largely unchanged from the the film and
novella _ Gabriel and Gretta are among those in attendance at a
Christmas party hosted by Gabriel's aunts Kate and Julia Morkham _
a gathering that includes tipsy guests, poignant toasts, a hint of
Irish nationalism and, yes, plenty of music. Characters sing and
dance for each other _ if not necessarily for the audience. The
play reaches its climax later in an expensive hotel where an
occurrence from the party causes Gretta to reveal an incident from
her past that her husband had not known about. That realization
causes a bit of psychological angst in Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have been together probably 10 to 15
years,'' says Bogardus. ``These people probably think they know
each other like the back of their hand. Then for this kind of
secret to come out ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's something she just put away,'' adds Prince. ``It
was tragic for her and, for whatever reason _ not to keep it from
him _ she just put it away, which I can totally relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   To Nelson, little revelations are part of human interaction, and
the relationship we're observing isn't on the brink of collapse.
``The Dead,'' Nelson reminds us, was a story first told by a
26-year-old man intent on exploring the exuberance and confusion of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the story we have is one about a long marriage,'' says
Nelson. ``It's rare to find in world literature a significant work
that's the story of a marriage that's been going on for a long time
and one that doesn't involve some melodramatic infidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarer still is a small-scale musical from literary material that
manages to earn both critical plaudits and a steady audience.
Adapted and directed by award-winning playwright Nelson (``Two
Shakespearean Actors'', ``Goodnight Children Everywhere'') with
music by Davey, ``The Dead'' sold out its limited run off-Broadway
at Playwrights Horizon before moving to Broadway's Belasco Theatre
in January. The New York Times' Ben Brantley called it ``one of the
season's most astonishing and laudable accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogardus and Prince both performed in the New York production,
their paths overlapping for two weeks toward the end of the run.
They replaced Christopher Walken and Blair Brown, the production's
original Gabriel and Gretta.
</P>
<P>
   Bogardus had gotten a peek at an early version of the script,
back when he was under consideration for the role of Freddy Malins,
a part that eventually fell to Stephen Spinella. In the spring, the
producers again contacted Bogardus in Los Angeles. Walken was going
to be taking a three-week break, and they needed a replacement for
Gabriel on very short notice. The actor, who admits he ``couldn't
make sense'' of the version he had read a few months ago, paused
before signing on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was talking on the phone with Richard (Nelson), I told
him I was a little nervous about coming into a show that quickly,''
said Bogardus. ``He said that, unlike other directors who leave a
show once it opens, he would be there for me _ as he was for Faith
_ for all the rehearsals. Based on that, I said I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't go entirely according to plan. The production
closed after two weeks, leaving Bogardus with a major case of
!italprojectus interruptus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just worked harder than at any time in my professional
career to learn this material and get into the show, and I realized
it wouldn't be until the last couple of shows that I would start
feeling really comfortable,'' he said. ``Then, when it ended after
only two weeks, it was sort of like unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back here, and get eight weeks at the Ahmanson, I feel
like, `Ah, I'm going to be able to complete this journey.'''
</P>
<P>
   That his co-star is once again Faith Prince, with whom he had
previously worked in William Finn's ``Falsettoland,'' makes the
journey even more comforting. Both actors say the opportunity to
start anew gives them the chance to make the characters their own
rather than trying to duplicate the work of their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you replace, you tend to do what was,'' says Prince,
``but here we've gotten to examine it and come up with our take on
it, through Richard's eyes. It's been great fun to rework it and
make it our own.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1903EDT &QL; 
