r e BC-BUENA-VISTA-PREVIEW-L     07-17 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUENA-VISTA-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING `SOCIAL' ON PBS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Wed., July 19, 2000.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Much has been made of how Ry Cooder ventured into Cuba in search of
musicians who hadn't been heard from for decades (a couple of whom,
in fact, had been thought dead) and rescued them from obscurity
with the recording of the hit CD ``Buena Vista Social Club.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to hear Cooder tell it, the resurrection of careers went
both ways. ``I wasn't doing anything, either,'' Cooder says with a
self-deprecating smile. The fruits of Cooder's inactivity, so to
speak, can be seen tonight on two area PBS stations, when Wim
Wenders' Oscar-nominated documentary ``The Buena Vista Social
Club'' premieres on television.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cooder had been busy before rediscovering the musicians
seen in ``BVSC.'' He had recently won a Grammy for ``Talking
Timbuktu,'' his collaboration with African guitarist Ali Farka
Toure. But his thirst for intoxicating world-music rhythms had
scarcely been slaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had collected records over the years _ what I could find,''
Cooder recalls. ``They weren't easy to find. A lot of this music _
most of it _ never traveled outside of Cuba at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, Cooder had discovered the music on a cruise to
Cuba. ``In all these intervening years, I thought, `If I don't get
down there someday, I'm going to miss the boat because this
generation's dying off all over the world, and I'll never get close
to this stuff at all.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, serpentine contacts _ friends of friends _ rooted out
the musicians. Pianist Ruben Gonzalez, thought dead and then found
without a piano of his own, erroneously was thought to be too
arthritic to play the instrument. Ibrahim Ferrer was frustrated and
initially unwilling to participate because his career had never
taken off after having been stalled in the early '60s. Compay
Segundo, after a colorful career in the '40s and '50s, had been
dispatched to China to chop down trees as part of a labor exchange
program.
</P>
<P>
   You know the rest: ``Buena Vista Social Club'' sold 3 million
copies worldwide and won a Grammy; it also inspired both Wenders'
popular documentary that revealed the depths of their love for a
music long considered obsolete and a spate of equally soaring solo
recordings from many of the principle artists. In addition to
acclaimed releases by Segundo, Gonzalez and Ferrer (all packaged
very similarly to the original ``BVSC''), Barbarito Torres
(``Havana Cafe'') and Eliades Ochoa (``Sublime Illusion'') have
produced albums; recently, singer Omara Portuondo released a CD
under the ``BVSC'' imprimatur, and Gonzalez has another due soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular bunch is touring in various configurations all
the time now,'' Cooder says (Portuondo will appear in L.A. in
September). ``It's fair to say they could work every day for the
rest of their lives. And they seem to want to do that. They're
happy to be out _ they're going to Japan, they're going to
Australia, they've been to Europe a bunch of times.'' Creature
comforts don't really factor into the equation for the Cuban
musicians, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ibrahim moved into a better apartment _ the holes in the
street are still so big, the cab leaves you off at the corner, and
you have to walk down, but it is better than he had before,''
Cooder says. ''He may even get a phone some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't seem to be about (money) for them,'' he
continues. ``Compay, for instance, people know him wherever he goes
now, and he's so happy about that. He has so much fun being
recognized, so much fun being this great figure who walks out on
stage to a huge roar. This is what's changed the most, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   And for fans who have fallen under the spell of Cuban music, has
Cooder got a Web site for you: Descarga.com, a Brooklyn-based
outlet for far more Latin music than any local megastore could hope
to stock. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Buena Vista Social Club.'' &QL; 
What: Oscar-nominated documentary on Cuban musicians rediscovering
their muses. &QL; 
Where:KCET and KCVR. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight on KCET and 9 tonight on KVCR. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
