<HEADLINE>
`TRUE WEST': REPLACEMENTS BROLIN AND KOTEAS LEAVE PLAY FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You loved the play. Now see the cartoon!
</P>
<P>
   Thus might an honest advertising writer, driven to desperation,
describe the newly recast revival of Sam Shepard's ``True West'' at
the Circle in the Square Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Two very brave actors, Josh Brolin and Elias Koteas, have taken
over from the production's original stars, Philip Seymour Hoffman
and John Reilly, with results that can most kindly be described as
flattening. What was once a playwright's dream made flesh, a
production in which theatrical exaggeration seemed truer than life
itself, is now a simple comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   When Matthew Warchus' staging of this 1980 study in fraternal
friction opened in March, it was hard to imagine anyone improving
on it. Hoffman and Reilly, largely known for their work in film,
delivered a priceless lesson in symbiotic stagecraft, alternating
in the leading roles of diametrically different brothers who by
degrees turn into each other.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which actor was Austin, the straight-arrow
screenwriter, and which was Lee, the slovenly renegade, you never
doubted the familial attraction and repulsion that kept them locked
in a psychological (and sometimes literal) stranglehold. Something
was definitely going on beneath the skins of these overgrown boys _
who, by the way, didn't look close to identical _ that made the
evening's conclusion deliciously inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Your heart aches for Brolin and Koteas, actors of the same
generation and cinematic background as their predecessors, who have
been placed in the painful position of tampering with near
perfection. For the time being Brolin is Austin, and Koteas is Lee,
with the reversal of parts scheduled for July 26, and they are as
unmixable as oil and water.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lee's grotesqueness and Austin's blandness have been scaled
up. Koteas evokes one of the homicidal yokels from the horror movie
``The Hills Have Eyes,'' while Brolin brings to mind John Davidson,
the eternally clean-cut singer. The actors seem stuck on these
heightened surfaces, composites of traits applied from the outside
rather than arrived at from within.
</P>
<P>
   That the staging remains essentially the same generates an
impression of neophyte dancers following a chart of ballroom steps
before they have found their own rhythms. When Brolin anxiously
hitches up his pants or compulsively dries a dish, it is with the
conscientious air of someone who has remembered to do so. He can
get away with this self-consciousness only in the inhibited
Austin's early scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Koteas takes a more flamboyant approach. Wearing a short
raincoat of the type favored by flashers, this Lee sits and walks
with his legs wide apart. His gestures are correspondingly large
and loopy, and he often tucks his lips over his teeth, perhaps to
conjure the image of the brothers' toothless father. The actor
courts the audience energetically, like a hillbilly clown.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting performances are commensurately larger, too, with
the unctuous movie producer Saul Kimmer (Philip LeStrange,
replacing Robert Lupone) as bizarrely silky as Liberace. Celia
Weston, the one original member of the cast, has broadened the
reactions of the brothers' mother without destroying the
character's essential spirit of bewilderment. She is now easily the
best thing in the show.
</P>
<P>
   It is never a good sign when you can separate actors from their
gestures, unless the playwright is named Bertolt Brecht. Brolin and
Koteas convey the comic sense of Shepard's play but none of its
troubling emotional sensibility. And without the fear beneath the
laughter, ``True West'' just isn't very funny.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRUE WEST'
</P>
<P>
   By Sam Shepard; directed by Matthew Warchus; sets and costumes
by Rob Howell; lighting by Brian MacDevitt; sound by Jim van
Bergen; original music composed by Claire van Kampen; fight
director, Rick Sordelet; production stage manager/associate
director, William Joseph Barnes; company manager, Alan R.
Markinson; production supervisor, Gene O'Donovan; associate
producer, Sandi Johnson; executive producer/general manager, Roy
Gabay. Presented by Ron Kastner. Circle in the Square, 50th Street,
between Broadway and Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Josh Brolin (Austin), Elias Koteas (Lee), Philip LeStrange
(Saul Kimmer) and Celia Weston (Mom).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
