u a BC-PRIESTS-ABORTION-NYT     07-17 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP OF PRIESTS WILL URGE VOTERS TO SUPPORT CANDIDATES WHO OPPOSE
ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A national organization of Roman Catholic priests will announce
a campaign Tuesday to urge voters to make opposition to abortion
their first priority in choosing candidates to support in the
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, Priests for Life, will make its case with
advertisements in newspapers and on television, according to its
national director, the Rev. Frank A. Pavone of the Archdiocese of
New York. The organization has scheduled a news conference Tuesday
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although Priests for Life will not endorse candidates or support
a particular party, it will aim part of its message at politicians
who support abortion rights, to try to persuade them to reconsider,
Pavone said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, he said, draws its inspiration for the
campaign from a statement adopted by the nation's Catholic bishops
in November 1998. That statement, titled, ``Living the Gospel of
Life: A Challenge to American Catholics,'' described abortion and
euthanasia as grave threats to civil society, and said political
leaders have a moral obligation to combat them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the scripts for three television commercials the
organization plans to film, one calls for Pavone to quote from the
bishops' statement, urging lawmakers who support abortion rights to
``consider the consequences for their own spiritual well-being, as
well as the scandal they risk by leading others into serious sin.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the script, the commercial is addressed to abortion
rights supporters generally, and does not name any specific
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In the script of another commercial, addressed to voters, Pavone
calls abortion ``the most important issue'' of the political
season.
</P>
<P>
   Pavone said the commercials may be broadcast by late August. He
also said the organization wants to speak not just to Catholics,
but to non-Catholics as well, urging all to be informed about the
election. ``I want the public to understand abortion as it is, as
an act of violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded nine years ago, Priests for Life has about 6,000 priests
and 40,000 lay people as members, said Pavone, who was given
permission to become its national director by the late Cardinal
John O'Connor, archbishop of New York. He said it has an annual
budget of $4 million, raised through donations.
</P>
<P>
   Its advisory board includes such prelates as Cardinal Alfonso
Lopez Trujillo, president of the Vatican's Pontifical Council for
the Family, Archbishop Charles J. Chaput of Denver and Archbishop
John F. Donoghue of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Priests for Life's plans have drawn the attention of Americans
United for the Separation of Church and State, of Washington, whose
executive director, the Rev. Barry W. Lynn, said that if the
organization singled out specific races or candidates with its
message, the advertisements would violate what the government
allows religious organizations to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's clear that it's a specific, unlawful intervention'' in
a political race, Lynn said, ``we will report it to the Internal
Revenue Service.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony DeStefano, Priests for Life's executive director,
said that the organization would steer clear of such involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very thorough, not only in consulting our own law
firm, but legal experts in the pro-life movement and in the
church,'' DeStefano said. ``We're on very, very solid ground. We're
not going to be endorsing or attacking any candidates by name,
period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
