<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG, PANTANI TRADE BARBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France _ The war of the roads turned into a war of
the words Monday when Lance Armstrong decided he'd heard enough
criticism from Italian rival Marco Pantani, whom he referred to as
``Elephantino.''
</P>
<P>
   The rift began after last Thursday's Tour de France stage when
the two cyclists reached the summit of Mont Ventoux in the Alps and
Armstrong let Pantani cross the finish line first. No big deal,
said Armstrong; Pantani had ridden a strong race and it was the
``gentlemanly'' thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   But when printed reports said that Pantani had been handed the
win, he felt insulted. He claimed he was stronger than Armstrong at
the summit and won the stage on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Pantani seemed to backpedal after his stage win
Sunday, saying he held Armstrong ``in high esteem,'' the Texan had
heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   A news conference was called Monday, the Tour's day off, for
Armstrong to address the media and talk about his overall lead,
which is more than seven minutes. But it didn't take long for
questions about his relationship with Pantani to come up, and it
didn't take long for Armstrong to light into his rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, in English we say _ oh, I won't say what we say _ but
it's unfortunate that Elephantino is showing his true colors,''
Armstrong said. ``I felt like it was a gift on the Ventoux. And I
also feel like it was a mistake to give the gift. He's a great
racer and a great climber, but after the last few days, his actions
and words are very disappointing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who often races with a bandanna over his bald head and
wears a gold earring, calls himself ``The Pirate,'' but the French
press had dubbed him ``The Elephant'' (``Elephantino'') for his
large, Dumbo-like ears.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nickname Armstrong liked saying with a snicker Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me that's his official name, because I can't say my name
is, say, `Big Tex,' '' said Armstrong. ``A nickname has to be given
to you by other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, I don't want to make a big issue of this,'' he said in
a gross understatement, ``because Elephantino is here to win stages
and I'm here to win the Tour de France.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I feel pretty comfortable where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johan Bruyneel, director of the US Postal Service team that
Armstrong represents, said that he told Armstrong it wouldn't hurt
to let Pantani win the stage, since Pantani was 10 minutes behind.
It could even help in later stages, Bruyneel said: ``He could be
more like an ally.''
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake, and it won't happen again,'' Bruyneel said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Pantani were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Marblehead, Mass., gave some insight as to how
cyclists spent their day off: ``We had breakfast, got driven down
the mountain, went for a ride for a couple hours, got driven up the
mountain, had lunch, took a short nap, had a massage, saw the
chiropractor, visited with a few friends from Boston.'' It was a
change of pace after racing more than 100 miles every day. ``Well,
for the first time I did miss having my laptop computer with me,''
said Hamilton . . . The Tour will observe a moment of silence
before Tuesday's stage in memory of the 12-year-old boy who was
struck by a car and killed last Friday. Even though the roads are
mobbed with miles of the publicity caravan, cyclists, press cars,
and sponsors' cars, it was the first time since 1988 that a
spectator has been killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
