<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4824 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-X-MEN-AZR &LR;      07-17 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MEN-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-X-MEN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `X-MEN' MISSES TARGET(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Bill Muller(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To demonstrate the pitfalls of blatant prejudice and
discrimination, (beginitalic)X-Men (enditalic)takes us back to the
political sensibilities of the '50s - the 1650s.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts with a full-blown witch hunt, as a
McCarthyesque figure (Bruce Davison) calmly tells the U.S. Senate
that all mutants must be rounded up and registered. Instead of
bursting into uncontrollable laughter, the extras in the gallery
nod approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   In the same 10 minutes, the movie compares the U.S. government
to Nazi Germany, then supplies a mob waving racist signs to drive
the point home.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. I thought this was supposed to be a movie about a comic
book.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if the filmmakers had stuck to cartoons,
(beginitalic)X-Men(enditalic) might have been better. But probably
not. Unlike the Marvel comic about superpowered mutants, the movie
has a profound case of the stupids.
</P>
<P>
   Example: All the world's leaders are gathering in New York for a
giant conference (this is pounded into our heads with news
reports), but the X-Men literally need a psychic to figure out that
this is the target of their archenemy, Magneto (Ian McKellen, who
does his best though forced to wear a very funny hat).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, despite the world's supposed hatred of mutants,
Professor X (Patrick Stewart) is able to operate a school for
mutant children out in the open, simply by hanging a ``school for
the gifted'' sign out front. Yeah, that ought to fool them.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's not really clear how much the mutants are being
hounded. The only evidence we have is a guy who kicks Wolverine
(Hugh Jackman) out of a bar. Given that criterion, I might be a
mutant.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, all the silly politics just seem out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the comic was created in the 1960s by Stan Lee, who drew on
the protest-torn era for material. But 40 years later, the same
themes just don't work, especially in what should be a fun
shoot-'em-up.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie fails there, too. The fight scenes are
(beginitalic)Matrix (enditalic)Lite, giving the distinct impression
that the actors spent a lot of time hanging from wires in front of
blue screens. Everybody's floating all over the place, and it just
looks silly. The famous X-Men jet leaves the hangar just once,
maybe because it resembles a plastic toy.
</P>
<P>
   The story is pretty simple: Magneto plans to make war on humans,
and the X-Men try to stop him. In case you miss something, don't
worry, Stewart's character explains everything about three times.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pointless romance between Wolverine and Rogue (Anna
Paquin), whose Southern accent fades in and out throughout the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   There also are too many characters, and they aren't given
anything to do. That's what happens when you use the first movie to
set up an inevitable sequel.
</P>
<P>
   The telepathic Jean Grey (Famke Janssen) does little more than
coo over the beds of various injured X-Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Storm (Halle Berry) spends much of the movie standing around
with a cool haircut. Her big line comes when she fights Toad (Ray
Park of Darth Maul fame).
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what happens to a toad when it's struck by
lightning?'' Storm asks. ``The same thing that happens to
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of the powers of the X-Men, which don't
seem to click on when needed. As a result, they spend much of the
movie as punching bags for the evil mutants.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, you start rooting for the appearance of
Nightstick Man, who just bonks everybody on the head and is done
with it.
</P>
<P>
   But where's the political message in that?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact Muller at Bill.Muller &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
