<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BEREZOVSKY-BOS     07-17 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BEREZOVSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL TYCOON QUITS DUMA, SAYS HE'LL OPPOSE PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Accusing President Vladimir V. Putin of trying to
create a dictatorship in Russia, media and oil tycoon Boris
Berezovsky said Monday he would resign his seat in parliament and
go into opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Once a staunch Putin ally, Berezovsky is often described as one
of the most powerful men in Russia. His dramatic announcement means
Moscow may be in for another round of bitter political fighting
after months of relative calm.
</P>
<P>
   His move came shortly after prosecutors opened several
high-profile criminal cases against some of the country's leading
businessmen. It also came amidst a Kremlin campaign to make
Russia's powerful provincial leaders more subservient to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from the Kremlin. Putin left
Monday for an Asian tour that will take him to China, North Korea
and ultimately Japan, where he will attend a summit meeting of the
Group of Eight industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky called the Kremlin's crackdown on Russia's governors
and on big business a threat to the country's fragile democracy.
``I don't want to participate in the destruction of Russia,''
Berezovsky, 54, told a packed news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power corrupts and absolute power corrupts absolutely,'' he
said, quoting 19th century British statesman Lord Acton. ``Russia
has no chance of surviving under an authoritarian model.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would formally resign from the State Duma, the lower
house of Russia's parliament, when it meets Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his lofty rhetoric, several analysts said Berezovsky's
real motive may have been self-preservation. The controversial
tycoon's business dealings have repeatedly come under scrutiny by
Russian law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack on Putin, analysts said, any crackdown against
Berezovsky or his business empire would look like political revenge
and be more difficult to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berezovsky is scared by Putin's latest moves. Now if he is
prosecuted it will appear political,'' said Yevgeny Volk, a
political analyst at the Heritage Foundation in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Markov, a Moscow-based political analyst, said Berezovsky
_ whose media holdings include Russia's largest television station,
several newspapers, and radio stations _ could mobilize the
nation's business leaders into a fierce and organized opposition to
the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berezovsky can offer a platform for all those who are unhappy
with what the Kremlin is doing,'' Markov said.
</P>
<P>
   By resigning his seat in parliament, Berezovsky would give up
the immunity from prosecution that Russian legislators enjoy. But
analysts said this was meaningless. If prosecutors come after
Berezovsky with the Kremlin's backing, they said, lawmakers would
quickly vote to strip his immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, a longtime Kremlin insider and one of Russia's
wealthiest men, is one of the so-called ``oligarchs,'' a group of
politically-connected moguls who used their government ties to
build fortunes under former president Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, he amassed a huge financial empire in media, oil,
aluminum, and aviation. He also emerged as one of Russia's most
ruthless and cunning political infighters. He was a key member of
the so-called Kremlin ``Family,'' a circle of bureaucrats and
businessmen around Yeltsin who helped Putin get elected in March.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Putin pledged to establish a
``dictatorship of law,'' create a level playing field for business,
and to eliminate the oligarchs ``as a class.'' Many were skeptical,
since Putin himself was widely seen as a creation of the tycoons,
who sought to protect their wealth.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, however, prosecutors have launched
investigations into some of Russia's most powerful firms. Among
them are the largest oil company Lukoil, the biggest automobile
manufacturer Avtovas, the metals giant Norilsk Nickel, and the
independent media holding Media-Most.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky called the probes ``a deliberate campaign aimed at
destroying big business'' in Russia. ``There is no reasonable
motive behind this, simply a desire to concentrate power,'' he
said. He called for an amnesty for all business dealings in the
chaotic decade since the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who wasn't sitting with arms folded during those
years has willingly or unwillingly broken the law,'' he said. ``And
those sitting in the Kremlin are in the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky had come under scrutiny earlier over an estimated
$600 million allegedly embezzled from Russia's national airline
Aeroflot. He has denied any wrongdoing, and a criminal case against
him was dropped in November. Berezovsky said he met with
prosecutors last week as a possible witness to a fraud case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is a rational person,'' he said. ``If he thinks it is to
his advantage to put Berezovsky in jail he will put Berezovsky in
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Putin's plan to make Russia's elected
regional leaders more beholden to the Kremlin. Putin wants to strip
the governors of their seats in the upper house of parliament, and
thus of their immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who claims the regional leaders flaunt the law and run
their provinces like personal fiefdoms, also wants the power to
remove elected governors who violate the law.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have assailed the changes as undemocratic, but some
analysts said that Berezovsky's stance is rooted in his close ties
to many governors whom he helped get elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berezovsky is above all a good power broker. He is strongest
when there are many independent competing centers of authority,''
said Markov. ``The Kremlin's plan to create a strong, central,
unitary state threatens Berezovsky's political future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
