 PERSONALS: How Your Space Measures Up 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
What with real estate prices soaring, the average high-tech office
worker is getting shoved into spaces smaller than ever, reports
Wired magazine. Once upon a time, the standard office cubicle was 8
by 8 feet. Cubicles today are as small as 5 by 6 feet. For
comparison purposes:
</P>
<P>
   _ The average Porta Potti is 11.7 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average casket is 15.2 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average Silicon Valley cubicle is 30 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average prison cell at San Quentin is 70 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BYGONES WON'T &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BE BYGONES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marianne Gingrich &LR; , Newt's ex-wife, is writing a tell-all book
about their marriage. Her proposal, which is circulating among
possible publishers, says she wants ``to describe what I saw in the
rise to power and in Newt's eventual demise. I can reveal what went
on in strategy meetings when we decided to take on the
establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the personal dirt? ``It was one of the uglier
situations of a wronged woman in Washington,'' an editor who has
seen the proposal told MSNBC's  &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR; . ``If Marianne
decides to really spill the beans on Newt, it could be very, very
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A quick check of the Macy's registry Monday, July 17,
revealed that although four of the 12 hand towels sought have been
bought, Newt and his new wife's bath mat needs are still unmet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT WINNERS WEAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When American athletes show up for the Olympics, they'll have to
submit to random drug testing, reports the New York Times, and sign
pledges to wear the official sponsor's clothes to awards ceremonies
if they win.
</P>
<P>
   The certified clothes for the awards ceremonies are by Adidas,
which has a two-year contract with the Olympics. ``In the past,''
Adidas'  &UR; Susan Halliday &LR;  told the Times, ``you'd have Coca-Cola do
a year of the Games, and then they're gone. '' Adidas, she said,
``is about long-term contracts and commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FATE AND LITERATURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Rama Lama &LR;  is reading a biography of  &UR; Billy Wilder  &LR; that
reveals that the director used to write ``cum deo,'' ``from God,''
on the first page of every one of his screenplays. After ``Lost
Weekend,'' which won a best-picture Oscar, he wrote on the first
page of ``Sunset Boulevard,'' ``I'll take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; David Margolick &LR; , who says he got great response to a query
for his last book, ``Strange Fruit,'' is working on a new one about
the June 22, 1938, heavyweight championship fight between
 &UR; Joe Louis &LR;  and  &UR; Max Schmeling &LR; . The fight, which was at Yankee
Stadium but was broadcast nationwide by radio, had significance
because Louis was black and Schmeling, a German, was considered an
example of the master race.
</P>
<P>
   Margolick wants to hear from people who either attended the
fight, listened or rushed out to celebrate Louis' first-round
victory. He's at 315 W. 86 St., No. 14F, New York, NY 10024, or
 &LR; margolick &LR; aol.com &LR; .
</P>
