<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BOOK-800&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE BOOK-BUILDING: A CHAPTER HERE, A CHAPTER THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: N.Y., Mich.)   By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Frommer's guide to France may be made up of chapters and
maps, but most readers know it as an indivisible and coherent
whole: a book.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, that book and a few hundred others will take a new
form on the Internet. They will be sold in component parts _
chapters, maps and even paragraphs _ that can be mixed and matched.
Readers will be invited to create customized books by picking
pieces of content a la carte from an array of already-published
guides.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers will have the option of receiving their books
electronically or ordering them printed, bound and delivered to
their door.
</P>
<P>
   The customization is possible because of a deal announced last
month between an online service called iUniverse and IDG Books, the
publisher of the Dummies guidebooks, Frommer's travel guides and
Cliffs Notes. With IDG's permission, iUniverse is creating a
digital system that enables pieces of every guidebook to be
assembled on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is one of the first steps toward a new editorial
marketplace that some publishers and technology companies have been
envisioning since the dawn of digital media. And it is the latest
challenge to the traditional definition of a book.
</P>
<P>
   Under this model, books have not only turned into streams of
electronic bits that are downloaded to hand-held devices or printed
on demand. They have also turned into databases _ pools of digital
information that people can extract and combine on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that you are going on a trip,'' said Patricia
Schroeder, president of the Association of American Publishers and
the former congresswoman. ``You may want a couple chapters of a
travel book, a couple chapters of a cookbook,'' she said, adding
that readers probably would not want to carry each of those books
for just a few chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine going into a bookstore and asking to buy only those
chapters. ``They are going to look at you,'' she said, ``and say,
`What?' ''
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, that request is not so crazy. ``The online
world is uniquely suited to providing this kind of highly targeted,
highly customized information,'' said David Sidman, director of new
publishing technologies for John Wiley &AMP; Sons. Four years ago,
Sidman helped to develop tools that enabled scientific journals to
be delivered online, article by article. Today, he said, selling
content this way ``represents a tremendous new revenue opportunity
for publishers of all kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel books, textbooks, cookbooks and how-to guides will be
some of the first books chopped into interchangeable parts,
according to officials at publishing and software companies
experimenting with the concept. In fact, some publishers are
already offering bits and pieces of content for downloading to
handheld devices like Palm organizers. And although no one is
talking about chopping up narrative books, like novels, anthologies
of short stories could be distributed this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so close we can just smell it,'' Schroeder said. ``This
is all going to be very doable, very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But before pages and chapters will be available for the picking,
several hurdles need to be cleared. For example, turning books into
what the industry calls ``disaggregated content'' could destabilize
the economics of publishing, something that most established
publishers are loath to do. What happens, they ask, if people stop
buying whole books in favor of a few popular chapters? A publisher
could cannibalize its own business if readers decided to buy a few
chapters for $5 rather than the entire book for $20.
</P>
<P>
   John Kilcullen, chief executive of IDG Books, does not think
that will happen. Although he has not yet set prices for the
material that will be available this fall, he said some chapters
might be given away as promotional materials and other prices might
be set proportionally, so that a 25-page chapter of a 100-page book
would cost about 25 percent of the book's list price. Other
sections, he added, could cost almost as much as the book itself,
particularly if they are in high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, authors might not be thrilled about having their work
sold in pieces or packaged with the work of others. Many recent
contracts include broad provisions for electronic rights,
publishers say, but few mention the possibility of selling pieces
for mixing and matching. Some agents and publishers are already
gearing up for new negotiations over modular content.
</P>
<P>
   William Gladstone, the founder of Waterside Productions, an
agency representing many authors in the series of Dummies books, is
encouraging writers to sign contracts that permit publishers to
sell content in pieces. He is betting that writers will earn more
royalties that way. ``I would advise them to be cooperative,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
