<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-INTERNET-BOOKS-2NDTAK     07-17 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BOOKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: he said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another hurdle involves technical barriers. If a book is going
to be chopped into digital pieces for mixing and matching, those
pieces need to be technologically compatible with parts of other
books. And to make those pieces searchable across databases,
companies will have to establish a standard means to identify the
piecemeal content. Right now, books have one standard tag _ their
International Standard Book Number, or ISBN _ that enables them to
be cataloged and purchased quickly at the checkout counter. But
their chapters, paragraphs, charts and graphs have no such numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Until standards are set, publishers are faced with ``a rat's
nest'' of problems, said James Lichtenberg, president of
Lightspeed, a consulting company for the educational publishing
industry. They must figure out how to build databases that
integrate their own products, as well as those of partners. They
have to decide how to slice their content and how to label it.
``You have to have very clear definitions,'' Lichtenberg said,
``things like `this means a photograph,' `this means a map.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the progress so far has come from the realm of education
and research. College professors, after all, have been mixing
chunks of editorial content for decades by assigning ``course
packs'' that are typically compilations of photocopied pages from
magazines, anthologies and nonfiction books.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with advances in copyright protection software and the
recent drive to create electronic books, many publishers have
embraced the idea of selling individual chapters from multiple
academic books.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw-Hill was one of the first to do so; it created a database
called Primis enabling professors to choose from 180,000 pages of
material spanning 20 disciplines (www.mhhe.com/primis). For
example, a professor can build a book that includes ``Notes of a
Native Son'' by James Baldwin and see that the selection adds $1.75
to the cost of the book. Other building blocks cost more, like 83
pages of ``The Turn of the Screw,'' by Henry James, priced at
$8.55.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are usually dependent on the popularity of the items and
how much McGraw-Hill may have to pay for reprint permissions, said
Ginny Moffat, vice president for marketing and custom publishing at
McGraw-Hill Higher Education. Features like color pages bump up the
costs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Another large textbook company, Taylor &AMP; Francis, will soon be
offering a database for building books. It announced last week that
it had signed a deal with Versaware, a publishing-technology
company that has developed its own customization system. The books
could be delivered to students over the Internet as files for
printing or downloading to handheld devices, said Harry Fox,
Versaware's chief executive. Or they could be printed and bound
nearby, then shipped to the college bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Manish Chopra, a graduate student at the University of Michigan,
is one reader who says he would appreciate the chance to buy books
in pieces, rather than whole. He recently visited a Borders
bookstore to find ``Consulting Demons,'' a book on corporate
consulting by Lewis Pinault. A friend had recommended that he read
the early chapters, which dealt with recruiting tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book was like $30 hardcover,'' Chopra said, ``and I was
like, I don't know if I want to buy it, because I was only
interested in the first four chapters.'' Instead, he stayed in the
bookstore, spent several hours reading the chapters, and put the
book back on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been given the chance to buy those chapters for a few
dollars, he said, he would have done so. ``It's always the case
that you don't need all the information,'' Chopra said. But if you
could buy it in pieces, he said, ``that would be a great tool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
