<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-NEW-WEB-LANGUAGE     07-17 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-NEW-WEB-LANGUAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT BIG LEAP? IT'S CALLED XML  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: A B&AMP;W illustration is available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By JOHN MARKOFF  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In the beginning, as it were, the Web was made possible by a
simple innovation known as Hypertext Markup Language, or HTML.
Through this language, which arranged text, images and buttons in a
World Wide Web browser, information could be read by computer users
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its power, HTML has flaws, the most obvious being an
inability to make distinctions between the presentation of computer
data and the data itself. HTML, in other words, deals only with the
``appearance'' of information. This is why the Web is sometimes
called a ``fancy fax machine'' _ great at doling out documents on
request but poorly designed for direct information exchanges
between computers on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Now, inevitably, the next generation of Web language, called XML
(for Extensible Markup Language), is emerging, and many software
designers can barely contain their excitement over its potential to
establish a real Internet lingua franca.
</P>
<P>
   By not only transmitting information but also interpreting what
that information means, XML, the brainchild of a Sun Microsystems
engineer, will greatly enhance a wide range of Internet companies
and applications, from automated industry supply chains to a new
class of Internet programs that users can gain access to at the
office, at home or on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like there's been this collective `Aha!' experience in
the community over the simplicity of this technology,'' said Howard
Katz, an XML software developer in Vancouver, British Columbia.
``It just feels right.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the difference between HTML and XML, consider a
document containing, say, baseball statistics, like those printed
in newspapers. As it travels through cyberspace, the document
contains separate bracketed ``tags'' embedded in the text, which
offer instructions to a browser, like Microsoft Explorer or
Netscape Navigator, on either the display of the information (HTML)
or its meaning (XML).
</P>
<P>
   The HTML tags display the information in neat columns and
boldface the names of the players and their teams. The XML tags, by
contrast, describe what each category of information is: player,
team, batting average, home runs, runs batted in. The genius of XML
is that each information category can have its own ``vocabulary,''
making it possible to easily identify and exchange information.
</P>
<P>
   XML designers are starting to use the language like a data glue
to hook together entire industries. For example, a computermaker or
a group of PC companies might automate their supply chains, using
the Web to link parts suppliers directly to their factories.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, XML may become the most crucial component underlying
the next big leap on the Internet. Microsoft has already moved
rapidly to build e-commerce tools based on its version of XML,
known as Biztalk.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is apparently preparing for an even more
significant committment to XML. In late June, Microsoft introduced
its new software strategy based on what its co-founder, William H.
Gates, is calling Next Generation Windows Services.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to create a new Internet operating system that will
shift an array of applications from the hard disks of personal
computers onto the Net. A range of software and services, from word
processing and spreadsheet programs to data storage and other
peripherals, will be on powerful network computers accessible
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users will thus be able to gain access to the power of
their computers whether they are in their office, at home or
traveling with a wireless connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Microsoft's new Internet strategy is XML, which
the company will use to rapidly connect its applications and make
them work across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a bitter pill for Sun Microsystems, one of
Microsoft's chief rivals. XML was first envisioned by Jon Bosak, a
Microsystems software engineer, who saw that HTML would not be
useful for turning the World Wide Web into what he calls an
``industrial strength infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   One of a small group of professionals who understood the true
power of an arcane publishing language known as Standard
Generalized Markup Language, or SGML, Bosak began pestering the
World Wide Web Consortium, the MIT-based group that designs
standards for the Web, with his notions in 1996. He came away with
the consortium's blessing to explore a way to bring the power of
SGML to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   He had become a believer in SGML after using the language to
single-handedly transfer the 150,000 pages of Novell's Netware
documentation from print to an online system.
</P>
<P>
   Between August and November 1996, Bosak, with the help of two
other SGML experts, Tim Bray and C.M. Sperberg-McQueen, created XML
as a scaled-down version of SGML, intended for use on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Their solution was, in principle, very simple. They used HTML's
tags (which are offset by brackets within the code), to describe
what a particular piece of information is, rather than what it
looks like.
</P>
<P>
   In an article written last year for Scientific American, Bray
and Bosak described the difference between the two languages with a
simple example: shirts. XML, they wrote, would ``label the parts of
an order for a shirt not as boldface, paragraph, row and column _
what HTML offers _ but as price, size, quantity and color.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach has been quickly grasped by everyone _ software
developers, Internet start-ups, corporate giants such as Microsoft
and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``We unleashed it on the world at the end of 1996, and it was
like hurling ourselves at a door that was unlatched,'' Bray said.
</P>
<P>
   Will the resulting technology offer a level playing field based
on a set of standards that all companies can use? It's not clear.
Sun, which created the Java programming language, has been slow in
popularizing the XML standard even though Bosak conceived it.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of Microsoft's intense antitrust battle and the
conflicting industry views over whether the company is an imitator
or an innovator, it will be quite a twist if Microsoft becomes the
biggest beneficiary of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
