<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS WIDOW FAILS TO APPEAL PHYSICIAN'S ACQUITTAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Reggie Lewis medical malpractice case formally came
to a close Monday as a judge dismissed Donna Harris-Lewis's appeal
of the May jury verdict clearing Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. of
negligence in her late husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the lawsuit that made front-page headlines when it
was filed four years ago ended with a whisper: Harris-Lewis missed
a filing deadline required to continue her appeal, prompting
Mudge's attorney to file a motion that the appeal be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, noting that Harris-Lewis's lawyer offered no
opposition, Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith granted the
request. His ruling came ten days shy of the seventh anniversary of
Lewis's death on July 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis accused Mudge, Lewis's chief cardiologist at
Brigham and Women's Hospital, of failing to diagnose her husband
with the heart condition that caused the Celtics star's fatal
collapse as he was shooting baskets at a Brandeis University gym. A
first trial ended in a hung jury last year.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his office Monday, Neil Rossman, Harris-Lewis's
lawyer, said he had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, when Rossman filed the notice of appeal for
Harris-Lewis, he said he did so ``to protect her appellate rights
and give her time to evaluate her options.'' At the time, he
offered no indication of the legal grounds on which she might base
her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of a notice of appeal, the first procedural step
necessary to appeal to the state Appeals Court, does not guarantee
that a full appeal will take place. But it does protect a
litigant's right to pursue an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The next step would have been for Harris-Lewis and her attorney
to order a transcript of the retrial, which ended in early May
after four weeks of testimony and five days of jury deliberations.
After reviewing the transcript, they would have had the option of
filing a full appeals brief that outlined the legal errors they
believe took place at trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris-Lewis missed a deadline last month to continue the
process, meaning that her appeal period had lapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's lawyer, William J. Dailey Jr., did not return a call for
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
