<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      07-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TRUTHS ARE APPARENTLY MORE ALIEN THAN OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Some days I believe aliens really
did land at Roswell in 1947, just as the conspiracy theorists
claim.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But instead of our government secretly recovering
microprocessors, fiber optics and other gizmos from the crumpled
spacecraft (and, uh, giving it all to Bill Gates and the Japanese
to sell to the rest of us), I think the co-pilot and a flight
attendant or two managed to survive the crash and slip into the New
Mexico night.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I figure, these aliens have lived quietly among
us, but sometimes they get a hankering for the adrenaline rush they
used to feel while hurtling through outer space with their heads
stuck out the window. So, for kicks and giggles, they dress up as
humans and sneak into Earth's major news events.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it sounds wiggy, but hear me out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, during the closing arguments in the
class-action suit against Big Tobacco, attorney Jim Johnson gamely
told a jury that his client, R.J. Reynolds, cannot afford to pay a
cent in punitive damages. ``Like many individuals,'' he said.
``Reynolds is living from paycheck to paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that: An industry with more than $123 billion in
revenues and $9 billion in earnings last year, and its CEOs
apparently are subsisting on Oodles of Noodles. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm just guessing, but I'd wager that, in a former life,
attorney Johnson reminded folks to fold up their trays and bring
their seats into an upright position prior to intergalactic
landings.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Strom Thurmond, the universe's senior
statesman.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after George W. Bush confided to the NAACP
convention last week that ``there's no escaping the reality that
the party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of
Lincoln,'' his campaign aides trotted out ol' Strom.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, borrowing from a Harry Truman campaign slogan, had just
mocked Republicans for their ``do-nothing-for-the-people
Congress.'' Thurmond stepped up to the mike and joked, ``Mr. Gore,
I knew Harry Truman. I ran against Harry Truman. And, Mr. Gore, you
are no Harry Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thurmond bolted from the Democratic Party in 1948 and
ran against Truman on the segregationist Dixiecrat ticket. Thurmond
didn't carry the mantle of Lincoln or even Roosevelt, but the hood
of Nathan Bedford Forrest.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington Post reporter Michael Powell and others have
pointed out, Thurmond was riled up by Truman's integration of the
armed forces. ``All the laws of Washington and all the bayonets of
the Army cannot force the Negro into our homes, our schools, our
churches and places of recreation,'' Thurmond bellowed on the
stump.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he had people sign an oath of allegiance to racial
segregation before they could vote in the Dixiecrat primary. Over
the years, though, his crusade has been dressed up as a battle over
state's rights or, as the Strom Thurmond Institute at Clemson
University portrays it, ``New Federalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Post asked the Bush campaign why it risked having
Thurmond revive memories of his white supremacist days, for which
he's never apologized. ``We are in a day when people make light of
their past,'' responded Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer, who said only
humorless Democrats had complained. (Can't you hear it? ``Please
return your trays to their upright position.'')
</P>
<P>
   All of this calls to mind a glowing foreword Thurmond wrote a
few years ago for a book by Philip J. Corso, a former Army officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreword, Thurmond said Corso ``has many interesting
stories to share with individuals interested in military history,
espionage and the workings of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Thurmond, the book was titled ``The Day After
Roswell,'' and it detailed Corso's claims that he'd helped our
government secretly recover microprocessors, fiber optics and other
gizmos from a crumpled spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's staff hurriedly explained he had no clue the book
was about woo-woo aliens when he wrote the foreword.
</P>
<P>
   For that, he expressed regrets.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com. The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
