<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEENS-SMOKING-BOS &LR;      07-17 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SMOKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ACCUSE TOBACCO INDUSTRY OF TARGETING MINORITY TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the US smoking rate continues to drop, Latino and
African-American teenagers are turning to cigarettes at an
increasing rate, drawing bitter accusations from public health
officials that the tobacco industry is targeting minority teens as
their customers of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Although Massachusetts teenagers are bucking the national trend
and smoking less than they didi in 1993, state officials are so
concerned that they've launched their first anti-smoking campaign
aimed specifically at African-American and Latina girls.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials across the country are particularly incensed
over advertisements for Virginia Slims cigarettes that depict
glamorous young African-American and Hispanic women under the
slogan, ``Find Your Voice.'' Although maker Philip Morris is
phasing out the slogan after complaints that smoking damages vocal
chords, state officials say such ads help fuel smoking among young
minority women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry is really increasing their advertising to
. . . minorities, particularly women,'' said Massachusetts Public
Health Commissioner Howard Koh. ``The tobacco industry has also
inflitrated every culture. These ads are powerful. They tell
society, particularly children, what's considered attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the rate of smoking among black high school girls
increased 54 percent from 1991 to 1997, twice the growth rate of
white students, according to a 1998 Surgeon General's report. Among
Latino high school girls, the smoking rate increased by about 37
percent. Those jumps reverse a decline in minority smoking during
the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the numbers are more encouraging. Smoking
among African-American high school students of both genders
declined 6.8 percent between 1993 and 1999, according to state
figures, while, among Latino high school students, it declined 2.6
percent. Figures for girls alone were not available.
</P>
<P>
   But Koh and other state officials say minority women are
particularly vulnerable, turning to tobacco as a way to deal with
depression, loneliness and stress. According to a 1997 Youth Risk
Behavior Survey, 30 percent of Latina girls under age 16 in
Massachusetts smoke cigarettes. Among African American girls, ages
16-18 in Massachusetts, 16 percent are smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry officials say they're being made a scapegoat.
They deny that they are stepping up advertising in minority
publications, or that they are trying to attract underage smokers
of any race or ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal with all our cigarette advertising is to reach only
adult cigarette smokers,'' said Tom Ryan, spokesman for Philip
Morris USA, the largest cigarette maker. ``We recognize (that) with
the right to manufacture and market cigarettes comes a
responsibility to help prevent kids from smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   As proof, Philip Morris is suspending future placement of
cigarette advertising in any publication whose readers younger than
age 18 constitute 15 percent or more of the total readership or is
read by more than 2 million people younger than 18. The company has
already dropped advertising in Elle, Mademoiselle, Sports
Illustrated and People.
</P>
<P>
   But activists and public health officials say tobacco companies
are masters at subtly recruiting young smokers _ the cartoon
character Joe Camel once pitched Camel cigarettes _ all the while
claiming to abhor the idea.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Virginia Slims ads, for instance, depicts a beautiful
young African woman with colorful fabrics on her head, accompanied
by text written in an African tongue. A second depicts a young
Hispanic woman looking slyly at the camera with text urging readers
to ``dance around naked.'' These ads appeal to African-American and
Latina girls, say activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies know that historically African American
teenage girls smoke at much lower rates than there Caucasian
counterparts,'' said Matthew Myers, president of the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids. ``In years past, the advertising themes focused
on thinness. The thinness theme simply didn't work in those
communities. Now Philip Morris is trying to associate freedom and
independence with their products.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Morris spokesman Ryan said his company has nothing to
apologize for except the original ad campaign's slogan, ``Find Your
Voice,'' which is now being phased out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing for Virginia Slims is . . . intended to appeal
to adult women who choose to smoke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Virginia Slims controversy, a 1998 state survey found
that 52 percent of storefront cigarette advertising in
Massachusetts targets minority. Often, the ads featured a minority
female as the central character.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Massachusetts Department of Public Health
responded with the ``Keep It Fresh'' campaign, intended to raise
awareness among several ethnic groups about tobacco industry
tactics to attract smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnic females are the target for the future,'' said Gregory
Connolly, director of the Massachusetts Tobacco Control Program.
``It's profit. It's business without a consciece.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep it Fresh, the first anti-smoking campaign in Massachusetts
aimed specifically at Latina and African American girls, promotes
healthier living through a series of road shows demonstrations. On
Monday, Brendan Fehr of the WB television show ``Roswell'' appeared
with campaign participants at Six Flags New England in West
Springfield, Mass. to promote the anti-smoking message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society feels that every woman should be skinny and beautiful
and every woman wants that,'' said Christine Ortiz, 17, who is
entering MIT in the fall. ``The tobacco industry knows that and
targets females through that image.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz is part of the truth campaign, a caravan organized by
teenagers who travel the country spreading an anti-tobacco message.
The campaign includes specific components devoted to
African-American and Latino youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows (teens) read Vibe and (tobacco industries) are
all over those magazines,'' said another caravan participant,
Chikira Cotten, 17, from West Nyack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But John Singleton, spokesperson for R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, the
second largest U.S. cigarette manufacturer, said the critics are
way off base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is that we will only advertise in magazines where
at least two-thirds of readership is 18 and over,'' Singleton said.
The ads ``are not by any means run predominantly in minority
publications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
