<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WILDE-LOVER-BIOGRAPHY     07-17 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDE-LOVER-BIOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE OTHER CENTRAL FIGURE IN THE FAMOUS CASE OF OSCAR
WILDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am true Love, I fill the hearts of boy and girl with mutual
flame,'' Lord Alfred Douglas wrote in 1892, when he was 22. ``I am
the Love that dare not speak its name.'' And oh, he was dangerous,
pouty lipped, sweet voiced, capable of ruining the thing he loved
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Hyacinthus, whom Apollo loved so madly, was you in
Greek days,'' Douglas' lover, Oscar Wilde, wrote to him.
</P>
<P>
   And of course Douglas, or Bosie, as he was called, has gone down
in history as the man who ruined Wilde. In 1895 Wilde was convicted
of ``gross indecency'' and imprisoned because of his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But 20-year-old Douglas Murray, who is ending his second year at
Magdalen College, Oxford, thinks that Lord Alfred, who died in
1945, has gotten a bad rap. Murray is the author of ``Bosie,'' a
new biography of Douglas (Talk Mirimax Books/Hyperion, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   Wilde ``was not sent to prison for Douglas,'' Murray said. ``He
was prosecuted for his relationship with rent boys,'' he added,
using a term for male prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bosie spent the two years Wilde was in prison defending Wilde,
writing articles to newspapers,'' Murray said. ``He petitioned
Queen Victoria for the release of Wilde.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has been called the youngest biographer in England
by British newspapers, was speaking on the telephone from Magdalen,
Lord Alfred's former college. He said he had uncovered hundreds of
letters that had not been seen by previous biographers. And he
added that he has drawn a more balanced portrait of a man who has
been portrayed as the epitome of spite and manipulativeness.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas was born in 1870 into a noble Scottish family, the son
of the famously nasty Marquess of Queensberry. He met Wilde, by
then the successful author of ``The Picture of Dorian Gray,'' in
1891. Wilde was bloated, awkward, a married father of two sons. He
was soon besotted, although their sexual relationship seems to have
been brief. Bosie taunted Wilde by taking other lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Bosie and his father had a hysterical dislike for each
other. ``You impertinent jackanapes,'' his father wrote him.
</P>
<P>
   And after Bosie received a letter from his father condemning his
homosexuality, he wrote back, trying to infuriate him, ``What a
funny little man you are.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Douglas who urged Wilde to sue for libel after his father
delivered a card to Wilde that the Marquess later testified was
meant to read, ``For Oscar Wilde _ Posing as a sodomite.'' Wilde
lost, but that trial led to the one that resulted in his
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   While in prison Wilde turned on Douglas himself, writing the
famous ``De Profundis,'' a long diatribe against Bosie. Although it
contained some of his finest prose, the letter also took Bosie to
task for slights like failing to serve him lemonade when he was
ill.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilde, broken in body and spirit, was released in 1897, the
two men reunited. Apparently they did not resume a sexual
relationship but rented a villa in Italy, pursuing their writing
and influencing each other's work, Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Bosie's mother threatened to cut off his allowance if he
didn't leave Wilde. Bosie agreed, but only after his mother
promised to give Wilde money. When Wilde died in 1900 from injuries
suffered in a fall in prison, Bosie mourned him desperately and
paid for his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was born in West London. His father is a civil servant,
his mother a teacher. His older brother is a lawyer. At 8 he began
singing in the St. Margaret's Church choir. He went on to the Royal
Academy of Music, then won a scholarship to Eton. Murray said he
was 14 when he came across ``De Profundis.'' He went on to read
Douglas' poetry and was entranced by it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he explained, he planned to write about Douglas'
poetry but discovered how autobiographical it was and decided to
write his life instead. After Eton, when he was about 17, he said,
he began researching and writing the book. At the time he was
teaching at a school near Aberdeen, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' executor, Sheila Colman, who, with her husband, looked
after Douglas in his final months, made his papers available to
Murray. After he finished the manuscript, Murray said he sat on it
for a year. Then, in his second term at Oxford, he was introduced
to Belinda Harley, a literary agent, who quickly sold it.
</P>
<P>
   In writing Douglas' biography, Murray had to contend with
Douglas' malice and his anti-Semitism. ``The effort of spending
time on him was only partly possible because he was such an
interesting and variable character,'' Murray said. ``The fact that
he changed so much, that fascinates me.''
</P>
<P>
   After Douglas left Wilde, he renounced homosexuality, converted
to Roman Catholicism and married Olive Custance. The marriage
failed. ``Bosie and Olive got on each other's nerves,'' Murray
said. ``But in later life, they saw each other every day. He was
absolutely distraught when Olive died.'' They had one son, Raymond,
who was institutionalized at 24 for schizophrenia. Douglas fought
for custody of his son, but it was denied because of his
relationship with Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Douglas became a carbon copy of his father. He
denounced Wilde, calling him talentless. He became so litigious,
Murray said, that ``at one point in the 1900s he couldn't stand in
court for one case because he was running in four cases at the same
time.'' In 1923 Douglas accused Winston Churchill of engaging in
war profiteering with Jewish friends and helping to blow up Lord
Kitchener.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Douglas taunted Churchill, saying, ``If you honestly
believe you're not guilty, then why haven't you sued me?''
Churchill did sue and won, and Douglas went to prison for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas ended his life penniless, his talent exhausted, living
in a basement apartment in Sussex. When he applied to the state for
a pension, it was denied because of his past.
</P>
<P>
   But in his 1938 memoir, ``Without Apology,'' he seemed to have
achieved some understanding of his life. In one passage he referred
to Wilde's last work, ``The Ballad of Reading Gaol'': ``The thought
that has only recently occurred to me is a terrible one. Did my
father really love me all the time, as I certainly loved him before
he turned against me, and was he only doing what Oscar says in his
great ballad all men always do, killing the thing he loved? Didn't
we all three, Wilde, my father and I, do it, more or less?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
