<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GERMS-TOOCLEAN18-COX     07-17 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMS-TOOCLEAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-germ agents may give germs the last laugh, some experts
fear
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fussy parents and compulsive cleaniks everywhere, Tufts
University microbiologist Stuart Levy has some startling advice:
Cleanliness is not next to godliness.
</P>
<P>
   Soap and water are fine, but in a world of scrubbing bubbles and
lemon-scented disinfectants, a small but growing body of research
suggests that Americans could use a little more dirt. In fact, Levy
says, a sparkling, germ-free household may contain the seeds of the
country's next public health nightmare and endanger the health of
the children parents are trying to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years we have seen an explosion of household
products that contain anti-bacterial compounds,'' Levy told the
International Conference on Emerging and Infectious Disease in
Atlanta on Monday. ``When we started looking at these products in
the mid-'90s, there were only a handful of them. Now there are over
700 of them. We are having trouble finding any households that
don't use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The tidal wave of bacteria-inhibiting products _ once limited
largely to household cleansers _ has exploded to include
chemical-impregnated bathroom tissue, soap, toothbrushes, towels,
mattresses, pillowcases, chopsticks, cutting boards, plastic
refrigerator containers, fabrics and even plastic toys.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, a former president of the American Society for
Microbiology, says that unlike traditional disinfectants _ alcohol,
bleach and hydrogen peroxide _ most of the new products that
promise to control germs contain a persistent anti-bacterial,
anti-fungal agent called triclosan, which marketers claim provides
the ``lasting protection'' that consumers want.
</P>
<P>
   Triclosan has been used effectively as a broad-spectrum
disinfectant in hospitals for at least 30 years, but Levy says the
rapid proliferation of its uses in the household may pose serious
risks to public health.
</P>
<P>
   He says the chemical's persistence and the host of products in
which it is being used provide an ideal opportunity for the
emergence of bacteria that are resistant, not only to triclosan,
but to commonly used antibiotics. In the pursuit of cleanliness,
American consumers may be contributing to the already serious
threat of antibiotic-resistant microbes.
</P>
<P>
   In laboratory tests, the levels of resistance that have emerged
in mutant bacteria that survive a dose of household disinfectant
containing triclosan have been low. But health experts say they
don't know what may be happening in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association is concerned enough to have
asked the Food and Drug Administration to require manufacturers of
triclosan products to prove that they really do inhibit bacteria.
And Swedish authorities, who have found the chemical in mother's
breast milk, are considering tighter controls on its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying that these products are dangerous, but we've
only used them widely for about five years, so the time to look is
now,'' says Levy. ``The bandwagon for these products is just
getting bigger. The public doesn't really know what they do and
don't do, and increasingly the public doesn't have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry says the public is, in fact, choosing
anti-bacterial products in droves, with sales of $400 million of
anti-bacterial hand soaps alone last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society is increasingly concerned about the very real
threat of disease caused by bacteria,'' said Ed Kavanaugh,
president of the Cosmetic, Toiletry and Fragrance Association.
``Anti-microbial products are an essential part of good hygiene
routine. Anti-bacterial personal care products provide an extra
measure of protection for consumers at home and doctors and nurses
in hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Levy, the founder of the Alliance for the Prudent Use of
Antibiotics, fears that the rapid growth of anti-bacterial
household products is chillingly similar to the mistakes doctors
and hospitals have made in the past 50 years with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive and inappropriate use of prescription antibiotics
since the development of penicillin in the 1940s had led to the
emergence of disease-causing bacteria resistant to all major
classes of the drugs. A small but growing number of deaths in
hospitals are now due to germs for which effective treatments no
longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   Levy says it is ironic that public concern about these so-called
superbugs is at least partly responsible for the sudden increase in
germ-fighting agents in the home and the marketing ``craze'' that
is fueling it. And that a germ-free household is not only futile
but may impair the long-term health of children growing up in those
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies suggest that the development of asthma, allergies,
eczema and other disorders is most prevalent among children reared
in ``excessively clean'' environments that prevented routine
exposure to a wide variety of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dirty environment is actually essential for the normal
maturation of the human immune system,'' Levy says. ``Parents who
are really concerned about the health of children need to be asking
themselves, `How clean?' And in most cases, the answer is
`soap-and-water clean, not chemically clean.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Alliance for the Prudent Use of Antibiotics:
http://www.antibiotic.org
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble: http://www.pg.com
</P>
<P>
   Microban Products Co.: http://www.microban.com
</P>
<P>
   Conference page: http://www.cdc.gov/iceid
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
