<SLUG> BC-SENATE-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ALREADY IN TROUBLE WITH JEWISH VOTE, LEADERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whether or not Hillary Rodham Clinton screamed an
anti-semitic slur at a campaign aide 26 years ago, it tells much
about New York politics that she has denied the claim with such
uncommon heat and with the direct assistance of her husband, the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Several Jewish leaders here said Monday they doubt the
allegation will have much impact on the first lady's Senate
campaign, in part, they said, because she is in trouble with many
Jewish voters already.
</P>
<P>
   Of a half-dozen local rabbis and Jewish leaders interviewed,
none thought reports of the alleged slur would change anybody's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent rabbi in Queens, who asked not to be identified,
called the report ``absurd,'' and said, ``No one has called me in
outrage about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Anti-Defamation League released a statement:
``Mrs. Clinton's public record shows no evidence of anti-Semitism
and we do not believe her to hold negative views about Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a wariness of Mrs. Clinton lingers. As the Queens rabbi
noted, ``Many people do not trust her. They really don't know what
she thinks about Israel especially. Jews like to know these things.
It helps them feel more secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio,
sought to tap into this distrust. Calling the report ``a serious
allegation,'' he said, ``I don't know who to believe. New Yorkers
don't know who to believe. And therein lies a good deal of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The flurry began late last week, when Internet columnist Matt
Drudge quoted from a new book about the Clintons by Jerry
Oppenheimer, a former National Enquirer editor.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer reports that, in 1974, after Bill Clinton lost a
race for Congress, Hillary, then his girlfriend, called campaign
aide Paul Fray a ``f------- Jew bastard.'' Fray is not Jewish,
though his paternal grandmother is.
</P>
<P>
   New York's main tabloids, the Daily News and the Post, picked up
the story Saturday, and cited Fray, his wife Mary Lee, and _ the
next day _ one other campaign worker, Neill McDonald, as confirming
the story. TV newscasts were fast to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton then took the unusual step of summoning reporters
to her house in suburban Chappaqua to deny and denounce the tale in
no uncertain terms.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, President Clinton rallied to her defense, took time out
from the Middle East summit at Camp David to make two phone calls
to the Daily News, one to its publisher, Mortimer B. Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there and (Hillary) never said it,'' the president was
quoted as saying in Monday's edition. ``In 29 years, my wife has
never, ever uttered an ethnic or racial slur against anybody. ...
She might have called him a bastard. ... But I've never heard her
tell a joke with an ethnic connotation. ... It's not in her.''
</P>
<P>
   As anyone in New York politics knows, if a story like this were
proved true, or were widely believed to be true, the results could
be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 percent of New York state's voters are Jewish _ 600,000
out of 5 million in the 1998 Senate race _ but they can be crucial
in a close election, and Clinton-Lazio is as close as they come.
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters of Jews tend to vote Democratic, but the first
lady is not doing nearly that well.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls, taken well before this flap, show Jews favoring
her over Lazio, 54-34. This may seem a healthy margin, but the rule
of thumb is that Democrats must attract at least two-thirds of the
Jewish vote, to win a statewide contest.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Alphonse D'Amato won three Senate elections, in part
because he pulled away as much as 40 percent of the Jewish vote. In
his last race, two years ago, he lost to Charles Schumer in part
because he lured only 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has long cut a controversial profile among Jews.
Much of it dates back to a comment early in her husband's
presidency, advocating a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions about her deepened last November, when, on a trip to
the Middle East, she sat nonchalantly at a forum while the wife of
PLO chairman Yasir Arafat claimed Israelis have fired poison gas at
Palestinian children. Then, while saying goodbye, she gave Mrs.
Arafat a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton waited 24 hours to denounce Arafat's remarks,
saying that the simultaneous translation she heard was milder than
the official version she read later. (Reporters who were along on
the trip, and listened to the same translation, dispute this.)
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent these stories may have an effect,'' one
executive of a Jewish organization said, ``it will be within the
context of the Arafat incident. But most of those who worry about
the Arafat incident aren't going to vote for her, anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
