<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth unit seals deal in Colombia
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _While speculation continues about consolidation of
global telecommunications, BellSouth on Monday completed a little
consolidating of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal valued at about $414 million, BellSouth-controlled
Celumovil announced consummation of its purchase of Cocelco, a
combination that establishes the first nationwide wireless carrier
in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Celumovil, which has revenue of $213 million and 466,000
subscribers, provides wireless service in the east side of
Colombia, including Bogota and Cartagena. Celumovil has acquired
Cocelco, which operates in the west of the country, including the
cities of Cali and Medellin. Cocelco, which has more than 200,000
subscribers, last year had revenue of about $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two companies will offer service in areas where 41
million people live.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, BellSouth, which has poured billions into Latin
America, said it is investing an undisclosed amount to become
majority owner of Celumovil, holding 50.4 percent. In May,
BellSouth paid $295 million for a 33.8 percent interest. The
Atlanta-based regional telecom company has investments in 11 Latin
American countries, most commonly as a wireless provider. Its
extensive presence in the region is rivaled only by Spain's
Telefonica, which owns primarily land-line phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the WorldCom-Sprint merger, the ambitious
Telefonica has _ like BellSouth _ been among those mentioned in
speculation about a range of combinations in the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Telefonica failed to merge with KPN Telecom,
a Dutch company in which BellSouth has a stake. Telefonica's
aggressive chief executive, Juan Villalonga, is reportedly under
pressure to resign for certain alleged improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
