<SLUG> BC-GAPAC-EARNINGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: RUNS WITH GAPAC-FORTJAMES
 &HT;    Profits fall, but beat forecasts
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Georgia-Pacific Group reported a 3 percent drop in
second-quarter profit on less demand and lower prices for building
products.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific reported quarterly net income of $206 million,
or $1.20 a share, down from $212 million, or $1.20 a share, in the
period one year ago. Sales were up sharply to $5.45 billion from
$3.81 billion due to recently acquired tissue and distribution
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat Wall Street expectations that Georgia-Pacific
would earn $1.16 a share in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Improvement in the Atlanta-based company's pulp and paper
operations helped offset the weakened housing supply sector.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific's containerboard and packaging segment reported
operating profits of $141 million, compared with $76 million a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The group's pulp and paper segment reported operating profits of
$148 million, compared with $26 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Unisource Worldwide, the company's new paper distribution
segment, contributed operating profits of $41 million.
</P>
<P>
   But profits in the building products segment dropped to $173
million, compared with $364 million a year earlier. The
distribution segment of building products recorded operating profit
for the quarter of $7 million, down from $35 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, Georgia-Pacific reported total sales of
$10.83 billion, up from $7.16 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Total profit for the first half of the year was $400 million, or
$2.30 a share, compared with $311 million, or $1.76 a share, a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group's results exclude the company's timber
business. The Timber Co. reported net income of $34 million, or 42
cents per share, compared with $49 million, or 57 cents per share,
in the prior period. That excludes a one-time, after-tax gain of
$50 million from the sale of timberlands in the 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, Timber Co. reported net income of $74
million, or 91 cents a share, compared with $96 million, or $1.11 a
share, excluding the one-time gain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
