<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, July 18. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-PRIVACY-REGULATE (Washington) _ The White House says it
will propose legislation to set legal requirements for surveillance
in cyberspace by law enforcement authorities similar in some ways
to those for telephone wiretaps. By Stephen Labaton and Matt
Richtel. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ As the Camp David summit meeting
moves closer to a supposed deadline of President Clinton's
Wednesday morning departure for Japan, the White House remains
officially committed to reaching ``an agreement'' before then and
talks shifted into high-drive for a crucial 48-hour period. But
some U.S., Israeli and Palestinian officials begin deliberately
lowering expectations for a breakthrough. By Deborah Sontag. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ The Frommer's guide to France may be
made up of chapters and maps, but most readers know it as an
indivisible and coherent whole: a book. This fall, that book and a
few hundred others will take a new form on the Internet. They will
be sold in component parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _
that can be mixed and matched. By Lisa Guernsey. (The story has
moved in ``f'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP (Washington) _ When George W. Bush is asked
what factors he is seeking in his running-mate, he talks about
things like preparedness to be president and compatibility. But he
never mentions the one factor that several of his advisers say is
hovering over his entire selection process: abortion. By Richard L.
Berke. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to: SCI-PROZAC-SAFETY (Undated) _ The new book ``Prozac
Backlash'' claims that the drug has more serious and more frequent
side effects than the public is aware of or than the label
indicates, but other medical experts take a much more cautious
approach. By Erica Goode. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
3,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Based on the frenzied
pace of speculative construction here this summer, the Hamptons
have never before been invaded by so many rich people wanting to be
wowed and demanding that it happen fast. By Blaine Harden.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under a 3-column photo. (photos NYT8, 9)
</P>
<P>
   NY-APPLE-GROWERS (Milton, N.Y.) _ Poor weather and a number of
economic forces, from depressed apple prices to spotty insurance
coverage to consumer demand for flawless fruit, have pushed New
York's Hudson Valley apple farmers to the brink. Many are wondering
aloud whether the 10-minute hail bursts in May and June will be the
straws that finally broke them _ and in the process altering an
austere landscape of gnarled trees and open sky forever. By Lisa W.
Foderaro. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
