<P>
   SYRIA-POLITICS (Cairo, Egypt) _ In his inaugural speech as
president of Syria, Bashar Assad focuses on repairing his country's
ailing economy and gives no sign that he will be any more flexible
than his late father in negotiating a peace deal with Israel. By
Susan Sachs. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS (Moscow) _ Boris Berezovsky, the archetypal
Russian tycoon, politician and, until lately, a force within the
Kremlin itself, says he will quit his seat in parliament and try to
form an alliance of big business and regional politicians aimed at
curbing President Vladimir Putin's growing power. By Michael Wines.
(Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-GARBAGE (Manila, Philippines) _ Loosened by a week
of monsoon rains, Manila's massive garbage mountain _ the symbol of
the nation's poverty _ collapsed last week and smothered hundreds
of squatters who make a living picking through it with metal hooks
for scraps of refuse. One week later, rescuers were still digging
through hundreds of tons of muck Monday, working in one-hour shifts
because of the rot of the soaking garbage, the poisonous gasses it
emits and the stench of the decomposing bodies that are buried in
it. So far, about 200 bodies have been recovered. Residents
estimate that as many as four times that number may have died,
though a complete death toll will probably never be known. By Seth
Mydans. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
1,400 words.
</P>
