<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GAPAC-FORTJAMES-COX     07-17 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPAC-FORTJAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific to buy Fort James in $11 billion deal
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Georgia-Pacific made another move to stabilize its
boom-or-bust business Monday, announcing an acquisition that would
make it world's largest maker of tissue products.
</P>
<P>
   Boosting its share of the tissue market would give
Georgia-Pacific a reliable growth vehicle as the company tries to
become less dependent on surges in the paper and housing markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based forest products giant plans to buy rival Fort
James for $11 billion. Fort James shareholders would get $29.60 in
cash and up to 0.2644 share of Georgia-Pacific Group stock for each
share of Fort James they own. Georgia-Pacific would assume $3.5
billion of Fort James's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Known mostly for its building products muscle in North America,
Georgia-Pacific would become a global powerhouse in tissue. The
move would knock Kimberly-Clark out of the top spot and
giveGeorgia-Pacific well-known consumer brands such as Brawny paper
towels and Quilted Northern bathroom tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step forward for Georgia-Pacific to a less
cyclical business, and this moves our (products) dramatically
closer to the customer,'' said Chairman and Chief Executive Pete
Correll.
</P>
<P>
   Like other forest products companies, Georgia-Pacific is prone
to wild swings in prices and demand. Although the paper side of the
business is enjoying an upswing from a major crash several years
ago, the building products side is taking a hit with the slowing
housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific said the Fort James acquisition will help brace
earnings because tissue manufacturing is more predictable than
paper and lumber businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Fort James and Georgia-Pacific together would have about half
the tissue market in North America. Its next biggest rivals are
Kimberly-Clark, maker of Scott tissue, and Procter &AMP; Gamble, maker
of Charmin.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal also would give Georgia-Pacific its first
foothold overseas, principally in Europe. That signals a dramatic
shift in strategy by Georgia-Pacific's chairman, who has repeatedly
said the company did not have the expertise or the breadth to take
on international acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the domestic synergies drove this deal, but suddenly
we find ourselves the owner of the second-largest tissue producer
in Europe, the No. 1 in France... I think we owe it to ourselves
and shareholders to look at this as a new platform of growth,''
Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   But recent shifts in strategies are worrying some analysts. Not
long before Georgia-Pacific acquired paper distributor Unisource
Worldwide last year, company management said it wasn't interested
in growth outside its building products business, noted analyst
Mark Connelly of Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unisource deal worked out well but left many investors
guessing as to the real strategic direction at G-P,'' said
Connelly, who downgraded Georgia-Pacific from ``buy'' to ``hold''
after the Fort James deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Now) they are picking up a major high-end consumer product
business that survives by going head-to-head with Procter &AMP; Gamble
every day,'' Connelly said. ``It's a business that G-P brings
little expertise to.'' Georgia-Pacific said it will sell plants
that make about 250,000 tons of tissue to help alleviate antitrust
concerns. The company will also get rid of ``non-strategic''
assets, which will be identified in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific also plans to cut $500 million in annual pretax
costs as a result of the deal. The acquisition is expected to add
to earnings after it's completed in the second-half of 2000,
excluding costs for goodwill, the company said. The companies have
agreed to a breakup fee of $125 million. If one of the companies
pulls out of the deal, that company would pay the fee.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the company's shares fell nearly 9 percent on
concern that it's paying too much for Fort James, whose costs have
risen on higher raw-material prices. The company's profits also
have been hurt by manufacturing problems stemming from the merger
of James River and Fort Howard, which created Fort James in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are buying a big, busted consumer-products company,''
said Mark Wilde, an analyst at Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown, who has a
``market perform'' rating on Georgia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service said it may cut its ``Baa2'' ratings
on the companies' debt because the acquisition would increase
Georgia-Pacific's debt by about $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
