<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK, UPSET BY SOME PLAYERS' CONDITIONING, IMPOSES FINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Bill Belichick may be tougher than Pete Carroll,
but so far the new coach is getting a dose of what the old one did
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The new Patriots czar was irate over the conditioning of his
team in general and a handful of players in particular. For that,
he took action that may have sent a strong message.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick failed second-year safety Tony George on his running
test and made him sit out practice. George, who is diabetic,
couldn't finish the grueling running test Sunday; as it turns out,
George's blood sugar was low.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick levied fines Sunday that totaled close to $30,000, and
there were more prices to pay Monday. Tackle Ed Ellis, who had been
booted off his Barcelona Dragons team in NFL Europe, was cut
outright, saving the Patriots $472,000 on the salary cap, as was
former University of Massachusetts tight end Kerry Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick publicly humiliated George, receiver Martinez
Williams, second-year guard Derrick Fletcher, and backup
quarterback John Friesz by keeping them out of both sessions,
morning and afternoon. He had the four ride stationary bikes for
what seemed an eternity and then do laps around the field while the
rest of the team practices. When the process was repeated in the
hotter, more humid afternoon session, Fletcher looked ready to
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return as a team was no better than average,'' said
Belichick. ``We have too many guys who are overweight and too many
guys who are out of shape, too many guys who haven't paid the price
at this point in the season. I talked to the team about that. I
talked to the team last night. Basically it's a situation where you
can't win in this league with 40 good players when the other team's
got 53. You need 53 to match with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a great display of reverse psychology, Belichick added, ``I
guess I haven't done a good job getting through to the players on
what they need to do prepare for a football season. Obviously I
have to do a better job at that to respond to the challenges that
are immediately ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Said safety Larry Whigham, ``He's pissed off right now. A couple
of guys are overweight. I was a couple of pounds overweight and he
was cursing me out. The running is not a big deal for the skilled
guys because we run. Tony didn't pass because he's a diabetic. He
was low on sugar he was ahead of the pack but he did it 19 times
and he couldn't do it the 20th. If you don't practice, you get
fined $3,000 for not practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fine money, however, was for players being over
their assigned weights. The players union allows a team to fine
players $50 for every pound over the assigned weight per day.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's running test is more grueling than the one used by
Carroll the past three years. Linemen are told to run 40 yards in
six seconds 20 times, with 30-second breaks in between. Fletcher
couldn't do it, and the 6-foot-6-inch, 350-pound guard from Baylor
was struggling mightily when he was running laps. Linebackers,
tight ends, fullbacks, and quarterbacks must run 50 yards in seven
seconds 20 times, while defensive backs, wide receivers, and
tailbacks must run 60 yards in eight seconds 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   George was scheduled to take another running test Tuesday. His
agent, David Canter of Team Sports, said he plans to appeal the
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony had it passed until his diabetes kicked in,'' said
Canter. ``I've advised Tony to speak to Coach Belichick about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friesz has no idea when he will be back on the field. He said
that he failed a similar running test with the Seattle Seahawks in
1994 but was reluctant to elaborate, saying, ``We're not supposed
to talk to the media about these things. I'd like to defer for my
own well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friesz did say he'd never missed a practice in his career
until Monday. Asked if he was upset about that, Friesz said, ``Of
course.'' Friesz seemed embarrassed about having to run around the
field. ``That's the implication that's tried to come across,
sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick even found reason to be unhappy with the weather. He
thought the morning session was too cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a couple of hot days to where they can be pushed in
training camp,'' he said. ``This isn't really indicative of the way
it is in preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when the players who failed would be allowed back on the
field, Belichick said, ``It's not a question of being allowed, it's
a question of being ready. They'll have to show that they're
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will not ``put the season in reverse'' to wait for
players to get into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a player comes on the field four days into practice, it's
a higher level the fourth day of practice than the first day,''
said Belichick. ``When I think they're ready, I'll put them out
there. I thought that I had told the team in minicamp what I
expected and what I had to do. Most of the players I have no
problem with. There were too many players who didn't get the
message, who didn't respond the way I think they need to respond to
play in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   How many players?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than what it should be,'' said Belichick. ``It
shouldn't be any at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is probably correct; so why aren't some players
getting the message? The tough talk apparently hasn't worked. Fines
may hit some of the younger players hard, but veterans don't
necessarily respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we showed signs of picking up the system,'' said
Belichick. ``We were functioning as a team. The players who are out
there are working pretty hard making progress and improving. We
don't have enough people out there and some of the ones out there
aren't ready to go like they need to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not May, it's July. That's where we are, so we'll work
from here. The clock's running. Games are on the schedule; nobody's
going to move them. We're going to be there and so are the
opponents we play. We'll see where everybody is. We have a certain
time frame to work in. It's not the offseason anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when a guy comes off an injury. It's another
when a player has a full opportunity and he can't go. You look at
Max (Lane), who couldn't do much in the offseason expect rehab his
knee. He's ahead of most of the people out there. It's a compliment
to him. They're not at a level he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the players in question were those who hadn't been
big on strength and conditioning, Belichick said, ``It's a little
of everything. I haven't added it up. Too many guys not practicing
and too many guys overweight. We're moving on. Whoever can keep up
will keep up. We're not waiting for anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
