<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-DIVERSITY-NYT &LR;      07-17 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DIVERSITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDO-CANADIANS GAINING POLITICAL POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ From his corner office in Canada
Place, a sparkling steel and glass high-rise, the premier of
British Columbia has a harbor view of Burrard Inlet, a sheltered
patch of sea water framed by mountains, but stained by history.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in 1914, Canadian officials detained a ship loaded with
376 Punjabi immigrants. After two months at anchor, the ship and
almost all its passengers were sent back to India, a reflection of
Canadian laws that then excluded virtually all immigrants from
India and that denied Indians living here the right to vote, run
for office or become lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the spot from here,'' mused the new premier, Ujjal
Dosanjh, rising from his chair to inspect the view from his new
seventh floor office. Born in a dusty village in Punjab in 1947,
the year that India won its independence and that Canada granted
long-resident Asians full citizenship rights, including the right
to vote, Dosanjh (pronounced doh-SANJ) is Canada's first provincial
premier of color.
</P>
<P>
   Dosanjh, the province's former attorney general, is the leader
of the province's New Democrats. When he was sworn in as premier,
the celebration featured samosa pastries and turbaned musicians
playing sitars.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of an Indo-Canadian to the leadership of Canada's
third-most-populous province reflects Canada's rapidly changing
ethnic nature.
</P>
<P>
   In another measure of Canada's embrace of its Asian immigrants,
Adrienne Clarkson, an ethnic Chinese refugee from World War II Hong
Kong, became Canada's governor general, or head of state, last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eastern Canada's two founding peoples may be the English and
the French,'' said Peter Newman, an author and journalist who lives
on a boat here. ``Well, in Vancouver the two founding nations are
now the Indians and the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   News media attention has traditionally focused on the roughly
350,000 ethnic Chinese living in this province, sometimes giving
this city the nickname ``Hong-couver.'' But the province's 250,000
Indo-Canadians are increasingly visible as a political and economic
force and are rapidly entering the Canadian mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Hanomansing, a 38-year-old Indo-Canadian reporter for CBC
television, is being groomed to become the network's national news
anchor. Baltej Dhillon has become the first Mountie allowed to wear
a turban. A 17-year-old Indo-Canadian girl from Ontario will lead
the nation's high school debating team next winter. And an
Indo-Canadian novelist from Montreal recently won a British
Commonwealth book prize for the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto at the Royal Ontario Museum, crowds are flocking this
summer to a new show, ``The Arts of the Sikh Kingdoms.'' And in
Ontario a leadership candidate for the nation's largest
conservative party, the Canadian Alliance, was photographed wearing
a Sikh head covering as he sought votes in a temple.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Canada's roughly half million residents of Indian origin
are Sikhs, a religious group centered in Punjab, a northern state
near Pakistan. As links grow, Punjabi state ministers regularly
visit here, and in September, Dosanjh is to lead a British Columbia
trade mission to his birth state.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada's House of Commons there are now five Indo-Canadian
members, including Gurbas Malhi, an Ontario Liberal who bills
himself ``the first turban Sikh elected in North America.'' The
other Liberal Sikh, Herb Dhaliwal of Vancouver, is federal minister
of fisheries and oceans. The other three Sikh members of Parliament
are from the Canadian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In Dosanjh's leadership race, news analysts complained that
before the vote, the New Democratic Party became stacked with
Sikhs. Party membership rose by 75 percent in just three months, to
24,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are Sikhs in Reform, Liberal, Conservative and NDP, but
it is wrong for people to join more than one party,'' said Dave
Hayer, a Punjabi newspaper publisher who is running for the Liberal
nomination in Surrey-Tynehead, a new provincial assembly district
created to accommodate the huge inflow of Sikh immigrants here.
</P>
<P>
   Hayer incarnates the Sikhs' two most salient faces _ a concerted
push into the establishment, and a taste for political battle. The
pin on his blazer is a reminder that Hayer recently completed his
term as president of the local Rotary Club, the first Indo-Canadian
to hold the post. But his main job, as assistant publisher of The
Indo-Canadian Times, North America's largest Punjabi newspaper,
fell into his hands after his father, Tara Singh Hayer, was shot to
death in his wheelchair on Nov. 18, 1998. The police have
identified as a suspect a 39-year-old trucker who leads a Sikh
temple in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Hayer's killing is a sequel to the political radicalization
that split the Sikh diaspora after Indian troops occupied their
holy site, the Golden Temple in Amritsar, in 1984. The following
year, an Air India plane from Canada blew up off Ireland, killing
all 329 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of Canada's obliviousness to the Indians in its
midst, Canada's prime minister at the time, Brian Mulroney, sent a
telegram of condolence to India's prime minister, although almost
all of those killed were in fact Canadian citizens. The Mounties
have said that suitcase bombs sent from Vancouver had destroyed the
Air India plane near Ireland, as well as another Air India plane
damaged the same day at Narita Airport in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, a Sikh radical attacked Dosanjh, one of
the few Sikh moderates who dared to speak openly against extremism.
Attacked from behind with an iron rod, Dosanjh's hand was broken as
he tried to defend himself, and he needed 80 stitches to recover
from head wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dosanjh and others believe that the radicalism has ebbed.
Moderates have won control of Vancouver's largest temples. The
provincial government is curbing community development grants that
once were channeled to radical Sikh temples. And the federal
government is moving to curb Punjabi hate-radio transmissions that
have been broadcast to Vancouver from neighboring Washington state.
Journalists who closely follow Canada's 15-year-old investigation
into the Air India bombing predict that charges will be filed this
fall against a group of Vancouver-based Sikhs.
</P>
<P>
   As the popular image of Sikh violence ebbs, the election of
Dosanjh came about with little discussion of race. After three
months on the job, his approval rating in a survey of provincial
voters by Angus Reid Inc. was 64 percent. ``It is a real tribute to
British Columbia that we have accepted diversity as much as we
have,'' Dosanjh said. ``My approval rating tells me that people
don't see color.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
