<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LIBERATE-KERTZMAN-BOS     07-17 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERATE-KERTZMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO BUYS INTO WORLD OF INTERACTIVE TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Seeking to speed up delivery of interactive
television to the masses, Cisco Systems Inc. said Monday it is
paying $100 million to buy a 3.9 percent stake in Liberate
Technologies, a California company headed up by Massachusetts
expatriate, Mitchell T. Kertzman.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's entry into the world of interactive television is viewed
by analysts as a significant endorsement in the nascent technology
that has lately garnered a lot of buzz, but has yet to prove itself
in the mass market.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to combine television with the Internet, allowing
viewers, for example, to chat with other people watching the same
show, gather statistics on the sports event they are watching, get
real-time stock quotes, play along with a game show, download a
video game or movie, or click to get more information on a product
being advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics question whether people will want to interact with a
medium that has essentially been a passive form of entertainment.
But analysts say that results from recent market trials have been
encouraging and that the technology is slated to grow into a $25
billion-a-year industry by the year 2005, according to estimates by
Forrester Research. The money is expected to come from advertisers
and viewers who will pay for premium services, such as movies and
games on demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to click on their television,'' said Josh Bernoff,
principal analyst with Forrester. ``There is not lots of empirical
evidence now to show that.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, about 5 million viewers in America will
be able to interact with programs and commercials on TV, Bernoff
said. That is projected to grow to 65 million viewers by the end of
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Driving that growth are cable and satellite television companies
seeking additional sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much in the cable companies' interest to put this
technology in your house, because every time you click, they get
revenue,'' said Bernoff.
</P>
<P>
   Both Liberate and Cisco are in a position to win big if
analysts' projections hit their marks. Liberate, which is based in
San Carlos, Calif., sells software that cable companies can use to
build a platform for interactive content, and Cisco, based in San
Jose, Calif., sells the networking equipment that links the
television to the Internet. Liberate, in its last fiscal year ended
May 31, collected $28 million in revenue from companies such as
MediaOne, Comcast, and Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our software is the foundation upon which they build their
applications and content,'' said Kertzman, Liberate's chief
executive, known in Massachusetts for having founded PowerSoft
Corp. in Concord and then selling the company to Sybase Inc. for
nearly $1 billion in 1994. Kertzman said interactive television is
much more prevalent in Europe, where Liberate software is deployed
in about 200,000 set-top boxes. ``In the US, we're still in the
early stages of this. But you're going to see the beginnings of
real deployment by the end of the year,'' said Kertzman.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has not been kind to Kertzman this year. After
hitting a high of $128.53125 at the end of December, shares in
Liberate have dropped 74 percent. The company, which lost $80.8
million last year, suffered greatly in the technology selloff of
March as investors fled startups with skimpy sales and high costs.
</P>
<P>
   Because the interactive television market is so embryonic, no
single company has emerged as the premier player. Microsoft Corp.,
seen as Liberate's primary rival, is expected to come out with a
similar software package later this year. With Cisco's entrance,
analysts expect the market for interactive television to heat up
considerably given Cisco's marketing muscle and industry clout.
</P>
<P>
   Liberate's stock fell 43.75 cents to close at $33.6875 Monday on
the Nasdaq Stock Market. Cisco's stock, also traded on the Nasdaq,
climbed $1.375 to close at $69.625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
