<SLUG> BC-BUSH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush to hit the road before convention
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Gov. George W. Bush continued playing the
vice presidential guessing game Monday, telling reporters on the
campaign trail that he would launch his pre-convention trip in
President Clinton's home state but declining to say when or where
he will announce his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not made a final decision,'' Bush said. ``When I do, I
will let you know _ maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Andy Card, manager of the Republican National
Convention, Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee and U.S. Rep. Asa Hutchison
and U.S. Sen. Tim Hutchison _ brothers and Arkansas Republicans _
Bush refused to say who is on his short list.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Times reported Monday that Bush had narrowed the
list to four candidates, Sens. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and Fred
Thompson of Tennessee and Govs. Frank Keating of Oklahoma and Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into those kind of details,'' Bush said
when asked how many people remain on his list.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to picking a running mate, Bush is working on travel
plans leading up to the Republican National Convention, which opens
July 31 in Philadelphia. Campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said
current plans, subject to revision, call for Bush to leave Austin
for Arkansas on July 28 for a trip that will include stops in
Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia before arriving in
Pennsylvania on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The states on the trip are critical ones that Republicans have
not carried since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Little Rock, Bush visited the Centers for Youth and
Families to pitch his ``Caring Fathers, Safe Children'' initiative,
which would direct the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
to encourage states to establish and publicize paternity
registries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's credentials as a family-friendly candidate took a hit
Monday when Business and Professional Women, a Washington-based
organization, reacted harshly to a memo written in 1998 by Bush
adviser Don Willett.
</P>
<P>
   Willett, challenging the proposed wording of a gubernatorial
proclamation honoring the women's group, said in the memo that he
questioned the existence of a ``glass ceiling'' that limits women's
advancement in the business world. He also likened day care to
placing children ``in the care of rented strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Shaffer, chief executive officer of Business and
Professional Women, said the comments ``trivialize the survival
issues of America's working families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the Bush campaign's mantra of compassionate
conservatism?'' she asked. ``Issues like child care, equal pay for
equal work and eliminating sexual harassment need more than lip
service from our national leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said Willett's comments were his
own and do not reflect Bush's attitudes on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush appreciates the concerns of working women and
recognizes their vital contribution to the work force,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Business and Professional Women is a nonpartisan, nonprofit
organization. The group has a political action committee that
endorses and makes campaign contributions to candidates, who
generally are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
