A4908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-INTERNET-CAMPAIGN-COX     07-17 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign funds to be posted on Internet
 &HT;    By Gaiutra Bahadur
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's now much easier for Texans across the state
to follow the money, along a cybertrail.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, political campaign finance reports filed
electronically with the Texas Ethics Commission will be posted on
the Internet, making them more widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Texas joins a group of about 20 states that mandate electronic
disclosure of contributions and expenses by candidates and
lawmakers, according to the California-based Center for
Governmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups hailed the online database's debut, officially
at midnight today, as a victory for open government.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, members of the public and the news media outside of
Austin had to make a special trip to the capital city or pay for
copies of the reports to be mailed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, campaign finance reports are available in three formats: on
paper, on computer diskette and at http://www.ethics.state.tx.us,
the ethics agency's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The information is available for every candidate, officeholder
and political action committee _ unless they have filed an
affidavit stating they don't have access to a computer to file
their reports electronically or they have raised or spent less than
$20,000 in a year. Statewide officeholders and candidates must file
their reports electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important step forward in making information
available to everyone in all parts of Texas,'' said Suzy Woodford,
the state's executive director of the group Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   However, some open government advocates said the victory was not
complete, since the specific addresses of contributors will not be
available online or on computer diskette.
</P>
<P>
   ``In concept, we thought it was a very good thing,'' said Craig
McDonald, director of the nonprofit, Texans for Public Justice.
``It has computer age promise, but it's going to have carbon paper
impact ...''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Madden, R-Richardson, one of the architects of the
law that excluded contributor addresses from online disclosure,
said that privacy was a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think somebody who donates to a campaign should
immediately have their information available to all these mail-out
groups,'' he said. ``The question was 'how do we protect the
average person on their donations?' and help them avoid harassing
solicitation letters, be they political or otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In a controversial ruling in March, Attorney General John
Cornyn, responding to a question from the Ethics Commission, said
addresses should also be excluded from computer diskettes.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said that ``there's no privacy issue at stake,'' since
the addresses are available on paper, and that it ``is nearly
impossible to tell who a donor is,'' without more information than
a name.
</P>
<P>
   Texans for Public Justice, which does not advocate online
postings of addresses, will file a formal request with the ethics
commission to make addresses available on computer diskettes. If
the request is denied, the group plans to sue the commission,
McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Cornyn's opinion stands,'' he said, ``if electronic
disclosure is undermined by his opinion and rendered almost
ineffective, we have no choice but to go to court.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
