<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-INVESTMENT-CLU     07-17 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-INVESTMENT-CLUBS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APING WALL STREET PROS, ONLINE INVESTMENT CLUBS GAINING
POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brittany Christ had bounced between three 401(k) plans in 12
years. She had been through a raft of Fidelity funds and bought
shares in Intel, Oracle and Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   She had even kept up with the latest books on investing. But it
was the Web that finally inspired her to form the Dart Throwin'
Monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Christ, 30, who works for Verizon
Communications in St. Petersburg, Fla., whipped together the
investment club in a few months by recruiting members in an online
chat room at Motley Fool, a Web site devoted to investor education.
</P>
<P>
   After enlisting a soldier, a lawyer, a software engineer, a
fireman, a toy store manager, another telecommunications worker and
``two administrative types,'' Christ and the eight other Dart
Throwin' Monkeys (more on that later) turned to Bivio, a new
Internet company based in Boulder, Colo., that offers services for
investment clubs, to build a private site where they could
communicate, store minutes from their meetings and keep tabs on
which member was worth what, when.
</P>
<P>
   The Dart Throwin' Monkeys could not be confused with the
Beardstown Ladies. After all, some of the Ladies, affable elders
from Beardstown, Ill., who created a cottage industry around their
investment club in the mid-90s before an accounting error deflated
their returns, say they still do not even have computers.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Monkeys are a new breed, taking advantage of a new crop
of Internet companies offering one-stop shops for investment clubs
at no cost. These companies merge communication tools with software
engines that handle complex administrative bookkeeping functions
and compile tax returns. And although sites like Motley Fool have
long provided a forum for investment club members, the new sites
take the clubs one step further.
</P>
<P>
   Bivio and another fledgling company, Actifunds of Cambridge,
Mass., also act as digital matchmaking services for people who want
to form clubs. Bivio, which opened in December has already signed
up 1,700 clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment clubs, in contrast to mutual funds or the brokerage
industry, are a cottage industry,'' said Robert Brooker, chairman
of Actifunds, which is completing its seed round of financing
before it opens shop. ``That's why we look at the total amount of
assets in investment clubs, we believe about $10 billion, as just
the beginning of the growth.''
</P>
<P>
   A third Internet venture, Foliofn, which began in May, lets
investors cheaply assemble mutual fund-like portfolios and plans to
expand its services to accommodate investment clubs. And message
board sites, operated by prominent Internet companies, are paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investment club space is an important space,'' said Bryan
Burdick, the top executive at Silicon Investor, a stock chat site
that is a unit of Go2Net. ``We think it's a natural fit for the
Silicon Investor community.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, more than 36,000 domestic clubs with an estimated
$1.5 billion in assets are members of the National Association of
Investors Corp., a 49-year-old nonprofit organization that has been
the main resource for investment clubs until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are craving ways to bring other people into their
investing experience, that's why the stock discussion sites are so
popular,'' said Ion Yadigaroglu, 30, co-founder and chief executive
of Bivio. Two years ago, Yadigaroglu formed his own club, named
Cosmic Returns Into the Far Horizons. It was an epiphany for
Yadigaroglu, an astronomer who grew up in the United States and
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent time at Stanford University in Palo Alto, Calif.,
studying astrophysics, and having had Jeff Skoll, eBay's first
employee, as one of his roommates, the Internet was on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent '92 to '97 in Palo Alto, so you couldn't avoid the
Internet, you couldn't avoid being involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is so enthusiastic about his new online
venture. Bivio's software application that matches new users to
existing members has led executives of the nonprofit group to
question whether online solicitations run afoul of Securities and
Exchange Commission regulations.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the notion of connecting people who might not all
contribute equally. In such cases, an investment club might be
subject to regulation as a mutual fund, according to SEC rules.
Membership interests in a club are considered securities ``if
members invest and expect to make a profit from the entrepreneurial
and managerial efforts of others,'' the agency's Web site says, as
opposed to sharing in stock picking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got an investment club and you advertise for
members, you're selling securities,'' said Robert O'Hara, a vice
president of National Association of Investors Corp. ``The SEC
frowns on that kind of activity. We have 117 chapters around the
country, and they are not allowed to advertise that they have clubs
looking for members.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has not made any direct comment on Bivio or the concept
behind it, but one former official said she did not see a problem
in the online migration of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural evolution that clubs would move online and do
most of their organizational work online,'' said Nancy Smith, a
securities lawyer and former director of the SEC Office of Investor
Education and Assistance, who now works for Foliofn.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason for the National Association of Investors Corp.
to see Bivio as something of a threat. While the association
primarily considers itself an educational organization, it does
sell accounting software. Bivio gives it away. Even so, Phyllis
Pawlovsky, a former president of the New York chapter of the
association, sits on Bivio's advisory board and thinks the two are
complementary.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``As a member of both organizations, I feel that both do their
share in increasing investment opportunities for the little guy,''
she said. ``NAIC teaches you how to evaluate companies. Bivio lets
you do it online and join an online community.''
</P>
<P>
   A more pressing question might be whether these companies can be
profitable. Bivio makes money by directing its users to third-party
services advertised on its site, like an online broker called
Buy-and-Hold.com, and then sharing the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these companies are indeed successful at creating a
compelling proposition for community investing and then use that to
extend relationships with the online brokerages, then it would
indeed be very valuable,'' said Andrew Goldfarb, who runs the
Boston office of the venture capital firm Jafco Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Offline or online, the intent of investment clubs now seems
about the same as it ever was: to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Christ had read Suze Orman, the personal finance empowerment
guru, and Peter Lynch, the former manager of Fidelity Magellan, and
the Beardstown Ladies' best sellers. Still, she did not feel like
she knew that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself between a beginner and a novice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Monkeys have ponied up a total of $985 after their
first round of monthly dues, about $30 to $50. Now, they are
weighing the merits of Kmart versus Target and Oracle versus Sun
Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Web aside, they still do some things the old way. Christ
picked from a Florida-focused Motley Fool board, so her club could
meet once a month in person. And the Monkeys prefer to pay for
National Association of Investors Corp.'s accounting software,
rather than totally entrust their bookkeeping to the free tools
offered by an untested dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   So what about that name? Christ explains that another member
lifted it from the 1973 best seller ``A Random Walk Down Wall
Street,'' by Burton Malkeil. In the book, Malkeil, a Princeton
professor, says a blind-folded primate tossing darts at the
business section of a newspaper could outperform the average
investment professional.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Malkeil actually wrote of a dart-throwing
chimpanzee. But whatever the animal, the Monkeys are confident they
can hit the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can do better than the experts on Wall Street,''
Christ said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
