<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4912 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MUSLIM-HOSTAGE-EXCLUS     07-17 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSLIM-HOSTAGE-EXCLUSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED HOSTAGE FEARFUL FOR FATE OF HUSBAND, SON, 16 OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines _ Looking shellshocked and disoriented as
tears of relief melted into a smile, an ailing German housewife _
released by Muslim rebels Monday after 85 days in the jungle _ took
her first wobbly steps of freedom at a military airbase here. She
said she hoped the remaining 18 captives, including her husband and
son, would soon follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling very happy to be released, but not 100 percent,
because the others are still hostage,'' said Renate Wallert, 56.
Wallert, who was suffering from high-blood pressure, chronic
anxiety, and other ailments after 12 weeks of captivity, was helped
out of a helicopter and leaned on an official's arm as she
staggered forward in a pair of yellow rubber beach thongs.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first Western hostage freed by the rebels, a
bittersweet gift for her 34th wedding anniversary since her husband
and 25-year old son were still captive.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in the hostage crisis that has dragged on for
three months _ punctuated by a failed military rescue, a rotating
team of negotiators, and a month-long hiatus in talks _ raised hope
that a deal as being cut so that the rest of the captives might
soon walk free.
</P>
<P>
   Wallert was one of 21 people snatched from a SCUBA diving resort
on the Malaysian island of Sipidan on April 23, Easter Sunday. The
group was transferred by boat to a jungle redoubt on Jolo Island in
the Philippines' Mindanao region, a base for Abu Sayyaf, a
breakaway faction of Muslim separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers demanded $1 million for each hostage and an
independent Muslim state. The government tried a military assault
instead, spurring the rebels to move the hostages and leaving talks
in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike two larger separatist groups with a clearer ideology who
have conducted a protracted guerrilla struggle, the Abu Sayyaf has
operated like bandits, taking hostages and demanding ransoms since
the death of their charismatic founder in December 1998. Earlier
this year they abducted 41 Filipinos, including schoolchildren, and
killed three of those hostages.
</P>
<P>
   All three groups operate in the mostly Muslim southern region of
Mindanao in this heavily Roman Catholic nation, with three million
to four million Muslims among 72 million people. Mindanao enjoyed
centuries of self-rule before Spanish colonization, but today it is
one of the country's poorest regions
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf had earlier released two Malaysian hostages, both
Muslims, but the prospects of freedom for the others looked slim
after the rebels refused to release Wallert when she became ill, or
a pregnant South African who miscarried a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia said from the outset that it would pay for the release
of its nationals and opened back-channel negotiations, infuriating
Manila. When the second Malaysian was released Friday, chief
Philippines negotiator Robert Aventajado said Malaysia had offered
to invest in development programs in the impoverished region, but
he denied that any ransom was paid. Other officials said privately,
however, that no one has ever been released by Abu Sayyaf without a
payment of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Jawa Selamat, the Malaysian hostage freed Friday, said
rebel chief Galib Andang, known as ``Commander Robot,'' had said
all hostages might be released soon. The rebels still hold two
Germans, seven Malaysians, two French, two Finns, two South
Africans, two Filipinos and a Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a German magazine reporter and three members
of a French television crew were abducted, as well as 13 Filipino
evangelists who went to the rebel camp to pray. In May, armed men
seized a group of German reporters and released them only after
$25,000 ransom was paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sorting out the demands as to which are doable and
which are not,'' Aventajado said Sunday. ``We are addressing the
root cause of the problem, which is poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Andang, the rebel leader, revised his demands to include
government assistance for projects to improve people's livehlihood
on Jolo, including developing an orange plantation on land he
controls turning it into a cooperative, Aventajado said. Other
negotiators said Abu Sayyaf was no longer demanding a Muslim
homeland, but still wanted the ransom money.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Guillermo Ruiz Ruiz, who went with Aventajado to
retrieve Wallert, said she was trembling and had covered her face
with her scarf when she was released from her captors' Jeep and
turned over to officials at a location outside the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was crying. She didn't actually know what was happening
until Secretary Aventajado identified himself and assured her she
was safe,'' said Ruiz, security adviser for the negotiating team.
``She didn't know if they were planning to kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said Wallert's mood brightened on the helicopter ride from
Jolo to Zamboanga, and that she snapped pictures out the window of
``the beautiful islands'' and of the negotitators who secured her
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   On April 28, a spokesman for Abu Sayyaf threatened to behead the
hostages if their demands were not met. On May 3, they moved the
hostages after Philippines troops fired into the camp. The hostages
were moved nearly 10 times, carrying Wallert on a stretcher each
time. A Finish hostage wrote a letter recently saying they were
near suicide from despair.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the others, Wallert said, ``They are very sad all
the time. They are sitting, waiting for release.''
</P>
<P>
   Clad in blue batik beach pants and a green shirt, she was flown
Monday evening to Manila and on to Germany to be reunited with her
other son.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Gloria, a fellow at the Ateneo Center for Social Policy
and Public Affairs in Manila and co-author of a newly-released book
on the Muslim rebels, described the Abu Sayyaf as ``loose,
reckless, heavily-armed . . . and linked to corrupt soldiers and
businessmen.'' She called the group ``a long-term security problem
for governments in southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Abu Sayyaf is not truly pushing for an independent Islamic
state,'' she said. ``This is a group that doesn't know what it
wants. They are making money off a political cause.'' She said the
group collected $50,000 from ransoms and payments demanded from the
foreign media covering the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine government and European countries with nationals
among the hostages have maintained a strict no-ransom stance, and
Aventajado insisted that no money had been paid for Wallert's
release. ``It was a goodwill gesture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Abu Sayyaf had been offered immunity from
prosecution, Ruiz refused to answer directly, saying, ``I guess
later on that could be taken up. . . . It will depend on the
negotations.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the Philippine army said about 100 suspected
members of a larger Muslim rebel group, the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front, killed 21 Christians, including a pregnant woman, in a
mosque in another part of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
   The group denied the accusation, saying it would never desecrate
a mosque, and suggested that the military was involved in the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Marites Danguilan Vitug, co-author with Gloria of ``Under the
Crescent Moon: Rebellion in Mindanao,'' said the hostage crises,
along with renewed fighting between the government and Liberation
Front, has ``opened very old anti-Muslim sentiment among
Christians. . . . That's a very painful division now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
