<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAGEAR-GREENBERGS-ART     07-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAGEAR-GREENBERGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENBERGS LIVING DOWN L.A. GEAR TROUBLES WITH SUCCESS AT
SKECHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Slug for this story was originally
SKECHERS-LAGEAR-GREENBERGS) 
 By KRUTI TRIVEDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Greenberg, the founder and president of the trendy shoe
company Skechers, is so determined to get his company's message out
that he follows a written outline when he recites a list of recent
feats.
</P>
<P>
   Skechers (pronounced SKETCH-ers), he says deliberately and
between glances at the crumpled bit of paper in front of him in the
company's booth last month at the Fashion Footwear Association of
New York exposition, is now the third most popular brand among
teen-agers, after Nike and Adidas. Company sales, he adds, jumped
40 percent last quarter compared with a year earlier. And as
retailers are becoming choosier about which shoe brands to stock,
both Lord &AMP; Taylor and Athlete's Foot have just signed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a Gap of footwear,'' Greenberg, 37, said, ``I
believe that Skechers would be that company.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's dogged focus shows as much about his ambitions as
about his determination to leave behind what many analysts see as a
nagging past.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Skechers USA Inc., based in Manhattan Beach, Calif.,
seems to be something of a find. As the shoe business slowly
revives from its recent slump, the small, 8-year-old family-run
company is leading the charge. Its winning formula is simple:
Skechers makes lower-priced versions of popular shoes like the
latest high performance Nikes and dress loafers by Kenneth Cole.
And its stock has been among the market's best performers this
year.
</P>
<P>
   That meteoric rise, however, followed a steep decline after
Skechers' initial public offering in June 1999 _ a sign, analysts
say, of concern that the company has some uncomfortable parallels
with the last Greenberg family project, L.A. Gear Inc., one of the
retailing industry's most spectacular collapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greenbergs are going to have to prove that Skechers is not
L.A. Gear,'' said John Shanley, a senior vice president at Security
Van Kaspar who once followed L.A. Gear.
</P>
<P>
   It was Robert Greenberg, Michael Greenberg's father, who founded
L.A. Gear and is widely blamed for its implosion. And while Michael
Greenberg founded Skechers _ as a distributor for Doc Martens
footwear _ and is its public face and spokesman, his father is the
company's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Greenberg sold everything from wigs to roller skates
before he stumbled on the idea that would make him famous: a
modestly priced hybrid of performance and fashion shoe that women
could wear while doing aerobics. L.A. Gear's revenues shot up from
$70.6 million in 1987 to $900 million in 1990, making it the third
largest in the country, after Nike and Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   But in a path that is almost unheard of for companies that flirt
with the billion-dollar mark, L.A. Gear fell apart almost as
quickly as it had grown. The stock, which hit a high of $50.125 in
1990, had tumbled to $11 by 1992. The company eventually filed for
protection under Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say L.A. Gear expanded too quickly. While the company
had been successful with stylish aerobic shoes, by 1991 it was
offering customers 500 different styles of shoes and apparel. The
expansion was poorly timed, occurring as the strongest growth in
the shoe industry was in men's athletic shoes _ a market that L.A.
Gear, perceived as a women's and children's shoemaker, never could
capture. The result was a retailer's nightmare: crate-loads of
inventory in the still-weak economy of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Legal problems also plagued the operation. L.A. Gear signed a
marketing deal with Michael Jackson in 1989 in an attempt to win
over men; when that strategy failed, the company entered a lengthy
breach-of-contract suit and counter suit tussle with Jackson. Both
Nike and Reebok also fought legal battles with L.A. Gear, claiming
that the company had illegally used their patented technology. All
the suits were eventually settled.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Greenberg and five other executives were the subject of
five shareholder securities fraud suits filed in 1990 and 1991. The
class action suits contended that members of the L.A. Gear
management team had issued public documents containing ``materially
false and misleading statements'' about the company that led to
L.A. Gear's stock becoming ``artificially inflated,'' according to
the settlement papers. The defendants eventually settled for a
total of $29.8 million without admitting or denying guilt.
</P>
<P>
   After losses began to mount and the company's credit line was
cut, Robert Greenberg was forced to sell a 30 percent minority
stake worth $100 million of preferred stock to Trefoil Capital
Investors, an investment fund founded by Roy Disney, nephew of the
late Walt Disney, and cede much of his control of the company. The
Trefoil team eventually ousted him in January 1992 and dismissed
Michael Greenberg, then an L.A. Gear national sales manager, soon
after.
</P>
<P>
   Trefoil bailed out in late 1997, after failing to turn the
company around. Under PCH Investments, which currently controls the
company, L.A. Gear entered and emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection in 1998 a much more modest operation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Greenberg insists that his family was unfairly
disparaged over L.A. Gear's tumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get that company to $900 million by accident,'' he
said. If given the chance, he added, his family could have saved
the company.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the inevitable comparisons with L.A. Gear,
Skechers officials say their company is closely monitoring its
growth, will license rather than make apparel and is just as
popular with men as with women.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Greenberg founded Skechers _ street slang meaning
frenetic teen-agers _ in 1992, just months after leaving L.A. Gear.
He convinced his father and David Weinberg, a former L.A. Gear
executive whom he describes as a ``member of the family,'' to join
his company in October 1993. Three of his brothers are currently
vice presidents at Skechers; a fourth manages the Skechers Sport
brand of sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales grew steadily, as the Greenbergs capitalized
on the shoe industry contacts they made in their years at L.A. Gear
to make sure that Skechers displays were given prime retail space.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, were wary. When Skechers went public in June
1999, the company had reduced its offering price and the number of
shares it offered. Even so, the stock lost value in its first day
of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company prices at $11 and then opens trading at $10.50,
that's generally kind of a sign of weakness,'' said Omar Sacirbey,
a senior editor at The IPO Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Greenberg declined to comment for this article. But Lloyd
Grief, a close acquaintance of the family and president of Grief &AMP;
Co. of Los Angeles, the investment bank that took L.A. Gear public
in 1986, said, ``I think he was stunned with his stock's original
reception.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor fears seemed justified when, just as its predecessor
had, Skechers ran into both inventory and legal troubles. Soon
after the initial offering, the company reported losses for the
third quarter of 1999, the period that is generally the strongest
in the shoe industry because of back-to-school sales. The company
had too many shoes in the retail channel and floundered when its
platform sneakers fell out of style, problems eerily similar to
those that had plagued L.A. Gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that kind of situation, especially when it comes
so soon after doing a public offering, institutions are very
wary,'' said Harry Katica, vice president for research at
Prudential Securities, one of Skechers' underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, a group of shareholders sued, contending that
the company had misled investors by not disclosing in its initial
filing that it was having legal problems with R. Griggs Group.
Griggs, the maker of Doc Martens shoes, sued its former business
partner five days after the offering, saying that Skechers had
pirated its designs for men's boots. Skechers stock, which had been
heading steadily downward, fell to its all-time low of $3.25 in
January, after the company announced that two more shareholder
suits had been filed. A total of five suits have now been filed;
the consolidated lawsuit is pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit is completely frivolous,'' Michael Greenberg said
in a prepared statement. ``Skechers vehemently denies violating any
of the security laws and believes all disclosures were made on a
timely basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Greenbergs' luck may be beginning to change. In March,
the company settled with Griggs and announced that 1999 net sales
rose almost 14 percent from 1998, to $424.6 million, despite the
unusually poor third quarter. The following month, the shares
finally regained their initial public offering price. Then, in May,
Skechers announced a blow-out first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   All this good news has led many analysts to believe that
Skechers may indeed be able to step out from behind the L.A. Gear
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Skechers, with its 900 different styles, is doing a good job
executing its strategy of being ``everyone and everything'' in
footwear, said David Turner, an analyst at Ferris, Baker Watts.
</P>
<P>
   The company's newest styles, like its Energy brand gym shoes,
have reignited interest among teen-agers. They have gone from being
on the ``uncool'' list last fall to the ``cool list'' this summer,
said Kevin Ume, president of element Holdings Inc., a marketing
firm that specializes in research on the buying habits of
teen-agers. During the back-to-school sales season, Skechers will
even be displayed at the high visibility area in Lady Foot Lockers
where the mall meets the store, a coveted spot usually reserved for
Nike.
</P>
<P>
   And right behind the teens are the investors, who seem willing
to forget the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skechers has not been on our coverage list but in the last
couple months it's just popped up,'' said Allison Boswell,
president of Allison Boswell Consulting, a group that surveys shoe
buyers. ``They were considered one of the top three fashion trend
setting brands. They were also named as a brand that would be
expected to have very high back-to-school increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Greenberg notes with a broad smile that the company's
stock is well above its initial price: shares closed Monday at
$16.375, a record high.
</P>
<P>
   Such successes are seen as vindication by the Greenbergs, who
are dreaming big again. ``I think Wall Street understands one
thing, and that's show me the numbers and deliver,'' Michael
Greenberg said. ``I think they're getting on board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
