<SLUG> BC-ABC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: IT WILL BE HARD TO ESCAPE FROM ABC'S FALL LINEUP
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ABC will begin a promotion campaign for its
fall lineup that seems intent on all but stalking viewers, forcing
them to be aware of ABC shows in almost every waking moment of
their lives _ when they withdraw cash from an ATM machine, shop in
the supermarket or use the urinal at the local bar and grill.
</P>
<P>
   And if the network does not find you in those places, it may
leave a message about its new comedy, ``Madigan Men,'' starring
Gabriel Byrne, waiting on your telephone answering machine when you
get home.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, part of the Walt Disney Co., is the network that has
promoted itself for several years with ads described by Madison
Avenue as ``the yellow campaign,'' after the predominant color of
the TV and print pitches. For the 2000-2001 season, ABC is changing
its theme from ``America's broadcasting company,'' used during the
1999-2000 season, to ``ABC . . . definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the ``yellow'' ads, which sought to create an
identity for the entire network as well as encourage viewership of
specific shows, were derided, but they have eventually gained
widespread recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the elements of the new campaign are a tie-in with KFC
restaurants, where yellow ABC promotions will be wrapped around 7
million buckets of fried chicken; floor ads in supermarkets with
yellow ABC squares on the linoleum promoting shows; and yellow
placards on ATM machines with Regis Philbin of ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' using lines like, ``It's a shame you can't withdraw
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But surely the parts of the campaign, created in-house, that
will draw most attention are the decision to call viewers at home
in the 10 biggest cities, leaving messages to watch the ABC Friday
night lineup of comedies, and the plan to display pictures of Norm
MacDonald of the comedy ``Norm'' behind urinals in New York and Los
Angeles, with catchy copy phrases like ``Another fine use of the
color yellow.'' Meanwhile, a motion-activated device will crank up
his voice uttering invitations to watch his series between comments
appropriate to the locations like, ``Hey, watch your shoes!''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cohen, the executive vice president of marketing and
advertising for ABC, said the network believed the yellow campaign
had made ABC ``the most recognized brand in television.'' The new
campaign is designed to reinforce the playful image of ABC's
promotions, he added, as well as what he called ``our uniqueness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ABC has placed ads on tops of taxi cabs and in the
sand on beaches as well as in unexpected places like candy bowls at
restaurants, bus benches and pizza boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The urinals ads are the work of the Los Angeles based company
Zoom Media, which has been posting ads and promotions in bathrooms
for 10 years. Zoom sells ads in about 15 cities in the United
States and Canada, with signs in stalls in women's bathrooms and
behind urinals in men's rooms. (ABC is sticking to men's rooms, at
least for the moment.) The ads are mainly aimed at young adults
ages 18 to 35, and thus are concentrated in places like bars,
nightclubs and health clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ABC plans on running the urinal ads only in New York and Los
Angeles, Cohen said, starting about four weeks before the new
episodes of ``Norm'' appear, which is now expected to be in
October.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plan to call viewers at home to push ``Madigan Men,''
Cohen said that ABC would use a form of technology that only
activates when it reaches an answering machine. Thus if someone
actually picks up the phone, the lines will go dead _ just the way
your average movie stalker might do.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that does not qualify as overt harassment, Cohen and
his partner, Michael Benson, the senior vice president of
advertising and promotion, defended the plan by saying that they
would be, in Cohen's words, ``sensitive to consumers' comments, if
we get that kind of feedback.'' He specified he meant feedback in
the form of calls and e-mails from viewers, not comments from
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see it as harassment,'' Cohen said, adding that it
was merely another step in the aggressive ``brand campaign that got
us noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson said of the overall campaign, ``We like to find unique
ways to talk to people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
