eruptions of Confederate fervor point to a culture that was dealt
with too leniently. We may know the political and economic
rationale that led to relatively easy reintegration of the South
into the fabric of the nation, but that doesn't mean we can't
regret the current consequences. By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ It is tempting to label Project
Vote Smart an oxymoron, in deference to the disrespect that many
voters and nonvoters alike heap upon our political system and the
politicians who prevail on Election Day. In truth, it is a project
that is attempting to make politics more respectable by encouraging
more people to vote and helping them to cast their ballots in an
informed manner. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BASHING (Houston) _ It quite rightly can be expected that
anyone who is a Democrat can, and likely will, talk tacky about the
Republican governor of Texas. But let's get one thing straight.
Talking bad about George W. Bush is one thing. Talking bad about
Texas is quite another. By JANE ELY. (Already filed.)
