<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-STROGANOFFBARONESS-2T     07-17 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROGANOFFBARONESS-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST STROGANOFF RETAINS VITAL ASSET: FORCE OF CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By WAYNE LEE GAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Baroness Helene de Ludinghausen sits on a
bench in the Kimbell Art Museum, surrounded by millions of dollars
worth of paintings, sculpture and decorative items that belonged to
her ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few feet of her are late medieval icons, pre-Columbian
and antique Chinese artifacts, and priceless paintings by
Botticelli, Poussin, Watteau and Van Dyck. There is also a lavishly
decorated, 11-foot-long, fine-print contract from 1692, in which
Czar Peter the Great grants immense privileges, as well as a
tax-free status, to one of his favorite subjects, de Ludinghausen's
great-great-great-great-great-great-great-grandfather, Grigory
Stroganoff.
</P>
<P>
   Baroness de Ludinghausen, 58, is the ``last of the
Stroganoffs,'' the scion of the Russian aristocratic family that,
for 500 years _ from the late Middle Ages until the Russian
Revolution in 1917 _ controlled a significant percentage of
Russia's land and answered only to the czar. A cross section of the
family's monumental artistic investments _ second only to the
collection of the imperial family _ is on display through Oct. 1 at
the Kimbell Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although her ancestors lost claim to the land and art when they
fled Russia during the revolution, de Ludinghausen displays the
personality that kept her family on good terms with the rulers of
Russia through five centuries.
</P>
<P>
   She is a working woman who doesn't live a life of privilege. De
Ludinghausen studied hard while growing up in Europe and the
Americas, and works at one of the most prestigious commercial
establishments in the world, the fashion house of Yves Saint
Laurent in Paris. Instead of aristocratic aloofness, she radiates
warmth and the conviviality of a natural-born politician or
salesman.
</P>
<P>
   From her ancestors, she says, ``I think I got a great love and
respect of everything beautiful. And I have a sense of fairness
toward people. I don't like people to be treated badly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stroganoffs first surface in history as a merchant family in
the early 15th century, and they earned the Renaissance era's
equivalent of megabucks when they discovered and mined salt in
northern Russia _ much like the Texans who made fortunes in
petroleum early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   The first Russian conquests in Siberia were financed and
directed by members of the Stroganoff family, who hired the
infamous Cossack outlaw Yermak to lead an army of mercenaries into
the frontier region. The gratitude of Czar Ivan the Terrible, who
granted monumental privileges in gratitude for their help, taught
the Stroganoffs a lesson they never forgot; they maintained firm,
friendly relations with the imperial family through the centuries,
always ready to help out with their now immense private wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew how to change, how to diversify,'' de Ludinghausen
says. By the end of the 16th century, the family employed around
6,000 workers in agriculture, mining and fur-trading, and owned 8.5
million acres in Siberia. The Stroganoff school of icon painting,
the last great flowering of medieval-style religious art, emerged
under their patronage, reflecting the wealth and the religious
devotion of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the Russian aristocracy, the Stroganoffs became
westernized during the 18th century. They learned to speak French
and built a palace in St. Petersburg, where a French chef invented
the mixture of sauce and meat immortalized in recipe books,
restaurants and grocery-store frozen food sections as ``beef
Stroganoff.''
</P>
<P>
   A Russian vernacular proverb says, ``Richer than the Stroganoffs
you'll never be.'' The immensely wealthy family collected, with
genetic good taste, a remarkable collection of international art.
</P>
<P>
   And, although thoroughly entrenched in the ruling class, members
of the Stroganoff family constantly advocated reform of the sort
which, if their advice had been followed, might have averted the
Bolshevik Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   De Ludinghausen's grandfather died before the revolution; her
mother, Xenia Ludinghausen-Wolff, escaped from Russia in 1919 on a
ship provided by the queen of Italy, sailing through the Black Sea
with her siblings, members of the imperial family, and her mother,
Princess Sonia Vasilichikovich.
</P>
<P>
   There were no Swiss bank accounts for the Stroganoffs; they left
their property and their fabulous collections in Russia. A few
members of the aristocracy managed to transfer their wealth, or had
extensive holdings in the west, but the heirs of the Stroganoffs
had to work for a living.
</P>
<P>
   And they were not the villains that postrevolutionary propaganda
depicts, according to Stephen R. de Angelis, an American cultural
historian currently living in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a jaundiced view that we have of a corrupt, profligate
society,'' he says. ``You wouldn't have any of the greatness of
Russia without these people. Look in the St. Petersburg phone
directory of 1908. It's full of listings for charitable
organizations, for the homeless, for hospitals, for homes for unwed
mothers, all of which were supported by the Romanoffs and the
aristocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   De Ludinghausen's father, Baron Andre Ludinghausen-Wolff, was an
aristocrat whose family had moved to Russia in the late Renaissance
_ hence the Franco-German surname. De Ludinghausen herself was born
in Paris in 1942, during the Nazi occupation, but spent most of her
childhood in Brazil, where her father worked for an American
corporation. She finished her high school education at the Kent
Denver School, a private girls' school in Denver, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard that American high school would be easy,'' she
says. ``But it was the hardest school I ever went to. All the girls
in my class were motivated. They had a tremendous sense of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing her college education in Switzerland, she went
to work for an antiques dealer in Paris _ where, one day, renowned
fashion designer Yves Saint Laurent overheard her speaking in her
husky voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, ``Is this your voice or do you have a cold?' ''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent apparently liked the voice, and the person behind
it, for he hired her shortly thereafter as an international
representative for his ready-to-wear line. Two years later, when
she was just 28, he made her director of the haute couture salon in
Paris, where she replaced a woman 40 years older. Because of her
youth, she had to work hard to gain the confidence of the
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be scary for a woman to come up those stairs to the
salon,'' she says. ``I make her feel comfortable. I tell her that
our clothes are so beautifully made that they will make her look
the best she can look.''
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Deroche, public relations director for the salon,
extols the baroness' style. ``She's a strong professional,''
Deroche says. ``Cheerful and dynamic. And she has extremely good
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   And a sense of humor too. When asked how she felt the first time
she walked past a frozen food case and saw the packaged beef
Stroganoff, she says, laughing, ``I've had beef Stroganoff that I
didn't like. But I wish that I could earn royalties on the name.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, she met her future husband, Robin Smyth-Ryland, an
English gentleman farmer and fox-hunting enthusiast from
Warwickshire, at a cocktail party in Manhattan. Fluent in French,
Russian, English and Portuguese, and at home in England, France,
the United States or Brazil, de Ludinghausen always considered
herself Russian, though she never visited Russia until after the
fall of communism in 1991. Then, steeped in the history of her
family, she made her first visit to Russia and vowed to preserve
her family's artistic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   She established the Ludinghausen Foundation, based in New York,
because many of its supporters are American, and Americans, she
says, are better at setting up foundations than the French. She
began leading tours to St. Petersburg, Russia, soliciting
contributions and turning over any profits from the tours to the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 300 people have visited St. Petersburg under her
guidance. On one very moving occasion, she returned to the city of
the Stroganoff salt mines, Solvychegodsk, where, as the first
representative of her family to visit the city in over 200 years,
she was greeted by an official contingent, schoolchildren in folk
costumes and traditional gifts of bread and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she has formed strong opinions about what should
happen in modern Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a monarchist,'' she says, meaning that she
would favor eventual restoration of a crowned head of state in
Russia. And she wants a return to centralized, authoritative rule
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like order and discipline,'' she says. ``There's not much of
that there, now. Russia needs to clean up, in every sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to start helping people. I tell them that they are
the new aristocracy, but they are acting like thieves. Freedom
doesn't mean just doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   De Ludinghausen's sense of organization _ and her extroverted
personality _ paid off with the organization of the Kimbell
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Penelope Hunter-Stiebel, the New York-based curator who
organized the exhibition for the Portland Art Museum in Oregon and
the Kimbell, was at first reluctant to take on an additional
project.
</P>
<P>
   But a meeting with de Ludinghausen in St. Petersburg persuaded
her to become involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a modern, working woman who has not lost one iota of
the Stroganoff heritage,'' Hunter-Stiebel says. ``Her vision is
clear. She is direct and forceful. To the core of her being, she is
Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was de Ludinghausen's attitude about what the exhibition
should be that finally swayed Hunter-Stiebel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said that this is not about how rich her family was,''
Hunter-Stiebel says. ``She said that she wanted the exhibition to
be a window on Russian culture, so that Americans can understand
Russia.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2004EDT &QL; 
