<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MISSTEXAS-3TAKES-TEX     07-17 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSTEXAS-3TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRANSFORMATION OF MISS RIO GRANDE VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: No period in Dr Pepper and Mrs Baird's Bakery is cq). 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I drive past the pale taupe house in Haltom City, Texas, which
abuts Fort Worth on its northeast side. Surely this unassuming,
low-slung residence can't be a renowned training center for a
legion of Miss Texas contestants. But once out of the car, I hear
confirmation. The house is leaking the unmistakable sound of a ``My
Fair Lady'' metamorphosis in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute, Jennifer. Stop there. Now, you know there is an
`r' in `your,' '' exhorts Mary McMullin, with a perfect blend of
cajoling and care. McMullin has been affiliated with the Miss Texas
pageant for 34 years, in a hyphenated position as executive
director-groomer-coach-trusted confidante to many very compliant
contestants. McMullin's refrigerator door acts as a casual trophy
case for her past successes, as evidenced by the picture of a
beaming Tatum Hubbard, 1998's Miss Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Jennifer Sharlow,'' McMullin intones, a
no-nonsense interrogator. ``Your platform issue is alcohol
awareness. Please talk to us about that. And while you're at it,
what is the state flower?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluebonnet, ma'am,'' Sharlow responds, unblinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state tree?'' McMullin probes.
</P>
<P>
   Pause. A furrow creeps across a young forehead rarely creased by
life's worries. Finally, a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pecan,'' Sharlow announces confidently.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sharlow comes across the one word that needs more
pronunciation guidance than others. ``Now, Jennifer,'' McMullin
reminds her acolyte. ``Remember, there isn't an `i' in `Texas.'
It's TEX-as.''' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am, `Tex-as.' `Tejas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's an endearing touch that Sharlow throws in the Spanish name
for her beloved home state. Such is Sharlow's adoration of all
things Lone Star, and the Miss Texas competition, that she will
work overtime to deliver the name of the state with chest-thumping
pride and proper-vowel diction. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one-year-old Jennifer Sharlow, the proud Miss Rio Grande
Valley (one of numerous regional pageants open to any state
resident), knows going in that the odds are stacked against her
even making the top 10. She's a first-year Miss Texas contestant
competing against 57 regional title holders, many of whom will
arrive with more experience and financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that matters for such a greenhorn as Sharlow. Just
stepping on the klieg-flooded stage at Will Rogers Memorial Center
Auditorium in front of a live audience will be a pageant summit,
culminating years and years of preparation, personal
consciousness-raising, working out, and, of course, some hair
spray.
</P>
<P>
   If one accepts the cliche that a beauty pageant can represent an
Emerald City escape hatch from a small-town existence, well,
Jennifer Sharlow's hometown, in size anyway, certainly qualifies.
Brock, a hamlet half an hour west of Fort Worth with a population
of around 1,000, has no movie theater or McDonalds, and makes do
with one country store, more serious necessities being available at
the Parker County seat of Weatherford. And Sharlow, in her
unfettered warmth and fervent desire to ``do right by others'' is
the archetypal small-town loyalist. Such is Sharlow's homespun
geniality that she could seamlessly fit into Thornton Wilder's
``Our Town.'' She's the kind of woman who has already made plans to
give her future husband the silver cross ring she received on her
16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Mary McMullin's Thursday-night training session, Sharlow
is a long way from Main Street, Brock. She is central-casting
ingenue, her chestnut hair falling gently about her white T-shirted
shoulders. Sharlow's first instinct is to smile, and hers is a
panorama of Chiclets teeth forming the essential facial gesture of
every Miss Texas contestant. As for Sharlow's laugh, it's an
abundant creation.
</P>
<P>
   It is T minus 11 days before Sharlow's nail-biting Miss Texas
personal interview, a grueling 12-minute session in which a
tribunal of seven judges will grill her on her chosen ``platform''
social issue of alcohol awareness. This subject hits a personal
chord for Sharlow. Her hands begin to wag and her cafe-con-leche
eyes brim with moistness as she wrestles with the sorrow over her
four friends killed by a drunken driver in a now infamous 1998
accident on the road to Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make eye contact with the judges when you talk about this,''
gently counsels coach McMullin. ``And just remember to be concise
and summarize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes ma'am,'' Sharlow gulps. ``Of course, the accident affected
my life,'' Sharlow says in a voice heavy with emotion. Then, in a
more pageant-ready tone: ``And, of course, I completely support
Mothers Against Drunk Driving. The more you talk about this issue,
the easier it is to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   With the substance of Sharlow's platform behind her, it's time
for the style. The interview demands just the right business suit,
flattering with not the least whiff of frivolity. Her selection is
a double-breasted, cobalt-blue outfit, off-the-rack from Dillards.
Matching blue pumps lend Sharlow even more just-so integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we are not going for a sexy look here but just
something classic, perfect for church or a date,'' observes
McMullin sagely.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow disappears behind a wall in Mary McMullin's pantry to
begin phase two of this late June evening's training session. She
soon emerges in a blinding magenta swimsuit that is cut as a hybrid
bikini-gym workout suit. As she circles around a sofa, Sharlow has
to balance on heels, suck in her stomach, avoid letting her
shoulders roll forward, and, as always, flash a smile so broad it
must make her cheekbones sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's it, use those heels,'' exhorts McMullin.
``Jennifer is a natural walker. She was born pretty, tall and slim.
Jennifer, use that posture to show, what are they called, those
six-pack abs. You've earned it.'' Indeed, Sharlow has come by her
form thanks partially to 12 weeks of oatmeal for breakfast, roast
beef and spinach for lunch, and grilled chicken for dinner.
Naturally, her choice of salad dressings has been ``no fat.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes Sharlow all of five minutes to switch from her
iridescent swimsuit into an evening gown. Now she's ready for her
talent training, and her song needs work.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow is a beloved regular at Weatherford's Shady Grove
Baptist Church, where her uncle is the minister. Her Miss Texas
talent is belting out the gospel-soaked ``Go Light Your World.''
The pageant stage will hardly be foreign to Sharlow, who is the
lead singer in ``The Sharlows,'' her family's gospel trio.
Sharlow's voice is a low and sultry contralto, communicating a
cleansing message with a premium on soul, not saccharine
preachiness.
</P>
<P>
   As Sharlow's voice fades out on her song, McMullin offers
several pointers. Sharlow needs a barrette to keep a pesky lock of
hair from tumbling into her eyes. Then, while singing, she must
gaze downward in order to catch the eye of every judge. But when
she mentions ``Jesus,'' Sharlow should look heavenward. Most
important, Sharlow should canvass the entire stage, as if she owns
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, ma'am,'' Sharlow eagerly assures McMullin. ``I've been
practicing that.'' ___ &QC; 
(MORE).MDUL/ nn
</P>
<P>
   The level of hard-core training and commitment Sharlow has
invested in the pageant is emblematic of the seriousness of the
women who pursue the Miss Texas crown. Everyone associated with
``The 2000 Miss Texas Scholarship Pageant'' would emphasize with
black eyeliner that the contest is all about winning part of the
$2.5 million in available cash and matching scholarship monies,
plus other prizes.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the academic boost from the Miss Texas organization
does little to calm the pageant's hard-core detractors. There will
always be those who hold that beauty pageants are about as deep as
a varnished nail, full of homogenized visions of molded femininity
e-nun-ci-a-ting their consonants too crisply, reflexively switching
on 1,000-watt smiles.
</P>
<P>
   But these jabs at beauty pageants ignore the quiet revolution
for new respectability. The two most familiar measures of aesthetic
appeal, the ``physical fitness in swimsuit'' and ``evening wear''
segments, only count for 15 percent of the contestant's final score
each. Much more significant is the 30 percent weight for the
personal interview and the 40 percent assigned to ``talent.'' The
latter category now produces Broadway-caliber displays of singing
and tap, theater and dance, while the personal interview compels
the candidates to speak cogently on such hard social issues as AIDS
awareness, suicide prevention and high school violence.
</P>
<P>
   For Sharlow, the Miss Texas competition acted, at the very
least, as an informal finishing school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pageant gave Jennifer enormous help just in presenting
herself, how to talk in front of people, to just learn what best
works for her,'' says Don Sharlow, her father. ``I mean she grew up
a lot just in the short time she was in the Miss Texas contest.''
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Julia E. Sharlow, Jennifer's always-beaming mother, recalls when
her 9-year-old daughter began following the Miss Texas and Miss
America pageants.
At that tender age, Sharlow scrounged up some kind of
Glinda-the-Good-Witch gown, tamed her recalcitrant locks and
competed in the Miss Future Parker County title. Pretty soon,
Sharlow would snare all the local titles _ ``Miss Parker County
Peach Princess'' and ``Miss Parker County Peach Queen'' _ growing
quite accustomed to posing for a picture next to a basket of Parker
County's finest fruit crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never put Jennifer up to doing any of the pageants,''
recalls Julia Sharlow. ``And while she lost some of those early
ones, I'm so proud that she always congratulated everyone,
especially the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Freud would have spotted Sharlow as a budding pageant
participant just by looking at her collection of every conceivable
Barbie doll ever manufactured with a crown. As a teen-ager, Sharlow
was the very model of ``yes ma'am, no sir'' decorum. She was a
cheerleader. And, yes, she was homecoming queen and was voted
``most lovable, dependable and spirited'' by her Brock High School
class. Naturally, her favored drink is Diet Dr Pepper. This
all-American wholesomeness comes through everywhere, even in the
recipes for ``sunshine carrots'' and ``apple crisp'' that she
submitted for the Miss Texas cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   The product of a very close middle-class family (Sharlow's
father is the ombudsman for the Texas Workers Compensation
Commission, her mother is a painter and art teacher), Sharlow is
responsible for her college tuition, making the Miss Texas
scholarship prizes that much more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow watched every penny spent in her bid for the Miss Texas
title. ``Oh yes, I was up at 6 a.m. gluing more beads and feathers
onto this,'' she says, grimacing as she pulls out a somewhat
wilted, feather-bordered mask needed for the ``masked ball''
evening-wear portion of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow's costume formula is often do-it-yourself, occasionally
starting with something off-the-rack from Goodwill Industries,
before adding a row of $5 beads, and, presto, a formal outfit is
born. For $50 at Whatchamacallit, Sharlow unearthed a pageant-ready
pleated pants suit studded with white pearls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love getting a good deal. I can't live without the `75
percent off take an extra 20 percent off' sale at Foley's
Department Store,'' Sharlow wrote in the pageant's telephone
book-thick official directory of contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Paging through the same directory, Sharlow exclaims: ``Look, if
you win you get all-year dry cleaning and carwashes _ whoo, now
wouldn't that be great?'' ___ &QC; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
