<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4931 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MISSTEXAS(3ndTake)-TE     07-17 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSTEXAS(3ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday, July 2, and T minus six days till the crowning of the
new Miss Texas. Move-in day for all the pageant contestants to Miss
Texas-central at Fort Worth's Holiday Inn South. Some of the
pageant's competitors pull up in Corvette convertibles, their
trunks bursting with an Imelda Marcos quantity of trunks, garment
bags and little Victoria Secret's satchels.
</P>
<P>
   No such grand entrance for Jennifer Sharlow, who ambles up the
walkway in a beaded pewter-toned dress, her faux leopard-print bag
dangling by her side. Though it is 10 a.m., Sharlow has her
foundation, blush and mascara all photo-op ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this really is the big time,'' says Sharlow. ``Last
night, I didn't sleep much, just tossed and turned.'' Then, Sharlow
takes a quick survey of her surroundings, and the scope of the
competition begins to sink in. ``There sure are lots of pretty
women here,'' Sharlow says.
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn's atrium greets Sharlow with a jungle of fellow
contestants in plum and fuchsia, turquoise and lime-green dresses.
Gratefully, Sharlow spots a familiar face, that of Julie Morphis,
Miss South Plains. They hug.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the pageant-contestant hug; there's method to this gesture.
Sharlow gently crosses her arms over the width of her compatriot's
shoulders. She never clutches at the hug's recipient, for fear of
crimping her outfit, nor does she allow her face to brush up
against the corresponding cheek lest an unwanted trace of lipstick
mar a pristine layer of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love your style,'' says a fellow contestant to Sharlow.
``No, YOU look really pretty,'' Sharlow automatically responds.
Sharlow's ``thank you's'' are doled out as fast as she receives the
compliments.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy of move-in day doesn't seem to faze Sharlow, not even
the prospect of having to share a queen-sized bed with a fellow
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I hope you don't accidentally kick each other overnight,
giving each other bruises,'' Sharlow's mother suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow dismisses that possibility with a laugh, then whips out
a can of hair spray, expertly forming a halo of maxi-hold around
her feathery new 'do. Now she is primed to meet the still-reigning
Miss Texas, Yanci Yarbrough. Yarbrough, the pride of Childress,
intercepts Sharlow, along with all the other contestants, after
they've signed their names (often dotting their ``i's'' with hearts
or flowers) to the official Miss Texas sign-in board.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Sharlow is locked in the empathetic force field of
1999's Miss Texas. ``Are you excited?'' asks Yarbrough, casting a
beatific look on Sharlow. ``It will be awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow's encounter with the reigning Miss Texas has fortified
her appetite. But with only 72 hours left before the swimsuit
competition, ordering lunch is a scene from the film ``Five Easy
Pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I please have the smoked chicken salad?'' Sharlow
requests sweetly. ``But could you hold the olives, the cheese, the
croutons and put the honey mustard dressing on the side?''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the contestants' anxiety level about last-minute
weight gain will prevent them from eating properly (one
contestant's lunch: a banana and mineral water), the Miss Texas
organizers have stocked one of the Holiday Inn's rooms with food
stations supplied by Mrs Baird's Bakery, Oak Farms Dairy, Dr Pepper
and Albertson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chips and hot sauce, chips and hot sauce _ and a big ole'
piece of cheese cake,'' says Sharlow, predicting the food she will
gorge on once the competition is finally over. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``And the winner is ... Miss Rio Grande Valley, Jennifer
Sharlow.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing her name called out, Sharlow's face melts into that
now familiar pageant contortion of incalculable joy and shock. At
first Sharlow can barely move. Then a visible ``Oh my gosh'' forms
across her trembling mouth. She is slowly absorbing that ineffable
moment of winning.
</P>
<P>
   First-time, long-shot Jennifer Sharlow has taken the ``Alpha
preliminary talent'' prize, beating out 37 other first-year Miss
Texas contestants. Sharlow clutches her blue-and-gold plaque that
marks her achievement and is soon swallowed by a swarm of sequined
and spangled fellow contestants basking in her reflected glory.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, surrounded by a parapet of arms, her face seems
to click into nostalgic playback mode. During the delivery of her
prize-winning song, she had subtly converted the entire audience
into her personal congregation. At one point, she had whispered
words of sermonlike wisdom before leading to a crescendo of
passion. She glided from side to side, imploring Jesus to ``light
your world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I said a little prayer because I was nervous, but I
just sang from my soul and did the best I could,'' says Sharlow.
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow's ``Alpha'' first-year award was only the beginning of
several minitriumphs in her Cinderella story. As the clock struck
midnight at the Miss Texas gala dinner, Sharlow was rewarded for
coming in 21st out of the 57 contestants. (The Miss Texas title was
awarded to Tara Watson, Miss Hurst-Euless-Bedford, in her fourth
stab at the crown.) In the end, Sharlow will take home an estimated
$1,450 in scholarship monies.
</P>
<P>
   All but bounding back to her parents, laden with Miss Texas
plaques, Sharlow is giddy: ``With these,'' Sharlow says, ``I just
paid for one semester of college'' at the University of Texas at
Arlington. ``You know, this week has not only given me some friends
for life, in addition to so much confidence, but, best of all, it
will be one of many things I will tell my kids and grandchildren
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharlow should also regale her future kin about the wonderful
quirk of Miss Texas pageant choreography that had her, in a blue
gown glittering like a constellation, in the front row as the
rumba-beat pageant finale concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl from Brock, for whom just walking up to that
microphone and announcing ``My name is Jennifer Sharlow'' was a
thrill, stood holding up her arms in a victorious pose. In Jennifer
Sharlow's young Miss Texas history, this was the crowning moment.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
