<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BELGIUM-SHEEP-NYT &LR;      07-17 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGIUM-SHEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEEP INFECTED WITH DISEASE, POSSIBLY SIMILAR TO MAD COW, TO BE
DESTROYED 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Federal agriculture officials plan to seize and
incinerate nearly 400 Vermont sheep in the coming days because four
of the group imported from Belgium have tested positive for a
disorder that may be similar to Europe's mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   Mad cow disease is not known to have ever passed from cattle to
sheep, except in the laboratory. But agricultural authorities
intent on sparing the United States the nightmare Europe has been
through said Monday they wanted to err far on the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a really difficult situation for these
farmers,'' said Andrew Solomon, a spokesman for the federal
Department of Agriculture. ``But from our perspective, this issue
is about a lot more than three individual farmers. It's about
safeguarding American livestock and American agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done in this instance is to act with an abundance
of caution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But one owner, Linda Faillace, whose family tends a flock of
East Friesian sheep from Belgium and makes Three Shepherds cheese,
described the planned seizure as a turn toward ``Gestapo tactics''
based on questionable science. Her family and the other main owner,
Houghton Freeman, a philanthropist, are asking the government to
hold off on the seizures until further tests can determine whether
the sheep really had a dangerous transmissible spongiform
encephalopathy, or TSE, a family of diseases that turn the brain
spongy with holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we felt these animals had TSE, or if we felt there was the
science showing these animals have TSE, we would have handed them
over very quietly and been done with it long ago,'' Faillace said.
``We're trying to help American agriculture, not hurt it. But just
to have the sheep victimized by power groups and bureaucracy needs
to be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Amidon, the lawyer for Freeman, who owns about 230 sheep,
said he and his client were trying to figure out what their rights
were: ``We are looking into the teeth of the full force of the U.S.
government,'' Amidon said.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, an estimated 180,000 cows have been infected since
the 1980s with mad cow disease, apparently through feed that
included the rendered brains of animals that had the disease, and
more than 70 deaths have been attributed to a human version called
new-variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. At first seemingly confined
to England, mad cow disease has turned up in France, the
Netherlands and elsewhere, but never in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Faillace's husband, Larry, has a doctorate in animal
science and worked with an authority on mad cow disease at the
University of Nottingham in the early 1990s. They imported their
flock, which now numbers 120, from Belgium in 1996. The family has
abided by an Agriculture Department quarantine put on the sheep in
1998, selling sheep only to the federal government, which would
test, then incinerate them.
</P>
<P>
   But all the tests had been negative until now, agriculture
officials say. The tests turned up positive, they say, for some
abnormal prions, the infectious proteins believed to cause mad cow
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The quick testing run on the sheep cannot determine which exact
disease they had, however, and it could be that they suffered from
scrapie, a fatal disorder of the same family as mad cow disease
that has been appearing in sheep for centuries but not affecting
humans, said Linda Detwiler, senior staff veterinarian at the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said: ``We'd be concerned about scrapie as well,
because it could be an atypical strain or something we don't have
in this country. If it's an atypical scrapie, the results for us
would be the same'' _ death for the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   It will take two or three years to determine exactly which
disease the sheep had, she said, because generations of mice
infected with samples from the sheep must be bred to see how it
plays itself out.
</P>
<P>
   Detwiler noted that neither mad-cow disease nor scrapie have
been shown to cause infections through milk, so there would seem to
be little need to worry about the cheese products made from the
imported sheep's milk. And though a few of the progeny of the
imported sheep were sold for meat, all were believed to have been
very young, meaning they carried a smaller risk of infection,
agriculture officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials say the Belgian sheep could have caught
the disease by eating contaminated feed while they were still in
Belgium. But Faillace said she and her husband had checked the feed
records for the sheep carefully, and they were born after a ban had
taken effect on the suspect feed containing rendered animals. She
also questioned whether the federal tests were accurate, citing
some internal contradictions and saying new testing methodology had
been used.
</P>
<P>
   Detwiler said the sheep's owners would be compensated for their
loss, and would be paid as much as they would have gotten if they
had sold the sheep _ which produce 10 times more milk than their
American counterparts _ for breeding, rather than a slaughterhouse
price.
</P>
<P>
   But the owners appear unwilling to go along gently with the
plan, and Faillace, whose family has invested more than $2 million
in the operation and remains in debt, said they have been receiving
calls of support from dozens of allies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
