u s BC-TRACK-JENNINGS-NYTR &LR;      07-17 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACK-JENNINGS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,500-METER CHAMP JENNINGS TAKES HIS FREE SPIRIT TO OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Usually, when an athlete wins and he wants
to thank someone, it's God, his parents or maybe a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon Gabe Jennings thanked the moon and the air.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't guessed it, a hippie won the men's 1,500
meters Sunday at the U.S. Olympic trials and is going to the
Olympics. This is big news because even back in the '60s, when
everyone was thanking the moon and the air, hippies didn't make the
Olympic team. That's probably because all the exercise the hippies
ever got then was stepping in and out of the Volkswagen bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't claim to be a free spirit,'' said Jennings, a Stanford
sophomore, ``but you're welcome to.'' And then a few minutes later
he allowed that he was. That's Jennings, he refuses to be put into
any box, even when there is no box at all. Calling him a ``free
spirit'' may be limiting him in an odd way.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings sleeps on the roof of a student-run co-op house at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   He walks around campus in a full-length orange-black-brown robe
native to Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised in a commune until he was 13.
</P>
<P>
   As Jennings ran his 1,500 Sunday a distinct drum beat was heard
throughout the race. His parents _ Jim, a philosophy and literature
teacher at Mendocino High School, and Suzanne, a children's fiction
writer currently at work on an anthology of women dealing with
pregnancy _ were beating the drums in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   And, Jennings was chanting to himself as he ran. Sometimes the
sounds are audible. Sunday he kept the chants _ rap he calls it _
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes like this,'' Jennings said. He proceeded to produce a
beat that had no decipherable words but that had a basic and
charismatic pull to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling the cosmic energy flow through me,'' Jennings
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he admitted, some people will dismiss his views as weird or
totally contrary to the established ``norm'' of athletic society.
He is unperturbed. In his world, different is not wrong. Different
is just different. Different is allowing your mind to hitch a ride
to whatever curious thought comes your way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to release the cosmic energy,'' Jennings said. ``I do
that in a variety of ways. I run to the top of a mountain. I scream
at the top of my lungs. I go skinny-dipping. And sometimes what I
do doesn't have to be so dramatic. Take a deep breath. Look at the
reflection of light on leaves and trees.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that may sound like the musings of someone with an idle
and wandering focus. Ah, but that would be underestimating
Jennings. Idle has never been his mind _ he is at Stanford you
know. Idle also has never been his body.
</P>
<P>
   He ran a 4:02.81 mile as a high school senior. He is the
National Collegiate Athletic Association champion this year in both
the indoor and outdoor 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   And when Jennings took the lead in the 1,500 with 600 meters to
go Sunday, not surrendering it, finishing strong, looking like the
best of the best, he showed once again there was a heart of a lion
inside the philosopher king.
</P>
<P>
   So the evidence is there all right. Maybe being inside a mold is
not the best place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``First thing I do when I wake up on race day,'' Jennings said,
``is to try to remember my dreams. When I go to sleep the night
before, I dream about the race. And when I wake up I dream about it
again. Today when I woke up I noticed my foot was tapping. That
doesn't happen very often. This was a good sign. I just knew this
was going to be a good day.'' As he relaxed in his Sacramento hotel
room, his dreams turned quiet.
</P>
<P>
   And then he started crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a happy cry,'' Jennings said. ``It warmed up my whole
body. It sent shivers down my spine. I let go of my ego. I felt
bigger than life. I felt reborn.'' And if you then expected
Jennings to say he levitated himself out of his hotel room and
floated over the Sacramento River while touching the hand of an
angel, you will have missed the point.
</P>
<P>
   This 21-year old man _ who has built a sweat lodge-tent on his
parents' Mendocino property, who believes in the spirit of man
above all else, who looks and acts like he was born 30 years too
late _ is going to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings has to be disciplined to do that. He has to be serious.
He is not a poof, a wild card, a verbal freak show, a mentalist who
can bend spoons.
</P>
<P>
   He is an Olympian. And his middle name is Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
