<SLUG> BC-AAA-SUED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN WOMAN'S FAMILY SUES AAA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Melissa Gosule's car wouldn't start, her family
did what thousands of other stranded motorists have done: They
called the American Automobile Association, confident the nation's
best-known emergency roadside service would take care of things
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   They failed, her parents say.
</P>
<P>
   In a wrongful death lawsuit filed Monday against AAA, Gosule's
parents say their daughter was forced to turn to the stranger who
killed her after a tow truck driver dispatched by AAA left her in a
parking lot, promising to return four hours later.
</P>
<P>
   If AAA and tow truck driver John Cubellis ``had done their job,
this would never have happened,'' Gosule's mother, Sandra Glaser,
said Monday. ``Melissa would still be with us today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosule's parents filed the lawsuit against AAA and Cubellis,
alleging their inaction on the night of July 11, 1999 forced a
desperate Gosule to turn to Michael Gentile for help when she was
stranded near a Cape Cod traffic rotary.
</P>
<P>
   Gentile raped and stabbed Gosule, 27, and is serving a life
without parole sentence after his first-degree murder conviction in
May. Gosule's body was found in a shallow grave in Pembroke, eight
days after she disappeared from the Bourne parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, attorneys for AAA of Southern New
England insisted the company was not to blame for Gosule's death.
``AAA Southern New England thoroughly rejects any allegation that
it bears any legal responsibility for this tragic event and the
heinous conduct of the individual responsible for Ms. Gosule's
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gosules are also suing AAA under Massachusetts' consumer
protection law, alleging the not-for-profit corporation has engaged
in ``immoral, unethical and unscrupulous'' marketing tactics. Any
judgment would be tripled under the law.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit pointed to a letter AAA used recently in a direct
mail solicitation urging people to join. ``In today's world,
relying on strangers has become a scary (and sometimes dangerous)
thing to do,'' it read. ``Why depend on strangers when `family' is
there to help?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Paris, the Boston attorney for Gosule's parents, said
that marketing campaign is exactly the kind of promise AAA failed
to keep when it came to Gosule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Gentile is behind bars, but he's not the only one who
should answer for Melissa's death,'' Paris said.
</P>
<P>
   Cubellis, who runs Cubellis Auto and Truck Repair in Buzzards
Bay, could not be reached for comment Monday. But last year, when
Gentile first faced charges, Cubellis told the Globe Gosule seemed
``fine and dandy'' when he saw her.
</P>
<P>
   Cubellis also said Gosule already had agreed to catch a ride to
Brockton with Gentile. ``She was in a public place, with public
telephones, and people passing by,'' Cubellis said then.
</P>
<P>
   On the day she disappeared, Gosule, a substitute teacher in
Boston public schools, returned to a parking lot at the Sagamore
Recreation Area after riding bike trails on Cape Cod, and found her
car wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   Gentile stopped shortly afterward and, according to the lawsuit,
Gosule used his cell phone to contact her mother and stepfather,
Peter Glaser, in Brockton around 6 p.m. Peter Glaser then called
AAA on its 24-hour emergency line.
</P>
<P>
   The agency called Cubellis at 6:20 p.m., but he did not arrive
until 7:45 p.m. at the Sagamore Recreation Area lot. Once there, he
allegedly told Gosule he was too busy to tow the car then, but
could come back around midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The parents allege Cubellis never tried to see if he could get
the car started, nor did he notify AAA he could do nothing for
Gosule for four hours. The AAA, in turn, the lawsuit claims, never
followed up with the Glasers to make sure the emergency help was
provided.
</P>
<P>
   Should they win damages, the family plans to donate some of it
to the Melissa Gosule Memorial Foundation to help combat domestic
violence and rape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
