<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWT GINGRICH'S WIFE PLANS BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marianne Gingrich, who was divorced in December from Newt
Gingrich, the former speaker of the House, has met with several New
York publishers to sell a proposed book about her life with him,
according to her agent, Edward Jay Acton.
</P>
<P>
   The book will describe Gingrich's role as a behind-the-scenes
partner in Newt Gingrich's rise and the intimate witness to his
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really wants to show how Washington has changed over the
last 20 years for women, especially because of the increased
attention from the media,'' Acton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich married Newt Gingrich in 1981, when he was a young
Republican congressman. He had recently divorced his first wife,
Jackie, who had been his high school math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Newt and Marianne Gingrich were separated in May 1999, after
Gingrich left office and it had been disclosed that he had been
having a love affair for the previous six years with an aide,
Callista Bisek. In August, Newt Gingrich, who is 56, plans to marry
Bisek, 33.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's proposed book will discuss her husband's affair, but
``this is not a get-Newt or a get-even book,'' Acton said.
Hopefully, Acton compared her book to ``What I Saw at the
Revolution,'' by Peggy Noonan, a speechwriter for President Ronald
Reagan. Gingrich has not yet sold the book, Acton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, 48, will write the book in the first person with the
help of Katherine Johnson. Johnson has previously written
authorized biographies of the authors Anne Rice and Dean Koontz.
</P>
<P>
   Acton has represented primarily liberal authors, including James
Baldwin, Ralph Nader and Tip O'Neill, the former Democratic speaker
of the House. Gingrich, who remains a Republican, met her agent
through a friend, Susan O'Neill, Tip O'Neill's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was unavailable for comment. A spokesman for Newt
Gingrich's office said he declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
