<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLESTONBARS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charleston considering shutting down the bars earlier
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ After drunks from downtown Charleston bars
kept wandering into her backyard garden, Nina Liu installed locks
on her two gates.
</P>
<P>
   That problem ended. Now the 60-year-old art dealer is among
sleep-deprived downtown residents who are counting on city leaders
to clamp down on the racket and littering, the flower pot smashing
and other vandalism that they blame on the bar crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Charleston City Council is scheduled to consider final
approval tonight of an ordinance requiring the city's bars and
clubs to stop selling alcohol at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a rancorous debate here, similar to the Atlanta City
Council's deliberations on closing the city's bars and clubs two
hours earlier, at 2 a.m. instead of the current 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A peek at Charleston illustrates how even this historic city,
known for its Southern hospitality and pleasant manners, isn't
above brawling over booze and its distasteful side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume goes up when it gets to be 2 or 3 in the morning,''
said Bill Regan, the city attorney. ``They throw beer cans. They
yell. Quite frankly, they urinate.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, a spate of high-profile violence has spurred the
call for shortening bar hours. The momentum has been more gradual
in Charleston, where Mayor Joseph Riley last year threw his crucial
support behind curbing alcohol sales in bars after hearing
complaints from residents and business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, 57, Charleston's mayor for the past 25 years, describes
the early-morning noise and vandalism by people leaving bars as a
threat to residents' quality of life. He has the backing of
downtown hotels, restaurants and other businesses whose officials
have expressed dismay at the late-night rowdiness. Westin Francis
Marion hotel managing partner Steven Dopp called it ``a very
unpleasant, unsavory party scene that runs until 5 o'clock in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Charleston establishments can sell beer and wine all
night long. Complaints about the raucous behavior are coming from
areas such as upper King Street, the French Quarter and
Ansonborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the neighborhood have all tried sleeping in different
rooms of our houses, hoping it will be better,'' said Liu, a
resident of the French Quarter, an affluent section that
Charleston's police chief fears is growing as unruly as the
more-famous French Quarter in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason anybody has to go out and get drunk after 2
o'clock in the morning,'' Chief Reuben Greenberg said. ``The bar
owners are trying to New Orleans-ize Charleston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't anything like that,'' said Portside Cafe Uptown
owner Jeff Filosa, 40, helping mobilize bars and their patrons to
fight Charleston's ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council passed the ordinance last month on the first of
three readings, after the city suffered a courtroom setback in
March. A state circuit judge ruled a previous ordinance forcing
bars to close at 2 a.m. to be unfair because it applied only to a
one-block-wide area that included a cluster of establishments on
upper King Street.
</P>
<P>
   One of the establishments, the Trio Club, had sued to block the
ordinance, and the judge's ruling sent the City Council back to
deliberations. The new ordinance has reignited the debate in the
city's booming tourism area and has made elected leaders sensitive
to complaints about traffic, congestion and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened to Atlanta is happening to Charleston,''
said City Councilman Henry Fishburne Jr., whose downtown Charleston
district includes early-morning bars and people who are complaining
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Filosa, a former waiter and bartender, said turning off the taps
as early as 2 a.m. would hurt businesses such as his. He said it
also would unfairly crimp the night life of Charlestonians such as
college students and waiters and others who work late in the city's
burgeoning hospitality trade.
</P>
<P>
   If noise is bad now, the ordinance's opponents say it would be
worse if bars turned out customers at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to cause more of a problem rather than
spreading it out over the night,'' said Christina Couture, 30, a
Charleston restaurant manager who frequents A.C.'s Bar &AMP; Grill
after getting off work as late as 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Piccirillo, A.C.'s manager, said bar patrons are getting
unfairly blamed for early-morning problems. That's also the case
with College of Charleston students, said its president, Alex
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Though upper King Street is popular among College of Charleston
students, Sanders said they cause far less trouble than ``the
people I'd call freaks, people with purple hair, body piercing and
those 1,000-mile stares. We get credit for them being college
students.''
</P>
<P>
   King Street deli owner Howard Fine said he's not had any
early-morning trouble since last year's closing of Red Hot
Tomatoes. But he added, ``To me, 2 o'clock is plenty late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some neighborhood bars that are not detrimental to
the city,'' said City Councilman Larry Shirley, who plans to offer
an amendment tonight allowing establishments to sell alcohol beyond
2 a.m. on Fridays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   He defended ``most tavern and bar owners (as) good, hardworking
people,'' including some who lost substantial income when South
Carolina banned video poker machines July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe anybody is going to go out of business because
they are going to have to close at 2 o'clock instead of 3 or
whenever they close,'' City Councilwoman Anne Frances Bleecker
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she's open to amending the ordinance, but not killing
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sweep away the broken beer bottles,'' she said, ``but
it is the noise that has the quality-of-life impact on the people
who live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
