<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFENDING HIS WIFE, CLINTON BROKE NEWS BLACKOUT ON SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a quiet Sunday morning in the middle of the
Middle East summit meeting when President Clinton picked up the
telephone at Camp David and tried to defuse a conflict that was
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Clinton, acting as a presidential peacemaker, had been
discussing the complicated issues dividing the Palestinians and
Israelis. But when he dialed up Mortimer B. Zuckerman, publisher of
the New York Daily News, Clinton was pushing another aspect of his
final-year legacy _ the election of his wife to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With six months to go in his presidency, Clinton sees his power
waning. But his clout is far from gone, especially in foreign
affairs, and Clinton showed that he can still grab a headline _ in
this case a screaming one that said in part, ``Prez Defends Hil on
Slur.''
</P>
<P>
   The president speaks regularly to Hillary Rodham Clinton about
her New York Senate bid, and on that particular morning the
campaign was reeling from allegations in the New York Post that
Mrs. Clinton had used an anti-Semitic slur three decades ago.
Clinton, during a lull in the summit meeting, decided to strike
back, going beyond a brief statement denying the allegation that
his aides had issued on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides said the telephone call to the newspaper was
his decision. Mrs. Clinton's aides also distanced themselves from
the president's action.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Clinton's call on Sunday was a rash act or a
well-thought-out counteroffensive coordinated with Mrs. Clinton, it
seemed to backfire. Remarks he made about the summit meeting
violated a news blackout that the White House itself had set, while
his attention-getting effort to snuff out a news story damaging to
his wife seemed only to add fuel to it.
</P>
<P>
   It was another example of Clinton, a man surrounded by dutiful
aides, acting on his own instincts, which have both served him and
failed him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extraordinary circumstance,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday, seeking to explain the
telephone call he learned of only after the fact. ``We live in a
world where the National Enquirer mentality has hijacked
journalism, and that has become an issue in New York. And these are
scurrilous and untrue charges, and the president wanted to set that
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the end of the interview with the News, commented
briefly that he was more optimistic about the peace talks than when
they began last week. The remark itself was harmless but it was
uttered after officials had agreed to withhold any comment until
the talks were over. Lockhart said the comments were ``outside the
rules'' but warranted by the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Although no substance on the peace talks ever came up over the
telephone, the potential was there for the chat to interfere with
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was not supposed to be an interview that dealt
with the peace process,'' a presidential aide explained Monday.
``It just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   White House stenographers usually listen in on Clinton's
telephone interviews and prepare instant, official transcripts. Not
this time. Aides only learned of the call after it took place and
scurried Sunday night to get from the Daily News a transcript of
the remarks dealing with the Middle East so they could release it
to the rest of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that when he's trying to bring peace to the Middle
East, he had to take a break to ensure peace among Jews in New
York,'' said a Democratic strategist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The president and Zuckerman know each other well. They have
traveled together to the Middle East, dined together and played
cards aboard Air Force One. Clinton, according to aides, considers
the Daily News friendlier than the Post, the other hard-nosed New
York tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In their Sunday morning conversation, according to two people
with knowledge of the call, Clinton told Zuckerman that there was
no truth to the allegations in the Post, which were based on a book
by a former National Enquirer reporter. The two men arranged for
the president to speak on-the-record to Michael Kramer, the paper's
managing editor.  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Kramer is also well known to the president. His former wife, Kimba
Woods, had been one of Clinton's early picks for attorney general
before her name was withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kramer called Camp David early in the afternoon. Clinton called
back about 5:30 p.m., unleashing a vigorous defense of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there and she never said it,'' the president said,
according to the News' article, which was labeled an ``exclusive
interview.'' ``In 29 years, my wife has never, ever uttered an
ethnic or racial slur against anybody, ever. She's so straight on
this, she squeaks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton went beyond rebutting the facts. As both he and his
wife have done, the president framed the allegation as part of a
string of attacks by political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also appeared to implicate the campaign of Mrs.
Clinton's rival, Rep. Rick Lazio. ``The only thing they have left
is character assassination,'' he said of Lazio's campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
