<HEADER>
A4943 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-BROPEN-DALY-COX     07-17 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-DALY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hope burns eternal in former British Open champ Daly
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland - Behind amber sunglasses that Elvis might
have worn to play golf, John Daly, with a couple days of blond
beard stubble and fresh off his flight, took his official
pre-tournament posture Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a little bit of home here,'' said Daly, 34, who
secured a British Open title at St. Andrews in 1995 to shock the
golf world. ``I don't know. I just always feel good here. The
course, the people _ it's nice to be able to walk out of your room
and come to the golf course. Everything's just great about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? St. Andrews represents the last time Daly existed
as any kind of a force in the game. His career has declined
dramatically since 1995, when he bombed drives over bunkers,
chipped masterfully, made putts from all over the famous property
and beat Costantino Rocca in a sudden-death playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago Daly was kissing the Claret Jug. Now, he's famous
for kissing off major championships. Last month, he ended the U.S.
Open at Pebble Beach with a 14 on his 18th and final hole and
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after St. Andrews, Daly has dropped another wife,
gone through another alcohol rehab and, once again, resumed
drinking. He has been off antidepressants since December.''I felt
like a (laboratory) rat,'' he said. Now, he longs to find the
prescription for victory. ``It (1995) was the last good year,''
Daly said, ``but I'm still here, the heart's still beating, and I'm
still fully exempt until 2005, so there's a lot of golf for me to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   If Daly can glue together his game for a week, it should be at
the Old Course, where he can drive as many par-4's as Tiger Woods
can and keep the ball in play. The key will leaving the pubs early
enough and making enough putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just sets up good for me,'' Daly said. ``Hopefully,
the wind will blow. If this tournament turns into a putting contest
with no wind, I don't like my chances, but if it blows again, I
like my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly draws a mob of reporters on the Old Course practice ground,
while other players look back over their shoulders, some shaking
their heads at the attention he still draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I came in here in '95 last time, I had been
playing awful,'' Daly said. ``Scoring-wise, I was playing worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he feels he can contend, Daly said, ``I'm not
going to say it would be a miracle, but I think a lot of people
would love to see it, especially me. I wouldn't be here if I didn't
think I had a chance. Let's just put it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything's relative with Daly. If he only has a couple vices
working and hasn't been to court lately, it's a calm sea. If he
marries again, it will be for a fourth time. His use of alcohol
hasn't destroyed him. His weight, often outrageous, actually
appears to be slightly lower. ``I think the only trouble I have
right now is my golf game,'' he said. ``For the first time in my
life, I can work on that and worry about that, and I don't have to
worry about all this other crap that everybody else seems to worry
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Woods have little difference in length, except that
Daly's averages often are for only two rounds of a tournament. Daly
suggests that he flies the ball farther but that Woods is longer by
the time his ball stops rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their drivers, they are worlds apart, especially with the
putter. ``If I had his putter right now,'' Daly said, ``I'd be
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Checking out a Golf Channel videotape of the 1995 British Open
recently, Daly noticed how open his putting stance was five years
ago. Since spotting the change, during practices at home, ``It
feels like I'm going to make everything. . . . The only way for me
to make a putt (before) was to decelerate and pull it.''
</P>
<P>
   As absurd as it is to compare Woods and Daly at this juncture,
when the world's best player is mentioned, the man who already has
the title loves to fantasize about playing against the man who
needs one for a career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be cool for me and him to come down Sunday here, man,''
Daly said. ``I'd love it. I know he's going to be there. I don't
know where I'm going to be. Hell, I may be on a plane home, I don't
know, but I'm going to be enjoying myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
