</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN VISITS CHINA IN HOPE OF STRENGTHENING A STRATEGIC AXIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Vladimir Putin of Russia arrived in
Beijing on Monday night on the first stop of an Asian tour intended
to revive his country's faded diplomatic role in the region and
build what could become a Chinese-Russian axis to counter American
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is expected to sign at least six accords with Chinese
leaders on Tuesday, including a joint statement with President
Jiang Zemin condemning American proposals for missile defense
systems over North America and Asia. Opposition to the American
plan has accelerated a relationship that Russia and China describe
as a ``strategic partnership'' intended to counter American power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partnership is an effort to oppose hegemony and supremacy,
and one single country dominating the world,'' said Zhao Huasheng,
director of the Russian Studies department at the Shanghai
Institute for International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Putin travels to North Korea, where he is expected
to ask that country's leader, Kim Jong Il, to forgo its missile
development program. The United States has told Russia and China
that the proposed American missile defense system is intended to
counter threats posed by smaller, missile-armed states like North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Putin then stops in Blagoveshchensk, in eastern Russia, for a
conference on a region that is experiencing increased immigration
from China. He ends his tour on the Japanese island of Okinawa,
where he is due to arrive late Friday for the annual gathering of
leading industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
   China is by far Putin's most important stop. It will be his
first visit there since he was elected president in March. And it
follows eight visits by his predecessor, Boris Yeltsin, who agreed
with Jiang in 1996 to establish the strategic partnership to build
a ``multi-polar world,'' a euphemism to describe opposition to
America's status as the world's sole superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia shares a strategic partnership with China and puts
relations with Beijing among the highest priorities of its foreign
policy,'' Putin said in an interview with China's state television
last week.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not yet clear how warmly Putin will embrace the
Chinese worldview, Western analysts say the rapprochement between
the countries is taking on an increasingly anti-American cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one level, this is classic realpolitik balance-of-power,
but on another it has the appearance of a united front against the
United States,'' said David Shambaugh, a China specialist at George
Washington University and the Brookings Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and Yeltsin had pledged to increase economic cooperation
between the two countries to bolster that partnership, but
bilateral trade has fallen far short of the targeted $20 billion a
year, stagnating at around $6 billion. Russian arms sales to China
account for much of that.
</P>
<P>
   Putin hopes to change this, though it will not happen overnight.
Russia's troubled economy presents a far less attractive export
market for China than the United States, Europe and Japan, and
Russian goods cannot compete in China against domestically
manufactured products or high technology imports from Japan and the
West. About the only things Russia can offer China besides arms are
commodities like natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Among the agreements Putin is expected to sign in Beijing is one
calling for a feasibility study for a gas pipeline from Russia's
Irkutsk region to China. That project has been talked about for
years with little progress, partly because China does not really
need more natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Another deal on the table during Putin's visit is Russia's sale
of a second pair of nuclear reactors for the Tianwan nuclear power
plant in eastern China. An initial two Russian reactors are
currently being built at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, weapons are likely to remain the strongest bond in the
two countries' economic relationship. China wants weapons to
modernize its military and Russia's overdeveloped arms industry is
begging for customers with cash. Already, China has bought advanced
fighter aircraft, submarines and Russian guided-missile destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has become even more important to China since Israel
bowed to American pressure earlier this month and canceled the sale
to Beijing of an early-warning radar system mounted atop a Russian
jet. Russia could supply China with similar technology.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's large delegation includes Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
and the director of Russia's arms exporter Rosvooruzheniye, Alexei
Ogarev. And China is expected to place additional weapons orders
during Putin's visit.
</P>
<P>
   China remains decades from developing a military force
sufficient to challenge the United States, but it is intent on
building a credible threat to Taiwan, over which Beijing claims
sovereignty. Though China has repeatedly threatened to recover
control of the island by force, it does not currently have the
military capability to do so.
</P>
<P>
   That military build-up is just one of the many areas in which
China and Russia's economic and political interests converge.
Russia not only offers China the hardware necessary to achieve its
goals in the Taiwan Strait, it acts as a potential diplomatic
counterbalance to any intervention by the United States, which
supports Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China, for its part, has stood by Russia in opposition to the
1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and in Moscow's brutal war against
separatists in Chechnya. Beijing sees parallels between those cases
and separatist movements in its own regions of Tibet and Xinjiang,
where it fears Western condemnation or even intervention if
conditions deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Putin first met Jiang earlier this month in Tajikistan,
bordering Xinjiang, where they signed an agreement to fight ethnic
separatism and terrorism in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those areas of common interest pale in comparison to the
American missile defense proposal, which both countries see as a
means of securing the United States military dominance in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, since this will affect both international security,
the security of Russia and China, I can tell you I expect that we
will have to have more consultations and discussions to find out
ways and means to eliminate or at least reduce this kind of
security threat,'' Sha Zukang, head of the Foreign Ministry's
Department of Arms Control and Disarmament, said last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
