<SLUG> BC-LAW-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP U.S. LAW FIRMS AGREE TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   By KRUTI TRIVEDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to increase their presence on both coasts and overseas,
two large U.S. law firms _ one in California and one in New York _
announced plans Monday to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro, based in San
Francisco, and Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam &AMP; Roberts, based in New
York, would create one of the nation's largest law firms, with more
than 860 lawyers in 16 offices. The merger would especially address
a weakness for Pillsbury, whose lawyers handle international
business, though only one is based abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after similar deals among American and
international law firms during the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The combined firm, which will be called Pillsbury Winthrop, is
expected to have more than $400 million in revenue next year, which
would make it one of the top 20 firms in the United States in terms
of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two firms have a shared vision of creating a major U.S.
law firm in our core practice areas in which we match up very
well,'' said John Pritchard, the chairman of Winthrop, which, like
Pillsbury, specializes in mergers and acquisitions, finance,
complex litigation, and capital markets. ``We have a vision of
creating a strong national firm headquartered on both coasts and
globalizing that firm.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed combination, which the firms called a merger of
equals, is intended to bolster Winthrop's technology practice,
especially in the Silicon Alley area of New York, Pritchard said.
Pillsbury, which has 81 lawyers in its Silicon Valley office,
bulked up its technology law arm when it merged with Cushman Darby
&AMP; Cushman of Washington in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As for Pillsbury, the merger would increase the firm's
international presence, said Marina Park, Pillsbury's managing
partner. Though Pillsbury, which has 596 lawyers, is more than
twice the size of Winthrop, the majority of its revenue comes from
domestic clients. The firm's sole international office consists of
one partner based in Tokyo. Winthrop has offices in Tokyo, London,
Hong Kong and Singapore; more than half of the company's revenue
comes from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The partners of both firms will vote on the merger later this
year. Mary Cranston, the chairwoman of Pillsbury, would be
chairwoman of the combined firm. Pritchard would be vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Both firms have seen revenue drop in comparison with their
competitors, according to the rankings in The American Lawyer
magazine. Winthrop, which ranked 93rd in 1998, dropped to 100 in
1999. Pillsbury, ranked 44th in 1998, fell to 46th.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of their United States and international counterparts,
both companies have been searching for a partner for some time.
Pillsbury started seriously looking for a New York-based partner in
January 1999, after Cranston was named chairwoman. Winthrop has
been considering merging for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is to globalize our practices because our
clients are globalizing and, more importantly, our competition is
globalizing,'' Pritchard said. ``Almost every law firm in the
United States that we know of is not only thinking about merging
with other firms, but many of them are in active discussions. We
are really at the forefront of mergers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2031EDT &QL; 
