<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4951 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     07-17 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE TALKS INTENSIFY, BUT UNCERTAINTY ABOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to delete `at a community college' from 16th graf.)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ As the Camp David peace summit meeting moved
closer to a supposed deadline of President Clinton's departure for
Japan on Wednesday morning, the White House remained officially
committed to reaching ``an agreement'' before then and talks
shifted into high-drive for a crucial 48-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   But some American, Israeli and Palestinian officials began
lowering expectations Monday for a breakthrough, even suggesting
that additional summit meetings may be needed. And the White House
left ample room for interpretation of its goal, since ``an
agreement'' could include anything from a more modest declaration
of principles to a full-blown accord between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Although American officials had previously said quietly that
Clinton's itinerary could be modified, the White House continued to
declare Monday that he had no intention of delaying his trip to a
Group of 7 meeting in Okinawa or of sending Vice President Al Gore
in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to complete the process before the president
goes,'' Joe Lockhart, Clinton's spokesman, said. Later, he added:
``You will know we are following the schedule when you see the
president walk up the steps of the plane, wave and the door
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Middle East experts, however, including some officials
on all sides, find it hard to imagine that the Palestinians'
leader, Yasser Arafat, could modify a well-documented personal
history of pushing things to the wire. And in Arafat's case, that
could mean an ultimate deadline not of Wednesday but of Sept. 13,
by which he has pledged to declare a state.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts envisioned the leaders taking a break of a couple
of weeks before reconvening for a continued summit meeting. But
others said that this would be highly risky because it would expose
what has been a completely secret, blacked-out negotiation to the
leaks, misinformation, disinformation and political pressures of
Israel and the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's feasible to do that, to break off and then return,'' said
a senior Israeli official. ``But I'm not sure it's a good idea to
let the energy dissipate. The rumors and false assumptions could
lead to terrible results.''
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Herzog, Israel's Cabinet secretary, who is in
Washington, said: ``It's clear that both parties must seize the
moment, not only the moment, but literally the day. We should be
thinking of Wednesday as a once-in-a-lifetime chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Israelis have been putting out the word that Prime
Minister Ehud Barak ``is not going to stay forever at Camp David,''
and expressing frustration that, in their view, Barak has taken
``giant steps'' toward Arafat while the Palestinian leader has
remained unyielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians are not showing flexibility and are not going
the extra mile,'' said Yuli Tamir, Israel's dovish immigration
minister who is serving as an Israeli spokeswoman in Washington.
``I think they are pushing Barak to cross his red lines, and I
think they are making a mistake. He will not change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has professed to be more optimistic than he was
at the start of the summit last Tuesday, Barak is ``more on the
pessimistic side,'' Avraham Burg, the speaker of Israel's
Parliament, told Israel Radio on Monday. Other Israeli ministers
and lawmakers who spoke to the prime minister expressed a similar
impression.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, who voiced unusual optimism late last week, on
Monday hit a peak of frustration, although it may have been
short-lived. One Palestinian official who is not inside Camp David
said that the Israelis seemed to be retreating on expected
concessions and that the Palestinians have told the Americans that
they do not plan to stay beyond Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one senior Palestinian negotiator, Abu Mazen, who is the
Palestine Liberation Organization's senior official after Arafat,
faces a personal deadline. His son, Tarek, is getting married in
Ramallah on Thursday, and the whole Palestinian peace team is
invited and planning to attend.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday looming, the pace and intensity of the
negotiations have quickened, and the teams worked well into the
morning until about 5 a.m. before breaking and resuming midday. All
three leaders are night owls, known to thrive in the post-midnight
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian officials outside the talks say that a
kind of high-tension fatigue is setting in. Lockhart said, ``Coming
back continually to the same issues with the same people, that kind
of environment is not always the best for the warm and fuzzies.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio reported Monday night that while key differences
remain on the thorniest issues of Jerusalem and the right of return
of refugees, progress has been made on some relatively minor issues
like water and the environment. Side talks are being held in
Emmitsburg, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But an American official there said that the side talks could
get only so far without knowledge of the parameters of a core
agreement, and Israeli and Palestinian participants who have
longstanding professional relationships have been crafting and
re-crafting individual paragraphs about civil affairs and economic
relations. Rather than twiddle their thumbs, some Palestinian
officials involved in the side talks have opted instead for long
shopping afternoons at the Pentagon City mall in Virginia where
many are staying, the American official said. (Some have been
seeking wedding presents for Tarek Abbas, Abu Mazen's son.)
</P>
<P>
   Barak summoned a former director-general of the Foreign Ministry
from Israel, Reuven Merhak, who is an expert on Jerusalem. He has
been stationed at Emmitsburg since arriving. But Israeli analysts
took his arrival as a sign that Barak wanted to have close by an
analyst who has thought through all the solutions for sharing the
holy city, including what Burg referred to recently as ``shrinking
and expanding'' Jerusalem _ annexing Jerusalem suburbs in the West
Bank to Israel while relinquishing Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The news blackout has held remarkably well through seven days,
which most take as a good sign that no one wants to blow up the
process. Inside Camp David, though, the delegations have ample
access to American newspapers and 60 or 70 television channels,
Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
