<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-ELLIS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Graham stops in Hillary country
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY _ His bag in the overhead bin several seats behind
him, Bob Graham asked U.S. Sen. Max Baucus of Montana if he could
pass it to him. Baucus was willing to do more for his fellow
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be happy to carry the bag of the future vice president,''
Baucus said. ``Can I carry your other bag?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham declined with a laugh. But there is one offer he's ready
to accept, if it is given, and that is to become Vice President Al
Gore's running mate. Said to be on Gore's short list, Graham, who
was considered for the job by Bill Clinton in 1992, said Monday
that the attention is more intense now than it was eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a lot more media attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Jay Leno poking fun at his penchant for note-taking and
reporters probing every detail of his life _ he saw the Broadway
play Sinatra Sunday night with his wife, Adele _ Graham is trying
hard not to appear too eager for the job.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Ellis Island he signed autographs and posed
for photographs. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who was there
with Graham to announce more money for restoration of Ellis Island,
stopped short of endorsing him but called Graham ``first rate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very fond of Sen. Graham. I have really admired him,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Ferraro, the former New York congresswoman who was
Walter Mondale's running mate in 1984, said if it were her
decision, ``He's at the top of my list.'' She said that with his
experience as governor from 1979 to 1987 and as senator, he is an
ideal candidate who ``understands the process''
</P>
<P>
   With Florida's 25 electoral votes, Ferraro said Democrats have
no choice but to compete there, and Graham could help the party win
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is a state where I think we can win even with Jeb Bush
there,'' she said. ``There is a large elderly population and
Democrats are right on issues that concern them. I think Graham
would be a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's wife thinks all the attention is very exciting. ``I
think it's really nice that he's getting the kind of national
attention he's been gettiing,'' she said, although she wished Leno
has not made fun of Graham's notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, Graham has carried a small notebook with him,
jotting down everything from how much he weighs in the morning to
tidbits about people he's met walking through airports. And he
shows what he writes down to almost anyone who asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notebooks are very helpful,'' Adele Graham said in a
rebuttal to Leno. ``If I need to know something about a day, I just
ask him and he looks it up and he'll have whatever names and
addresses I need.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, she is taking all the attention her husband is getting
in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very good life now, `` she said. ``And whatever
happens we'll continue to have a very good life.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
