<SLUG> BC-PEACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES FOR MIDEAST PEACE DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton sought Monday to wring a final
peace agreement out of the Israelis and Palestinians before he
leaves for Japan as talks entered a second week with the two sides
apparently no closer to a deal than when the talks opened.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview with the New York Daily News, Clinton said
``some progress'' had been made toward ending more than a half
century of hostilities between the two sides, although he confessed
that he is still not at all sure the negotiations will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, it's hard,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he vowed to press on even though he described his
negotiations with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat as ``the hardest thing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some progress, but I can't say I know we'll
succeed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to depart for Okinawa, Japan, Wednesday morning to
attend the so-called Group of Eight economic summit. White House
officials said they were optimistic an agreement could be reached
before then that would lead to the settlement of competing claims
to Jerusalem and where the final borders of a Palestinian state
will be drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that when the president leaves the parties will have
wrapped up their business,'' White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``the pace and intensity (of the discussions) have
both quickened'' in anticipation of Clinton's departure and he
noted that the leaders had spent ``two straight, very long nights''
trying to work through remaining problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to borders and the final status of Jerusalem,
several controversial issues have to be resolved. They include what
to do about more than 3 million Palestinian refugees who have been
driven from their homes since Israel became a state in 1948, and
the 40,000 Israeli settlers who now reside in territory that is to
be returned to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But while Clinton and his aides continued to put a positive spin
on the talks, both Israeli and Palestinian officials were sounding
doubtful that the remaining obstacles could be overcome before
Clinton's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying it can't happen,'' said one Israeli official
familiar with the talks. ``But it will be very, very hard because
of the differences that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg agreed with that
assessment, telling Israeli Radio that Barak had told him in a
telephone call that things are not going well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not really optimistic,'' Burg said in the interview.
``We have not reached the moment of truth, the moment of decision.
It is more on the pessimistic side than the optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Cabinet minister Yuli Tamir, who heads the offices of
immigration and absorption, told Israeli army radio that Arafat has
been reluctant thus far to give in on any of the key issues in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he continues to insist on the things that he insists upon,
there will be no agreement,'' Tamir said.
</P>
<P>
   But a Palestinian official said Barak has hardened his positions
because of public unrest back home and the fact that many in his
governing coalition have abandoned him. This official said Barak is
refusing to relinquish control over any key parts of Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians are intent on designating as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a position,'' he said, ``will not lead to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Arafat also still considers Sept. 13 a hard deadline for
reaching an agreement. The Palestinian leader has said that he
intends to declare a Palestinian state on that date if there has
been no final peace settlement by then. The threat has been taken
seriously by Israel, which has countered that it would be forced to
annex part of the still-occupied territories as a security
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton convened the talks at the presidential retreat on
July 11, Barak was reportedly ready to relinquish control of up to
90 percent of the West Bank. Israel has already withdrawn
militarily from 40 percent of the territory and the Gaza Strip.
Barak was reportedly also ready to accept the return of thousands
of refugees to Israel and the West Bank, even though opponents of
such a move say it would create serious security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of dividing Jerusalem, however, is proving to be the
most difficult to resolve. Over the weekend, Barak summoned an
expert on Jerusalem to help in the talks. He has offered to redraw
the holy city's borders in order to include more Palestinian
territory. But Arafat is insisting that a Palestinian capital must
include parts of the old walled city in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
