<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco industry attempts to delay final judgment
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There's nothing routine about a $145 billion punitive
damages verdict.
</P>
<P>
   So on Monday, less than three days after jurors ordered
cigarette makers to pay the largest civil penalty in U.S. history,
the tobacco industry began fighting back by questioning the
normally routine matter of signing a final judgment to close out
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big issue,'' Philip Morris attorney Dan Webb told
Judge Robert Kaye during a brief hearing on post-verdict matters.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said he had expected to sign a formal order this week
wrapping up the trial, but would hear arguments before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Webb maintains the nation's first class-action trial of the
tobacco industry isn't over and punitive damage money can't be paid
until courts decide case-by-case on the compensatory damage claims
of as many as 700,000 Floridians with smoking-related illnesses.
Such a process could take 75 years, Webb said Friday in the
immediate aftermath of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies also want Kaye to slash the jury's damages
figure, which they say far exceeds their ability to pay. Florida
law prohibits a verdict that would bankrupt a company. During their
closing arguments, the five cigarette makers said they couldn't
afford more than $381 million in combined damages, or less than 0.3
percent of the jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers' attorney Susan Rosenblatt said Monday that plaintiffs
want a final judgment entered quickly so interest on the $145
billion can begin accumulating while the case is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ``big issue'' of the final judgment, Webb
said the industry is still awaiting a hearing on 64 pending motions
from the trial. Kaye and plaintiffs' attorneys tentatively agreed
those matters could be discussed in August.
</P>
<P>
   Once trial motions are disposed of, the industry has vowed to
appeal the class-action status of the estimated 300,000 to 700,000
sick Florida smokers. About two dozen other state and federal
courts around the U.S. have rejected such class-action suits,
generally finding smokers' circumstances and histories too varied
to be covered by a single court action.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt scoffed at Webb's scenario of hundreds of thousands
of additional tobacco trials. She suggested large numbers of
smokers with the same diseases could be grouped together to
determine their eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the nightmare they're presenting,'' Rosenblatt said.
``It's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
