<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4960 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS-JEFFERSON     07-17 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JEFFERSON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons hope Shawn Jefferson is the deep threat they've needed
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. - One Sunday afternoon in the fall of 1998,
Shawn Jefferson was on the wrong sideline when the Falcons put it
together.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pounded New England 41-10 that day in Foxboro Stadium.
For Jefferson, it was educational.
</P>
<P>
   When his agent called the first morning of free agencyin
February and said the Falcons were panting and ready to deal,
Jefferson knew what they were seeking, even before he agreed to a
four-year, $14.2 million contract later that day.
</P>
<P>
   They want Jeffersonto go deep. His new team was great at going
deep in 1998 but terrible last year.
</P>
<P>
   After the big Atlanta win in 1998, Pete Carroll, then New
England's coach, told the Pats, ``Don't be surprised if you see
that team in the Super Bowl,'' Jefferson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do what I'm supposed to do, I think I can help this team
get back to where it was,'' Jefferson said. On the Falcons' way to
Super Bowl XXXIII, running back Jamal Anderson got most of the ink
for his 1,846 rushing yards. But that bruising running attack set
up a great downfield passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta averaged 15.8 yards per completion and 8.8 per attempt,
and the Falcons were No. 1 or No. 2 in the NFL in most passing
categories.
</P>
<P>
   In the game against the Patriots, Atlanta averaged 15.6 yards
per attempt and 9.9 yards per completion.
</P>
<P>
   But last offseason, coach Dan Reeves released speedy wide
receiver Tony Martin, who had led the Falcons in `98 with 66
receptions and 17.9 yards per grab. Then, the Falcons averaged 13.3
yards per completion and a paltry 7.3 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the 6-foot, 180-pound sprinter Jefferson. He never has
caught more than 54 passes a season in nine years on the NFL. But
his per-catch averages the last four years have been the best of
his career 15.4 yards, 15.6, 22.7 and 17.5. Quarterback Chris
Chandler, who openly pined for Martin last summer, isn't
complaining. ``He's been outstanding. He's got even more (speed)
than I thought,'' Chandler said. ``He's got a great attitude, he's
a good route runner, has great quickness and has experience.'' Tim
Dwight, a sprinter himself, took over for Chris Calloway in the
middle of last season and will play plenty again. But team
officials want to try to keep Dwight healthy by reducing his
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight is 5 feet 8. ``That's why a guy like (6-foot-5 reserve
receiver Brian) Finneran can beat some guys deep,'' Chandler said,
``just because he can catch a ball over somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, the 11th of 12 children from a family in
Jacksonville's infamous Blodgett Homes housing project, never has
been the main man.
</P>
<P>
   He was a ninth-round draft choice of the Oilers in `91 but was
traded to San Diego. There, Martin was the primary receiver,
including the 1994 season when the Chargers went to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego cut Jefferson for salary reasons, Bill Parcells signed
him to a contract with the Patriots in `96, and he went to another
Super Bowl. But rookie receiver Terry Glenn was the star that
season.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson has been compared with Martin. Falcons wide receiver
Terance Mathis said to forget such comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret Tony and I have had the best relationship so
far,'' Mathis said. ``Now, Shawn and I are developing a good
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair that everybody keeps saying, `Is this guy going
to fill Tony's shoes, be the next Tony?' Shawn is his own person.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Reeves likes that person. ``We're using him some in the
slot, too,'' the coach said. ``The thing is, he's an extremely hard
worker, and that helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson knows no other way. In a 144-game career, he has
missed one game, because of a concussion. The co-owner of ``Any
Occasion Catering'' in Marietta, he also has been successful
investing for himself on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, you have to do things (all out),'' Jefferson
once told the Boston Globe. ``Any play could be your last. When I
walk away from this game, I don't want to be able to say, 'I could
have done this,' or, 'I could have done that.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
