<HEADER>
A4961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-OLY-JENNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-17 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OLY-JENNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECCENTRIC AND EXTREME, JENNINGS SEES `NO LIMITS, NO BOUNDARIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gabe Jennings grew up in a wilderness
community in northern California where his home was one of the few
with indoor plumbing, electricity came from generators and
television was nonexistent. He never watched the Olympic track and
field trials or the Summer Games until four years ago, when his
family had moved to Madison, Wis., and he was a senior in high
school, working in a running-shoe store.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first taste of the Olympics,'' Jennings said. ``I
remember dreaming about where I would be in four years. All kids
with aspirations do that. But it's one thing to dream. It's quite
another thing to make your dreams come true.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, using a punishing kick that began with 550 meters
left in the 1,500-meter race, Jennings surged to the front and
never relinquished his lead at the Olympic trials, winning in a
personal-best 3 minutes 35.90 seconds. He is also the collegiate
1,500-meter champion from Stanford who, at 21, is the most visible
symbol of an encouraging emergence of young American
middle-distance runners.
</P>
<P>
   He runs with shuffling strides, speaks in jazzy riffs, which
befits a music major, and is often referred to as a throwback to
the 1960s because of his counterculture nature. He has been known
to sleep on the roof of his co-op at Stanford, wear a flowing
Moroccan robe around campus and attend his classes in bare feet.
Last week, in an online column for Runners World magazine, he
ranted about everything from his training to his bowel movements.
He credited his victory here to the energy of a full moon and said
that his emergence from a bout of depression earlier this season
came from consorting with nature, which should not be surprising
for a guy whose middle name is Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the earth, the wind, the trees,'' Jennings said. ``I
feel its spirit. It puts me in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He resists easy categorizing, however. The laid-back hippie
image is popular but incorrect. More accurately, he is a sort of
type-A Maynard G. Krebs, emotional, highly driven, wildly elated
over success and badly discouraged over defeat, which is the most
attractive and troubling aspect about his personality, according to
his coach, Vin Lananna.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings once injured the band of connective tissue that runs
down the outside of his legs from clasping bongo drums tightly for
hours. To become proficient enough to major in music at Stanford,
he played the keyboard six hours a day until he wrenched his back.
Wanting to run like a Kenyan, he began trying to train like a
Kenyan, logging more than 100 miles a week as a sophomore and
developing shinsplints. And he is the rare athlete to injure
himself by running too aggressively in a pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe is a man of extremes,'' Lananna said. ``He strives for
perfection. You worry about stuff like that. Every time, you might
not be able to be first or get the world record. There's a
difference between shooting for this and being devastated if it
doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lananna, a native of Brooklyn, has decided to temper his young
runner's obsessive training but not to rein in his aspirations for
greatness. Stanford has become the epicenter for a revival of hope
for American distance running. Jennings' teammate Michael Stember
finished third in the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Too much time is spent complaining that environmental, genetic
and sociological reasons prevent Americans from competing with
Africans and other runners, Lananna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally coming to accept in the U.S. that the bar is not
going to get lower and we need to step up,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   That step will require a giant leap to the next rung of
international competitiveness. ``I feel reborn, ready to run with
the big guys,'' Jennings said. Despite his breakthrough performance
on Sunday, though, he is nearly 10 full seconds behind the world
record-holder and Olympic favorite in the metric mile, Hicham
el-Guerrouj of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm running for the silver medal now,'' he said today
after being told of el-Guerrouj's enervating training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the success of Jennings is not so unlikely as it might
sound. He grew up in Forks of Salmon, Calif., on the Salmon River
in Klamath National Forest, where the family chopped its own wood
for heat and grew its own food in a garden. His parents, Jim and
Suzanne Jennings, were teachers at the community school. Once a
year, Gabe said, youngsters from three area communities
participated in what was called the River Olympics, which included
picnic events like three-legged races but also serious running
events. To train for the yearly competition, Gabe said he ran about
two miles to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad said, `If you want to be good, you've got to run to
school every day,''' Gabe said.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to Wisconsin when Gabe was 13, first to
Jefferson, then to Madison, the capital, which has its own thriving
counterculture scene. He played quarterback in junior high, then
began running full time when the family moved to Madison, ``where
the whole city doesn't revolve around Saturday night football
games.'' He won nine state titles, ran a 4:02.81 mile and received
a scholarship to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know me don't see it as conflict,'' Jennings said
of his running and his lifestyle. ``The media tries to categorize
me, call me hippie, alternative. I work hard. My social life and
beliefs don't interfere with my running or get in the way of my
training.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, he said, he awakened to find his foot tapping
and realized it would be his day. He took his customary nap before
the race and awakened so overcome with happiness that he said he
began crying. ``I felt like I had already won the race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With his parents banging drums in the stands, Jennings crossed
the finish line first, took off his spikes and heard Lananna say,
``Jennings, put your shoes on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But coach, I already ran the race,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as he began the formal processing for the American
Olympic team at a local hotel, Jennings wore a gauzy shirt and
jeans and carried his slippers in his hand, the soles of his bare
feet as black as chimney soot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bourgeoisie lifestyle makes my skin itch,'' Jennings said.
``I feel a need not to fit the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Running for him seems as free as the wilderness that he grew up
in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no limits,'' he said, ``no boundaries, no fields, no
courts to cage you in.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he did make one recent concession, he admitted, as a
friend approached and congratulated him on the shaving of his
goatee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go a little more mainstream,'' Jennings said with a
laugh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
