<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS &LR;      07-17 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SUPPORTS LAW THAT BANS 
EXECUTION OF PREGNANT WOMEN 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Answering a question over which his
Democratic opponent had stumbled, George W. Bush on Monday said
that he supports a little-known federal law that prohibits pregnant
women from being executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a second life involved,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican presidential candidate is a strong
supporter of the death penalty, he added: ``No matter what your
position is on abortion or on the death penalty, you shouldn't put
a pregnant woman to death.''
</P>
<P>
   The question and the response were largely academic because few
pregnant women end up on death row and no executions in the United
States are carried out within the nine-month term of a normal
pregnancy. But the responses of the two presidential candidates
contrasted almost as sharply as their opposing views on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The question was initially asked of Vice President Al Gore on
Sunday by moderator Tim Russert during a discussion of abortion on
NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you're talking about,'' Gore initially
replied when Russert asked him about the federal ban on putting
pregnant women to death.
</P>
<P>
   However on Monday, Gore said he had read the law.
</P>
<P>
   He said he supports it, even though he knows of no case in which
it would apply since it takes more than nine months for the death
penalty to be carried out, and that the condemned are not allowed
contact visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do support that statute because the principle of a woman's
right to choose governs in that case,'' Gore said at a news
conference in his campaign headquarters in Nashville, Tenn. ``I
don't know of any real case where that has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The provision was enacted in 1994 as part of a federal law that
expanded the death penalty to numerous federal crimes. The
legislation was signed into law by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know what the circumstances would be in that
situation. I would, you know, it's an interesting fact situation,''
Gore added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush both support the death penalty, but they differ on
abortion. Gore supports abortion rights, and Bush opposes them.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked Bush about Gore's Sunday response while the
Texas governor was campaigning in Clinton's home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that my opponent was unable to take a position
on that issue,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Bush said he was narrowing his list of
prospective running mates but noted he still hadn't decided on a
vice presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   While in Little Rock, Bush visited a private, nonprofit agency
providing services to children and families. He said that, if
elected president, he would urge all the states to establish
paternity registries, similar to what some states, including Texas
and Arkansas, already have.
</P>
<P>
   Paternity registries help protect the rights of unmarried
fathers who want to claim responsibility for their children. But a
father who fails to register within 30 days of a child's birth can
have his parental rights terminated, which can allow an adoption to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, after a short, rousing speech encouraging campaign workers
in Nashville to jump whole-heartedly into his race, called a news
conference to attack Bush's record in dealing with Texas' budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the state's surplus had decreased from $6.4 billion in
1999 to $350 million (legislative leaders say $390 million) today,
Gore said: ``The same thing that he has done to the surplus in
Texas would be done, and more, to the surplus that we have in our
nation, just by taking the proposals that he has put out so far.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore's staff also distributed photocopies of a Washington Post
column written by one of Bush's top economic advisers, Harvard
economist Martin Feldstein.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used the column to point out that Feldstein had conceded
that Bush's Social Security plan would require the system to go
into a deficit for the first time in its 65-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, when the Social Security trust fund `runs dry,' his
words, they will start borrowing for the Social Security trust
fund. Read it for yourself in black and white,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush's plan, which would give retirees 2 percentage
points of their Social Security payments to invest in the stock
market, would put the Social Security trust fund as much as $3
trillion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
$$$
</P>
