<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GEN-MILLS-MARKETPLACE     07-17 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MILLS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: INVESTOR'S DOUBLE TAKE ON GENERAL MILLS' PLAN FOR
PILLSBURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GENERALMILLS-PILLSBURY) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In announcing that it would pay $10.5 billion for
Pillsbury, General Mills served notice Monday that it wanted to be
the king of convenience foods, an important area for time-pressed
consumers and the companies that want their business.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street turned the tables on General Mills, putting
pressure on the company to make the deal with Diageo, the owner of
Pillsbury, pay off. Concerns about the bite the acquisition will
take out of earnings for the foreseeable future caused investors to
push down General Mills' share price by $2.6875, or 7.4 percent, to
$33.625.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly distressing was the company's forecast of a 20
percent reduction in earnings for the next two years. While
investors had expected earnings of $2.20 a share in fiscal 2001,
they will get $1.73, estimated John McMillin, a food stocks analyst
at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock is down because when General Mills shareholders saw
that 20 percent hit, they felt like they needed one of Diageo's
stiffest drinks,'' McMillin said. With Pillsbury off its books and
a partial spinoff of Burger King under way, Diageo becomes a
company focused on its global liquor and beer businesses. Diageo's
American depository receipts gained 62.5 cents, to $36.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sanger, chairman and chief executive of General Mills,
said the combination would make the company the fifth-biggest food
maker in the United States, with more than 80 percent of its
products in the convenience-food or quick-preparation categories.
He also predicted that it would add to earnings in 2004 through
product innovation, international expansion, a doubling of the
company's food-service business and savings from streamlining
production and purchasing. Sanger said he planned to keep all the
brands, except for the Pillsbury cake mixes and Green Giant canned
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Sacrificing some earnings along the way to a sound strategic
goal can be palatable to investors if a company is in a rapidly
growing industry. But in the food industry, where growth of 5
percent is respectable these days, the specter of diminished
earnings made investors uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to hearing that from Amazon, but that is not what you
want to hear from a food maker,'' said Daniel Peris, a stock
analyst with Argus Research who downgraded General Mills. ``When
investing in a food company, one is looking for stability.''
</P>
<P>
   General Mills is already a player in the cereal, cake mix,
yogurt and meal-preparation-mix areas of the supermarket, where its
brands include Lucky Charms, Betty Crocker, Yoplait and Hamburger
Helper. The merger will give it a presence in some other aisles,
with products like Green Giant frozen vegetables, Progresso soups,
Pillsbury ready-to-bake biscuits and Haagen-Dazs ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   The combination would seem to make a stronger company. But some
analysts and investors are concerned that fitting all those new
elements into the corporation will take up much of management's
attention _ maybe more than they bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   ``There remains skepticism about whether General Mills can
really use this acquisition to grow its top line,'' said Erika
Gritman Long, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``People are very
focused on what Pillsbury's been able to do. The data the company
gave was that it grew 1 percent, while the rest of the category
grew 4 percent. It has lagged its own category.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the deal represents the so-called second stage in
food-company consolidation. In the first stage, top companies like
Bestfoods and Nabisco were swept up for premium prices. Now, with
companies of similar size pairing off to improve their competitive
position against behemoths, the task gets more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mergers of equals are going to require work,'' McMillin
said. ``I do think this will build a better General Mills, but they
are having to take a step back. There were people in the room today
at the analysts' meeting who were wondering, `Are they marrying the
girl next door just because she's the girl next door? Or were they
really dying to get their hands on the Doughboy?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sanger said he was enthusiastic about the Pillsbury lineup and
was convinced the market would share his enthusiasm once the news
was absorbed. There is a $642 million bet riding on that. Under
terms of the deal, General Mills has to pay just $4.5 billion in
cash, together with $5.4 billion in stock, if the share price
reaches $42.55 within a year after the deal closes in December. If
the price is $38 a share or lower, it pays $5.1 billion in cash,
along with the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bet that doesn't look too good out of the gate,''
McMillin said. ``But it's a creative way to share the potential
benefits down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
