<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-COVERDELL_SURGERY18-C     07-17 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL_SURGERY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Sen. Coverdell has surgery to stop cerebral bleeding
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., underwent two hours of
emergency surgery Monday to stop bleeding in his brain after
suffering a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, 61, was listed in serious condition at Piedmont
Hospital and was in the intensive care unit, where doctors said he
will remain indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors declined to predict Coverdell's prognosis for recovery,
adopting what they termed a ``wait-and-see'' approach during the
next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give the senator a little bit of time to
recover and get over all of this,'' said Dr. Gary Gropper, who
diagnosed Coverdell's cerebral hemorrhage and performed the
surgery. ``It's a serious condition. Any time that you have a
cerebral hemorrhage and you require my services, it's serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Coverdell's condition was life-threatening, Gropper
said, ``I think it's very serious and something we'll have to keep
a close eye on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Coverdell's office received anxious words of
support from
</P>
<P>
   Senate colleagues, and staff members fielded calls from
concerned constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was rushed to Piedmont Hospital in an ambulance about
10 p.m. Saturday after complaining of severe headaches Doctors
performed tests Sunday but his condition worsened, prompting
doctors to operate at 11 a.m. Monday to stop the bleeding and
relieve pressure building inside Coverdell's skull.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Coverdell's family, doctors and the senator's
staff released few details about the extent of the bleeding and the
specifics of the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's aides said he had worked part of the day Saturday,
but declined to offer any details about how and when he first
experienced symptoms, or when doctors diagnosed the cerebral
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who is a heart surgeon, rushed to
Atlanta on Monday to be with Coverdell's wife, Nancy, and field a
few questions about Coverdell's condition at a 3 p.m. news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family and others have obviously reached out and asked
that we don't go into too much interpretation and personal
details,'' Frist said. ``What's important is that we are at a
wait-and-see.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gropper, doctors operated on a blood clot in one of
Coverdell's temporal lobes, a portion of the brain that controls
visual recognition, auditory perception, memory and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Patients can and do recover from cerebral hemorrhages, but the
extent of recovery depends on how much bleeding occurred and in
what part of the brain, according to Dr. Laligam Sekhar, a
professor of neurosurgery at George Washington University Medical
Center in Washington. ``If the patient is diagnosed quickly enough,
then we can perform surgery to relieve the pressure by removing the
blood clot and stopping the bleeding,'' Sekhar said. ``General
recovery is excellent, although the person may still have some
effects as a result of the location of the hemorrhage.'' Doctors
said Coverdell suffered no pre-existing condition that they were
aware of that might have caused the hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Monday, senators called Coverdell a
dedicated and hard-working member of Congress and offered prayers
for a quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a senator that works any harder, that has a
more indomitable spirit,'' said Sen. Trent Lott, R-Tenn., the
majority leader. ``Our thoughts and our prayers are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who tapped Coverdell last year to
serve on his presidential steering committee, sent his ``love and
best wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for a successful outcome to today's surgery and look
forward to his continuing service to Georgia and the nation,'' said
Bush. Coverdell served as Peace Corps director in the
administration of Bush's father, President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's staff reacted with shock and visible concern as the
severity of his condition became known. The senator was known for
frequently working 12-, 14- and 16-hour days, including weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just all praying and keeping him in our prayers,'' said
Heather Hammerstrom of Duluth, Coverdell's receptionist at his
Washington office. Gov. Roy Barnes, who served with Coverdell in
the state Senate, called Coverdell's family before the senator went
into surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prayerful and hopeful that Paul will recover,'' Barnes
said. ``I wouldn't be writing Paul off. Paul is a strong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
