<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UGANDA-POLITICIAN-ART     07-17 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-POLITICIAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UGANDA, AN ASPIRING PRESIDENT'S JAIL TIME WINS POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT13, -14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda _ It was not the most conventional way for an
aspiring president of Uganda to warm up a crowd. But it seemed to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Nasser Ntege Sebaggala said at a rally downtown
recently, ``for welcoming me at the airport when I was coming from
jail in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd rose up in cheers remembering that day in February,
when Sebaggala, 52, a businessman and former mayor of Kampala,
arrived home after serving one year of a 15-month federal prison
term for passing bad checks in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers were uprooted along the route from the airport and
strewn on the road. He took six hours to travel a distance that
normally might last an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Sebaggala has become a political phenomenon in Uganda, despite
his obvious flaws. He is a convicted fraud. He is not
well-educated.
</P>
<P>
   His English is not only atrocious but comical. One of the
national newspapers cruelly ran a verbatim transcript of an
interview in English not long after he came home. His native tongue
is Luganda, the language of Uganda's largest ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   He is popular because of his flaws, not to mention a well-honed
populist touch. In the same way that some Americans may see a bit
of themselves in Bill Clinton's indiscretions, some Ugandans who
feel left behind in the nation's slow economic revival embrace the
entire package of Sebaggala. They actually like the idea that he
may have stolen $44,000 in one of the world's richest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Sebaggala,'' Mark Mukiibi, 25, a teacher, said at the
rally. ``He knows the people of the Uganda. He understand the
problems of Ugandans.''
</P>
<P>
   Mukiibi dismissed any suggestion that Sebaggala's stint in
prison might make it hard for him to run for president. ``That was
a very short time,'' he said. ``It was not even a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Sebaggala can, in fact, translate that
popularity into the presidency. Early next year, Ugandans will
elect a leader for only the third time in 21 years. If he runs _
and he says he will _ Sebaggala will face President Yoweri
Museveni, who is his opposite in nearly every way.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni, in office since he fought his way to power in 1986,
graduated from Dar es Salaam University in Tanzania and is able to
make campaign speeches into little history lessons. His English is
flawless. He is a military man, while Sebaggala is a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni's career was in many ways formed against the
dictatorship of Idi Amin in the 1970s, while Sebaggala's businesses
did quite well then.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni is often given credit for turning Uganda around after
the ravages of Amin and another dictator, Milton Obote. But many
people say Sebaggala's popularity is a reflection of the things
still undone in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty and unemployment are still high. Uganda's involvement in
the war in neighboring Congo is unpopular. Many people are tired of
Museveni after 14 years in office and would like the political
system, a so-called no-party state, opened up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much cynicism'' about Museveni, said Charles
Onyango-Obbo, the editor of The Monitor, an independent national
newspaper. ``They are just throwing Sebaggala in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People were laughing at him'' when he first returned home,
Onyango-Obbo said of Sebaggala. ``He couldn't speak proper English.
But it's made him terribly popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebaggala, one of 23 children in a Muslim family of several
wives, began his career as a sales representative of a dairy
company in the early 1970s. In 1973 he started a textile company
and became one of the leading businessmen in Kampala, as black
Africans took over the economy after Amin expelled the ethnic
Indian business class in the early 1970s. He was mentioned in
newspaper articles as Uganda's youngest millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, he beat the incumbent mayor of Kampala,
Christopher Iga, who was backed strongly by Museveni, in a vote
seen as a rebuke to the president. Soon after his election, he
attended a conference on garbage disposal in the United States and
ended up arrested in Boston. He was charged with passing eight
fraudulent traveler's checks worth $44,000 and was convicted in
December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, trafficking in fake currencies and traveler's checks
became a way of life for a certain class of businessman as Museveni
liberalized the economy and foreign exchange in the late 1980s. But
Sebaggala, who opened a foreign exchange business in 1992, denied
that he had done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview he said that among $2.5 million in deposits he
had made in the Bank of Boston were some bad traveler's checks that
a few customers had passed him without his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say you can't put me as responsible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prison term only made his legend grow. He was released in
December 1999, and his homecoming was a national event. He made his
political ambitions clear as soon as he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am no longer a businessman,'' he said at the time. ``I am a
full-time politician.'' Then the next day: ``I have come not only
to liberate this country but to bring a revolution. If I am
arrested you should not demand for my bail, because most people
cannot afford the bail fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has campaigned around Uganda, at one point being
shot at by government soldiers in the town of Mbarara, in what the
government said was a mistake and Sebaggala says was an attempt on
his life. He was a strong supporter of a boycott of the referendum
held in June on whether to continue Museveni's ``no party'' system.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk of revolution, Sebaggala is not proposing
anything especially radical. He wants a return to multiparty
politics. He wants to increase the use of irrigation in farming,
which employs more than 80 percent of Ugandans. He wants to attract
more foreign business, particularly technology companies. He says
he would expand education.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of his political ideas had come from his time in
the United States, which he said he admired very much despite the
prison term. There is one area especially in which he would like
Uganda to be more like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always when I am in campaign I mention your countrymen, like
George Washington,'' he said. ``You remember that they tried to put
him for a third term? He said it was enough and the young
generation should take over. What he did was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give the example that the more than 40 presidents, they
relinquished power and have been buried in America. None of them
went into exile.''
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, since independence from Britain in 1963, every
president has gone into exile. If all goes well, he would like to
make Museveni the first not to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
