<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-COVERDELL-SIDEBAR18     07-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-SIDEBAR18 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coverdell's type of stroke less common but more serious
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The bleeding in the brain that sent Sen. Paul
Coverdell into emergency surgery Monday is the less common of two
types of injury arising from problems with circulation in the
brain. But it is often more serious.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the 750,000 strokes that occur each year in the
United States are ischemic, caused when an artery to the brain is
blocked by a blood clot or narrowed by deposits on the walls of the
blood vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell suffered the less common hemorrhagic stroke, the broad
name for several types of bleeding into the brain caused by slow
leakage or sudden rupture of a blood vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Hemorrhagic stroke accounts for 20 percent of strokes in the
United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hemorrhagic stroke is the deadlier of the two. Mortality with
hemorrhagic stroke is 50 percent, whereas the mortality with
ischemic stroke is around 20 percent,'' said Dr. Michael Frankel,
chief of neurology at Grady Health System and associate professor
of neurology at Emory University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the survivors (of hemorrhagic stroke), a significant number
of people remain with some disability,'' he added, stressing that
he was not familiar with the details of Coverdell's case. ``A
proportion of people can return to work and to their previous level
of functioning, but with them it is the exception, rather than the
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemorrhagic stroke and ischemic stroke have similar symptoms _
weakness on one side of the body, difficulty speaking, balance
problems, confusion, sudden severe headache _ arising from the same
problem, the death of brain tissue. But the mechanics are deeply
different.
</P>
<P>
   The blockage that triggers ischemic stroke starves an area of
the brain of oxygen. In cerebral hemorrhage, bleeding into the
brain, or between the surface of the brain and the membranes lining
the skull, places pressure on brain tissue. The brain responds by
swelling; compression against the unyielding skull causes tissue
death.
</P>
<P>
   Cerebral hemorrhages tend to fall into two categories, Frankel
said. In one, accounting for about 15 percent of strokes, a small
blood vessel that has been overstressed by high blood pressure
tears or gives way, allowing blood to leak out and form a clot that
presses on nearby tissue. In the remaining 5 percent of strokes, an
aneurysm _ a balloon-like outpouching of the wall of one of the
larger arteries of the brain _ suddenly ruptures. That allows
uncontrolled bleeding into or around the brain that may, or may
not, form a clot over the aneurysm site.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid surgery can relieve increased pressure on the brain,
though brain tissue that has died cannot be revived.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery is usually necessary with aneurysms, Frankel said,
because the risk of a secondary rupture is so high: up to 50
percent of patients will have a second bleed from the same defect
within six months if the aneurysm is not repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the most common type of hemorrhage, a hematoma inside the
brain due to high blood pressure, surgeons can go in and take the
clot out,'' he said. ``More often, they will not take it out,
because going in can cause more damage than it will do good.''
</P>
<P>
   Though aspects of hemorrhagic stroke remain mysterious _ it
isn't known, for instance, exactly why some vessels deep in the
brain are particularly vulnerable to leakage _ some risk factors
are well-recognized.
</P>
<P>
   They include uncontrolled high blood pressure (consistently more
than 140/90); alcohol and drug abuse; use of anticoagulant
medications; increased age; and gender. Hemorrhage from aneurysm
rupture is slightly more common in women; deep intracerebral
hemorrhage is more often seen in men.
</P>
<P>
   Race is also a factor: African-Americans are at higher risk of
both types of stroke than whites, probably because they are more
vulnerable to high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to addressing the risk factors that can be
controlled, it is vital to be familiar with the symptoms of stroke
and to respond to them, Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   In a study he co-authored recently, only one-third of metro
Atlanta residents could identify even one stroke symptom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you or a family member experience weakness or numbness on
one side of the body, difficulty speaking, severe headache or any
of the other major symptoms, call 911 immediately,'' he said.
``Don't wait for the symptoms to go away. Treat this as you would a
heart attack: Get to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
