A4973 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      07-17 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys ready to begin answering questions
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys had only two head
coaches over their first 34 seasons of existence. But when owner
Jerry Jones met the media Monday for his annual camp-opening news
conference, he had a new face beside him for the third time in
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Switzer lasted four seasons, Chan Gailey only two. But
this time, Jones stayed within the organization with a man he knows
well. Former defensive coordinator Dave Campo celebrates his 53rd
birthday today as he officially opens ``Camp Campo'' with the first
of two-a-day practices.
</P>
<P>
   How well Campo performs in his new role is one of the questions
the Cowboys will at least begin to answer over a five-week training
camp at Midwestern State University.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest questions involve the offense, which finished as
only the 16th-best in the NFL last year after losing receiver
Michael Irvin to what became a career-ending neck injury. The
Cowboys also lost longtime fullback Daryl Johnston to a recurring
neck injury, and he too retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect our coaches, with Dave's leadership, to step up and
add an element of leadership to take up some of the slack of not
having some of those veteran players around,'' Jones said. ``With
the coaching staff and veteran players we have now, we must
recognize that there's a void there and do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations are to have a team that is real exciting
offensively, entertaining offensively. That's the focus. I believe
we have the talent on defense, but our challenge in this camp is to
really get this thing going offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's tenure as defensive coordinator makes him the perfect
tutor for the offense, having spent his career studying offenses
and devising ways to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well aware that offenses bring people into the stands, and
I'm well aware what offenses mean in this league,'' Campo said.
``There's no question that when you look around the league, the
team that scores the most points wins. So I'm excited to get over
there, and I really feel like I have a good knowledge of the type
of things you need to do offensively to make it hard on a defense.
You've got to know how to take advantage of your personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Other questions:
</P>
<P>
   1) How will Dallas handle life without The Playmaker? As a rule,
the Cowboys have struggled without Irvin in the lineup, be it
because of injuries or suspensions. But this time they're better
prepared after acquiring the speedy Joey Galloway in the offseason
to complement Rocket Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   2) Who will step up in place of cornerback Deion Sanders? Not
only did he defect, but he went to the division-rival Washington
Redskins, who have built an imposing team over the last couple of
offseasons. Former Brown Ryan McNeil has had four jobs in a
seven-year career, none more pressure-filled than taking Sanders'
former slot.
</P>
<P>
   3) Was it the offense or the quarterback? It was no secret Troy
Aikman wasn't comfortable in Gailey's offense, but now he's gotten
his wish. The Cowboys are returning to the basic packages that made
Aikman a perennial Pro Bowler and earned him three Super Bowl
rings. Now he needs to put up the numbers and prove he's still
capable.
</P>
<P>
   4) What's left in Emmitt Smith's legs? It has to be asked every
year of the 31-year-old running back, who has 3,592 carries over a
10-year career. His 1,397-yard 1999 season proved he's not ready
for the rocking chair, but wear begins taking its toll on all
athletes at some point.
</P>
<P>
   5) Can a big heart make up for small stature on an every-play
basis? Dat Nguyen had a knack for always being around the football
during his college days at Texas A&AMP;M and his Cowboys rookie season,
in which he played mostly in nickel situations. How will the 5-11
middle linebacker perform against his larger counterparts on a
regular basis? The Cowboys have penciled him in as the starter in
the position often referred to as ``quarterback of the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   6) How successful was the 2000 draft? Four of the Cowboys' 1999
draft picks are listed as likely starters this year. Besides Nguyen
at middle linebacker, Solomon Page is expected to start at right
guard, Ebenezer Ekuban will start at right defensive end, and end
Peppi Zellner could start on the left side (while Greg Ellis
continues to rehabilitate a broken leg).
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys didn't have a first-round pick this year, but there
are spots where rookies could make an immediate impact. Keep an eye
on defensive backs Dwayne Goodrich and Kareem Larrimore.
</P>
<P>
   7) Can the offense rebound? Aikman's displeasure and the loss of
several receivers to injury led to a floundering offense. James
McKnight should be back, as should Wane McGarity. Add Galloway,
Ismail and the emerging Jason Tucker, and there should be plenty of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   8) Will the Cowboys be more disciplined? Dallas led the league
in penalties last year, and this area will be emphasized in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   9) Can the Cowboys improve outside Texas Stadium? They didn't
win on the road after the season opener at Washington and are 6-18
in road games over the last three years. Couple that with a
schedule that has them packing their bags four times over the first
six weeks, and that improvement had better come quickly.
</P>
<P>
   10) The Cowboys beat the Redskins twice last year, but
Washington ran away with the NFC East title. The Redskins have
added the second and third picks of the draft and opened the bank
for Sanders, making them the preseason favorites for a repeat
division title and more.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
