<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GENERALMILLS-PILLSBUR     07-17 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERALMILLS-PILLSBURY-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MILLS TO ACQUIRE IT PILLSBURY, ITS LONGTIME NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Britain) (See also GEN-MILLS-MARKETPLACE column) 
 &HT;     By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They grew up together on the banks of the
Mississippi River, two 19th century milling companies that competed
head to head and made this city the flour capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Their decades-old signs still face each other across the river
in symbolic combat _``Gold Medal Flour,'' from General Mills, on
the west bank, and ``Pillsbury's Best'' on the east. On Monday,
though, General Mills and Pillsbury said they were uniting to
create a food giant with more than $12 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The initial announcement came from Diageo, the British
conglomerate, that acquired Pillsbury more than a decade ago.
Diageo said early Monday that it had agreed to sell Pillsbury to
General Mills in a $10.5 billion deal, forming the fourth-largest
food company in the world. The merger would bring together such
well-known brands as Cheerios, Wheaties, Haagen-Dazs, Yoplait
yogurt, Hamburger Helper, Jolly Green Giant vegetables and
Pillsbury bakery items, though not all these products would remain
within the new company's stable.
</P>
<P>
   The planned merger comes during afrenzy of big food company
combinations, in which food makers are trying to bolster their
growth prospects through acquisitions and global power plays.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills and Pillsbury now saythey believe that Betty
Crocker and the Pillsbury Doughboy are a good fit and that
marketing and distributing their products together will yield huge
benefits. The companies also say they know each other well, and
their cultures are quite similar, which should make it a friendly
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Though many here worry about the job cuts that are sure to
follow, others are pleased that two companies that grew up together
on the Mississippi will remain in Minneapolis under the General
Mills name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that Pillsbury is being acquired by General
Mills,'' said Sharon Sayles Belton, the mayor of Minneapolis.
``They have a history of strong ties to the community. And I think
General Mills is going to grow. Short term there may be some job
losses, but long term there'll be growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason the concern here is muted is that ownership of
Pillsbury returns to Minneapolis after more than a decade in
London, where the company was controlled by Diageo.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies and their milling stories are really the
signature of Minnesota,'' said Nina Archabal, director of the
Minnesota Historical Society. ``To have these companies joined and
governed in Minnesota is a tremendous benefit to our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after starting out in the flour milling business,
General Mills and Pillsbury took widely divergent paths. They both
created premier brands, with Pillsbury staying closer to bakery
items and General Mills becoming a dominant player in the cereal
business. But they also strayed from their roots.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury acquired Burger King in 1967, helping make it into a
major player in the fast food business, before the two companies
were eventually acquired by Diageo, which specializes in liquor.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills also departed from the flour and ceral business,
gaining control over Izod/Lacoste, the retailers Eddie Bauer and
Talbots, Parker Brothers games and Red Lobster and Olive Garden
restaurants, all of which are now gone.
</P>
<P>
   Only in recent years, after a series of divestitures and
spinoffs, has General Mills sharpened its focus on cereal, bakery
items and yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company suffered during a period of competitive
price-cutting in the cereal industry in the early 1990s, General
Mills has been a strong performer in most of its businesses over
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently passed Kellogg's as the nation's leading
cereal maker, though the two are neck and neck, and its Yoplait and
Columbo yogurts give it supremacy in the category. General Mills
has also extended its product lines with Frosted Cheerios and Honey
Nut Cheerios as well as Go-Gurt, a squeezable tubed yogurt product
designed for children.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives have also tried to capitalize on health news
to promote their cereals, moving into organic food with the
purchase of Small Planet Foods Inc. They are working on creating
more convenience and instant foods for the growing number of
Americans who are eating on the go.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such innovation, General Mills has largely
outperformed other food companies in the past two years. Most are
facing slow growth prospects in a mature market with increasing
pressure from bigger and bigger retailers. General Mills,
meanwhile, has promised double digit profit growth and Wall Street
had cheered its plans, at least until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company fell sharply Monday because some analysts
and investors worried that Pillsbury was going to be a drag on
earnings. While the company has a hot food service division and
some healthy profits in refigerated products like Pillsbury dough
items and Haagen-Dazs, canned vegetables and other frozen items
have been a drag.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe General Mills may have felt pressured to
make a deal and been forced to pay too heavily for Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid a stiff price for this,'' said Art Cecil, a food
industry analyst at T. Rowe Price, which owns a large stake in
General Mills. ``I'd rather they not have done it. I thought Mills
was a great situation. They had great cash flow, innovative
management; it seemed a tidy situation. And now earnings are going
to be diluted by a fairly significant amount.''
</P>
<P>
   John McMillin, a longtime food analyst at Prudential, disagrees.
Though he says General Mills is going to have to do a lot to
convince Wall Street that this is a good deal, he believes the
company is moving aggressively to build a giant food portfolio
after more than a decade of trying to slim down and get out of
restaurant and nonfood businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Mills has been on a diet for most of the 15 years I've
followed it,'' McMillin said. ``But this deal with Pillsbury gives
them more growth opportunities, and growth is a rare commodity in
the food industry.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives at General Mills say that for antitrust reasons the
new company, which will be called General Mills, will divest itself
of Pillsbury's dessert business, which is second only to General
Mills'. The company will also sell its canned vegetable business,
but keep Green Giant frozen vegetables and meal starters, thereby
retaining the Jolly Green Giant icon.
</P>
<P>
   The company also hopes the Pillsbury Doughboy will fit in well
with marketing efforts that have kept Cheerios and even Betty
Crocker in the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the merger makes General Mills not just a much bigger
company, but one that is more diversified in the refigerated
section with ice cream to go with its yogurt and frozen vegetables,
breakfast offerings and more.
</P>
<P>
   Executives say that General Mills' marketing will help boost
Pillsbury brands that are growing at a slower pace than their
categories.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills brands, on the other hand, have been able to grow
faster than their categories, and that is a large part of the
growth story.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind these initiatives will be Steven Sanger, the
54-year-old chief executive at General Mills. Sanger, who took over
in 1995, has said that primary drivers in the food industry will
include increasing convenience (``driven by the pace of consumer
lifestyles,'') concerns about health, and international sales. He
also stresses creating products to be sold outside of supermarkets
and, eventually, the use of biotechnology to create more nutritious
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, General Mills' strength in the past year has been in
marked contrast with Pillsbury's, which has been going through an
earnings slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills has long been considered the bigger and better run
company here in Minneapolis, and some Pillsbury staffers are
wondering what that will mean for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough day here,'' said Dorrese Bona, a 20-year
employee at Pillsbury, as she sat in her cubicle just hours after
the announced merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with changes comes opportunity. General Mills has some
good brands so we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees at Pillsbury were wondering Monday whether they would
be moving just outside of Minneapolis, to Golden Valley, Minn.,
where General Mills headquarters is located on a 50-acre campus.
But company officials said that they had run out of space in Golden
Valley, and Belton of Minneapolis said she was assured that many
Pillsbury employees would remain downtown, in a 40-story office
tower called the Pillsbury Center.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two companies have more than 6,000 employees in
Minnesota, most of them in Minneapolis. The General Mills
headquarters is suburban and breezy, but more corporate; Pillsbury
is urban yet relaxed, with Pillsbury Doughboy dolls on nearly every
desk and the halls decked with the Doughboy and the Jolly Green
Giant standing in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Though some have called the General Mills corporate culture more
``button down'' and the Pillsbury culture more ``free-wheeling,''
several executives Monday said they were both relaxed and
welcoming, in a Minneapolis kind of way.
</P>
</TEXT>
