<HEADLINE>
MOVIE STUDIOS SUE WEB SITE TO BAN DVD-CRACKING SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first day of a case that could test the limits
of Hollywood's control over its digital properties, lawyers for
eight movie studios on Monday urged a federal judge to stop a Web
site operator from distributing a software program that unscrambles
the encryption on DVD movie disks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers asked the court to act before the studios suffer the
same fate as record companies, which have seen their
copyright-protected songs traded freely by millions of individual
Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The studios are trying to show that Eric Corley, publisher of
2600, a computer hacker magazine and Web site, violated copyright
law by posting on his Web site _ and linking to other Web sites
that do the same _ a program that breaks the code called CSS, or
Content Scrambling System, on DVDs. Once the program, known as
DeCSS, is invoked, a movie can be copied and sent across the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of world copying is here and the process has
begun,'' said Leon Gold, a partner with the New York law firm
Proskauer Rose LLP and lead lawyer for the studios. ``It will
become an avalanche unless this court acts.''
</P>
<P>
   A section of the federal Digital Millennium Copyright Act of
1998 makes it illegal for anyone to offer to the public a device
that is primarily intended to circumvent a technological barrier
controlling access to a copyright-protected work. But Corley's
lawyers argue that the law must be balanced against the First
Amendment concept of ``fair use,'' which allows consumers certain
freedoms with copyrighted works.
</P>
<P>
   The case will determine whether the new technology
``fundamentally means the end of fair use,'' Martin Garbus,
Corley's lead lawyer, said in his opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants have argued that DeCSS is legitimately used to
allow people who already own DVDs to view the disks on computers
running the Linux operating system, which they are unable to do
without descrambling the encryption.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Kaplan, the judge in the case, granted a preliminary
injunction in January requiring Corley to remove DeCSS from his
site.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he heard testimony from the studio's first witness,
Michael Shamos, a computer science professor at Carnegie Mellon
University.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan came down from the bench to view a laptop computer on
which Shamos showed first a DVD of ``Sleepless in Seattle'' and
then a copy of the DVD that he and an assistant had descrambled
with the DeCSS program and compressed with another program.
</P>
<P>
   Shamos said the practice of using DeCSS to copy movies is on the
rise. ``I believe as long as there's a DVD out there the people
ripping them won't stop until they've all been ripped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on cross examination, Garbus sought to highlight how
difficult the process is to perform, noting that it took Shamos and
his assistant 20 hours to obtain the compressed, unscrambled
version of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you agree with me that this is very tough stuff?''
Garbus asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not fun,'' Shamos conceded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
