<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE GROWTH OF TRASH-TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Earlier this week, Inger Miller and Chryste
Gaines sat under a sweltering tent, explaining how they had earned
their place on the Olympic team by finishing second and third,
respectively, in the 100-meter finals.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour earlier Marion Jones had smoked Miller and Gaines
to win the race going away.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones walked in, all lights shifted to her from Miller and
Gaines. Everyone tried their best to make nice.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable question came up about Jones possibly winning
five Olympic gold medals this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones forced a smile: ``If I had a penny for every time I was
asked that question, I'd be rich,'' she said. Gaines and Miller
glanced over and said in unison: ``You're not?'' Everyone including
Jones laughed. ``That may have been a bad choice of words,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the mildest form all week of the sort of trash-talking
and sniping that punctuated the sprinting competition among
American runners. The normally stoic Michael Johnson has fired
salvos at Maurice Green and others as a guest columnist. He chided
Green for being less than mature, doubted whether Gaines would even
make the team and questioning Miller's consistency.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Miller said Johnson's braids must have been braided
too tightly.
</P>
<P>
   One can argue that Jones started it all by proclaiming that she
intended to win five gold medals in Sydney _ not five medals, but
five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Jones, Miller, Green and Johnson, one wondered how
long this sort of wolfing had gone on between the runners? Have
they always talked and challenged and blustered, or is this just
more fallout from the dot-com generation of commodification?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Green jumped into his car and said the talking is
nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been like this,'' he said. ``Media is just
bringing it out more.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Coachman sat in her room Monday afternoon thinking about
the spate of trash-talking, contemplating whether trash-talking has
always been like this.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, she said, it has. In the 1948 Games in Paris,
Coachman, a high jumper, became the first African-American woman to
win a gold medal. She was also the only American women to win a
medal that year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the months before the Games, Coachman, who was also an
extraordinary sprinter, was a target, and a couple opponents had
public things to say about beating her. One competitor in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Patterson,'' she said, referring to a friend and rival
who died in 1996. ``When I first met Mickey she was winning all
these 100-yard dashes and we met either in a meet or at a trial.
Anyway she was going around talking: `I'm going to be Alice
Coachman, she's not that tough. I'm going to beat her.' When I
arrived in San Antonio everybody told me how she'd been going
around talking about how she was going to beat me. I said that's
fine. She tried to beat me, but she couldn't beat me. But she was
the one that was talking about how she was going to beat me, just
like a lot of them are doing to Marion Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the extent of it then,'' Coachman added. ``Now it's a
little different now because money's involved. Everybody's trying
to win, if you don't win that money's not there. Most big companies
won't promote a person who's not a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Smith, the former sprinter who coaches Maurice Green, didn't
totally agree with Coachman. ''It's about `I can beat you'; it's
the same thing you did when you were a kid. I don't want people to
get the idea that it's money that makes athletes talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman have always talked,'' Smith said. ``Before, the media
wouldn't print that. Now they're printing it because it's a
different slant.''
</P>
<P>
   The most peculiar aspect to the so called ``trash-calling'' is
not the athletes talking but the media reaction to the talking. The
same media that despises trash-talking as a signature of massive
cultural dysfunction also embraces it.
</P>
<P>
   Trash-talking becomes a commodity to be marketed like soft
drinks and outer wear. The athletes play into it like kids on the
playground surrounded by an inciting crowd, trying to incite them
into a brawl: ``Athletes are doing nothing new. It was always like,
`Man, I'll beat you.' `Oh, yeah? Watch. Come on out here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Only now, two reporters are standing there, and one
sensationalizes it, and it then becomes a competition between the
media as to who can put out the best sensationalized information to
draw the public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Coachman wasn't really buying it. She thought there was
something demeaning, belittling about all the trash-talking over
the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Would she be any different if she were competing in the 1990s?
</P>
<P>
   Coachman laughed and said, ``I would have been talking-trash,
too, if money was involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
