<SLUG> BC-SOFTBALLBRAWL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Covington mom in brawl at ball game faces hearing
 &HT;    By Andrea Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA- A Covington, Ga., mother may face criminal charges in
connection with a Saturday fight at a girls softball game that
ended with hospital trips for a player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lawrence, a coach for her daughter's Girls of Summer team
and wife of a Covington police officer, is scheduled to appear in a
probable cause hearing Aug. 2 after two parents and an umpire filed
applications for her arrest Monday in Newton County Magistrate
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Covington police Capt. Willie Davis said the altercation began
when two 14-year-olds argued over a play at first base during a
tournament at Turner Lake Park. When umpire Steve Hodges stepped in
to separate them, Lawrence and opposing coach Debbie Pugh ran onto
the field and began arguing, police said. Pugh told police Lawrence
grabbed her throat, threw her to the ground and kicked her in the
head.
</P>
<P>
   Police said players and more parents _ about 40 in all _ rushed
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Crawford, mother of the Buford Bomber first baseman, said
Lawrence shoved her head into a pole while she was trying to get
her daughter off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Police and league officials broke up the fray and ejected both
teams from the park.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh sustained minor head injuries and was treated and released
from DeKalb Medical Center. The first baseman was treated for neck
pain and released from Newton General.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time metro parents have come to blows over
children's sports. Cherokee County banned nine adults from a park
after a brawl last year. Coweta County parks ban for life anyone
who fights at county-sponsored events.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hailey, the director of parks and recreation for Newton
County, said the fight never should have happened. ``We're supposed
to be out there for the kids, and it seems like some of us forget
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
