u p BC-BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP-(T     07-17 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION ISSUE CASTING A SHADOW OVER BUSH'S V.P. SELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla., Okla., Neb., Tenn., Kan.)   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Gov. George W. Bush is asked what he is
looking for in a running mate, he talks about things like
preparedness to be president and compatibility. But he never
mentions one factor that several advisers say is hovering over the
entire process: abortion.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first presidential campaign, Republican advisers
say, in which the Republican candidate truly appears to be weighing
whether to pick a No. 2 who supports abortion rights. He has that
luxury because conservative stalwarts do not seem to mind. Many,
like Pat Robertson, are so eager to win back the White House that
they are willing to go along (albeit grudgingly) with just about
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bush's overtures to politicians who favor abortion
rights, namely Govs. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania and George Pataki of
New York, has decidedly scrambled the selection of a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Several advisers to Bush said, for example, that they are
certain Ridge would be at the top of the list were it not for his
stand on abortion. Ridge is from an important state, has an
impressive resume and, perhaps most importantly, gets along quite
well with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But one after another, several Bush advisers expressed
skepticism that the Pennsylvania governor would be picked. Some
predicted that the governor would settle for someone who is safely
anti-abortion, like Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Sen. Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska or Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee. Bush is
expected to make a decision in the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see it,'' said one Bush adviser who thinks Ridge
would make an ideal running mate in many ways _ except for the
risk. ``But why would you throw a monkey wrench into the gears of
your base?''
</P>
<P>
   He and other loyalists said they were especially worried that
choosing Ridge would infuriate the Catholic Church, which they
consider as much of a concern as the Christian Right.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have your No. 2 person not carrying out the dominant
position on the most difficult issue of the day would cause some
pause,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., who opposes abortion
rights. ``A bugle that doesn't sound a clear note doesn't rally the
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News Poll released Monday found that of Bush's current
supporters, about a third of those surveyed said they would be less
likely to vote for him if he picked a running mate who backed legal
abortion. They would not vote at all _ or defect to Pat Buchanan,
the abortion foe who is seeking the nomination of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, in an interview, questioned Buchanan's potency. ``I don't
think he's going to be factor,'' he said, ``And he's not about to
push Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida said in an interview that an abortion
rights position should be ``no disqualifier'' for his brother. His
choice favors abortion rights: Colin L. Powell. (But Bush aides
said Powell has made his disinterest clear.)
</P>
<P>
   Former President Gerald Ford weighed in for Ridge, scoffing at
the idea that abortion foes would desert the party. ``Where are
they gonna go?'' Ford asked in an interview published Monday in the
New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A minority of Bush advisers take issue with those who say Bush
is less inclined to take a risk. They argue that because Bush is
entering his convention ahead in the polls, he has more leeway to
pick a running mate who supports abortion rights. Some go as far as
to say that alienating conservatives who oppose abortion _ risky as
it would be _ could appear bold and entice not only to Republicans
who favor abortion rights but to swing voters and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who would say, `Good for Bush!''' said one
close Bush adviser who is pushing for Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Abramowitz, a political scientist at Emory University and
authority on abortion politics, said: ``You've got a nominee who is
clearly pro-life. You've got a platform that's clearly pro-life. I
think a display of independence could go over very well. Offending
an important interest group in your party, in its way, can have a
positive impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the case of Ridge, several Bush advisers explained that
the dangers were far deeper than the conventional wisdom that
religious conservatives would squawk and perhaps frustrate any
attempts at harmony at the party's national convention that opens
late this month.
</P>
<P>
   But some advisers to Bush _ even ones who favor Ridge _ said the
deeper concern in the Bush camp was over the reaction from the
Catholic church because the Pennsylvania governor is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not be able to hold functions in Catholic settings;
Catholic colleges, Catholic high schools, Catholic institutions,''
said one Bush adviser who otherwise said Ridge would make the best
choice. ``Every city that you were to go to, there would be bishops
and cardinals who would protest.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican operative who discussed the selection process
with Bush in the last week said, ``I don't think he's afraid of the
Christian right.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats grouse that Bush has a deeper bench of prospects
than Al Gore, the vice president has the advantage of not having
any single issue looming over his short list.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It could be, of course, that while his advisers are wrestling
with the possibilities, Bush really never intended to pick an
abortion rights candidate. Some abortion rights advocates say
Bush's toying with pro-choice candidates has been one grand shell
game to stroke his friends _ and placate abortion right supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale said he auditioned some
politicians in 1984 that he never intended to pick as his running
mate out of nothing more than friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all friends of mine,'' Mondale said. ``One of the
reasons I wanted to talk to them was I liked them and I didn't want
to hurt anyone's feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, that seemed to be what was happening when Bush
met with Pataki on Friday. After all, no Bush adviser has dared to
predict that Bush could win New York in November. And Bush is even
friendlier with Ridge than Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to Bush and Pataki said Monday that after the
two had their high-profile meeting Friday morning, they privately
met again over lunch that day. And some Bush advisers said the
Texas governor appeared to be taking a close look at Pataki
because, though he is Catholic, he has not had difficulties with
Catholic leaders in New York, as Ridge has had in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Those advisers said the problem for Ridge is he has now become
too closely identified with the abortion issue, as happened with
Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey. Whitman, for her part, argued
that an abortion rights running-mate would hardly be a drag on the
ticket. ``I've just talked to too many Republicans across the
country who say, `I don't want this to be the definer,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and other abortion rights Republicans can take heart
that Ronald Reagan picked a running mate in 1980 who _ unlike
Reagan _ had opposed a constitutional prohibition against abortion.
George Bush, the running mate, had little choice but to emphasize
that he opposed abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But he squirmed a bit at his joint news conference with Reagan:
``Please do not try to keep reminding me of differences I had,''
Bush implored.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Reagan-Bush ticket, the questions eventually
subsided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
