<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION WOULD BACK EVERETT APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox outfielder Carl Everett will have the right to
appeal any suspension handed down by Frank Robinson, baseball's
vice president of on-field operations who is expected to announce
his ruling as soon as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Players Association is prepared to file an
appeal if Everett asks, and would represent him in a subsequent
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Everett maintained his silence for a second day, and was in the
lineup playing center field and batting fifth against the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard anything about anything,'' said Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams, who earlier in the day, while guest of honor
at a BoSox Club luncheon, angrily reacted to a question about
Everett from emcee Chris Collins of New England Cable News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when I'm going to hear anything,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in contact with Frank's office,'' said Red Sox
spokesman Kevin Shea, adding that general manager Dan Duquette had
spoken with Robinson. ``They indicated they're in the fact-finding
stage of the process. They've read the umpires' report and they're
going to look at the video and they hope to gather all the material
(Monday and Tuesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Several officials in baseball's hierarchy were reluctant to
speculate on the severity of the penalty Everett is expected to
receive for twice making physical contact with umpire Ronald Kulpa
after being ejected from Saturday's 6-4 win over the New York Mets
at Fenway Park. Sox reliever Rod Beck suggested that Everett might
get five games for each time he came in contact with Kulpa. A
number of baseball officials at Fenway Park Monday night predicted
that Everett will be suspended at least 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez was suspended five games May 3
for hitting Robbie Alomar of the Cleveland Indians with a pitch
after being warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspending an everyday player, Everett, for five games,'' one
person in the baseball hierarchy said, ``is the equivalent of
giving Pedro 20 games, in terms of the amount of actual playing
time he'll miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who received the umpires' report Saturday night,
received a videotape Monday. Robinson said Saturday he had already
seen the incident _ in which Everett appeared to strike Kulpa with
the beak of his helmet, then head-butted him _ on TV.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it difficult to predict the penalty, those officials
said, was that this is Robinson's first year on the job, and this
will be his first ruling on physical contact between a player and
an umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Because it involved an umpire, one official said, Robinson gave
the matter precedence over other incidents that occurred on the
weekend, including a brawl in Colorado Saturday between the Rockies
and Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Robinson gave Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox a
five-game suspension for making contact with umpire Derryl Cousins.
In that incident, Cox grabbed Cousins's arm.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's contact with Kulpa appeared to be much more
aggressive, but one official said that Robinson's absence of a
track record in these matters makes it impossible to predict how he
will rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Carl being an All-Star, and because it involves an
umpire, this is obviously a high-profile case,'' said one major
league official.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the longest suspension given a player by Robinson is the
eight-game penalty he gave Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter for his
part in a brawl with fans in Chicago's Wrigley Field May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Another official suggested that any suspension greater than
eight games will be contested by the union, which would be expected
to argue, among other things, that forcing a player to sit out for
that length of time would put him at risk of injury upon his
return.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a significant change in the disciplinary process
since Major League Baseball abolished the league offices and placed
all authority in the commissioner's office. Previously, league
presidents handed down suspensions and heard subsequent appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, with input from executive vice president Sandy
Alderson, now makes disciplinary decisions. Appeals are heard by
Paul Beeston, baseball's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Beeston who overturned the suspensions Robinson gave to
12 members of the Dodgers for the Wrigley Field incident. Beeston
upheld the suspensions of four players and two coaches; the
stiffest suspensions of eight games were given to Dodgers catcher
Kreuter and coaches Rick Dempsey and John Shelby.
</P>
<P>
   Monday at the BoSox Club luncheon, Collins asked Williams a
question about the difficulty of managing the team in the absence
of Everett. Collins suggested that Williams would be working with a
23-man roster, since he also doesn't play Izzy Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been demonstrably sensitive on the issue of
Alcantara, whom he didn't play for two weeks until starting him
Saturday, and he bristled at being asked about Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just went into a 2 1/2-minute tirade,'' Collins said. ``He
said how he loved the Boston fans, but that it was people like
these guys (Collins) and other members of the media that try to
manage the team and create this bad atmosphere. He said he was
insulted by the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Williams walked away from the microphone and sat
down. He never mentioned Everett by name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
