<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-1STL     07-17 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TYCOON SAYS HE WILL SEEK TO RALLY OPPOSITION TO PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 18th graf to correct name to Vladimir Gusinsky sted Boris
Gusinsky)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Berezovsky, the archetypal Russian tycoon,
politician and, until lately, a force within the Kremlin itself,
said on Monday that he will quit his seat in parliament and try to
form an alliance of big business and regional politicians aimed at
curbing President Vladimir Putin's growing power.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky said that he is resigning on Wednesday because ``I do
not wish to take part in the dismantling of Russia and the
imposition of authoritarian rule.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the bluntest attack yet by a major figure on the popular
Putin, who has taken dead aim at Russia's business oligarchy and
its 89 regional governors in a bid to reimpose Kremlin control over
a virtually untamed political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   It also carried considerable risk for Berezovsky, an unpopular
public figure and one of the very tycoons Putin's administration is
sizing up. His plan for a new anti-Kremlin movement drew catcalls
when he first hinted at it earlier this month, and most experts
give it scant chance of quick success.
</P>
<P>
   By resigning from parliament's lower house, the Duma, Berezovsky
also will surrender his immunity to prosecution just as the
government is threatening criminal action against other tycoons _
and after prosecutors questioned him last Friday in an inquiry
involving the Russian airline Aeroflot.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon news conference here, Berezovsky took pains to
suggest that he seeks to a create a new loyal opposition to a
president whose convictions and honesty he still admires. Were last
March's presidential election to be held today, Berezovsky said at
one point, he would vote for Putin again.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sounded like an angry and betrayed man, one who
blasted the Kremlin's attacks on his fellow tycoons as nothing more
than a bald attempt to usurp power for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Russia is facing a choice: whether we will follow the
Latin American model, with an authoritarian power and market
economy, or the European model with a liberal power and market
economy,'' he said. ``The only possible option,'' he said, is the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   Russia experts here and in Washington say the tycoon's
announcement shows how swiftly Berezovsky, who had an open door to
the Kremlin during former President Boris Yeltsin's final years in
office, has become estranged from Putin's administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any relationship between Putin and
Berezovsky,'' said Vyachaslav Nikonov, a top Russian political
analyst. ``Otherwise, Berezovsky wouldn't correspond with Putin by
sending him these open letters.'' Nikonov said that with
Berezovsky's access to the Kremlin cut off, he is now reduced to a
game of modest opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sending messages in different directions. One is to the
Kremlin, saying you guys are making a big mistake without me.
Message number two is to the governors: I'm your best friend. And
three is to the liberals: I'm your last hope for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Berezovsky, a 54-year-old former mathematician who
acquired immense riches by exploiting Russia's lawless capitalism
early on, seems an unlikely spokesman for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He is widely assumed to have vast interests in Aeroflot;
AvtoVAZ, Russia's biggest automaker, and Sibneft, one of the
largest oil companies, among other concerns. He denies some of
those claims, but makes no bones about wielding great influence _
and even financial control _ over a media empire that includes
Russia's quasi-state television network, ORT, the Moscow business
newspaper Kommersant and the magazine Vlast, the Russian word for
``power.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is even richer: Berezovsky is widely believed to be
one of the Kremlin insiders who decided during Yeltsin's final days
in the presidency that Putin should be groomed to succeed him. ORT
played a major role in promoting Putin's election this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But then, experts still debate whether the Kremlin's assaults on
the governors and the tycoons are aimed at stabilizing Russia's
shaky democracy, as Putin says, or at aggrandizing the president's
power, as Berezovsky contends.
</P>
<P>
   Since being sworn in as president in early May, Putin has carved
Russia into seven administrative districts and installed his own
appointees in each one, moving swiftly to consolidate federal power
and patronage in a single place.
</P>
<P>
   He has also proposed to effectively abolish Russia's upper house
of parliament, which now consists of the 89 governors and their
appointees, and replace it with a more independent group of
legislators. Over Berezovsky's strident objections, the Duma seems
on the verge of doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's war on the tycoons began days after Putin's
swearing-in with a raid on the offices of Vladimir Gusinsky, who
controls a media empire that includes Russia's largest independent
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has denied any involvement in that or moves since then
against a half-dozen other oligarchs in the oil, metals and auto
industries. But neither has he disavowed them, and it has become
apparent in the last week that the actions have his tacit approval,
if not his outright authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky revealed on Monday that federal prosecutors had
questioned him for two hours on Friday about allegations that up to
$600 million in proceeds from Aeroflot, the privatized Soviet
airline, had been laundered through Swiss banks. He insists that
the accusations are groundless and that, in any case, he is but a
witness in a case that centers on other people.
</P>
<P>
   But news reports quote prosecutors as saying Berezovsky, long
said to have a huge but hidden interest in Aeroflot, is a target of
the inquiry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his news conference on Monday, Berezovsky said he had decided
to quit parliament in part because he did not believe it right to
side with his fellow oligarchs against Putin while having an
immunity from prosecution that they lack.
</P>
<P>
   The government's attack is ``no accident, not the initiative of
some over-zealous bureaucrat. It is essentially aimed at destroying
large independent businesses,'' he said. ``I do not want to enjoy
parliamentary immunity in such a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, noting that Berezovsky and other tycoons have
usually been major rivals in the last decade, offered a less
charitable assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to know that if these people want to get him, having
parliamentary immunity is not going to make any difference,'' said
Paul Saunders, director of the Nixon Center, a Washington-based
research organization that specializes in Russian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an opportunity to take a fairly high-profile,
dramatic step to once and for all make it clear to everyone that he
opposes what is happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
