u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-17 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERC driver legal at St. Andrews
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The sun was high and hot. The sweaters
came off. Young lasses donned the two-pieces and raced to the
beach, letting the North Sea lap at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the older locals groused about how dreadfully hot it
was getting around the historic Old Course on Monday. When the
mercury soared to almost 70 degrees, some sought the comfort of the
nearby pubs. They seemed oblivious to the fact the population back
in Houston was smoldering in 100-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of some, the totally un-British Open-like
weather was about the only thing causing sweat to form on many
brows as the week unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Much cooler and calmer heads were prevailing on one front in
particular _ the use of the controversial and banned-in-the-U.S.
ERC driver from Callaway. Neither players nor Callaway
representatives were throwing any salvos regarding use of the club
in the 129th British Open that begins Thursday. It will be a legal
club. And when hit straight, it can provide anywhere from five to
20 yards more than other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   On the PGA Tour, however, it is not legal. It's not even for
sale in the U.S. The USGA has ruled that the club is non-conforming
because it has a spring-like effect that is in excess of USGA
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, anybody can play the club if he so desires
because the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club has deemed the club is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most of the 156 competitors won't take advantage of the
extra yardage the club provides off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not tried to promote the ERC on the PGA Tour because
it is a non-conforming club,'' said Mike Galeski, Callaway's
representative for players on the tour. ``We understand that, come
Sunday night, there are a lot of players who have to go back to the
States and won't be able to use it again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, only a handful of the players in the tournament
will put the ERC in their bags. Galeski estimated the number is
likely to be between 20 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   And the pros get these clubs for free. Rest assured there are
many more being used around the world. Visitors to St. Andrews were
willingly plunking out 500 pounds (about $800) for the right to buy
one.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have had success with it on the European Tour is
Mark McNulty, who shot a 62 in the first round of qualifying on
Sunday. Fred Couples is said to have experimented with the club at
the Advil Western Open two weeks ago and may use it this week.
Colin Montgomerie may use the club as well.
</P>
<P>
   Others have shunned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't play it,'' Tiger Woods said. ``What happens if I like
it?''
</P>
<P>
   What would happen is that he'd have to leave it on this side of
the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hype surrounding the club, it will be conditions at
St. Andrews that have more of an influence on whether select
players use the club. The fairways are harder and faster than most
courses in the U.S. That means drives are rolling farther, and if
they are off line, the error is compounded.
</P>
<P>
   With the scattering of so many pot bunkers around St. Andrews,
the extra length is not worth the risk for most players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the length; it's a matter of hitting one straight,''
said Jim Carter, who is on the Callaway staff of players. ``That's
the key.''
</P>
<P>
   What pro golfers want is one thing: clubs they are comfortable
with and in which they have confidence. It doesn't really matter
what label those clubs bear. Whatever they think gives them the
best chance to shoot low numbers is what usually ends up in the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions. Occasionally, a player will sign an
endorsement package with a club or ball manufacturer and see
results slip, but because of the contractual obligation, stay with
the product.
</P>
<P>
   But normally, it's a matter of going with what works.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just switch one week to another driver,'' said Vijay
Singh. ``The club might be longer. But you're giving away some
accuracy at the same time if you use it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was Notah Begay III who summed up the feelings of
most players.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game has always been about being in control and being
comfortable,'' he said. ``And I feel like I'm in control with the
driver I'm using. So it would be silly of me to try to squeeze 10
more yards when I don't really need it. I know for a fact the ball
goes farther with it. But why change when something's working?''
</P>
<P>
   Considering Begay has won the last two tournaments he's entered,
who's to argue?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
