<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS INTENSIFY AS DEADLINE LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ With Wednesday's deadline fast approaching,
President Clinton stepped up his meetings with Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators on the seventh day of Middle East peace
talks, giving every indication he would leave for Japan whether
there is a peace deal or not.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on all sides have speculated that Clinton's departure
Wednesday is not set in stone, suggesting he might postpone his
trip to the G-8 summit, a meeting of industrialized nations that
begins July 21. But in restating the travel plans Monday, White
House officials seemed to be prodding negotiating teams on a day of
talks that officials described as ``intense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a schedule to keep,'' White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart told reporters. ``That schedule has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said: ``I expect when the president leaves the parties
will have wrapped up their business.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks fueled speculation about the status of the talks as
reports flooded out of the Middle East that the Israeli team was
displeased with the direction of the negotiations, which are
focusing on a series of disputes, including the status of Jerusalem
and the future of Palestinian refugees. After a phone conversation
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the speaker of the Israeli
Parliament, Avraham Burg, said in a radio interview that Barak was
``not optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wants to reach an agreement, but that we are not
there yet,'' Burg said on Israeli radio.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, on the other hand, continued to signal greater
optimism than they had a week before. A Palestinian official also
said the delegation would be willing to stay beyond Wednesday, a
proposal the Israeli team has already agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the American side decided to extend the period of the
talks, then I don't think that we will reject it,'' Palestinian
spokeswoma Hassan Abdel Rahman said. In addition to the limitations
imposed by Clinton's schedule, a senior member of the Palestinian
team, secretary general Abu Mazen, is supposed to leave by Thursday
to attend his son's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   US officials suggested that strict timetable had led to a shift
in atmosphere inside the presidential retreat, where some 35
delegates have been sequestered for a week. Keeping later and later
hours, sometimes until 3 a.m., the negotiators skipped dinner on
Sunday night to keep working. They are now working in an
environment that has ``intensified,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace and the intensity have both quickened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 7 miles from Camp David, teams of negotiators also
continued to gather in the town of Emmitsburg to work on so-called
``non-core'' issues, such as water issues and economic affairs.
Unlike the participants at Camp David, they are not bound by
secrecy rules. Still, the Emmitsburg teams did not report any
breakthroughs Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, questions surfaced about Clinton's decision to break
his own news blackout about the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged by accusations that his wife once made an anti-semitic
slur, Clinton took a break from the peace talks on Sunday to
telephone the publisher of the New York Daily News to solicit an
exclusive interview in her defense.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview that followed, Clinton also talked about the
peace summit, despite a strict US-imposed gag rule. Lockhart, who
did not know about the interview until later, said Clinton was
``outside the rules we've set down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
