<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4986 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     07-17 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS MASKED FAN SAYS RANGERS CAN STILL WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lone Ranger rides again.
</P>
<P>
   And I do mean lone.
</P>
<P>
   Every big-time media mogul in town, every ``football guy,''
every golden throat worth his overpriced designer hair spray, will
gather Tuesday in Wichita Falls, Texas, to celebrate the first day
of ``meaningless'' two-a-days at Camp Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: If it's all so danged meaningless, why
in the name of Dave Campo will virtually every media outlet from
the Rio Grande to the Red River and beyond be on hand to chronicle
each drop of sweat that trickles down Troy Aikman's precious
forehead?
</P>
<P>
   And did anybody bother to turn out the lights on the way out of
town?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. The answers would be just as meaningless as the next
six weeks in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Bor-ing.
</P>
<P>
   It's good riddance anyway. Wichita Falls is the perfect place
for all those brainwashed ``football guys'' to gather over their
red draws and talk blocking schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I've got a baseball season to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, a guy goes on vacation for a couple of weeks and everybody
wants to pull the plug on the Texas Rangers, just because they had
a bad June. Give it a rest, will ya? Can't we hold off on the white
flag at least until we see what happens this weekend in Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   This does not put me in a popular position with most of my
colleagues, who have been all too willing to call off the Rangers
season and get on with more important issues, such as red-zone
percentages and whether little Dat Nguyen is really big enough to
fill Randall Godfrey's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Enough already. This baseball season is just getting
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, while I was temporarily out of pocket, Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin did a first-rate job of keeping the
bath water in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks have been trying to pull the plug,'' Melvin
acknowledged Monday from Tulsa, Okla., where he was watching the
club's Double-A team. ``I've been scrambling just as fast to keep
it plugged in.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens for at least a little sanity around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan here, and we're trying to stay with it,'' Melvin
said. ``I don't want to deviate from that plan because we're still
a young club. I'm not going to make a deal just for the sake of
making a deal. I'm not being pushed by Tom Hicks to dump money. If
I make a deal, it'll be because it can help us in the next two
years or in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after a miserable stretch in June, have played much
better. They took two of three in Arizona to kick off this road
trip, including a gritty, don't-give-up-on-us-yet comeback against
Randy Johnson and the Diamondbacks on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Johnny did a heck of a job managing in that
series,'' Melvin said. ``Everyone contributed. I have no complaints
about the way we've been playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we had that one horrible 10-game stretch. We lost
nine of 10 and Seattle and Oakland were both winning nine of 10.
But we can't make that go away. It happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, enough to sink an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen in a week's time,'' Melvin said. ``Teams
can have injuries. It's going to come down to the
(trading-deadline) wire whether we do anything or don't do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is asking for patience and a little time. This isn't a
football season, where you give up if your team starts 4-4 or 3-5.
Baseball remains a marathon. You don't win the race with a 10-day
sprint in June.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, in fact, is filled with glorious stories of comeback
teams throughout history.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees had pulled the plug back on July 19, 1978, when
they trailed the Red Sox by 14 games in the American League East,
then Bucky Dent probably wouldn't be the most hated man in New
England today.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the Giants had given up in 1951, when they lost the
opener of a doubleheader Aug. 11 to fall behind the hated Dodgers
by 13 1/2 games? We'd have never been thrilled by Bobby Thomson's
``shot heard 'round the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there was the infamous final week collapse
of the 1964 Phillies, who led by six games with seven to play and
blew it, allowing the Cardinals to win the National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Even as recently as '97, the Angels enjoyed a double-digit lead
at the All-Star break, only to fall apart in the second half and
watch the Mariners win the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's past is filled with dozens of such comeback stories.
It can happen again. That's why they play 162 games.
</P>
<P>
   Even a complete collapse by Texas in Seattle this weekend
wouldn't necessarily predicate a Rangers surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember the wild-card scenario, too,'' Melvin
noted. ``If Seattle sweeps us, they're having a good year, but
there are other clubs in the wild-card race that are either
struggling or could struggle. If (the worst) were to happen (in
Seattle), then we'd have to make a decision about battling for the
wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has three options to consider as the July 31 deadline for
trading players without them clearing waivers approaches: (1) Do
nothing and continue to battle to make the playoffs, either by
winning the division or the wild-card race; (2) give up the season
and trade free agents-to-be John Wetteland and David Segui for
prospects; (3) try and walk a fine line by trading Esteban Loaiza
for a top-flight prospect or two while still trying to remain
competitive in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Option 3 is interesting but dangerous. If he trades Loaiza to
another wild-card contender, say Toronto or Cleveland, the move
could come back to bite him.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? It's a common question among the small-minded, who
are convinced the Rangers can go nowhere even if they should
somehow make the playoffs. I'll let Melvin answer that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Cleveland and the Yankees; they aren't the same
quality clubs they've been over the last few years,'' Melvin said.
``That's what gives you hope that anything can happen. A couple of
years ago, no one thought San Diego could get by Randy Johnson and
Houston, or the Braves, but they wound up in the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp Cowboy? Excuse me, but the Lone Ranger has a baseball
season to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Are you with me, kemo sabe?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
