<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TV-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS COLUMN: RICH GET CABLE DEALS, POOR GET RABBIT EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a fascinating confluence of events: Last Friday, a
blue-ribbon commission studying baseball's economics recommended
that teams share up to 50 percent of their local revenues,
including television fees.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, a lawsuit filed against the Yankees by MSG
Network revealed that the team has made a deal with the
many-tentacled International Management Group to create a cable
television network that will pay the team $65 million next year and
$119 million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Teams were jealous enough of the Yankees' MSG deal, which
expires after this season, when the world champions will receive
$55.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the envy of teams with puny television deals, which
cannot support a $100 million payroll or win three World Series in
four seasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Pirates, with only $7 million in TV cash, or the
poor Padres, with a mere $6 million, according to Broadcasting &AMP;
Cable magazine. The Expos have no TV deal!
</P>
<P>
   Even a new Pirates or Reds stadium won't level the revenue field
much; eventually, the Yankees will get a new ballpark that will
generate so much cash that George Steinbrenner's squad may have no
solvent teams to compete against.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the blue-ribbon panel. It hardly seems possible that
Steinbrenner endorsed the creation of a network that would generate
still more TV cash in order to kick half of it back to revenue-poor
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a sitdown between Steinbrenner and Harvey Schiller, the
chairman of YankeeNets, the parent company of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for my Padres pals,'' the Boss says. ``They've lost
$72 million since 1995 and I've made $64 million. Dang it, if I
prosper, the Pods got to prosper. Got it, Harv?''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, teams contribute 20 percent of their net local
revenues to a major league pool, with only one-quarter of the money
redistributed to teams below the industry's average local revenue.
The rest goes equally to all clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The panel suggested pooling 40 percent to 50 percent of all
local revenues in a yet unspecified way.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Steinbrenner, the future impresario of the New York
Sports Network and sovereign of a new stadium with 150 luxury
suites, to gladly hand over half of these wonderful revenues to
enhance the cause of major league socialism.
</P>
<P>
   Who is to say sharing more revenues will help struggling teams?
Why give the weak sisters a windfall for being, well, weak sisters?
</P>
<P>
   Page 1 of the commission's report noted that existing revenue
sharing has not helped competitive balance; needy teams did not use
the cash to pay players. ``Some low-revenue clubs,'' the report
said, ``believing the amount of their proceeds from revenue sharing
insufficient to enable them to become competitive, used those
proceeds to become modestly profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission linked more revenue sharing to setting minimum
payrolls, discouraging teams from lining their greedy pockets. Good
old George Steinbrenner can help. If he pooled half his network
cash, the poor teams could sign more players and post higher
profits. All thanks to George. Imagine the acclaim that would
shower down on our corporate Yankee Doodle Dandy if he personally
pushed other teams into the black.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, in a market that doesn't sustain a team with a teensy
payroll, lost $5.1 million from 1995 to 1999. Just send a few more
million over the border, George, just a few more. Help put us over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's owner, Jeffrey Loria, might have trimmed his losses
if he hadn't jacked up his TV contract demands beyond what any
station would sanely pay.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees, there is no such concern. MSG would likely pay
semi-insanely to keep the Yankees, the bulwark of the network. What
would MSG carry in the spring and summer without the Yanks? Metro
Guide programming?
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision would probably pay from $75 million to $100 million
a year to preserve the Yankees on MSG. But MSG is in a war of
retention. In its lawsuit, MSG claims that the new Yankee network
is not an offer that it can match, under its right to match any
outside offers for Yankee rights. &QL; 
challenging Cablevision to do exactly what I.M.G. plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to match,'' said Bob Gutkowski, who made the
Yankee deal at MSG when Paramount Communications owned it.
Paramount outbid Cablevision's Sportschannel New York (now Fox
Sports New York) to snare the Yankees. Eventually, Cablevision
acquired Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Gutkowski, now the president of Worldwide Entertainment &AMP;
Sports, has seen the other side of the Yankee equation. Between
1997 and 1999, as an executive for the Marquee Group and SFX
Sports, Gutkowski counseled Steinbrenner on creating a network of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees don't want to sell their rights, so George is
creating an equity base and a competitor,'' he said, noting that
Cablevision's matching right does not preclude the Yankees from
changing their desires from a straight rights deal to a network.
``I think the Yankees will win. And losing the Yankees will be a
huge body blow to Cablevision. MSG may have to be folded into Fox
Sports New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first phase of the Yankees-MSG battle, Judge Barry A.
Cozier issued a preliminary injunction to keep the Yankees from
consummating the network deal. Barring a settlement, the two sports
fat cats will meet in court on July 31, the day the network deal is
set to close. Now, this is great interleague baseball. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
