<HEADLINE>
BID FOR HONUS WAGNER CARD BRINGS $1.1 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story has been shorted.) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A collector from Southern California paid $1.1 million Saturday
for the rare, early 20th-century Honus Wagner tobacco card that was
once co-owned by Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Siegel of Santa Ana, Calif., made the 13th and final
online bid on eBay for the card, which was included in cigarette
packs made by the American Tobacco Co. in 1909. An estimated 50 of
the cards still exist.
</P>
<P>
   The card was considered the most expensive artifact in sports
memorabilia until $3.05 million was paid for Mark McGwire's 70th
home run ball.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel was the buyer, said a person involved in the auction, and
was unavailable for comment, pending a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With a 15 percent buyer's fee, the full price being paid is
$1.265 million.
</P>
<P>
   The card was bought nearly four year ago by Michael Gidwitz, of
Chicago, who paid $640,500 at auction. Previously, Gretzky and
Bruce McNall, the former Los Angeles King owner, acquired the card
for $451,000 in 1991, then sold it in 1996 for use in a promotional
contest staged by Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The contest winner then sold the card to Gidwitz to pay taxes on
the prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
