<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED AMERICAN-NORTHWEST MERGER ON THE ROCKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By DAN REED 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ American Airlines executives have all but
given up on reaching a deal to buy rival Northwest Airlines this
month because the two companies remain far apart on price, insiders
and others familiar with the negotiations say.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a Justice Department decision Friday to extend its
antitrust review of the proposed merger of UAL Corp. and US Airways
by at least 20 days has removed pressure to reach a deal quickly,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The May 24 announcement by UAL, parent of United Airlines, and
US Airways merger triggered a scramble by competitors, including
American and Delta Air Lines, to seek out potential partners of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   But the key dividing point between American and Northwest is
money: Northwest Chairman Gary Wilson is insisting that his company
is worth about $10 billion, or $100 per share. American executives
have valued Northwest at $56 per share, or roughly the same premium
that UAL would pay for US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The hangup over a purchase price has derailed American's plan to
put a merger proposal of its own before regulators this month _ as
the Justice Department contemplates the United-US Airways deal.
It's unclear how long the Justice Department review will go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to do the deal, but not at any price,'' said one
senior American executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest stock, which has run up in recent weeks on merger
speculation, fell $1.31 a share yesterday to close at $36.62. AMR
gained 50 cents a share to close at $32.62.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman for American, based in Fort Worth, and Northwest,
based in Eagan, Minn., declined to comment on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   American executives have said that they did not want to launch
another round of industry consolidation, but that the company will
not stand still if other carriers combine. If forced to review
multiple proposed mergers at the same time, regulators might balk
at all such deals rather than risk a marked loss of competition,
analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   American, the second-largest passenger carrier behind United,
would be 50 percent smaller than the combined UAL-US Airways.
Northwest is the nation's No. 4 carrier. American and its parent,
AMR Corp., employ more than 27,000 people in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks say American and Northwest executives
have been in regular contact, and have generally agreed to how a
merger of the two carriers would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's price only, nothing else,'' one source said of the major
sticking issue.
</P>
<P>
   The American executive suggested that American might now
reluctantly wait for the Justice Department to complete its review
of the UAL-US Airways deal before moving to acquire a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like we're going to get anything up to
Washington before Justice rules on United-US Air,'' the executive
said, unless Northwest executives ``are willing to talk in
realistic numbers pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive noted that Northwest's asking price is more than
American's $4.8 billion value in the stock market, even though ``we
have twice the revenues and they have a fleet of old airplanes that
aren't worth much.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how much American and Northwest are willing to bend
in their positions on price. Julius Maldutis, a veteran airline
analyst for the CIBC Oppenheimer investment firm, suggests that
Wilson's demand might merely be a bargaining tactic.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson runs a significant risk, analysts said. AMR could
present the financier, who led the investment group that acquired
Northwest a decade ago in a $3.3 billion leveraged buyout, the best
opportunity to cash out of their investment.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2128EDT &QL; 
