<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOWING THEM WITH EXCESS IN THE HAMPTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and NYT9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ To take the temperature of excess in the
Hamptons this summer, join Jay Lieberman in the shower of the new
12,000-square-foot house that he hopes to sell for $8 million,
preferably to someone who will pay cash.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a builder, has taken a seat in the glassed-in shower
stall of the ``his'' bathroom in the master bedroom. He proudly
points to a shower head that is 10 inches in diameter and is
capable of caressing the human body with 22 gallons of water per
minute (about nine times the maximum flow allowed in New York
state, but unlikely to result in any legal woes). That super-sized
spritzer costs $800. But it is merely an appetizer for what awaits
across the hall in what Lieberman calls ``the last word in
bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``hers'' bathroom has a skylight, radiant heat in the
floors, wiring for satellite television and views of the pool and
tennis court. Like the ``his'' bath, the showpiece here is in the
shower: an all-exposed, hand-machined, hand-polished,
nickel-plated, thermostatic mixer with overhead shower and hand
sprayer on a cradle. It cost $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anything in this house that I did not pull out all
the stops for,'' Lieberman boasts. ``Whoever takes this house will
be a client with a lot of money who walks in and says, `Wow!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the frenzied pace of speculative construction here this
summer and the frazzled lives of workers doing the building, the
Hamptons have never before been invaded by so many rich people
wanting to be wowed and demanding that it happen fast.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion has driven construction costs to record levels,
seduced builders, architects and even carpenters to build houses on
``spec,'' choked roads with commuting workers and encouraged
subcontractors to insist on bonuses merely for showing up on time.
It also has enriched and exhausted nearly everyone willing to drive
a nail, paint a wall or dig a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's house ranks among the most expensive ever built in
the Hamptons without a contracted buyer. Part of the reason it is
so expensive is what goes on in its 9{ bathrooms. Each bath,
excepting the maid's, has faucets imported from England that cost
an average of $2,000 each. The company that made them, Barber
Wilsons &AMP; Co. Ltd., does faucets for the queen of England and for
Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't price yourself out of this market,'' said Carmine
Cornacchio, owner of Cornacchio Electric here in Southampton. He
and his crew of 20 electricians specialize in custom wiring for
houses selling for $2 million to $3 million. Such houses,
Cornacchio said, usually include devices that, for example, allow
an owner stuck in traffic on the Long Island Expressway to turn on
the hot tub with a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the sentiments of many architects, builders and
subcontractors in the Hamptons, Cornacchio said that this year it
had become all but impossible to put off mansion-hungry clients by
charging outrageous prices.
</P>
<P>
   Several subcontractors said they were making record profits, and
a few have used the windfall to buy big-ticket toys, like
airplanes. But they also said it would be bad business to talk
publicly about their new wealth. Steven Gaines, who lives in the
Hamptons and whose best-selling book ``Philistines at the
Hedgerow'' (Little Brown, 1998) chronicles the hijinks of rich
residents, said his plumber now owns a plane. Gaines said, however,
that disclosing the plumber's name would mean that he would have to
find somebody else to fix his toilet.
</P>
<P>
   John Tortorella builds swimming pools for the rich and famous in
the Hamptons. His clients have included Billy Joel, Peter Jennings
and Kathleen Turner. This year, he said, has been the busiest and
most lucrative of his 19 years in the swimming-pool trade. But he
said overwork is making him question the meaning of success.
</P>
<P>
   He is exhausted, his employees are exhausted, and still the
orders for bigger, more costly and more complicated swimming pools
keep rolling in. Five years ago, he said, a $200,000 pool was
considered ``pretty huge.'' Now, his company, J. Tortorella
Swimming Pools, is rushing to complete five pools, the cheapest of
which will cost $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are talking `backyard concepts,' with a pool, a spa, a
pergola, a stone bridge, wrought iron gates,'' said Tortorella, who
has begun to design his biggest pools along historical themes like
the lost island of Atlantis, ancient Egypt and Stonehenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody used to talk about the go-go '80s like they were so
wonderful,'' he said. ``Well, the '80s were like child's play. It
is ridiculous now. The amount of time and stress that my people
have had to put up with is inhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   The minting of millionaires in Manhattan is far outpacing the
supply of skilled labor and good property in the Hamptons,
according to local government officials on the East End of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of prime lots dwindles, the chief building
inspectors in the towns of Southampton and East Hampton said,
million-dollar houses are being built near town dumps and on
misshapen or poorly drained parcels of land.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are building on properties now that they wouldn't have
even looked at 10 years ago,'' said Don Sharkey, the chief building
inspector for the Town of East Hampton. ``In a couple of years, we
are going to run out of buildable parcels.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of land, combined with local moratoriums on some
kinds of subdivisions and the possibility of far more restrictive
development rules in the near future, have helped push home prices
this year to levels that stun veteran real estate agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the biggest-ever across-the-board quarterly jump
in home prices in the Hamptons,'' said Diane Saatchi, president of
Dayton-Halstead Real Estate, which publishes a quarterly report on
home prices in seven markets in the Hamptons. Figures for the first
quarter of 2000 came out last week.
</P>
<P>
   They show that in the Village of East Hampton, summer home to
the likes of Spielberg and Martha Stewart, the average price of
houses has jumped in the last three years to $2.1 million from $1.2
million. More than two-thirds of that increase occurred during the
first quarter of this year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi, voicing an opinion shared by many builders and
architects, speculates that the boom is fueled by continued
strength in the stock market and by aging baby boomers in Manhattan
who find themselves with buckets of excess money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have gotten to a point where they are in their prime
earning years, their kids are through college, and they need houses
that are big enough to accommodate several generations and kids
from multiple marriages,'' said Saatchi, who has been selling real
estate in the Hamptons for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their reasons, buyers are spreading so much money so
fast that the craftsmen in the Hamptons are at risk of drowning in
a flood of trickle-down economics. The unemployment rate in
Southampton hit a record low of 2 percent this spring. For skilled
labor, New York State employment officials said, the jobless rate
in the Hamptons is about zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East End of Long Island is the tightest
skilled-construction market in the United States, without
compromise,'' said Daniel McMillan, regional vice president of
Trade Source, a company in Greenwich, Conn., that recruits and
places craftsmen in construction jobs around the country. ``We have
hired a former Navy recruiter to go around the Hamptons and talk to
anybody who is wearing work boots and driving a pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   With more jobs than workers to fill them, Trade Source two weeks
ago began offering a free carpenter's course to recent high school
graduates. The first class was convened in an office building in
the Suffolk County hamlet of Bohemia, about an hour's drive from
the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure that if I improve my skills, I can bump my wages from
$15 to at least $25 an hour out in the Hamptons,'' said John
Vitale, 23, who showed up for the course. ``The money is definitely
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep pace with demand, a number of Hamptons builders have
begun hiring immigrants from Central America to frame houses,
shingle roofs and build swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broke out of the landscaping business about two years
ago, and now they are rising through the trades,'' said Al Tuff, a
builder in Bridgehampton who employs recent immigrants and who said
his business would shut down without them.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Velasquez, a Salvadoran immigrant who has been in the
United States for six years, earns $23 an hour and works 12 hours a
day, seven days a week, for Tuff, who also employs Velasquez's two
sons, Carlos and Victor, both in their early 20s. They, too,
usually work 12 hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just too much work,'' Velasquez said.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials in the Hamptons are struggling to find ways to
slow the pace of development, and a few are conceding that local
governments have all but lost the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last decade, we have been building houses at a rate of
a house every single day,'' said Jay Schneiderman, the supervisor
in the Town of East Hampton. ``We have added probably 20,000 people
to our summer population without changing any significant
infrastructure. That is creating tremendous stress on the quality
of life in this area. It has not been a balanced approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneiderman said that town governments, even with millions of
dollars to spend on buying up vacant land, were finding it
difficult to persuade speculators to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``A builder would rather build a spec house,'' Schneiderman
said. ``He knows that the profit he'll yield will far exceed what
he'll make selling us vacant land. That makes it difficult to
preserve vacant space.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, builder of the $8 million house with the pricey
shower heads, said: ``Even I realize that there is a certain amount
of property that should be preserved. Things are obviously getting
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Difficult or not, Cindi Crain, a former magazine editor, said
she was going ahead with her dream house, which she is planned on
two acres of land she bought for $1 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Crain, 31, who has family money (Crain Communications, publisher
of Advertising Age and Crain's New York Business), said she had
been warned repeatedly by friends about the impossibility of
getting a house built on time and within a budget.
</P>
<P>
   She has been forced by soaring design and construction prices to
raise her budget for her planned 6,000-square-foot house to about
$3.5 million from $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   She intends to elude the pain of summer in the Hamptons by
sticking to back roads, staying away from overcrowded restaurants
and never commuting from Manhattan on Fridays or Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   And why is this worth $3.5 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``You really feel the sea out here. You suck in the sea air,''
Crain said. ``You can still chill out in the Hamptons, if you know
what you are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
