<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-COWBOYS18-COX     07-17 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys' coach Campo celebrates birthday, new job
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas - _ Today, on his 53rd birthday, Dave Campo
assumes control of the Dallas Cowboys, a football team he has
considered family for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is no stranger at training camp. He has watched Troy
Aikman and Emmitt Smith capture three Super Bowls. He has been an
assistant for Jimmy Johnson, Barry Switzer and Chan Gailey. He has
seen good times and bad times, which makes him uniquely qualified
for the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is a change of coaches there will be some
uneasiness, but my relationship with the organization is a big
plus,'' Campo said. ``There is no question that I understand the
expectations of the fans and the organization. Dallas is different
than any other city in the United States. That comes from being
successful over a 40-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's excitement can be detected by his cheerful demeanor and
positive outlook. He resembles a child awaiting his first Little
League baseball game. The weight of training camp, which begins
today, kept him from sleeping Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can match team owner Jerry Jones' enthusiasm, it's
Campo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave is someone who is very bright, someone who knows what it
was like when we were successful and what it was like when we
weren't,'' Jones said Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave certainly fits that bill very well. The staff has a great
deal of respect for his skills and knowledge of football. A lot of
players lobbied for Dave because they know he has an opportunity to
do a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones decided that the head coach should be someone ``in the
family'' after he fired Gailey last winter. The outspoken owner
admitted he made a mistake by hiring Gailey, a former Pittsburgh
Steelers assistant. The players were never comfortable with
Gailey's offensive system, which ultimately cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   In Campo, the Cowboys have someone they have known since 1989,
the year Jones bought the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Campo inherits a team with a small nucleus of people which won
its last Super Bowl in the 1995-96 season. Aikman, Smith, safety
Darren Woodson, defensive tackles Leon Lett and Chad Hennings, and
offensive linemen Larry Allen and Erik Williams have links to the
team's glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   The key to 2000, though, depends largely on a group of newcomers
and players under 25.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin, Daryl Johnston and Deion Sanders have moved on.
Receiver Joey Galloway, linebacker Joe Bowden and cornerback Ryan
McNeil have moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is too busy to worry about a leadership gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really worry about the guys we don't have,'' Campo
said. ``I worry about the guys we do have. If we get an injury,
we're not going to use that as an excuse. If we do, we'll have to
have the young talent step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the offense will have a new look. The Cowboys, with
the speedy Galloway and Rocket Ismail starting at receiver, will
pass the ball more. The team had become too predictable and
conservative during Gailey's two years in Dallas. With former
Cowboys assistant Jack Reilly as the new offensive coordinator and
former coordinator Ernie Zampese as an adviser, Jones believes
Dallas has the tools to contend for another title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won a Super Bowl in four years,'' Jones said, ``and
that's a major drought for me.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The Cowboys have reached a contract agreement with their
top draft choice, Tennessee cornerback Dwayne Goodrich. The
second-round pick signed a four-year deal worth $3.2 million.
Georgia linebacker Orantes Grant, the final player to come to
terms, signed a three-year contract for $770,000.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Rick Cantu at rcantu(at)statesman.com or
445-3953.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
