<SLUG> BC-TELEMARKET-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER U.S. ATTORNEY SENTENCED TO PRISON FOR TELEMARKETING FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in New Hampshire on Monday sentenced a former
U.S. attorney and commodities regulator to 24 months in prison for
becoming a co-conspirator with the operators of fraudulent
telemarketing scams of the type he had once investigated and
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence received by John Field III, 60, was a bit more than
one-fourth of the maximum 87-month term he could have faced. It
reflected his cooperation during a three-year period after he had
been caught by federal investigators, and agreed to cooperate in
sting operations and the recording of telephone conversations.
These led to the conviction of more than 18 fraudulent securities
and commodities telemarketers in six states and the District of
Columbia, who had netted nearly $200 million, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Field also faces sentencing in federal court in New Jersey on
other conspiracy charges connected to the telemarketing schemes,
which were aimed at elderly people and bilked them with the promise
of returns on investments in fraudulent cable and satellite
broadcasting operations. Federal prosecutors in New Jersey are also
expected to seek leniency at sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Field was the U.S. attorney for the southern district of West
Virginia from 1972 to 1977 and a former director of enforcement for
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In requesting leniency for him, federal prosecutors in Concord,
N.H., conceded in a motion to Judge Joseph DiClerico that Field had
let ``greed'' cancel out the years he spent protecting the public
from fraud and wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   They stated in the motion: ``While his crimes were egregious,
his cooperation has been exceptional. With the help of Field, the
government was able to quickly master the manner and methodology
used by the criminal enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gunnison, an assistant U.S. attorney in New Hampshire
who helped investigate the cases that led to Field and his work on
behalf of telemarketing fraud rings, said that Field, upon leaving
his post as a regulator, had taken on the work of helping his
clients in their intent to skirt and evade the laws regulating
commodities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
