<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     07-17 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY'S FIRST FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Philip Fischer, a specialist in pediatric and adolescent
medicine at the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota, believes there is no age
at which an infant is automatically too young to travel by air. He
and some of his colleagues take issue with a report in a British
medical journal depicting perils to the very young in flight.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose last month when Edward Lister, owner of the
Travel Medicine Clinic in Rancho Mirage, Calif., a nurse belonging
to the International Society of Travel Medicine, asked the members'
e-mail forum if there was any reason not to let a family take a
3-week-old infant on a 2,000-mile air trip to visit relatives.
Plentiful dialogue followed, with almost all the medical experts
supporting Fischer, a leader in the field of children's travel, in
his statement: ``I would personally not restrict air travel because
of a child's age.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer had one caveat. ``A 2,000-mile air trip probably
involves a big transition and some physical challenges for a
postpartum mother and for a family adjusting to a new baby,'' he
said. ``I would hope the scheduled itinerary is appropriate for all
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sheila Mackell of Oakland, Calif., a pediatrician and member
of the society, said she likewise asked patients whether they were
ready for such a journey.
</P>
<P>
   In the travel medicine dialogue, many experts pointed out
reasons that parents often undertook long air journeys with
newborns: the family may prefer to have the delivery someplace
other than where they live, or, commonly these days, the family may
have adopted a baby in another state, or another country, and want
to hurry home and settle in.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David R. Shlim, a specialist in high-mountain illness and
traveler's diarrhea, who has a clinic in Jackson Hole, Wyo., said:
``Many women who live in a developing country will leave that
country in the last month of pregnancy in order to deliver in a
safer environment. Often they have to leave their spouses behind
and even children who might be in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are understandably anxious to get back to their life in
Nepal, or India, or Africa, as soon as possible after delivery. It
is this group that is most likely to want to travel with a newborn
baby. We flew home to Nepal from Bangkok with our first child when
he was 8 days old.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Rosselot, a nurse practitioner and public health expert who
directs a clinic in Briarcliff Manor, N.Y., and her husband took
their adoptive daughter on an air trip when she was 9 days old. The
couple flew to California to meet her when she was 2 days old, then
flew to Houston and on to San Antonio to complete adoption
formalities before returning to New York through Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Rosselot said that on her trip, Continental Airlines asked her
how old the baby was, but said that 9 days was old enough and let
her board. Clients of her clinic now tell her they have received
conflicting information from an airline on the phone and then at
the boarding gate, and sometimes aboard, and have met varying rules
when they took connecting flights from California to Texas and home
to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sparse material published on the subject is a notation
in Health Information for International Travel 1999-2000, the
``yellow book,'' published by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. Under ``Air Travel During Pregnancy,'' there is this:
``Women traveling with infants should keep in mind that newborns
under 6 weeks old should not fly because their alveoli are not
completely functional.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Phyllis E. Kozarsky of the Emory University Travel Clinic in
Atlanta, who helped write this guideline, said that the 6-week age
limit represented a theoretical consensus ``since there are really
no firm data to support or refute.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackell in Oakland characterized as inconclusive a report
published in the British Medical Journal in 1998 saying that
infants who traveled by air were more likely to be victims of
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome. She said that this study had raised
wide concern in the travel-medicine community.
</P>
<P>
   She and Kozarsky both said, however, that when an infant was
involved they usually asked ``is this trip necessary.'' Kozarsky
said: ``Occasionally we see adoptive parents who will be traveling
to pick up their babies from overseas or even within the country
and wish to bring the child home as soon as possible, and thus the
question arises. If there is no urgency, however, one might be a
bit more conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of transmitting infections, Mackell said that the
air in planes was perfectly good but that the passenger sitting
next to the baby might be carrying something, and long proximity
could be a problem. One participant in the dialogue, Dr. Alison
Clough of the Travel and Geographic Medicine Clinic in Tucson,
Ariz., a family doctor, said that studies had shown airline air to
be quite clean and she believed that most post-air-travel colds and
flu she had seen were picked up in airports and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Of seven major domestic airlines, three are concerned with
minimum passenger age. Continental will not accept a child who is
under 7 days old, according to Julie Gardner, a spokeswoman.
United, according to Chris Nardella, a spokeswoman, wants a
doctor's letter saying a child under the age of 7 days is able to
fly. If American Airlines is asked the question, according to John
Hotard, a spokesman, it replies that it does not accept infants
under 3 days of age. But he said: ``If someone arrives with a baby
in a bassinet, our agent is not going to say, `Excuse me, ma'am,
may I inspect your baby?'''
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines, US Airways, Delta and Northwest Airlines
report no restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Karl Neumann of Queens, a travel-medicine expert who
specializes in pediatrics, had a few suggestions for parents taking
infants _ or young children _ on planes. First, he said, parents
are sometimes told their children need copious liquids in flight,
and this is not the case. ``It just gives them a stomachache,'' he
said. However, he said, the swallowing involved in breast-feeding
or taking a bottle will often relieve earache in ascent and
descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lap children,'' that is children under the age of 2, can
travel free domestically, but the experts said these babies
traveled most safely in a rear-facing child seat strapped into an
airline seat. This means buying a ticket for the child. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April, Northwest instituted a ``special delivery'' fare for
parents going overseas to adopt a child. In company with KLM, it
has a reduced fare to 100 destinations the lines serve in Asia,
Africa, Europe, India and the Middle East. Information may be found
on the Northwest Web site at www.nwa.com. Enter ``adoption fare''
in the inquiry box. For special services: (800) 322-4162.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways created special adoption fares in April. These
too provide a 65 percent discount on the full economy fare from 21
United States cities to any point on the line's main routes. The
line does not have a minimum age for passengers, according to John
W. Lampl, its spokesman. Information: (800) 247-9297.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
