u w BC-CONGRESS-MARRIAGE-TAX     07-17 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MARRIAGE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PRESSES ATTACK ON REPUBLICAN TAX PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate moved toward passage of an
election-year tax cut for married couples, the Clinton
administration renewed its attack Monday on the tax agenda being
promoted by the Republican majority in Congress, calling it a
fiscally reckless attempt to help the wealthy at the expense of
working people.
</P>
<P>
   The treasury secretary, Lawrence Summers, said the Republican
tax cut proposals ``primarily benefit the highest-income
Americans'' and would explode in cost as time went by, imperiling
the nation's ability to deal with long-term challenges like
maintaining the solvency of the Social Security and Medicare
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans defended their plans as prudent and said President
Clinton was misguided in casting all tax debates as a contest
between rich and poor. And they pressed on with their effort to
pass their proposed tax cut for couples, heartened by new, larger
projections of the federal budget surplus from the Congressional
Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office, in a report to be released publicly on
Tuesday, estimated that the budget surplus outside of Social
Security will be nearly $2.2 trillion over the next decade. The
projection is $1.3 trillion higher than the budget office's last
estimate, which came in January, and $300 billion higher than a
projection released last month by the White House's Office of
Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a bill last week to repeal the federal estate
tax, joining the House, which had passed it last month. The House
plans to take up bills this week to expand tax breaks for
Individual Retirement Accounts and 401(k) retirement plans and to
repeal some of the tax on Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The focus in Congress Monday was on the Republican plan to
reduce taxes on nearly all married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Packaged as an attempt to alleviate the so-called marriage
penalty, the quirk in the tax code that leads many two-income
couples to pay a higher tax bill than they would if they had
remained single, the bill debated in the Senate Monday would
actually amount to a tax cut for married couples who do not pay the
penalty as well as those that do.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the bill failed to address the underlying
complexities in the tax code that create the marriage penalty, and
offered an alternative proposal that would have given a tax cut
only to those couples who actually paid more because they are
married, and limited the benefits to couples with incomes of less
than $150,000. The Democratic proposal was defeated by a vote of
50-46.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans brushed aside complaints from Democrats that
high-income people would benefit from their plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not shy away from the fact that our bill benefits
virtually every American family,'' said Sen. William V. Roth Jr.,
R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   With projections of the federal budget surplus growing and tax
cuts proving to have more support among Democrats than even a few
months ago, administration officials stressed that Clinton would
also like to enact tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the president would continue to insist that they
primarily benefit low- and middle-income people and that they not
be adopted before bipartisan agreement on other issues like the
addition of prescription drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis released Monday by the Treasury Department said that
the wealthiest 1 percent of taxpayers by income _ about 1.2 million
households earning $346,000 or more _ would receive 27.5 percent of
the benefits of the tax cuts being pushed this year by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 percent of taxpayers by income _ 11.5 million
households with incomes of $115,000 or more _ would receive 60.2
percent of the benefits, the analysis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2139EDT &QL; 
