<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JULY 18 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT (moved on Friday, July 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 14,
about the $144.8 billion judgment against the tobacco industry in a
lawsuit in Florida misstated the surname of a former Wall Street
executive who had testified for the plaintiffs. He is Joe Cherner,
not Turner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-TV-TALK-POLITICS-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 16,
about network television interviews with Vice President Al Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush referred incorrectly in some copies to Mr.
Gore's position on the death penalty. He is in favor of it, not
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-BOLSTER-PROFILE-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 9,
about Bill Bolster, the president of CNBC, misstated his role in
the expansion of local morning news programming in New York City.
What he started in 1992 was the first weekend morning program, not
the first morning program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-RESEARCH-NYT (moved Sunday, July 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 16,
about software research at  &UR; cobi &LR; Microsoft &UR; coei &LR;  based in part on a
statistical technique developed by Thomas Bayes, an English
mathematician and clergyman, misstated the century in which he
worked. It was the 18th, not the 17th.  &QL; 
