<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ROCK-TSHIRTS-FASHION-     07-17 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-TSHIRTS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD MALL RAT T-SHIRTS LEAD HIP LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Courtney Love's band mates in Hole were probably the
first to revive them, in long ago 1998. The fashion tyro Jeremy
Scott is rarely seen without one. Lara Flynn Boyle, the actress,
sported a sequined version to the Golden Globe Awards. The
alternative rocker Perry Farrell, the model Shalom Harlow and the
designer Stella McCartney are devotees of a fashion trend that
originates in the least fashionable arena you can imagine.
``Arena'' is intended literally here. What these people are wearing
generally started as souvenirs from that dubious rock genre: the
big-hair, heavy metal band.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely acknowledged that the perversity of taste knows no
limits. So it wasn't entirely surprising that, as the fashion time
machine lurched through the decades of the late 20th century, it
made stops at 1960s helmet hair, '70s glam rock, the '80s power
suit and the kitsch-pop '90s effusions of Hello Kitty. But who
could have predicted a vogue for Iron Maiden T-shirts, the older,
rattier and more reworked, the cooler?
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably says something about the willingness to accept
almost anything as a fashion statement without examination,'' said
Howard Kramer, the assistant curator at the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame in Cleveland, whose collection includes the original rock
T-shirt, made for an Elvis Presley concert in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Just as likely, the trend suggests something about pop culture's
renewable amnesia and appetite for cheesy aspects of the past.
``The kids who're wearing these band T-shirts wouldn't necessarily
have listened to this music in the first place,'' said Laura Wills,
whose Screaming Mimi stores in Manhattan and in Tokyo do a thriving
business in $80 T-shirts made for bands like Whitesnake, Rush or
Motley Crue. ``For one thing, they're too young.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one is too young, apparently, to escape being haunted by
irony. How else to explain a model, Sophie Dahl, impersonating
Debbie Harry in ads for Alexander McQueen eyewear? Or models sent
out wearing Joey Ramone bangs at Martin Margiela's fall 2000 show
for Hermes? Or the vision of Sarah Jessica Parker in ``Sex and the
City'' wearing an T-shirt showing David Bowie from the era of
Aladdin Sane?
</P>
<P>
   No longer just the province of independent retailers like Trash
and Vaudeville or Patricia Field, the trend has been seized on by
chains like Urban Outfitters, which promotes the stylishness of
T-shirts intended for the most antifashion cohort imaginable:
teen-age stoners who play air guitar. ``It's just, like, a big
thing _ everybody's doing it,'' said Billy Basinski, the proprietor
of Lady Bird, a store in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. The shirts
themselves are vintage, a rag trade euphemism for used. But in the
hands of Heidi Sjursen, the designer of Custom Heidi, they are
cleaned, fringed and studded with rhinestones and beads. ``She does
all that slicing, ribs them up and makes them totally trashy '80s
slut,'' Basinski said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sjursen is through, the shirts look more like
something a mall rat might have worn to see Def Leppard play the
Meadowlands in the summer of '89.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stylists love them,'' Basinski said. ``Rock 'n' roll people
love them. The English love them. Americans can't afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain of Sjursen's shirts, cut into halters, punctured with
grommets and sewn into dresses, retail for over $200. ``You can't
get enough AC/DC for the French,'' said Basinski, adding that other
hot sellers are dresses made from T-shirts of Farrah Fawcett Majors
in her best-known cheesecake pose and anything with Michael Jackson
with the black glove, circa ``Thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer Stephen Sprouse once called a torn rock T-shirt and
slash of black eyeliner the perfect outfit for cocktails _ speaking
for guys. Rolling Stone called the T-shirt the ``ultimate rock
garment,'' proposing it as a ``$10 signifier.'' But even in the
early days of the rock T-shirt, which by consensus originated in
the late-'60s flowering of psychedelic rock in San Francisco, they
were rarely cheap. As early as 1974, Rolling Stone reported, fans
were offering $100 for thrusting tongue T-shirts marking the 1972
Rolling Stones American tour.
</P>
<P>
   The most democratic, adaptable and seasonless article of
apparel, the T-shirt most likely evolved from Civil War union suits
and the long john. It went on to become civilian America's uniform
after soldiers who had received them as standard issue came home
from World War II. Marlon Brando helped popularize T-shirts as
outer wear in ``The Wild One.'' But, Alice Harris wrote in ``The
White T'' (HarperCollins, 1996), it was not until Sen. John F.
Kennedy was photographed relaxing at his Georgetown town house in
1959 that the T-shirt, ``socially speaking, arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late '70s, three out of 10 Americans owned a T-shirt
bearing some sort of design. Some 48,000 T-shirt companies enjoyed
a total of $3 billion to $5 billion in revenues. ``T-shirts used to
be more of a premium piece than a commercial piece,'' Kramer of the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame said. ``People who had them invariably
worked security for the shows. They were swag.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until arena rock took hold that artists saw T-shirts
as ``an enormous revenue stream,'' Kramer said. ``They made a lot
of people a lot of money. Artists who never saw a dime out of
record sales used T-shirts as a way to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Given their ubiquity, vintage T-shirts do not seem to have
survived in enormous quantities. ``I scour the country,'' said
Wills, the proprietor of Screaming Mimi's, whose New York branch is
on Lafayette Street in Manhattan. ``I just found six good ones with
dates. There are tons of companies doing knockoffs of the old
shirts, but that's not what the kids want.'' Sjursen relies on a
Salvation Army connection in her hometown, which she declined to
name.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely the shirts worn until, as Sprouse put it, they
feel silky that are most coveted. ``The older, the better,'' Wills
said. ``The grungier, the better. People really like them worn.''
</P>
<P>
   The true rock faithful seek out T-shirt rarities: the infamous
Vivienne Westwood design for the Sex Pistols, depicting Queen
Elizabeth II pierced by a safety pin, or else shirts printed with
images of cult musicians, like the glam rock New York Dolls. For
the most part, however, people embrace the irony of wearing a
Whitesnake T-shirt to hip downtown events like the Thursday night
party Ultra, held at a club called Spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hit a peak,'' said Ive Bjork, the assistant manager at
Patricia Field on West Eighth Street in Manhattan, where rock
T-shirts customized by designers known as Halah and Self Mart sell
for as much as $400. ``Stylists, men from Boston, everyone's buying
them,'' Bjork said. ``You get such a glimpse of what type of person
it is from what they're into.''
</P>
<P>
   At the store Filthmart on East 13th Street in Manhattan, whose
stock is mainly discontinued merchandise recovered from warehouses,
the top sellers are AC/DC, Motley Crue, Led Zeppelin and Iggy Pop.
At Sjursen's Web page, www.hoverground.com, the hot shirts of the
moment feature Skid Row and the American flag logo from the Rolling
Stones ``Steel Wheels'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out doing typical rocked-out T-shirts,'' said
Sjursen, whose new designs venture into the world of shirts with
cigarette ads. ``I did them all, Skid Row and Motley Crue. But
never Bon Jovi. I draw the line at Bon Jovi, OK?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
