<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BOBANVILLE-COX     07-17 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BOBANVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Kim Folstad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - It's not that the title of Bo Banville's
autobiography, ``Bo Doesn't Live Here Anymore,'' isn't clever.
</P>
<P>
   It's a darn good name, really, for a book about a guy who's
lived in 22 states and overseas, gone to 28 schools, and won and
lost dozens of jobs, scores of women and thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that some sort of subtitle also seems called for _ a
warning, if you will. Something that cautions young men,
especially: Read. Laugh. Enjoy. Even ponder the more poignant
parts. But, whatever you do, Don't Try This at Home.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bo knows adventure. And Bo knows how to have a good
time. But Robert ``Bo'' Banville, 56, is the Evel Knievel of
business and personal relationships: He flies high and falls short,
catches fire and burns out, heals up and gets hurt again.
</P>
<P>
   Bo doesn't know boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   He's living a quiet life as a diamond salesman in Port St.
Lucie, Fla., now, and is known around the Treasure Coast as an
auctioneer for charity functions. But Banville, also known as Bo
Wyley in his younger years, spent most of his career as a disc
jockey at various radio stations, many in the South. And he still
has a bit of show biz left in him. Dressed to impress in a Tom
Wolfe white suit, he pours a glass of Zinfandel _ at 9:30 a.m. _
and explains how he came to write his tale of paternal sin and
personal salvation.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it's all a little hard to believe: The voluptuous
(37-22-36), violet-eyed wife who, unfortunately, had a dangerous
mean streak. The stint with an escort service that ended when he
found out one of his most attractive clients was actually a man.
The undercover work for the Drug Enforcement Administration,
keeping tabs on high-profile partiers.
</P>
<P>
   So Banville pulls out a montage of old newspaper clippings and
business cards to back up his claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the book is factual,'' he says. ``With some
embellishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, it would have been easier to write and sell as
fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back to the reason I wrote the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   ``To show that whatever happens in your life, you can overcome
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That message would have been lost, Banville says, if he'd gone
the fictional route. And there were some important stories to
relate along with all his outrageous tales about cheating hearts,
gorgeous groupies and promotional stunts at small-town radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took three months before he told his friend and
co-author, Arlene Lawless, ``the bad stuff.'' He struggled with
explaining the off-and-on relationship he's had with his daughters
(whose names, along with those of most of the women in Banville's
life, have been changed for the book).
</P>
<P>
   And he was embarrassed to tell her too much about the time he
hijacked the radio station in Kinston, N.C., in 1985. When she
called to verify the story, Lawless reports, ``they said they still
talk about it to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hardest chapters to write were those discussing the
sexual and physical abuse Banville says his father, a career
military man, got away with for years. ``Part of me didn't want to
tell anybody what a monster he was,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, want others who have been abused to know that
it's possibions, no matter what happened in the past.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of inspiration was so important to him, he says, he and
Lawless decided to get the book to a wider audience as quickly as
possible by publishing it on iUniverse.com. It can be ordered
online for $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, if it sells, Banville will settle down. In the meantime,
though, he's gone through a few more women, jobs and addresses. And
there's a sequel in there, somewhere, he's sure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
