<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BRUNSWICKMARCH18-COX     07-17 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUNSWICKMARCH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. - It has been an uneventful two weeks since July
4th revelry turned into a bottle-throwing, car-burning melee that
pitted blacks against police in a rundown section of this port
town.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the appearance of cordiality, though, anger remains.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, it surfaced when about 200 residents, preachers
and black community leaders gathered near the epicenter of the
disturbance to protest what they say is a pattern of police
harassment topped off by recent offensive comments by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   A ``peace and unity'' rally was held at Albany and K streets,
next to the McIntyre Court public housing complex and within site
of the charred grass where a police cruiser was burned during the
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   The march was organized by the Rev. Burnette Fulton Sr., who
earlier condemned the holiday weekend violence that marred the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to carry a message that we as a black community don't
condone the actions of the perpetrators,'' Fulton said before the
rally. But he said the melee was spurred by long-simmering
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Fulton and his supporters marched 10 blocks from
Albany Street to the Old City Hall to bring their grievances to the
mayor's doorstep. The marchers filled much of Gloucester Street in
front of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Minister Odis Muhammad of the Nation of Islam called on Mayor
Brad Brown to meet with the demonstrators. ``The citizens of this
city have a problem and you shouldn't hide behind the walls of City
Hall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not attend the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Many black residents were angered earlier when Brown said those
involved in the holiday disturbance were ``all hoodlums, drug
dealers, pimps for prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was messed up, what he said. That's a lie,'' Kendra
McCrae, a 28-year-old secretary, said Monday. McCrae witnessed the
violent episodes both in Brunswick and nearby St. Simons Island.
``He shouldn't down our community like this if he is the mayor of
Brunswick. He's just talking about black people like we're
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown stood his ground Monday. ``The folks crying foul really
need to look at the situation and the destructive damage that
occurred to public property and realize that these type actions put
a bad light on the community and do not foster peacefulness and
unity, he said.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrae said she was on the beach at St. Simons when the holiday
disturbance began. She said police sprayed pepper spray in her
direction, cursed her and told her to ``get off our beach and get
off our island.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn County Police Chief Carl Alexander said Monday that was
``an absolute lie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not mistreated at the beach,'' Alexander said. ``Our
message to our (officers) is that you treat every person with
dignity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Three men have been arrested as a result of the July 4th
outbreak. Police continue to look for other suspects. Two
nightclubs, which Brunswick police and elected officials say
contributed to the rowdy atmosphere, remain shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   The disquiet in Brunswick won't completely fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something needs to change,'' said McCrae. ``It's due. We're
due. We are human beings, just like them. It's time they treated us
like humans, not like wild, untamed animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
