<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NY-EUROPE-BANKS-NYT     07-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EUROPE-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SAY SCHEME EXPLOITED RUSSIAN TASTE FOR CHICKEN LEGS
</HEADLINE>
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Using forged documents and shipments of frozen
chicken legs to Eastern Europe, a father and son from Westchester,
N.Y., with links to Russian organized crime stole more than $35
million from banks and financiers in Latvia and the United States,
Manhattan prosecutors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The men, Nickolai and Serguei Kouznetsov, who already face a
half-dozen civil lawsuits in Florida, Illinois and New York, and an
accomplice were indicted Monday on charges that they sold _ and
resold _ the same chicken legs to multiple buyers.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, one Latvian bank lent them $3.5
million on the basis of forged documents stating that 6 million
pounds of chicken were in a Florida warehouse, when they had
already been sold abroad and shipped to Tallinn, Estonia.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments mark the first stage of an investigation into
the scheme, which exploited a Russian love of dark-meat chicken,
one of America's largest exports to that country, said Robert
Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The younger suspect and the only one in custody, Serguei
Kouznetsov, 28, was arrested on Friday at his mother-in-law's house
in Lindenhurst, N.Y., the authorities said. He was denied bail
Monday after an assistant district attorney, Clark Abrams, told the
judge that, according to international law enforcement officials,
Kouznetsov had worked with Russian organized crime members.
</P>
<P>
   ``His position is that he's not guilty and he's going to contest
the charges vigorously,'' said Kouznetsov's lawyer, Austin
Campriello, who also said that his client had an American-born wife
and twin boys who turned 2 years old on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that his father, Nickolai, 50, along with Igor
Ilchenko, 38, who owns an Estonian company, were fugitives and
might be in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury also indicted two corporations run by the
Kouznetsovs, NASL Corp. in Manhattan and Claremont Trading in
Tortola, the British Virgin Islands, and an Estonian corporation
run by Ilchenko, Joint Stock Co. Trendors.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the scheme began on Long Island, where the
Kouznetsovs sold frozen chicken-leg quarters, along with whole
chickens, beef liver, turkey thighs and hot dogs, to various
chicken exporters. Among those exporters was one of the largest
such U.S. companies, Trans Commodities Inc., based in New York City
and run by Sam Kislin, who has been a contributor to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and other New York politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the indictment, the Kouznetsovs did not stop at
selling the chicken legs once. They obtained a loan from the
Paritate Bank in Latvia by using as collateral false warehouse
receipts showing that more than 6 million pounds of chicken were
being stored in a warehouse in Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of the warehouse receipts, the Paritate Bank wired
$3.5 million to the Kouznetsovs' account at the Bank of New York.
But the chicken had already been sold to another purchaser and was
on a ship on its way to Estonia, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether investors had made any
independent effort to verify whether the chicken actually existed.
``There are a lot of suckers at that bank,'' said John Moscow,
deputy chief of the Manhattan district attorney's investigation
division.
</P>
<P>
   In this manner, the men stole 130 million pounds of chicken
worth more than $35 million, pledging it to financial institutions
in return for loans while selling it to other purchasers instead,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment filed by Morgenthau's office covers only the $3.5
million loan from the Paritate Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme was far larger, according to a civil lawsuit filed by
the insurer Lloyd's of London in federal court in New York. The
lawsuit states that four financial companies insured by Lloyd's
have lost $38 million in stolen chicken.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, the four companies discovered that the
64,000 tons of chicken they supposedly owned had disappeared from
warehouses and ships, had been sold to others, and that they had
been duped with a trail of false documents, including shipping
bills, warehouse receipts and even forged certificates from the
U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors declined to comment on whether any of those who
financed the chicken purchases or bought the chicken from NASL were
under investigation, but they emphasized a wide-scale and
continuing inquiry. Morgenthau said, ``This is a case that has
legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
