<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSPECTED-TERRORIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORISM SUSPECT WAIVES EXTRADITON HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ An Algerian indicted in the United States on charges
of terrorism waived his right to an extradition hearing Monday and
will be turned over to the Americans in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Mokhtar Haouari, was indicted last Jan. 6 in New
York on charges of helping another Algerian living here, Ahmed
Ressam, who was arrested in December as he traveled into Washington
state from Canada. The police say Ressam's car carried explosives
and other bomb-making equipment as he crossed the border on Dec.
14.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari, 31, was arrested later in January in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers did not complete the arrangements to expedite Haouari's
transfer to the United States until minutes before his extradition
hearing was to have begun Monday. After Haouari had read and signed
the agreement, Judge Lise Cote ordered him turned over to the
Americans without delay. Haouari will remain in custody and leave
for New York after Canada has approved its paperwork, which could
take up to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari's lawyer, Joseph Elfassy, said Haouari wanted to face
the charges promptly and move on. ``We are convinced now that there
will not be enough proof to find him guilty,'' Elfassy said. ``so
our position was not to drag the case any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Haouari admits knowing Ressam, but denies any involvement in
terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
   Had Haouari followed the two-and-a-half-year extradition process
in Canada, the United States could have charged him only with the
six offenses cited in the extradition request. Waived his right to
a hearing means that the Justice Department can bring new charges.
</P>
<P>
   Elfassy was confident, saying: ``We are convinced that the
United States will not charge him with any offenses other than the
ones he faces already. So we agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said he had decided to change tactics after a court
in Los Angeles had postponed Ressam's trial until February 2001.
Elfassy had wanted Ressam to testify at Haouari's trial in New
York, a move that seems a highly unlikely prospect now, because of
the postponement.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari's waiver closely follows an arrest by the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police on June 26 of Mohamed Zeki Mahjoub, who, the
Canadian Security and Intelligence Service says, is a terrorist
leader closely allied with Osama bin Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
