<SLUG> BC-DEBEERS-DIAMONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA'S WINSPEAR DIAMONDS REJECTS OFFER FROM DE BEERS AS
INADEQUATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ De Beers Consolidated Mines, the South African diamond
giant, is finding unexpectedly tough resistance to its expansion
into a potentially lucrative property in the Canadian north.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers is thought likely to eventually gain control of its
first North American diamond mine by purchasing Winspear Diamonds,
a small Vancouver-based company. Winspear owns a site at Snap Lake,
about 150 miles northeast of Yellowknife, in the Northwest
Territories, that it calls one of the richest undeveloped diamond
properties in the world. It is putting up a fight that could make
success for De Beers more expensive than the big company
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian diamonds are regarded as especially important to De
Beers now because the company is trying to avoid marketing diamonds
mined in African war zones. Last week, it pledged not to trade with
companies that profit from diamonds used to finance African
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, De Beers offered 259 million Canadian dollars, or
roughly $175 million, for Winspear. Although that was a 77 percent
premium to the price of Winspear's shares, the company's board
called the offer opportunistic and inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Winspear moved to back up that contention,
saying that under new projections, the size of its ore reserves had
tripled and the potential rate of production would double.
</P>
<P>
   That sounded implausible to De Beers, particularly since
Winspear based the new projections on drilling information not
disclosed in a prospectus to shareholders a month earlier. De Beers
officials called the projections an attempt to thwart its takeover
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No reserve has yet been defined on the Snap Lake property,''
said Richard Molyneaux, president of De Beers Canada. He said
excavation of the ore on the Winspear property ``at a relatively
low depth, under a lake, has not been undertaken anywhere in the
world, and brings with it a number of significant risks.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Winspear's chief executive, Randy Turner, formally
rejected De Beers' price, and said it had been approached by other
companies, which could lead to a higher offer.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the new projections put the value of the Snap Lake
property at 1.35 billion Canadian dollars, or more than $900
million, and that previous assessments made the property worth at
least 500 million Canadian dollars _ almost twice what De Beers had
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the world's production of new diamonds comes from De
Beers, and two-thirds of the gems sold go through its distribution
system. The company missed out on early exploration in Canada, but
has become more determined since Molyneaux, an experienced mine
operator in South Africa, arrived early this year. De Beers gets 35
percent of the output from the Ekati mine in the Northwest
Territories, but has no operation of its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
