<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House Plans a Bill on Cyberspace Surveillance
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that it would propose legislation to set
legal requirements for surveillance in cyberspace by law
enforcement authorities similar in some ways to those for telephone
wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates and civil liberties groups welcomed some
aspects of the proposal but said they remained alarmed about a new
FBI computer system that searches and intercepts private e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Books Ordered by Chapter or Verse
</P>
<P>
   This fall, hundreds of books like travel guides will be sold on
the Internet in parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _ that
can be mixed and matched a la carte by readers. Buyers will have
the option of receiving their books electronically or ordering them
printed, bound and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-U.S. Attorney Is Sentenced
</P>
<P>
   A former U.S. attorney and commodities regulator was sentenced
to 24 months in prison for becoming a co-conspirator with the
operators of fraudulent telemarketing scams of the type he had once
investigated and prosecuted. The sentence received by John A. Field
III, 60, was a bit more than one-fourth of the maximum 87-month
term he could have faced, reflecting his cooperation with
investigators after he was caught.
</P>
<P>
   Tylenol to Be Sold in Japan This Fall
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that American drug companies are cracking open the
Japanese market, Johnson &AMP; Johnson is planning to announce that
Tylenol will be available in Japan early this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks End Mixed in Light Trading
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed in lackluster trading. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 8.48 points, or 0.1 percent, to 10,804.27.
The Nasdaq composite index rose 28.49 points, or 0.7 percent, to
4,274.67, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged up 0.51
point, to 1,510.49.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific to Buy Fort James
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group said that it would buy Fort James for $7.5
billion in cash and stock, creating the world's largest maker of
tissue as it moves away from the cyclical pulp and paper market. It
will also assume $3.5 billion in debt. Shares of Georgia-Pacific
fell $2.25, to $26.375, while shares Fort James soared $8.4375, or
34 percent, to $33.
</P>
<P>
   Two Law Firms Plan to Merge
</P>
<P>
   Two large law firms, Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro, based in San
Francisco, and Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam &AMP; Roberts, based in New
York, announced plans to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Prozac Ages, Still Causing a Furor
</P>
<P>
   As Prozac edges into adolescence and Eli Lilly's exclusive
patent nears expiration, Prozac is causing a stir. Two
psychiatrists contend that Prozac and its cousins are often
indiscriminately prescribed and have more serious side effects than
the public is aware of.
</P>
</TEXT>
