<P>
   (NYT7) LITTLE ROCK, Ark. -- July 17, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN --
With the Republican National Convention two weeks away, Gov. George
W. Bush began trying to build excitement about it Monday in his
playful, teasing manner, saying for the first time that he was
closing in on his selection of a running mate and letting his
advisers dribble out details about the five-day trip he would make to
the event. Gov. George W. Bush listens as Deborah Tillman, left,
holding a book entitiled "Do I  Have A Daddy" addresses a Leadership
Forum at the Centers for Youth and Families in Little Rock, Ark.,
before heading to Milwaukee later in the day. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 17, 2000 -- ROCK-TSHIRTS-FASHION --
Rock T-shirts are no longer just the province of independent
retailers like Screaming Mimi's or Patricia Field in New York, they
have made a comeback in a major way. The trend has been seized on by
national chains like Urban Outfitters. At Screaming Mimi's, Yuko
Ozeki, left, wears a vintage Iggy Pop T-shirt. At Patricia Field,
Agnes Makush, right, is in a Duran Duran T-shirt. Rock T-shirts
suggests something about pop culture's renewable amnesia and appetite
for cheesy aspects of the past. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BALTIMORE -- July 17, 2000 -- SCI-BODY-IMAGE-2 --
Having a poor body image is now considered a reliable predictor of
future eating disorders, including anorexia, bulimia and binge
eating. Several studies in the field of body-image research have
documented growing dissatisfaction with appearance and linked it, in
part, to the relentless parade of reed-thin figures in magazines,
billboards, movies and sitcoms. Dr. Beth Williams-Plunkett, left, and
Dr. Miriam Arenberg lead Girl Scouts on an appreciation tour of the
female form, part of a program called "Feast, Famine and the Female
Form: Exploring Body Image Through Art." Girl Scouts at the Baltimore
Museum of Art view "Little Dancer, Aged 14", left, by Degas.
(Salvatore C. DiMarco Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GOODLAND, Kansas -- July 17, 2000 -- SCI-LIGHTNING --
To study lightning, scientists from the New Mexico School of Mines
and Technology turned on 13 specially built lightning detectors that
were laid out in cornfields under radar observation. Dr. Ron Thomas
of the New Mexico School of Mines and Technology monitors signals
from 13 lightning detectors in Kansas and Colorado. (Kevin
Moloney/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BALTIMORE -- July 17, 2000 -- SCI-BODY-IMAGE-1 --
Having a poor body image is now considered a reliable predictor of
future eating disorders, including anorexia, bulimia and binge
eating. Several studies in the field of body-image research have
documented growing dissatisfaction with appearance and linked it, in
part, to the relentless parade of reed-thin figures in magazines,
billboards, movies and sitcoms. Dr. Beth Williams-Plunkett, left, and
Dr. Miriam Arenberg lead Girl Scouts on an appreciation tour of the
female form, part of a program called "Feast, Famine and the Female
Form: Exploring Body Image Through Art." Girl Scouts at the Baltimore
Museum of Art and discussing "At the Bathers Pool" by Robert
Colescott. (Salvatore C. DiMarco Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 17, 2000 -- SCI-PROZAC-SAFETY -- At
least two recently published books say that Prozac and related
antidepressants are often indiscriminately prescribed and pose the
risk of serious side effects, but critics of those views call them
alarmist and overblown. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOZEMAN, Mont. -- July 17, 2000 --
SCI-FUNGUS-HERBICIDE -- Members of Congress believe that Dr. David C.
Sands and other researchers may be on to a powerful and
environmentally safe method of killing not only coca plants, but also
marijuana and poppy plants. The members have asked the government of
Colombia to test a strain of Fusarium oxysporum over the next two
years. Sands holds out a clear plastic petri dish filled with a white
fuzzy fungus growing across the bottom. This substance, he believes,
is the key to ending much of the world's production of illicit drugs.
(Jim Robbins/The New York Times)
</P>
