<P>
   (NYT10) MILTON, N.Y. -- July 17, 2000 -- NY-APPLE-GROWERS --
Usually, when hail descends on the picturesque apple orchards of the
Hudson Valley, it strikes fitfully, creating havoc on a farmer's
field of Empires, say, but sparing his McIntoshes.  But this spring's
hail was  different. Two storms pelted newly formed apples with
jagged balls of ice on more than 7,000 acres. Ordinarily, apple
farmers would curse Mother Nature and hope for better luck. But a
number of forces -- from depressed prices resulting from a worldwide
glut to spotty insurance coverage to consumer demand for flawless
fruit -- have pushed Hudson Valley farmers to the brink. (Suzanne
DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. -- July 17, 2000 --
NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH-2 -- Based on the frenzied pace of speculative
construction in Southampton, N.Y. this summer and the frazzled lives
of workers doing the building, the Hamptons have never before been
invaded by so many rich people wanting to be wowed and demanding that
it happen fast. The invasion has driven construction costs to record
levels and seduced builders, architects and even carpenters to build
houses on 'spec." Cindy Crain, 31, a former magazine editor, is going
ahead with her dream house in Southampton. The budget for Crain's
planned 6,000-square-foot house has been raised to about $3.5 million
from $1.5 million. Crain with designer Will McGaul. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
