<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MALCOLMX-DIARY-NYT     07-17 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MALCOLMX-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW STUDENT PLEADS GUILTY TO STEALING MALCOLM X'S DIARY FROM
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three days into his trial on charges of grand
larceny, a former court clerk pleaded guilty Monday to stealing the
diary of Malcolm X from an evidence safe in Manhattan state Supreme
Court, where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk, Douglas Henderson, 41, had already admitted to
prosecutors that in 1991 he stole the diary, which the civil rights
leader had in his jacket pocket when he was assassinated at a
Manhattan ballroom in 1965. But he decided to go to trial anyway in
hopes of being cleared.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Henderson, who is a law student at New York Law
School, pleaded guilty before Judge Jeffrey M. Atlas in State
Supreme Court in Manhattan, swiftly concluding a trial in which two
of Malcolm X's daughters were expected to testify Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 146-page diary was first discovered missing from court
archives last May, when a private collector in California planned
to sell it through the auction house of Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield.
The mock-leather diary, which was bloodstained and bullet-pocked,
contained the phone numbers of Malcolm X's friends and a schedule
of planned appearances. One expert at the auction house estimated
its sale would bring $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The diary had been part of the evidence at the trial of three
men who were convicted of killing Malcolm X, and was supposed to
remain in the archives of the case. When Henderson stole the diary,
he left behind an empty evidence file in the safe marked ``1965 Red
Diary with Three Bullet Holes.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, he sold it to a memorabilia dealer, Mark
Schafler, for $5,000. After his arrest, Henderson at first said
that he had planned to return it to Malcolm X's family.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who apparently has long been fascinated with Malcolm
X, attended the prestigious Horace Mann School in the Bronx,
graduated from Lehman College, and is now a second-year student at
New York Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a top assistant of the tennis player Jimmy Connors,
and was a friend of Arthur Ashe and former Mayor David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   He said was reluctant to plead guilty initially because of his
aspirations to be a lawyer, people involved in the case said. If
convicted, he faces seven years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2210EDT &QL; 
