u w BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-17 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONTEMPT CASE, STARR'S FORMER SPOKESMAN DENIES MISLEADING A
JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charles G. Bakaly III, the former spokesman for the
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, testified Monday that he never
misled a federal judge about the role he had played as a source for
an article in The New York Times that discussed whether President
Clinton could be indicted while in office.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stand in his defense at a trial in which he is
charged with criminal contempt, Bakaly insisted that there was
nothing untruthful in a sworn declaration he had provided to the
judge. In it he said he had never provided any ``nonpublic
information'' to The Times for the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it true?'' Michele A. Roberts, a defense lawyer, asked
Bakaly about his signed statement to the court in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it was,'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it remain true today?'' Roberts asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it does,'' Bakaly said.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration was provided to Judge Norma Holloway Johnson,
the chief judge of the federal district court here, by the office
of the independent counsel during an investigation into whether
anyone in the office had leaked the information that led to the
article.
</P>
<P>
   After the declaration was filed, Bakaly gradually disclosed to
investigators that he had provided the newspaper with some
documents in connection with the article. He also told
investigators that he may he have inadvertently confirmed some of
the information that he said the reporter, Don Van Natta Jr., had
told him he had learned from sources outside the counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   When the office learned of these later disclosures by Bakaly, it
informed Johnson that the original declaration was inaccurate.
Johnson charged Bakaly with criminal contempt and is hearing the
case without a jury. Bakaly could face up to six months in prison
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly, a 44-year-old lawyer from California, offered a
two-pronged defense Monday.
</P>
<P>
   First, he argued that in an effort to steer Van Natta from
writing the article, he had provided information that was not
secret but was in documents already in the public record.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he argued that fellow lawyers in Starr's office had
omitted some changes he had proposed in the declaration, which
would have provided a more complete account of his dealings with
Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article, published on Jan. 31, 1999, cited unnamed
associates of Starr as saying the independent counsel had concluded
that he had the constitutional authority to indict Clinton while he
was still serving as president.
</P>
<P>
   The article was published when the Senate was considering
whether to convict Clinton on impeachment charges voted by the
House. Clinton's lawyers complained that the article was an effort
by the independent counsel's office to influence the impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said Monday the reporter had come to him with information
he said he had learned from sources outside the office about
internal deliberations on whether to indict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said he first told him that his sources might not be well
informed. He also sent Van Natta part of an internal memorandum
about how Leon F. Jaworski, the independent prosecutor during
Watergate, had felt about the issue in connection with President
Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly testified he regretted having sent that document.
Although it was historical and factual, he said, providing the
document ``caused harm to the morale in the office and harmed my
colleagues.'' But he continued: ``The key thing is I did not give
him any nonpublic information or information that related to grand
jury matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by John Griffith, a Justice Department
lawyer, Bakaly acknowledged he did not initially admit he had been
the source for some of the information in the article.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith asked Bakaly about a meeting in the office of
independent counsel the Monday after the article appeared. He asked
Bakaly if he had told lawyers at the meeting that there were parts
of the article for which he had been responsible. Bakaly said it
did not come up in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson urged Bakaly to answer more directly. Then he said,
``No,'' he had not talked about his role in the article.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination continues Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
