<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH DEBATE HYPOTHETICAL ISSUE: EXECUTION OF A PREGNANT
WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ The national debate over the death penalty took
an odd turn Monday when Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas each discussed what to do in the hypothetical case of
a pregnant woman facing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the issue was one of abortion rights: He would let the
woman decide whether the execution should be delayed, allowing her
the option of whether or not to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, who has presided over more executions than any other
governor in the country, it was a matter of pointing to the
compassion in his conservatism. He said he would support delaying
such an execution ``because there's a second life involved.''
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the issue has apparently been moot.
Experts on the death penalty said the situation had never arisen on
the federal level since Congress created an exclusion for pregnant
women when it expanded the federal death penalty law in 1994.
Several states, including Texas, have also enacted such exclusions,
but no experts reached Monday could remember a single case in which
a pregnant woman faced execution.
</P>
<P>
   The question first came up on Sunday in an interview with Gore
on the NBC News program ``Meet the Press.'' The vice president, who
backs the death penalty, was asked whether he would support it if
the condemned prisoner happened to be pregnant. Gore replied that
he was unfamiliar the issue and would have to examine it.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Gore said he would allow a pregnant
woman to choose whether to delay her execution until she gave
birth. ``The principle of a woman's right to choose governs in that
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At an earlier news conference in Little Rock, Ark., Bush tweaked
Gore for his answer in the television interview, saying he was
``surprised, frankly,'' that the vice president had needed time to
think about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty opponents said that the subject was a bit far
afield in the larger debate on capital punishment but that it
nonetheless underscored the kind of harsh reality involved in
putting people to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``This question is yet another illustration of the fact that the
discussion and debate around the issue is becoming more specific
and less abstract,'' said Diann Rust-Tierney, director of the
capital punishment project at the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Gore addressed the issue after flying here to his home state
Monday, armed with new poll numbers showing his race with Bush
growing tighter.
</P>
<P>
   He continued his attack on Bush's record in Texas and, in
casting his own candidacy in classic Democratic terms as a fight
for the disadvantaged, made personal reference to his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of what this campaign is all about, I think of my
own upbringing,'' he told a gathering of his field workers from the
50 states at a rally in Nashville, his campaign headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two sets of really good friends, one in Washington,
D.C., and the other in Carthage, Tenn.,'' he said of his
son-of-a-senator winters and his family-farm summers. He said the
friends in Washington came from well-to-do families, went to
college and enjoyed lots of advantages. The ones in Tennessee, he
said, ``were just as bright _ at least as bright _ and had at least
as much potential as the ones I grew up with in Washington, but
they did not have the same opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   This disparity ``broke my heart, because I saw that they did not
get what they deserved in life by virtue of their talent and their
potential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I travel around this country today,'' he added, ``I see
young men and women and Americans of all ages like my friends who I
know deserve to have the barriers removed, the opportunities opened
up so that they can reach their full potential.''
</P>
<P>
   This theme dovetails with the policy formulations Gore has been
developing over the last several weeks, particularly as he rails
against the ``special interests'' like big oil that he says Mr.
Bush is serving.
</P>
<P>
   This was officially Commerce Secretary William Daley's first day
as Gore campaign chairman, and, in a Nashville briefing with
campaign workers from around the country that that was closed to
reporters, the vice president pointed to a new CNN/USA Today poll
that showed him trailing Bush by only 2 points, 43 percent to 45
percent; that was considerably closer than last month's CNN poll,
which had Gore trailing by 12 points. A new CBS poll also showed
Gore narrowing the race, to 2 percentage points, 41 percent to 43
percent; in mid-May, Gore trailed in that poll by 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch with his mother and a conference with campaign
strategists, Gore greeted the dozens of workers who staff his
Nashville headquarters. Standing on a chair, surrounded by the
mostly college-age crowd, he adopted the language that his
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 26, uses on the campaign trail to
reach her under-30 audiences.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing to their sense of idealism, Gore warned the young
workers to avoid the ``ironic detachment'' that afflicts the
cynical. He said some people became detached because they were
afraid that if they gave their hearts to something, they would only
be let down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it everything you have got, he exhorted them, ``and then
some.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference later in the day, Gore was asked how he
would square his criticism that Bush had mismanaged the state
budget in Texas with his earlier assertions that Bush was a weak
governor who had little power.
</P>
<P>
   ``What power he does have he has used to ill effect,'' Gore
replied. He called Bush's budget a ``two-page ditty'' that served
only the special interests.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of his record as governor, Bush has often noted that
the people of Texas re-elected him in 1998 with nearly 70 percent
of the vote. To that, Gore scoffed on Monday, ``People in the other
49 states vote in this election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
