<HEADER>
A5052 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG--COLUMN-SFCH     07-17 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FIGURING SHARES POST SPIN-OFF
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY ARTHUR LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I am a Hewlett-Packard shareholder who received shares of
Agilent Technologies recently when HP spun it off. Can you tell me
how to figure the cost basis for the Agilent shares and the new
cost basis for my HP shares?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Take the original cost basis of the HP shares and
multiply by 0.78. That is the new cost basis for the HP shares.
Divide the number of HP shares into that result to get your
per-share cost basis for HP.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder _ 0.22 times the original cost of your HP shares _
will be your cost basis for Agilent. Divide the number of Agilent
shares into that figure to get your per-share cost basis.
</P>
<P>
   HP says the Internal Revenue Service declared the Agilent
distribution tax-free. This means that you don't have to pay taxes
on the Agilent shares immediately _ only if you sell them, in which
case you could be liable for a capital-gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   So you also will want to know the official purchase date of your
Agilent shares: It is the same as the purchase date for your HP
shares.
</P>
<P>
   An HP spokesman says you should have received materials at the
time of the distribution that would have answered your question. It
may be that you discarded them without looking them over.
</P>
<P>
   If you want fresh copies, call HP's investor relations
department at (650) 236-5234. You can find the same information at
HP's Web site. Go to www.hp.com, click on ``Investor Information,''
then click again on ``FAQ _ Agilent distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO SHAREHOLDERS IN ANY COMPANY: Always take the time to
carefully examine the documents your company sends you.
</P>
<P>
   Early 401(k) Withdrawals
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am sitting on a large amount of money in a 401(k) plan, am
under age 55 and no longer employed by the company whose plan it
is. Can I take distributions from the plan now without paying the
10 percent penalty tax for early withdrawal?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been different if you had left the employer during
or after the year in which you reach age 55, says Joe Calderaro,
technical coordinator with the Internal Revenue Service. In that
case, you could have taken advantage of a quirky exception to the
rule that normally requires you to wait for distributions until age
591/2 to avoid the penalty tax.
</P>
<P>
   Switching Stockbrokers
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have two accounts with a discount broker _ a standard
account and a Roth individual retirement account. This broker's
performance was excellent until this year, but now I want to find
another broker. I wonder whether switching will trigger a taxable
event _ capital gains _ in my standard account. And what about the
Roth? Will I have to pay some sort of penalty tax?
</P>
<P>
   A: You won't be hit with a capital-gains tax in your standard
account unless you sell shares of stock that have risen in value
since you bought them. It isn't necessary to do that merely because
you are switching brokers. Just sign the standard forms authorizing
your next broker to transfer your account intact from your present
broker. The stock will go to the new broker in the form of stock,
the cash in the form of cash.
</P>
<P>
   You also can roll over your IRA without penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Such transfers are done all the time, without tax-related
hitches _ and that's as it should be. It wouldn't be fair to
penalize you because your broker turned sour. And it wouldn't be
fair to give lousy brokers such a powerful grip on their
dissatisfied customers.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column,
901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
