<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PAPER-MERGER-NYT &LR;      07-17 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA-PACIFIC PAYING $7.5 BILLION FOR FORT JAMES; EARNINGS BEAT
FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Georgia-Pacific Group said Monday that it would buy the Fort
James Corp. for $7.5 billion in cash and stock, creating the
world's largest maker of tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Based on closing prices on Friday, the deal calls for
Georgia-Pacific to pay $37.17 for each share of Fort James, 80
percent in cash and 20 percent in stock. It will also assume $3.5
billion in debt. The combined company will have about $25 billion
in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific will divest 250,000 tons of tissue capacity to
ward off potential Justice Department objections. And it will
divest some commodity operations to raise cash.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition surprised many analysts. Georgia-Pacific has
been steadily adding to its portfolio of retail and away-from-home
papers _ tissues, napkins and other products used in businesses and
restaurants _ and owns AngelSoft, Coronet and other well-known
brands. Still, it derived more than 90 percent of its $17.8 billion
in revenue last year from lumber, paperboard and other highly
cyclical commodity papers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, most analysts saw the company as more similar to commodity
paper companies like International Paper and Weyerhaueser than to
tissue producers like Procter &AMP; Gamble and Kimberly-Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured G-P would acquire other commodity paper companies,
or maybe be bought itself,'' said Mark Wilde, an analyst with
Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, though, Georgia-Pacific has been telegraphing its
search for ways to unleash itself from the cyclical pulp and paper
market for some time. In late 1997, it created a tracking stock for
its timber operations. And during the last two years, it bought the
Chesapeake Corp.'s tissue operations and Unisource Worldwide, a
distributor of office paper, washroom supplies and janitorial
services. Earlier this month, it bought exclusive rights to
distribute the Xerox Corp.'s printer and copier papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been moving away from a commodity, raw material-based
strategy, and you can expect us to continue that,'' said A.D.
Correll, Georgia-Pacific's chairman and chief executive. The
company's second-quarter earnings, which it also released Monday,
puts Correll's yen for higher-margin products into focus. The
company's pulp and paper business had a strong quarter, but weak
demand and prices for its building-products segment pulled profit
down to $206 million, about $5 million less than in the quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Per-share earnings of $1.20 beat analysts' forecasts of $1.16,
but Charles Hill, director of research at First Call/Thomson
Financial, which tracks company earnings, said most analysts had
cut their estimates in anticipation of a bad quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fort James, which owns well-known brands like Quilted Northern,
Brawny and Dixie Cups, does own some pulp plants, but it uses much
of its production for its tissues. If the merger goes through,
Georgia-Pacific will command about a third of the North American
market for retail and away-from-home paper.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the prospect does not thrill investors. Shares of
Georgia-Pacific fell $2.25, to $26.375. Fort James soared $8.4375,
to $33. ``They'll have to really show that this merger will work
before the Street will buy into it,'' said Wilde of Deutsche Banc
Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Fort James will not be easy for Georgia-Pacific to digest. Fort
James was formed in 1997 when James River and Fort Howard merged,
and it has had a rough time integrating back-office operations and
product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific recently installed a sophisticated software
system that ties in all its operations, from orders to production
to accounts receivable to human resources, and analysts expect it
to add Fort James' operations to the system as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, which already carries about $6.5 billion in
debt, is borrowing $10 billion more to finance the deal. Correll
has said he wants to get debt down to $9.5 billion by early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Correll said divestitures would accomplish much of that, but he
declined to identify what those would be. But Wilde suggested that
lumber operations were ``high on the hit list.''
</P>
<P>
   Correll also promised that by the third year of the merger, he
would have wrested at least $500 million in annual costs out of the
combined companies. He added that he had already pinpointed ``a
fair number of job reductions'' and would soon deliver the news to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Fort James' top management seemed to be on that list. Miles
Marsh, Fort James' chief executive, was not included in Monday's
conference call with analysts.
</P>
</TEXT>
