<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH--STOCKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENENTECH STOCK  
 FALLS WITH DIP  
 IN DRUG SALES
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An unexpected dip in the sales of a breast
cancer drug drove shares in Genentech Inc. down 5 percent Monday,
making the South San Francisco giant one of the rare losers on a
day when biotech stocks enjoyed a modest rally.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued before the market opened Monday, Genentech
reported operating earnings of $78.2 million (29 cents per share)
for the quarter ended June 30, matching analysts' consensus
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Those second-quarter figures were 7 percent higher than the
year-ago quarter, when Genentech reported operating earnings of
$73.2 million (27 cents).
</P>
<P>
   But investors zeroed in on the fact that sales of Herceptin,
Genentech's breast cancer treatment, slipped 3 percent last
quarter, compared with the first three months of the company's
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech spokeswoman Sabrina Johnson said the drop occurred
because Roche, the Swiss drug giant that owns a controlling
interest in Genentech, stockpiled Herceptin in the first quarter in
preparation for introducing that drug in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Those Roche orders helped lift Herceptin sales by 26 percent in
the first quarter to $68.7 million. But when the Swiss firm cut its
Herceptin purchases in the quarter just ended, the result was a $2
million dip that surprised analysts who were expecting total
Herceptin sales above $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said sales were artificially elevated because Roche
(previously) bought a significant amount of Herceptin,'' said
analyst Eric Schmidt with SG Cowen. ``What they forgot to do is
tell us that last quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech Chief Financial Officer Lou Lavigne said the company
has warned investors in the past that large drug sales to overseas
marketing partners could cause ``fluctuations'' in
quarter-to-quarter sales. ``That shouldn't have been a surprise,''
Lavigne said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had the last word Monday, driving Genentech shares
down $8 to close at $153.50 on volume of 1.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's retreat stood in contrast to a 3.9 percent rebound
in the Amex biotech stock index, which consists of 17 large biotech
firms. Last week, the index slipped 7.3 percent as a wave of profit
taking erased some of the gains the biotech sector had registered
in June and early July.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech aside, biotech seemed back in favor Monday as shares
in 15 of the 17 firms in the Amex index gained ground, including
Chiron Corp. of Emeryville, which rose $2.19 to close at $54.88.
</P>
<P>
   A second and larger index, which reflects the performance of 200
smaller biotech firms, also rose 2.3 percent Monday, with gainers
outnumbering losers 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech, meanwhile, continued to accent the positive in its
earnings report, including its sales of Rituxan, a treatment for
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Genentech reported Rituxan sales of $102.8
for the quarter, beating the $94 million analysts had expected. The
surplus in Rituxan sales helped offset the Herceptin shortfall and
allowed Genentech to meet its earnings-per-share target.
</P>
<P>
   Lavigne, Genentech's CFO, said the company also introduced two
new drugs during the quarter, an improved clot buster for heart
attacks and a time-release version of its growth hormone drug that
eliminates the need for daily injections.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, this was a very, very solid quarter,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's earnings are complicated by charges stemming from
its purchase by Roche in 1999 and Roche's subsequent spin-off of
Genentech shares. For the most part, Wall Street ignores the
charges and focuses on operating earnings.
</P>
<P>
   When acquisition-related charges are considered, Genentech lost
$14.2 million (5 cents) in the second quarter. During the same
period a year ago, the company lost $923.2 million ($3.59).
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
