<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TYLENOL-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      07-17 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYLENOL-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON &AMP; JOHNSON EXPECTING TO SELL TYLENOL IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sign that American drug companies are cracking open the
Japanese market, Johnson &AMP; Johnson will announce Tuesday that
Tylenol will be available in Japan early this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the second largest market for over-the-counter drugs in
the world. But for decades, the government has kept many foreign
drug makers out. And, many drugs available to Europeans or
Americans are not approved for sale in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Tylenol has been available in the United States since 1955, and
is now available in 46 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson executives said Monday that the company did
not begin trying to get approval to sell Tylenol in Japan until
1995. In 1997, it signed a partnership agreement with Takeda
Chemical Industries, Japan's largest drug company, to jointly
market the pain reliever. The Japanese government agreed that the
companies could sell Tylenol last year. Since that time, the
companies have talked to more than 3,000 Japanese consumers to find
out how best to market the pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a demanding government in Japan,'' said Fred Walker,
marketing director for the company's McNeil Consumer Healthcare
division in Japan. ``There is a demanding consumer. We needed to do
our homework.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading over-the-counter pain reliever in Japan is now
Bufferin, which is made by the Lion Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson will market Tylenol the same way similar drugs
are sold in Japan. For example, the company will offer granules of
Tylenol, flavored and packaged in an envelope, which quickly
dissolve..
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson officials would not disclose how much Tylenol
it expects to sell in Japan or how much of the profits Takeda will
get.
</P>
<P>
   For years, strict Japanese requirements for foreign drug
companies have kept many popular medications out. A turning point
came last year when Viagra, the anti-impotence drug, was quickly
approved. The government then agreed that oral contraceptives could
be sold. The contraceptives had been under review by the Japanese
government for at least nine years.
</P>
</TEXT>
