<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INSURE--DISGRACE-SFCH     07-17 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURE--DISGRACE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE SCANDAL CREATES QUANDARY OVER HOW TO PICK
COMMISSIONERS  _ AND AVOID FURTHER PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush's
scandalous downfall, cries for reform are resounding throughout
California.
</P>
<P>
   Some reformers argue that the office of insurance commissioner
should be changed from elective back to appointive, to depoliticize
it.
</P>
<P>
   Others want to keep the position elective but ban insurance
companies from contributing to the election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Still others say that simply finding an honest person to fill
the office should be the uppermost concern.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned under pressure on June 28, after state
Assembly hearings disclosed that he let insurers avoid as much as
$3.7 billion in fines stemming from alleged mishandling of
policyholder claims after the 1994 Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the insurers were permitted to wriggle out by paying
$12 million into nonprofit foundations that Quackenbush created.
Foundation money was then allegedly used to finance political
events that benefited Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's many critics have been quick to point out
that the insurance industry provided major financial support to
Quackenbush's successful election campaigns in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Some want to eliminate the public's right _ granted a decade ago
by Proposition 103 _ to elect insurance commissioners. They say the
system has failed and that insurance commissioners should once
again be appointed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Others feel that it would be unfair _ not to mention politically
hazardous _ to deprive Californians of their precious voting
rights. They point out that the passage of Proposition 103 came
about, in part, because voters were displeased with an appointed
commissioner, Roxani Gillespie, who also &LR;   &LR; was perceived as being
too cozy with the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot legislate honesty,'' says Harvey Rosenfield, the
author of Proposition 103 and head of the Foundation for Taxpayer
and Consumer Rights in Los Angeles. ``Punishing the voters by
stripping them of the right to elect isn't going to eliminate
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for insurance commissioner in California depend
heavily on contributions, because it costs millions to wage an
effective campaign. That's largely because TV ad time is
prohibitively expensive in the densely populated Los Angeles and
San Francisco areas.
</P>
<P>
   But allowing insurance companies to make contributions
inevitably produces conflicts of interest, because the insurers are
_ supposedly _ regulated by the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Says San Francisco attorney Ray Bourhis, who represents
consumers in insurance disputes: ``It's the same as putting a
collection plate on the bench of your local Superior Court and
asking whether litigants want to contribute to the judge's son's
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Quackenbush's conduct is enough to justify a change in
the way the commissioner is chosen is highly debatable.
</P>
<P>
   The foremost supporter of such a change _ not surprisingly _ is
Gov. Gray Davis, who proposed it a couple of days after Quackenbush
said he was stepping down. If the proposal were adopted, it would
give him the power to make the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent supporter is state Sen. Jackie Speier,
D-Hillsborough, a consumer advocate who pushed such a proposal
through a Senate committee in May as details of the Quackenbush
scandal were unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   However, the proposal has powerful opposition in Sacramento.
Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, quashed an
attempt to bring the Speier measure to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Burton explained that he preferred not to change a setup that
was approved by the voters.
</P>
<P>
   California is one of 12 states in which commissioners are
elected, according to the National Association of Insurance
Commissioners, and Quackenbush is not the only elected commissioner
to become mired in scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, elected commissioners in Louisiana,
Mississippi and Florida have been forced to resign because of
illegal conduct, notes Jerry Davies, a spokesman for the Personal
Insurance Federation in Sacramento. Appointed commissioners, he
says, have generally had less trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   However, Davies concedes that the current, elected Florida
incumbent, Bill Nelson, is one of the top commissioners in the
nation. Nelson has a reputation for effective crackdowns on
insurance agents who defraud consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Campaniano, who served as appointed insurance commissioner
of Hawaii from 1987 to 1991, maintains that whether commissioners
are appointed or elected does not in itself determine how good a
job they will do.
</P>
<P>
   Campaniano says the key to the job is to not play favorites, but
rather to strike a balance between the interests of consumers and
companies. He points out that one of the duties imposed on
commissioners is to make certain that insurers remain solvent _
which means occasionally granting permission for premium increases,
however unpopular they may be.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Senn, the elected insurance commissioner of the state of
Washington, says having to go before the electorate every four
years helps her do her job better, because it makes her ``much more
responsive'' to the wishes of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Noted for her battles with health care insurers over
questionable rejections of patient claims, Senn has been described
as the best insurance commissioner in the nation by consumer
advocate (and presidential candidate) Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Senn points out that her state has a law prohibiting insurance
companies from contributing to election campaigns of would-be
insurance commissioners. She says that she also voluntarily
declined to take contributions from health maintenance
organizations _ arguably something she would not have gotten
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   John Garamendi, Quackenbush's predecessor and the first elected
California commissioner, says he declined to accept
insurance-company contributions during his campaign on the
Democratic ticket in 1990. Yet he managed to raise $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that you have to rely on insurance-company
contributions is a falsehood, a sham,'' Garamendi says. He contends
that such contributions constitute ``potential bribery'' and should
be made illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Garamendi acknowledges that some of his financing came from
trial lawyers, the natural enemies of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK, he says, because ``the insurance commissioner
doesn't regulate the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sirola, a spokesman for State Farm Insurance, the
property/casualty insurer with the largest market share in
California, says his company ``leans toward'' making the
commissioner's job appointive again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the same reason we don't elect the chairman of the
Federal Reserve, Supreme Court justices or banking commissioners,''
he explains. ``Regulators should be above politics. We find it very
difficult to operate in those jurisdictions where the regulatory
positions have become heavily politicized.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirola says that State Farm does not make political
contributions and that the company favors banning contributions
from insurers and ``anyone who derives income from the insurance
mechanism, including lawyers and body shops.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
