<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      07-17 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WEST NILE VIRUS IS FOUND IN STATEN ISLAND, WESTCHESTER AND
SUFFOLk  
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After finding two dead crows infected with the West
Nile virus on Staten Island, New York City officials announced late
Monday that they would spray about half the borough with a
pesticide starting Wednesday night to try to kill mosquitoes that
carry the disease before it is spread again to humans.
</P>
<P>
   The confirmation that the virus had returned to New York City
was announced on the same day that state health officials said that
for the first time this year it had also turned up in samples, or
pools, of mosquitoes collected in Westchester and Suffolk Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The two announcements offered the best evidence to date that a
virus never before seen in North America until last year _ when it
was blamed for seven deaths and the infection of 62 others in the
New York area _ had survived the winter and was again flourishing.
The findings also suggest that it may now also be working its way
back and forth between insects and birds, a step necessary before
it can be spread to humans, health experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The virus can cause encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain
and central nervous system that is sometimes fatal. The elderly,
children under 5 and people with weakened immune systems are the
most vulnerable to life-threatening cases.
</P>
<P>
   No human infections have been found so far this year, a point
that Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and other city officials made
repeatedly Monday in urging city residents not to overreact. But
state and city health officials again urged residents to use bug
repellent, long-sleeved shirts or long pants when going outside at
night, particularly if visiting coastal or wooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't panic,'' Giuliani said at a Staten Island news
conference, standing next to Neal L. Cohen, the city health
commissioner; Guy V. Molinari, the borough president; and Richard
Sheirer, the city director of emergency management.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not mean there has been an outbreak of West Nile
virus _ yet,'' the mayor said, as he prepared to explain the
pesticide effort, which will be completed from the ground on
Wednesday and Thursday morning. ``But it is absolutely necessary
that we do this.'' At this point, the city has no plans to do
aerial spraying.
</P>
<P>
   The spraying will start at 10 p.m., EDT, Wednesday and continue
until about 5 a.m. Thursday in the Rossville and Westerleigh
sections of Staten Island, where the dead birds were found. City
officials intend to spray a pesticide known as Anvil, which has the
active ingredient Sumithrin, a substance considered similar to the
natural pesticide produced by chrysanthemum flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Anvil breaks down in sunlight and water and is considered
``relatively nontoxic'' to humans, dogs, cats and other mammals,
city health officials said, but they recommended that people and
their pets stay inside during the spraying, and that windows and
air conditioners be turned off.
</P>
<P>
   So far, city officials say they plan to extend the treatment to
other boroughs only if they find infected birds or evidence of the
virus elsewhere, but Giuliani warned, ``You have to leave all the
options open to protect people's health.''
</P>
<P>
   The infected crows found in Staten Island were identified as a
result of a regional effort to quickly detect the presence of the
disease. Health officials hope that by moving immediately to kill
mosquitoes in areas where the disease is found and urging the
public to avoid exposure to surviving insects, they can prevent a
widespread outbreak. Efforts have also been under way since the
start of spring to kill mosquito eggs.
</P>
<P>
   In New York State alone, 700 birds, 55,000 mosquitoes and 200
humans have been tested so far this year. To date, 32 mosquitoes
have been found with evidence of the virus _ those confirmed Monday
in Westchester and Suffolk Counties. A total of about 25 infected
birds have also been found, most of them in the last two weeks,
with the ones outside Staten Island picked up in Rockland,
Westchester and Suffolk Counties in New York and in Bergen County
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, New York City officials announced plans for ground
spraying in parts of Queens, but the effort was canceled after two
laboratories concluded that a chicken thought to have contracted
the virus was not infected.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Suffolk County, on eastern Long Island, announced
their own plans Monday for ground spraying in selected areas of the
county. The county is also considering aerial spraying, said Millie
Svatek, a spokeswoman for the Suffolk County Department of Health
Services. And it intends to distribute insect repellent for free
Tuesday to county residents.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Health Commissioner Antonia C. Novello contacted
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, asking the
agency to help coordinate the response between New York and its
neighbors. Throughout the region, people are being urged to
eliminate standing water where mosquitoes can breed by making sure
roof gutters drain properly, disposing of tires and cleaning and
chlorinating swimming pools, outdoor saunas and hot tubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
