<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COULTER--BANKING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BOFA  
 CEO RETURNS  
 TO BANKING
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Coulter, one of the leading lights in the
soap opera that shook Bank of America, is back in banking.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief executive of the giant San Francisco bank,
bought in 1998 by North Carolina's NationsBank, is taking an
unspecified top-level job at Chase Manhattan Corp., the
third-largest bank in the United &UR;  &LR; States.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, who will turn 53 later this month, will work for the
New York bank ``in a very senior role. We just haven't decided what
that is yet,'' Chase chief executive Bill Harrison told the British
magazine Euromoney in a recent interview. A Chase spokesman
declined to elaborate, and Coulter did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter's return to banking comes nearly two years after he
engineered the sale of BofA, only to find himself forced out by
NationsBank chief executive Hugh McColl days after the takeover was
completed and publicly blamed for risky investments that led to
hundreds of millions of dollars in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Since his unceremonious ouster, Coulter has kept a low profile.
But that hasn't stopped him from playing an active role in
California business and cultural affairs. He sat on several
corporate or charitable boards, including that of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist
Group, the San Francisco high-tech investment bank bought by Chase
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first time, nor the last time, that there will be
ironic twists of fate,'' said Tony Price, a San Francisco executive
recruiter with the search firm Russell Reynolds Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Being outmaneuvered by McColl apparently hasn't tarnished
Coulter's reputation. His personal decency, analytical skills and
knowledge of corporate finance are widely respected in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Coulter was one of a handful of top candidates
interviewed for the CEO slot at Chicago's Bank One Corp., the No.
4. U.S. bank, sources said. Former Citigroup executive James Dimon
got the job.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Coulter became a senior partner and manager of the
Los Angeles office of the Beacon Group, a tony investment boutique
and money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   It was by that route that he came to New York's Chase, a bank
that traces its origins to the Rockefeller family and is one of
elite names in U.S. finance. Two months ago, Chase bought Beacon
and hired its founder, former Goldman Sachs merger adviser Geoffrey
Boisi, to head its rapidly growing investment banking operations.
The bank got Coulter in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter at first was leery of returning to banking in a
subordinate role, several people familiar with his thinking said.
Up until a few weeks ago, he was forging ahead with his Beacon
projects, including a series of joint investments with Japan's
Softbank Venture Capital.
</P>
<P>
   But then Chase's Harrison turned on his considerable sales
skills. After a meeting that lasted several hours some weeks ago,
Coulter agreed to stay at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives are still working out the nature of Coulter's
responsibilities, people familiar with the matter said. It's not
clear whether he will remain in Los Angeles or move to New York.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Coulter isn't taking a Chase job because he needs
money. In addition to a BofA severance package worth an estimated
$100 million, Coulter also cashed in as a Beacon partner.
</P>
<P>
   The price Chase paid for Beacon wasn't disclosed, but an earlier
bid for the firm came in at $400 million. If Chase's price was
similar, that would have meant, on average, a windfall of more than
$25 million for each of Beacon's partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done very well in his new situation,'' said Price.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
