<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL--FINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PUC HUNG UP ON WHETHER TO FINE PAC BELL FOR SALES PITCHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State regulators are sharply split over whether
to sanction Pacific Bell over complaints that it misled customers
into buying services they didn't want or need.
</P>
<P>
   Public Utilities Commission Judge Maribeth Bushey ruled late
last week that the local phone company should be fined a record $49
million _ $5 million more than her initial ruling in December _ for
marketing abuses. For example, the judge chastised the local phone
company for labeling a package, brimming with extras such as
three-way calling and voice mail, as the ``basics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Commissioner Josiah Neeper, who was assigned to oversee the
case, argues in an alternate decision that no fine is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Neeper said Pac Bell's marketing practices ``do not violate
statutory and current decisional standards.'' He also said Pac Bell
made it clear that its ``basics'' package is unrelated to basic
phone service. Pac Bell says it first sells new customers the local
package, and then in a separate part of the call talks about extra
features.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the issue will come up before the full commission as
early as August 3.
</P>
<P>
   But it is too early to say for certain how the other four
commissioners will rule. An adviser to Commissioner Henry Duque
said he has not made up his mind yet. An aide to Commission
President Loretta Lynch said he was not sure how she would vote.
She could not be reached for comment yesterday. The
telecommunication advisers for the other commissioners did not
return calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fork in the road for the commission,'' said Chris
Witteman of Greenlining, a consumer watchdog group in San
Francisco. ``It's two opposing views of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pac Bell and consumer advocates routinely do battle
over allegations that the company mistreats customers, this battle
is particularly crucial because the potential fine is large.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell, which took out full-page ads opposing the fine in
newspapers across the state, hailed Neeper's proposal as a sign
that the fine could be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we said all along, Pacific Bell follows all rules and
regulations,'' Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Utility Consumers Action Network, the San Diego group
that helped start the case, dismissed Neeper's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassment,'' said Michael Shames, the group's
executive director. ``I'd be shocked if this proposal was
adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
