<HEADER>
A5064 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-TEENS-2TAKES-N     07-17 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEENS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF PHAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 2nd take is 1100 words of do's and don'ts.) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Left to my own devices, I would not have spent my first
afternoon in London hanging out with men dressed as nuns.
</P>
<P>
   But my traveling companions _ two teen-age boys _ overruled me
and dragged me to the balcony of the Prince Charles Cinema for a
showing of ``Sing-A-Long-a Sound of Music.'' Soon I found myself
belting out ``Edelweiss'' along with my son, Will Griggs, 14, and
his friend, Wyatt Fenner, 15, and cheering the guy in the yodel
girl outfit who won the fancy-dress contest at intermission. While
I might have planned an itinerary of ambling through Hyde Park,
picking my way through the antiques on Portobello Road and sipping
Pimm's Cup at the Ivy in Covent Garden, I had to give in to the
boys.
</P>
<P>
   Giving in to the boys turned out to be a good guiding principle
for this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Our five-day jaunt to London in April was my fifth vacation with
teens. Over spring break, while my husband putters in our garden
and enjoys the suburban solitude, I usually go off with one or both
of our teen-age children (my daughter, Cornelia, then age 16, had
different vacation dates this year), often with friends or a cousin
in tow, to destinations that have also included Los Angeles, Las
Vegas, Paris and the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   I always dread these trips and they always turn out great. They
have produced some bad sunburns and sore feet but, amazingly, not
even a small argument. With school out and many two-career couples
trying to plan vacations that will appeal to teen-agers, it helps
to have a clear-headed view of what works and what doesn't. Today's
sophisticated children are used to the stimulation of big cities
(we live outside Washington, and my nephew, who sometimes travels
with us, lives in New York). And many have travel opportunities
that adults would envy. Yes, they are privileged, but they are
still teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that I'm about to travel alone with a gaggle of kids,
I've had friends look at me with pity and share their favorite ``I
took the trip from hormonal hell'' horror story. For example, a
colleague told me about arriving with her 14-year-old daughter at
the King David Hotel in Jerusalem with a fabulous swimming pool.
When she suggested a swim, her daughter responded that she
preferred to retire to her room alone and order room service pizza.
</P>
<P>
   My nephew, now 21, sulked through much of a family drive through
the Irish countryside two years ago and confided to me afterward
that he rated a vacation in direct relation to the amount of time
he was cooped up in a car with his parents. That's a cautionary
note for parents who are planning to pile the teen-agers into the
SUV this summer for a cross-country trek or a camping trip.
</P>
<P>
   I can empathize. At 16, on my first trip to Europe, I pretended
to sleep during a car trip through the Alps because I wanted to
punish my parents for relentlessly pressuring me to register my
delight at every sight.
</P>
<P>
   So I began traveling with my two teen-age children with a proper
sense of trepidation. But over the years, I've learned that one key
to success is carefully mixing what they want to do with what you
want to do.
</P>
<P>
   In London, that meant Tower of London, yes. (Like Queen
Elizabeth I, teen-agers like gory stuff and outsized diamonds.)
British Museum, no. British war rooms, yes. (They've seen enough
World War II movies to make Whitehall interesting.) Parliament, no.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon, we all got dressed up for high tea at Brown's
Hotel. (The boys' version of fancy dress for tea was nice sweaters,
no dirty sneakers.) They loved the ritual of pouring the tea
through a strainer and pronounced the lumps, Britain's far more
interesting version of sugar cubes, ``awesome.'' Will, a piano
player himself, enjoyed the Gershwin and Porter tunes played by the
hotel's pianist.
</P>
<P>
   I got to go antiquing, in a manner of speaking, when Will took
me vinyl shopping on Camden High Street and I found myself thumbing
through long out-of-print '60s albums at Rhythm Records. Greeting
the visages of old friends like Peter Noone (Herman of Herman's
Hermits) and Petula Clark (of ``Downtown'' fame), I felt as if I
were back on Carnaby Street during my first trip to London in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   That, essentially, is the joy of traveling with kids this age.
It can re-establish the connections between your life and that of
your teen-agers, who often do their best to shut out their parents.
That is the guiding spirit for the road rules I've developed.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
