<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5071 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     07-17 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NATHAN MOST, CREATOR OF EXCHANGE-TRADED FUNDS, STILL A VISIONARY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY KATHLEEN PENDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Most of Hillsborough got his start trading safflower
seeds and coconut oil futures.
</P>
<P>
   He later developed a product that helped save the American Stock
Exchange from oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Today he's in the middle of a mutual fund revolution.
</P>
<P>
   And he's only 86.
</P>
<P>
   Most is the originator of the exchange-traded fund _ a low-cost
mutual fund that tracks an index and trades throughout the day on a
stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He developed the first ETFs, called Spiders, at the American
Stock Exchange. Today, he's a consultant with San Francisco's
Barclays Global Investors, which has introduced 45 ETFs called
iShares and will launch 12 more this month.
</P>
<P>
   ETFs already have more than $47 billion in assets, and giant
Vanguard Group plans to introduce a line of them, called Vipers,
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most says he probably wouldn't have come up with exchange-traded
funds were it not for his background in commodities trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Most worked for Pacific Vegetable Oil in San
Francisco as vice president of finance and head of safflower seed
trading.
</P>
<P>
   When that company was liquidated, he went to the Pacific
Commodities Exchange, where the main product was coconut oil
futures. A worldwide drought in 1974 made millionaires out of his
traders, but when the rains came, the market reversed itself and
half of his traders went bust.
</P>
<P>
   After the exchange was shut down in 1976, Most joined the newly
created Commodities Futures Trading Commission in Washington, D.C.,
as technical assistant to the chairman. In 1977, he moved to the
American Stock Exchange in New York, where he eventually headed up
new product development.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, the Amex was losing stock listings and Most
was casting around for ideas to make up for dwindling volume on the
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He set his sights on open-end mutual funds that track the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which were among the biggest-volume
securities not traded on an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end mutual funds had already been trading on stock
exchanges for many years but have a nasty habit of trading above or
below the true value of their stock holdings. This makes them
riskier, and more complicated, than regular, open-end mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Open-end funds are always sold and redeemed at net asset value.
This price, known as NAV, is calculated by adding the value of all
the stocks in the fund, based on their closing prices, and dividing
by the number of fund shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, for some people, is that open-end funds are priced
only once a day, at the close of trading, so investors can't buy or
sell at intra-day prices. Some index funds, including many of
Vanguard's, won't even let most shareholders trade by phone or
mouse _ they have to send written orders via snail mail.
</P>
<P>
   Most figured there might be a market for an S&AMP;P index fund that
investors could trade throughout the day. But there were two big
problems.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there was nothing in the Investment Company Act of
1940, which regulates mutual funds, that allowed them. However, a
provision in the act allowed exceptions if they were in the
``public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us three years to get exemptions to the 1940 Act,'' he
says. ``We ended up getting exemptions from almost (all the
provisions) of the act.''
</P>
<P>
   The second challenge was devising a mechanism to keep the fund
trading at or very close to net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was a ``creation unit.'' This is a large basket of
stocks that mimic the index the fund tracks. Think of it as a
mini-index fund with $5 million to $10 million worth of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Large institutions _ such as Morgan Stanley Dean Witter or
Salomon Smith Barney _ can assemble a creation unit and exchange it
for shares in the ETF. For each creation unit, institutions get
50,000 retail shares, which they can sell to individual investors.
When they want out of the fund, they turn in retail shares and get
creation units back.
</P>
<P>
   Once the ETF shares begin trading on a stock exchange,
institutions help keep their price at NAV through an investment
strategy known as ``arbitrage.'' This involves simultaneously
buying and selling related securities to lock in a profit.
</P>
<P>
   If the price of the ETF and the price of the underlying stocks
drifts apart, arbitrageurs will buy retail shares and redeem
creation units, or buy creation units and redeem retail shares,
until the two prices come back into line.
</P>
<P>
   ETFs are very cheap to run because the fund deals only with a
few large institutions that trade in creation units. Everyone else
buys and sells ETF shares just as they would any stock, through a
brokerage firm. A regular mutual fund deals with its customers
directly, which is far more costly.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1993, the Amex introduced its first ETF, managed by
State Street Bank. Shares in the fund are called S&AMP;P 500 Depositary
Receipts, or Spiders for short.
</P>
<P>
   Most says it took about two years for Spiders to catch on, but
once they did, other ETFs followed.
</P>
<P>
   The Amex added Spiders based on the S&AMP;P 400 midcap index and
various sector indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Most helped Morgan Stanley create 17 ETFs tied to foreign stock
indexes called the World Equity Benchmark Series, or WEBS.
Recently, Barclays Global Investors took over WEBS and renamed it
iShares.
</P>
<P>
   Other ETFs, which also trade on the Amex, include the Diamonds,
based on the Dow Jones industrial average and the wildly popular
Nasdaq-100 Trust, better known by its ticker symbol QQQ or
``Cubes.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, ETFs (including iShares) account for more than half of
the trading volume on the Amex.
</P>
<P>
   The original S&AMP;P 500 Spider is the largest. With $22 billion in
assets, it accounts for almost half of all ETF assets combined.
</P>
<P>
   But the most active is the volatile Nasdaq 100, managed by the
Bank of New York. Its average daily trading volume is $16.8
billion, about 53 percent of all ETF trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   Most says ETFs ``pretty near'' rescued the Amex, ``but they
don't like to admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Weber, Amex senior vice president of new product
development, would only say that ETFs ``have been growing extremely
well and are clearly an important part of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Most retired from the Amex in 1996 and moved back to
Hillsborough. But he soon tired of household chores and contacted
the Pacific Exchange in San Francisco about setting up a
technology-oriented ETF.
</P>
<P>
   That never happened, but Most discovered that Barclay's Global
Investors wanted to get into ETFs in a big way. BGI is the nation's
second-biggest money manager, ``but whoever heard of them?'' he
asks. Because BGI deals mainly with institutions, it has little
retail name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   BGI chief executive Patricia Dunn saw ETFs as a way to play the
``democratization'' of the markets. ``More and more, it's
individuals, instead of institutions, that control investment
assets,'' she says. But ``moving full scale into the retail market
was not feasible for us. The neat thing about iShares and ETFs is
that they provide a really leveraged way to approach individual
investors and their financial advisers _ and one that we could
afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn assigned BGI executive Lee Kranefuss to head an ETF
business and hired Most as consultant. Most was also named chairman
and president of the iShares Trust.
</P>
<P>
   BGI is promoting iShares with a $12 million print and television
advertising campaign. Since the first ones were introduced in May,
iShares (excluding the rebranded WEBS) has attracted $2.3 billion
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Most says ETFs would have displaced mutual funds long ago ``if
there had been the computing power we have today. Now that we have
the computing power to buy the basket (of stocks) with a single
command, I think these (ETFs) will replace closed-end funds first
and then we will be hitting the mutual funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that can happen, there's one more big problem that must
be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ETFs must publish a list of its holdings each day, so
institutions know how to assemble the creation units.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a problem for index funds, because they're tracking
well-known portfolios of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be a problem for actively managed funds. Most of
these funds don't even like disclosing their portfolios twice a
year, as required by law, much less every day.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on its size, it might take days, weeks or even months
for a mutual fund to build, or dispose of, a position in a
company's stock. Most active-fund managers fear that if everyone
knows what they're doing, other investors will jump in ahead of
them, making the fund's trades less profitable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why all ETFs, so far, are index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most says he's working on a way to create ETFs for actively
managed funds, but he won't disclose any details.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Tomorrow: The pros and cons of investing in ETFs. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
