<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-TEENS-2NDTAKE-     07-17 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEENS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: I've developed.  
RULES OF THE ROAD
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BE SPONTANEOUS. If you have your heart set on your
teen-agers' seeing every painting in the Louvre, you are in for mal
de mer. In Paris, my daughter, Cornelia, then 15, and her cousin
Ted, 14, inhaled the Louvre one evening in less than two hours.
They were more interested in the museum shop than the museum. I
didn't push.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Internecine warfare often begins when you are determined that
kids see and take in all the classic sights. Instead, give them
just a taste and hope that it will inspire them for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   2. THINK KITSCHY. Last year, Cornelia, Will and Ted lobbied hard
to go to Atlantis in Nassau. They'd seen Atlantis' many television
commercials and loved the look of this kitschy resort, best
described as a combination of Disney World and Las Vegas built on a
fabulous beach. Actually, two beaches _ a real and a fake.
</P>
<P>
   I would have much preferred a quieter place, but the three kids
loved the elaborate water slides, the bustle of the giant hotel and
the casino, where they courted danger and got thrills from trying
to pump coins into the slot machines and ogling Michael Jordan, who
was at the resort with his kids and hit the gaming tables at night.
(When the three tried to use the slots, they were nearly always
chased away by the pleasant but firm hotel staff, since anyone
gambling must be at least 21.)
</P>
<P>
   AAtlantis turned out to be a great place for real talks. Every
afternoon, I persuaded one of the kids to take a long beach walk,
which gave me a chance to catch up on what each of them was up to.
</P>
<P>
   Tackiness ruled in 1997, when the kids chose Las Vegas as our
destination. My two kids each took a friend, whose parents chipped
in to cover their expenses. They loved the kitsch, from the fake
pyramids at the Luxor to the mock Coney Island of New York, New
York. While the amusement park at the MGM Grand occupied an
afternoon, they also enjoyed an old-fashioned stage show with the
requisite white-suited and sequinned Elvis impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   I got into the flashy spirit of things by renting a stretch limo
(white with purple-tinted windows) for a 45-minute ride down the
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   3. DON'T CHANGE THE SLEEP CYCLE. Teen-agers sleep an average of
20 out of 24 hours, or so it seems on vacation. Don't plan early
excursions. In Paris with Cornelia and Ted in 1998, I let them
sleep until noon. I got up early, got coffee and a croissant at a
patisserie near our Left Bank hotel, and went for walks and museum
visits on my own, or with my sister, who joined us.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age metabolism got jump-started later, and they were in
a better mood to see Notre Dame and the Eiffel Tower. They were
enthusiastic about Paris night life, including eating late in nice
restaurants. Although they complained a bit about all the walking,
our outings were liberally sprinkled with shopping in trendy
boutiques like Agnes B. Ted, a gifted artist, liked drawing the
gargoyles at Notre Dame.,
</P>
<P>
   4. DON'T BOOK EXPENSIVE SIGHTSEEING EXPEDITIONS. I can't stand
the idea of missing a famous landmark if it's in striking distance
so, in Las Vegas, the Grand Canyon beckoned. The kids were game,
and I spent $600 chartering a plane to fly us over the majestic
site. On the flight, air turbulence made one of the kids sick and
two others fell asleep; we would have been a lot happier spending
the afternoon by the pool.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the kids didn't recognize enough of the names of
the old-time stars like Rita Hayworth and Clark Gable to make a
slow ``Homes of the Stars'' bus tour worth an entire afternoon. But
they loved the footprints at Mann's Chinese Theater.
</P>
<P>
   5. BUNK ALONE (IF BUDGET PERMITS). A vacation is not the optimum
time to instill order.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris and Las Vegas, I shared a room with my daughter and her
friend. Within a day, the floor was covered in dense layers of
clothes, which made me crabby. Not having to keep her room neat was
part of the point of a vacation, Cornelia pointed out, something I
had agreed to in a weaker moment. At Atlantis, where I shared a
room with a friend from home, we were all much happier.
</P>
<P>
   After supervising one eve-of-departure clean-up by the kids, I
left a generous tip for the hotel maid to make up for their mess.
</P>
<P>
   With two 15-year-old males hovering between boyhood and manhood
as my London mates, the young gentlemen, as the staff referred to
them, had one minor mishap in the room they shared (mine was on
another floor). They called me in a panic one night at 11, claiming
to have ``mistakenly'' ordered an X-rated movie from the pay movie
selections. (After selecting the movie, they probably realized
their choice might appear on my bill.) I told them not to worry.
Flexibility is good.
</P>
<P>
   6. A POOL RULES. In Los Angeles, I thought the kids would get a
kick out of a cool Art Deco hotel in Santa Monica that I had always
liked, the Shangri-La. I was wrong. Their interest in architecture
was limited to the hotel's lack of a pool. I conceded defeat and
checked us into a Holiday Inn a few blocks away, where our bland
room was poolside. The kids were thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   In London, where my indulgence to myself was splurging on a
lovely hotel, One Aldwych, my first glimpse of the boys came late
in the morning, when they would meet me for a workout in the hotel
gym. Then we'd all go for a swim in the blue-tiled pool, which
played music underwater. The boys thought the pool was ``phat.''
</P>
<P>
   7. LOOSEN THE LEASH. It's important to find safe opportunities
to let teen-agers go off by themselves. Will and and his friend
Wyatt love the theater. The three of us went to two plays, then I
let them have a night to themselves. I went to dinner with a friend
living in London and they went to ``The Lion King'' and had dinner
at Orso, a West End restaurant. They had a midnight curfew, which
they dutifully observed.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, while my sister and I attended a classical music
concert, my daughter and her cousin went to a movie on the
Champs-Elysees. They loved the independence and the daring sense of
exploring on their own.
</P>
<P>
   8. GET A SWEET CAR. A convertible may cost extra, but if you are
driving a lot, teen-agers will tolerate the travel if you have a
car they like. A CD player can overcome a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE MORE, THE MERRIER. Teen-agers are pack animals. Let them
bring friends. Often, other parents are thrilled when their
children get an invitation to travel and they expect to help defray
the cost. Having pals along makes any trip more fun and encourages
better, more considerate behavior. Above all, these trips have
reminded me how much fun it can be to hang out with teen-agers.
Instead of insisting they be little adults, you can try being a big
kid; at least, that's my approach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
