<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EFAX--DISASTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFAX INVESTORS  
 VICTIMIZED BY  
 WOEFUL TIMING
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The news keeps getting worse for eFax investors.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Jfax of Hollywood agreed to buy eFax, a free Internet
faxing service based in Menlo Park, for $74 million, a paltry sum
compared with what similar firms fetched before the Nasdaq swooned
in April and dot-coms fell out of favor. Rival Onebox.com in San
Mateo, for instance, sold for $787 million in February.
</P>
<P>
   But $74 million looks like a small fortune compared with the
final price, after executives changed the terms of the deal last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Under the final pact, announced Friday, Jfax will hand over just
13 million shares _ instead of the 18.5 million originally agreed
on. That values the deal at about $26 million based on Monday's
stock prices. Jfax closed at $2.03 yesterday, up 14 cents.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal for eFax investors gets worse: More than half the
Jfax shares have been earmarked for hedge fund investors with
preferred stock and a technology company that did work for eFax.
Citadel Investment Group will claim 7.2 million shares. Integrated
Global Concepts, the technology firm, will get 2 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves just 3.8 million shares _ or $8 million _ for most
eFax investors. Under the deal, each share of eFax translates into
0.281 share of Jfax, or 57 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the new deal was announced, eFax shares were trading
at $1.03. So instead of a premium, eFax investors will actually
receive only half the market value for their shares. Efax closed at
72 cents a share yesterday, down 95 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lousy deal,'' one investor fumed on an Internet chat
board.
</P>
<P>
   But eFax executives said it was the best option on the table.
The company was running low on cash, so it had to borrow $5 million
from Jfax to keep the company going until the deal closed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, since the deal was announced, eFax stock has fallen
roughly twice as much as Jfax. Executives said they needed to
adjust the terms of the deal to take into account the shifting
market values.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Kenck, the firm's chief financial officer, said he
sympathizes with investors. Kenck said he bought about 3,600 shares
_ mostly for $11 to $12 per share. And his stock options typically
have a strike price in the double-digits _ making them worthless at
the current values.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
