r f BC-POWER--BARGE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-17 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER--BARGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 READY OR NOT, POWER BARGE HEADED FOR BAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; A floating power plant has departed from its
berth in Texas and is expected to arrive in the Bay Area early next
month as an emergency stopgap to prevent further power failures,
PG&AMP;E Corp. said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, it remains unclear whether necessary permits and
authorization can be obtained for the 95-megawatt floating plant to
be brought into service this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If not, PG&AMP;E may be forced to moor its jet-turbine-equipped
barge in the bay until next year, absorbing any related costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power crunch isn't going to go away,'' said Greg Pruett, a
spokesman for the company. ``It's not going to be solved
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The barge, purchased by PG&AMP;E last month, was towed from its
berth in Freeport, Texas, on Sunday and is expected to reach the
Panama Canal by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   It is tentatively slated to reach the Bay Area by August 8 or 9.
</P>
<P>
   Protests are already being planned. Greenaction, a San Francisco
environmental group, said it will monitor the barge's progress and
will hold a rally when it arrives, to oppose use of a floating
power plant in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outdated, polluting technology,'' said Bradley Angel, the
group's executive director. ``And the plant would be used only on
the days when air quality would be worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The four turbine engines atop the barge run on jet fuel and have
not been upgraded to meet tighter emission standards since the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has said that, without additional electricity-generating
resources, Bay Area homes and businesses may face a replay of the
recent ``rolling blackouts'' that cut off power to 35,000 customers
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Thaeker, manager for reliability controls with the
California Independent System Operator, the nonprofit agency that
oversees statewide electricity flow, said PG&AMP;E is essentially
rolling the dice that it will receive approval to operate the
floating plant by the time it arrives in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've turned around on this thing there's been a
hurdle we hadn't expected,'' he said. ``We still have a lot of work
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E is hoping to moor the barge offshore from a substation near
Hunters Point, San Francisco International Airport or Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   Thaeker said it will cost as much as $15 million to transport
and temporarily deploy the barge in the Bay Area _ a cost that
ultimately will be passed along to PG&AMP;E ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
