<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-FRAY-NYT     07-17 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-FRAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY NO CHARGE IS UNANSWERED BY MRS. CLINTON'S SENATE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-CLINTON) 
By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The answer to the question of whether Hillary Rodham
Clinton ever made the anti-Semitic slur attributed to her by two
long-time enemies from Arkansas politics may forever be lost to
time and the conflicting accounts of what actually went on the
night that Bill Clinton lost his first race for Congress in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But that Mrs. Clinton felt compelled, at the near-unanimous
urging of her senior advisers, to call reporters to her home on a
Sunday afternoon to explicitly deny the charges, and that President
Clinton took a break from Middle East negotiations to telephone a
Daily News editor to back up his wife, reflects more than passing
concern over the latest storm to pass over Mrs. Clinton's campaign.
Their actions suggest the need to address persistent doubts about
her among Jewish voters _ which her advisers acknowledged Monday _
and, more fundamentally, lingering doubts about her trustworthiness
across the electoral spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For most public figures, a charge of the sort raised _ that she
made an obscenity-laden anti-Semitic remark to Clinton's campaign
manager 26 years ago _ might have sunk out of sight. It is an old
anecdote coming out a little more than three months before an
election. It is made by two people with a history of enmity toward
the Clintons, and repeated by a third person who said he overheard
the conversation from outside the room.
</P>
<P>
   The book where the incident was first recounted, ``State of A
Union: Inside the Complex Marriage of Bill and Hillary Clinton,''
is written by a former reporter for The National Enquirer, Jerry
Oppenheimer, as Mrs. Clinton's aides have been quick to note in an
attempt to question its credibility. The alleged recipient of the
anti-Semitic slur is Baptist, though he says his paternal
great-grandmother is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton and her campaign team found themselves
answering questions about it for the fourth day Monday, evidence
that the charge was not being dismissed as implausible. And Rep.
Rick Lazio, her Republican opponent who had stepped back when the
allegations first emerged, addressed the issue Monday in what his
aides said would be a continuing attempt to use it to raise
questions about Mrs. Clinton's honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been three people that have made what I think is a
serious allegation,'' Lazio said outside a school in Harlem. ``Mrs.
Clinton has denied that allegation. I don't know who to believe. I
don't if New Yorkers know who to believe. And therein lies a good
deal of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's senior campaign consultant, Mike Murphy, said, ``I have
no doubt now that trust is becoming the major issue of the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advisers reacted quickly to this latest allegation precisely
because her credibility has been challenged so regularly over the
past eight years, and she could not afford, at this point in her
campaign, another episode that raised questions about her
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   The president called an editor of the Daily News on his own
accord on Sunday, according to the first lady's advisers, who
suggested Monday that presidential intervention might not have been
called for. They would not speculate as to why Clinton made the
call.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to the first lady, Mrs. Clinton and her
advisers made a deliberate calculation to rebut the story after
determining that it had the potential to turn into a brushfire.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came Sunday in a late-morning telephone conference
call between Mrs. Clinton and her aides, after they watched Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi declare on ``Fox News
Sunday'' that Lazio was getting substantial support from Jewish
voters in New York, ``and I think that's one of the reasons why
Hillary is uttering these anti-Semitic comments, if in fact she
is.''
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, the story had appeared on the Drudge Report on the
Internet, in The New York Post and in The Daily News, but Mrs.
Clinton's advisers figured that it was only a matter of time before
it spilled over into other newspapers, The Associated Press and
local television news. They agreed that Mrs. Clinton needed to
personally rebut a charge that was already stirring concern among
some of her Jewish supporters, and seemed not to be going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept here is, let's not have any whispering
campaigns,'' one of Mrs. Clinton's senior advisers said Monday.
``Let's get the truth out. Let's not allow false information
promoted by a book to be used in a whispering campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mrs. Clinton's associates had worried that such a quick
and heated reaction would only draw additional attention to the
story. And Murphy suggested Monday night that the mere fact of a
president interrupting Middle East negotiations to call a newspaper
editor gave new life to a story that might have been on the
decline.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, for all their concern, reaction among Jewish
leaders has been relatively mild. Assemblyman Dov Hikind, the
Brooklyn Democrat who represents an Orthodox neighborhood, said
Monday that the incident raised ``the whole issue of credibility in
terms of things that Hillary Clinton says and does.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hikind, who has been wary of Mrs. Clinton's views on Israel,
given her support for a Palestinian state, went out of his way to
say he did not consider her anti-Semitic. A number of Jewish
organizations, including the Anti-Defamation League and the
American Jewish Committee, issued statements supporting Mrs.
Clinton Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Mrs. Clinton looked momentarily startled when told
what Lazio had said about her credibility, but then said: ``I'm not
going to respond to that. I said yesterday that it was untrue, it
did not happen and I think it's regrettable that there is an
accusation of that banality that is made.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of her most long-term advisers, James Carville, said
Monday that given the Clintons' history in politics, and voters'
fascination and polarized views of them, he did not believe this
would go away any time soon. ``My counsel to them is that this is
only the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
