<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5078 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BOOKS-RHAPSODY18-COX     07-17 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RHAPSODY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Showgirls' author Eszterhas latest offering outrageous
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Parents usually depend on their children for the
truth. Screenwriting wild man Joe Eszterhas is no exception.
Despite making adults-only films such as ``Showgirls'' and ``Basic
Instinct,'' he styles himself a family man. He quotes his
25-year-old son's reaction to ``American Rhapsody,'' the outrageous
comic novel that hit bookstores July 18:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please get some very heavy security when you go on the book
tour, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpted in the current issue of Talk magazine, ``American
Rhapsody'' is an entertaining but thoroughly salacious read that's
part journalistic tale, part racy fiction and likely to rile a lot
of important people and their fans. It uses all real names (as well
as a few derogatory nicknames) but not all real events. Just some _
like Monica and Bill and the blue dress. With chapter titles such
as ``Ross Perot on Drugs,'' ``John Wayne McCain Chickens Out,''
``Better Than a Lava Lamp,'' (about New Age guru Jean Houston),
``Hillary Loves Eleanor,'' ``George W. Bush Defines Himself'' and
the final, ``Willard Comes Clean,'' (written from the point of view
of the president's body part that got him in trouble), the book
provides equal opportunities to rile readers of every political
persuasion. Along the way, the author also dishes dirt on Hollywood
power players such as David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas, long one of Hollywood's highest paid screenwriters
with 35 films to his credit, has had less success in that area
since his 1995 film ``Showgirls,'' set in the world of Las Vegas
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   He works to put a pos-- tive spin on his novel, suggesting it
provides a breath of fresh air. ``The book is so revolutionary in
how it looks at political figures, it's impossible to say how
they'll respond,'' he says by phone from Malibu, Calif. ``No one's
on a pedestal in this book.'' Least of all, the man he calls ``the
first rock and roll president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Two who come out a little better than the rest are Laura Bush
and Jane Fonda _ an odd twosome _ but even they do not escape
unscathed. Sharon Stone, on the other hand _ who starred in ``Basic
Instinct'' _ gets trashed, though her official response to the book
has been to compliment Eszterhas on his knack for comedy. It's
difficult to believe a usually conservative house such as Alfred A.
Knopf published ``American Rhapsody,'' but they're solidly behind
it with a whopping first printing of 200,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas, 56, a former Rolling Stone writer, began the book
three years ago during a midlife crisis and a troubled screen
career that drove him to Maui to write. The timing coincided with
the president's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip of the whole impeachment process had a feel that was
at times rhapsodic,'' Eszterhas said. ``Because it became
entertainment and theater, it became an absolute guilty pleasure
for a lot of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that after writing screenplays for 25 years he's seeing
a link between politics becoming entertainment and entertainment
becoming politics. ``The process by which a president is made
inaccessible to the public is the same process by which a movie
star is made inaccessible to the public,'' he said. In the book, he
facetiously raises the prospect that in the future Clinton could
star in ``Basic Instinct 3'' with Stone. ``But in my mind, he's
much more of a rock and roll star,'' Eszterhas said. ``Men of our
generation really wanted to be rock and roll stars. Some of us have
grown up and know in our hearts we are not. But Bill Clinton hasn't
gone through that process. He really is in his own head, I'm
convinced, Mick Jagger on Chef Boyardee sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas dodges a question about whether there's any limit to
what he'll say about someone _ for in this book he's hinted that
several were cocaine users, others anti-Semitic, still others
outright amoral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiction sometimes illuminates truth more than fact does,'' he
says. Inserted in the body of the novel are monologue chapters
printed in boldface, to indicate fiction, he says. But other
chapters _ not in boldface, so presumably nonfiction _ contain
descriptions of events Eszterhas could only have imagined. Despite
his research, there's no bibliography. With this book, Eszterhas
hasn't evolved beyond what Edmund Morris attempted in ``Dutch,''
last year's controversial fictionalized biography of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd mind if someone fictionalized his life in this
way, Eszterhas said it had been done to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Showgirls,' the Philadelphia Inquirer hired a
psychiatrist who, based on the few things written about my
upbringing, made all these psychosexual judgments about me. It's
been done to me. I survived. I thought some of the psychologist's
opinions were pretty off-the-wall. I certainly grant the
possibility Kenneth Starr might think I'm pretty off-the-wall in
describing his lust for Gennifer Flowers,'' he laughs. ``There is
that possibility,'' he muses, ``but I'll deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas writes (boldface) monologues for Al Gorf (sic),
McCain, Bob Dole and George W. The one he's proudest of is the
fictional monologue he wrote for Hillary Clinton, in which she
explains, ``... I plead guilty to a quest for ... power _ in the
name of children, women, black people, gay people, the elderly, the
disabled, the ill. ... That is worth the humiliation and pain and
inner destruction I've sentenced myself to.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls writing her thoughts his biggest act of literary
conceit and says, sadly, he's heard the White House is furious
about the book.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas has no plans to turn his book into a movie but does
see it as a possibility for some quirky, independent director or
producer. Meanwhile, he has two movies now being cast _ a dark
comedy, ``Male Pattern Baldness,'' with Paramount Pictures, and a
thriller, ``The Trap,'' at Synergy. He plays down any notion
Hollywood is angry with him, saying the book party for him drew 300
heavy hitters from the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Anne Morris at amorris(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
