<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5079 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-TOWNWATER18-COX     07-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNWATER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Texas town faces prospect of running out of water as sole
source evaporates
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THROCKMORTON, Texas _ After three years of drought, this North
Texas town's prayers for rain have gone unanswered, and now it's
time to do something.
</P>
<P>
   Without a saving storm, Throckmorton's 1,036 residents will be
out of water in three months when their sole source, Lake
Throckmorton, goes dry. And Monday, nearly 100 townspeople and
volunteers from as far away as New Jersey and Chicago began
building a 14-mile pipeline to bring water from a neighboring
community.
</P>
<P>
   An $800,000 state grant will pay for the pipe and a pumping
station, but the town doesn't have the money to rent equipment and
pay workers. So they're planning to do it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of locals have signed up to build their own lifeline in
the summer heat, and others have volunteered to take meals to the
workers or offer a spare bed for out-of-town volunteers. Local
businesses and surrounding towns have offered to lend backhoes and
other digging equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Throckmorton is treating every remaining drop of
water as a gift. The town has banned watering lawns, washing cars
and filling swimming pools and has urged residents to conserve
water any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad situation _ it really is,'' said Darlene Petty, a
bookkeeper at First National Bank in Throckmorton who drives to
Abilene or Wichita Falls to wash her car. ``You're real worried
that you're going to run out of water completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Drought has forced 129 Texas cities to launch water conservation
measures, but Throckmorton _ a farming and ranching community that
has produced former Dallas Cowboy star Bob Lilly and some dominant
football teams _ is the only one in imminent danger of running out
of water.
</P>
<P>
   The town is coping in creative ways. A local oil company planted
a 12,600-gallon water tank on its property to keep its lawn and
shrubs alive with trucked-in water. The city has hauled water from
Woodson, 10 miles to the south, to fill the town's only public
pool.
</P>
<P>
   A local church is treating its baptismal water with chlorine for
repeated use. One local woman uses gray water from her family's
washing machine to water the back yard. Billy Fowler, 65, said he
waters his two rows of okra plants with used bath water.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Cadillac grill with her two sons, Kathy Bailes
debated the ethics of washing her sons' four show goats before a
livestock show in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, we wouldn't think anything about it, but now ... ``
said Bailes, whose husband, Jeff, is on the City Council. ``We're
going to have to get permission from the city to wash them, or
we'll have to take them somewhere else, I guess, because we can't
show them dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really makes you think about things that you take for
granted,'' Bailes said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has ever seen the lake go completely dry, not even during
the infamous drought of the 1950s. But now the summer heat and
North Texas wind are relentlessly evaporating what's left of the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Days like today _ 101 degrees with 20 mile per hour wind _
we're going to lose at least three-quarters of an inch of water
(from the lake),'' said Steve Bowlin, Throckmorton's director of
public works and the organizer of the pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
   The town has rallied in the face of its most serious crisis.
Water use is down by two-thirds from three years ago, Bowlin said.
He gets calls when someone sees a neighbor wasting water, but so
far he has written only four warning letters, and no one has been
fined for violating the emergency rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we know which way to go, we're commencing to get to
work, and we're laying pipe,'' Bowlin said. But time is running
out. Lake Throckmorton is at 13 percent of capacity, 14 feet below
its normal level. The latest study estimated the town has 90 days
before the lake runs out of drinkable water.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush declared the county a disaster area last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The lake, which depends on runoff from rains, began dropping
during the 1998 drought that gripped Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When last year's rains missed Throckmorton County, Bowlin began
talking to surrounding communities about buying water for his
thirsty town.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin began negotiating with Albany, 32 miles away, before
focusing on Graham, which has a reservoir and sells water to a
water supply company whose lines end 14 miles northeast of
Throckmorton. The Graham City Council voted last week to sell the
water to Throckmorton.
</P>
<P>
   When the rains come back and the lake fills again, Bowlin said,
the pipeline will provide a permanent backup water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The town is still looking for more equipment to dig the trenches
and more bodies to assemble the pipe segments, Bowlin said. He
hopes they can finish the pipeline in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for anybody to do it for us; we're just
asking for a little help,'' Bowlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Settled by ranchers and farmers who cleared the mesquite and
prickly pear from the rocky, reddish soil, Throckmorton isn't used
to depending on outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The population has remained essentially the same for a century,
and even in an era when many small towns have seen their downtowns
wither away, Throckmorton's main strip still has a core of local
businesses: a saddle shop, a pharmacy, the Cow Country Motel, a
restaurant, two banks, a couple of churches, gas stations and a
senior citizens' center.
</P>
<P>
   People still watch out for each other's children here. They know
whose birthday is coming up and what kind of icing they like on
their cake. They donate faithfully to send local girls to
cheerleader camp. They toss horseshoes and run three-legged races
during the summer Pioneer Days festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say we're stuck in the '40s and '50s, and we
are, and that's not a bad thing,'' said Bowlin, who moved here from
Yoakum a few years ago with his wife and four children. ``This is
neighbor helping neighbor out here.''
</P>
<P>
   And something about that has struck a chord with strangers. Last
week, a national network did a story on Throckmorton's plight, and
Bowlin's phone began lighting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got people calling from all over the United States who
want to come to Throckmorton, Texas, to help lay this pipeline,''
he said. ``It is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Dave Harmon at dharmon(at)statesman.com or
445-3645.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
