<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5083 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-JERUSALEM-HOTE     07-17 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JERUSALEM-HOTELS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTELS IN JERUSALEM: FROM ORIENTALIST FANTASY TO DIPLOMATS' DIGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: 3rd take is a 400-word information box.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Israel's independence day this May, the electricity in our
Jerusalem apartment suddenly blew out. We knew the holiday would
make it impossible to get an electrician until the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed like a good time to check out the city's new
hotels, the 300-room Olive Tree and the 400-room Novotel, part of a
planned four-hotel complex near the venerable American Colony Hotel
in East Jerusalem. Our children, Emma and Adam, ages 6 and 4, were
out of school anyway, and both hotels featured swimming pools and
moderate rates, according to their advance publicity. My wife,
Debbie Sontag, chief of the Jerusalem bureau of The New York Times,
was to join us later. At the Olive Tree, run by the small local
Royal Plaza chain, the three of us were greeted warmly by the front
desk staff, who were outfitted in Ottomanesque finery. The kids
particularly liked the mirror-spangled brimless caps. The Olive
Tree opened late last year, just in time for the anticipated
millennial tourist boom here. Aimed mainly at Christian tour
groups, it is a Holy Land theme inn, constructed around an ancient
olive tree said to have marked a traditional stopping place for
pilgrims to Jerusalem's Old City. The Damascus Gate is just 15
minutes by foot, along a route that passes the Garden Tomb _ a
tranquil spot that Victorian archaeologists insisted was Jesus'
true burial place _ and a brace of souvenir shops, the best of them
being the Armenian-run Palestinian Pottery.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rates were reasonable by Jerusalem standards: $180 for a
double (including a kosher buffet breakfast, a feature of most
Israeli hotels). I knew from a previous quick look around that the
rooms were clean and well appointed, if a bit small and spartan.
But none were available. The children's disappointment was tempered
by the news that the indoor pool area was still under construction.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So we walked next door to the gleaming new Novotel. An
airport-terminal-like lobby and dining room seemed utterly
unpopulated. There was no one at the front desk, and, aside from a
few kitchen workers in the middle distance, no visible hotel
employees at all.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following signs, the kids quickly discovered the small outdoor
pool, but the shaded and unheated water was pronounced too frigid.
When we returned to the lobby, a pleasant young woman at the
reception desk explained that the hotel had not yet published a
rate list. Rooms were available, but we could not be told the cost
until the next day, when the off-site reservations office, closed
on holidays, could be consulted by telephone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her guess, though, was about $250 for a couple and two children,
who could share a pull-out couch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. That wasn't much different from the gracious and tasteful
American Colony Hotel, a short stroll away, which I had originally
ruled out for economy's sake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A cloistered compound developed from a 19th-century pasha's
manse, the American Colony boasts some of the most pleasing public
spaces in Jerusalem: an open dining courtyard with burbling
fountain, a luxuriant ``summer bar'' garden, and _ the main
attraction for my charges _ a sheltered, grassy pool area,
including a wading pool.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Colony has, in fact, only one real competitor,
though it is utterly different in style and scale: the King David,
the lodging of choice for state visitors to Israeli West Jerusalem
and high-end tour groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were welcomed by the courtly porter, George Qumssiyah, who
had retired after 50 years on the job only to return months later
as a part-timer. As I registered, the manager, whisking by my tired
and thirsty children, summoned a waiter to serve ``our young
guests'' two fruit-juice cocktails.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is essentially a small town, and we were hardly
anonymous visitors. A year and a half before we had stayed in the
hotel for a week, and since then, as with the other major hotels
here, my wife and I had been in and out for meals and meetings
dozens of times.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The photo ID required by hotels of local residents like
ourselves was in my case the government press card carried by all
correspondents based in Israel. So the front desk receptionist knew
from a glance at the card that I was a reporter (though not my
specific affiliation, which wouldn't have been of much interest to
them anyway). That alone entitled us to a 10 percent discount,
since the American Colony actively courts foreign journalists, who
constitute a distressingly large share of Jerusalem's business
travelers. Local residents are routinely given discounts at the
city's better hotels. An ``executive'' double room _ with the desks
and data ports that are not included in all standard rooms _ listed
for $250 a night. Children under seven (our present category) are
free . Shortly afterward we were upgraded to a third-floor suite.
They extended this courtesy, they said, because the suite happened
to be free that evening, and we were a family of four seeking one
room for one night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Room six turned out be an enormous stone-and-tile Orientalist
fantasy. Filling a strategic interior corner overlooking the leafy
courtyard, it was bathed in light from the south and west. Down an
interior flight of limestone stairs from the small entry hall were
two quilt-topped queen beds; a couple of petite antique writing
desks; an oversized armoire; and a formal sitting area with six
mosaic-inlaid straight-backed chairs, arrayed as if awaiting
relatives on a chaperoned wedding night.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the bathroom, a suite in itself, with a huge
Jacuzzi-rigged tub. A separate stone shower stall with multiple
jets. And terry-cloth robes. And slippers. And fresh fruit. We were
home.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After an afternoon swim, we had a room-service meal served
quickly and decorously: a crisp Margarita pizza ($11) for the
children, and a succulent ``Persian'' lentil soup ($7) for me _
good value by Jerusalem hotel standards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cozy Cellar Bar and grassy outdoor Summer Bar are perhaps
the best stocked and most aesthetically pleasing drinking spots in
the city, and it is all too easy to order one of the fine cognacs
or single-malt whiskeys. But inquire first. I once paid a
breathtaking $50 for an ounce and a half of Bowmore. Not that it
wasn't delicious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Comparing almost any hotel in Jerusalem to the American Colony
is inherently unfair. This is an institution, rich in history and
character. It is imbued with a sense of intimacy _ there are only
84 rooms _ not shared by any major Jerusalem hotel, upscale or
otherwise. The independently managed gift shops include the city's
best English-language bookstore. A string quartet offers regular
recitals in an airy upstairs salon. The Middle Eastern food is
excellent. Though proudly and distinctly Arab, it is a studiedly
neutral meeting zone between the city's Palestinian East and
Israeli West (as one of the area's few nonkosher luxury hotels, it
operates fully during the Jewish Sabbath, making it a popular
Friday dinner spot for secular Israelis).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, feeling that I hadn't given the Novotel a
proper chance, I returned, this time alone. The front desk could
now give rates, and the previous estimate wasn't too far off: for
my wife and me and two children the base rate would have been $227;
a standard double is $151, but children 3 or older cost an
additional $38 each. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was quickly and courteously booked into a seventh-floor room
at a single rate of $131, a bargain by Jerusalem standards. It was
an odorless, colorless, compact rectangle with a firm queen bed and
adjacent fold-out couch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was not unpleasant: the room was bright, and impressively
soundproofed. From the single large plate-glass window, I had a
sweeping view over the Old City to Mount Scopus and the Mount of
Olives. A room-length desktop featured built-in shelving, a
telephone with a data port, and a new flat-screen color television
set.
</P>
<P>
   The four of us would have fitted easily, if tightly.
Facilitating multiple occupancy, the small bathroom was separate
from the small shower room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But two months after its opening, the Novotel was not yet ready
for prime time. There was a room service button on the telephone
but no room service menu. The minibar was humming but empty. Cable
TV choices were limited to a few Israeli channels and international
news networks; there were no movies, pay-per-view or otherwise.
There was no shop on the premises for newspapers or sundries,
though one is scheduled to open this summer. A small gym was still
under construction, but has since opened. Heading for the pool for
a pre-breakfast dip, I was surprised to find it locked; the pool
area is open only from 10 a.m. until 6 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Novotel was well scrubbed, well situated, and
reasonably well run. The buffet breakfast, in a basement dining
hall, was abundant and tasty, with a good
Mitteleuropa-meets-the-Middle East array of salads and cheeses and
hummus and smoked fish. &QL; 
The Jerusalem Hilton, , which opened three years ago, has been
encroaching on the King David's official-entourage business,
especially for American delegations _ either because of
buy-America-first policies, or because one too many Secret Service
agents has seen the King David's film clip of its fire-bombed west
wing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 385-room Hilton is a short walk from both the Old City gates
and modern Jerusalem's pedestrianized center. Its cool austerity,
the hard-edged creation of the ubiquitous Moshe Safdie, Israel's
celebrated architect, is appealing to some, off-putting to others.
The basement-level commercial gallery has a convenient assortment
of trinket dealers, travel and car rental agencies, beauty parlors
and a fast-service photo shop.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pool area, stark and sunlit, with comfortable chaise
loungues and lots of fluffy towels, includes an outdoor Jacuzzi and
a large wading pool for toddlers. You can swim from the main pool
under a glass barrier directly into the small but well-equipped
gym, used by President Clinton during his recent visit (there is an
$11 daily gym fee). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are standard American chain deluxe: strong on bathroom
fixtures, short on charm, with pay-per-view movies and data ports.
At a base rate of $350 for a single, $390 for a double, this is not
bargain lodging. Add another $40 a night for rooms directly facing
the terrific view of the Old City: if you traveled any distance to
get here, you deserve to gaze on those massive floodlit walls. With
our two kids and the Hilton's no-more-than-three-humans-per-room
policy, we would require a ``family room,'' for $490. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet few customers pay the full freight. Israeli citizens, as in
almost every hotel in the country, are charged 25 to 50 percent
less than foreign tourists. Package tours and other regular group
customers also get preferential rates. The State Department, for
example, negotiates a $230 rate for a standard single, my wife
learned when she stayed there for a couple of nights covering a
visit by Madeleine Albright last fall There was some spoiled fruit
and a mold-covered room-service dinner abandoned in her room. It
took three calls to the front desk to get it removed; rooms where
guests checked out after noon could not be adequately cleaned
before the next check-in, it was explained.
</P>
<P>
   The room itself was clean and functional, as it had been when I
stayed there a few months earlier, with a king-size bed and a good
work space, though surprisingly dim lighting. Its Old City view was
dominated by the construction site for a long-delayed retail and
office complex next door. But the bathroom, with its marble tub and
separate high-pressure shower stall, was big, brightly lighted, and
well stocked with plush towels and Ahava lotions and shampoos. Here
was some of the deluxe pampering that might be expected from the
location and price. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For true self-indulgence, right up the street is the King David,
the city's first and still its best full-service luxury hotel.
Until I stayed there, though, I wasn't convinced. There is an
off-putting air of officiousness to the place, an inevitable
byproduct of playing official host to Israel's A-list guests for
half a century. Its grand-hotel air seemed at odds with the
country's essentially informal culture. It can take half an hour to
get a cup of coffee in the ornate Baghdad Deco wood-inlaid lobby.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But to be a guest, we discovered, was to be treated cordially
and expeditiously, all the time. Which one has a right to expect:
standard rooms start at $398 double. For our family of four, the
most economical option was a studio room listing for a
heart-stopping $604 a night.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet when we stayed one night in November the 300-room hotel,
unusually, was not nearly full. Our Israeli residency as verified
again by a glance at my government photo ID card, brought the suite
down to $400 a night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then we were upgraded to a luxurious two-room ``club suite'' _
Room 338 on the southeast corner, with the unmatched King David
view of the floodlit Old City walls and the great lawn and pool
area that is the city's biggest and best-kept private green space.
The listed rate for a club suite was $840, more than twice what we
paid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Impeccably redecorated with inlaid woods and fine fabrics, the
bedroom and sitting room were spacious showcases of subtle lighting
and high-grade cabinetry. The big desks and two-line telephones and
large-screen television sets in each room made it easy to work.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our full-course room-service dinner came in 15 minutes; it was
excellent, as was the service, though the menu was mostly of the
rootless Continental variety. The empty table disappeared quietly a
couple of hours later _ and a small Easterish basket of plush toys
and sweets appeared in its place. It was my daughter's birthday,
which I had mentioned to a doting doorman; from then on, everyone
working in the hotel seemingly knew that Emma had just turned 6.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking thing about the King David is not its opulence
but its personnel, who have become an integral part of local
history. Flip on the television and you are confronted with one of
those welcome-to-the-hotel films one would normally click past
without a thought. But this one is different. It is the story of
Israel, as lived and told by the waiters and cooks and chambermaids
and doormen of the King David hotel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The video doesn't pull punches: it shows July 22, 1946, in all
its destruction and carnage, when Menachem Begin's underground
Irgun movement blew up its west wing, killing 91 people, most but
not all of them members of the billeted British forces who were
Irgun's targets. Hotel employees vividly recall the fierce
Arab-versus-Israeli fighting within rifle range of the hotel in
1948 and again in 1967 _ but they also remember the elaborate
pyramid-motif cake they baked for their cherished guest Anwar Sadat
in his historic visit in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   History, after all, is what Jerusalem is all about. The open
rear verandas of the King David are the perfect spot to take it all
in: the 16th-century Ottoman city walls, the 7th century's great
gold Dome of the Rock and the many visible remnants of the far
older city underneath, from Herod's massive stone foundations to
the tombs and alleys of the Mount of Olives above. It is no
ordinary hotel, and it is no ordinary city. (BBOX) &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the results fell short of expectations. Though Jerusalem had
a third more visitors from January to March than in the same period
last year, the supply of rooms still exceeded the demand. For
tourists, that was the good news. The bad news was that prices,
already high for less than posh lodgings, were raised past Midtown
Manhattan levels, and there they have stayed. But few people pay
the full listed rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is tour-group land, and whether the travelers are
Christian pilgrims or furrow-browed academics or an extended family
on a bar-mitzvah junket, they are probably paying a third less than
do walk-in foreigners. (Israelis get steep discounts.)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In most of Jerusalem's hotels, the ``high season'' includes the
entire summer; winter break from Hanukkah to the Epiphany; and the
mini-seasons of Passover, Easter week and Succoth. These rates are
for standard rooms as of this month. They include breakfast buffet.
Food is kosher in all hotels listed except the American Colony.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Novotel Jerusalem, 9 St. George Street, Jerusalem 97200; (972-2)
532-0000, fax (972-2) 532-0011. Single $131; double $151, with
discounts available to Novotel cardholders.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Plaza Olive Tree Hotel, 23 St. George Street, Jerusalem
97200; (972-2) 541-0410, fax (972-2) 541-0445;
www.royal-plaza.co.il; $153 single, $180 double. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Colony, Shechem Road, Jerusalem 97200; (972-2)
627-9777; fax (972-2) 627-9779; on the Web at
www.americancolony.com; Single $150, double $200. Suites and large
``pasha'' rooms are available at additional cost. A 15 percent
service charge is added to room rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem Hilton, 7 King David Street, Jerusalem 94101; (972-2)
621-1111; fax (972-2) 621-1000; www &QL; 
.hilton.com; single $350, double $390. There is an extra $40 charge
for a view of the Old City; suites and family rooms are also
available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   King David Hotel, 23 King David Street, Jerusalem 94101; (972-2)
620-8888, fax (972-2) 620-8880; www &QL; 
.danhotels.com; single $375; double $398; suites also available.
There is an extra $200 charge for a view of the Old City.
</P>
</TEXT>
