<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL-SOCCER-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING A BALL IN BRAZIL BY KICKING ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Brazil)   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
(Editors: a 500-word box, ``Taking the Team on the Road'' explains
how to arrange a soccer tour. It appears at the end of story.) 
 By ANNASUE McCLEAVE WILSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to admit to being a soccer mom. That cliched title is
easier to bear, however, when the games are played on a crescent
moon of a beach in Brazil, where the team kicks up sand as white
and soft as baby powder. Our family loves soccer, that jogo bonito,
``beautiful game,'' as they call it in Brazil. My son John, 14, has
played since kindergarten, and his coach, Paulo Barreto, is a
Brazilian who played professionally there. His Cincinnati company,
Paulo's Brazilian Soccer Training and Camp, began organizing trips
last year to his hometown, Florianopolis.
</P>
<P>
   The coin toss to see whether my husband, John, or I would
accompany John on a trip there last March was agonizing. Not only
was the trip too expensive for everyone to go, but we would have
had to take our two younger children out of school. I won.
</P>
<P>
   This particular eight-day trip was designed for a team, but not
all of John's team, the Cincinnati Classics, participated, so they
were supplemented by other boys and girls of the same age and
ability from around Cincinnati. Parents were welcome, and of the 17
players, only 5 traveled without a parent, making us a group of 39.
</P>
<P>
   Other camps offer various levels of training and can include
international tournament play for players who hope to play at the
college level and beyond, but this trip offered the right balance
of soccer and vacation for us. Our trip revolved around three
matches with local teams and four morning training sessions, but
equally important was the beachfront hotel and organized afternoon
sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   Florianopolis, on the island of Santa Catarina, is about 350
miles down the coast from Sao Paulo. Our 24-hour trip was not made
easier by the way we were routed by the travel agency _ through
Detroit, Miami and Sao Paulo _ but the teen-agers seemed oblivious
to the inconvenience. When they were not giving water to thirsty
dogs in travel cages or bumping into airport police officers on
bikes, they managed to find enough open space at each stopover to
kick around a soccer ball. In Sao Paulo, they sprawled over the
floor of the airport terminal, lounging or sleeping on backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Several in our group thought the island of Santa Catarina, on
which most of the city of Florianopolis is built, looked like one
of the islands of Hawaii from the air. The hilly countryside is
laden with subtropical flora, and both land and sea are dotted with
ancient black boulders that must have looked like gods to the
Tupi-Guarani Indians who first inhabited the region. The island is
connected to the mainland by two bridges, although one, the
Hercilio Luz, is closed to motor traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Our bright blue hotel, the Ingleses Praia, sat beside a beach
called Praia dos Ingleses, on the northeast shore of the island,
about 22 miles from downtown Florianopolis. The beach was named for
English explorers who poked around there about 1700. Each room had
a balcony, cool tile floors, air-conditioning and surprisingly
spacious bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   We ate breakfast and occasionally another meal at the hotel,
buffet style. Fruits and juices were fresh and delicious, but all
else paled in the morning before the coffee. It was deeply rich and
black, served with hot milk.
</P>
<P>
   Our first evening at the hotel, the parents in the group were
content to laze wearily on the veranda, drinking caipirinhas, a
lime drink usually made with cachaca, Brazilian sugar-cane liquor.
A few of the boys perused the small strip of beachfront restaurants
and souvenir shops selling T-shirts and crocheted bikinis and
thongs on either side of the hotel (their favorite souvenirs were
fake designer watches, but because the dollar is strong against the
real, almost everything seemed inexpensive).
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, they brought out a ball and began to kick it around
on the beach under the stars. This attracted some local people and
soon a full fledged game was on. Not one Brazilian guy walking
along the beach _ student, vendor or fisherman _ could keep his
foot off the ball if it came near him during our practices, and
their skill was remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The team's first training session was at the Hotel Fazenda Jomar
on the mainland near Santo Amaro da Imperatriz, a spa town founded
to commemorate an imperial visit in 1845 by Dom Pedro II, emperor
of Brazil. Having traveled inland 18 miles, we were in dense green
mountains, and the group practiced on a field in danger of being
enveloped by the lush vegetation surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we all took advantage of the resort's amenities. The
team swam in the pool, went rafting in rapids not rapid enough to
be classified, and sank paddle boats in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   On a shaded veranda, an accordionist played German music, a
reminder of the large influx of Germans who emigrated to this part
of Brazil in the 19th century. Several parents joined an ecological
walk around the grounds, which led to a waterfall of rare beauty;
on our way up, we disturbed a lizard the size of a small alligator.
</P>
<P>
   Florianopolis has two professional soccer teams, the Figueirense
Futebol Clube, based on the mainland, and the island's Avai Futebol
Clube, both of which cultivate players from a young age. After a
day of practice and a couple of scrimmages on the beach, our first
match took place against the Figueirense youth team in the club's
stadium in Florianopolis. The Brazilians, who were a year or two
older than John, won, 8-1, which did not seem to diminish the
excitement of playing a challenging opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Our game with the young Avai team two days later took place just
before the professional match between Avai and Caxias (from the
city of Porto Alegre). As the game went on, the stands filled up
with fans who cheered on both teams (we lost, 2-0) but who were
unforgiving of their pro team when it lost.
</P>
<P>
   After the game with Figueirense, our bus took us to the beach at
Joaquina, which is on the east side of the island and is famous for
surfing championships held there each year. After an open-air
lunch, the team wandered the beach, climbing the huge rocks at one
end and examining jellyfish that washed onto the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Praia da Joaquina are massive sand dunes of Saharan
proportion and, even though the wind whipped up the sand so
fiercely it practically blinded them, the team was determined to go
sandboarding. John and the boys happily forged their way up the
dunes over and over again, and dumped their weight in sand onto the
floor of the bus on the way back to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we boarded a schooner and headed for the island of
Anhatomirim, where the team was to practice in the shadow of the
Santa Cruz fort, built in 1744. A Brazilian school group about the
same age as ours happened to be touring the fort, too, and it
wasn't long before another impromptu match was on.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian girls watched the American boys with obvious
pleasure, much to the consternation of the Brazilian boys, which
gave the game an edge it might not ordinarily have had. The
Brazilian boys, on the other hand, didn't know what to make of the
four highly skilled girls playing on our team. Only the parents
were in awe of the setting: on one side a centuries-old fortress
and on the other, the magnificent sea.
</P>
<P>
   After morning training another day, the group ventured downtown.
The two bridges to the mainland shadow 19th-century ocher-colored
market buildings along the old waterfront. Across the street from
the Praca 15 de Novembro, the city's main square, John stopped at
the entrance to the pink Cruz e Souza Palace to have his picture
taken beside the guard, who wore an elaborate uniform and held a
rifle with a bayonet. The team climbed the steps to the bright
white Metropolitan Cathedral, where a Mass was being said, then
plopped down pretending to be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Since this day of sightseeing had little appeal for them, the
high point of the excursion was stopping at a shop called Futebol
Mania to buy official Figueirense and Avai jerseys. A few fathers
wandered off to the bus station to find Cuban cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Our meals outside the hotel were in seafood restaurants or in
churrascarias, places serving meat smorgasbords called rodizio (all
you can eat). Seafood lunches were waterside, in open-air
restaurants that served us at long communal tables _ local shrimp
in butter and oil, mussels in salsa, deep-fried whitefish, served
with plates of beets, shredded carrots and tomato, clay pots of
rich black beans, and crisp, deep-fried manioc root. When Barreto
realized that our ravenous American teen-agers kept passing on the
plates of fish and making faces, he arranged that they be served
chicken with rice and French fries instead.
</P>
<P>
   One evening we were taken to a cafe colonial, a Brazilian-style
high tea inspired by the customs of European immigrants in the 19th
century. On the beach, we snacked on corn on the cob served in the
husk and drank cool milk right from coconuts. The team's favorite
drink was Guarana, sweet green soda with lots of caffeine. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   A cultural exchange had been arranged for us the afternoon
before we left at the Colegia Energia, a private school in
Florianopolis that prides itself on its English instruction. When
we arrived, we were met with wild cheers, as if we were a busload
of American movie stars. Our boys were a little stunned at such a
reception and we had to remind them to keep smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The school had prepared a short program and presented each of
our team members with souvenir notebooks. A soccer scrimmage was
held in which our girls soundly beat four Brazilian girls. While
our boys were outclassed on the field, they were mobbed by
Brazilian girls and boys asking for e-mail addresses and
photographs. Once our team got used to the attention, those who
spoke a little Spanish _ none spoke Portuguese _ tried to talk to
the students, who answered in their halting English.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, we lost our last match, against the Astel Futebol
Clube, but only by a single goal. Once, John collided with an Astel
player, knocking him to the ground. He reached down to help the
Brazilian to his feet, but was scolded by Barreto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you leave him alone,'' he said. ``Find him after the game
if you want.''
</P>
<P>
   When we returned to Cincinnati, the team went on to become
division champions, at least partly because of improved soccer
skills. But the trip had also provided the players with a surprise,
the opportunity to represent their country by their actions: how
they played the game did matter.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE TEAM ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Americans need visas to travel in Brazil. For general
information about Florianopolis, see  &UR; www.florianopolisbrazil.com. &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team soccer trips usually involve individual matches or a
tournament, daily training and sightseeing. These companies are
among those that offer customized tours for team travel to Europe
and the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo's Brazilian Soccer Training and Camp, 12074 Crestfield
Court, Cincinnati, Ohio 45249; (513) 489-6447. Paulo Barreto, a
former professional soccer player, organizes team trips to
Florianopolis, in southern Brazil. Our trip cost $1,400 each,
including all meals (some excursions cost extra). An
air-conditioned bus with a driver was at our disposal 24 hours a
day. Barreto also can make arrangements for individuals or families
traveling to Florianopolis.
</P>
<P>
   Travel and Play, 2800 Euclid Avenue, Cleveland, Ohio 44115;
(800) 824-8347; www.travelandplay.com, offers customized tours for
teams in several sports to Europe and South America. For soccer
trips, contact Barry Walmsley, a former professional player in
England. Package prices for 12 to 14 days are$1,300 to $2,000 a
person and include air fare, ground travel, hotels and meals.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone United Overseas Travel, 199 West Third Street, Red
Hill, Pa. 18076, (215) 679-3544, fax (215) 679-0891, www.keyuntd &QL; 
soccer.com, specializes in customized international travel for
teams. Transportation, hotels, sightseeing and meals can be
included in package prices. The average trip of &QL; 
10 to 12days will cost about $2,000, &QL; 
with two meals a day, air fare, sightseeing and accommodations,
according to Mike Freed, who handles soccer trips for Keystone.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at the Ingleses Praia Hotel, Rua Dom Joao Becker, 447
Praia do Ingleses CEP 88058 600, Florianopolis, Santa Catarina,
Brazil, (55-48) 269-1300, fax (55-48) 269-4108. It is a beachfront
hotel with 100 rooms, all with ocean views. Double rooms are small
but nicely appointed with tile floors and large private bathrooms;
suites have sitting rooms and kitchenettes. Doubles cost $41,
suites $150, at 1.8 reals to the dollar. WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   Churrascaria Meneghini, Rua Leoberto Leal, 249 Viaduto de
Barreiros, Sao Jose, Santa Catarina, Brazil, phone and fax (55-48)
246-1069, serves rodizio, an all-you-can-eat buffet of various
meats, from prime rib to steak to sausages. Lunch or dinner for two
is about $24, not including alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Deca, Canto da Lagoa, Lagoa da Conceicao, Florianopolis; (55-48)
232-6462, is an open-air seafood restaurant serving dishes like
local shrimp in butter and oil, mussels in salsa and deep-fried
whitefish, at communal tables. Lunch or dinner for two is $18.
</P>
<P>
   Pegorini Grill is in the upscale Beira Mar Shopping Mall, on the
island part of Florianopolis, (55-48) 324-0748. A churrascaria with
the usual assortment of meats and salads, it also offers live music
in the evening. Dinner for two is $24 without drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
