<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. SENATE CANDIDATE CORZINE FILES TO SELL $41 MILLION IN GOLMAN
SACHS STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jon Corzine, who spent a record $36.7 million to win the
Democratic primary in New Jersey for U.S. Senate, filed Monday to
sell $41 million worth of stock in Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which he
once headed.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign spokesman said Corzine wanted to diversify his
investment portfolio.The candidate has lent his campaign $33
million so far.
</P>
<P>
   The stock sale is expected to take place in a public offering in
about two weeks. Goldman Sachs had offered its executives and
former partners the opportunity to sell up to 15 percent of their
shares, but in the end they were restricted to about 10 percent, or
411,668 shares in Corzine's case.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine and other Goldman Sachs former and current
executives may get to sell another batch of shares if the company
finds demand for its shares great enough.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is selling more Goldman shares than any other
individual, Corzine, who resigned as co-chairman after the firm
went public in May 1999, will still be one of the biggest
individual owners of Goldman Sachs stock, owning about 4 million
shares worth about $400 million at Monday's closing price of about
$100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Goldman Sachs' current and former partners have been
prohibited from selling any stock in the firm. In connection with
the May 1999 initial stock offering, Goldman Sachs said in filings
with the Securities and Exchange Commission that those insiders
would hold their shares for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs allowed only one previous exception to the
restriction on stock transfers. Last year it allowed the current
and former partners to give shares away for charitable reasons, a
move that reduced the tax burdens the partners faced. Corzine
donated about 175,000 shares to public charities and private
foundations then, according to a document Goldman Sachs filed with
the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday, when the Corzine campaign filed its latest
financial disclosure with the Federal Election Commission, it had
spent $34.7 million and incurred an additional $2 million in debts,
easily surpassing the spending record for an entire Senate campaign
and more than quadrupling the previous record for spending in a
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has lent more than $33 million to his campaign, but Shea
said Corzine was in no hurry to pay himself back with proceeds from
the stock sale. ``He hasn't decided yet how to reinvest this money,
but he's not likely to use it to repay loans,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Corzine's opponent in the November election, Rep.
Robert Franks, released his own campaign finance filing showing
that he had spent $1.9 million to win the Republican primary. He
actually had more cash on hand at the close of the reporting period
Saturday _ $301,399 to Corzine's $211,862, according to the
campaign filings.
</P>
<P>
   But Franks, who earns $136,673 a year as a congressman, raised
$221,350 between the June 6 primary and the close of the reporting
period Saturday, including $122,100 from political action
committees and $99,250 in individual donations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Corzine's holdings in Goldman Sachs were worth about $234
million when Goldman Sachs went public in May 1999, ending the last
major partnership on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The price temporarily fell two weeks ago, when the company
announced that it would allow its current and former partners and
two institutions that own large stakes in the firm to sell a total
of about 40 million shares in a secondary public offering that is
expected to occur in about two weeks. The partners, who now are
being allowed to sell 16.4 million shares, could get the right to
sell another 6 million shares if the offering is oversubscribed by
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Goldman Sachs officials will begin a tour of major
financial centers to promote the stock offering. The price of the
shares being sold will be determined after that tour.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which is expected to occur in early August, could push
down the price as the supply of stock available to the public
increases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
