<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs lede item to correct Gallup poll result to 45-to-43) 
BUSH LEAD GETS SMALLER; HOUSE SPENDING RECORD LIKELY TO
FALL  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH LEAD GETS SMALLER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three new polls taken over the weekend indicate that Gov. George
W. Bush's lead over Vice President Al Gore is narrowing. A CBS News
survey shows Bush leading Gore, 43 to 41 percent, down from his
47-to-39 edge in May. A Zogby poll has Bush holding a 45-to-41
lead, compared to a 47-to-39 edge a month ago. And a USA Today/CNN
Gallup poll has Bush leading Gore 45-to-43, compared to 50-to-41 a
week ago. The CBS poll covered 596 adults and had a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus four percentage points, meaning the
Bush lead was statistically insignificant. Significantly, however,
Bush's potential voters were more likely than his rival's to say
they supported him enthusiastically. And when people who leaned to
Bush or Gore were added to those firmly committed, Bush led 46 to
43. When Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party and Ralph Nader of the
Green Party were added to the poll, Bush beat Gore, 42 to 37, and
Nader and Buchanan got 4 percent each. In the Zogby poll, which
surveyed 890 likely voters and had a three percentage point
sampling error, Bush led Gore, 43 to 37, when other candidates were
added, with Nader getting 6 percent and Buchanan receiving 3
percent. In the USA/CNN poll, which surveyed 1,063 registered
voters over the weekend and has a four percentage point error
margin, Bush led Gore, 45 to 43, when other candidates were added,
with Nader picking up 5 percent and Buchanan getting 3 percent. The
USA/CNN poll showed Gore gained support from women and independents
in the past week, apparently helped by the endorsement of former
Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   THE INTEREST GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE SPENDING RECORD LIKELY TO FALL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's only July and already the hard-fought congressional contest
in the Los Angeles suburbs between Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Pasadena,
and State Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Burbank, is on the verge of becoming
the most expensive House race in American history. With about $7.5
million raised so far, the candidates seem all but certain to
surpass the $8 million record set in Georgia in the 1996 contest
between then-Speaker Newt Gingrich and his Democratic challenger,
Michael Coles. Rogan, one of the House impeachment managers in the
case against President Clinton, is facing a stiff challenge in a
once-Republican district that has been trending more Democratic in
recent years. Liberal groups have made Rogan one of the year's top
targets in the Democratic effort to regain control of the House,
and by the time independent expenditures by outside groups are
factored in, the overall cost of the race is sure to be even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee and Chicago
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE
</P>
<P>
   Memphis and Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
