<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-RATES-1STLD-WRI     07-17 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RATES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S CENTRAL BANK LEAVES SHORT-TERM RATES ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert Nikkei figures in 12th graf and `or nearly $900
million' in 18th graf.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Despite signs of strength in Japan's economy, Bank of
Japan policy-makers voted Monday to prolong their policy of keeping
short-term interest rates at virtually zero, attributing the
decision to concerns over the fallout from the failure of a highly
indebted department store company last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement unusual for its attempt to explain the decision,
the central bank said it had decided to leave rates alone because
of continued uncertainty about employment and wages. Even more
unusual was its mention of the the failed department store
operator, Sogo Co., which declared bankruptcy under loans totaling
more than $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pointed out that the board needed to see how the
commencement of reconstruction proceedings of Sogo Co. could affect
market developments and business sentiment,'' the bank said in a
statement issued Monday afternoon after its nine-member policy
board concluded its regular monthly meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation had been building for weeks that the Bank of Japan
would nudge interest rates raise upwards Monday for the first time
in 10 years because of evidence that the world's second-biggest
economy is in a sustainable recovery from its worst period of
protracted economic weakness since World War II. Central bank
officials themselves have said that keeping rates so low is
abnormal and temporary, hinting that recent evidence of economic
strength like improved corporate profits, rising production and
higher business investment justified a rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the collapse of Sogo, which operates 25 stores and employs
10,000 people, dampened the optimism about Japan's recovery and
served as a sobering reminder of how much bad debt still infects
the Japanese banking system. Rising interest rates would make it
more expensive and difficult for debtors to repay loans, which
could lead to more insolvencies and business failures.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's decision to leave rates alone was welcomed by
economists, government officials and politicians, many of whom have
argued in recent weeks that the bank lacked a clear-cut rationale
for raising rates and ran the risk of short-circuiting the economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank seemed adamant about raising rates last week,'' said
Ronald Bevacqua, senior economist at Commerz Securities in Tokyo.
``The fact that they didn't do it immediately was related to Sogo,
which reinvigorated uncertainty about the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the news was likely to have a positive impact on stock
and bond markets, which had been bracing for a slight increase in
rates, but weaken the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Koll, chief economist at Merrill Lynch in Tokyo, said he
believed Monday's decision would force the bank to postpone a rate
increase for at least another year and perhaps longer. ``I actually
think in terms of the business cycle, we're peaking out right about
now,'' he said. ``Industrial production is now growing 7 percent
compared to last year, but I think at the end of the year, we'll be
at about half that pace.''
</P>
<P>
   How the bank will determine that its concerns about Sogo can be
safely set aside is a bit of a mystery. There will be little
economic data released between now and Aug. 11, when the policy
board meets again, and the bank did not spell out which tea leaves
it would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic conditions are now strong enough to be compatible
with rising rates, so unless we see some unexpectedly weak
indicators over the next month, we could see an increase in
August,'' said Masaaki Kanno, senior economist at J.P. Morgan in
Tokyo. ``Stock prices are probably going to be quite important.''
</P>
<P>
   He said if the benchmark Nikkei 225 stock index, which at
17,286.83 is now down 8.7 percent for the year, rises above 18,000
and stays there, the bank might raise rates next month. (By the
midday trading break on Tuesday, the Nikkei index was down 81.88
points, or nearly half a percent.)
</P>
<P>
   While there was widespread praise for the bank's restraint, the
decision raised questions about when the bank will carry through on
its intentions to eventually raise rates. ``The importance of the
decision is not so much about interest rates as it is about
credibility,'' said Marshall Gittler, a currency strategist at the
Bank of America in Hong Kong. ``The Bank of Japan is now the
central bank that cried wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Masaru Hayami, the bank's governor, has made it clear that he
wants to raise rates and quickly, arguing that the so-called
zero-interest rate policy was adopted as an emergency measure in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Such an extremely loose monetary policy normally runs the risk
of fueling inflation. But Japan has the opposite problem _ prices
are falling here. Consumer spending is erratic at best, and
bankruptcies are rising to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Although business investment has picked up, companies are not
borrowing to finance their expenditures despite exceptionally low
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that monetary policy in this current
environment when everyone is trying to pay down debt is largely
irrelevant,'' said Richard C. Koo, chief economist at the Nomura
Research Institute Ltd. ``So I think a little too much emphasis has
been placed on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Koo said the bank was right to delay a rate increase in the wake
of Sogo's demise. Sogo failed after the government abandoned plans
to use 97 billion yen, or nearly $900 million, in taxpayer money as
part of a plan to forgive some of Sogo's debts.
</P>
<P>
   That turnabout was initially hailed as a sign that politicians
would stand aside and allow painful structural adjustments to take
place in the economy, and while investors are generally still
applauding the government's decision, they have also begun trying
to assess the costs of that decision.
</P>
<P>
   What has become increasingly clear is that, whereas the original
plan would have required a handful of major banks and the taxpayers
to shoulder the burden of Sogo, allowing the retailer to fail under
court supervision will spread the pain to scores of smaller
financial institutions and trade creditors.
</P>
<P>
   The government will also presumably have trouble coming to the
rescue of other heavily indebted companies, now that it has set a
precedent with Sogo. ``If this kind of thing goes on unabated, we
could actually break the cycle of growth that the Japanese economy
is in,'' Koo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
