<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWS-ART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNICIPAL ARTS COMMISSION PUTS `COWS ON PARADE' OUT TO PASTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Cows on Parade'' in
Chicago and New York will not be hoofing their way to Kansas City.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several hours of lively debate centering on the essence of
art, the Municipal Arts Commission voted 4-2 Monday to kill a
proposal that would have spread decorated, fiberglass cows around
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the commission decided to pursue a more original plan,
leaving the door open for suggestions on what that public art
display might look like. Dozens of people attended the hearing,
many to voice their opposition to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we endorse `Cows on Parade' we're saying this is the best
Kansas City has to offer,'' said commission member Richard Pierre
Nadeau. ``I'm profoundly saddened by that thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau had written a letter to the mayor that sparked the
hearing and the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I submit to you, serious public art is not decorated cows,''
said Nadeau.
</P>
<P>
   A sculptor who went only by the name ``Stretch'' and several
like-minded people attended the hearing, dressed in T-shirts
depicting a cow turned upside down with an X through it. Throughout
the hearing they waved signs that read, ``Cows are bad. Original?
Not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely a no vote on cows,'' said Stretch.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the hearing, Linda Off spoke on behalf of
the American Royal, the Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art and the
Kansas City Zoo, the agencies that would have benefited from the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an excellent way for artists to be known,'' said Off.
``It's a very public, participatory event.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argued that the project had been successful and
profitable in other cities where it had been tried, particularly in
Chicago. The Kansas City version of ``Cows on Parade'' would have
followed the Chicago model, which enlisted nearly 300 artists to
decorate fabricated fiberglass cow forms.
</P>
<P>
   Local corporations would have been invited to sponsor the cows
and have their names listed on accompanying plaques for $5,000
each, for a potential corporate outlay of $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $5,000 paid by a sponsor, $1,000 would have gone to the
artist; after expenses the rest would have gone to the Royal, the
Kemper and the zoo. Some of those against the project argued that
$1,000 was not enough money to compensate local artists.
</P>
<P>
   Off said no taxpayer dollars would have been spent on the
project, which had drawn the support of Mayor Kay Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The cows would have been placed on city property next year from
May to August. After that the cows would have been auctioned, with
proceeds also going to the three beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is a worthwhile endeavor,'' Barnes wrote in a
letter to the commission. ``I view `Cows on Parade' as a community
arts project of a temporary nature, which allows a large number of
people to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed with the mayor's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Holmes, a commission member, didn't like the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't like cows,'' Holmes said. ``But this is
too big a thing to be a follower. Frankly, I just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the project were hoping to duplicate the success that
occurred in other cities. Chicago's event attracted global media
attention. And a 500-cow display has opened in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Kosloff, the commission chairman, told members he was
concerned that the decision was being based on good art vs. bad
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arts Commission is asked to approve encroachment issues on
public property,'' Kosloff said. ``It's a temporary project. All of
us in our own hearts will decide whether it's good art or bad art
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosloff's argument was not enough to stem the tide of
discontent; one artist after another lambasted the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the vote was taken, its outcome prompting applause from
the artists in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good project, but they went about it wrong,''
said Myra Morgan, an art gallery owner for 35 years who spoke
against the plan. ``If they would have gone to the arts community,
it could have been a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes thinks the right decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it was very original,'' said Holmes. ``And
the organizations that stood to benefit certainly don't need help
fund raising.''
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that maybe another idea might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Posey, a commission member, was un sure what direction
supporters would go in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the project is dead or what,'' said Posey.
```But I do know, we all want to see a public exhibit of some
sort.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
