<SLUG> BC-GE-HARMON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARMON INDUSTRIES AGREES TO $425 MILLION PURCHASE BY GE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Harmon Industries
Inc., a Blue Springs, Mo., railroad safety equipment company
started more than 50 years ago, on Monday agreed to be bought by
General Electric Co. for $425 million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harmon will be acquired for $30 a share, upon approval from
regulators and shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon's stock jumped Monday by $16.38 a share and closed at
$29.56 in heavy trading on the Nasdaq exchange. The buyout is
expected to be tax-free for Harmon shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the buyout, Harmon will become part of GE Harris Railway
Electronics, a joint venture of GE Transportation Systems of Erie,
Pa., and Harris Corp. of Melbourne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A Harmon executive said Monday that it was too early to
determine the buyout's effect on Harmon's work force, which
includes about 800 Kansas City area employees and 2,000
companywide.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that drew us to GE is their people,
technology, quality of products and customer service,'' said
Stephen L. Schmitz, Harmon's chief financial officer. ``We will
work to put the two organizations together in the best possible
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing had been decided about the merger's effect on either
company's facilities, Schmitz said. In addition to its Blue Springs
corporate headquarters, Harmon has plants in Grain Valley, Mo., and
Warrensburg, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take that as a negative; this could be very beneficial
for our area,'' Schmitz said of the merger. ``It's a good
combination for our employees and our customers. This will take the
technology we've been developing forward.''
</P>
<P>
   GE thinks the combining companies are complementary rather than
overlapping, said Susan Breon, a spokeswoman for GE Transportation
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``GE Harris Railway is in software development and systems
integration for rail-signaling equipment,'' she said. ``Harmon is
more the producer of the actual equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   The top executives of both companies said combining the two
businesses would reap benefits for both entities.
</P>
<P>
   John Krenicki, president and chief executive officer of GE
Transportation Systems, said Harmon's products corresponded to GE
Harris' product line and expanded General Electric's offerings in
railroad signaling and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn E. Olsson, Harmon's president and chief executive officer,
said the merger would help the company reach its long-term goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all employees of Harmon can take pride in the fact
that we are joining forces with one of the best recognized
corporations in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would end the independence of a company started in 1946
by Robert C. Harmon, an engineer who persuaded Kansas City Southern
Railway to place an order for electronic equipment with his
fledgling company.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon was succeeded by his son, Robert E. Harmon, who became
president in 1969. The company went public in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Olsson joined Harmon Industries as president and chief operating
officer in 1990. He became chief executive officer in December
1994, when Robert E. Harmon stepped down from the company's daily
operations but remained chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon grew through the late 1990s, posting record sales and
profits in 1998. In recent years, Harmon also has acquired several
smaller companies and has established subsidiaries in Canada,
Mexico, Australia, England and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   However, big railroad mergers and the subsequent congestion led
to less demand for Harmon products in 1999, prompting a
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Harmon closed facilities in Lee's Summit;
Riverside, Calif.; and Long Island, N.Y. The closings and transfers
resulted in additional jobs for Harmon in Missouri, where it now
has about 1,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   GE Transportation had sales of more than $2 billion last year
and employs about 6,700. GE Harris Railway has about 460 employees,
mostly in Melbourne, Breon said. GE Harris Railway also has a
facility in Germany, she said. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
