<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ACCOUNTING-NYT &LR;      07-17 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNBIASED ACCOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 18,
2000:
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, would not appear to be asking for very much. He wants
independent audits of corporate financial statements to be just
that, independent. Yet his seemingly innocuous proposals aimed at
guaranteeing independence are drawing heavy resistance from the
accounting profession and, because the industry is rich and
powerful, from Capitol Hill. Ordinary investors should pull for
Levitt to win this struggle because the rules he has proposed are
calibrated to protect their financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   By law, public corporations hire outside auditors each year to
examine their financial statements. The idea is to reassure
investors that corporate reports on earnings and other measures of
financial health have been prepared according to professional
standards. Recently, public confidence in these outside audits has
been shaken by a number of explosive financial crises. Investors
lost a lot of money, in part because they relied on fraudulent or
misleading financial reports issued by companies and certified by
their auditors.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the corporate failures is the insidious appearance of
a conflict of interest. Accounting firms increasingly perform
lucrative consulting services for companies they audit. The
commission is now asking whether this relationship creates an
unhealthy incentive for accounting firms to perform less aggressive
audits. In some recent cases where a company's financial condition
turned out to be much worse than investors had been told, the
accounting firm that performed the errant audit had also provided
its client with substantial non-audit services.
</P>
<P>
   Is there proof that the non-auditing work caused auditors to
wink at impropriety? No. But suspicions lurk.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has now issued new rules for public comment and possible
adoption by the end of the year that address those suspicions. The
proposed rules would solidify two principles. One is that auditors
should not own stock in the companies they audit. The second is
that an accounting firm should not be allowed to audit other
services provided by the same firm.
</P>
<P>
   Toward those ends, the proposed rules would require auditors to
disclose non-auditing services they provide their clients and would
prohibit auditors from doing external audits for companies for
which they also provide internal audits. The new rules would also
prohibit accounting firms from designing computer systems that
generate financial statements for companies they audit.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five major accounting firms oppose the chairman's
efforts. So does the major association of public accountants.
Several members of Congress from both houses have sent letters to
the chairman questioning the need for the proposed rules. But
Levitt is right to proceed. Investor confidence requires not only
the absence of conflicts of interest but the absence of the
appearance of such conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has proposed nothing draconian, only common-sense rules
to make sure that outside auditors perform and appear to perform
independent audits. For that the chairman deserves Congress'
enthusiastic support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000717.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-PHILLIES-YANKS-SL     07-17 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PHILLIES-YANKS-SLUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE STRUGGLES AGAIN IN LOSS TO PHILLIES
</HEADLINE>
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone wanted the baseball Monday night even
before the national anthem was played at Yankee Stadium. Cone's
shoulders were hunched and he looked as if he were walking uphill
as he strolled to the mound and waved his glove toward Umpire Mark
Hirschbeck. Hirschbeck did not respond and made Cone wait for the
ball. The wait only delayed the start of another depressing night.
</P>
<P>
   Once Cone got the ball, once Cone dug his cleats into the dirt
and tried to get comfortable, everyone stared at him and everyone
wondered how he would fare. Cone is a proud and ornery pitcher not
accustomed to failure, but this season has disappointed him and
caused the doubts and the questions about his future to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Cone did little to stem those doubts and questions Monday night
as the Philadelphia Phillies belted two homers off the 37-year-old
right-hander and held on to beat the Yankees, 10-8. Monday is the
anniversary of Cone's magical perfect game against the Montreal
Expos last season, but aside from Cone's two crucial postseason
victories in helping the Yankees to a second straight World Series
title, his pitching since last July 18 has essentially been
imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral continued Monday night as Cone allowed six runs in
five innings and lost his sixth straight decision, a career high.
It also extended his streak without a victory to a career-worst 12
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden has pitched well in two appearances and would be a
candidate to replace Cone in the rotation. But Manager Joe Torre
said before the game that Cone was not pitching for his spot last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to pitch five days from now, as far as I'm
concerned,'' said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Since Orlando Hernandez is expected to miss his start against
the Detroit Tigers Wednesday night because of a sprained right
elbow, Cone has a little more time to assert himself and remain in
the rotation. He stifled the Toronto Blue Jays, 3-0, on April 28,
his only victory in a 1-8 season. With the Yankees fighting the
Jays for first place in the American League East, how much longer
can Torre continue to use an ineffective Cone?
</P>
<P>
   After Pat Burrell smashed a slider that was just above his
ankles over the center field fence for a three-run homer in the
fifth last night, Cone put his hands on his hips and stared toward
the outfield. He looked exasperated and frustrated, which is how
the Yankees felt, too. They still felt that way when Bobby Abreu
ripped a grand slam off Jason Grimsley in the seventh to put the
Phillies ahead, 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think David Cone's mind-set is more of looking for an answer
right now,'' said Torre. ``I think the big thing bothering him is
how good he feels physically and it's not translating into what it
should translate into. It baffles him, why it's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cone has struggled, he has rarely had a decent slider. But
he used a nifty slider to strike out Kevin Sefcik and Abreu in the
first Monday night. One inning done, Cone must have thought. Five
or six more like that and he could talk about the beginning of a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   But by the second inning, Cone was in trouble as he walked Scott
Rolen on five pitches and Mike Lieberthal crushed his next pitch
into the left field bullpen for a 2-0 lead. Cone lifted his hands
above his head, dug around the rubber and kicked his left leg into
the air as he waited to resume pitching. His reddened face was
filled with a frown.
</P>
<P>
   David Coggin, who was pitching at Class AA Reading five weeks
ago, walked the bases loaded with two out in the Yankee third. Tino
Martinez lined a single to right, and after one runner scored,
Bernie Williams also tried to score on the hit. Abreu's strong
throw to Lieberthal was about 10 feet up the third base line and
beat Williams, but Williams crashed into the catcher with his left
shoulder and his left leg to jar the ball loose and tie the score,
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Williams later bowled over Tom Prince, who replaced Lieberthal
(sprained left ankle), when he scored New York's fourth run. But
even though the Yankees scored the game's last four runs, they
could not catch the Phils on this night, and Coggin earned his
second victory in his fifth major league start.
</P>
<P>
   And Cone's woes went on. After a 1-2-3 third inning, he
encountered more problems during an ugly fourth. Abreu lined a
double to right and Rolen slapped a routine grounder to shortstop.
Derek Jeter darted to his left and had the roller glance off his
glove for what should have been an error, but it was ruled a single
and there were two runners on instead of one on and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Prince blooped a single to center to make it, 3-2 and Cone was
sweating now, trying to keep the Yankees in the game. Cone uncorked
a slider that bent beneath Burrell's knees, but the rookie did a
tremendous job of reaching down and driving the ball about 430
feet. It was tough for the Yankees to watch the ball soar, even
tougher for them to watch Cone sputter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coney is not going to quit,'' said Torre. ``He's going to
solve this. We're going to help him do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
