<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p BC-POLL-GOP-KAN &LR;      07-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-GOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI VOTERS SHOW REPUBLICAN LEANINGS, POLL INDICATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri, long
recognized as a bellwether of the nation's political mood, appears
_ for now _ to be tilting Republican.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polls commissioned by The Kansas City Star showed last week that
GOP candidates for president, U.S. Senate and governor were leading
their races. Although polls for the Senate and governor's races
were extremely close, in both cases the Republicans clung to leads.
</P>
<P>
   In bad news for Vice President Al Gore, who is visiting Kansas
City today and Wednesday, GOP opponent George W. Bush was leading
by 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Two other questions in The Star telephone poll also showed a
Republican tilt. One asked Missourians whether they would like to
see Democrats or Republicans control the U.S. House after the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP came out on top with 46 percent to the Democrats' 39
percent. Fifteen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which idea they favored to ensure the future of Social
Security _ a plan similar to Bush's proposal or one like Gore's _
respondents picked the Bush method 37 percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Republicans do seem to have an edge,'' said Ken
Warren, a St. Louis University political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats shot back that the races would turn around once voters
became more fully engaged and started examining the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent it's easier to electrify your base if you're
the party out of power,'' said Roy Temple, executive director of
the Missouri Democratic Party. ``In the end, Democrats are
Democrats for a reason. When people start thinking about the
issues, it'll be clear which is the better choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore flies to Kansas City today to take aim at a state long
known for backing both Democrats and Republicans. He is scheduled
to attend a rally in downtown Kansas City at 5:30 p.m. today and
attend a private fund-raiser. On Wednesday he is to attend an
anti-crime event in Raytown.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the vice president hope that the events will help
him cut into the 48-percent-to-37-percent edge Bush recorded in The
Star poll. Although Missouri supported Bill Clinton in 1996, the
state found itself favoring the Republican candidate so far this
year. Other states in a similar position are Minnesota, Wisconsin
and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Star poll also showed Republican John Ashcroft leading
Democrat Mel Carnahan in the U.S. Senate race by 47 percent to 43
percent, barely within the poll's four-point margin of error. In
the race for governor, Republican Jim Talent led Democrat Bob
Holden by 41 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are proving to be more than competitive in a key area
_ fund-raising _ that could help them in November. So far Carnahan
has raised $6.2 million in his race to unseat Ashcroft, while the
senator has brought in $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's race, Democrat Holden was leading with $6.6
million raised to Talent's $4.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   But in another indictor of potential GOP strength, Bush by
himself got more votes _ 275,366 _ in Missouri's March presidential
primary than the 260,654 votes that Gore and rival Democrat Bill
Bradley brought in together.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, though, have said that those numbers were skewed
because the Democratic primary race was largely over in March while
the GOP battle was in full force, thanks to Bush challenger Sen.
John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Missouri always had been a conservative state,
often led by conservative-to-moderate Democrats. Over time,
Democrats have become more liberal on issues such as taxes,
abortion and crime, said GOP spokesman Daryl Duwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not where a lot of people find themselves any more,''
Duwe said of the Democrats. ``They realized the party they were
backing wasn't voting the way they would vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say proof of that can be found in the 163-member
Missouri House. Ten years ago the GOP had just 58 members. Today
they are at 76 and hope to get a majority come November for the
first time in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a sense, the GOP says, that Democrats are barely
clinging to their narrow majorities in the nine-member
congressional delegation and the 34-member state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Once longtime Democratic incumbents step aside because of term
limits or retirement, the GOP thinking goes, Republicans will claim
those largely rural seats and take majority status.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the rural areas the Democratic Party hasn't been what those
voters are about,'' Duwe said. ``Democrats are holding those seats
by force of personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the hustings this year, Republicans say they sense
something new: Voters who once claimed to be Democrats are now
hedging, saying they plan to divide their votes between the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a swing,'' said Republican Danielle Moore, a
retired teacher from Fulton, who ran for the 20th District House
seat two years ago. ``I am noticing that more people seem to be
identifying themselves as split-ticket voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jim Howerton, a House member running for the 31st
Senate district seat south of Kansas City, said he was getting a
positive reception from longtime Democrats as he went door to door.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, Howerton said two words: Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether people feel like Clinton's done all the things he's
been accused of or not, they're just tired of it,'' Howerton said.
``It's left a sour taste in people's mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, veteran Democratic state Rep. Henry Rizzo said
he was confident of his party's chances in November. But he
acknowledged that he was encountering a lot of Democratic voters
who simply had not yet tuned in to the races. Democrats running
statewide must pull in big totals from the state's two largest
cities to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``What scares me worst than anything is voter apathy,'' said
Rizzo, who represents northeast Kansas City. ``I'm very concerned
about it. Democrats are not fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to Kansas City today illustrates some of the same
problems he faces in other states. Instead of venturing out to
suburban areas that are in play this year, Gore will be spending
his time shoring up the Democratic base with his stops downtown and
in Raytown, known as good Democratic turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be reaching out toward the suburbs, toward trying to
broaden his base to ensure his victory,'' said Warren, the
political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, added Warren, already was doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan cautioned that a lot of time remained between now and
Election Day. Most voters trust Democrats more to handle issues
such as Social Security, Medicare, education and health care; once
that message sinks in, the polls will turn around, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the message we really need to get out,'' the governor
said. `We really have fought in the trenches for these issues.
These things just haven't fallen out of the sky.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
