A5240 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HOSPITALS-2TAKES-KAN &LR;      07-17 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT INCOME IS KEEPING SOME AREA HOSPITALS IN THE BLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the health-care
industry engulfed in turmoil in recent years, some Kansas City area
hospitals have made millions of dollars in profits while others
have bled red ink.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an extreme example, financial losses and a weak asset base
prompted Health Midwest to close Park Lane Medical Center last
year, depriving some Raytown area residents of a neighborhood
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to financial disclosure documents filed with the
Internal Revenue Service, some area hospitals have logged healthy
profits, aided by an infusion of investment income.
</P>
<P>
   Such hospitals, however, lost money or barely broke even from
their primary function: taking care of sick people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment income was the only thing that really saved us last
year,'' said G. Richard Hastings, president and chief executive
officer of the St. Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System, which
includes St. Luke's Hospital and Shawnee Mission Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1998, investment income of $10.8 million turned
a loss of $1.3 million at St. Luke's Hospital into a net gain of
$9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals elsewhere tell a similar story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing from our members around the country that the
difference between red ink and black ink this year has been
investments and philanthropy,'' said Richard Wade, a spokesman for
the American Hospital Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wade blamed ``underpayments'' by private insurance and the
federal Medicare program for elderly patients. ``Sixty percent of
the nation's hospitals are losing money every time they treat a
Medicare patient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that, some hospitals depend on investment income to
heal their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said hospitals typically invest in a balanced
mix of bonds, stocks and money market funds to limit fallout from
stock market swings.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there is cause for concern if hospitals depend too
much on investment income.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need growing patient revenue streams to adequately
compensate our employees and invest in new patient care
technologies,'' said Tom Cranshaw, senior vice president of
strategic planning for Health Midwest, Kansas City's largest
hospital system. The 15-facility system includes Research Medical
Center, Baptist Medical Center and Overland Park Regional Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Some local hospital officials say their financial situation has
improved in the last year or two because of cutbacks,
consolidations and, in at least one case, the removal of a hospital
from direct state control.
</P>
<P>
   Industry critics contend that hospitals are weighted down by
top-heavy administrations that drain valuable resources.
</P>
<P>
   But hospital officials here and around the country say they're
caught in a bind. Many of them are lobbying their elected
representatives and senators to reverse Medicare reimbursement cuts
tied to the 1997 Balanced Budget Act. If such relief does not come
through, they say they might have to cut services.
</P>
<P>
   One service that faces possible cuts is free care for indigent
persons. That worries Sheri Wood, executive director of the Kansas
City Free Health Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cause of concern for the community,'' Wood said.
``We've got a quarter of a million people in the Kansas City area
that are uninsured or underinsured.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial profiles of most area hospitals are outlined in
documents such as Form 990, which nonprofit hospitals are required
to file annually with the Internal Revenue Service. The most
recently filed Form 990s are from calendar year 1998 or fiscal year
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The results of for-profit hospitals can be obtained from
Medicare cost reports.
</P>
<P>
   According to its most recently filed Form 990, St. Luke's
Hospital and some affiliated operations had total revenues of $294
million during calendar year 1998. Total expenses were $284.5
million, and the hospital logged net income of $9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But without investment income of $10.8 million, St. Luke's would
have lost $1.3 million at the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings blames the financial squeeze on the Balanced Budget
Act, which cut St. Luke's Medicare reimbursement by $9.6 million in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings' competitors have the same complaint. Cranshaw blames
the Balanced Budget Act for forcing Health Midwest to close Park
Lane Medical Center last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balanced Budget Act reduced the patient revenue of Park
Lane for the same level of patient care activity in the range of $4
million between 1998 and 1999,'' Cranshaw said. ``Because of that,
it was impossible to reduce costs and maintain quality of care. The
hospital had run out of cash.''
</P>
<P>
   While they all provide health care, results can vary widely
among different hospitals. Location plays a role. For example, the
ill-fated Park Lane was in a low-growth area just north of Raytown.
</P>
<P>
   Research Medical Center, Health Midwest's biggest hospital,
earned net income of $15.9 million in 1998, including $8 million in
investment income.
</P>
<P>
   But Health Midwest's second-biggest hospital, Baptist Medical
Center, lost nearly a million dollars at the bottom line in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Research and Baptist are only 1.5 miles from each other. But
Cranshaw noted that Research performs more intensive, specialized
procedures, such as neurosurgery and open heart surgeries, that
generate more patient revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare cuts have eaten into the bottom line at St. Joseph
Health Center, said George Zara, president and chief executive
officer of Carondelet Health, which operates the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph is projected to have earned about $8 million in net
income during the fiscal year that ended June 30, with more than $7
million of that coming from investment income, Zara said. That's
down from the previous year, when St. Joseph posted $10.2 million
in net income, including $4.9 million in investment income.
</P>
<P>
   But things are improving at another Carondelet hospital, St.
Mary's Hospital of Blue Springs. Zara said St. Mary's is projected
to have earned about $1.5 million during the fiscal year that ended
June 30, up from $246,748 the previous year. The improvement was
mostly due to hefty increases in patient volume.
</P>
<P>
   Why the difference between the two hospitals? Zara said St.
Joseph has more Medicare patients than St. Mary's, and large
numbers of Medicare patients pose a financial liability in today's
hospital marketplace. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
