u s BC-BBO-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT     07-17 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT BLUE JAYS, 7-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ If there had been a sarcasm detector strapped to
Manager Bobby Valentine as he answered questions before Monday
night's game, the machine would have been humming. Was there
anything really wrong with the New York Mets, or were they simply
playing well but losing close games? Is his team underachieving?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've underachieved, obviously,'' said Valentine. ``I
haven't gotten out of these guys what I could have. I think we
could have won a lot more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Valentine being serious, or just flip? One thing was
certain: the Mets were stumbling, having lost 9 of 12, and Monday
night's game against the Toronto Blue Jays and their rookie
starting pitcher was one they had to win.
</P>
<P>
   They finally prevailed, 7-5, when a fielder's choice grounder by
Mike Piazza and a single by Todd Zeile gave the Mets two runs in
the 11th inning. The Mets got six no-hit, shutout innings from
their bullpen, with John Franco (4-3) earning the victory and
Armando Benitez his 21st save.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani started the game-winning rally with a single off
losing pitcher Pedro Borbon (1-1), who walked the next two hitters
before Piazza and Zeile came up.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' bullpen overcame the erratic performance of the
veteran Rick Reed, who was returning from the disabled list against
Pasqual Coco, a 22-year-old who came up from Class AA to make his
major league debut. Neither starter was effective, but Coco
succeeded in keeping the Mets hitless with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' first hit in that situation came in the eighth, off
John Frascatore. Lenny Harris, who had three hits, singled with two
outs, then stole second _ becoming the first Met this season to
steal two bases in the game. Derek Bell, who had been 1 for 21,
followed with a run-scoring single that tied the game, 5-5, and
ensured Reed of a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was making his first start since June 29, when he broke his
left wrist and strained his left calf. Last season, injuries
unrelated to his pitching arm actually helped Reed pitch better
down the stretch, because he was rested.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are expecting the same effect this season, but they
will have to wait for it to happen. Reed was on a pitch count
Monday night _ he threw 101 pitches _ and the Mets had a 12-man
pitching staff on Monday night as protection against a short outing
by Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Reed lasted only five innings, giving up five runs (four earned)
on five hits and five walks. Reed's stuff looked good; he struck
out three, all swinging, and he got the last batter he faced to
ground to second after falling behind in the count, 2-0. But he
could not command his pitches with consistency, and though one of
the walks was intentional, the total of five matched a career high.
</P>
<P>
   Reed walked the first batter of the game, and by the end of the
inning the Mets trailed, 2-0. Joe McEwing quickly changed that.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the second, Todd Pratt drew a walk and McEwing,
a spry left fielder, came to bat. He suddenly sent a pitch
rocketing toward the upper reaches of the Skydome, and the ball
crashed into the netting well up the left field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   That tied the score, 2-2, erasing a lead the Blue Jays had taken
in the first inning when Carlos Delgado belted his 30th home run,
leading the American League. With two outs, Delgado smoked a pitch
423 feet into the second deck, giving him four seasons in a row
with 30 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays regained the lead immediately when they batted in
the second. Reed fell behind Darrin Fletcher, 2-0, and Fletcher
drove the next pitch into the right field bullpen for a homer,
putting Toronto ahead, 3-2. Jose Cruz doubled off the wall in
left-center on the next pitch, but Reed retired the next three
hitters to escape more damage.
</P>
<P>
   Things worsened in the third. Reed walked Delgado and Brad
Fullmer with one out, and Tony Batista grounded to shortstop Melvin
Mora for a potential inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Mora did his part, but the normally sure-handed Edgardo Alfonzo
did not. An accurate relay throw would have easily beaten Batista
and ended the inning, but Alfonzo's throw bounced in the dirt and
got by Todd Zeile as Delgado scored to give the Blue Jays a 4-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Batista, on second base because of the error, was able to score
when Fletcher followed with a single up the middle. Jay Payton
might have had a chance to throw him out at the plate, but his
throw was several feet to the right of Pratt, the catcher.
</P>
<P>
   It was 5-2 Toronto, and Coco was somehow keeping the Mets from
mounting successful rallies. He had gotten Alfonzo and Mike Piazza
to ground out with a runner in scoring position to end in the first
inning. He had induced a pop-up from Derek Bell with a man on
second to end the second and gotten another pop-up from McEwing
with the bases loaded and two outs in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got a run in the fourth, when Lenny Harris tripled and
scored on a wild pitch, but the Mets were 0 for 6 with runners in
scoring position off Coco.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza doubled off the top of the fence in left-center leading
off the fifth, and Coco was removed after he hit Zeile. Paul
Quantrill came in, and the Mets scored a run on a ground ball to
make it 5-4. But they managed no more hits in the inning and left
runners at second and third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
