<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-17 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HOSPITALS-2NDTAKE-KAN     07-17 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``in today's hospital
marketplace.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medicare cuts have been especially hard on academic medical
centers, which have suffered reductions in special payments
designed to subsidize the cost of training medical interns and
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Truman Medical Center, the primary teaching hospital for the
University of Missouri-Kansas City School of Medicine, lost $6.7
million during the year that ended April 30, 1999, after earning
$363,875 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Medicare cuts caused by the Balanced Budget Act,
Truman chief financial officer Allen Johnson pointed a finger at
lower payments from Missouri's Medicaid managed care program.
Truman and other academic medical centers typically treat a large
volume of Medicaid patients and uninsured patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts us in a very big hole,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Kansas Medical Center, which also is an
academic medical center, has seen its financial fortunes improve in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   President and chief executive officer Irene Cumming said KU
Medical Center cut costs several years ago to meet the challenges
of tighter reimbursements. In addition, KU officials say the Kansas
City, Kan., medical center has enjoyed improved financial results
since it was removed from direct state control and placed under an
independent public hospital authority in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But times have been tough for Bethany Medical Center in Kansas
City, Kan. Bethany lost more than $9 million from December 1998
through May 1999, the first six months of operations under its
current owner, the Sisters of Charity of Leavenworth Health System.
Its performance improved during the next 12 months, but it still
lost $13.6 million during the year that ended May 31 of this year,
said Jim Paquette, chief executive officer of the Sisters of
Charity's Kansas City region.
</P>
<P>
   Paquette said he expects further improvement this year and said
Sisters of Charity, which also operates St. John Hospital in
Leavenworth and Providence Medical Center in Kansas City, Kan., is
determined to keep Bethany open to serve its resident base in the
urban core of Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System, which includes St.
Luke's Hospital, responded to the financial squeeze in September
1999 by laying off nearly 300 employees, the majority of whom did
not work directly in patient care. The cuts included social workers
and the hospital's Wanna Be Well child-care program for sick
children. Some programs within the system were consolidated at one
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said the belt-tightening has contributed to a financial
turnaround at the health system, which expects to make an operating
profit of $6.4 million and a net profit of $7 million or $8 million
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastings worries about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress and the president don't come through with more
money, then there is only one other choice, and that's to reduce
the amount of free care we provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Many hospitals provide free care to indigent patients who lack
health insurance. Hastings said St. Luke's provided $29 million
worth of such care in 1999. Cranshaw said Health Midwest provided
tens of millions of dollars worth of free care last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a zero-sum game,'' Cranshaw said. ``As reimbursement
declines, there is the challenging need to sort through the
available funds for charity care and reinvestments into
state-of-the-art technology we need to continue our mission of
quality patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Karen McCarthy of Kansas City said hospitals received
some relief from Medicare cuts under legislation passed in 1999,
and more such legislation is on the table.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy is a co-sponsor of the Hospital Preservation and Equity
Act of 2000. Now in the House Ways and Means Committee, the bill
would restore $6.7 billion in Medicare reimbursements to hospitals
in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must correct this inequity,'' McCarthy said. ``We are
seeing increased needs in health care, with patients in underserved
and unserved areas, because hospitals do not have the ability to
operate and subsidize the growing Medicare patient population. It
is critical that the unintended consequences of the 1997 (Balanced
Budget) Act be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other co-sponsors include Rep. Pat Danner of Smithville, Rep.
Dennis Moore of Lenexa and Rep. Ike Skelton of Lexington, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   A similar proposal in the Senate, the Hospital Preservation Act,
is co-sponsored by Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri and Sens. Sam
Brownback and Pat Roberts, both of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The additional $7.7 billion that our new bill will provide
over five years is further action to protect and preserve
Medicare's ability to meet the needs of the American people,''
Ashcroft said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hospital officials watch and wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, we're going to have to reach a consensus on
what is a reasonable payment for the services we're providing,''
Zara said. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
